<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHELSEA-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COVER ARTICLE ON DAUGHTER IRKS CLINTONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton and his wife, Hillary, said on
Wednesday night that they were ``profoundly saddened'' by People
magazine's decision to run a cover article on their daughter,
Chelsea, in its next issue.
</P>
<P>
   Neither People magazine nor the White House would discuss the
article in detail on Wednesday night, although the magazine issued
a statement making it clear that the article, entitled ``Grace
Under Fire,'' is about Miss Clinton's relationship with her mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a great deal of admiration for this mother-daughter
relationship,'' Carol Wallace, the magazine's managing editor, said
in a recorded statement released by a spokeswoman. ``Over the
years, we have written about the White House in good times and
bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Explaining its decision to feature the Clintons' daughter, Ms.
Wallace said Miss Clinton is ``nearly 19 and a poised young
adult.'' The statement said the magazine's editors consider her ``a
valid journalistic subject'' because she is a witness to a
continuing ``family drama'' and important historical events _ a
clear reference to the impeachment trial arising from the
president's relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Reached at his home in Manhattan, a People executive editor,
Cutler Durkee, said he had not been involved in editing the article
and could not comment.
</P>
<P>
   The president and Mrs. Clinton issued a statement on Wednesday
night saying they ``deeply regret and are profoundly saddened'' by
the magazine's decision. For the six years of the Clinton
presidency, the statement said, the media have generally respected
their daughter's privacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, despite personal appeals with respect to her
privacy and her security from her parents, People magazine has
chosen to run the story,'' the statement said. ``We can only hope
that the media will continue its policy of restraint with respect
to our daughter.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's spokeswoman, Marsha Berry, said on Wednesday
night that the article would make it ``very difficult'' for Miss
Clinton, now a student at Stanford University, to have a private
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's just trying to go to school, and she hasn't done
anything to draw attention to herself,'' Ms. Berry said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
