</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-HURRICANES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVILS BEAT HURRICANES, 4-1 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENSBORO, N.C. _ Devils Coach Robbie Ftorek reunited Patrik
Elias with Petr Sykora and Jason Arnott on Wednesday night for the
first time in several games, and the line combined for three goals
and three assists to lead New Jersey to a 4-1 triumph over the
Carolina Hurricanes.
</P>
<P>
   Sykora had two goals and assisted on a goal by Elias, who also
had an assist, as the Devils returned to their winning ways after a
loss to Nashville and then a tie with Detroit on Monday night in
New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our lines have been changed a lot all year because of injury,
or we have so many guys that can play, you have to get people into
the lineup,'' Ftorek said. ``So we made a lot of changes because I
want to play guys and not get stale.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin Brodeur, who made a number of spectacular saves against
Detroit, had another inspired performance in goal with 29 saves for
the Devils. He allowed only a power-play goal by Keith Primeau.
</P>
<P>
   Several players, as well as Ftorek, credited Brodeur for the
victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marty was really good again,'' Denis Pederson said. ``You need
a goaltender like that to kill penalties like we did. We gave up a
power-play goal tonight, but we've been doing really well on the
penalty kill the last few games.''
</P>
<P>
   Primeau's score was the first power-play goal the Devils allowed
over the past 30 times in which they played a man short, spanning
eight games.
</P>
<P>
   Brodeur was particularly superb late in the second period, when
Bobby Holik took two penalties, and late in the third period, when
the Devils had to kill a penalty to Scott Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   Two of Brodeur's saves in the second period came from
point-blank range, on Robert Kron in the eighth minute and on Kent
Manderville in the 15th. Brodeur also had fine glove saves on Ray
Sheppard, Adam Burt and Glen Wesley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the toughest were in the third, when they were coming
with speed and Primeau had a breakaway,'' Brodeur said of his
saves. ``I also got lucky when they disallowed that goal and
Sheppard hit the post.''
</P>
<P>
   Carolina had a goal by Marek Malik disallowed early in the third
period, when the Devils had a 2-0 lead, because Ron Francis was in
the crease.
</P>
<P>
   Elias opened the scoring with his eighth goal of the season, on
the Devils' first shot in the game, 5 minutes 31 seconds after the
opening face-off. It came from close range on the left after a pass
from the other side by Sykora, who took the puck away from Curtis
Leschyshyn in Carolina's zone.
</P>
<P>
   The goal by Elias held up until Sykora got his first of the
night, 75 seconds into the last period. After Primeau scored,
Krzysztof Oliwa had his fourth goal of the season and Sykora got
his second of the game and 16th of the season with 2:14 left.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
