<HEADER>
A1238 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     02-04 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RODMAN A BAD IDEA FOR LAKERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ This just in: The Lakers are interested in Dennis
Rodman.
</P>
<P>
   In other news, President Clinton pledged his allegiance to
Promise Keepers, Sean Penn flew into town via Southwest Airlines to
promote his latest movie and Calista Flockhart is said to be
weighing a sweet endorsement deal with Mars candy. Snicker,
Snicker.
</P>
<P>
   The bare-bones truth? The Lakers need to add Rodman to their
roster about as much as Flockhart needs to lose another pound.
</P>
<P>
   We're not talking about a Chicago team loaded with veterans and
led by a vocal superstar. This is a young Lakers team with a lot of
growing up to do.
</P>
<P>
   You have center Shaquille O'Neal, who is no Michael Jordan when
it comes to goading his teammates into greatness.
</P>
<P>
   You have impatience personified in Kobe Bryant, who has yet to
be convinced that grand things can happen to those who come off the
bench.
</P>
<P>
   And you have an unheralded starting point guard, Derek Fisher,
who is having to massage so many egos on a daily basis it's no
wonder his skin is becoming calloused.
</P>
<P>
   The last thing a team with an immature streak needs is to have
is the NBA's Peter Pan swoop in for a season. In the Lakers' case,
Rodman isn't the answer to their prayers for an NBA title, he's a
death wish.
</P>
<P>
   Shame on team executive vice president Jerry West for even
entertaining the thought of acquiring basketball's bad boy. This
was a story that should have had no legs _ like a lot of NBA
players will, come the fourth quarter of Friday's openers.
</P>
<P>
   West should have followed the cue of a growing segment of the
public at-large and simply ignored Rodman, the soon-to-be
38-year-old character-turned-caricature.
</P>
<P>
   Just because owner Jerry Buss likes Rodman _ you know what they
say about birds of a feather (or in this case, feather boa) _ it
doesn't mean West was under any obligation to pick up the telephone
and touch base with Rodman's agent.
</P>
<P>
   By acknowledging Wednesday that he had done so, West, wittingly
or no, telegraphed a distress signal to the team he has assembled
to challenge Utah and Houston and San Antonio and Portland for
Western Conference bragging rights in this shortened season:
</P>
<P>
   I love you. You're perfect. Now change.
</P>
<P>
   If West was wild about the team he had assembled, why would he
give a second thought to a guy who, last time anyone checked, was
hosting an all-night pre-Super Bowl bash in Miami with wife Carmen
Electra?
</P>
<P>
   That's one conditioning method we don't recommend to the kids at
home. It's surely not the one endorsed by 16-year veteran Derek
Harper, who reported to training camp in amazing shape. Then again,
West acquired Harper to help set an example for the younger Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   They can be quite a headache to deal with, the headstrong bunch
of individuals who wear the purple and gold.
</P>
<P>
   As far as providing relief, Harper acts like an aspirin. Rodman
would be more like a sledgehammer.
</P>
<P>
   If the Lakers were to wind up with Rodman, the shortened season
would provide the only real comfort, the concentrated schedule
providing fewer practice days for Rodman to kiss off in favor of
the casinos in Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Rodman is a gamble for any team, though we understand the
temptation.
</P>
<P>
   His mastery of one of the NBA's lost arts is laudable, his place
in league history, unimpeachable. Rodman is the seven-time
defending rebounding champion, his average of 16.8 boards a game in
that span a testimony to his tenacity, timing and toughness.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago Bulls would have been hard-pressed to win their
third consecutive NBA title this past spring without Rodman.
Remember his 14 rebounds in a four-point Bulls win in Game 4 of the
Finals?
</P>
<P>
   That's the Rodman West wistfully described Wednesday; the
heads-up player with the boundless energy.
</P>
<P>
   It's too bad Rodman can't suppress his id, because without that
there'd be no idiot. As it is, the last thing a Lakers team already
disposed to distraction needs is a casino-crawling, club-hopping,
cross-dressing clown.
</P>
<P>
   Even at 15 rebounds and $21,195 a game, that addition would be
no bargain at all. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
