u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-OPEN-1STLD-WR     02-04 1041
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-OPEN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-720&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPEACH-SCENE, IMPEACH-BORK)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs 10th graf to make date of Chase's trial 1805, stead of 1804) 
INCREASING NUMBER OF SENATORS FAVOR PUBLIC DELIBERATIONS IN
IMPEACHMENT TRIAL  (See also IMPEACH-RDP, IMPEACH-BLUMENTHAL,(sw) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Support is growing in the Senate to suspend its
19th-century impeachment rules and allow public viewing of the
final deliberations on whether to remove President Clinton from
office.
</P>
<P>
   Senate rules require impeachment deliberations to be conducted
behind closed doors, and senators have soundly rejected two
attempts in the trial to open debate on procedural motions.
</P>
<P>
   But backers of a bipartisan measure say an increasing number of
Republicans and virtually all Democrats recognize the importance of
opening the final debate on acquitting or convicting the president.
</P>
<P>
   It would take two-thirds of the Senate, or 67 senators, to
change procedures drawn up in 1868 for the impeachment trial of
President Andrew Johnson. Both sides say a vote to suspend those
rules, which will likely happen next week, is too close to call.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of the mounting support, traditionalists like Sen.
Robert C. Byrd of West Virginia, a Democrat, and Sen. Ted Stevens
of Alaska, a Republican, both of whom voted to close debate on the
procedural motions, now favor opening the final deliberations. ``I
don't think the final arguments will change anyone's mind, so I see
no reason to close them,'' Stevens said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Trent Lott of Mississippi, the majority leader, has
expressed skepticism about the proposal, but a senior Republican
aide said on Wednesday that Lott is now reconsidering the idea.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say opening the final deliberations would set a bad
precedent, violate the American trial tradition of having jurors
deliberate privately, and unnecessarily prolong the trial because
all 100 senators would feel obliged to use their alloted 15
minutes. ``I don't believe the public would be denied anything
essential if the sessions are closed,'' said Sen. Mitch McConnell,
R-Ky.
</P>
<P>
   This debate illustrates a clash between age-old Senate
traditions and contemporary public demands for openness in
government and the realities of late 20th-century communications.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have come to expect more knowledge of their
government's decision-making process,'' said Sen. Kay Bailey
Hutchison, R-Texas, who is the proposal's main author.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison noted that her plan would not overturn Senate
precedent, but actually return to the tradition of open trials that
began with the impeachment of Samuel Chase, an associate justice of
the Supreme Court, in 1805 and ended with Johnson's proceedings 64
years later.
</P>
<P>
   The American public has been clamoring for a speedy end to the
trial, but there has been scant focus outside the Capitol about how
to conduct the senators' closing debate. In a Gallup poll last
month, those surveyed were equally divided on whether the Senate
should debate the impeachment issue in public or private.
</P>
<P>
   Twice in the trial, Sens. Tom Harkin of Iowa and Paul Wellstone
of Minnesota, both Democrats, asked the Senate to suspend its rules
and allow open deliberations.
</P>
<P>
   The first vote, to open debate on whether to dismiss the
charges, failed, 57 to 43. The second vote, to open debate on
whether to take depositions from three witnesses, was defeated, 58
to 41.
</P>
<P>
   In each case, senators said the closed sessions permitted a
candid and constructive discussion that allowed the Senate to forge
ahead with trial procedures.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question, when you have the prying eye of the
camera and the outside world looking in, that affects the
dialogue,'' said Sen. Chuck Hagel, R-Neb., who supported closing
the debate on the procedural motions, but now wants to open the
final debate.
</P>
<P>
   Many other senators are undecided on the issue, having focused
this week on more immediate questions of whether to allow live
testimony or videotaped depositions in the trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't made up my mind,'' said Sen. James M. Jeffords,
R-Vt. ``My instincts would say open it up, but tradition is to keep
it closed. The propensity of senators to want to maximize their
time adds a lot of hours.''
</P>
<P>
   But supporters of an open debate are pressing their case.
Hutchison has sent a letter to all her colleagues, reminding them,
``We are making history, and future generations, as much as our
own, deserve to know how we did so.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Last week, CNN asked the Senate and Chief Justice William H.
Rehnquist, who presides over the trial, to open all proceedings,
arguing that to do otherwise violated the First Amendment. The
18-page brief was laced with references to the ways in which the
First Amendment and the media had evolved since 1868.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only during this century has our commitment to the principle
that debate on public issues should be open become not merely a
nationally shared philosophy but an element embedded in
constitutional law,'' the brief said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our society in 1868 _ and more significantly still, our law in
1868 _ was far different than it is today,'' the brief said.
``First Amendment jurisprudence as we know it _ as it governs and
binds the Senate _ is essentially a creature of the 20th century.
That jurisprudence assures public scrutiny, not public ignorance.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate has changed, too: senators who voted on the 1868
impeachment were selected by state legislatures; since 1913 they
have been elected by popular vote.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of opening the debate dismissed the notion that
senators should be treated like normal jurors. The identities of
these 100 jurors are well known, as their votes will be. The
senators face no constitutional protections against public reaction
to their votes. Senators face the approval or rejection of the
voters the next time they seek re-election.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'd be a mistake to close the final debate,'' Hagel said.
``It would cast too much of a cloud of suspicion. I say, throw the
doors open and let the American people hear it. Maybe it would be a
little cleansing tonic to run through the gears here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-04-99 0035EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
