r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN     02-04 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAN LAKERS WIN IT ALL?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ The opening of the NBA season is a bit like that
dreaded annual family reunion for the Lakers. They're the awkward
14-year-old boy who walks into the room, feeling all grown up and
proud, only to have Aunt Martha shatter the illusion with a
two-handed pinch of the cheeks.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the Lakers return to the NBA another year older and feeling
a year wiser. But like that gawky 14-year-old trying to survive
puberty, they are an unfinished work of nature, still hoping not to
get stuck sitting at the kids' table.
</P>
<P>
   It was only last May, after all, that the Lakers were getting
spanked by their elders, dealt a 4-0 sweep by the seasoned Utah
Jazz in the Western Conference finals. The NBA lockout was long,
but not nearly long enough to erase the sting and embarrassment of
that defeat.
</P>
<P>
   So now the Lakers return, a slightly changed group and perhaps a
more mature one for the experience. They certainly hope so. The
annual ritual of being dubbed the league's most talented team, only
to finish the season tagged as too immature to win it all, is
getting old.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, we read and we listen,'' said guard Derek Fisher.
``We know how certain people feel about us. And not only are we
tired of it ourselves, but I think it's a natural human reaction to
want to prove other people wrong. I think that's where we are right
now. Sometimes that's what it takes.''
</P>
<P>
   Once again a favorite to win the Western Conference, and
possibly the NBA championship, the Lakers re-enter the fray in this
lockout-shortened season with only subtle changes from the team
that was so badly outclassed in the 1998 conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Van Exel's testy attitude is gone; Derek Harper and his 15
years of NBA experience take his place. Travis Knight, a skilled
young forward, is back to add depth but certainly isn't the missing
piece to a championship puzzle.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, barring a last-minute move to gamble on Dennis Rodman,
the Lakers will rely almost solely on their own maturation process
to get past old hurdles, namely the Jazz.
</P>
<P>
   There is evidence that process has taken place. From the brief
training camp in Santa Barbara to the daily practices the last two
weeks, the Lakers have shown a new commitment to working toward a
title, rather than just expecting one based on their talents alone.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Del Harris, often quick to criticize his players,
concluded training camp with the assessment, ``It's been the best
attitude among our practices here the five years I've been in Los
Angeles, for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   And he wasn't alone in that feeling. Players cite a more
competitive atmosphere, and maybe it's the removal of Van Exel and
the tension he had with Harris. Or maybe it's the presence of
Harper, a tough-talking, no-nonsense leader who commands the
respect no one else did. Or maybe it's the presence of three
energetic rookies, including one, Ruben Patterson, who seems
hell-bent on proving something the second calisthenics begin.
</P>
<P>
   And maybe that six-month lockout simply gave the Lakers six
months longer to reflect and grow up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It starts with us looking in the mirror, with each of us, how
accountable we are to ourselves, and really asking ourselves the
question, how committed we are to working this out all the way to
the end,'' said forward Rick Fox. ``Because with that comes
sacrifices of individual honors and individual games.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a question a player will ask himself at the beginning
of the season.... And if you've got a group of guys that never ask
that question to themselves, you've got a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   In talent and skill, the Lakers are much the same as they were.
Their starting five hasn't changed. At their core is Shaquille
O'Neal, the game's most dominant center, and Eddie Jones, an
All-Star guard and defensive gem. Their small forward is the
do-it-all Fox and their point guard is now Fisher, less experienced
and less of a scoring threat than Van Exel but probably more
reliable. Robert Horry, a small forward in stature, will again play
as a converted power forward.
</P>
<P>
   Their shortcomings, then, are also the same as they were. The
Lakers lack a true power forward who can rebound and bang with Karl
Malone (thus the interest Tom Gugliotta, whom they failed to get,
and Rodman, whom they might still obtain). They have no ace spot-up
shooter in the rotation, and their best pure shooter is a rookie
(Sam Jacobson) who won't get many minutes. And without Van Exel,
the Lakers lack the kind of player who will make the game-winning
shot with the clock running down.
</P>
<P>
   But their bench is one of the deepest in the league, with Kobe
Bryant, Elden Campbell and Harper. And while the Jazz and Houston
Rockets have grown older, the Lakers believe they have grown wiser.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that beat us last season was execution,'' Bryant
said. ``People are talking about the mindset of the team, the
maturity of the team. The fact of the matter is, veteran teams
execute (plays). Because they've been in the league.... they focus
on execution, they pay attention to detail. Us as a young team, we
haven't done that. That's why we've been losing. Utah executed us
right off the court.... That's what maturity means to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Slightly retooled, motivated by their own shortcomings, still
loaded with the best talent money can buy, the Lakers once again
eye a title run. Their elders taught them a lesson to end 1997 and
'98. Now it's up to the young Lakers to prove they learned that
lesson.
</P>
<P>
   So have they?
</P>
<P>
   ``Until we get put in that situation, the playoff situation, I
don't know,'' Bryant said. ``Maybe against Utah in the Western
Conference finals. Then you'll know.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
