<HEADER>
A1258 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-USC-LADN     02-04 0710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HACKETT LOOKS TO FILL THE GAPS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC had barely announced its football signings
Wednesday evening, and coach Paul Hackett was already busy making
references to next year's recruiting class.
</P>
<P>
   His first full year of recruiting completed, Hackett is eager to
keep plugging holes, and the most conspicuous absence among the 21
recruits who signed national letters of intent Wednesday was a
running back.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since 1995, Tailback U. did not sign a
tailback.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sets the stage for the most important recruit for 2000 to
be a running back,'' Hackett said. ``We have to go out and recruit
the top running back in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   USC tried to sign several running backs, including Joe Weber
(Texas A&AMP;M), Onterrio Smith (Tennessee) and Charles Drake
(Michigan), but came up short with each player.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have felt from the very beginning we were in a tough battle
for Joe Weber,'' Hackett said. ``He chose to go away and there's
not a heckuva lot you can do about it. Joe Weber was a key guy for
us. What we didn't want to do, though, was recruit just another
running back.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for Hackett, the Trojans did much better filling
other positions. They were ranked anywhere from eighth to 14th
nationally by the major recruiting services, which was slightly
higher than last season.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans also did a good job meeting last year's No.1
priority: linemen.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to a last-minute windfall, USC signed five offensive
linemen after securing commitments from Lucas MacKay and Eric
Torres on Tuesday. The Trojans also signed All-American defensive
tackle Bernard Riley of Los Alamitos and his highly regarded
teammate, tackle Sagan Atuatasi.
</P>
<P>
   ``The addition of Luke and Eric right at the end... that really
makes a difference,'' Hackett said. ``We think Bernard Riley can be
an instant impact player.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hackett had hoped to sign between 10-12 linemen, so he still
feels shortchanged in that department.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't sign five more each of the next two years, you can
have a setback,'' Hackett said. ``I wanted as many as 10 linemen.
Maybe our pool of people was too shallow. I would have loved seven
defensive linemen and five offensive linemen.''
</P>
<P>
   As Hackett gains more experience recruiting, he's also learning
a few lessons. One of them is that USC's efforts to increase its
nationwide recruiting might have been a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans signed just three players from outside California,
and only one player (kicker David Newbury) from Texas, where they
had made a major push. They also got shut out in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had said I wanted to work nationally. That is a
disappointment. How we performed nationally is not what I thought
it would be,'' Hackett said. ``We're not going to change. I don't
think one year is a true gauge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very disappointed we didn't get two or three more people
from out of state. (Texas) was one of the biggest eye-openers. That
was tough.''
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans did well in California, however, and have at least
seven players (linebacker Markus Steele, Riley, Newbury, cornerback
Darrell Rideaux, and wide receivers Marcell Allmond, Kareem Kelly,
Steve Stevenson) that are considered potential starters by the
coaching staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think when you look at the class, you've got to look at
Markus Steele,'' Hackett said. ``He has the kind of range that
Chris (Claiborne) had. He plays with great intensity. He's a great
blitzer. We'll start him at the outside linebacker position but he
could play middle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the wide receiver group is premier. I'm going to be
accused of being a part-time track coach.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly (200 meters), Rideuax (100 meters) and Allmond (110
hurdles) all won state titles at last year's track championships,
while MacKay is one of the top throwers in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Notes: The Trojans lost cornerback Nijrell Eason of Long Beach
City College on Wednesday. Eason, who verbally committed last week,
signed with Arizona State.
</P>
<P>
   Offensive lineman Norman Katnik of Foothill in Santa Ana may not
enroll until next spring, although it still hasn't been decided,
Hackett said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
