<BODY>
 !dlim!!head!IOC discord 
over reforms!dlim! !by1! !by2!Daily News  Wire Services !dlim!
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; !text! &LR; Threatened with the loss of their cherished right to
vote on Olympic host cities, International Olympic Committee
members in Lausanne, Switzerland, on Wednesday expressed deep
resistance to sweeping reforms to the bidding process proposed by
IOC president Juan Antonio Samaranch.
</P>
<P>
   During a hastily organized private breakfast attended by 41 IOC
members, in town for a world summit on drugs and sports, many
complained to top Olympics officials that the reforms sought by
Samaranch were indiscriminate and unnecessarily harsh.
</P>
<P>
   In a series of emotional and sometimes bitter exchanges between
IOC members and the committee's executive board, the members argued
that innocent members were being unfairly punished for the abuses
of their colleagues, said IOC members who attended the closed-door
breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we have some bad apples, they should be thrown out, but
don't tell us the whole general assembly is corrupt,'' said Italian
IOC member Mario Pescante.
</P>
<P>
   !arrow!Apology in Utah: &UR; !off! &LR;  Tom Welch, the man at the center
of the Salt Lake Olympic storm, apologized for the discomfort
caused by the scandal but insisted that other Olympic leaders knew
more than they now claim.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is ironic that those who were so supportive of our efforts
to secure the games now feel the need to distance themselves,''
said Welch, the man who led the committee seeking the Olympic bid
for Salt Lake, in a letter to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   !arrow!U.S. ripped: &UR; !off! &LR;  Former Olympic champion Sebastian Coe
accused the United States of double standards, citing reports that
sprinter Dennis Mitchell escaped a drug ban by blaming sex and beer
for his positive test.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to foster confidence... when somebody like Dennis
walks away after claiming that elevated levels of testosterone were
due to sex and beer the night before,'' Coe said. ``This stretches
credibility to the breaking point.'' &UR; !end!!dlim! &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
