A1261 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      02-04 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEAVEN HELP YOU, RICK NEUHEISEL, WARN THE FOES OF WASHINGTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Jim Lambright had this annoying habit of walking
through the University of Washington's figurative yard and stepping
on rakes, repeatedly bonking himself on the head.
</P>
<P>
   Although it amused small children, the football coach's
carelessness was an embarrassment to athletic director Barbara
Hedges and others on campus. So they fired him, and picked up all
the rakes.
</P>
<P>
   Then they made the controversial hire of Rick Neuheisel, and
what happens?
</P>
<P>
   BONK!
</P>
<P>
   Neuheisel's first significant moment as Husky coach raised a
knot on his brow at least as ugly as any spotted on Lambright. In
addition to recruiting a sub-mediocre class, Neuheisel was caught
in an NCAA violation and accused of tampering by his former
employer.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to Seattle, Rick. Tried any of our banana-slug lattes?
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for him, judgment on the worthiness of Neuheisel's
$1-million-a-year contract must await a season or two of actual
football. If it were based on letter-of-intent day, Gary Pinkel
might be getting a call from Seattle saying, ``Can we talk again?''
</P>
<P>
   Claiming ignorance of the law, Neuheisel owned up Wednesday to a
violation Sunday when he sent five assistants to visit recruits at
home. In 1995, the NCAA adopted a rule that confined recruiting
contact on the Sunday before letter day to campus visits.
</P>
<P>
   He said that in his four years at Colorado, his recruiting work
had already buttoned up by the final Sunday. But the compressed
schedule caused by his abrupt arrival at Washington pushed him
unknowingly into a forbidden zone.
</P>
<P>
   Although he claimed not to know of the violation until he was
called by a high school coach Monday morning, he reported the
violation to UW compliance director Ralph Bayard, who told the
Pac-10. This sort of self-reporting is lauded by the conference and
often results in less time standing in the corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a mistake,'' Neuheisel said.
</P>
<P>
   The official version sounds plausible _ too much work in too
little time, an honest mistake, self-reporting, public confession.
The proper response to carelessness. Unless a rival recruiter can
establish Washington gained an improper advantage, the Huskies
likely will suffer no more punishment than an order to go to bed
without dinner.
</P>
<P>
   It is the other allegation that holds more intrigue. Bayard said
that his counterpart at the University of Colorado distributed a
letter Jan. 28 across much of the college football nation claiming
that Neuheisel called his former players at Colorado and encouraged
them to transfer to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   If the charge proves true, it could be a major violation and the
NCAA tanks would surround the Tubby Graves building until Neuheisel
and his staff came out with their hands up.
</P>
<P>
   While Neuheisel steadfastly denied what he called ``falsehoods''
spread about his phone work, he did acknowledge making calls. But
he claimed the calls merely wished good luck to the players he had
come to know and enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   Problem is, he was the Washington coach at the time. NCAA rules
say there can be no talk between a coach and players from different
schools.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA rulebook is a Bermuda Triangle of bureaucratic
sophistry and hypocritical supermorality in which a number of
coaches have ventured, never to return. Having said that,
Neuheisel, Hedges and all of their peers are willing signatories to
the silliness, so they can't argue. They are their own rules.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the Colorado claims are true _ Bayard said no specific
incidents were described in the letter _ awaits further
investigation. Without saying so directly, Neuheisel, Bayard and
presumably the rest of the Husky athletic honchos are furious with
what they perceive as a scurrilous personal attack against
Neuheisel for the grief he caused by taking the UW job after he
said he had no interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Insulted? Yeah,'' said Bayard. ``I responded (by letter to
Colorado) to that effect.''
</P>
<P>
   Bayard's feeling illuminates a matter that doesn't need a ruling
from the NCAA: When a school engages in the business of coaching
piracy, there are consequences beyond the change of nameplates on
the door.
</P>
<P>
   While Neuheisel can't be condemned for taking a better job,
neither can folks at Colorado be denied their anger over being
jilted and/or misled. Nor can Northwestern be faulted for wishing
locusts upon Boulder for CU's abrupt hijacking of its coach, Gary
Barnett.
</P>
<P>
   It's big-time college sports at its seamiest. While the ruthless
cycle is an annual event, this particular episode has potential for
high smarminess because of the continuing contempt for Neuheisel in
Colorado, as well as the national anger directed at Washington for
warping the salary scale by paying a young coach big money for his
potential instead of past achievement.
</P>
<P>
   Wonder how Lambright is feeling this morning?
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
