<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-FURS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEVERLY HILLS WANTS FURS TO CARRY DEATH NOTICE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEVERLY HILLS, Calif _ ``I love it,'' said Rebecca Witjas, a
ballet instructor from Malibu, as she stood before a mirror,
admiring a full-length spotted lynx coat she was trying on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it wears me, it's so huge,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Witjas' enthusiasm dimmed when told that furs sold in
Beverly Hills could soon carry a tag saying: ``Consumer notice:
This product is made with fur from animals that may have been
killed by electrocution, gassing, neck breaking, poisoning,
clubbing, stomping or drowning and may have been trapped in
steel-jaw, leg-hold traps.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh my God, I think that's really reasonable,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   So goes the latest controversy in Beverly Hills, where the City
Council voted 3 to 1 with one abstention on Tuesday to place a
referendum on the May 11 ballot asking voters to decide whether fur
coats sold here should carry such a warning. If approved by voters,
national animal rights groups say, it could be the first such law
in the country. A group of residents and volunteer activists
gathered more than 3,300 signatures supporting the measure, which
also drew the backing of the actor Jack Lemmon.
</P>
<P>
   The issue has been framed more in terms of truth-in-labeling
than the ethics of luxury. The group backing the measure, Beverly
Hills Consumers for Informed Choices, produced a secretly recorded
videotape of salespeople telling people posing as customers that
the animals were put down humanely, rather than mentioning some of
the more gruesome ways in which they can be killed, said Luke
Montgomery, the campaign manager for the group.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a product that costs thousands of dollars, and the
point we're making is, whether it's deliberate deception or
misinformation, the consumer has the right to decide,'' Montgomery
said.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Kaplan, the president of the Fur Association of Southern
California, denied that fur retailers hid the information or
intentionally misled people and said the videotape had been edited
to take comments out of context.
</P>
<P>
   The fur retailers have an ally on the City Council: Though the
vote placing the issue on the ballot was a formality, Mayor Less
Bronte voted against it. In an interview, he said the labels could
harm the city's reputation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-04-99 0108EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
