A1265 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-TULANE-RECRUIT-TE     02-04 0524
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TULANE-RECRUIT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAGEDY INTERSECTS WITH ENNIS PLAYER'S BIG DECISION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STACEY FEDUCIA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The telephone at Vera Hawkins' home would not stop ringing.
</P>
<P>
   ``How is Veronica? We heard she'd been hit by a car; is she all
right? How is Quentin? Was he hurt in the accident? What about the
people in the other car?''
</P>
<P>
   Two months ago, there was no telephone in Vera Hawkins' home. It
was a luxury for a family attempting to recover from a fire almost
two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   It was an anomaly that her son, Ennis High School defensive back
Quentin Brown, would go through college recruiting season without
that ubiquitous link to coaches. He made do, though, by talking to
schools from Ennis coach Sam Harrell's office until the family
could afford to have its own line installed a few weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   After Arkansas revoked an offer, and New Mexico's interest
vanished with a coach transfer, Brown had finally secured a visit
to Tulane on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   It was his chance to be the first in his family to go to
college.
</P>
<P>
   He took his mother to work that morning, then went home to get
his 9-year-old twin sisters, Monica and Veronica, ready for school.
He dropped them off on his way to class.
</P>
<P>
   The telephone at Ennis High School rang.
</P>
<P>
   Veronica had been hit by a pickup truck. Quentin rushed out to
get his mother and meet the ambulance at the emergency room.
</P>
<P>
   En route, a car entered an intersection from a stop sign.
Quentin slammed on the brakes and started to skid, unable to avoid
the collision. The air bag deployed in his face. The other car
started to spin, throwing a child, who was not wearing his seat
belt, from the back seat.
</P>
<P>
   The child died Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``\RThe car\S was just there,'' Quentin said. ``It just happened
so fast.''
</P>
<P>
   Vera Hawkins arrived at the emergency room to find Veronica with
a broken leg and Quentin with bruised ribs. The college trip would
be canceled.
</P>
<P>
   He was disappointed, but was it OK to feel that way, knowing
that another child would not have the same opportunity?
</P>
<P>
   ``He won't talk about it too much,'' Vera Hawkins said. ``We've
been talking to him and telling him it wasn't his fault that it
happened. I just thanked God that nothing serious happened to my
children.''
</P>
<P>
   The telephone rang at Vera Hawkins' home.
</P>
<P>
   Tulane coaches called to see how Quentin was feeling. Coaches
from South Carolina called, as well. Questions about his health
yielded to questions about where he would decide to go to school.
The call Tuesday morning from Tulane yielded a scholarship offer,
sight unseen, and Quentin Brown had a decision to make.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was getting phone calls all day and all night,'' Quentin
said yesterday. ``I couldn't go to sleep because I was thinking
about where I was going to go and what I was going to do. I was
really confused. I guess I'm really relieved.''
</P>
<P>
   A telephone rang at Tulane yesterday, informing coaches that
Ennis defensive back Quentin Brown had signed a letter of intent to
play college football there.
</P>
<P>
   Some things, however, a phone call can't cure.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
