A1267 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN     02-04 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL-AMERICAN PARADE LEADS TO UCLA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A cornerback has not passed the SAT and there is
no punter. Otherwise, it's tough to find fault with UCLA's 1999
football recruiting class _ the consensus choice as No.1 in the
Pac-10 and one of the top-five nationally.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the dominant program in the West, UCLA can be selective,''
said SuperPrep Magazine recruiting guru Allen Wallace, who rated
UCLA's class No.5 in the nation. ``The Bruins had a super effort
with an eye towards elite talent.''
</P>
<P>
   The 20-man class features 10 defensive players and five Parade
All-Americans: Venice quarterback J.P. Losman; San Jose linebacker
Marcus Reese; offensive lineman Shane Lehmann (Corona) and Bryce
Bohlander (Salem, Ore.); and Westlake tight end Mike Seidman, whom
UCLA coach Bob Toledo called ``the plum of the class.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a prototype NFL tight end,'' Toledo added. ``He's exactly
what we're looking for. They're hard to find.''
</P>
<P>
   A year after landing the nation's top-rated class, UCLA signed
either the No.1 or No.2 player in California at eight positions:
Seidman, Losman, Reese, Lehmann, Monrovia tailback Akil Harris,
Newhall receiver Jerry Owens, Fresno cornerback Ricky Manning and
Anaheim kicker Nathan Fikse.
</P>
<P>
   ``They got top-20 players nationally at every position,'' said
Student Sports Magazine's Brentt Eads. ``There's great balance.
From the quarterback to the kicker, they got a stud.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have the horses on the track. Now they have to get them
saddled and headed in the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Another way to judge UCLA's performance is by the small number
of coveted players it did not sign: Los Alamitos defensive tackle
Bernard Riley (USC), Seattle tailback Paul Arnold (Washington),
Glendale (Az.) defensive end Norman Boebert, and Concord cornerback
Atari Callen.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, the Bruins landed all the regional players on their
most-wanted list. Longtime observers believe the 1998 and 1999
recruits are UCLA's best back-to-back classes in at least a decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key is to put building blocks on top of each other,''
Toledo said. ``I think we're building that foundation.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike last year's frenetic signing day, when Justin Fargas and
DeShaun Foster kept the suspense high, the Bruins had no
last-minute drama. Their commitments were secured weeks in advance,
with the exception of Seidman and Harris, the Monrovia tailback who
initially committed to Colorado but changed his mind after coach
Rick Neuheisel bolted for Washington.
</P>
<P>
   With Foster, Jermaine Lewis and Keith Brown returning, UCLA kept
its tailback list short. Harris saw the depth chart and did not
flinch.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's an example of true recruiting clout,'' Wallace said.
</P>
<P>
   Losman was the first player to commit, accepting Toledo's
scholarship offer during a one-day camp in June. He is expected to
graduate early from Venice H.S. and enroll for spring practice,
where he'll compete with four returnees for the starting job.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a specimen,'' Toledo said. ``I haven't seen a high school
guy throw the ball like him since John Elway. We don't have a guy
in the program with his arm strength. There are guys in the NFL who
don't throw the ball like him.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins' priorities were cornerback, kicker and punter. They
signed two cornerbacks, Manning and Gardena's DaShaun McCullough,
who has not attained a qualifying score on the SATs. They signed
Fikse, the top-rated kicker in the west. But they failed to sign a
punter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have a punter in the program, and I'm concerned,''
Toledo said. ``We're talking to guys about possibly walking on.
We're taking all comers.''
</P>
<P>
   Note: The Bruins have one scholarship available. They are
recruiting Harvard-Westlake's 300-pound junior, Alex Holmes, who is
petitioning for college eligibility. Holmes played tight end at
Harvard-Westlake but is expected to play defense in college.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
