r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-RANGERS-PUERTO-RI     02-04 0307
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-RANGERS-PUERTO-RICO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS COULD LAND PUERTO RICO SERIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The Rangers, whose roster of Latin-American
players is appealing, appear to be the No. 1 candidate to
participate in the first regular-season series played in Puerto
Rico.
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Alderson, Major League Baseball's executive director of
baseball operations, acknowledged yesterday the possibility of
regular-season games being played this season in Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   Alderson, though, declined to identify the organizations being
discussed for such consideration. However, The Associated Press
reported the Rangers' three-game series scheduled for May 10-12
with the Chicago White Sox at Comiskey Park could be moved to San
Juan, according to unidentified officials in the commissioner's
office.
</P>
<P>
   Those officials consider the possibility of the series being
moved to Puerto Rico as a 50-50 proposition.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers president Tom Schieffer and White Sox general manager
Ron Schueler, though, lack any knowledge of Major League Baseball's
plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never heard anything about it,'' Schieffer said. ``No one
has contacted us about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The San Diego Padres scheduled their April 4 home opener against
the Colorado Rockies to be played in Monterrey, Mexico, and Major
League Baseball continues to consider a proposal that would allow
the Seattle Mariners to open the 2000 season in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Schieffer acknowledged why the Rangers might be viewed as an
attractive draw in Puerto Rico: Juan Gonzalez, the two-time
American League Most Valuable Player, seven-time All-Star Ivan
Rodriguez and infielder Luis Alicea, all Puerto Ricans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd certainly be glad to talk to people about it,'' Schieffer
said, ``but no one has asked us to do that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
