<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-REID-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS' DAVE REID NEVER GOES OUT OF STYLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ All you really need to know about Dave Reid is
he owns two 1979 Volkswagen Beetle convertibles.
</P>
<P>
   OK, maybe that's not all you need to know, but it's a good
start.
</P>
<P>
   Reid is a lot like his Beetles: simple, hard-working and
reliable. In many ways, he's the Volkswagen of NHL players.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the type of player who can give us strong skating and
physical, defensive play,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``I
don't even think it's necessary to score that many goals from that
position, at least not for us. What he gives us there is
consistency.''
</P>
<P>
   Reid's numbers certainly aren't Corvette-like. He has three
goals and seven assists and is even on his plus-minus rating. But
he has been in the lineup for 44 of 47 games, and he's not giving
Hitchcock any reason to take him out. That wasn't the case in
training camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had to prove himself to us all over again, and he's done
that,'' Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   Reid played in only five of the Stars' 16 playoff games last
season, sitting out primarily because of a nagging injury that
hampered his lower back and hips. Reid, 34, tried to play through
the pain, but he says he knew it effected his performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even when I wasn't playing, I was getting it worked on, and it
was killing me,'' Reid said. ``It just became something that
wouldn't allow me to even work out properly.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, doctors told him it would be a chronic problem that
could bother him for the rest of his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just told them, `No, it wouldn't be,' '' Reid said.
</P>
<P>
   Reid stayed away from weight lifting and concentrated on aerobic
activities for much of the summer; he came into training camp at
the lowest level of body fat he has been at in some time. That
allowed him to fend off the younger legs of Jason Botterill, 22,
and Jamie Wright, 22, two players who were competing with Reid for
a left-wing spot on the third or fourth line. Both Botterill and
Wright are with the Stars' minor-league affiliate, the Michigan
K-Wings, and Reid has also defended his territory against veterans
Dan Keczmer and Brent Severyn.
</P>
<P>
   But Reid knows with 35 games remaining in the regular season and
the most important games ahead in the playoffs, he has to be ready
to perform every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like it used to be, where you could have a little
slump or something,'' he said of a career in which he was a solid
lock as a lineup regular for the Boston Bruins and Toronto Maple
Leafs. ``Now, I can't afford to have two bad games, because I'll be
out of the lineup. And it's hard to prove yourself while you're
sitting in the press box.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock said he sees that motivation in Reid.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's living day to day, and that's the way he has to live,''
Hitchcock said. ``He's playing with more strength on the puck and
more jump; his recovery or reload time is better. He knows the
things he has to do to be a better player, and he's doing them.''
</P>
<P>
   Kind of the same way he's learning the simplistic beauty of the
inner workings of a Volkswagen.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to learn, and you have to adjust, and you have to go
forward,'' Reid said. ``I think I learned a lot from last year.
Now, I'm healthy, and I'm getting a chance to play, and I think
that's showing up. I do have more confidence in my game, I know
that even if I get taken out of the lineup, I still know I can
play. And that's a big step forward.''
STAYING FIT
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock worked the Stars out for 90 minutes on the ice
yesterday, part of the team's conditioning as they play one game in
a 10-day span. Hitchcock said he expects to have similar-length
workouts during the next week. The Stars typically work out on ice
for 45 to 60 minutes a day.
BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   Stars center Joe Nieuwendyk, who said he might rest his right
knee after recovering from tendinitis, went through the entire
workout. ``He just seems to get stronger,'' Hitchcock said. ``He
was one of our best players.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars have blown some third-period leads recently, but they
have been strong in protecting leads throughout the season. They
have only outscored teams 37-36 in the third period, but the Stars
are 22-1-4 when leading after two periods and 8-1-2 when tied after
two periods. They are 12-2 in one-goal games.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
