<SLUG> BC-BKW-BOSTONCOLLEGE-NOTREDAME-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BC NO MATCH FOR ND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; SOUTH BEND, Ind. _ From the moment the Voices of Faith gospel
group sang out their last round notes of ``The Star-Spangled
Banner'' before a crowd of 2,617 in Joyce Center, it was obvious
Boston College didn't have much of a prayer.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Notre Dame, the No. 6 women's basketball team in the
country, was playing too well to be stopped Wednesday night. Far
from it. Shooting just 38 percent, the Irish were stoppable at
virtually every tentative turn. Every sloppy pass. Every bad shot.
Or so it seemed.
</P>
<P>
   It's just that Boston College couldn't stop them. And so it was
that the No. 20 Eagles came out losers, 74-59, in a game that,
examined piece by piece, looked winnable. Until you looked at its
entirety.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have such balance,'' said BC coach Cathy Inglese. ``They
have kids who can drive to the outside, they've got three kids who
are a threat from the 3-point line, they've got the big one inside.
So even though they're having a bad shooting night, you couldn't
just sag everybody in on Riley. You had to be honest with all their
players.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley is center Ruth Riley, the team's leading scorer (17.8
points per game) and rebounder (9.2). She scored just 2 points in
the first half as the guards got the job done while she sat on the
bench in foul trouble. She got 16 in the second when it was her
turn to go to work.
</P>
<P>
   The Irish have that kind of team, with someone always ready to
step up. In the first half, it was the backcourt of Niele Ivey (13
points) and Danielle Green (8).
</P>
<P>
   ``It gave us a lot of confidence knowing Ruth was on the bench
and the guards were taking over the scoring,'' said Notre Dame
coach Muffet McGraw.
</P>
<P>
   Riley's 18 points ended up leading four Notre Dame players in
double figures, with Ivey (17), Danielle Green (14, plus 11
rebounds), and Sheila McMillen (13) all coming up big. For the
Eagles, Alissa Murphy had 20, while Whitney Steele and Brianne
Stepherson each added 12.
</P>
<P>
   Confidence was the magic word. From the first minutes, it was a
notably different Irish squad from the lackluster bunch that lost
to BC, 78-65, in their first meeting this season, at Conte Forum
Dec. 30. ``Last time we played Boston College, I played poorly, so
I just wanted to go out there and be intense,'' said Ivey. ``I came
into the game knowing I had to play better than last time.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, so did her teammates. After trading leads for the
first 10 minutes, Notre Dame began to pull away when Ivey hit her
third 3-pointer _ she had four by night's end _ to put the Irish
up, 21-16. After a BC 20-second timeout, Steele hit a layup to
bring the Eagles within 3, 21-18. But they got no closer as Notre
Dame edged forward quietly until an exclamatory 3-pointer by
McMillen three seconds before the buzzer put the Irish up by 10,
35-25, at the half.
</P>
<P>
   Amid an abundance of errant passes, juggled receptions, and
airballs, the story was told under the boards, where BC got
outrebounded, 13-4, offensively.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not getting many second shots, that was the big thing for
us,'' said Inglese.
</P>
<P>
   In their earlier meeting, BC outrebounded the Irish, 34-28,
largely on the strength of freshman Becky Gottstein's 16. This time
ND held her to three.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was our game plan,'' said McGraw.
</P>
<P>
   As the second half began, BC cut the lead to 6, 37-31, with a
steal and driving layup by Murphy. Three-pointers by Ivey and
McMillen helped get the Irish lead up to 16 with 15:36 remaining
before Stepherson answered with a three. That started a 12-point
Eagle run as Notre Dame went without a basket for almost six
minutes and its lead shrank to 4, 50-46, with nine minutes left.
But the Eagles ran out of steam, and ND got away.
</P>
</TEXT>
