<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRINCIPAL-ATTACKED-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARENTS, SCHOOL OFFICIALS SOUGHT IN WAKE OF ATTACK ON PRINCIPAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY LISA VAN PROYEN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Concerned parents and school administrators have
met with police at Burton Street Elementary School in hopes of
easing tensions there, after the principal was beaten in what
detectives suspect was a hate crime.
</P>
<P>
   The attack on Principal Norman G. Bernstein on Monday at the
school has highlighted problems between him and some parents who
object to his management style and have petitioned to remove him
from the campus.
</P>
<P>
   Administrators and parents alike said they believe the attack
was not tied to tensions on the campus, where Bernstein has been
principal for seven years. He has said he plans to return to the
school once he recovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel so sorry,'' said Lorena Aguilar, whose son is among
750 students at the campus.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just want things to cool down,'' said Socorro Serrano, a
school district spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Bernstein, 65, was beaten into unconsciousness in front of the
school by two men who told him, ``We don't want you here anymore,
principal. Do you understand that, white principal?''
</P>
<P>
   Police said they have no suspects in the crime, which they are
investigating as racially motivated. Bernstein did not see the
attackers clearly enough to provide police with a description.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crime is a serious crime and we're going to investigate it
to its fullest extent. But we need witnesses,'' said Sean Kane,
commanding officer of the Los Angeles Police Department's Van Nuys
Division.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators stepped up security at the campus and asked anyone
with information to call them at (818) 756-8371 or (818) 756-8346
after hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm stunned,'' said Los Angeles County Supervisor Zev
Yaroslavsky, whose district includes Panorama City.
</P>
<P>
   Yaroslavsky said he will ask his colleagues to issue a $25,000
reward for information leading to the arrest and conviction of
those involved in the surprise attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``The community needs to come together to make a clear and
united voice against hate crimes,'' he said during a news
conference at the school. ``We will not tolerate any kind of
violence against any of our educators.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day, crisis counselors consoled children, some of
whom wrote ``get well'' cards to their principal.
</P>
<P>
   The mugging occurred about 6:30 a.m. Monday as the principal
parked his car in front of the school to report to work at 8111
Calhoun Ave., police said. When he got out of his car, he was
assaulted by two men.
</P>
<P>
   Bernstein said in an interview that he tried to fight off the
attackers, but one held a sharp object to his neck, nicking him and
then knocking him unconscious.
</P>
<P>
   The violent confrontation left school staffers and parents alike
baffled about how this could happen at their historically safe
campus, which opened eight years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm worried about my child's security here and what's going to
happen,'' said one parent, Gloria Lopez.
</P>
<P>
   Nine-year-old Edith Orozco said she also wants answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel sad. I like him. He helped me in third grade when I
fell down and he picked me up,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles school board member Julie Korenstein met with
faculty members and parents to discuss the attack and the morale on
campus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very distraught. I feel badly about it,'' said Korenstein,
whose district includes Panorama City. ``My hope is to be able to
sit down and resolve the issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Issues that parents have raised about Bernstein include: the
dismantling of bilingual education because of Proposition 227; the
year-round schedule; and how the principal manages his teachers and
staff.
</P>
<P>
   School administrators postponed a meeting scheduled for today
with parents that was called to discuss the transitioning of
students to the English immersion classes.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting was postponed to avoid further tensions and to allow
some time for people to calm down, Serrano said.
</P>
<P>
   One teacher, who declined to be identified, voiced support for
Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   ``He does listen to the parents, and he's doing the best job he
can,'' she said. ``If they're upset with the principal, they should
go through the district meetings.''
</P>
<P>
   John Liechty, the Los Angeles Unified School District's
assistant superintendent of instruction assigned to the San
Fernando Valley, said he is aware of parental concerns with
Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been some concerns brought forward by some
parents,'' he said, declining to provide more details.
</P>
<P>
   One parent, Sandra Velasquez, disagreed with the school going to
a year-round calendar, so she pulled her children, ages 7 and 10,
out of Burton Elementary and sent them to a traditional calendar
school in September.
</P>
<P>
   The attack still rattled her.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has always been quiet here,'' she said. ``This is very
weird this is going on.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
