<HEADER>
A1284 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCCARTHY-COLUMN-LADN     02-04 0920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTHY-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINES PAST, PRESENT SAY `SEMPER FI'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
( Dennis McCarthy is a columnist at the Los Angeles Daily News.) 
BY DENNIS MCCARTHY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMP PENDLETON &UR; ,  &LR; Calif. _ The young Marine sergeant stood at
attention, anxious for his turn to say thank you to a World War II
legend _ 80-year-old Medal of Honor recipient Mitchell Paige.
</P>
<P>
   Sgt. Jason Neale had just been named Marine of the Year by his
commanding officer in the 1st Marine Division at Camp Pendleton _
judged the best and brightest young Marine in his outfit. But right
now, he looked more like a star-struck kid waiting to ask John
Wayne for an autograph.
</P>
<P>
   His eyes never strayed from the shiny, beautiful medal hanging
from Paige's neck _ the highest honor this country bestows for
bravery.
</P>
<P>
   Neale knew exactly why this man had been awarded that coveted
medal by President Franklin D. Roosevelt. How as a young platoon
sergeant on Guadalcanal in the Pacific theater in October 1942,
Paige's machine-gun platoon repelled wave after wave of enemy
soldiers trying to overtake its hilltop position.
</P>
<P>
   How when reinforcements finally arrived the next day, they found
Paige's whole platoon either dead or severely wounded. Only Paige
was still able to fight _ moving from machine gun to machine gun,
firing from the hip until there were no more enemies left to
charge.
</P>
<P>
   His bravery is legendary in the Marine Corps, and now here he
was in person with hundreds of other retired Marines from past wars
and campaigns, celebrating the 1st Marine Division's 58th
anniversary this week at Camp Pendleton.
</P>
<P>
   Today's Marines getting a chance to pay their respects to
yesterday's.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sir, this is a great honor to meet you,'' Neale said, saluting
Paige. ``I'm a machine gunner too, sir.''
</P>
<P>
   Paige smiled and stuck out his hand to congratulate Neale for
being named Marine of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good luck, son,'' Paige said, as another wave of young Marines
moved in to salute and shake the hand of a real fighting legend.
</P>
<P>
   Off to the side, Lou Weiner of Tarzana, who served with a
howitzer unit of the 105th on Guadalcanal, stood watching the scene
with Maj. Gen. Michael Hagee, the division's commanding general.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at them,'' Hagee said. ``These young Marines have read
about the battles these men fought for this country, but to talk to
them and see them in person, well, it brings the history alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``You men are the reason we're here today,'' the general said,
turning to Weiner and a handful of other old Marines, including Abe
Goldberg, the oldest original member of the 1st Division at 88.
</P>
<P>
   The men smile, their chests puffed out with pride. After all
these years, it was wonderful to hear words like that, wonderful to
feel the respect and admiration of today's Marines who are young
enough to be their grandkids.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is sir this, sir that,'' Weiner said, laughing.
``They sir you to pieces. I love it.''
</P>
<P>
   Half an hour later, the men were moving slowly through a chow
line in the mess hall, looking at a selection of food none of them
ever enjoyed as Marines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you one thing, they sure eat a heck of a lot better
than we ever did,'' Weiner said as a young female Marine, Pvt.
Alison Kellam, laughed.
</P>
<P>
   That's another thing yesterday's Marines never had, either _
women in the ranks.
</P>
<P>
   ``One woman Marine told me she joined because she hated her
father and mother, and wanted to get away from home,'' said Korean
War vet Kevin Burns, adding with a laugh: ``After being in the
Marines four months, she said she now loved her father and mother,
and her home. She said the Marines taught her the importance of
discipline.''
</P>
<P>
   Kellam, who has been in the Marines since April 1998, agreed.
``My whole life and values have changed,'' she said. ``I've got
more structure to my life, and a lot more confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   An hour later, yesterday's Marines were on a bus to witness
another thing that has changed significantly since their day _
weaponry and firepower.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lord, would I have loved to have this thing in Korea,'' said
Vince Masascio, holding a grenade launcher. ``All we had were M-1
rifles, carbines, .45s and a lot of hand grenades.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, Ed Sundberg of Oxnard looked over some mortar launchers.
``When we landed at Guadalcanal in that first wave, I had 12
grenades strapped to my chest, a rifle, three bandoleers of
ammunition and a backpack with C rations in it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was rainy, wet and miserable. We spent the first few days
burying the dead who washed ashore. The only food we had after the
C rations ran out was from the fish heads and rice we captured from
the Japanese.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rice was full of maggots. When you're starving, you begin
to look at them as a source of protein, not maggots.''
</P>
<P>
   A couple of the young Marines looked at each other and made
faces. Eating maggots to survive? Ugh!
</P>
<P>
   ``It took me more than 47 years to talk about these things, and
see my old Marine buddies again,'' Sundberg said. ``Seven years
ago, I couldn't tell you what I'm saying now.''
</P>
<P>
   A group of young Marines in a foxhole watch as Sundberg and a
couple of other old Marines walk across a dirt road to see a
howitzer firepower display.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, sometimes we get to complaining about things,'' one
of them said. ``Then we think about the old-timers and what they
went through, and we realize we've got nothing to complain about.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
