<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLIPPERS TO SIGN DOUGLAS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The last domino finally has fallen and will
deliver crusty veteran point guard Sherman Douglas to the Clippers
in 24 hours or less.
</P>
<P>
   With the NBA's roster deadline dropping today at 3 p.m., PST,
the team is expected to sign the New Jersey free agent to a
contract worth $2-$2.5 million this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The object of a team sport,'' said first-year coach Chris
Ford, ``is to keep bringing in people who are going to help the
team. If it comes to fruition, we went out and got the best we
could.''
</P>
<P>
   Douglas, the Clippers' target in an earlier bid to ``upgrade''
their point-guard stable, was seeking to claim all of the team's
$3.7 million salary-cap bounty during discussions last month.
</P>
<P>
   But the nine-year vet also was open to signing with his hometown
Wizards if they and their big-ticket free agent, Rod Strickland,
ended a rocky relationship. While Douglas waited, the Clippers
re-signed the incumbent, Darrick Martin, to a one-year deal.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Elgin Baylor, the Clippers' vice president of
basketball operations, kept Douglas, who averaged 8 points and 4
assists as a backup for the Nets last season as the ace up his
sleeve.
</P>
<P>
   When Strickland re-signed with the Wizards on Wednesday,
Douglas-to-the-Clippers was back on.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the deal goes through,'' Ford said, ``hopefully we can have
him at practice tomorrow (today).''
</P>
<P>
   Ford said he has spoken to Martin and Pooh Richardson, his
current backup, about making room for Douglas.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said they understood,'' Ford said. ``I just wanted to be
honest with them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
