</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXAS-HIGH-SCHOOL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS HIGH SCHOOL HAS 7 DIVISION I SIGNEES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ANDY FRIEDLANDER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Justin Faust never played a down of football
in his senior year at Arlington Lamar High, tearing up his knee
before the opening game. As a junior, he was a part-time player,
sharing the featured running back role with Mohammed Shittu and
running the ball only 60 times all season.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, the 6-foot, 195-pounder sat down at a table in the
Lamar library and signed a letter of intent to play major college
football.
</P>
<P>
   ``What that tells me,'' said Faust, who will join the Stanford
Cardinal in the fall, ``is that there's no question about Lamar's
reputation for turning out talent. Our reputation is unmatched
anywhere. This is Tailback High.''
</P>
<P>
   And Defensive Lineman High and Defensive Back High, and about
any other position, too. The Vikings, who won their fourth
consecutive district championship last season (including a
co-championship with Martin in 1996), now have taken the lead in
the college recruiting race as well.
</P>
<P>
   At a mass signing ceremony yesterday morning, 13 Vikings signed
letters of intent to play college football, seven of them with
Division I schools. That beats the 11 who signed from state Class
5A Division I champion Duncanville, and matched Duncanville's seven
Division I signees. And Lamar will get an eighth player in the I-A
ranks when defensive lineman Nick Losada signs. He already has
received an appointment to the Air Force Academy but is waiting on
possible opportunities at Clemson and Tulane.
</P>
<P>
   Those numbers give Lamar its biggest class of
scholarship-winners ever, one that ranks not only among the area
leaders, but the national leaders as well. The list includes one of
America's highest-profile recruits, defensive tackle Cedric
Hilliard (Notre Dame), as well as star running back Tommicus
Walker, a TCU signee and the younger brother of Nebraska standout
Joe Walker.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our biggest class, but it isn't news,'' coach Eddy
Peach said. ``We had 36 kids playing college football last year.
This has been a trend for years.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Hilliard: ``I think coaches from in and out of state know
where to come to find good ballplayers. I mean, we've had something
good going on here for a while, but a group like this will probably
help get Lamar players even more exposure.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not as if Lamar players need it.
</P>
<P>
   This year, several players required little to no sales pitch to
colleges, including Hilliard, Walker and Faust, among others. But
not everyone was in that boat. Linebacker John Paul Mulligan, for
example, put together a highlight tape and sent it to schools
around the country before eventually signing with Texas
A&AMP;M-Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not coach's job to get you a scholarship,'' Mulligan
said. ``He'll tell the colleges about you and speak up for you. But
he's a football coach, not a salesman.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, sometimes those jobs are one and the same. Ray
Biery III, father of wide receiver Ray Biery IV, said Peach was
instrumental in helping his son earn a scholarship to Missouri
Southern.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our situation, we kind of worked together with him,'' Ray
III said. ``We kept in touch and bounced ideas off each other.
Coach Peach is well connected and well respected by college
coaches, and we were in touch with him all the time trying to get
things going for Ray.''
</P>
<P>
   And the result was good news on signing day for Biery and 12 of
his teammates. Of course, there will be more to come, this year and
in future seasons.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the hottest prospect on next year's Vikings will be
Reggie Harrell, a 6-foot-4, 210-pound wide receiver-defensive back
who already has recruiters drooling over his size and speed. After
spending much of last season on the bench behind Lamar's sparkling
seniors, Harrell will get the chance to win his scholarship in the
fall.
</P>
<P>
   And the scouts will be there to see it. Count on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most recruiters you talk to are already familiar with Lamar
and the program here,'' said defensive back Justin Browne, who
signed with North Carolina. ``I'm sure seeing a group like this
coming out this year will make people want to make sure they make a
stop here next year to see what's coming up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
