<SLUG> BC-SUPERIOR-EARNINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKER OF WHEELS ON ROLL AFTER SETBACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY GREGORY J. WILCOX  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Wheel manufacturer Superior Industries
International Inc. said Wednesday that it has rebounded from last
summer's labor strife at General Motors Corp. as fourth-quarter
earnings and sales hit record levels.
</P>
<P>
   For the quarter, Superior earned $19.55 million, equal to 71
cents a share, an increase of 25 percent from the prior year's
period, on sales of $152.7 million. In the 1997 fourth quarter,
Superior earned $15.65 million, or 56 cents a share, on sales of
$150.9 million.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterly earnings exceeded analysts' expectations by almost 11
percent, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Superior, which makes original equipment aluminum wheels for
leading domestic and foreign car and truck companies, has secured a
number of significant supply contracts that helped boost
fourth-quarter results and could drive growth through 1999. They
include wheels for Ford Motor Co.'s Windstar and General Motors
Corp.'s new GMT800 full-size and light-truck program, which is
considered that company's most significant vehicle introduction in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were real pleased with the quarter and those (contracts
brought) major increases for sure,'' said R. Jeffrey Ornstein,
Superior's vice president and chief financial officer.
</P>
<P>
   The company also makes accessory products for the national
automotive aftermarket. It has plants in Van Nuys, Mexico, Europe,
Kansas and Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   For the year, Superior earned $52.32 million, or $1.88 per
share, compared with income of $55.39 million, or $1.96, in 1997.
Sales in 1998 totaled $539.4 million vs. $549.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   The dip reflects the impact of the GM strike on second- and
third-quarter performance. During the strike, Superior idled 200 of
the 1,000 workers at its Van Nuys plant and shut operations at its
plants in Kansas and Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, GM accounted for about 47 percent of Superior's
sales.
</P>
<P>
   Superior's stock, traded on the New York Stock Exchange, closed
Wednesday at $27.375, down $1.125, a slide of 3.95 percent.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
