<SLUG> BC-TEKELEC-SHARES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEKELEC IN MARKET'S WOODSHED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY BEN SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALABASAS -- The market pounded telecommunications equipment
maker Tekelec on Wednesday, the day after the company missed
analysts' fourth-quarter earnings estimates by more than 15
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Shares dropped $4.6875, or 23.44 percent, to close at $15.3125.
More than 19 million shares traded hands, or about 31 times the
30-day average trading volume in the company, which makes network
switching equipment and diagnostic tools.
</P>
<P>
   After the markets closed Tuesday, Tekelec reported
fourth-quarter income of 16 cents per share, compared with the 19
cents per share anticipated by a group of analysts surveyed by
First Call Corp.
</P>
<P>
   In a conference call after the release of its numbers, Tekelec
officials blamed the shortfall in the quarter on failure of several
anticipated sales contracts to close on time. For the year,
however, the company reported 59 cents per diluted share, nearly
meeting the First Call estimate of 60 cents per share.
</P>
<P>
   An announcement that Tekelec had won a deal to supply US West
with equipment worth $5 &UR;  &LR; million to $6 &UR;  &LR; million may have tempered
the sell-off. At one point in early trading, the stock was down by
more than $6, or about 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Tekelec officials were unavailable for comment Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Wednesday that Tekelec deserved a drubbing but
predicted that the shares will likely return to the $20-plus range
if it meets coming estimates.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're in the Wall Street doghouse,'' said analyst Tim
Savageaux at Volpe Brown Whelan. ``They missed the quarter, and
people were disappointed with that. But there were several rays of
light.''
</P>
<P>
   Savageaux said he has cut his 12-month target price on Tekelec
shares from $30 to $22 because he expects investors will balk at
paying a price-to-earnings premium for the stock until it meets
estimates for a few quarters.
</P>
<P>
   Having struggled for market share throughout the 1990s,
supplying mostly smaller and newcomer telecom operators, Tekelec
emerged last year as a recognized if still relatively minor
supplier to blue-chip firms. That was highlighted in October when
the company landed a contract to sell Sprint between $4 &UR;  &LR; million to
$5 &UR;  &LR; million worth of switching equipment, then again with the US
West deal.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say they expect the company to gain further recognition
and business from big players this year.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
