<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-IOWA-STATE-TEXAS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IOWA STATE PROGRAM ATTRACTS QB FROM FORT WORTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STACY FEDUCIA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Fort Worth Dunbar High School quarterback
Ronald Veal spent a summer in throwing camps, honing his arm,
working with receivers, dreaming of leading the Wildcats to the
District 9-4A championship, then the playoffs, then college ...
</P>
<P>
   Then he broke his collarbone in a Week 6 game against Trimble
Tech and his season ended.
</P>
<P>
   Veal (6-foot-2, 217 pounds) found himself on the sideline as the
Wildcats lost two of their final four games and finished 7-3 and
out of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went into a state of depression,'' Veal said. ``I was afraid
I wouldn't get a chance to show anybody what I could do. I was sick
to my stomach that I couldn't be out on the field, helping my
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Veal's fears were put to rest yesterday when he signed a
national letter of intent, accepting a scholarship from Iowa State.
His teammate, tight end Erron Matthews, signed with the Cyclones as
well, bringing Dunbar's total to five Division I signees this
season.
</P>
<P>
   A total of 20 football players from Fort Worth schools signed
letters of intent yesterday in ceremonies at six schools.
</P>
<P>
   Veal's signing capped a four-year journey from an expelled
freshman attending alternative school to an accomplished senior
attending a university known for its psychology program, his major
of choice.
</P>
<P>
   His career at Dunbar started with an altercation with a teammate
about Veal's No. 4 jersey _ the same jersey number he will wear at
Iowa State. The fight resulted in Veal's expulsion and he finished
the season at an alternative school.
</P>
<P>
   A dislocated shoulder ended Veal's sophomore season after the
third game. He moved from linebacker to quarterback his junior
year, and through five games that season, Veal had rushed 105 times
for 587 yards with five touchdowns. He had also completed 74 of 163
passes for 1,115 yards with 11 touchdowns and five interceptions _
and earned second-team all-district honors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't worried about him not getting recruited _ it would
have been different if it had been a knee or something like that,''
Dunbar coach Bob Jones said. ``More than anything else, he knew it
hurt our chances at getting to the playoffs. I would've loved to
have lined up against anybody with him at full strength. That's why
Iowa State knows they're getting a steal.''
</P>
<P>
   Recruited as a running back, Veal knew that Iowa State would be
the place for him when he arrived in Ames and it felt like ``a
family reunion.'' The prospective psychology and philosophy
double-major was given the opportunity to meet with a distinguished
member of the Iowa State psychology faculty.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had a room full of cabinets of studies they had done for
television, editorials, journals,'' Veal said. ``I only had an hour
and a half with him, but it went by so fast. I even brought home
some of the studies to read on the plane.''
</P>
<P>
   Though he could start the season third on the depth chart, Veal
aspires to get his doctorate in psychology, rather than further his
football career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to set my focus on going to the NFL because I
know how fleeting this can be,'' Veal said. ``My high school career
hasn't been a whole bed of roses. I've had enough setbacks that I
know not to take things for granted.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
