<HEADER>
A1310 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-ROCKETS-ROBERTS-H     02-04 0918
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-ROBERTS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
He will not need a snow-cone head of hair. A record for tattoos
will be unnecessary. His large body won't be pierced all over.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stanley Roberts does not need to accessorize to be noticed.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking a big man to step in for the injured Antoine Carr, the
Rockets landed one of the biggest. Rather than join the pursuit of
free-agent free spirit Dennis Rodman, the Rockets instead came to
terms with Roberts on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts is listed at 7-0 and 290 pounds, but estimates have him
weighing closer to 320. Although he has had injury problems during
his seven-year career, he played in 74 games last season, averaging
6.2 points and 4.2 rebounds for the Minnesota Timberwolves.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts is expected to join the Rockets in Los Angeles today or
Friday but is not expected to play against the Lakers in the season
opener Friday or against the Golden State Warriors on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rockets hailed his addition as a short-term solution to
the void left by Carr's injury and a long-term answer for their
almost annual search for a quality, wide-bodied backup for Hakeem
Olajuwon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need another big man,'' Rockets coach Rudy Tomjanovich
said. ``Stanley Roberts is a very talented player. If he can do
what we think he can do, what we have seen him do, he'll be an
asset to this team.''
</P>
<P>
   That is not all that is expected, however. Olajuwon, who has
long preferred to have a weightier backup to wear down opposing
centers, was delighted with the news. But he also planned to put
Roberts to work on the training routine Olajuwon has used to
recapture the leg strength he seemed to have lost last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a great addition,'' Olajuwon said. ``I think a player
like Stanley Roberts has tremendous potential. For him to come to
our team with the right players around him that work together will
increase his work ethic. I think he'll have a big role to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want him to complement. Once he comes to the team,
we'll work with him on a strict diet, exercise, stretching, where
he has a new life that can bring out his potential. He has
tremendous potential. When he does this, he will realize this
potential.''
</P>
<P>
   Although most of the Rockets players said they would not have
objected had the team chosen to bring in Rodman, Olajuwon was not
sure Rodman could have fit in as easily as he believes Roberts
will.
</P>
<P>
   ``The team chemistry, everything so far, has worked,'' Olajuwon
said. ``The team and the organization would be very skeptical to
bring that risk of distracting chemistry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think it (the pursuit of Rodman) was serious. Stanley
Roberts is the right move.''
</P>
<P>
   Forward Charles Barkley said he was not concerned with how well
Roberts fits in or Rodman might have, as long as Roberts is ready
to play and can handle more game time when the compressed schedule
tests the Rockets' depth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't worry about chemistry,'' Barkley said. ``I worry about
guys playing well. Dennis is a very good player. We need guys to
play minutes. With the schedule, playing games back-to-back, we
need guys who we can plug in. Obviously, our center is Hakeem. We
need him (Roberts) just to play a couple minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care who we bring in as long as they're ready to play.
Dennis is a good player. Stanley's a good player. That's something
for you guys (the media) to sit around and argue about.''
</P>
<P>
   Roberts, who turns 29 on Sunday, could be considered a different
sort of gamble, given his conditioning problems throughout his
career. But Olajuwon was not the only Rockets player who said he
believed that weighty issue would successfully be addressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guarantee if he comes here, he's going to be dedicated, and
he's going to give his all,'' forward Eddie Johnson said. ``If he
doesn't, he's going to hear from me, and he's going to hear from
other guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was among the most supportive of the idea of bringing in
Rodman, praising him Wednesday as a winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm at the point I just want to win championships,'' Johnson
said. ``All I know, when that guy gets on the floor, no one
outplays him.''
</P>
<P>
   But despite feeling that way about the player the Rockets did
not seriously pursue, Johnson said Roberts would provide the sort
of big man the team lacked last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always good to have a big body,'' Johnson said. ``Stanley
has shown an ability to be a force in the middle. We just need big
bodies.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the ability to have a guy like that, and when Antoine
comes back from his surgery, and our good young guys in Othella
(Harrington) and Pig Miller, we've got some big guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Roberts has long been recognized as more than large. With a good
shooting touch and a combination of post moves, he averaged 10.4
points as a Magic rookie and 11.3 in his second season with the
Clippers. That season, the Clippers pushed the Rockets to a fifth
game in a playoff series, with Roberts averaging 11.4 points and
8.2 rebounds against Olajuwon.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts was so well thought of then that he was among the names
mentioned in trade rumors involving Olajuwon, a coincidence that
six years later Olajuwon found amusing, if irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were talking about trading me for a lot of people,''
Olajuwon said. ``Right now, we're thinking about playing together.
I'm looking forward to having him on the team. He's welcome. I
think he can really help us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
