<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 02:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1315 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-WAGNER-HNS     02-04 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-WAGNER-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
Billy Wagner often recalls the day the football coach at Ferrum
(Va.) College told him to forget about that sport and concentrate
on baseball.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although Wagner was gifted at both sports, it was the best
career advice he ever received.
</P>
<P>
   That advice paid off Wednesday to the tune of $10.3 million,
which is how much the Astros will pay Wagner over the next three
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The 27-year-old closer blessed with a lightning bolt for a left
arm will make $2.1 million in 1999, $3.2 million in 2000 and $5
million in 2001. The deal could be worth more in the second and
third years if Wagner reaches certain incentives.
</P>
<P>
   By reaching an agreement, Wagner and the Astros avoided an
arbitration hearing, which was set for Feb. 17.
</P>
<P>
   Although the contract represents a significant salary boost for
Wagner, who made $280,000 last season, he seemed more pleased to
have the security of a long-term contract. Wagner saw his career _
not to mention his life _ flash before his eyes last July when he
was struck in the head by a batted ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``This sure makes it a lot easier to go out there and take those
line drives,'' Wagner joked. ``One minute you're looking at death,
and the next minute you're looking at a three-year deal. This is
just an unbelievable day for me and my family. It's a great
occasion, and I'm glad I'm going to be here for another three
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite having just two full seasons in the majors, Wagner has
made his mark in Houston and around the league. He has 62 career
saves, including 30 last season _ the third-highest single-season
total in franchise history.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Wagner set a major-league record by averaging 14.4
strikeouts per nine innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Billy's one of the premier relievers, and he does it in a
dramatic way,'' Astros owner Drayton McLane Jr. said. ``That's what
people liked about Nolan Ryan and some of the other strong
pitchers. People get excited in the ninth inning when Billy comes
in to close a game.''
</P>
<P>
   Wagner converted 30 of 35 save opportunities in 1998, including
a stretch of 19 in arow.
</P>
<P>
   He realizes expectations might be greater now that his salary
has gone up, but Wagner said he intends to approach his job the
same way he always has.
</P>
<P>
   ``The money is not going to change me,'' Wagner said. ``Me and
my wife (Sarah) are simple people. I'm sure that with a higher
price tag, the criticism is going to come along with it. But that
was no different than when I was getting paid $280,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I blow a save (now), what are they going to say? `You stink
worse.' I'm not worried about that. I'm just going to do my job the
best way I know how.''
</P>
<P>
   Astros general manager Gerry Hunsicker had been discussing a
multiyear deal with Wagner's agent since the end of the 1998
season. A one-year agreement seemed unlikely after the two sides
exchanged numbers through the arbitration process. The Astros filed
at $2 million compared to Wagner's $3.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``This deal benefits both sides because the arbitration process
_ as much as anything else in our game _ can create a negative
relationship,'' Hunsicker said. ``Any time you can avoid a hearing,
that's in the best interest of everyone involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Billy Wagner has emerged as one of the best closers in all of
baseball, and you can't win a championship without a reliable
closer. More important than that, this team is built around
character, and Billy certainly exemplifies that on and off the
field.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunsicker, who is one of the best talent evaluators in baseball,
seldom falls far from the mark in his assessments of players.
</P>
<P>
   But he was one of 11 baseball executives who missed the boat on
Wagner in the 1993 draft. Hunsicker, who was working for the New
York Mets at the time, used his No. 1 pick on righthander Kirk
Presley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't make one of the brightest decisions of my career when
I bypassed a young pitcher out of Ferrum College and chose another
(pitcher) who never got out of (Class) A ball,'' Hunsicker said.
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Ricky Gutierrez is the only remaining
arbitration-eligible player on the Astros' docket. The two sides
are concentrating on a one-year deal, and they were $725,000 apart
at the time arbitration figures were exchanged.
</P>
<P>
   So far, both sides seem to be sticking to their guns. Hunsicker
said, ``I'm hopeful that we can avoid a hearing with Ricky and make
it a clean sweep.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
