</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBW-SOFTBALL-PITCHER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PITCHER DELIVERS LIVELY PERSONALITY AND ARM TO TEXAS-ARLINGTON
SOFTBALL TEAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DARRIN SCHEID 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Texas-Arlington softball player Cassie Brand
walks the line between excited and bizarre each time she steps
inside the pitching circle.
</P>
<P>
   Brand said she's not silly-hyper-goofy. There is no jumping
around and acting foolish simply to draw attention.
</P>
<P>
   It's more like focused-talkative.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to communicate,'' Brand said. ``It's important that, no
matter what the situation is, everybody is pumped up. It keeps
everybody in the game. I want other teams to know we're not going
to let down.''
</P>
<P>
   Brand mixes her lively personality with a exceptional right arm,
said UTA third-year coach Debbie Nichols-Hedrick.
</P>
<P>
   After one trip to South Mountain Community College in Phoenix to
watch Brand pitch, Nichols-Hedrick said Brand could be vital to the
1999 Mavericks. When UTA opens the season at noon Sunday against
Texas at Allan Saxe Field, Brand will take her pitching talent _
and other habits _ to the Division I level.
</P>
<P>
   Nichols-Hedrick has no doubt it will be a smooth, chatter-filled
transition.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has a lot of hop on the mound, a lot of personality,''
Nichols-Hedrick said. ``She has charisma, and that kind of
excitement is something we need to bring into this program. She
also has great movement on her pitches, and she throws very hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Brand, a 5-foot-9 native of Chandler, Ariz., never expected to
be a highly recruited player out of junior college. That's because
she was sought with little intensity out of high school.
</P>
<P>
   But daily work with junior-college coach J.J. Johnson and
pitching coach Dallas Kullman at South Mountain expanded her
talents.
</P>
<P>
   In the past two years, Brand said she has developed a fastball,
screwball, changeup, rise, off-speed rise and drop pitch. She was
selected first-team, All-Southwest Region her freshman year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I owe a lot to Coach Kullman,'' Brand said. ``I think he saw a
lot of potential in me that I didn't see as a senior in high
school. He taught me to move the ball around. I would struggle
every single day, go home and cry and come back the next day and
work on it all over again.''
</P>
<P>
   Her sophomore year showed even more improvement.
</P>
<P>
   Brand was selected to the All-America team of the National
Junior College Athletic Association. She was one of 14 players from
the United States invited to compete in the National Junior College
Canada Cup last summer. Before she got to South Mountain, the
school had won three of its previous 60 games.
</P>
<P>
   In the past two years, South Mountain went 31-16.
</P>
<P>
   Brand said she signed with UTA because she has relatives in
Arlington. She also wanted to play for Nichols-Hedrick, the former
All-America pitcher from Louisiana Tech.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the right decision, and I feel good about our team,''
Brand said. ``Whether I'm pitching or not, I'm just excited to be
getting this season started.''
</P>
<P>
   With Brand on the mound, the team is able to move 1998 pitcher
Andrea Becker to third base along with Angela Perry,
Nichols-Hedrick said. An injury to Laura Lewis means Elizabeth
Harsma will move from second base to shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   Sherri Wardlow will take over at second. Nichols-Hedrick said
the other starting positions will be determined later.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of my goals is to have a team that hustles from start to
finish,'' Nichols-Hedrick said. ``That's what I have liked in
practice so far.''
</P>
</TEXT>
