<HEADER>
A1352 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WWW.MORTGAGE.REFINANC     02-04 1450
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WWW.MORTGAGE.REFINANCE.COM-WORTH-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFINANCE YOUR HOME VIA THE INTERNET  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Personal-Finance Editors)   (This helpful 1,175-word ``separate buy'' personal-finance is from
the January issue of ``WORTH'' magazine. To publish this article,
it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's sales
representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES.
If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us
at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been filed into the ``f'' financial
news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``l'' lifestyle news
files.)  
  
 By SCOTT BURNS  
 c.1999 Worth Magazine  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For most American borrowers _ which is to say most American
homeowners _ down is up.
</P>
<P>
   However, the financial markets perform in the coming year, it's
very likely that the biggest financial opportunity for U.S.
consumers in 1999 will be the refinancing of their homes via the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The math explains why mortgage lenders and brokers are swamped
with applications. The rate on a refinanced mortgage is likely to
be at least 160 basis points (1.6 percentage points) lower than the
original mortgage rate, approximately the yield on the stocks in
the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 Stock Index.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, the principal amount of the typical home mortgage
equals about two years' worth of the owner's income. Closing costs
average about 2 percent of the face value of the mortgage, or about
two weeks' salary.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, refinancing a mortgage is like investing two weeks' salary
to collect the dividends on a portfolio worth more than two years'
salary _ with no risk.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, a refinancing is as good as a salary increase for
most borrowers. Maybe better. While the major benefits-consulting
firms were forecasting 4.5 percent raises for 1999 only a few
months ago, economic angst may dampen that figure.
</P>
<P>
   But millions of homeowners will be able to increase their
spending power by more than 3 percent by refinancing _ even more if
they roll consumer debt into the new loan.
</P>
<P>
   Borrowers still have to deal with lenders, alas, and their
endless and intrusive requests for information. But at least the
Net brings some welcome anonymity to the seven-step process,
described below:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCOUTING THE MARKET &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Before the Internet, the mortgage market consisted of whatever
the local lender or broker had to offer. But the Web allows
consumers to shop among mortgage lenders, comparing rates, fees,
maturities, and restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   A good place to start is the Federal Reserve site
(www.bog.frb.fed.us/releases). Download the ``historical data''
version of release H.15 to see if rates have risen or fallen in
recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Median home prices in cities across the country are available
through the ``NAR Press Releases'' link at www.realtimes.com.
Real-estate-information publisher HSH (www.hsh.com) features a
three-year graph of typical mortgage rates, a collection of
calculators, and a regularly updated report on average rates.
</P>
<P>
   The best way to compare what specific lenders are offering is
through the Web sites of mortgage brokers, most of which do
business with several lenders around the country.
</P>
<P>
   Among the most active brokers are HomeShark (www.homeshark.com),
E-Loan (www.eloan.com), and QuickenMortgage
(www.quickenmortgage.com).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CHECKING CREDIT &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Mortgage rates depend largely on the borrower's credit rating.
Quick credit tests can be found at www.mortgage-net.com and
www.hsh.com. And consumers can obtain a copy of their credit report
from www.creditreport-net.com.
</P>
<P>
   I suggest taking the test and foregoing the report: One of the
markdowns in credit scoring systems is the number of credit
inquiries in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CHOOSING THE MORTGAGE YOU WANT &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   A generation ago, home mortgages came in one flavor: 30 years,
fixed rate. Now maturities on fixed-rate loans range from 15 to 30,
and rates can be fixed or vary according to changes in one of three
common indexes.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, there are balloon notes payable in three, five, or
seven years and adjustable thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   The mortgage world is further subdivided into ``conforming''
loans (which carry principal amounts of $227,150 or less and are
eligible to be pooled and turned into tradable securities) and
``jumbo,'' or nonconforming, loans (which carry higher principal
amounts and interest rates).
</P>
<P>
   These days, fixed-rate mortgages have it all over
adjustable-rate mortgages. Adjustable-rate borrowers, after a
brief, low-rate introductory period, pay about 7.46 percent at a
time when fixed-rate borrowers are paying 6.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The new combination instruments also look pretty dubious right
about now, so homeowners should spend most of their search
comparing 15- and 30-year fixed-rate loans.
</P>
<P>
   Borrowers can shorten the terms by increasing the amount they
pay each month _ an idea popularized by Marc Eisenson in his book,
``The Banker's Secret,'' which can be ordered at
www.goodadvicepress.com.
</P>
<P>
   But most people hear about a money-grubbing variant on the idea,
the biweekly mortgage, hyped at www.usmr.com. I challenged the hype
in a newspaper column, archived at www.scottburns.com/980614su.htm.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DETERMINING FEES AND EXPENSES &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Most lenders on the Web now provide potential borrowers with a
list of closing fees and expenses. Make sure you comparison shop _
not all of these lenders underprice conventional lenders.
</P>
<P>
   HomeShark is one that aims to cut about $1,000 out of the
standard mortgage cost and pass the savings along to the borrower.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; QUALIFYING FOR THE LOAN &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   A borrower now making a mortgage payment of $1,000 a month
should easily qualify for a new mortgage with a lower monthly
payment, right?
</P>
<P>
   Wrong. The problem, at least with conforming loans, is often
something called the back-end ratio. This is the total of a
borrower's mortgage, home insurance, and real-estate tax payments
(which are usually limited to 28 percent of gross income), plus all
other fixed commitments _ car loans, credit-card debt, child
support, and the like.
</P>
<P>
   The combined total is limited to 36 percent of gross income. In
other words, non-home-buying commitments can't exceed 8 percent of
gross income. If they do, the mortgage amount is reduced
proportionately.
</P>
<P>
   It's not difficult to exceed 8 percent. Consider a two-earner
couple with a combined income of $100,000 who are financing two
$25,000 cars for five years at 8 percent. Their total monthly
payments will be $1,014 a month, or 12.2 percent of income.
</P>
<P>
   Add two credit-card balances of, say, $2,000 and minimum monthly
payments of $40 each, and they've lost another 1 percent. (Strictly
speaking, most lenders look at 10 months' worth of payments or so
to estimate the level of monthly installment debt.)
</P>
<P>
   With all these pitfalls, it's a good thing the Web is loaded
with qualification calculators. Two good ones can be found at
www.financecenter.com/calcs.html and www.interest.com/hugh/calc.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ASSEMBLING DOCUMENTATION &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   No two ways about it, this is a headache. A checklist of the
required items can be found at www.hsh.com, and it's a bit
daunting.
</P>
<P>
   Where are those W-2s? Where did last month's bank statement get
to? The load is even worse for the self-employed, who need at least
two years' worth of personal tax returns as well as their most
recent corporate tax returns and profit-and-loss statements.
</P>
<P>
   My advice: Make a numbered list of documents, number the
documents, and make a complete copy of the application package.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; APPLYING AND CLOSING &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   This is the easy part, comparatively speaking. Computers have
accelerated the decision-making process, so an answer _ an
affirmative answer, we hope _ should be forthcoming in short
order. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITOR'S NOTE: Contributing editor Scott Burns _ who also wrote
the excellent recent WORTH article we slugged
BC-401(K)-WEBSITES-NYTSF _ is the personal-finance columnist for
the Dallas Morning News. His E-mail address is
scott &LR; scottburns.com, and his Web-site address is
www.scottburns.com.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (To publish this helpful 1,175-word ``WORTH'' magazine article,
it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's sales
representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES.
If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us
at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-04-99 0211EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990204.0082 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 02:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1353 &Cx1f; tab-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WWW.MORTGAGE.REFINANC     02-04 1451
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WWW.MORTGAGE.REFINANCE.COM-WORTH-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFINANCE YOUR HOME VIA THE INTERNET  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
