<SLUG> BC-WEB-COMPARISON-SHOPPING-&AMP;SIDEBAR-WORTH-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`JUST BROWSING...': COMPARISON-SHOPPING ON THE INTERNET  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDITORS: Note helpful sidebar at end of story)   (This user-friendly 525-word ``separate buy'' story _ WITH HANDY
100-WORD SIDEBAR _ is from the January issue of ``WORTH'' magazine.
To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert,
please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been filed into the ``f'' financial
news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``l'' lifestyle news
files.)  
  
 By ALLAN HOFFMAN  
 c.1999 Worth Magazine  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a shopper, no matter how high your credit-card limit, there
is one thing you almost never have: perfect information. Is $521
the best deal on that Nikon? You'll never know.
</P>
<P>
   Or will you? Visit CNET's Shopper.com, enter the description of
a product you're looking to buy, and in seconds you'll have a list
of stores that carry the item.
</P>
<P>
   Not just any list, but a shopping mega-list _ database-driven
and info-packed _ that's almost certain to save you time and money.
The list tells you what you'll pay at retailers from Irvine,
Calif., to Peabody, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   As it happens, $521 is not the best price on that Nikon digital
camera, the Coolpix 600. Shopper.com lists 25 stores that carry the
product, as well as each store's phone number and location, the
approximate shipping cost, and the product's availability.
</P>
<P>
   One store wants $498.95, while another _ a popular mail-order
retailer _ wants $599.95. Complete information, or something close
to it. A shopper's dream.
</P>
<P>
   Think of Shopper.com and its brethren, the Web's
comparison-shopping sites, as search engines for products and, more
importantly, prices at far-flung merchants.
</P>
<P>
   Computers, books, CDs, toys, home electronics _ all the major
products peddled on the Web can be found at one of the
comparison-shopping sites, from Bottom Dollar to Robo Shopper.
</P>
<P>
   For price and convenience (those mantras of the serious
shopper), these sites just can't be beat, especially during the
holiday season, when mall frenzy disrupts suburban traffic patterns
and lines twist around cash registers in a consumption-crazed
version of Dante's ``Inferno.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if you don't buy any products online, you can use these
sites to compare prices with those at your local retailer.
</P>
<P>
   That said, a few caveats are still in order:
</P>
<P>
   l) Avoid sites that list prices for only a few merchants. Either
the site's database is puny or, worse, the site charges merchants
to be listed. ``That's ultimately limiting,'' says James McQuivey,
an analyst at Forrester Research. ``The consumer will eventually
learn he's getting something that's fundamentally at odds with the
value the Internet provides.''
</P>
<P>
   2) Beware of stale information. The best sites reveal when a
price was last updated. Always confirm the price by phone or at the
merchant's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   3) Even at sites that don't charge merchants for listings,
expect some intermingling of objective information with
advertisements. At Shopper.com, the initial sale list places
sponsors at the top. Does that help you? Not at all. Choose the
``Re-sort by Price'' link.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes comparison shopping is integrated into search engines,
as at Excite. More common are stand-alone comparison-shopping
sites.
</P>
<P>
   In a year or two, expect to see comparison shopping everywhere
you turn on the Web: portal sites like Yahoo!, news and
entertainment sites, even personal home pages.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, these sites will provide entirely new ways of
deciding what to buy, allowing you to generate detailed
side-by-side comparisons, read customer reviews, and otherwise
match your desires with the right product.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the consumer,'' says McQuivey, ``this is phenomenal.''  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (100-WORD SIDEBAR FOLLOWS) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LET'S MAKE A DEAL: THE BEST OF THE COMPARISON-SHOPPING SITES &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BOTTOM DOLLAR &LR;  &QL; : Computers, books, magazines, movies, CDs,
toys, video
games, electronics, sporting goods (www.bottomdollar.com).  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CNET SHOPPER.COM &LR;  &QL; : Computer products (www.shopper.com).
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EXCITE PRODUCT FINDER &LR;  &QL; : Computers, electronics, games and
toys, wine,
groceries, garden supplies, movies, sporting goods, cameras,
flowers (jango.excite.com).  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HOTBOT SHOPPING DIRECTORY &LR;  &QL; : Clothes, electronics, books,
computers,
travel (shop.hotbot.com).  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KILLER APP &LR;  &QL; : Computer products (www.killerapp.com).
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PRICE SCAN &LR;  &QL; : Computers, books (www.pricescan.com).
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PRICE WATCH &LR;  &QL; : Computer products (www.pricewatch.com).
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ROBO SHOPPER &LR;  &QL; : Computers, books, music, movies
(www.roboshopper.com).
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (To publish this helpful 625-word ``WORTH'' magazine article,
it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's sales
representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES.
If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us
at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
