<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DONOR-BEWARE!-GIFT-TAX-WORTH-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEELING GENEROUS? DON'T BE NICE UNTIL YOU KNOW THE PRICE  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Personal-Finance Editors _ ideal for tax time)   (This user-friendly, 625-word ``separate buy'' personal-finance
story is from the January issue of ``WORTH'' magazine. To publish
this article, it must be purchased from the New York Times
Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or
fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert,
please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been filed into the ``f'' financial
news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``l'' lifestyle news
files.)  
  
 By JOSEPH ANTHONY  
 c.1999 Worth Magazine  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Who besides Dr. Seuss's Grinch would impose a penalty on gift
giving? The U.S. government, of course, which makes sure that the
generous have to worry about not just income taxes but gift taxes
as well.
</P>
<P>
   An unpleasant light was briefly shone on the tax treatment of
gifts last year when baseball fans began wondering aloud whether
someone who gave St. Louis Cardinals slugger Mark McGwire back his
62nd-home-run ball would be liable for a gift tax.
</P>
<P>
   Proving just how tricky gift-tax rules can be, the IRS made two
different statements within 48 hours about tax liability. At first
the donor owed big time, then he or she was off the hook. The ball
was retrieved by an employee of the Cardinals, ending the debate.
</P>
<P>
   For people making more prosaic gifts, there are still several
considerations to keep in mind.
</P>
<P>
   If you give any one person a gift worth more than $10,000, you
will have to file a gift-tax return. But that doesn't mean you'll
actually have to pay tax on the gift this year. Instead, the effect
of the gift tax will be to reduce the amount (currently $625,000)
that can be transferred free of estate tax at the time of your
death.
</P>
<P>
   You can give up to $10,000 to an unlimited number of people
without worrying about gift tax. If you're married, you and your
spouse can give $20,000 to any individual without having to file a
gift-tax return, but you must file Form 709 to notify the IRS of
the ``split gift.''
</P>
<P>
   One other goody: There's no limit on the size of your gift if
it's for tuition or medical care. So feel free to pick up the cost
of your grandchild's Ivy League education. You'll want to be sure
to write the check to the institution, though, and not to the
individual.
</P>
<P>
   You may want to give a child or other relative non-appreciating
assets, such as cash, instead of appreciating assets like stocks.
Reason: Whoever receives your gift of an appreciating asset will
have the same cost basis that you had.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you bought $1,000 worth of stock that is now worth $7,000,
the recipient of that gift will have to pay income tax on
everything above $1,000 when the stock is sold,'' says Ed O'Hanlon,
a certified public accountant in Portland, Ore.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if you hold the stock until you die, the recipient will
get it with a stepped-up basis _ that is, the value of the stock at
your death. If you're not otherwise subject to estate taxes, that
can be a better deal for the person you want to have the stock.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, if you are going to have a large estate,
making a gift of an appreciating asset can be beneficial in the
long term.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get that future appreciation out of your estate,'' says
Bruno Graziano, senior analyst with tax-guide publisher CCH. ``The
appreciation will be taxable to the recipient, but that tax could
be less than the tax your estate might have to pay.''
</P>
<P>
   If you give someone a painting, jewelry, or other rarity, you'll
need to have it appraised. ``I would recommend getting three
independent appraisals and going with the middle or average of the
three,'' says Mark Rigotti, a CPA in Taylor, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   The appraisal value _ which should be the amount for which you
could sell the item on the open market _ is the amount you will
declare on any gift-tax return.
</P>
<P>
   The best news of all: There are no gift taxes on contributions
to qualified charities. Happy donating.  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (To publish this user-friendly 625-word ``WORTH'' magazine
article, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES.
If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us
at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
