<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-PEPPERDINE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOYOLA UPSETS PEPPERDINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ There was no margin for error and Pepperdine erred
in a big, lazy way.
</P>
<P>
   The Waves' hope was to meet frontrunning Gonzaga in two weeks in
a war that would settle the top seed in the West Coast Conference
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Waves require unforeseen and unexpected help after
failing terribly on defense in a 90-77 loss to Loyola Marymount on
Wednesday at Gersten Pavilion in the 125th meeting between the
schools.
</P>
<P>
   The Waves, who had a six-game winning streak ended, could get a
smidge of a revenge when the schools meet again Saturday in Malibu.
But without a loss by 25th-ranked Gonzaga (18-4, 8-0 WCC) before
the aforementioned Feb. 19 clash, a win against LMU would serve as
little consolation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way we tried to approach that before (Wednesday) was if no
one beat Gonzaga that was all right because we have a chance to
beat them,'' Pepperdine coach Lorenzo Romar said. ``But now, you
have to play your game, but at the same time in the back of your
mind you are wondering, `Will they lose a game?' ''
</P>
<P>
   The way Bulldogs have plowed through conference play to this
juncture, that doesn't look likely. Gonzaga has won seven of its
conference games by nine points or more.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very unfortunate that it's come down to this,''
Pepperdine senior forward Marc McDowell said. ``But if we keep
playing like we did here, it won't make much difference.''
</P>
<P>
   In what was clearly a battle of styles _ Pepperdine's defense
against LMU's run-and-gun _ it was the Lions who won out.
</P>
<P>
   Almost to the point where the Waves, the best defensive team in
the league, stopped playing defense in the second half, getting
beat in transition and allowing a plethora of open shots.
</P>
<P>
   LMU, which scored the last four points of the first half to tie
it at 34-34, scored 56 points in the second half. The Lions shot 50
percent from the field and rendered Pepperdine's size advantage
meaningless with it's full-throttle approach. It contributed to the
most points scored against Pepperdine this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``You give us a lot of credit when you say (we played) not much
defense,'' Romar said. ``We didn't defend at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Davis and Rupert McClendon both came off the bench to
pace six Lions (10-11, 5-4) in double figures with 16 points
apiece. Jelani Gardner led Pepperdine (16-8, 7-2) with 19 points,
but was forced to play 38 minutes because of ineffective guard
play.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got caught up in playing up-tempo with them and it got the
best of us because we weren't getting back on defense,'' said
Tommie Prince, usually Pepperdine's defensive stalwart. ``Even when
we did make our shots, we still weren't getting back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
