A1378 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-DUCKS-LADN     02-04 0584
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUCKS WIN 3-0
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM -- Matt Cullen finally made it to the top on Wednesday
night, and he took full advantage of his opportunity in the Mighty
Ducks' 3-0 victory over the Chicago Blackhawks before 15,254 at the
Pond.
</P>
<P>
   After a solid rookie season, Cullen has played on the second,
third and fourth lines this season. He had only 10 points in his
first 41 games, but Anaheim coach Craig Hartsburg desperate to snap
his team's five-game winless streak (0-4-1) moved the young center
between Paul Kariya and Teemu Selanne.
</P>
<P>
   Cullen responded with a goal and an assist as the Ducks
(18-22-9) won for just the second time in nine games (2-6-1).
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim's performance wasn't especially brilliant, but it was
good enough to beat the Western Conference's worst team.
</P>
<P>
   For two periods Chicago controlled much of the play, but it was
the Ducks who took an early lead on Kariya's 21st goal at 3:34 of
the first period. Cullen put then put the Blackhawks away 24
seconds into the third period with his fourth goal of the year
while Anaheim was on the power play.
</P>
<P>
   Guy Hebert, seemingly fully recovered from the flu, made those
goals standup by stopping 35 shots and recording his career-high
fifth shutout.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the first period was played in Anaheim's defensive zone,
but the Ducks took a 1-0 lead into the second on a goal that had to
make Hartsburg especially happy.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't pretty, but it was just type the Anaheim coach has
been looking for from his team. Cullen deflected Ruslan Salei's
point shot and Kariya was right in front of the net to pick up the
rebound and lift a backhander over Jocelyn Thibault's glove just
before he was knocked to the ice by Jamie Allison.
</P>
<P>
   Kariya's goal was just his third point in the last five games.
The Anaheim captain has led the league in scoring much of the
season, but he now trails Pittsburgh's Jaromir Jagr, 72-63.
</P>
<P>
   Kariya thought he had another goal midway through the second
period. Kariya found himself wide open in the slot after getting a
pass from Selanne. His wrist shot had Thibault beat cleanly and the
winger began to raise his arms, but the shot hit the crossbar and
stayed out.
</P>
<P>
   While Chicago had the territorial advantage in the first period,
the Blackhawks really had only one good scoring chance and Hebert
got some help from the post on a shot by Todd White, who had blown
around Jason Marshall.
</P>
<P>
   The second period was a different story. Chicago had 15 shots on
goal and several excellent scoring chances.
</P>
<P>
   Hebert had to be sharp and he was -- right from the opening
minute when he made a glove save on White.
</P>
<P>
   The Anaheim goalie also thwarted Nelson Emerson and While --
again -- on point-blank chances about five minutes into the period.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks failed to score on a brief 27-second two-man advantage
just before the second period ended. But Anaheim's power play unit
scored the crucial goal early in the final period.
</P>
<P>
   Selanne got a pass to Cullen in the right circle. The Anaheim
center waited for Chris Chelios to slide by and with all kinds of
time beat Thibault with a shot high over the Chicago goalie's
shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim, the league's top-ranked power play at home, has scored
at least one power play goal in 23 of 26 games at the Pond.
</P>
<P>
   Marty McInnis completed the scoring with an empty net goal with
11.1 seconds left in the third period.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
