<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-SHELBURNE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OAKMONT READY TO SHINE FOR LPGA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE SHELBURNE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The course is fit, the scoreboards are up, there's
no major rain _ or wind _ anticipated, and seven of this year's
top-10 money-winners are in the field.
</P>
<P>
   Oakmont Country Club is ready for the first Valley of the Stars
Championship (formerly Los Angeles Women's Championship), which is
next week at the hillside Glendale course.
</P>
<P>
   ``The golf course is raring to go,'' said Greg Frederick,
Oakmont's head pro and recently elected vice-president of the
Southern California PGA Board of Directors.
</P>
<P>
   Frederick is proud of his course, one defended fiercely by some
of the most-difficult greens in the area. He expects Oakmont to
represent itself as well as it did last year, when one of the best
fields on the LPGA Tour averaged 3.5 strokes over par.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what it is,'' Frederick said, ``is really a U.S.
Open-type venue for the tour, and we're thankful to get the
opportunity to show off Oakmont.''
</P>
<P>
   Defending U.S. Open champion Se Ri Pak and three-time player of
the year Anika Sorenstam lead a field that also includes area
players Helen Alfredsson of Glendale and former Oakmont junior star
Emilee Klein.
</P>
<P>
   Liselotte Neumann, Dottie Pepper, Julie Inkster, Meg Mallon,
Kris Tschetter and 1998 Nabisco Dinah Shore champion Pat Hurst join
Sorenstam on the current top-10 list and also will be taking
another shot at Oakmont next week.
</P>
<P>
   This time, it appears the field will be able to dodge the
weather problems that have plagued the tournament through the
years, bringing hail and sleet in the '80s and gale-force winds
that knocked down more than 50 trees before the '97 event. Last
year, heavy rains washed out Saturday's play, leaving shallow lakes
spanning some of Oakmont's fairways and reducing the tournament to
36 holes.
</P>
<P>
   That weather also gave Oakmont a chance to showcase the skills
of course superintendent Dave Flaxbeard and his groundskeeping
crew, whose nightlong repair work left competitors with sensational
playing conditions for Sunday's closing round.
</P>
<P>
   Dale Eggeling said she can't wait to get back and not just
because she's defending champion. She likes the fact that Oakmont's
twisting, tree-lined fairways and fast, undulating greens force her
to plan her shots more carefully than at many of the LPGA stops.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love a tough course because I concentrate better,'' she
said. ``The way this golf course is laid out, when you step up to
the tee, you pretty much know where you have to hit it. On this
course, you really have to focus, and I like a course like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Skills challenge at Vista: Valencia eighth-grader Brandon
Christiansen, who placed fifth in last year's national Toyota Golf
Skills Challenge, will have the advantage of local knowledge in
this year's qualifying competition. And so will a lot of other
Santa Clarita Valley golfers.
</P>
<P>
   Vista Valencia, Christiansen's home course, will be one of two
Southern California sites in the national qualifying round that
will advance the six flight winners at each of 25 sites to the
national final.
</P>
<P>
   Vista Valencia will host the eight-event skills test April
23-25, followed by an April 30-May 2 qualifier at Fullerton GC.
Christiansen had the best overall score of more than 1,400
competitors last spring at Fullerton, earning a trip to the
national final at Ojai Inn and Spa, where he placed fifth in the
kids (age 8-13) division.
</P>
<P>
   Competition is also in junior (14-17), men's, women's, senior
men's (50-over) and open divisions. Competitors are awarded points
for skill in long-driving, short irons, trouble shots, middle
irons, chip shots, putting, greenside-bunker play and pitching over
a hazard.
</P>
<P>
   Entry fee at Vista Valencia is $20. The entry at Fullerton is
$25. Competition lasts about four hours and golfers can sign for
either or both events. Registration information: (800) 932-8337.
</P>
<P>
   Names in the game: Henry Liaw, Christiansen's talented age-group
rival who shot a course-record 58 at Alhambra GC last year, is
bidding to become one of the youngest participants ever in a PGA
Tour event. Liaw, 13, will play in a Buick Invitational qualifier
Monday at Eagle Crest in Escondido. The eighth grader at Alvarado
Middle School in Rowland Heights will be shooting against pros but
he might not be such a longshot. He followed his 58 at par-70
Alhambra with a 7-under-par 65 one week later at the Industry Hills
Babe Zaharius course, where the official record is 69 . . .
</P>
<P>
   Former Cal State Northridge golfer Gary Finneran recorded his
third hole-in-one last week, acing the par-3, 210-yard 17th hole at
Sunset Hills Country Club with a 4-iron. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Westlake senior J.T. Kohut could compete in as many as four PGA
Tour qualifiers before starting his final high school golf season
March 1. Kohut will try to qualify for next week's Buick
Invitational on Monday at El Camino Country Club in Oceanside and
has signed up for a Nissan Open qualifier next Friday at Los
Seranos and for a Tucson Open qualifier Feb. 22 at Arthur Park GC
in Tucson, Ariz. He shot even-par 72 while failing to qualify for
the Phoenix Open at Papago GC in Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   Kohut, who has narrowed his college choices to USC and UCLA,
seems sharp for his PGA Tour qualifying run. Last week on his home
course at par-71 Sunset Hills, he double-bogeyed the first hole and
finished with a 64. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
