r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-DUCKS-WRITETHRU-L     02-04 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUCKS WIN 3-0
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM -- Matt Cullen finally made it to the top on Wednesday
night, and he took full advantage of his opportunity in the Mighty
Ducks' 3-0 victory over the Chicago Blackhawks before 15,254 at the
Pond.
</P>
<P>
   After a solid rookie season, Cullen has played on the second,
third and fourth lines this season. He had only 10 points in his
first 41 games. But Anaheim coach Craig Hartsburg, desperate to
snap his team's five-game winless streak (0-4-1), moved the young
center between Paul Kariya and Teemu Selanne.
</P>
<P>
   Cullen responded with a goal and an assist as the Ducks
(18-22-9) won for just the second time in nine games (2-6-1).
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he played very well tonight,'' said Hartsburg. ``I
thought he complimented them well, so we will play him there on
Friday in Tampa Bay.''
</P>
<P>
   Hartsburg's said there is ``nothing written in stone'' about
Cullen's spot on the line, but a critical third-period power play
goal certainly didn't hurt his chances for more playing time with
the Ducks' two star wingers.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim's performance wasn't especially memorable, but it was
good enough to beat the Western Conference's worst team.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the game went on I thought we got stronger and stronger,''
said Hartsburg, who is now 3-1 versus the team that fired him last
spring. ``Now we have to carry this on to the next game.''
</P>
<P>
   For two periods Chicago controlled much of the play, but it was
the Ducks who took an early lead on Kariya's 21st goal at 3:34 of
the first period. Cullen then put the Blackhawks away 24 seconds
into the third period with his fourth goal of the year while
Anaheim was on the power play.
</P>
<P>
   Marty McInnis scored his 15th goal of the year into an empty net
with 11.1 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   One goal is all Guy Hebert would have needed, but he was
thrilled to see Cullen give the Ducks a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too many times we have let teams creep back in games,'' said
Hebert, who stopped 35 shots and recorded his career-high fifth
shutout of the season. ``That (goal) was huge, it made everybody
feel better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then we started playing better. Maybe we've finally learned
from some of our mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the first period was played in Anaheim's defensive zone,
but the Ducks took a lead into the second thanks to a goal that had
to make Hartsburg especially happy.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't pretty, but it was just the type of goal that the
coach has been looking for from his team. Cullen deflected Ruslan
Salei's point shot and Kariya was right in front of the net to pick
up the rebound and lift a backhander over Jocelyn Thibault's glove
just before he was knocked to the ice by Jamie Allison.
</P>
<P>
   Kariya has fallen nine points behind Pittsburgh's Jaromir Jagr
(72-63) in the scoring race, but he was a factor all night,
recording seven shots on goals while avoiding Chris Chelios
constant stickwork, including several two-handed slashes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chelly plays hard against everybody, not just Paul Kariya,''
said Hartsburg. ``You may not like, but you have to accept it.''
</P>
<P>
   While Kariya was being hounded by Chelios, high-scoring Chicago
winger Tony Amonte was taking his licks from Anaheim's defensemen,
especially Jason Marshall and Kevin Haller.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we did a good job on Tony, he didn't have much open
ice,'' said Hartsburg.
</P>
<P>
   While Chicago had the territorial advantage in the first period,
the Blackhawks really had only one good scoring chance and Hebert
got some help from the post on a shot by Todd White, who had blown
around Marshall.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago had 15 shots on goal in the second period and Hebert had
to be sharp early. He made a glove save on White in the opening
minute and thwarted Nelson Emerson and White -- again -- on
point-blank chances about five minutes into the period.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks failed to score on a brief 27-second two-man advantage
just before the second period ended. But Anaheim's power play unit
scored the crucial goal early in the final period.
</P>
<P>
   Selanne got a pass to Cullen in the right circle. Cullen waited
for Chelios to slide by and with all kinds of time beat Thibault
with a shot high over the Chicago goalie's shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim, the league's top-ranked power play at home, has scored
at least one power play goal in 23 of 26 games at the Pond.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
