<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-DAVIS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 DAVIS CALLS MEXICO JOURNEY A `HOME RUN'  &HT;     By CARLA MARINUCCI 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  MONTERREY, Mexico _ California Gov. Gray Davis wrapped up
his three-day trip to Mexico Wednesday, calling the effort a ``home
run'' that produced tangible gains for California in business,
academic exchange and trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was overwhelmed by the reception in Mexico,'' said Davis, in
an interview as he jetted home Wednesday night from Monterrey,
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everyone understood the sincerity, my reaching out to
the people of Mexico. It exceeded my expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis closed out his Mexican trip less than 150 miles from the
border with Texas, a state that has slipped past California as
Mexico's primary trading partner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor (George W.) Bush has done a very good job developing
a relationship with President (Ernesto) Zedillo,'' said Davis as he
arrived earlier in Monterrey, a business powerhouse and capital of
the Mexican state of Nuevo Leon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't begrudge any jobs Texas has won ... but I think we
have a strong case to make that business leaders throughout Mexico,
and in Monterrey, should look at California,'' Davis said. ``We
have a ways to go to catch up, but we're off to a good start.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis refused to engage in what he called ``a rift on the
border'' with Bush, but he was clearly elated Wednesday by two
major developments. Davis disclosed that Zedillo will make his
first-ever official visit to California, and he celebrated a major
deal in which telecommunications giant Telmex will relocate its
U.S. headquarters from Houston to San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Davis recounted last night how he himself sealed that deal at
the home of Mexican billionaire Carlos Slim Helu, the Telmex
chairman.
</P>
<P>
   He said he and Slim had had informal talks for weeks about the
company's possible move to California. Davis said the reception at
Slim's home provided the setting he needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many times was I going to have dinner with Carlos Slim?
That was the moment,'' Davis said. ``And I learned a long time ago
to seize the moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis spent the final day of his trip in Monterrey, a business
and financial magnet of 3 million people, meeting with Nuevo Leon
Governor Fernando Canales Clariond, who presides over the sprawling
state that borders Texas.
</P>
<P>
   With a state delegation of business and academic leaders at his
side, Davis saw clear evidence of the Mexican demand for foreign
products as they traveled highways lined with American-grown
businesses, from Wal-Mart and Sam's Club to Amway and Whirlpool.
</P>
<P>
   Davis announced that Canales, like Zedillo, had agreed to bring
a trade mission to California. He also said that the two governors
would work together with Delta and Aeromexico airlines to develop
direct air routes between Monterrey and California.
</P>
<P>
   The governor said he expects Zedillo to be ``treated like a rock
star'' when he arrives to address the California Legislature in
May.
</P>
<P>
   Davis also traveled to the Instituto de Tecnologico de
Monterrey, a private university specializing in technology
education, where he held an international video conference on
academic issues.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, pushing for more academic exchanges, said he wants to
double the number of exchange students, currently 200, between
Mexico and the California State University system.
</P>
<P>
   And in one of the more unusual aspects of his trip, Davis _ a
lifelong politician _ said he has picked up a political tip from
his Mexican counterpart that he is considering importing to
Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   The tip came at a session at which Davis toured the Nuevo Leon
governor's palace, where 2,000 people had patiently lined up to
make direct, personal appeals to the governor's office. Their
once-a-month chance to get direct action for problems ranging from
legal troubles to neighborly disputes is part of a year-old program
that Canales calls ``Direct Line.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, he told Davis, more than 11,000 citizens have come to
have their complaints heard, and an astounding 96 percent of them
had their problems solved, Mexican government officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Davis appeared enthralled as he sat with Canales and heard an
appeal from a small businessman, Reynaldo Gardia, who arrived
literally hat in hand to ask the Mexican governor for a loan
refinance.
</P>
<P>
   Canales, who meets each month with citizens and directs his
Cabinet to do likewise, ordered it done.
</P>
<P>
   The California governor said he was ``very impressed'' by
Mexican attempts to give citizens direct contact with their
political leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm inclined to adopt something similar in California,'' he
said. ``We don't spend enough time talking to individual citizens.
... It's a very wise thing to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
