<HEADER>
A1406 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEARST-ANNIVERSARY-SF     02-04 1812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-ANNIVERSARY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 THE KIDNAPPING THAT GRIPPED THE NATION  &HT;     By WILLIAM CARLSEN 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  SAN FRANCISCO _ On a crisp, clear winter night 25 years ago
Thursday, three armed kidnappers burst into a Berkeley, Calif.,
apartment and carried off a 19-year-old newspaper heiress wrapped
in a blue bathrobe.
<P>
   Her name was Patricia Campbell Hearst, and her kidnapping _
complete with gunshots and squealing cars a few blocks south of the
University of California campus _ set off one of the most bizarre
sagas in modern history.
</P>
<P>
   Before it was over, the granddaughter of publishing magnate
William Randolph Hearst had joined her kidnappers _ a small band of
self-styled revolutionaries who called themselves the Symbionese
Liberation Army _ helping them rob banks and plant bombs before she
was eventually arrested in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Her trial, held in San Francisco's federal courthouse, was
billed as the ``trial of the century'' _ the first time since the
Lindbergh kidnapping trial in the 1930s that the term was used with
any seriousness. Eventually she served two years in federal prison.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the 44-year-old Hearst hurries through the busy life of
an East Coast society matron, devoted to a raft of charities,
raising two teenage daughters, appearing in the occasional John
Waters movie. It is a life so normal that her kidnapping now seems
like a mirage, an event so implausible and so long ago that it is
as if it never happened.
</P>
<P>
   It was a different era, but one that bears at least one uncanny
similarity to the present. On the day of the kidnapping, the nation
was preoccupied with talk of the impeachment of the president, and
special prosecutor Leon Jaworsky was demanding that Richard Nixon
turn over the fateful White House tapes.
</P>
<P>
   Lines at gas stations extended for blocks, as the Arab oil
embargo squeezed supplies. On the Sunday before the kidnapping,
only 11 stations in San Francisco had enough gasoline to open.
</P>
<P>
   The Vietnam War was nearly over and, despite Watergate, the
nation at times seemed to be trying to reclaim some of its earlier
innocence. ``American Graffiti'' had debuted in movie theaters the
previous year, and ``Happy Days'' was playing on television.
</P>
<P>
   But the act of terror that struck a quiet Berkeley neighborhood
on the night of Feb. 4, 1974, reminded the nation that the radical
political turmoil that had begun in the 1960s was still in full
force, at least in the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   In its first ``communiques'' after the kidnapping, the SLA
railed against the establishment, demanding that the wealthy Hearst
family _ her father was chairman of the Hearst Corp. and editor of
the San Francisco Examiner _ use its millions to feed the poor.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, Patty Hearst would be heard in tape recordings denouncing
her parents as ``pigs,'' a phrase that sent shudders through
mothers and fathers across America.
</P>
<P>
   And on April 15, a little more than two months after her
kidnapping, Hearst, now calling herself ``Tanya,'' appeared in the
jerky frames of a surveillance video, holding a rifle as she and
her kidnappers robbed the Hibernia Bank in San Francisco's Sunset
District.
</P>
<P>
   When she was arrested 17 months later, after one of the most
intensive manhunts in FBI history, she gave the revolutionary
clenched-fist salute. Asked her occupation when was being booked
and fingerprinted, she replied: ``urban guerrilla.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with F. Lee Bailey, his famous law partner, J. Albert
Johnson was hired by the Hearsts to defend their daughter against
the Hibernia bank robbery charges.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said he spent hours every day with Hearst at the jail,
while Bailey held press conferences and attended to pretrial work
on the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just allowed her to express her feelings, to come out of
it,'' Johnson said late in January. ``It was never planned as a
deprogramming, never. She just slowly freed herself from the
brainwashing.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time her trial began four months later, Hearst's
transformation back to being a frightened Berkeley sophomore was
complete.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst testified that after her kidnapping, the SLA kept her
blindfolded for more than 50 days in a closet in a Daly City,
Calif., safe house, incessantly haranguing her with radical
rhetoric. She also explained that she took part in the Hibernia
Bank robbery out of fear that she would be killed if she did not.
</P>
<P>
   But the man who prosecuted her, former U.S. Attorney James L.
Browning, has never wavered in his belief that Hearst was guilty
and her trial and its outcome just.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her defense was physical duress, but it never squared with the
facts,'' said Browning, 66, who recently retired from the San Mateo
County Superior Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``When she was in that bank,'' Browning said, ``she acted with
verve and great purpose, and she avoided apprehension for a year
and a half, when she had plenty of opportunities to walk away and
come home. The fact is she had joined them.''
</P>
<P>
   It took the jury little more than a day to convict her,
concluding that she had been a willing participant in the Hibernia
Bank robbery.
</P>
<P>
   In 1979, after serving two years of a five-year sentence,
President Jimmy Carter commuted her sentence and she was freed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patty was a victim of her times,'' said Johnson. ``She was a
victim of a cruel kidnapping. She was a victim of the American
people, who despised her because she represented the radical nature
of young people at the time. She was the victim of the rich, who
thought of her as impudent and disrespectful, and a victim of the
left and the poor who saw her as a spoiled little rich girl.
</P>
<P>
   `'But most of all she was a victim of the system that prosecuted
her,'' said the 65-year-old Boston lawyer. ``In all my life, I've
never seen such an injustice as her conviction.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Harris broke into the apartment 25 years ago, dragged the
screaming Hearst down a flight of stairs and threw her into the
trunk of a stolen white Chevrolet. He was accompanied during the
kidnapping by Donald DeFreeze, also known as General Field Marshal
Cinque, and Angela Atwood, while other SLA members waited in nearby
cars.
</P>
<P>
   DeFreeze, Atwood and four other SLA members died in a shootout
with police in Los Angeles three months later.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Harris works as a private investigator for defense
lawyers in the Bay Area. He and his wife, Emily, were arrested with
Hearst in San Francisco in 1975, and they were convicted of her
kidnapping. They served eight years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just lucky to be alive,'' said the 54-year-old Harris in a
recent interview. ``I should be dead or in prison, and I'm amazed I
survived.''
</P>
<P>
   Divorced from Emily, Harris said he is now happily married to a
local defense attorney and they have two children. He said he is
still committed to the underdog, working every day as a defense
investigator to represent ``people at the bottom of the pile.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been there. I had another chance. I feel empathy and
compassion for people, even if they've done heinous things.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Hearst, he said he is already on record as disputing many
of the details she wrote about in ``Every Secret Thing,'' her 1982
book about the kidnapping and her time in the SLA.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview published in the Oakland Tribune in 1988, Harris
claimed that Hearst was already rebelling against her parents
before her kidnapping and had second thoughts about her engagement
to live-in boyfriend Steven Weed. He said she willingly joined the
SLA and called her enthusiastic, highly intelligent and
strong-willed. He had opposed letting her join.
</P>
<P>
   But even now, Harris said, he is still a bit bewildered by her.
``She was a very interesting person, and not everybody would have
responded (to her kidnapping) like she did. Now she's turning out
like her mother (the late, staunchly conservative UC Regent
Catherine Hearst).''
</P>
<P>
   Not quite.
</P>
<P>
   While she enjoys many of the trappings of her family wealth and
has become a fixture at East Coast celebrity and charity functions,
she has never lost a certain quirkiness and sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   She co-authored a novel titled ``Murder at San Simeon'' and has
appeared in minor roles in several campy John Waters movies,
including the 1990 film ``Cry Baby,'' where her role was a parody
of a prim, suburban housewife.
</P>
<P>
   In Waters' most recent film, called ``Pecker,'' Hearst plays an
obnoxious New York art collector who shows off her cleavage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell people,'' she said to one interviewer about her entree
into acting, ``If you want to be in films, wait tables _ don't get
kidnapped.''
</P>
<P>
   Her most outrageous moment came in 1995 at a Thierry Mugler
fashion show in Paris, when she strode down the runway in giant
shoes and performed a striptease.
</P>
<P>
   She declined to be interviewed for this story. Her husband,
Bernard Shaw, a San Francisco cop who first met Hearst when he was
moonlighting as her bodyguard, is now head of security for the
Hearst Corp. in New York. He said his wife sees the 25th
anniversary of her kidnapping as ``just another day going by'' and
would rather not dwell on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's really busy,'' Shaw said, counting off a list of
charities Hearst is involved in. No other books or movies are
currently in the works. ``She's waiting to see what might come
along.''
</P>
<P>
   In earlier interviews, Hearst often laughed at the fact that her
parents never thought her marriage to Shaw would last more than a
few months. ``They gave us a Sears vacuum cleaner for a wedding
present,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw pointed out that in April, they will have been married for
20 years. ``We're doing really well,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the four-unit building near the corner of Benvenue Avenue and
Parker Street in Berkeley, a woman behind the sliding frosted-glass
door cautiously asks who is there, just as Hearst's fiance, Steven
Weed, did about 9 p.m. on that February night a quarter of a
century ago.
</P>
<P>
   The brown-shingle building looks much as it did then. The
shingles are a little faded; the eucalyptus tree is still out
front. Two cars are parked in the wide cement driveway where 25
years ago the white Chevrolet was waiting with its motor running
for the three kidnappers and their victim.
</P>
<P>
   The woman, who does not identify herself, says she is not the
owner of the two-story, two-bedroom unit that was converted into a
condo 11 years ago, and she does not feel right about letting
anyone in to see the historic location.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, we know about its history,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Then she pointed to a hole in a wood shingle to the right of the
door and one in the aluminum door frame, where the kidnappers fired
off rounds to scare away neighbors who had appeared that night to
see what was causing all the shouting and screaming.
</P>
<P>
   ``People still come around occasionally asking about the place,
out of curiosity, but fewer and fewer of them these days.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
