<HEADER>
A1408 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r n &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PEBBLE-BEACH-SFCHRON &LR;      02-04 0967
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEBBLE-BEACH-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 MONTEREY PENINSULA ENGAGED IN GOLF COURSE WARS  &HT;     By MICHAEL MCCABE 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEBBLE BEACH, Monterey County _ There's a war over golf being
waged here, but it has little to do with who can stay out of the
bunkers during the AT&AMP;T Pebble Beach National Pro Am golf
tournament, which starts Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Pebble Beach Co., which owns nearly half of the gloriously
beautiful 5,300 acres that many consider one of golf's holiest
shrines, has big plans to build another golf course _ the area's
eighth.
</P>
<P>
   It also wants to develop 316 lots for luxury housing _ plus 53
more housing  &LR; units for affordable housing _ and build a new
41,000-square-foot clubhouse, complete with restaurants, banquet
rooms and shops.
</P>
<P>
   To do so, the company will need to remove as many as 33,222
Monterey pine trees. It will also have to tear down an equestrian
center and polo field to accommodate the Tom Fazio-designed golf
course, to be located between the Cypress Point and Pebble Beach
courses.
</P>
<P>
   In return, the Pebble Beach Co. has agreed to build a brand-new
``state-of-the-art'' equestrian center costing as much as $5
million in a new 41-acre location near Highway 68.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Monterey County environmentalists _ and many
Pebble Beach residents _ are aghast.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this plan goes through, the Del Monte forest will be
totally gone,'' said Janice O'Brien, a member of the Concerned
Residents of Pebble Beach. ``The whole mood and look of the place
will be radically changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Pebble Beach Co. officials insist they have the right, and a
burning need, to develop property they have owned for years and for
which they have paid taxes and maintenance costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our golf courses _ including Spyglass, Spanish Bay and Pebble
Beach _ are virtually sold out year-round,'' said Rich Patterson,
Pebble Beach Co.'s director of community affairs. ``This will ease
demand on all the golf courses at Pebble Beach and will allow us to
continue in the kind of business we have been in for 80 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Pebble Beach is a private enclave accessible only through toll
gates, where nonresidents pay $7.25 for the privilege of touring
the 17-Mile Drive, the Del Monte Forest, the baronial mansions
along the shoreline, the world-class golf courses and the
ultra-posh resort now known simply as the Lodge. It costs $325 to
play a round of golf at Pebble Beach Co.'s golf courses, among the
most expensive in the country.
</P>
<P>
   The project has undergone several revisions in recent years. It
has been reviewed by the county planning staff, which is in general
recommending approval. The project is expected to go before the
county Planning Commission in April and to the county Board of
Supervisors for approval in the summer, according to Jeff Main,
Monterey County senior planner. If county approvals are granted,
then the plan will go to the California Coastal Commission.
</P>
<P>
   What development might do to the cherished stands of Monterey
pine and other plant species that depend on its habitat is what
divides residents of Monterey County. Indeed, many residents of the
Monterey peninsula, which includes Pebble Beach, are so frustrated
by the amount of development taking place that there is a nascent
campaign to form a new county.
</P>
<P>
   Particularly worrisome to many is the fate of the Monterey
pines, many of which are dying. A virulent and incurable fungus
known as the pitch canker is sweeping through the last stands here,
killing healthy trees and threatening to turn the verdant hills
brown.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of years ago, Monterey pine blanketed the coast. But
drier weather, rising temperatures and human encroachment have cut
its range to just three native stands: on the Monterey Peninsula,
in Ano Nuevo State Reserve along the San Mateo County coast and in
Cambria north of San Luis Obispo.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the infection, the native stands are considered the best
hope for combating pitch canker. Plant geneticists estimate that up
to 15 percent of Monterey pines are resistant to the fungus and
could be used to regrow devastated stands. The Pebble Beach company
plans to `'mitigate'' the removal of the trees by replacing them
with new trees, possibly by working with nurseries to find trees
that have survived the disease and then cloning them.
</P>
<P>
   But Mary Ann Matthews of the local chapter of the California
Native Plant Society said the approach will not work.
</P>
<P>
   ``The existing Monterey pine at Pebble Beach are natives, and
they have the greatest genetic diversity and hold the greatest
promise in finding resistant strains,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Nielsen, a member of Concerned Residents of Pebble Beach,
is also worried about traffic, water and the loss of the beloved
equestrian center, which many believe is so historically valuable
that it is an irreplaceable treasure.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a nutshell, we don't want the golf course,'' Nielsen
said.``We believe the equestrian center and the polo field are
community property, and that the company has no right to simply
destroy it and put a golf course there.''
</P>
<P>
   John Tormey, who formed a group called Alliance for a Balanced
Community that backs the company's plans, says that although
opponents of the Pebble Beach Co. have used ``sniper fire'' so far,
the war could escalate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each side has a nuclear weapon. The environmentalists can
force a referendum if the county board approves this project _
which most of us expect will happen, on both counts,'' Tormey said.
``And if the referendum wins, which it probably would, the Pebble
Beach Company can argue they cannot be denied because it violates
their Fifth Amendment right not to have their private property
taken away for public use without just compensation. And here I
think we are talking about $150 million.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
