<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-BOOKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DEATH VALLEY' A GOOD, HOT READ
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICH MARTIN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Death Valley and Yosemite national parks are
unique not only for their scenery but for their history, yet
information of the past beyond roadway plaques can be as
inaccessible as the historic sites themselves.
</P>
<P>
   No more. ``Death Valley to Yosemite: Frontier Mining Camps &AMP;
Ghost Towns'' by L. Burr Belden and Mary DeDecker (Spotted Dog
Press; $14.95) fills in the details about lesser-known aspects of
these two regions' colorful past. As a bonus, it also includes
information on hikes in ghost towns.
</P>
<P>
   The authors, old-timers from those parts, have collected the
tales and presented them as the truth. They may well be authentic,
but even if only legends they're great stories about the miners,
soldiers, outlaws and oddballs drawn to the West by the land, the
minerals and the seeming promise of quick, easy wealth.
</P>
<P>
   There's a band of robbers that hides out in a canyon after
holding up a stagecoach, only to find the ravine holds a rich vein
of gold. One of the bandits knows a senator, and they arrange to
give the stolen money back and to make claims. The senator, of
course, has a stake in the mine _ in Panamint, one of the many boom
towns in Death Valley. Later owners of the mine got wise to a
planned robbery of their silver, so they thwarted the would-be
perpetrators by casting the metal in 700-pound cannonballs.
</P>
<P>
   Other discoverers of gold and silver included a soldier, a boy
shepherd and lost travelers. One man reputedly found a rich
outcropping of gold right underneath a spot where his burro had
wandered off in search of grass.
</P>
<P>
   The boomtowns were tough places. Of the first 31 buildings built
in Monoville, 23 were liquor stores, while Rhyolite, Nev., bragged
of having 53 saloons and two churches. In Skidoo, a Death Valley
outpost, a man who killed a banker was lynched from a telephone
pole in the sheriff's absence; already dead, he was hanged a second
time to show off frontier customs for a visiting Los Angeles
journalist.
</P>
<P>
   The 192-page book _ which includes archival photos and prints,
along with easy-to-read maps to long-forgotten sites that might
otherwise go unnoticed _ is published by a tiny Bishop company
rapidly becoming a valuable commodity in Eastern Sierra history.
``Death Valley to Yosemite'' would liven up a vacation, a day hike
or a backpacking trip in the two areas, despite some rather
disruptive editing flaws and questionable oversights.Our rating:
(zap)HHH &UR; !off! &LR;
</P>
<P>
   How can a book about the Sierra Nevada mountain range possibly
rise above the myriad others in print?
</P>
<P>
   Simple: The author can go off the beaten path and take the route
rarely traveled. He can explore lesser-known trails and stress the
personal, spiritual aspects of the wilderness experience.
</P>
<P>
   Presto. Phil Arnot's ``High Sierra: John Muir's Range of Light''
(Wide World Publishing/Tetra; $12.95) provides a panorama of
odysseys the hiker can enjoy, in a range of locations that span the
chain. Moonlit treks. Mountaintop layovers. Spring runoff. Autumn
colors. Lunar rainbows. Splendid waterfalls. Solo hikes.
</P>
<P>
   Arnot, an environmentalist, mountaineer and explorer, knows the
Sierra as if it is spiritual home. The breadth of his knowledge is
impressive.
</P>
<P>
   The advice of the native Californian is useful and the black and
white pictures in the 372-page book are generally excellent. Maps
would have completed the package but are noticeably absent. At
least Arnot describes clearly how to reach trailheads.
</P>
<P>
   I have firsthand knowledge of one of the hikes listed, a climb
of Mount Dana, and he provides a competent narration. I only wish I
had taken his advice and followed a comfortable pace to the top
rather than racing; as he wrote, if you're out of breath all the
time, you're going too fast.
</P>
<P>
   Arnot shows not how to conquer the Sierra but how to enjoy them.
Our rating: HHH
</P>
<P>
   Wayne F. Moss' ``The Trinity Alps Companion'' (Ecopress; $14.95)
is an adequate guide that relies on four decades of personal
experiences to shuttle the reader along.
</P>
<P>
   Describing his boyhood home in Northwestern California, he lists
a wide range of day hikes, backpacking trips and fishing
opportunities. Maps and photos complement the profiles.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the 254-page book is memorable for all the wrong reasons.
</P>
<P>
   The author describes his youthful hikes and proves his knowledge
of the area, but the writing is far from riveting. Moreover, the
book is structured way too much on Moss' own past, as if it were an
expanded journal, and a particularly weepy one. In the end, it's a
terrible disservice to the newcomer looking for a good hike in the
Trinity Alps.
</P>
<P>
   Consider one of the author's endless meanderings, which all too
often are reduced to meaningless drivel:
</P>
<P>
   ``I find satisfaction enough in lying down on the sun-warmed
rocks and becoming a speck on a grain of sand on the shoreline of
the cosmic ocean, a microscopic flash in geologic eons. Looking
over Granite Creek Canyon, my eyes can soar like a hawk. Let others
catalogue and classify the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Say what? Our rating: H
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-04-99 0348EST &QL; 
