<DOCNO> NYT19990204.0110 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 09:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1529 &Cx1f; tad-z
s k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV07-C     02-04 0561
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: LEARNING EURO LESSONS
 &HT;    Moving in (k) commentary and (f) financial categories for
release Sunday, Feb. 7.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAVOS, Switzerland _ My hotel bill here was denominated in both
Swiss francs and euros, a currency that won't exist in notes and
coins until 2002, but one that has nevertheless already altered the
fiscal map of Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The Europeans have set up a system of fixed exchange rates among
11 nations that still differ greatly in such matters as pay scales,
social welfare benefits and the demand for goods and services. But
investors and borrowers seem to like the euro, which they see as
more than the sum of its parts.
</P>
<P>
   Bankers confide that the euro's smart liftoff came because
long-term interest rates in the euro zone are now a full percentage
point lower than U.S. Treasury bonds. Investors are content to
accept the lower euro yields because they think European bond
prices will rise in the next few months, thus providing them with a
capital gains windfall.
</P>
<P>
   Down the road, Switzerland, Britain and other strong players who
remain out of the euro game are bound to join in. There was even
some talk here at the World Economic Forum that Russia should adopt
the euro to ease its grave economic and social plight.
</P>
<P>
   Gold and currency reserves held by the 11 partners in the
European monetary union exceed those of the United States and Japan
combined. ``Size is critical,'' says C. Fred Bergsten, director of
the Institute for International Economics, a Washington-based
research group.
</P>
<P>
   Bergsten told the forum that Europe and America should cut a
deal that would keep the dollar and the euro in sync with each
other, within a loosely defined trading band.
</P>
<P>
   But Willem Duisenberg, head of the European Central Bank, told
the gathering that price stability counts for more protecting the
dollar against a surging euro. Duisenberg said he favors a
``tripolar system,'' based on the dollar, the euro and yen, once
the Japanese recover their fiscal footing.
</P>
<P>
   Although Tokyo markets remain weak, Masayuki Matsushima, who
heads the Bank of Japan, called the introduction of the euro on
Jan. 1 ``a great political event'' that has already had a major
impact on Asian ideas about future economic links.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Asians have a ways to go. Over a dinner with
journalists, Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir bin Mohamad boasted
that his currency, the ringgit, no longer can re-enter Malaysia and
was worthless when taken abroad. ``We have driven the currency
speculators from the scene,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The logic behind these patterns calls for a single planetary
unit of value, a system that would end currency speculation and
ensure fiscal stability once and for all. Based on Duisenberg's
tripolar concept, the dollar-euro-yen, or the dey, would restore
the way things were during Roman Empire, when a single gold-based
currency was used by people everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   It's an idea that would get you laughed out of the Davos
meeting. But perhaps in a generation or so, hotels here will bill
in deys.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass is a Washington, D.C.-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers. His e-mail address is aglass(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
