<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 10:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1565 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN07-CO     02-04 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Falwell's quasi-apologies are old-hat
 &HT;    For release Sunday, Feb. 7, 1999.
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now that the Rev. Jerry Falwell has apologized for publicly
stating that the Antichrist is a Jewish male who probably is alive
today, are we all expected to turn the other cheek and forgive the
man?
</P>
<P>
   What for? This isn't the first time he's done something like
this.
</P>
<P>
   In 1985, he went to South Africa to voice support for the white
regime there and called Bishop Desmond Tutu ``a phony,'' adding
that Tutu was not a legitimate leader of South Africa's blacks.
</P>
<P>
   He apologized for that, too, much in the way he apologized for
the Antichrist remark: partly.
</P>
<P>
   He said he did not mean to impugn Tutu's religious role or
integrity but maintained that any claim by Tutu that he was a
political spokesman for South African blacks was phony. And he
stuck by that. Even President Reagan, a close friend of Falwell's,
disavowed the reverend's remarks.
</P>
<P>
   In his stirring of anti-Jewish emotions several weeks ago, after
he told a Tennessee audience that the Antichrist was a Jew, Falwell
defended himself with a press statement saying that, based on
certain portions of the Scriptures, he really believes what he
said. (He also said there is honest disagreement among evangelical
Christians about that issue, that some believe the Antichrist will
be a Gentile.)
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, he admitted later, the Tennessee sermon lacked
tact and judgment. So he apologized, not for what he believes _ he
still thinks the Antichrist is a Jew _ but for making the statement
publicly. But, he concluded, he did not think his Antichrist
pronouncement to be anti-Semitic.
</P>
<P>
   And now we are to forgive, I suppose.
</P>
<P>
   There are some guys who can get away with shooting their mouths
off and some who cannot. Falwell presumably can; so can Reggie
White, the football player/ordained minister who made that medieval
speech to the Wisconsin
</P>
<P>
   Legislature last March stereotyping Hispanics, Jews, blacks and
homosexuals. He had a great season for the Green Bay Packers, never
had to apologize.
</P>
<P>
   Two men who could not get away with it were Los Angeles Dodgers
executive Al Campanis and CBS football analyst Jimmy ``The Greek''
Snyder. After they made comments regarding anatomical abilities or
disabilities of black athletes, they were exiled into a land-based
hell, eventually to their graves.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not defending those two men, although what Snyder said could
be defended, but I'm trying to determine why they were cast out
while Falwell and White were not. Does this have something to do
with the fact that they are ministers? Can ordained persons get
away with anything?
</P>
<P>
   Falwell, when he's not partly apologizing for his incendiary
remarks, spends much of his time trying to convince the public that
Bill Clinton had a hand in the murders of everyone who has died in
the last few decades; videotapes and booklets available for a
price.
</P>
<P>
   He leaps across the line between religion and politics as the
separation of church and state becomes even more blurred these
days.
</P>
<P>
   There are some in the Christian Right who do have tact and
judgment. Falwell doesn't. ``I apologize to my Jewish friends here
and around the world and I apologize to the Christians here for
having created any kind of rift,'' he said last week.
</P>
<P>
   And what will he say next for which he will later apologize?
What he needs to learn is to control his mouth from the start. I
know he's entitled to his beliefs; I've got a bunch of my own. But
I know when and not when to enunciate them.
</P>
<P>
   What I would like to do with Falwell is what my mother always
did with me when I uttered a profanity: Wash his mouth out with
soap!
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
