<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990204.0128 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 10:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1566 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN07-COX     02-04 0567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Dancing on the Constitution
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Impeachment Two-Step that many Republican senators are
tempted to dance is a constitutional abomination that, of all
people, legislators who fancy themselves conservative should recoil
from with horror.
</P>
<P>
   The framers of the Constitution pointedly set the high threshold
of a two-thirds majority for conviction by the Senate to avoid just
the sort of sly partisanship that would be enshrined in precedent
if the Senate goes through with this mischief.
</P>
<P>
   No less conservative a legal scholar than Robert Bork has argued
persuasively against the approach.
</P>
<P>
   The scheme would first have the Senate vote on whether, as a
matter of fact, the president is guilty as the House asserts. A
majority _ readily available, of course _ would make that
declaration. Then a second vote would decide whether President
Clinton should be removed. That would take the two-thirds vote that
is not at hand.
</P>
<P>
   There is a surface appeal to this approach, if only by analogy.
Don't courts first decide guilt or innocence and then, if the
verdict is guilty, decide punishment? Indeed, but impeachment isn't
a copy of criminal trials and wasn't meant to be. It is a
profoundly political process, meant to remove officials whose
misdeeds are judged to pose a danger to the fundamental workings of
the state, issues of criminal guilt or innocence aside.
</P>
<P>
   Even sticking with the lame comparison, however, the suggested
approach fails. For the procedure's imitation court findings to be
valid, a judge would first have to consider, as the impeachment
process has not, whether the charges are specific enough, whether
evidence was illegally obtained and whether prosecutorial
misconduct tainted any hope of a fair trial.
</P>
<P>
   But there are far larger reasons for shunning this approach than
its mere failure as an analogy.
</P>
<P>
   First, if the idea isn't unconstitutional it is certainly
extra-constitutional, subverting the express intent of the framers.
The Constitution says that upon impeachment and conviction, a
president ``shall'' be removed from office. It doesn't say
``whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   Second, the precedent would set subsequent presidencies up for
harassment by quasi-impeachment whenever the White House and
Congress were in different partisan hands. The constitutional
balance of power between the executive and legislative branches
would be permanently distorted.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Republicans are playing with this goofy idea for several
political reasons and no good ones.
</P>
<P>
   They don't want to seem to be saying House Republicans went off
half cocked. (But they did!) They fear Clinton will otherwise claim
he has been exonerated. (Unlikely. He must know many who have hung
with him would gag on that. But even if he did, so what?) And the
ploy would, heh-heh, corner Democrats into appearing to vote to
retain a president who has been proved guilty. (Of something; the
articles are vague.)
</P>
<P>
   The Constitution doesn't suggest the Senate hold a kangaroo
court. It calls for a straight up or down vote on the articles of
impeachment, period. It is time to take that vote.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
