<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 10:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1569 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-QUOTAS-BOS &LR;      02-04 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-QUOTAS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SWITCH, BOSTON WON'T APPEAL THE LATIN CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH DALEY AND ANDY DABILIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston School Committee, fearing possible damage to school
desegregation efforts nationwide, has decided not to ask the
Supreme Court to rule on the constitutionality of the city's
admissions policy for Boston Latin School.
</P>
<P>
   The unanimous vote comes after weeks of intense campaigning by
local and national minority and education leaders to persuade the
committee not to appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Those groups, including the NAACP and the US Department of
Education, believed the case would lose before a high court
unfriendly to affirmative action, thus leaving school systems
across the nation vulnerable to challenges from parents who don't
want race-based student assignment of any kind.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a case that would be isolated to Boston,'' said
Boston School Superintendent Thomas Payzant after the vote. ``The
whole country would have to live with the decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Only two months ago, the School Committee said the case was so
important it had to be decided by the Supreme Court, and voted to
appeal. Wednesday night, School Committee members and Payzant
defended that choice, saying it was the only one available at the
time.
</P>
<P>
   The prestigious school has been challenged twice in the past
three years by white students asserting the race-based admissions
policy was unconstitutional and unfairly cost them seats at Latin.
</P>
<P>
   The decision does not affect next year's admissions to Latin and
the city's two other exam schools. The committee had already
decided to have a race-blind admissions policy for the magnet
schools while the case was being appealed. But now, the School
Committee will have to devise a new admissions policy that will
both withstand constitutional scrutiny and ensure some level of
diversity in the exam schools.
</P>
<P>
   They also will have to do the same for exam-school prep classes.
The committee voted 4-2 Wednesday to have a one-year race-blind
admission policy for those classes also.
</P>
<P>
   Any formula will be difficult: A federal court has twice ruled
that two admissions policies were too unfavorable to white
students. The latest policy that school officials had to dismantle
admitted half of the students to the exam schools based on test
scores and grades only, while the other half were admitted based on
scores, grades, and race. The original policy had set aside 35
percent of seats for blacks and Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be hard. But it's almost like a diversion when they
start talking about diversity,'' said Steve Backman, a Boston
public school parent who wants the system to use other admission
criteria for the exams schools, such as examples of student work.
``The reason so many people are so unhappy with who gets in is
because they only rely on one test. We need other methods.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, a Dorchester ninth-grader became the second white
girl to challenge Latin's admission policy, saying she was denied
entrance despite scoring better than minorities who got a seat. The
School Committee's policy prevailed in a lower court but, in
November, an appeals court ruled it was unconstitutional and
ordered the plaintiff, Sarah Wessmann, to be admitted to the
school. The School Committee decided to appeal in December.
</P>
<P>
   The School Committee's reversal highlights a new, concerted
national effort by civil rights groups to keep public school
affirmative action away from the conservative court. The Supreme
Court has never ruled on a secondary public school race-based
admission policy. But it has consistently ruled against affirmative
action cases in the public and higher education sector.
</P>
<P>
   In Piscataway, N.J., the School Board in 1997 decided not to
defend to the Supreme Court the layoff of a white teacher to retain
a black teacher. The board settled the case using money from civil
rights groups, in part to avoid giving the Supreme Court a possible
precedent-setting case, according to news accounts.
</P>
<P>
   And Boston, national, and local leaders said that was their
reasoning in urging the committee not to appeal. The NAACP, which
was part of the original case, loudly decried the planned appeal in
recent months.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have over 50 years of history and clearly, the case is not
strong enough,'' said Leonard Alkins, head of the Boston NAACP
branch. ``The nationwide dangers outweigh any benefit to the
city.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, while the decision may have some minority leaders and
school superintendents nationwide breathing a sigh of relief over
busing programs, Boston is already facing an end to its 25-year
desegregation program. Two weeks ago, Mayor Thomas M. Menino
declared that the city will return to neighborhood schools within
six years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This vote is an indication they are at the end of the road and
reality is staring them in the face,'' said City Councilor at Large
Peggy Davis-Mullen. ``They need to proceed to not assigning any
student to schools by race.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
