<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Postage stamp column prompts letters
 &HT;    By Ernest Murray
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ Letters, I get letters...
</P>
<P>
   A recent column on my misadventures at the post office prompted
some quick responses.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Arthur Logan of Cincinnati, Ohio, writes:
</P>
<P>
   ``Get a life! You don't have enough wit to be a Dave Barry, so
stick to editing as opposed to writing.
</P>
<P>
   ``You obviously don't have the mental muscle of the financial
side of your business because you don't understand the great
benefit of controlling costs, saving consumers money and still
making a profit as the post office is doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're doing a great job of destroying the trust the American
public has in newspapers. Your type of arrogance will lead to the
demise of another newspaper and no one will be the wiser.''
</P>
<P>
   DBuis1055(at)aol.com E-mails:
</P>
<P>
   ``As a postal worker myself, I hear a lot of comments like yours
from other customers. I sometimes wish we had competition on the
first class monopoly so people like you could go somewhere else!
Maybe that's what you want?''
</P>
<P>
   And on a happier note, Mr. Joseph E. Caldwell of Charlotte, N.C.
writes:
</P>
<P>
   ``Lewinsky talks constructive''
</P>
<P>
   ``Olympic panel expels 6 members''
</P>
<P>
   ``S. African violence escalates''
</P>
<P>
   ``Girl, 16, to fight on front lines''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yikes and good grief! Why, oh why do I buy the newspaper?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well _ 'Zits,' two local dudes in the paper, Doug Robanchek
and Tommy Tomlinson, and the all-too-rare little story like yours
today in the Observer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to the post office for some one-cents but they were
out, so I blithely put on two 32s per envelope. Things like
mortgage, electric, cable, etc. gotta be paid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Though I'm but 55, I recall my folks talking in 1947 or so
about rationing in WWII. Hmm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never been to Lufkin. Back in '85 a gal and I left Charlotte
on a sort of Jack Kerouac 'On the Road' thing. I-40 to Flagstaff.
Back to Santa Rosa, then through Lubbock, Abilene, Shreveport and
New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man, Y'all got a big state.''
</P>
<P>
   For better or worse, thanks to all who wrote. And Mr. Caldwell,
if you ever do get to Lufkin, look me up at the paper. I'll be in
the newsroom, not the accounting department.
</P>
<P>
   Ernest Murray is managing editor of The Lufkin Daily News.
E-mail: emurray(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
