A1608 &Cx1f; tad-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GERMANY-NOINTEREST05-     02-04 1061
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-NOINTEREST05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Despite Germany's efforts, Jewish travelers not interested in
visiting
 &HT;    By Douglas Belkin
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Sam Hamill and his wife Estelle are
taking a three-week tour of Eastern Europe this summer: Poland,
Austria, Hungary and a host of other countries. Germany, Estelle
says, as if stating the obvious, will not be among them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not interested,'' the suburban Boynton Beach woman says,
waving her hand dismissively. ``There's plenty of other places that
I'd rather go.''
</P>
<P>
   And that, the German government says, is an attitude it would
like to change.
</P>
<P>
   More than half a century after the Third Reich tried to
annihilate Jewish people, shiny brochures filled with smiling
countrymen and bucolic landscapes printed by the German National
Tourist Board are inviting them back.
</P>
<P>
   A 36-page pamphlet called ``Germany for the Jewish Traveler'' is
the first public relations tool of its kind put out by the German
government. An expanded version is planned next year.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike general tourism brochures, many of which make no mention
of the war or the Holocaust, ``Germany for the Jewish Traveler''
deals with it head-on. The brochure calls the history of the
Rhineland ``ruthless'' and ``unparalleled in human history'' while
tracing regional anti-Semitism back to the 12th century.
</P>
<P>
   But the apology-cum-invitation hasn't had the desired effect so
far, tourism experts say.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Gilbert, a travel agent who specializes in Jewish tourism
and who last week received an unsolicited copy of Deutschland
Magazine from the German government, said there has not been so
much as a ripple of interest among her Jewish clientele.
</P>
<P>
   ``They may be trying to create something, but so far I haven't
had a single inquiry,'' Gilbert said.
</P>
<P>
   Employees of Isram Travel in New York, one of the largest
operators of European tours in the United States, say trips
centered on ethnicity and heritage in Eastern Europe have steadily
increased since perestroika opened the region a decade ago. But for
Jews, that has not carried over to Germany. A first-of-its-kind
trip marketed toward American Jews and focusing on Jewish history
in Berlin offered last year was canceled because enough people
didn't sign up.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no interest,'' said Eileen Hart, the company's vice
president of marketing. ``And it's like anything else, we need to
offer trips that sell.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the lack of interest here, there is a tremendous amount
of state-sponsored emphasis on Jewish history and culture in
Germany. Most major cities have Jewish war memorials and museums,
guide books point out. And Germany is home to one of the
fastest-growing Jewish communities in Europe. Though only 6,000 of
the country's pre-war Jewish population of 400,000 survived the
war, about 70,000 Jews, many emigres from the former Soviet Union,
have since moved there.
</P>
<P>
   That immigration is partly motivated by the declining Russian
economy, but it also has roots in the German government's intense
effort to make amends for its past. Since 1951 more than $60
billion in restitution has been paid to Jews and the nation of
Israel, according to Hannelore Kohler, an officer at the German
Information Center in New York. A high school exchange program
between Germany and Israel has been going on for years and nearly
120,000 Germans travel to Israel annually.
</P>
<P>
   The sheer number of publicly supported memorials to victims of
the Holocaust and the once-thriving German Jewish community is
impressive. In Berlin alone, there is a Jewish Department of the
Berlin Museum, a Holocaust exhibit titled ``Topography of Terror''
and a new Berlin Jewish Museum under construction. A national
Holocaust memorial is being debated.
</P>
<P>
   Not far away is the Wives of Jewish Husbands memorial, dedicated
to the hundreds of non-Jewish women who successfully protested the
arrest of their Jewish husbands in 1943; a German resistance
memorial marking where two Nazi generals plotted to kill Hitler;
and a Walter Rathenau Memorial, dedicated to a German Jew who was
appointed foreign minister in 1922 and later assassinated.
</P>
<P>
   The nearby Wannsee Villa, where the Holocaust was engineered in
January 1942, is also now a museum.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Leonid Feldman of Temple Emanu-El in Palm Beach said he
has been approached by members of his congregation to travel to
Eastern Europe and he would like to include Germany.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is obviously going to be an emotional issue for some
people,'' Feldman said. ``But I think we have to be frank _ the
fact is Germany has done an amazing job cleaning up their act and
being a very close friend to the Jewish people.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, any sea change in attitudes may take another generation.
The feelings of American Jews, especially older Jews, remain
largely rooted in the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was on the outskirts of the country once,'' said Sonya
Cornell, a grandmother who lives in Delray Beach. ``And I felt very
uncomfortable. You can feel the history in the air. They are mean
people. They are a cruel people, I can't get over that.''
</P>
<P>
   There is another side to that loathing. Helga Brenner-Kahn, of
the German Tourism Board in New York, said the catalyst for the New
York-produced brochure _ as well as ``From Horror to Hope,''
printed by the German Information Center _ was the number of
questions her office fields about German-Jewish history from
tourists.
</P>
<P>
   But the Jewish Traveler brochure _ of which 10,000
English-language copies were printed _ marks an about-face in the
way the tourism board has dealt with the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1992 brochure called ``Today's Germany,'' the third page
contains a section titled ``A Country with a Great History.'' In a
single page the history of Germany is outlined from the Saxons and
Bavarians right up to the unification of East and West Germany.
Neither Hitler nor the Holocaust is mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was rushed,'' Brenner-Kahn said.
</P>
<P>
   The board's more forthright attitude has extended to public
relations efforts for recent events such as this year's celebration
of the 250th birthday of the poet Goethe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you in the press releases about Goethe's
birthplaces, we made it a point to mention Buchenwald, which is
very near.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
