</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE FEATURES BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These feature stories are moving today to clients of the New
York Times News Service. Stories are for release Friday, February
5, 1999, unless otherwise embargoed.
</P>
<P>
   So specialty editors won't have to look at every day's budget,
Cox's features budgets have daily themes according tothis schedule:
</P>
<P>
   Monday for Tuesday: Technology
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday for Wednesday: Automotive
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday for Thursday: Food, CD reviews, video reviews
</P>
<P>
   TODAY: Movie reviews, travel, books and fashion
</P>
<P>
   Friday for Saturday: Religion, science &AMP; health, and home &AMP;
garden
</P>
<P>
   In addition, separate budgets move daily with spot news, sports,
business and commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the category they're listed under. Stories
moving to duplicate categories are marked. An ETA is given if a
story will move after 8 p.m. Eastern.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   SAVE TIME: Stories marked as a CoxNet layout are available for
purchase in paginated form: www.nytsyn.com/pageexpress.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE-MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-TESTS _ CHICAGO _ Resistance testing _ checking whether a
particular strain of the AIDS virus is susceptible or resistant to
various AIDS drugs _ could be a powerful tool in the future,
particularly for pregnant women, infants and people who are already
resistant to several drugs, a study says. The Conference on
Retroviruses and Opportunistic Infections ends in Chicago Thursday.
(Kim, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH-BRIEFS _ Health Watch briefs from the CDC. (Guthrie,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL
</P>
<P>
   COXNET-TRAVEL 0129: Worlds collide at Bellagio, the grandest and
most ambitious resort that Las Vegas has witnessed. Developer Steve
Wynn, whose Mirage and Treasure Island casinos are nearby on the
Strip, has loaded Bellagio with so many options for fine dining,
entertainment and cultural enrichment that he has effectively upped
the ante on what this tackier-than-thou gambling kingdom expects
from its glittery citadels. (Kessler, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   FIRST-TIME GAMBLER -- Craps? blackjack? poker? I hadn't
considered any of these games since my last 9th grade sleepover.
Then I saw Banana-Rama. (Kessler, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL BRIEFS _ Exhibits in the Northeast to focus on Black
History Month (Staff, N.Y. Times News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (EDS: This is the CoxNet Travel page for the current week. This
layout is now available.)
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-NOINTEREST _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Despite Germany's
public relations efforts, many Jews are not interested in traveling
to the country. (Belkin, Palm Beach Post) MOVED SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   GETAWAY-FESTIVALS _ Southern happenings. (Thrasher, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   FASHION
</P>
<P>
   STYLE-TEDDYS _ Funny, how men flounder around lingerie shops
every Valentine's Day when the inventor of modern day lingerie was
a man. Some 75 years ago, Theodore Baer invented the silky
``teddy'' for women to wear under their suddenly-popular flapper
dresses. Photo-driven centerpiece focuses on the best teddie's
available (both the lingerie and huggable varieties). (Walton,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH COLOR PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Embargoed until Sunday, Feb. 7
</P>
<P>
   FASHION-BUCHMAN _ Dana Buchman, a Tennessee native, doesn't
quite design in the fast lane. During Fashion Week this month in
New York, she will present her collection in her showroom instead
of on the runway. And she doesn't bother with the
wear-my-dress-for-the-Oscars pleading with celebrities. ``I'm not
into that kind of promotion,'' she says. (Her Luxe line, however,
does include gowns.) Buchman caters to women like her, the
35-and-older crowd, the kind now waiting for her fashion show and
pecking at their salads. (Anna, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   COXNET ENTERTAINMENT 0204 _ Part comedy, part drama, ``Sports
Night'' is this TV season's critical darling, even as it struggles
for ratings (it often trails Fox's ``Guinness World Records:
Primetime'' and WB's ``Felicity''). And don't even think, despite
the title, that it's about sports. (Kloer, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   STAR FILE _ Q&AMP;A with actor Mel Gibson (Ringel, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   RINGEL ON VIDEO _ So, you're having football withdrawals now
that the Superbowl is over. Never fear, there are plenty of classic
football movies to help ease your pain. (Ringel, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO REVIEWS _ ``There's Something About Mary,'' ``Mulan.''
(Staff, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
