<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 10:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1614 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILNER-ON-BOOKS05-COX     02-04 0557
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILNER-ON-BOOKS05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It just goes to show that you can't never tell
 &HT;    By Jay Milner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ The headline over the New York World's review of
the brand new novel April 12, 1925, was: ``F. Scott Fitzgerald's
Latest a Dud.''
</P>
<P>
   The novel was ``The Great Gatsby.''
</P>
<P>
   A few days late a book reviewer named Isabel Patterson wrote in
the New York Herald Tribune that ``The Great Gatsby'' was ``neither
profound nor durable.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the reputedly brilliant H.L. Mencken called ``The Great
Gatsby'' ``not more than a glorified anecdote, and not too probable
at that.''
</P>
<P>
   And so on and on. There were a few reviewers who praised the
short novel by the young Fitzgerald, but they apparently were in
the minority, and their praise was light.
</P>
<P>
   I found those and other reviews of Fitzgerald's 1925 classic in
an old (1971) paperback edition of ``In His Time,'' a collection of
essays, letters, reviews and other pieces by and about Fitzgerald
and his work. It proved once again, as my wife likes to point out
from time to time, ``that you can't never tell.''
</P>
<P>
   So, 75 years later, the 100 best American books of the century
are chosen by a distinguished panel and No. 2 on the list is none
other than Fitzgerald's ``The Great Gatsby.''
</P>
<P>
   What does this prove about reviewers, then and now? I'm not sure
I know. It might be that those 1925 reviewers, including the
brilliant H.L. Mencken, were too close to the time to see that
Fitzgerald's short novel was, and is, the story of America. I'm not
even sure Fitzgerald himself was aware of this when he wrote it.
I'd guess he didn't, that he was just writing what he saw and heard
and he had a discerning eye and ear.
</P>
<P>
   Mencken, in his rather detailed rant against the book, wrote:
``The theme is the old one of a romantic and preposterous love _
the ancient fidelis ad urnum motif reduced to a macabre humor. The
principal personage is a bounder typical of those parts _ a fellow
who seems to know everyone and yet remains unknown to all _ a young
man with a great deal of mysterious money, the tastes of a movie
actor and, under it all, the simple sentimentality of a somewhat
sclerotic fat woman....
</P>
<P>
   ``This clown Fitzgerald rushes to his death in nine short
chapters. The other performers in the Totentanz are of a like, or
even worse quality... ``
</P>
<P>
   ``The story is obviously unimportant,'' Mencken continued,
``...it is certainly not to be put on the same shelf with, say, ``
'This Side of Paradise.' `` And so on and on.
</P>
<P>
   Makes me wonder about my own ``reviews.'' I don't even know what
fidelis ad urnum means, not to mention what a ``sclerotic fat
woman'' looks like. You see, ``The Great Gatsby'' is, in my
unhumble opinion, one of the best American novels ever written. Do
I, therefore, know what I'm talking about?
</P>
<P>
   Oh yes, here's an item: ``James Joyce's 'Ulysses' was voted the
most essential classic novel for the next 100 years by 47 critics
and writers polled by the British bookseller Waterstones. Second
was Fitzgerald's 'The Great Gatsby', followed by Proust's
'Remembrance of Things Past.' ``
</P>
<P>
   To quote one of my best friends, ``that just goes to show you
can't never tell.''
</P>
<P>
   Jay Milner writes for Cox newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
