u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET     02-04 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Thursday, Feb. 4, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Friday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUYING-VOTES (Oakland, Calif.) _ A Democratic Party offer of
free chicken and potato salad to get voters to the polls in
Oakland's 16th Assembly District race ``comes very close to the
perception of buying votes,'' but does not break the law, according
to the Secretary of State's office. By MARSHA GINSBURG.
</P>
<P>
   WILD-PARROTS (San Francisco) _ Mark Bittner, caretaker of the 50
curious wild parrots who frequent Telegraph Hill, is being forced
to flee the coup. The 120-year-old home he's been living in is
scheduled for a major renovation, since it has no foundation, and
the property owner has asked him to leave. By MACKENZIE WARREN.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-SCHOOLS (Sacramento, Calif.) _ Gov. Gray Davis' plan to
require a high-school graduation test is drawing questions from
Latino groups and some Democratic lawmakers over whether more
minority students would fail the exam or drop out of school. By
ROBERT SALLDAY.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   LOST-AND-FOUND (Albany, N.Y.) _ Easy come. Easy go. You can't
take it with you. Or, sometimes, keep it on you. From Grand Central
Terminal in Manhattan to Walt Disney World, lost and found items
pile up everywhere. Walt Disney World collects Space Mountain
casualties _ wigs and toupees _ amid its 1,000-item daily intake of
lost items. By KATE GURNETT.
</P>
<P>
   LOST-AND-FOUND-NET (Albany, N.Y.) _ Golf clubs. Your relatives.
Porcelain China. A homing pigeon. These lost items, and more, are
being sought on a myriad of Internet sites dedicated to
lost-and-found items. By KATE GURNETT.
</P>
<P>
   DREADLOCKS-CONVENTION (San Francisco) _ Staajabu, who goes by
only one name, is proud of her dreadlocks. In a show of support for
other dreadlock fans, she is presenting the second annual Dreadlock
Conference on Saturday in Sacramento. It will explore topics such
as the history of dreadlocks, tips on caring for locked hair,
employment rights and laws protecting people with dreadlocks. By
VENISE WAGNER.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-SUNDANCE (Park City, Utah) _ ``Wear warm shoes and don't
take anything personally.'' Such was the warning from one movie
industry insider as I prepared to attend my first Sundance Film
Festival _ an obligatory rite of passage and shivery initiation for
anyone more than casually concerned with the future of independent
(i.e., idea-driven) cinema in this country. By JOHN KRICH.
</P>
<P>
   TV-THE-60S (Undated) _ ``The '60s,'' the NBC miniseries, is much
like the decade it ambitiously sets out to portray. It starts out
with great promise, but in the end leaves almost everyone who went
through it disillusioned. By MARK McGUIRE.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-GRIFFITH-PROFILE (Undated) _ Actress Melanie Griffith says
her up-and-down career shifts don't bother her, especially now that
she is happily married to actor Antonio Banderas. Griffith stars in
``Another Day in Paradise,'' which opens Friday at theaters
nationwide. By LOUIS B. PARKS.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-IRRESISTIBLE-REVIEW (Undated) _ There's nothing funny,
romantic or interesting about ``Simply Irresistible,'' a romantic
comedy starring actress Sarah Michelle Gellar. Gellar, TV's ``Buffy
the Vampire Slayer'' is doing no interviews for this film. Clearly,
she wants to forget it. By LOUIS B. PARKS.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-CAKE (Undated) _ John McCrea of the band Cake says he gets
tired very easily, but there's nothing boring about a Cake
performance. Cake's music acts as a postmodern recycling bin for
pop-culture kitsch. Herb Alpert trumpet lines intersect with
wailing P-Funk keyboards, and disco bass lines bump up against
crying pedal-steel guitars. By RICK MITCHELL.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   RICH-WOMEN (San Francisco) _ Sometimes the biggest career
mistake you can make has nothing to do with your career at all. It
has to do with money. In ``Smart Women Finish Rich,'' author David
Bach provides financial tips _ such as taking full advantage of
401(k) programs _ that men also need to consider. By DAVE MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   OVER-40-BIAS (San Francisco) _ ``Finished at 40,'' the recent
cover story in Fortune magazine, raises some startling issues about
bias in the workplace against older workers. Here's how to cope
with the stereotype _ and show that older can be better. By DAVE
MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PASTA (Albany, N.Y.) _ Pasta may be the perfect food. It's easy,
convenient, inexpensive and, thanks to the Food and Drug
Administration, it's more nutritious than ever. By RUTH FANTASIA.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Here's a novel approach to
dealing with the San Francisco Board of Supervisors' penchant for
excessive lawmaking: Limit each supervisor to one piece of
legislation per month. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ For refusing to admit that she
and the president had an affair, Monica Lewinsky was threatened
with prison and made to testify more than 20 times _ most recently
this week. Her privacy has been invaded in a manner unmatched in
U.S. history, and she's been robbed of a life for the last 13
months. By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
</TEXT>
