<HEADLINE>
SLATE 60: LARGEST AMERICAN CHARITABLE CONTRIBUTIONS OF 1998  
 COMPILED BY ANN CASTLE
</HEADLINE>
  (www.slate.com) 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Note: The list actually runs to 65. The last eight contributors
are tied at $15 million. A tie among several contributors will
account for numerical gaps in the list. Following is an abbreviated
list; for the complete list, see BC-LIST-LONG-SLATE-NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   1. JAMES E. JR. and VIRGINIA STOWERS--$327 million to create the
INSTITUTE FOR MEDICAL RESEARCH in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   2. MARTHA R. INGRAM--$300 million worth of Ingram Micro stock to
VANDERBILT UNIVERSITY (Tenn.) to support athletics, health care,
public service, research, and teaching.
</P>
<P>
   3. DAVID and CHERYL DUFFIELD--a $200 million pledge toward
finding a home for every stray or abandoned dog and cat in America.
The donation was inspired by the Duffields' affection for their
longtime pet, a miniature schnauzer named Maddie. David Duffield is
a co-founder of human resources software maker PeopleSoft. The
gift, believed to be the largest ever made to help companion
animals, is intended to end the euthanasia of millions of homeless
dogs and cats and in the process create a ``no-kill nation.''
</P>
<P>
   3. KIRK KERKORIAN--a $200 million pledge to benefit the PEOPLE
OF ARMENIA from this 81-year-old son of Armenian emigres.
</P>
<P>
   3. ALFRED MANN--$100 million to the UNIVERSITY OF SOUTHERN
CALIFORNIA and $100 million to the UNIVERSITY OF CALIFORNIA AT LOS
ANGELES.
</P>
<P>
   6. BILL and MELINDA GATES--a total of $189.57 million, including
$100 million to the PROGRAM FOR APPROPRIATE TECHNOLOGY IN HEALTH.
</P>
<P>
   7. JAMES E. ROGERS--$178.5 million, including $130 million to
the UNIVERSITY OF ARIZONA.
</P>
<P>
   8. THE KATHRYN and JOE ALBERTSON FAMILY--a three year pledge of
$110 million to PUBLIC SCHOOLS IN IDAHO through the family
foundation.
</P>
<P>
   9. JOAN KROC--$105 million, including $80 million to San Diego's
SALVATION ARMY.
</P>
<P>
   10. RALPH and BETTY ENGELSTAD--$100 million to the UNIVERSITY OF
NORTH DAKOTA.
</P>
<P>
   10. SANFORD I. and JOAN WEILL--a $100 million pledge to the
CORNELL UNIVERSITY Medical School (N.Y.).
</P>
<P>
   12. THE SAM and HELEN WALTON FAMILY--$91.7 million, including
$50 million gift to the UNIVERSITY OF ARKANSAS College of Business
Administration.
</P>
<P>
   13. THE DANIEL R. EFROYMSON FAMILY--$90 million to the
INDIANAPOLIS FOUNDATION and the CENTRAL INDIANA COMMUNITY
FOUNDATION to create the Efroymson Family Fund.
</P>
<P>
   14. JAMES GABBERT and MIKE LINCOLN--$70 million to the land
conservation group TRUST FOR PUBLIC LAND in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   14. ARTHUR L. and ANGELA WILLIAMS--$70 million to LIBERTY
UNIVERSITY (Va.).
</P>
<P>
   16. THEODORE FORSTMANN--$50 million to the CHILDREN'S
SCHOLARSHIP FUND (Washington) to help more than 50,000 public
school children around the country attend private schools.
</P>
<P>
   16. W. JEROME ``JERRY'' FRAUTSCHI--$50 million to MADISON, WIS.,
for the development of a downtown cultural district.
</P>
<P>
   16. JOHN WALTON--$50 million to the CHILDREN'S SCHOLARSHIP FUND
as a companion gift to Theodore Forstmann's (above).
</P>
<P>
   19. PETER B. LEWIS--$49 million, including a $40 million pledge
added to Lewis' 1995 gift of $10 million to the SOLOMON R.
GUGGENHEIM FOUNDATION (N.Y.).
</P>
<P>
   20. GORDON and BETTY MOORE--$47.5 million, including $35 million
to CONSERVATION INTERNATIONAL (Washington).
</P>
<P>
   21. MICHAEL R. BLOOMBERG--$45 million to JOHNS HOPKINS
UNIVERSITY (Md.), adding to his 1995 ``first installment'' of $55
million.
</P>
<P>
   21. SHELBY M. C. and GALE DAVIS--$45 million to the ARMAND
HAMMER UNITED WORLD COLLEGE OF THE AMERICAN WEST near Santa Fe,
N.M.
</P>
<P>
   21. BERNARD MARCUS--$45 million to the KENNEDY KRIEGER
INSTITUTE, a Baltimore-based organization that treats children with
developmental disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   24. RICHARD D. COLBURN--A commitment of $42 million to the
COLBURN SCHOOL OF PERFORMING ARTS in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   25. JON HUNTSMAN--$40 million to the Wharton School of the
UNIVERSITY OF PENNSYLVANIA.
</P>
<P>
   26. GEORGE SOROS--$38.6 million, including $20 million to the
PUSHKIN PROJECT to fund Russia's cash-strapped provincial
libraries.
</P>
<P>
   27. KATHERINE B. LOKER--$34 million, including $17 million to
the UNIVERSITY OF SOUTHERN CALIFORNIA.
</P>
<P>
   28. THE JOSEPH L. and PHYLLIS MAILMAN FAMILY--$33 million
through their family's foundation to the COLUMBIA UNIVERSITY School
of Public Health (N.Y.).
</P>
<P>
   29. C. EDWARD and CAROLE McVANEY--$32.2 million to the
UNIVERSITY OF NEBRASKA in Lincoln.
</P>
<P>
   30. ROBERT E. McDONOUGH--$30 million to GEORGETOWN UNIVERSITY
(Washington).
</P>
<P>
   31. ALBERTO W. VILAR--a total of $29.1 million: $25 million to
the METROPOLITAN OPERA (N.Y.) in the form of a $20 million donation
and a $5 million challenge gift.
</P>
<P>
   32. TED TURNER--$27 million from the CNN founder to a variety of
organizations focusing on energy, water/toxins, forests/habitats,
and population issues.
</P>
<P>
   33. JOHN F. McDONNELL and JAMES S. McDONNELL III--26.5 million,
including $20 million to WASHINGTON UNIVERSITY School of Medicine
(St. Louis).
</P>
<P>
   33. ROBERT WOODWARD--$26.5 million ABILENE CHRISTIAN UNIVERSITY
(Texas).
</P>
<P>
   35. PAUL ALLEN--$26 million, including $10 million to the STATE
OF WASHINGTON for athletics facilities.
</P>
<P>
   36. WALTER and LEONORE ANNENBERG--$25 million, including $10
million for INDEPENDENCE MALL.
</P>
<P>
   36. DONALD and DORIS FISHER--$25 million to the EDISON PROJECT.'
</P>
<P>
   36. DARLA MOORE--$25 million to .
</P>
<P>
   36. MARY and ROBERT PEW--$25 millionto the COMMUNITY FOUNDATION
FOR PALM BEACH AND MARTIN COUNTIES (Fla.).
</P>
<P>
   36. DANIEL T. and MERLENE PHILLIPS--$25 million pledge to the
BOYS &AMP; GIRLS CLUBS OF AMERICA.
</P>
<P>
   36. DANIEL L. RITCHIE--An 18,000 acre parcel of land known as
the Jones Ranch, worth an estimated $25 million, to the UNIVERSITY
OF DENVER.
</P>
<P>
   36. JULIAN H. ROBERTSON JR.--$25 million to LINCOLN CENTER (New
York City).
</P>
<P>
   36. PETER and ADA EGBERT ROSSIN--$25 million to LEHIGH
UNIVERSITY (Pa.).
</P>
<P>
   36. RICHARD and DIANE SCRUGGS--$25 million to the UNIVERSITY OF
MISSISSIPPI.
</P>
<P>
   45. PAUL and DAISY SOROS--$24 million, including a $20 million
trust to help underwrite American graduate education for immigrants
and their children.
</P>
