<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 12:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1686 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PAYBACK-REVIEW-LADN     02-04 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAYBACK-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
Our rating: 3 stars 
By BOB STRAUSS  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Mel Gibson's sick streak gets another amusing
workout in ``Payback.'' It's a brutally jaunty, fanatically
fetishized, cartoon crime thriller.
</P>
<P>
   It's not really a remake of John Boorman's severe '60s
masterpiece ``Point Blank,'' but rather a different take on the
same Donald Westlake source novel, ``The Hunter.'' Neither is
``Payback'' a great movie like ``Blank'' was, though it's admirably
just as nasty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Payback'' doesn't need to be great, however. It's the kind of
movie that's so committed to its silly, relentless agenda, you're
beaten into enjoying it almost to the point where you'd ask for
more.
</P>
<P>
   Almost.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson is Porter (no last name, or is it no first?) a
professional crook who was left for dead by a double-crossing
partner (Gregg Henry's Val) and a scorned wife (Deborah Kara Unger)
after they successfully heisted $140,000 from Chinese money
launderers. But Porter survived two bullets in the back, and a few
months later he's back on the streets of a decrepit, unnamed
eastern city, seeking revenge and his half of the loot.
</P>
<P>
   Just his half? Nothing for pain and suffering? Seems so.
Porter's motives are pretty inscrutable, both to viewers and the
parade of Val's higher-up mob bosses (William Devane, James Coburn,
Kris Kristofferson), who keep thinking the implacable avenger wants
more money than he really does.
</P>
<P>
   What Porter really wants, apparently, is any excuse that
presents itself to kill a Val associate, regardless of how
peripherally they're connected to the flashy, pain-loving gangster.
Porter would also like a high-class hooker (``ER's'' Maria Bello),
whom he drove around in a previous incarnation, to quit the trade
and be his baby. His is a simple life, but a full one.
</P>
<P>
   An array of colorful secondary characters add a kind of richness
to the movie's minimalist, killing machine mechanics. David Paymer
is typecast, but effectively so, as a low-rent weasel who foolishly
views Porter's rampage as his ticket to a higher class of crime.
Bill Duke and Jack Conley register as a pair of distinctively
annoying, crooked cops.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's Lucy Liu. She plays Val's leather-clad
dominatrix Pearl, a sadomasochist of such dedication that she
swoons in ecstasy whenever guns are pointed in anyone's direction.
Objectification is way too weak a word to describe this act _
full-blown fantasy freakout is a little more accurate. Indeed, Liu
takes the lewd stereotype to such ridiculous lengths, it could be
said that she effectively demolishes it.
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, the actress, who plays ``Ally McBeal's''
uproariously uptight Ling, gets to cut loose here like nobody's
business. And let's face it: Pearl embodies everything this
pornographically vicious movie aspires to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Payback'' was co-adapted and directed, for the most part, by
Brian Helgeland, who's had wildly varying luck at screenwriting for
the films ``L.A. Confidential,'' ``The Postman'' and the
Gibson-starring ``Conspiracy Theory.'' That last one led Gibson,
whose company produced ``Payback,'' to give Helgeland a shot at
directing.
</P>
<P>
   The novice helmer had some good ideas, such as the
color-drained, cool blue look of the photography; its retro-faded
non-sheen helps to stabilize the crazy, comic book tone of the
action. Still, Gibson reportedly had a hunk of the film's final act
reshot by another, unnamed hand, supposedly because the actor was
worried that bad-to-the-bone Porter came off just a bit too
unredeemable for his movie-star image.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe. But the guy's still a violent sociopath, even if he is
the hero. And that's one of the few qualities that makes Gibson an
occasionally interesting actor.
</P>
<P>
   Like Clint Eastwood before him and Nicolas Cage since, Gibson is
one of Hollywood's few major movie stars who has a consistent
appreciation of perversity. ``Braveheart's'' savage butchery, his
genuinely unhinged work in the first ``Lethal Weapon,'' those
demented ``Mad Max'' dress-up derbies; Gibson clearly has a bent
for the bent.
</P>
<P>
   And he seems to enjoy himself so much more in those kinds of
things than in his serious or charm-dependent star turns. At least,
it appears he gets more comfortable as the mayhem gets kinkier.
</P>
<P>
   ``Payback'' isn't exactly a good movie, but it is good, dirty
fun. And it's good for Mel. And it's fun for us.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-04-99 1231EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990204.0152 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 12:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1687 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOE-REVIEW-LADN     02-04 0515
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOE-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
Our rating: 3 stars   &HT;    By BOB STRAUSS  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A fine, observant study of a recovering alcoholic
goes somewhat astray in ``My Name Is Joe.'' But for the most part,
it's an absorbing portrait of a good man who's cleaned up his act
but is ultimately undone by the messy world he inhabits.
</P>
<P>
   That restricted, hopeless locale is one of the poorer districts
of Glasgow, Scotland, and it says something about the nature of the
place that the film had to be subtitled for Americans to understand
it. The working-class accents _ make that nonworking-class accents
_ are emblematic of the locals' inescapable entrapment in their
neighborhood's pathological culture.
</P>
<P>
   Which is not the same thing as saying they're dumb, or even
necessarily doomed. Indeed, protagonist Joe Kavanagh (Peter Mullan,
in a Cannes Film Festival prize-winning performance) is as bright
and humorous and self-aware as a bloke could be, especially now
that he's flushed with the kind of optimistic drive many newly
sober addicts exhibit.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, director Ken Loach, the English radical with the
keen, sympathetic eye for society's castoffs, is not about to
depict Joe or his associates in any way that disrespects their
humanity. Though he's recently been indulging his penchant for
muddled, lefty politics in films such as ``Carla's Song'' and
``Land and Freedom,'' Loach's best films of late _ ``Riff-Raff,''
``Raining Stones,'' ``Ladybird, Ladybird'' _ all detail the
personal struggles of Britain's poor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe'' is terrifically compelling while it's doing just that.
Mullan exudes a middle-age everyguy charisma similar to that of
Paul Newman a few decades back. Though Joe is unemployed and just
slightly larcenous _ he drives the getaway van when members of the
ex-addicts soccer team he coaches steal a consignment of cool new
uniforms _ Mullan invests him with gruff sweetness and
nigh-irresistible charm.
</P>
<P>
   Joe is also touchingly vulnerable and wary of the dark side
drink brought out of him. While shyly but persistently wooing
government health counselor Sarah Downey (Louise Goodall), he tells
her right up front what a mean drunk he used to be. This does not
deter her from embarking on an affair with Joe any more than their
obvious class and education differences do. The relationship proves
a good one. Until ...
</P>
<P>
   A subplot involving a young soccer player (David McKay) and his
still-using wife (Anne-Marie Kennedy) takes on increasing
significance as both Joe and Sarah try to help the troubled couple.
As a result, and rather unconvincingly, Joe gets more and more
deeply involved with local mobsters. The film unnecessarily
descends into crime thriller cliches and violence, much of it an
apparent effort to force Joe back to the bottle.
</P>
<P>
   It feels like overkill. The virtues of ``My Name Is Joe'' may be
small, homely ones, but they would have been amply sufficient to
carry the film to a satisfying, less melodramatic conclusion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
