<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-THE-60S-HNS </SLUG>
  
 BUY THE MUSIC, BUT SKIP `THE 60s'  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK McGUIRE  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The '60s,'' the NBC miniseries, is much like the decade it
ambitiously sets out to portray. It starts out with great promise,
but in the end leaves almost everyone who went through it
disillusioned.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, yeah: And it has a great soundtrack.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with this two-part movie (Sunday and Monday, 9 p.m.
EDT, check local listings) is right there in its promotional tag
line, the double-entendre ``Movie Event of a Generation.'' It sets
out to do too much, promises more than it can deliver, and
disappoints all. This isn't even a movie event of a weekend.
</P>
<P>
   What viewers are left with is a four-hour excuse to link
together documentary footage we've seen before, show actors in
bizarre clothes and play cool tunes. This is ``Forrest Gump''
without the story.
</P>
<P>
   And that is too bad, since the tumultuous decade has enough
built-in dramatic confrontation _ militarily, culturally,
generationally, racially _ to fill a series. In short, NBC picked a
perfect vehicle for a miniseries _ and blew it.
</P>
<P>
   The network, which scored big time with its outstanding
``Temptations'' miniseries a few months back, went to the '60s well
once too often (its stab at the 1860s, an updating of ``The
Tempest,'' was lame). It's enough to make you angry, not because
it's so bad, but because it should have been so good.
</P>
<P>
   Executive Producer Lynda Obst was the editor/author of ``The
Rolling Stone History of the Sixties,'' and had the perfect
pedigree for the project. If she only had a script.
</P>
<P>
   The premise is solid: track the 1960s through the eyes of two
families, one black, the other white.
</P>
<P>
   The Herlihys are a middle-class Catholic clan from Chicago, with
eldest son, Brian (Jerry O'Connell), the football star and dad's
favorite. Middle son Michael (Josh Hamilton) is the straight-A's
kid with a social conscious, while daughter Katie (Julia Stiles)
grows up without anyone noticing until it's too late.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the Taylors, headed by Willie Taylor (Charles
Dutton), a black Baptist minister from Greenwood, Miss. He was an
early organizer for the Freedom Riders in the early '60s, but his
son Emmet (Leonard Roberts) does not share his belief in nonviolent
tactics.
</P>
<P>
   The two families cross paths on occasion _ Michael goes down to
Mississippi to a freedom march, Emmet and Katie are in
Haight-Asbury during the Summer of Love _ but mostly the fictional
characters are used as sketchy props to string together highlights
of the decade.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Herlihy signs up for the Marine Corps, excited to go to
Vietnam. He returns sullen and bitter: We can guess why he turned,
but they never show us the specific reasons other than shots of him
looking fierce and frightened in short battle scenes.
</P>
<P>
   Michael enters the anti-war movement, but we don't know how much
of his activism is out of conviction, and how much is part of an
effort to woo Sarah (Jordana Brewster), a Barnard College student
activist. Katie leaves home pregnant, but it's not made clear why
she can't return.
</P>
<P>
   We know why Emmet turns his cheek on nonviolence, but the story
of the Taylors is woefully undertold _ close to abandoned _ in the
second half of the story.
</P>
<P>
   The only character who is given any substance is Bill Herlihy
(Bill Smirtrovich of ``Life Goes On''). We understand his
conflicted rages and confusion as his children are caught up and
swept away in the evolving maelstrom of the times, a tide he is
unable to stem. In the end, the World War II veteran lets love
trump understanding; it was the only recourse.
</P>
<P>
   There are other flaws. We could go on, but you don't have to. If
you want, go ahead and buy the soundtrack (there really is a pretty
good one in stores: Bob Dylan (with Joan Osborne), The Temps, James
Brown, The Band, and Marvin Gaye, among others).
</P>
<P>
   As for the movie, figuring out what Dylan could possibly be
saying most of the time is easier than watching this mess.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the television and radio writer for the Albany
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. E-mail:
mmcguire(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
