<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE THREE-LAWS-AND-YOUR-OUT LAW 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Here's my simple idea for keeping the San
Francisco Board of Supervisors from spending its time passing
useless, symbolic ordinances: Limit each supervisor to one piece of
legislation per month.
</P>
<P>
   That would keep them from doing most of the silly things they do
_ like passing resolutions against pie-throwing, condemning the use
of animals in medical research and drafting ordinances limiting
handgun sales in San Francisco to one a month.
</P>
<P>
   You mean I'll only be able to buy 12 guns a year? I'll have to
cross the Bay to arm my militia?
</P>
<P>
   That isn't quite the issue here, nor is it whether you hate guns
and Charlton Heston. The issue is whether the legislation does
anything.
</P>
<P>
   You see, there's only one gun store in town, the San Francisco
Gun Exchange. Supervisor Michael Yaki's legislation isn't going to
do much, because the store doesn't sell heaps of cheap handguns to
middlemen who resell them to bad guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we saw someone buying in quantity, we'd notify the
authorities,'' said co-owner Bob Posner, who is on good terms with
all the law enforcement authorities because they shop at his store.
</P>
<P>
   Ask the authorities where the illegal guns come from. They'll
tell you, and those places are out of the city's jurisdiction.
</P>
<P>
   In San Francisco the main shooting sport is taking political
potshots at those who deal in politically incorrect products. The
Board of Supervisors is constantly popping away with small-bore
symbolic legislation in Posner's general direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, the Department of Parking and Traffic does more to
control sales of guns here because of all the cars they tow out
front,'' Posner said.
</P>
<P>
   The supervisors have more symbolic legislation to come. Yaki has
an ordinance drafted that would limit ammunition sales before New
Year's and the Fourth of July to prevent people from shooting guns
into the air.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that even idiots who shoot guns into the air know
enough to save up ammo for holidays. Never mind that no one in San
Francisco has ever been hit by a falling holiday bullet.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that the city's legislative analyst said the San
Francisco police only receive a half-dozen reports of gunshots on
each holiday, and most turn out to be firecrackers. Never mind that
shooting a gun within the city is a felony, and cops can arrest
idiots who do it.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to have symbolic laws that pretend to address gun
violence, but do nothing.
</P>
<P>
   As for San Francisco joining other cities in a lawsuit against
gun manufacturers, that's another issue, a complicated one.
</P>
<P>
   For example, part of the suit depends on holding manufacturers
responsible for not introducing personalized, high-tech safety
devices that haven't been invented yet and are likely never to be
practicable.
</P>
<P>
   It's tough to beat the gun makers. It's easier to pick on the
one gun store in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The supervisors should try doing some things that aren't purely
symbolic _ with their one piece of legislation per month.
</P>
<P>
   Pardon me, I'm a liberal, but I just have to say it: When
useless legislation is outlawed, only useless legislators will be
outlaws.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the supervisors really take the prize: Tom Ammiano's
color posters from the last election, showing him practically
wrapped in the flag, have won a national ``Polli'' award for best
poster from the American Association of Political Consultants.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty ironic, considering I tried to regulate political
consultants,'' Ammiano said.
</P>
<P>
   Now here's news that matters. Supervisor Mark Leno has declared
Feb. 11 as ``Wild Parrot Day'' in San Francisco. The 50 glorious
green parrots that live on Telegraph Hill will be starring in a
children's fable called ``The Wild Parrots of San Francisco'' by
Sundance Festival award winners Judy Irving and Christopher Beaver.
The movie is a mix of fiction and nonfiction, much like San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   There's another flock of parrots in San Francisco, a flock that
lives in the palms along Dolores Street. They're hungry and
starting to maraud, swooping in to bird feeders in Upper Noe
Valley.
</P>
<P>
   You have to love these parrots. Like many of us, they've found a
home in a curious place and made it curiouser.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
