<SLUG> BC-PASTA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PASTA, THE PERFECT FOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RUTH FANTASIA  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Pasta may be the perfect food.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy, convenient, inexpensive and, thanks to the Food and
Drug Administration, it's more nutritious than ever.
</P>
<P>
   Always low in calories (about 200 per cup cooked) and fat (one
to two grams per cup), manufacturers are now required to fortify
pasta with folate, a B vitamin that may prevent neural-tube birth
defects such as spina bifida and help reduce the risk of heart
disease.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, some flavored pastas contain large amounts of
dietary fiber. But watch out for sodium. While some pastas are
sodium-free, others contain as much as 45 milligrams per cup.
</P>
<P>
   Often, the most time-consuming thing about pasta is boiling the
water. So, put the pan of water on the stove as soon as you arrive
home and read the mail or talk to your family while you wait.
</P>
<P>
   Allow 3/4 cup dry pasta (about one cup cooked) for each serving
if using in a side dish or 1 1/2 cups dry if using as an entree. If
you have trouble figuring out how much spaghetti (or other long,
thin pasta) to add to the pot remember, one 1-pound box contains
enough for four entree servings.
</P>
<P>
   Don't fret about making too much; extra cooked pasta can be
tossed with a tablespoon of olive oil, sealed in a plastic bag and
refrigerated up to three days.
</P>
<P>
   Pasta sauces can be made from almost anything in a matter of
minutes. Here are a few suggestions:
</P>
<P>
   _ Cut 2 pork chops into thin strips. Heat 2 teaspoons olive oil
in a saute pan, toss in pork and 2 tablespoons pine nuts and cook
until pork is no longer pink. Toss pork mixture with cooked pasta
and top with fresh basil and parmesan cheese.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cook 1 (10-ounce) package frozen broccoli florets in microwave
for 3 to 4 minutes on high power. Drain well. Heat 2 tablespoons
olive oil in skillet. Add 2 cloves chopped garlic, 1/4 cup yellow
bell pepper strips, broccoli, 1/2 pound peeled shrimp, cooked
pasta, salt and pepper to taste. Cook until shrimp are pink and
pasta and vegetables are heated through. Drizzle with fresh lemon
juice.
</P>
<P>
   _ Heat 1 tablespoon olive oil in a large saute pan. Add 2 cloves
chopped garlic, 1 can chopped tomatoes, 1 teaspoon dried or 1
tablespoon fresh oregano, 1 teaspoon dried or 1 tablespoon fresh
basil and cooked pasta. When pasta and tomatoes are heated, add 1/2
cup crumbled feta cheese and toss until cheese begins to melt.
Serve with slivers of parmesan cheese on top.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
