<SLUG> BC-OVER-40-BIAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T BECOME A VICTIM OF OVER-40 BIAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVE MURPHY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Suppose affirmative action was changed to
include everyone over 40. How many politicians would have the
chutzpah to vote against it?
</P>
<P>
   Affirmative action is designed to help groups who are getting
discriminated against in the workplace, and people over 40
certainly qualify. How bad is it? The cover story in the Feb. 1
issue of Fortune magazine called ``Finished at 40.''
</P>
<P>
   If anyone ever did include people over 40, you can bet those
politicians who suddenly decided to embrace affirmative action
would come up with some justification for changing their minds.
They would not just come out and say, ``I know where my bread's
buttered _ and people over 40 have a lot of butter.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, those who have supported affirmative action
for decades might feel awkward. After all, people over 40 certainly
haven't faced the type of bigotry in society that racial minorities
have, and God knows there are tons of chief executives over 40.
</P>
<P>
   Workplace prejudice has been around forever. But for a lot of
people over 40 _ particularly white males _ this may be the first
time it has hit home.
</P>
<P>
   The Fortune story also mentions a 1998 survey by management
consulting firm Watson Wyatt Worldwide, which asked 773 chief
executives to identify the age when people's productivity peaked.
The average response was 43.
</P>
<P>
   Once in a while, people have the skill and the power to change
the system. If you have it, use it. But if you don't, here are some
ways to lessen the impact of age discrimination on your career:
</P>
<P>
   _ Understand the stereotype.
</P>
<P>
   Older workers won't work as hard as younger ones, they're more
set in their ways and they don't embrace new technology. That's the
stereotype.
</P>
<P>
   Is it true? Sure, sometimes. Name any stereotype and you can
always find someone who fits it; that's how it became a stereotype.
Once a stereotype is in place, it's almost impossible to get rid of
it because narrow-minded people will always find enough anecdotes
to reinforce their position.
</P>
<P>
   _ Expect people to deny that discrimination exists.
</P>
<P>
   There will continue to be plenty of workers over 40 or 50 or 60,
and companies will point to them and say, ``See? We don't
discriminate.'' They're the same sort of people who point to Jesse
Jackson and Colin Powell and Michael Jordan and say, ``See? Blacks
have equal opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   They're rationalizing. It's a waste of time to try to convince
them they're wrong.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't give people an excuse to extend the stereotype.
</P>
<P>
   Except in cases of extreme bigotry, companies find a way to keep
their top people. If you're not one of the top people at your
company _ at least within your classification _ either become one
or find another job or another company.
</P>
<P>
   If you find yourself going through the motions or saying
``that's not my job,'' you'll not only make it harder for yourself,
but for everyone else your age.
</P>
<P>
   _ Be better than the competition.
</P>
<P>
   If all you have are the same qualifications as someone 10 years
younger, getting or keeping a job will be almost impossible unless
you're a union member or have blackmail photos of the boss. The
younger workers have more potential than you do.
</P>
<P>
   Your experiences in work and in life give you a lot to offer an
employer. But that won't do you any good if you don't package it
well.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-04-99 1252EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990204.0158 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 12:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1710 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RICH-WOMEN-HNS &LR;      02-04 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RICH-WOMEN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOK OFFERS MONEY ADVICE FOR WOMEN THAT GUYS NEED, TOO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVE MURPHY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Sometimes the biggest career mistake you can
make has nothing to do with your career at all. It has to do with
the most tangible thing you get out of your career: money.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco financial adviser David Bach, author of the
recently published ``Smart Women Finish Rich,'' said in an
interview that workers of both sexes often don't get as much as
they can out of their pay and benefits. Here are some of his
workplace-related tips:
</P>
<P>
   _ Put as much as possible into your 401(k) plan.
</P>
<P>
   If your company lets you put in 15 percent of your salary, do
it, Bach said. He said that having money taken out of your paycheck
before you have the chance to spend it makes it simpler to save.
</P>
<P>
   The money that goes into your 401(k) isn't taxed at the time you
deposit it, so even putting in the 15 percent will reduce your
take-home pay by less than 10 percent because of the tax savings.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't try to time the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   It's best to invest for the long term, particularly with money
intended for retirement. Even if stocks seem to be near a peak,
Bach suggests putting your long-term money in them because
traditionally they have done so much better than bonds or bank
accounts.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just can't build enough for retirement if you invest too
conservatively,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to time the market often causes people to miss out on
major rallies. As an example, Bach said that if someone invested
$100 in the S&AMP;P 500 in 1946 and left it there for 50 years, it
would have grown to $31,000. If that person tried to time the
market, however, and missed just 5 percent of the best growth
months during those years, the investment would have grown to only
$2,000, he said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Take your 401(k) with you.
</P>
<P>
   When people leave a company, they often leave their 401(k) money
in their existing account rather than rolling it over into an IRA
or their new company's 401(k). That can cost you a lot of money.
</P>
<P>
   The 401(k) might have more fees than an IRA, and your former
company might lose track of you if you move. Bach also said that if
your former company shifts its 401(k) plan from one investment
company to another and its trustees can't find you, the money
probably will be put in a money market account rather than a stock
or bond fund.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't borrow from your 401(k).
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a huge mistake,'' he said. ``I tell people the last
place to go is your retirement account. That's why it's called a
retirement account.''
</P>
<P>
   One potentially dangerous aspect about borrowing from the 401(k)
is that if you quit or get fired, the employer can kick you out of
the plan. If that happens and you can't repay the loan immediately,
the money you borrowed is considered a distribution _ meaning you
could have to pay income taxes and a 10 percent penalty.
</P>
<P>
   _ Get paid what you're worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the average worker right now is earning 10 to 30
percent less than they could be if they took a more proactive role
in their career,'' Bach said. ``If you're a worker who's truly
adding value, you'd better be earning near the top of your pay
scale.''
</P>
<P>
   If you believe you're underpaid, don't rush right in and demand
a raise. Bach suggests talking to your boss or clients and asking
how you can add value to their business.
</P>
<P>
   ``After you've done that, then you go back,'' he said. ``The key
is you've got to add value first.''
</P>
<P>
   Although most of the book's suggestions would work equally well
for both sexes, Bach said he aimed it at women because many have
never been taught about investing, often relying on men to do it
for them. He said good investing is probably more crucial for women
than men because they are out of work more often; in the book, he
says that a typical woman spends 11 1/2 years of her working life
out of work, compared with only 16 months for the typical man.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Bach said, women who develop financial savvy
are usually better investors than men. In the book, he says that
investment clubs run by women have outperformed those of men in
nine of the last 12 years, according to the National Association of
Investors Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``When women are given the education on money,'' Bach said,
``then they're great on saving, they're great on commitment.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest obstacle for both sexes is procrastination, Bach
said. In the book, he writes about how people consider what would
happen if they received a 10 percent pay cut. Would they have to
quit their job? Would they have to sell their home? Would their
spouse leave them? Probably not. Then why not put the 10 percent
into savings?
</P>
<P>
   ``There are really two options in life: You can be either
reactive or proactive to circumstances,'' Bach writes. ``And it's a
lot more fun and a lot less painful to be proactive _ to make
decisions about your life before events take control of you.''
</P>
<P>
   For those who have trouble finding the money to save, Bach said,
consider the money you spend on coffee or snacks each day. In the
book, he recalled talking to a 23-year-old woman who spent $5 a day
on coffee and sweets. If she had saved that money, it would add up
to nearly $2,000 a year for her retirement plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``If she put in $2,000 every year, and she invested it all in
stocks (which have enjoyed an average growth rate of 11 percent a
year over the last 50 years), chances are that by the time she
reached 65, she would have more than $2 million sitting in her
account,'' Bach writes.
</P>
<P>
   ``In other words, she would be able to retire a
multimillionaire.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-04-99 1253EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
