<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 13:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1725 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOME-PROJECT-BOS &LR;      02-04 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-PROJECT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT TO DO WHEN THE TOILET FLUSHES ALL BY ITSELF _ AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Never let it be said that a house is maintenance free. It just
isn't so, no matter how many electronic gizmos you may have in it.
</P>
<P>
   It's a little like the misbegotten claim that a perennial garden
is a no-maintenance garden. You know, those perennials, the ones
that keep coming back year after year; plant them once and forget
about them. That's not so, either. Anyone who has a perennial
garden will tell you, loud and clear, how much work it is.
</P>
<P>
   It's the same with the house. There's always something wrong.
Windows don't wash properly. Doors open and close by themselves,
and bind aginst the jamb as well. Toilets flush without human
help. &QL; 
 &QL; 
The ``thinking'' toilet &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the toilet with a mind of its own. It flushes all
by itself, usually in the middle of the night.
</P>
<P>
   The reason usually is that the flapper or rubber ball that sets
on the drain hole at the bottom of the tank, where water normally
goes into the bowl during a flush, does not seat properly in the
opening. A slow leak occurs, and the lower the water goes in the
tank the sooner the flapper pops up and the toilet flushes.
</P>
<P>
   A simple adjustment to move the flapper may be all that is
needed, to make sure the flapper or ball seats properly.
</P>
<P>
   Sometmes the flapper does not seat properly because the drain
opening is corroded, or has a mineral buildup on it. Smooth it out
by rubbing with emery cloth, a fine sanding and grinding substance.
</P>
<P>
   This did not work for one homeowner whose toilet just wouldn't
stop flushing when it felt like it. The flapper or ball was seating
properly, adding to the frustration.
</P>
<P>
   The homeowner looked long and hard at the innards of the tank,
until she noticed the little tube that fills the overflow tube
seemed quite low. She lifted it an inch or so and the spontaneous
flushing stopped.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently the filler tube was so low that it siphoned water
away, lowering the water in the tank, leading to the self-flush. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Windows don't come clean &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Consider dirty windows, so dirty or stained that nothing cleans
them.
</P>
<P>
   Last week we mentioned a super cleaner called ClearVue, which
might do the job on those impossible windows, but we did not know
where it was sold. Dr. Ed Rafferty of Lynn, Mass. took time out of
his busy schedule to tell us that ``every supermarket carries
ClearVue. I happened to pick some up from a jeweler.''
</P>
<P>
   It comes in a 24-ounce spray bottle, Rafferty said.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks, Ed Rafferty. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Door has a mind of its own &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Maybe a homeowner doesn't ``do'' windows, but he has to use
doors, and if they get out of adjustment or stick or simply refuse
to open or close properly, then he has to do something about it.
</P>
<P>
   And here is what you can do.
</P>
<P>
   If the door sticks or binds, say, at the top corner on the latch
side, first check the hinges to make sure they are tight. Often a
loose hinge will let the door drop a bit, causing the bind. If a
hinge is loose, redrive the screws or fill the holes with
toothpicks, kitchen matches or other filler material so the screws
will tighten.
</P>
<P>
   Another material to fill the holes if a screw is loose (no pun
intended) is Mr. Grip, a thin strip of aluminum with little holes
punched in it, like a cheese grater. The barbs in these gripper
strips grab the screw tightly when it is driven. Mr. Grip; is sold
in many hardware stores.
</P>
<P>
   If the hinges are tight, the bind may indicate that the door is
not quite vertical. To correct this, install shims (thin pieces of
cardboard) behind the leaf of the lowest hinge. Remove the hinge
leaf, insert the cardboard shim, and remount the leaf. This will
not correct a severe bind; if the door is really sticking, and in
more than one place, shave or plane the binding surfaces so it fits
properly. You may have to saw off a thin layer to make it work.
</P>
<P>
   Shimming behind the leaf of a hinge is also done when the door
swings of its own accord. You open it and it swings shut. You close
it and if it doesn't latch, it swings open. Sometimes you have to
shim the bottom hinge leaf rather than the top.
</P>
<P>
   Try it. It does, indeed, work. Some refrigerator doors are set
off-vertical on purpose, so when someone raids it, he doesn't have
to close the door; it will close by itself. That's OK for a
refrigerator, but not for a bedroom or bathroom door.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-04-99 1306EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
