<HEADLINE>
MONICA'S STORY 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ For refusing to admit that she and the president
engaged several times in oral sex, Monica Lewinsky was threatened
by the federal government with prison and made to testify more than
20 times _ most recently this week before all-male members of
Congress and a videocamera.
</P>
<P>
   Her privacy has been invaded in a manner unmatched in U.S.
history, and she's been robbed of a life for the last 13 months.
</P>
<P>
   Does the punishment fit her crime? It's useful to go back to the
beginning and take a look at Lewinsky's sworn affidavit to Paula
Jones' lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   You remember the affidavit? The one she submitted in December
1997, the first time she (drum roll) perrr-jured herself? On a
purely technical level, yes, it's full of lies. The biggest leads
off Item No. 8: ``I have never had a sexual relationship with the
president. ...''
</P>
<P>
   We know that Lewinsky, Bill Clinton and the majority of the U.S.
college students who were queried in an 8-year-old Kinsey survey do
not consider oral sex actual ``sex.'' We also know that Lewinsky
and the president engaged in enough of the former to satisfy the
definition of the latter for millions of Americans _ including
Congress and Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   (That the pair's activities may not have satisfied the tortured
definition of ``sexual relations'' agreed to by Jones' attorneys
explains a lot of why we're all now stuck watching ``Capitol Hill
90210.'')
</P>
<P>
   A smaller lie pops up further along in Item 8: ``The occasions
that I saw the president after I left my employment at the White
House in April 1996 were official receptions, formal functions or
events related to the U.S. Department of Defense, where I was
working at the time. There were other people present on those
occasions.''
</P>
<P>
   As we now know, after she left her job at the White House,
Lewinsky and the president actually saw each other at their own
private functions.
</P>
<P>
   Item No.3 is a tricky one: ``I cannot fathom any reason that the
plaintiff would seek information from me for her case.''
</P>
<P>
   Another lie, right? Except, taken from the standpoint of sexual
harassment law, Lewinsky really did not possess any information
that would be of use to a woman making such a claim against
Clinton. Lewinsky's non-sexual sexual relations with the
commander-in-chief were not only consensual, they were her idea.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, when she addressed the heart of the Jones case (also Item
8), she told nothing but the truth: ``(The president) did not
propose that we have a sexual relationship; he did not offer me
employment or other benefits in exchange for a sexual relationship;
he did not deny me employment or other benefits for rejecting a
sexual relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not know of any other person who had a sexual
relationship with the president, was offered employment or other
benefits in exchange for a sexual relationship, or was denied
employment or other benefits for rejecting a sexual relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, though we may never know why Lewinsky and
Clinton lied about their consensual non-sexual sexual relationship,
their truth had nothing to do with sexual harassment; their lies
did not subvert any legal process or deny Paula Corbin Jones her
civil rights.
</P>
<P>
   According to the inevitable leaks that sprang right after
Lewinsky's ``confidential'' testimony on Monday, one of the
president's lawyers read an apology to her from her one-time
sort-of lover. He's sorry ``for all the trouble the investigation
and impeachment trial had caused her.''
</P>
<P>
   That makes Item No. 7 in Lewinsky's affidavit all the more
poignant. It may be a lie for some folks _ it may be untrue for her
now _ but it wasn't the day she swore: ``I have the utmost respect
for the president, who has always behaved appropriately in my
presence.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
