<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-DUVAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVID DUVAL'S SHADES OF GREATNESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEBBLE BEACH, Calif. _ Everyone has their own label for him now.
Best golfer. Robot. Mystery Man.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone wants to pick away at the man behind those wraparound
sunglasses, to penetrate this inscrutable performer who can be
shooting the best round in history, yet walk up the 18th fairway
and barely crack a smile, as was the case when he turned the final
round of the Bob Hope Classic into a milestone by shooting a 59 _
on national television.
</P>
<P>
   That's what happens when you have won nine times in your last 29
tournaments, when it's just past Groundhog Day and your earnings
are already above $1 million for the year.
</P>
<P>
   That's what happens when you shoot 26 under par in back-to-back
tournaments, a performance so overwhelming that Tiger Woods
jokingly says he wants a shot a side in your next match.
</P>
<P>
   So it is only natural that David Duval is out here this week at
the AT&AMP;T Pebble Beach National Pro-Am dealing as much with the
media as with the golf courses he hopes to tame by Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   You want to know about David Duval? Who he is? What he is?
</P>
<P>
   Take a look.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `I was at the NHL All-Star Game in Tampa with my son,'' recalls
Mark O'Meara, who with victories in two majors last season and five
career wins at Pebble Beach knows something about good golf. ``I
went up to Fox's press box, and somebody said, `Someone shot a 59.'
I said, `Yeah, right.' They said, `No, we think it was Duval.' I
said, `No, wait a minute, wait a minute. I know he's playing good.
But a 59 on that course?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Couple that with Duval's victory in Hawaii at the Mercedes
Championship a week earlier, in which he carded his first
astounding 26-under aggregate, a 266, and you have something that
defies explanation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all know how good he is,'' says O'Meara. ``But what David
has done is pretty much beyond belief.''
</P>
<P>
   On that Duval is in agreement. In coming from seven strokes back
in the fifth and final round to win the Hope by a stroke with
another 26-under total (334) _ and tie the PGA Tour record for
lowest round _ he had 11 birdie putts, six from 3 feet or fewer.
The putt he rolled in for the eagle on the par-5 18th that gave him
the 59 was 12 feet.
</P>
<P>
   He says his impassive look coming up to the green on 18 was
dictated more by surprise at what he was doing than anything else.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a case of `What have I done to deserve this?' '' Duval
says. ``The best way to answer how I can grasp what happened is
that I can't grasp what happened. I don't appreciate what happened.
I've gotten to appreciate it a little more. But it's just so hard
to describe. It's so hard to do, you don't expect to do it. It's
just not something that entered my mind. All of a sudden, it's
over, you did it. And you ask yourself, `What just happened?'
</P>
<P>
   ``It might be the only chance I really have to do it. To be able
to make that putt is, I guess in that circumstance, almost
surprising. To just think of the course of 40 or 50 years, it might
be the only time it happens. The odds are so stacked against you,
it will be something I'll never forget.''
</P>
<P>
   Prior to Duval, only Al Geiberger (1977 Memphis Classic) and
Chip Beck (1991 Las Vegas Invitational) had carded 59s in Tour
competition.
</P>
<P>
   But neither of those came in the final round and neither came
without the aid of some remarkable shots around the green _
extraordinary long putts or chip-ins.
</P>
<P>
   Each day Duval says he understands more about what he did, if
not how he did it.
</P>
<P>
   When someone asks him if he has the golf ball from that round,
he smiles. ``Oh, yeah,'' he says. ``Hidden away in my house (in
Ponte Vedra, Fla.).''
</P>
<P>
   Duval says the significance of making that final putt was not
necessarily that it gave him the 59 but that it proved he could
handle pressure with a tournament on the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 59 is not going to do anything for me when you need to win
at Augusta, he says. ``If I face a situation to make a reasonable
putt to win a golf tournament, I can go back and draw on the putt I
made to shoot a 59.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Duval knows he is different now. Or viewed differently. Until
the Hope, he was a rising star on the PGA Tour, but one of many,
and still a step behind Woods.
</P>
<P>
   He came out of Georgia Tech in 1993 with ambitions of being
better than his father, Bob, who is now on the PGA Senior Tour.
</P>
<P>
   David had been a Collegiate Player of the Year, a four-time
Division 1 All-American. His first stop was the Nike Tour in 1993,
where he won twice. He struggled for two years, finishing 201st on
the PGA money list in 1993 and 195th in 1994, earning a combined
total of $71,000 in a handful of PGA events.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, he made the quantum leap to a full-time spot on the PGA
Tour, jumping to 11th in earnings with $881,436. The only thing
missing was a victory. He had seven seconds and four thirds, and
everyone knew he was an emerging force _ except on Sundays, when
tournaments are won or lost.
</P>
<P>
   In less than two years, all that has changed. Instead of saying
he couldn't win, Duval has had a tough time not winning.
</P>
<P>
   He won three times at the end of 1997, followed up last year
with four wins and four seconds, and has already won twice this
season.
</P>
<P>
   At 27, he is beyond hot. Over the last 16 months, he has won
almost a third of the tournaments he has entered. O'Meara thinks he
could win four or five more times this season, which likely would
put him above the $3 million mark in earnings, not an unreasonable
assumption since he will play in another 15-17 events. One thing,
though _ O'Meara thinks Duval can reach that total by the US Open
in June.
</P>
<P>
   The hardest part, says Duval, who has shot a course-record-tying
62 at Pebble Beach, is dealing with all the things away from the
course, the looks he gets when he plays, the whispers he hears.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoy it,'' he says. ``It's an adjustment. For the most
part, everyone understands and has been supportive. I try and be
accommodating as far as autographs. There's not going to be a lot
of interaction on the golf course. And sometimes I have bad days.
That's just how it is. Hopefully, I don't offend those people too
bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Unquestionably, there's a rivalry brewing with Woods, although
both players say they worry about themselves, not anybody else.
``What you want to do out here is prove you're better than any
other player,'' says Woods. ``David has been doing that. He's been
killing us.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Meara sees Duval and the way he handles the attention and
merely shrugs. ``His personality is his personality,'' says
O'Meara, who nosed out Duval for 1998 Player of the Year honors by
virtue of his wins in the Masters and British Open. ``And he's not
going to change that. And you have to admire a guy that's that way.
He goes along and does his business and does it quite well. I mean,
I don't think anything is distracting David Duval right now. His
game shows that.''
</P>
<P>
   Duval agrees. His personality is his personality. The man on the
golf course, behind the sunglasses, is different than the David
Duval you will find on the street or joking around with his buddies
on the Tour, such as Phil Mickelson and Fred Funk.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ah, yes, the sunglasses, those wraparound protective shields
that hide his eyes and, some contend, his soul as well.
</P>
<P>
   When he started on the Tour, Duval was 40 pounds heavier, had a
goatee, and wore the sunglasses that revealed nothing to the public
watching him. He was, he said, ``just another blond-haired,
blue-eyed, stereotypical PGA golfer.''
</P>
<P>
   The pounds and the goatee are gone, but the sunglasses remain.
He wears them because he wants to, not because he needs to. He says
they allow him to focus on the course, to zone in on what he must
do.
</P>
<P>
   Ask him about his aloof persona on the course and some bells go
off in his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm very approachable,'' he says almost defensively.
``I think I'm as accommodating as anyone in the game. I don't know
what else I can do. I don't know what I can do about that, so I
don't think about that. I don't worry about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ask him about his reaction _ that seemingly muted reaction _
after he made that putt for the 59 and Duval will reveal more of
his personality. ``I might have done a few laps if there wasn't a
group behind me,'' he says with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Now Duval must live with what he has created. He says, ``No
problem.'' He will continue to wear the sunglasses, continue to
play golf on his terms. Duval says he still gets uncomfortable when
he is called a superstar or the best player in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Yet he acknowledges that despite the rankings which still list
Woods as No. 1, he should occupy that perch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know how to play,'' he says. ``It's been a lot of hard work,
and I think I'm pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't bother with comparisons to Woods. ``I just go out
there and do my job,'' he says. ``If I'm on the leaderboard and
he's up there, I'll know what he's doing.''
</P>
<P>
   His schedule for the year is pretty much laid out. He will play
fairly steadily through May, then reassess where he wants to go.
The majors _ beginning with the Masters in April _ are paramount.
</P>
<P>
   Asked which would be most special if he does capture a major, he
doesn't hesitate. ``The US Open,'' he says. ``It's our
championship. And besides, everyone always complains about the
courses. It's funny to hear the best players in the world sound
like a bunch of old women, complaining about everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Duval has few complaints these days, although he dislikes match
play, which he will experience in San Diego later this month at a
world championship event and during the Ryder Cup matches at The
Country Club in Brookline, Mass., in September.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never get what you deserve in match play,'' he says. ``The
No. 1 player might shoot six shots better than the No. 3 player and
the No. 3 player might play a round in 3 over and win, and that's
not right.''
</P>
<P>
   But that's being picky. Right now David Duval feels he can do
anything on a golf course. Some people say he is in that magical
area known as ``the zone.''
</P>
<P>
   It's more than that.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe fellow touring pro Scott Simpson's assessment is more
accurate:
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy's really good.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
DUVAL ON A ROLL &QL; 
(! used as column separator) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Before he broke through for his first PGA Tour win in October 1997,
David Duval was considered another very good player who had not
won. How times have changed. In the last 16 months, Duval has been
on fire and is generally regarded as the No. 1 player in the world.
That honor officially belongs to Tiger Woods, but just compare the
numbers for the two young stars since Duval's first win: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Duval! Woods &QL; 
Tournaments ! 29! 29 &QL; 
Wins ! 9! 1 &QL; 
Top 10's ! 18! 16 &QL; 
Money ! $4,967,031!$2,166,930 &QL; 
Missed cuts ! 3! 0 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
