<HEADER>
A1733 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-HOTLINE-BOS &LR;      02-04 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-HOTLINE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOTLINE'S COOL RECEPTION COSTS TAXPAYERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MOHL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Massachusetts is running a toll-free hotline on
electricity deregulation that is costing taxpayers a fortune while
attracting only a handful of calls from consumers each day.
</P>
<P>
   Through the hotline's first 10 months of operation, the state
paid Compaq Computer Corp. more than $746,000 to run it. Over that
10-month period, the hotline received 14,600 calls, which works out
to an average cost of $51 a call.
</P>
<P>
   Calls to the hotline hit a peak of 3,568 during May, when the
state launched a TV and radio advertising campaign promoting the
hotline and electricity deregulation. The call volume has steadily
dropped since then, hitting a low of 264 in December, an average of
about 12 calls each business day.
</P>
<P>
   As the call volume has dwindled, state officials have scaled
back the hotline's hours, reduced the number of operators from 10
to two, and renegotiated the contract several times with Compaq.
But state officials haven't been able to fix the hotline's biggest
problem _ the absence of electricity competition.
</P>
<P>
   The state's electricity business was officially deregulated last
March, but because market-level prices are being phased in,
companies haven't started competing yet for residential customers.
As a result, nearly everyone is still buying electricity the same
way they always have _ from their local utility.
</P>
<P>
   This status quo situation hasn't generated the type of confusion
the hotline was intended to handle. According to hot-line reports,
callers are asking general questions about their local utilities,
their monthly bills, and how competition will work. When they ask
for a list of companies from which they can buy power, they learn
that four companies are licensed to sell power to residential
customers but aren't doing it yet.
</P>
<P>
   The state had expected calls to last 10 to 12 minutes on
average, but a spokeswoman for Compaq said calls are lasting an
average of two to three minutes. A state official said the average
call length rises to five minutes when the time it takes to log the
call and mail out a state guide to deregulation is included.
Hot-line operators are temporary workers hired by Compaq and
trained by the state.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Sargent of the Massachusetts Public Interest Research Group,
a critic of the state's deregulation law, said the lack of
electricity competition means the hotline is attempting to answer
consumer questions before consumers are ready to ask them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's outrageous that we have a consumer hotline that
is charging taxpayers $50 a call. At that rate, you should be
talking to the top utility experts in the country, but instead
people are talking to someone who is basically reading a script,''
Sargent said.
</P>
<P>
   David O'Connor, head of the state's Division of Energy
Resources, which oversees the hotline, predicted call volume would
pick up over the next several months as competition among companies
for residential customers begins in earnest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal has always been to be slightly ahead of the market,''
O'Connor said.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor's agency is planning to promote the hotline again in
March in advertisements on billboards, buses, and trains. Most
utilities print the hot-line number in their bills.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Daniel Bosley, a Democrat from North Adams who
played a key role in drafting the deregulation law, said the
hotline and consumer education campaign were high priorities of
lawmakers. He said there was mass confusion about deregulation in
California when regulators there failed to set aside enough money
for an education campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Bosley acknowledged the hotline won't get really busy until
consumers start getting calls at dinner time from electricity
marketers. But he said those annoying calls may be coming, noting
that several retailers have told him they plan to start competing
for customers in the coming months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Admittedly, we're ahead of ourselves,'' Bosley said. ``But
even if we're ahead of the curve, we needed this. It's seed
money.''
</P>
<P>
   The hotline opened for business at the end of February. Compaq
was awarded the hot-line contract under an abbreviated state
bidding process for ``deals too good to pass up,'' under state
contracting guidelines. Compaq was seen as a good fit for the
hotline because the company was already operating a technology
hotline for state workers.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq hired temporary workers to answer calls at a facility in
Shrewsbury and the state trained them on the details of
deregulation. The state agreed to pay a fee for each call handled,
but Compaq was guaranteed a set amount of money each day based on
an agreed-upon minimum number of calls.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, that minimum was 70 calls at $26.97 apiece, or a
total of $1,888. Calls after the initial 70 would be priced at
$15.75 apiece. The per-call price was scheduled to drop as daily
call volume increased.
</P>
<P>
   But as calls proved to be shorter and call volume declined, the
contract was revised. In September, weekend hours were eliminated,
the number of operators was reduced to four, and the price per call
for the initial 70 calls was reduced to $25.83.
</P>
<P>
   But call volume continued to decline so the contract was revised
again last month. Only two operators are working now and the
minimum daily call volume was reduced to 35 at a price of $26.83 a
call. That means the state will pay 48 percent less if the
operators handle 35 calls or less a day. Calls in excess of 35 are
priced at $15.75 apiece.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
