<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COOL CAMELLIAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CAROL STOCKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WALTHAM, Mass. _ Their brilliant satin petals bursting from
swollen green buds, the camellias at the historic Lyman Estate
greenhouse seem as miraculous as an early spring. Camellias have a
hopeful vivacity that has won the protective patronage of both the
Buddhist priests who first collected and bred them for ancient
temple gardens in China and the Western aristocrats who 1,000 years
later built Victorian ``camellia houses'' to display these tender
trophies.
</P>
<P>
   If the best thing about camellias is the way they seem to laugh
at winter, the worst is that they must do it behind walls of glass.
Even their lack of hardiness here has a silver lining, however, for
it creates a good reason to visit the Lyman greenhouse, where
thousands of plants thrive in moist and warm air. West Coast
trendies may be hooking up to oxygen tanks in spa lounges, but New
Englanders only need visit a greenhouse in February to feel
buoyant.
</P>
<P>
   You may not have seen a camellia, but you've certainly heard the
name. These are fabled flowers. Naturally occurring in China and
Japan in shades of pink, red, and white, camellias originally
followed in the path of the Buddha, dispersed by traveling monks
who had bred them to assume different forms. There are so-called
peony camellias, anemone camellias, singles, and doubles.
</P>
<P>
   Because camellias were popular with the Victorians, they have
been immortalized in music and literature as a symbol of tragic
romanticism. Who could forget French courtesan Greta Garbo as the
dying Lady of the Camellias?
</P>
<P>
   In the Old South, this favorite of pre-Civil War plantations
like Charleston's Middleton Place soaked up the ``Gone With the
Wind'' mystique of lost gentility.
</P>
<P>
   In the more button-down North, camellias were also treasured,
but symbolized something different: trade with China, and its
attendant wealth and status.
</P>
<P>
   Legend has it that camellias were first mistakenly imported as
tea plants when Chinese merchants, intent on protecting their
export markets, pulled a fast one, selling European traders the
ornamental in place of its sought-after cousin, the tea bush
Camellia sinensis, said Lynn Ackerman, managing horticulturalist at
the Lyman Estate.
</P>
<P>
   But they still caught on. And how.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Theodore Lyman made a fortune in the China Trade and copied the
stately country seats of England when he built the estate he named
the Vale in the 1790s. He also loved plants and in 1800 began the
oldest-surviving greenhouse complex in the United States, which the
family added onto through the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   In 1840 one room of that greenhouse was heightened and deepened
to become a separate camellia house, as these bushes require cooler
temperatures than most greenhouse plants.
</P>
<P>
   For five generations the Vale was the Lyman family's summer
home. Gardeners would cut camellias through the winter and deliver
them to the family's townhouse on Beacon Hill, where they were
proudly displayed in imported China Trade vases.
</P>
<P>
   The favorite classic ``formal double'' possesses a well-bred
symmetry that appealed to French designer Coco Chanel, who was
doubtless aware of the plant's aristocratic associations. Cloth
camellias still decorate Chanel accessories.
</P>
<P>
   Like fashion, however, real flowers suffered the peaks and
valleys of a popular craze, and eventually most flower fanciers had
discarded their camellia collections for newer plants. Besides,
camellias are tricky to grow. Central heating is death to them. As
Ackerman put it, ``If your camellias are comfortable, it's probably
too cool for you. And if you're comfortable, it's probably too warm
for your camellias.''
</P>
<P>
   Amazingly, the Lyman estate remained devoted to its camellia
collection, even after the property was donated to the Society for
the Preservation of New England Antiquities in the 1950s. Today the
camellia house contains 13 original plants the size of small
dogwood trees and several dozen younger specimens. A few sweet
olive plants scent the sunny lean-to to provide the fragrance most
camellias lack. An exception is Camellia lutchensis, whose smallish
white flower exudes an intense sweetness. The bushes bloom against
a 20-foot-high red brick wall that retains splashes of milky white
from when it was originally painted with a lime wash to reflect
light and warmth.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The greenhouse sells a few Florida-grown camellia plants at $15
to $25. Ackerman said she has had good luck with them in an
unheated room of her own home, but unless you have a greenhouse you
are well advised to invest your money in the many orchids the
greenhouse also sells, and enjoy camellias at the Vale.
</P>
<P>
   With the population shift to the Sun Belt, camellias have gained
popularity among those who can grow them outdoors year-round,
however, and you'll find them gracing many a tract-house lawn in
California, trying to maintain their dignity. Sacramento even
dubbed itself ``Camellia City.''
</P>
<P>
   Camellias can grow outdoors in some sheltered spots on Cape Cod
and the Islands. The new Polly Hill Arboretum on Martha's Vineyard
has a few.
</P>
<P>
   Among the newer, more cold-hardy varieties to try if you are a
neighbor to the south are Nicky Crisp and Donation. Both are
Camellia x williamsii hybrids available from Heronswood Nursery in
Kingston, Wash. (360-297-4172, www.heronswood.com), and both are
relatively fast-growing and self-cleaning (meaning they drop their
ugly brown spent blossoms), traits the old-fashioned C. japonica
unfortunately lacks. For more information, contact the American
Camellia Society at 912-967-2358.
</P>
<P>
   The Lyman greenhouse offers many other treats in its several
rooms, including blooming bougainvillea and orchids, fragrant
rosemary, and of course a gift shop. There's also an antique marble
statue of dancing cherubs and a yellow-eyed black angora cat to
greet visitors. Once a stray, the feline now catnaps in sunny
splendor but is banned from the camellia house when nesting
cardinals take up spring residence there.
</P>
<P>
   Fans of historic greenhouses visiting the Lyman will be
heartened to see how this one has come back to life. With the aid
of full-time assistant Nancy Askin, Ackerman has in her 10 years on
the site helped convert a white elephant into an enchanted kingdom
that is just shy of being self-supporting through its plant sales,
including a well-attended Mother's Day weekend herb sale and a
shade plant and hosta sale a month later. Ackerman teaches several
plant workshops, including one in April on growing orchids in the
historic mansion, closed now except for tours or weddings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With an estimated 10,000 visitors a year, the once-sleepy
greenhouse has gotten so busy that starting last year Ackerman
extended what has been a four-day ``camellia festival'' into a
monthlong ``camellia blooming period.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more relaxed having it over a longer period,'' said
Ackerman. ``Strolling through a greenhouse should be a leisurely
experience. This way we only get 50 or 75 people a day.''
</P>
<P>
   A $37,000 grant from the Massachusetts Historical Commission
allowed the thick glass panes to be replaced, many with glass from
another antique greenhouse recently bulldozed for development in
Milton, said Ackerman. ``But the mullions here were made out of
such good materials, cypress and redwood, that we had to replace
remarkably few.''
</P>
<P>
   The SPNEA, which owns 34 other historic properties, recently
created the post of director of landscapes, reflecting its
commitment to period gardens. In this role, Betsy Igleheart has
secured a historical commission grant for $75,000 to restore the
421-foot brick ``peach wall,'' which defines the property's outdoor
perennial beds and was once used for espalier fruit trees.
</P>
<P>
   The future is suddenly looking brighter for historic landscapes,
which means that camellias will once again get to tell their story.
</P>
<P>
   The Lyman greenhouse is open Mondays through Saturdays from 9
a.m. to 4 p.m. Admission is free.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
