<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 13:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1737 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-2TAK     02-04 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPANKING'S PUNISHING LESSONS 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA F. MELTZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although a proposed anti-spanking campaign for Oakland, Calif.,
is not expected to pass when the full City Council considers it
later this month, the proponents of the non-binding ``No Spanking
Zone'' should at least be applauded for their efforts.
</P>
<P>
   For years, parent educators and psychologists have been saying
that spanking is the least effective way to discipline children,
yet their advice is widely ignored: 94 percent of American parents
spank their 1- to 5-year-old children, according to a 1995 Gallup
Survey of Parenting in America.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spanking continues to be a mainstay of tactics used by
parents,'' says Murray Strauss, one of the nation's leading
researchers on spanking and co-director of the Family Research Lab
at the University of New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   It's no suprise, then, that the Oakland proposal has been
controversial, even though all it would do is mandate ``No Spanking
Zone'' signs in public places. But despite the dire, indeed
shocking, statistics, parent educators see signs of hope.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On a recent morning, Linda Braun, director of Families First
Parenting Programs in Cambridge, Mass., got a frantic call from a
father.
</P>
<P>
   There had been a struggle that morning as his 5-year-old son
left for kindergarten. The boy, already in the car pool van, wanted
to go back inside for something he had forgotten. The father,
anxious not to keep the driver waiting and also to teach his son to
plan better, said no. Frustrated and enraged, the son spat at his
father out of the open car door. Equally enraged, the father's
instinct was to haul his boy out of the car and give him the
spanking of his life. Instead, he gave in to a second instinct: He
turned his back and let the car pull away.
</P>
<P>
   Then he called Braun.
</P>
<P>
   ``He planned to go home and spank him that night. He felt he
shouldn't but he didn't know what else to do,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Therein lies the dilemma not just for this father but for all
parents who know spanking is wrong but do it nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't know what to do instead,'' says psychologist Roni
Leiderman, director of the Family Center at Nova Southeastern
University in Fort Lauderdale, Fla. She says parents tend to repeat
the patterns of their own parents: If you were spanked as a child,
you are more likely to spank your children.
</P>
<P>
   The argument against spanking is that parents are a child's most
important teachers. When we spank, the lessons we teach are not
only negative but also antisocial:
</P>
<P>
   --It's OK for big people to hurt little people;
</P>
<P>
   --It's OK to resolve conflict through force.
</P>
<P>
   The lesson they are not getting is how to control the impulse
that led to the behavior that got them in trouble in the first
place. In fact, a child who is spanked chronically, once a week or
more, is more likely to feel the need for revenge, not for remorse,
says parent educator and author Nancy Samalin.
</P>
<P>
   ``What gets a child to change his behavior is that he feels
badly, loves his parents, and wants to please them. A child who's
spanked only wants to get even,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Since a child has very limited ways to exert power, getting even
usually comes out in oppositional behavior that parents rarely
connect to the spanking: not eating, not doing homework, not going
to the bathroom. ``It's as if the child is saying, `I'll show you,
I have some power, too,' '' says Braun, who is also a professor at
Wheelock College Graduate School.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Parents who insist spanking works are only looking at short-term
results, says University of Tulsa psychologist Terry Luce, an
authority on the impact of aggression on children.
</P>
<P>
   ``You may get immediate compliance, but it's because you're
instilling fear. That prompts a child to stop doing the behavior
while you are watching, or to do it in a way you won't find out
about, in order to avoid another spanking,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   But to change his behavior so he doesn't do it at all only
happens when he internalizes why the behavior is wrong. That leaves
parents with a choice, says Luce: ``Do you want to stop the
behavior now, without regard to long-term consequences, or do you
want to stop it for good?''
</P>
<P>
   For many parents, getting away from spanking means coming to
grips with significant emotional baggage.
</P>
<P>
   Leiderman tells of a mother who came to her parenting class and
confessed she regularly spanked her children with a wooden spoon.
The spoon was the same one her grandparents had spanked her mother
with and her mother had used on her.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-04-99 1313EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990204.0169 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 13:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1739 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHILDCARE-PHOTOS-2ND &LR;      02-04 0941
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDCARE-PHOTOS-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... used on her.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``She didn't want to perpetuate this family tradition, but she
felt (to do anything different) was a slap in the face to people
she loved,'' says Leiderman. It took her months to gain the courage
to tell her parents and grandparents, ``I appreciate what you did
for me, I love you, but for me there's going to be a different
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Other parents argue, ``I was spanked and I turned out OK.'' To
that, Leiderman's response is to ask simply, ``If there's an
alternative, wouldn't you want to try it?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The strategy she and others offer is summed up in one word:
exit.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're angry enough to hit or to scream something abusive,
you're out of control. That itself is frightening to a young
child,'' says Braun. She recommends using as few words as possible
to say how upset you are and then to leave the room. Insisting your
child leave _ ``Go to your room! I don't want to see you!'' _ often
puts you in a secondary power struggle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Better for you to go,'' says Braun. ``If a toddler or
preschooler follows you to the bathroom and bangs on the door
crying, just stay there until you have control again.''
</P>
<P>
   When you reunite, acknowledge the incident _ ``Wow! We were both
really upset, weren't we?'' _ but buy some time: ``We'll talk about
it later.'' Then resume your activity.
</P>
<P>
   With a child 5 or older, tell him as you leave: ``I'm too angry,
we're not understanding each other, and I need to leave the room,''
or, ``I can see you're furious and I am, too. We need to separate
to calm down.'' Don't say, ``I can't be with you.'' ``That's just
too hurtful to many children,'' says Braun.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what your child's age, when the time comes to initiate
a discussion, talk about:
</P>
<P>
   --What happened: ``When you left for school this morning, you
spat at me.''
</P>
<P>
   --How you both felt: ``You were frustrated I didn't let you get
out of the car, and I hated being spat at.''
</P>
<P>
   --What the rule/limit is: ``In our family, spitting isn't
allowed. Spitting is wrong.'' Be clear, simple, and firm.
</P>
<P>
   --How you're going to help him: ``We need to help you with two
things: getting organized for school so you don't forget anything
and remembering to never spit again.''
</P>
<P>
   --Consequences: ``I can't read to you tonight. I hope that will
help you remember how upsetting this was to me.'' With an older
child, brainstorm solutions or consequences together: ``This wasn't
OK. What do you think should be the consequence?''
</P>
<P>
   Samalin says that a consequence that removes you from an
intimate interaction, especially one a child enjoys, is more
powerful than we realize. ``Children care deeply about how we feel
about them, even teenagers,'' she says. She is the author of ``Love
and Anger: The Parental Dilemma'' (Penguin).
</P>
<P>
   For many parents, this strategy feels wimpy. Luce argues it's
not. ``You are not relinquishing control when you explain why a
behavior is wrong. Don't think punishment,'' he says, ``think
discipline and consequences. That's what leads to learning, which
leads to self-control.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although Braun urges parents to plan from the start never to
spank, she says that if you find yourself spanking once or twice a
year, rather than berate yourself or justify it with a
``my-parents-spanked-me'' defense, ``Find someone you respect to
reflect on what happened and explore options.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether you are a rare spanker or a chronic one, Samalin has the
last word: ``The bottom line is, hitting hurts. If you love
someone, why would you want to `teach' them by hurting?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
TIPS FOR PARENTS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Parents who disagree about spanking typically make matters
worse in three ways: Children of all ages learn to manipulate each
parent to get what they want; parents focus more on the spanking
than on the behavior that caused it; over time, each parent becomes
more entrenched in his/her position. The parent who spanks thinks,
``She's such a marshmallow, I have to be the one to teach this
kid,'' and the parent who doesn't thinks, ``He's so strict, I have
to be kind and loving.'' The solution is for parents to talk calmly
about their positions, get information about them, and work to be
in agreement.
</P>
<P>
   --Parents whose anger gets out of control or who spank once a
week or more may benefit from professional parenting help. Families
First offers several workshops on limit-setting and alternatives to
spanking. Call them at 617-868-7687.
</P>
<P>
   --Some preventative measures to keep a child's behavior from
escalating so you both lose control: Match expectations to a
child's stage of development and temperament; reinforce positive
behavior whenever you see it; ignore negative behavior as much as
you can, as long as it's not safety- or health-related; learn to
read her cues so she doesn't get to the end of her rope.
</P>
<P>
   --When behaviors are going downhill, put control in your child's
hands: ``Your choice is to stop throwing the food or leave the
table;'' ``You and your brother can decide nicely what show to
watch or turn off the TV.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AFTERTHOUGHT _ About the age of 2, two children of the same age
can begin to vary widely in height and weight, even though both are
perfectly healthy. From ``The Parents' Answer Book,'' edited by Ann
Pleshette Murphy (Golden Books).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Barbara Meltz's e-mail address is meltz(at)globe.com. Her
columns are now on line at Boston.Com, keyword ``parenting.'' For
photocopies of past columns, send a self-addressed, stamped
envelope to Barbara F. Meltz, The Boston Globe, Box 2378, Boston,
MA 02107-2378. Please specify the column.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-04-99 1315EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990204.0170 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 13:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1740 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      02-04 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SCIENCE FICTION _ OR IS IT? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA WELTNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I've always been impressed with the way that writers create
worlds out of their imagination, but it wasn't until I read the
science fiction novel ``Dune'' that it occurred to me how much like
gods writers really are. Frank Herbert created an entire planet
that bore only a faint resemblance to any we know. He invented
desert biospheres filled with amazing flora and fauna, then came up
with his own remarkable strategies for coping with an inhospitable
environment.
</P>
<P>
   As I read the ``Dune'' series, I couldn't imagine myself
creating an alternative universe. Yet in the dead of this winter,
laid low by the flu, I've begun dreaming another world into being.
</P>
<P>
   The planet I've been imagining is a gigantic magnet, its two
poles created by a spinning core of molten iron and nickel
thousands of miles beneath its surface. In addition to an
atmosphere, my planet also has magnetic fields, which I call its
``magnetosphere,'' which surge from each pole. At the end closest
to its nearest star, powerful solar winds compress the magnetic
field into a circular shape like a head. At the other end, the
magnetic field streams into a long tail, as if my planet were a
living creature swimming against the currents of space toward its
sun. The magnetosphere protects life on my planet from the star's
infrared, ultraviolet, gamma, and cosmic rays, which would
otherwise prove lethal.
</P>
<P>
   Since the magnetosphere remains stationary while my planet
spins, the planet has constantly changing magnetic fields. The rise
and fall of these magnetic fields affects all the creatures that
live on it, controlling their sleeping and waking, cell division
and hormone production in a ``circadian'' rhythm. In fact, my
planet and all its living creatures vibrate in harmony. As a mother
sleeping beside her child draws the infant into a synchronized
breathing pattern, so my planet ``entrains'' all its children, even
its trees and plants. If existence were a song, my planet and its
living parts would be humming together, and this silent rhythm
would be their lifeline. When I say my creatures are on the same
wavelength as my planet, I speak of a matter of life and death.
</P>
<P>
   My planet also has a magnetic grid overlaying it. If the grid
were visible, my planet would appear to be segmented like an orange
and crossed with intersecting lines. The organisms on my planet
tune in to these magnetic pathways and rely on them for survival.
They're able to do so because they have within their bodies a
substance I call ``magnetite,'' a mineral that reacts to the pull
of magnetism.
</P>
<P>
   My humanoid characters possess magnetite crystals, especially
around the membrane that covers and protects the brain. Long rows
of these crystals also line the bodies of swimming creatures and
surround the eyes of those that fly. As a result, the airborne
creatures, from birds to butterflies, use the planet's magnetic
grid to guide them along migration paths thousands of miles long
while the sea creatures on my planet follow invisible
electromagnetic contours that outline underwater mountains and
valleys. They actually have an additional sense _ an
electromagnetic sense _ that operates like a built-in homing
device. This is a planet perfectly responsive to the life it
creates, nurtures, and protects.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, now that I've invented such a remarkable place, I
need a plot. Scientists on my planet have begun using wavelengths
of the electromagnetic spectrum for commercial purposes, creating
intensities a billion times more powerful than those existing
naturally. Some of those wavelengths correspond almost perfectly to
the resonance capacity of living cell membranes, to what effect no
one knows. My humanoids are electromagnetic organisms who absorb
these new electromagnetic pulsations in their bodies as well. For
the first time in their evolutionary history _ day in, day out,
everywhere they go _ they are subjected to newly created
electromagnetic fields of various frequencies and intensities.
</P>
<P>
   Can these frequencies affect brain-wave patterns, damage immune
systems, create physiological stress, adversely affect cell growth,
or cause disease? There are many reasons to think so, but no one
knows for sure. As their inventions for communication become more
ubiquitous, those who profit from them are less and less willing to
tolerate research into what impact this is having on my planet and
its inhabitants.
</P>
<P>
   When the facts are finally in, will it be too late? This would
make a gripping story, don't you think?
</P>
<P>
   I just can't decide what to call my planet. I asked B. Blake
Levitt, from whose book, ``Electromagnetic Fields,'' I learned all
these things.
</P>
<P>
   She says its name is Earth.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Linda Weltner's web site is www.shore.net/weltner)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
