<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INS05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ARRESTS POINT TO CORRUPTION THREAT ON BORDER
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As drug smuggling from Mexico has surged, U.S.
officials have worried that cash from the cocaine cartels would
tempt American gatekeepers along the 2,000-mile Southwestern
border.
</P>
<P>
   Those suspicions appeared to be confirmed this week as the FBI
announced the arrest of four Immigration and Naturalization Service
(INS) border inspectors on bribery and related charges that
officials say allowed two tons of illegal drugs cross the border at
Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Among those arrested, Rafael Landa had the job of checking cars
and trucks for contraband as they tried to enter the United States
through Nogales, Ariz. Instead, Landa waved through vehicles loaded
with cocaine in exchange for an accumulated $300,000 in bribes,
according to an indictment handed down late last month by a grand
jury. Two of his colleagues were charged for similar offenses.
</P>
<P>
   A fourth inspector, Maria De Los Angeles Alabado, a 21-year
veteran of the immigration service, was arrested and charged with
accepting $500 for permits to allow Mexican citizens to travel to
around the United States for up to six months.
</P>
<P>
   Also indicted for paying bribes and drug trafficking were five
members of two reputed Mexican drug smuggling organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officials believe that smugglers paid $800,000
altogether in bribes, said Ed Hall, spokesman for the Phoenix
office of the FBI, which leads the Southern Arizona Corruption Task
Force.
</P>
<P>
   However, Hall and others declined to speculate on whether the
handful of arrests is an indicator of much deeper problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been plenty of intelligence of corruption along the
border, and that's why the task force was set up,'' Hall said.
``It's still a priority on the whole Southwest border, and we're
going to continue looking into it.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Rep. Lamar Smith, R-Texas, who chairs the House
immigration subcommittee, said, ``It's a problem that the
congressman is aware of. He continues to monitor it very closely.''
</P>
<P>
   The temptation of drug dollars has been a growing concern of
U.S. officials in the Southwest since the U.S. Coast Guard's
heightened vigilance along the Florida border began causing
smugglers to reroute their trafficking through Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   As much as 70 percent of the illegal drug traffic to the United
States now comes through Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the Border Patrol has strengthened its numbers
and added new high-tech equipment in the Southwest, making it more
difficult for illegal traffickers to cross the open lands near the
Mexico-U.S. border. And that has increased the pressure on the
official entry points.
</P>
<P>
   ``Smugglers try to find the point of least resistance,'' said
Russell Bergeron, an INS spokesman. ``One of the alternatives would
be to attempt to bribe an inspector.''
</P>
<P>
   The overall record for the INS has been good, Bergeron said,
adding that a government review found that only 28 INS border
workers were convicted of corruption between 1992 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
   However, the INS has been rapidly expanding, increasing its
border inspection work force by 43 percent in only three years to
almost 4,700. And although Bergeron said that his agency has not
relaxed its background checks in the hiring drive, others have
expressed doubts about oversight of the newcomers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time an agency has this huge growth, it raises concerns
that the people put in positions to mentor these new employees are
prepared to do it,'' said T. J. Bondurant, assistant inspector
general for the Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vast majority are honest, but the border inspectors, both
in Customs and INS, are in vulnerable positions,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
