A1747 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPUTERS-TRAVEL-BOS &LR;      02-04 0957
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-TRAVEL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVELING LITE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By Simson L. Garfinkle  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Although I do a fair amount of business-related traveling, a
few years ago I realized I was always leaving something important
at home. One time I was at a conference and wanted to get a file
off somebody's laptop, but I didn't have a floppy disk. Another
time I had gone away for a week, planning on getting a lot of
writing done, and discovered that I had left behind my laptop's
power supply.
</P>
<P>
   I dealt with my problem by creating a travel checklist. The list
has important things to bring, and things I should check the day
before I travel. When I remember to use it, my trips generally go
much better.
</P>
<P>
   Norton Mobile Essentials 1.0 from Symantec is supposed to
automate much of the same type of trip planning. Mobile Essentials
has three parts. The first part, ``Before You Go,'' is designed to
help you prepare your laptop and yourself for that business trip.
It tests your modem, runs SCANDISK on your computer's hard drive,
and checks for viruses. Next the program lets you make a backup
copy of your laptop's important files to a floppy or zip drive _
just in case something should go wrong. There's also a database of
important phone numbers, such as hotels, America Online dial-ups,
international phone numbers to report lost credit cards, and even a
traveler's checklist _ one that's remarkably similar to mine.
</P>
<P>
   Mobile Essentials also has a ``Location Controller,'' which is
supposed to reconfigure your laptop's Windows operating system for
different places. Norton will automatically change both your
clock's time and time zone (something that Windows should do, but
doesn't), remap your laptop's drives, configure printers, and so
on. Although this is a good concept, the execution needs more work.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Norton has created the ``Connection Doctor,'' which is
designed to diagnose common dial-up configuration problems.
Unfortunately, the Connection Doctor's main emphasis is hardware
problems: it won't diagnose problems caused by your Internet
service provider.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, I was somewhat disappointed with Mobile Essentials,
because it doesn't do what I need. My big problem these days isn't
configuring dial-ups, but file synchronization: I need some files
that are on my desktop, and others that are on the network. I solve
this problem by using the Windows 95 Briefcase. Before I leave, I
copy the directories that I'll need into the ``Briefcase.'' When I
travel I work out of the electronic briefcase. When I get back, I
use the Briefcase's ``update all'' feature to copy the modified
files back to my desktop computer's hard drive.
</P>
<P>
   And Mobile Essentials also doesn't really explore a mobile
user's security needs. Virus checking and critical file backup is a
good start, but what laptop users really need is a program that
makes a complete copy of their laptop's hard drive, so if it gets
stolen they can get a replacement and restore all of the data and
applications.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the program should encrypt all the data on the user's
hard drive, so that the stolen data won't be useful to anyone else.
One program that does just that is PGP Disk, by Network Associates.
It costs $39.95, and it's good insurance for any traveling
info-worker.
</P>
<P>
   Although it always helps to carry a floppy with your laptop,
floppy disks are becoming less useful all the time. The reason is
size: although computer hard disks have gone from 200 megabytes to
20 gigabytes over the past five years, the amount of data that you
can put on a 3.5-inch floppy has remained more or less the same.
Fortunately, high-speed network connections have made floppies
largely a thing of the past for desktop users. Now with a little
bit of work, you can make floppies largely irrelevant for laptops
as well.
</P>
<P>
   One of the easiest ways to get data from one laptop to another
is to beam it using infrared radiation. Practically every laptop
manufactured within the last three years has an infrared port;
Windows 98 makes it easy to use this port with ``Infrared
Recipient.''
</P>
<P>
   Infrared Recipient constantly monitors your laptop's infrared
port, sending out the name of the computer you are using and
looking for other notebook systems that are in range. When it sees
another computer, your laptop makes a funny little purring noise
and the name of the other machine appears inside the infrared
monitor window. Once the other computer shows up, you can send it a
file or a whole directory by simply dragging the file to the
infrared recipient folder. The files automatically get beamed
across the link and end up on the other computer in a directory
called ``My Received Files.''
</P>
<P>
   A much faster way to move files between two laptops is to use
Traveling Software's Laplink Professional and the company's new USB
Cable. The purple cable plugs into the USB ports of two laptops and
lets you send data much faster than over an infrared beam. Unlike
the Windows 98 built-in program, you can use Laplink Professional
to send files in both directions and browse the remote computer's
hard drive. Laplink Professional is also a remote access program:
you can use one laptop to control the second laptop over the USB
cable. Controlling a second machine over the USB cable is useful if
you are giving a presentation and there are too many people to fit
around one computer: just use a second laptop as a spare screen!
(Laplink Professional can also use the infrared port in the event
that you accidentally forget the cable at home.) Together, Laplink
Professional and the USB cable cost about $200.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Simson L. Garfinkel can be reached at plugged-in(at)simson.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
