<SLUG> BC-MEDNOTES-SCI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY CAN'T CONFIRM BLOOD-PRESSURE LINK  
 NEW HEART MONITOR CAN GO UNDER THE SKIN 
BENEFITS NOT CERTAIN FOR ANTIOXIDANT PILLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
 
 Study can't confirm blood-pressure link
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As they've looked for ways to prevent mental decline in older
people, doctors have thought that controlling high blood pressure
might be a key. A new study of more than 2,000 elderly people in
East Boston, however, failed to find a strong effect of high blood
pressure on mental sharpness over nine years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all have this great fear that we are going to lose our
minds as we age,'' said Robert J. Glynn, a biostatistician at
Brigham and Women's Hospital. ``I had hoped that we would find this
(blood pressure) was really important, but the evidence was not
compelling.''
</P>
<P>
   Previous research has yielded conflicting findings about the
effects of high blood pressure, which can cause minor or temporary
strokes that some investigators thought could impair brain
function.
</P>
<P>
   The volunteer subjects were men and women ages 65 to 102
participating in the East Boston component of two large studies of
hypertension, or high blood pressure. They had blood-pressure
readings taken nine years apart and were given brief cognitive
function tests every three years to check for any mental decline.
Glynn said there was a slight relationship between higher systolic
blood pressure (the higher of the two numbers in a blood pressure
reading) and declines in cognitive function, but that there wasn't
strong enough evidence to support a link.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; New heart monitor can go under the skin
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Doctors often have a hard time finding the cause when someone
faints repeatedly, but a new, thin heart monitor that can be
implanted under the skin can aid enormously in the search for
clues, says a Boston researcher.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Mark Josephson, a cardiologist at Beth Israel Deaconess
Medical Center in Boston, said the 2-inch-diameter, 3/4-inch thick
monitor ``is like the black box on an airplane used to determine
the cause of a crash.'' Josephson said the monitor ``records
important data that can be saved and replayed later'' to determine
why the person fainted.
</P>
<P>
   The monitor, made by Medtronic Inc. and called Reveal, functions
like a tiny electrocardiograph and stores evidence of abnormal
heart rhythms for later study.
</P>
<P>
   Conventional heart recorders, like the standard Holter monitor,
are more cumbersome, with external electrodes that have to be
connected to the skin. People usually wear the monitor for a day
and may not faint during that time, said Josephson. The new monitor
``can capture the rare events you wouldn't get on a Holter,'' even
if worn for many days, Josephson said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   A study in the journal Circulation last week showed that the
Reveal monitor identified whether the fainting was due to abnormal
heart rhythms in 86 percent of patients, according to a statement
from the company.
</P>
<P>
   Josephson said use of the Reveal monitor may save the cost and
discomfort of electrophysiological studies done in the hospital
that attempt to provoke the arrhythmia. But the cost-effectiveness
of the monitor has yet to be proven, he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Benefits not certain for antioxidant pills
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even though foods containing antioxidant substances like
vitamins A, C, and E seem to lower the risk of heart disease,
there's no scientific basis for recommending that people take
antioxidants in pill form, says the American Heart Association.
</P>
<P>
   Antioxidants mop up excess amounts of free radicals _ substances
produced in the body that are believed to play a role in the
development of atherosclerosis, which can lead to heart attacks.
Foods high in vitamins C and E and beta carotene, a form of vitamin
A, have been shown to reduce risks of heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this doesn't necessarily mean that high levels of
antioxidants achieved by consuming vitamin pills will provide
similar benefits or are even safe,'' said Diane Tribble, a
scientist at the Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory in
California and a member of the heart association's nutrition
committee. The association's journal, Circulation, this week
published the scientific advisory on antioxidant supplements.
</P>
</TEXT>
