<HEADLINE>
STANSKY MOVES MAGELLAN IN THE RIGHT DIRECTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Robert Stansky will mark his third anniversary at the helm of
Fidelity's giant Magellan fund next month, and shareholders should
celebrate with him.
</P>
<P>
   Stansky has managed to bring the rare combination of stability
and performance to what is arguably the toughest job in the mutual
fund world, qualities Magellan sorely needed in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``People gave Magellan and Bob a lot of heat,'' said Eric
Kobren, publisher of Fidelity Insight, an independent newsletter.
``I think he's done a fantastic job.''
</P>
<P>
   Stansky, 43, was under the gun during his first months on the
Magellan job because he seemed to be taking his sweet time
unloading the large and disastrous bond portfolio inherited from
predecessor Jeffrey Vinik. Billions of dollars fled the fund.
</P>
<P>
   No one is giving him heat now.
</P>
<P>
   Magellan turned heads in 1998 when it handily beat the Standard
&AMP; Poor's 500 stock index _ rising 33.6 percent vs. 28.6 percent for
the index. Skeptics had doubted the lumbering growth fund, with $84
billion in assets, could ever accomplish such a performance again.
</P>
<P>
   But Magellan has outrun the S&AMP;P 500 for an even longer stretch
during the Stansky era. Over the two-year period between the end of
January 1997 and the same point this year, the fund earned 70.5
percent, just a shade better than the S&AMP;P's 68.1 percent. It's a
narrow margin, to be sure, but four out of every five growth funds
failed to beat the index over the same period of time.
</P>
<P>
   The Magellan strategy: slow, seemingly glacial portfolio shifts
that earned market index-like returns, plus a few bold moves when a
rare opportunity presented itself.
</P>
<P>
   Such an opportunity came during plunging markets for technology
stocks in the summer and fall of last year. That made many stocks
Stansky favored much cheaper to buy, and it also freed him from the
problem of the fund's sheer size. For any one stock to have a real
impact on Magellan's performance, the fund has to buy shares worth
hundreds of millions of dollars. Purchases of that magnitude, even
spread out over time, almost always push the price way up and make
the investment more expensive to accumulate. The normal equation of
supply versus demand is temporarily thrown out of whack.
</P>
<P>
   But the tech stock plunge suddenly produced an abundance of
sellers. Magellan could buy in bulk and not price itself out of the
market.
</P>
<P>
   Stansky bought more Microsoft Corp., already the fund's
second-largest holding. He bought more Cisco Systems Inc. and Intel
Corp. He loaded up on America Online Inc., which became Magellan's
third-largest holding by the end of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, he took advantage of the tech dip,'' said James
Lowell, publisher of Fidelity Investor, another independent
newsletter. ``That's sort of a return to the old afterburners that
used to drive the fund.''
</P>
<P>
   Those tech shares certainly were the real catalyst behind a
booming fourth quarter at Magellan. As technology stocks began to
stage a furious rally in early October, the fund rose with them.
Magellan soared 27.2 percent in the last three months of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Fund analysts note Magellan's 1998 return beat the S&AMP;P 500 but
actually trailed the 35.7 percent average return of growth funds
investing exclusively in big stocks. But Magellan's portfolio did
not fit into that best-performing category at the start of the
year. Stansky's holdings were a blend of growth stocks (companies
with quickly rising earnings) and value stocks (companies whose
share price has fallen to bargain prices). He had maneuvered
Magellan into the best group of stocks by taking advantage of the
opportunity in technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's developed a very good strategy for running an $80 billion
fund,'' said Russ Kinnel, equity funds editor at Morningstar Inc.,
a Chicago fund-tracking firm. ``That's probably more encouraging
than any of the return data.''
</P>
<P>
   Stansky has made other changes at Magellan, beginning with
number of stocks it owns. His roster has been trimmed from about
500 to 334, eliminating small positions that rarely have an impact
on performance.
</P>
<P>
   Even Stansky's fans caution that Magellan is too big to ever
truly clobber the market as it did many years ago. Kobren and
Lowell both praise Stansky but rate Magellan as only a ``hold.''
Think of it as perhaps a core growth investment in a broader,
long-term portfolio, they say.
</P>
<P>
   Another gloomier measure of the Stansky era: Magellan customers
have cashed in $10.1 billion more shares than they have bought
since the fund changed managers, according to Financial Research
Corp. Most of the declines took place in Stansky's first year and
the fund has been closed to most new investors since 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre can be reached by e-mail at boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
