<HEADLINE>
STARR SOURCES; VIET NEWS; JUDGING STORIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Before the presidential impeachment scandal grinds to a halt,
could The New York Times find itself following Monica Lewinsky,
Vernon Jordan, and Sidney Blumenthal to the witness stand?
</P>
<P>
   Several First Amendment experts worry that the Times _ and other
media outlets _ might be compelled to finger their confidential
sources as part of an investigation into alleged leaks coming from
independent counsel Kenneth W. Starr's office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been worrying about this ever since the first
investigation started,'' says Jane Kirtley, executive director of
the Reporters Committee for Freedom of the Press. ``I think there
is such a scenario.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's almost inevitable'' that reporters will be asked
to reveal sources ``as this investigation goes along,'' says Paul
McMasters, the Freedom Forum's First Amendment ombudsman. As the
trial ends, ``more and more attention by the media and the courts
will be paid to what exactly the relationship between the
prosecutor and the media was.''
</P>
<P>
   This speculation comes after news that presidential attorney
David Kendall will seek sanctions against Starr for allegedly
leaking a story to the Times Sunday that Starr was considering
whether to indict President Clinton. Starr has said he plans to
conduct his own investigation of the Times matter. And there is
already a court-ordered probe of possible leaks from Starr's
office, although there are no reports to date of journalists being
quizzed about their sources. (Last year, Globe columnist John Ellis
revealed publicly that he had received information from Starr's
office. Globe vice president and assistant to the publisher Alfred
S. Larkin Jr. said Wednesday that Ellis was contacted by an
investigator, but refused to cooperate voluntarily. No subpoena has
been issued.)
</P>
<P>
   Kirtley says any investigation of leaks could hinge on whether
it is guided by the Washington, D.C., shield law _ which offers
absolute protection for confidential sources _ or the more
ambiguous ``federal privilege'' for protecting the identity of
sources.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would expect every journalist to invoke reporter's
privilege,'' says McMasters. But he warns that many reporters could
end up ``facing the difficult choice of court sanctions or giving
up their sources.''
</P>
<P>
   In an article Tuesday on Kendall's latest complaint about Starr
leaks, Times Washington editor Adam Clymer told his own paper, ``We
do not discuss our sources.'' If Times staffers were compelled to
reveal their sources, company spokeswoman Nancy Nielsen says, ``We
would take appropriate legal advice.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With 107,000 Vietnamese residents in its home base of Santa
Clara County, Calif., the San Jose Mercury News decided it was
staring at a community in need of its own newspaper. So last week,
the 291,000-circulation daily rolled out the first 20,000 copies of
Viet Mercury, a free Vietnamese-language weekly paper.
</P>
<P>
   According to Mercury News executive editor Jerry Ceppos, there
already were at least three indigenous Vietnamese dailies and a
number of weeklies in the area. But he characterizes all of them as
``partisan in one way or another.''
</P>
<P>
   The Viet Mercury, produced by a separate six-person Vietnamese
staff, will include stories prepared for that paper and some
stories translated from the Mercury News. At the same time, some
Viet Mercury articles will be translated into English for the
Mercury News.
</P>
<P>
   Ceppos says that after a start-up period, ``the goal is
absolutely to have it support itself.'' So far, the signs are good.
After planning for a 32-page issue, the debut Viet Mercury ran 88
pages. ``And I'm told you can't find last week's issue anywhere in
town anymore,'' says Ceppos.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A discarded idea for media accountability is picking up steam
again, thanks to help from an unlikely source. The news council _
an independent body that adjudicates citizen complaints against
media outlets _ has been pretty much of a dead letter since a
national news council collapsed in the early 1980s. The one success
story has been the 28-year-old Minnesota News Council.
</P>
<P>
   Now, there's a new Washington (State) News Council and the
stirring of a similar effort in Oregon. And they have one of
journalism's pit bulls to thank. ``Probably the impetus was the `60
Minutes' piece that Mike Wallace did,'' says John Hamer, the former
Seattle Times editorial board member who is the council's executive
director.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, Wallace began advocating for news councils to
increase media accountability. In late 1996, he and a ``60
Minutes'' crew sat in when the Minnesota News Council ruled that a
local TV station's report on Northwest Airlines' safety record was
journalistically flawed. The impact of that ``60 Minutes'' piece
was startling.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had inquiries immediately from people in 29 states,'' says
Minnesota council executive director Gary Gilson.
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, Hamer characterizes the local journalistic community's
response to the Washington News Council as mixed. ``The management
of both major dailies (The Seattle Times and The Seattle
Post-Intelligencer) have been saying we'll stay neutral right
now.'' But tellingly, the Times is allowing a staffer to serve as a
media member of the council.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
