<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLD VINYL FLOORING MAY CONTAIN ASBESTOS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I plan to put ceramic tiles on my bathroom floor. The house
is nearly 70 years old. There is vinyl flooring there now, and I
was told that under that vinyl is asbestos. What can I do now
before putting in the ceramic tile?
</P>
<P>
   BILL GENTLE, Arlington, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. You won't know what is under the vinyl until you test both
the vinyl that's on the floor now and anything underneath. Sheet
vinyl, installed as recently as 15 to 20 years ago, may have a
white or gray backing; if so, it is probably asbestos. Break off a
small piece and have it tested by an asbestos abatement company (in
the Yellow Pages). If there is no asbestos, you can go ahead and
scrape up everything to the wood floor. Then put down a sheet of
concrete board (WonderBoard is one brand), and apply the tiles with
a thin-set mortar. You could do the same over the existing sheet
vinyl.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My house has hot-water heat with four zones. The radiators
are baseboards. One room is not very warm but other rooms beyond it
and further down the system are warm enough. There are not many
radiators in the baseboards of the room in question but there are a
lot of bare pipes (without fins) under a baseboard cover. Can I try
clamping fins on some of those bare pipes?
</P>
<P>
   PAUL SCHOTTLER, Acton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. I think the fins will help a lot because they will radiate
more heat into the room than the bare copper pipe will. The
installers might just have missed putting in the fins or using
finned pipes; I can't imagine how this could happen, but it is
possible.
</P>
<P>
   Sellers of the fins are Samuel Hurwitz Co., Plumbing Supply, 120
Southampton St., Roxbury, MA, 617-442-3500; and Patented
Manufacturing Co., Dept. PP, Lincoln, MA 01773.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The saga of varnished hardwood floors continues: S.C. of Revere
told us this: ``I got tired of the rugs on several
beautifully-varnished hardwood floors, so I took them up. I was
also concerned how long the varnish would last if it was not
protected, especially since I have two dogs. A contractor did the
varnishing, and on the floors with an oil-based polyurethane, I
have no scratches or any other damage. There are lots of scratches
on the water-based polyurethane.''
</P>
<P>
   S.C.'s commentary illustrates the superiority of oil-based
polyurethane over water-based polyurethane, although the
contractor-installed, oil-based polyurethane might have been
moisture-cured polyurethane, superior to both the other varnishes.
The moisture-cured varnish cannot be installed by the layman; it
must be professionally applied. According to many floor men,
moisture-cured is the best.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My old-fashioned steel milk can is still in good shape; that
is, it is not falling apart and has no holes. But there is some
rust; in fact the whole outside of the can has a patina of rust, an
orange color. How can I clean it up? Is there a shop that does this
sort of thing?
</P>
<P>
   SHEILA WHALEN, Holliston, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. The only shops that I know of that treat metal are those that
do replating, and since your can is galvanized, there is nothing to
replate. So here is what you can do: Dip fine steel wool in paint
thinner and rub off the rust. Once it is clean of rust, you can
give it a very fine coat of oil, which will help prevent further
rust. So will keepng it in a dry, warm place, such as a house. To
apply that thin coat of oil, sprinkle a few drops of mineral or
lubricating oil on a cloth, knead the cloth to spread the oil
around, and wipe down the can. Dispose of oily cloths safely by
burning them.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I think I have a bat in my bathroom. I saw it on a towel
rack, then scooting on the floor. I closed the door and am not
happy about going back in. How can I get rid of it?
</P>
<P>
   AFRAID OF BATS
</P>
<P>
   A. The bat probably got into the bathoom from the attic or other
nook in which it was hibernating. If it doesn't go back to its
roost, it may die because of its hibernation being disturbed. If
you dare go back into the bathroom, open the window wide and turn
on all the lights in that room. The bat is likely to leave. If that
doesn't appeal to you, call an animal control person, who is listed
in the Yellow pages under ``Exterminators.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader
questions. Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107. The
Handyman chats on line Thursdays, 1-2 p.m, at
http://www.boston.com, keyword: Chat.)
</P>
</TEXT>
