<HEADLINE>
MOOD SWINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Of dogs and ski trails and, well, a bunch of stuff like that:
</P>
<P>
   I realized last Sunday at Wompatuck State Park that my dimming
enthusiasm about cross-country skiing had nothing to do with
cross-country skiing, but with the general impotence of the most
recent New England winters.
</P>
<P>
   Not in the mountain country so much, because Alpine ski areas,
especially those with half-mile or more altitude, produce plenty of
machine-made snow to help nature over her dry spells.
</P>
<P>
   No, it's the backyard I'm talking about. The woods and golf
course, the summer meadows turned to winter whalebacks, all those
places that, when covered with snow, become snow playgrounds. The
world refreshed and bright and amazingly fun.
</P>
<P>
   To my mind, a perfect winter Sunday this side of the Alpine
slopes combines cross-country skiing, Bloody Marys and Mozart, not
necessarily in equal amounts.
</P>
<P>
   And, just as I remember winters in my childhood when it seems we
played pond hockey every afternoon into the dark, it now seems that
we had winters with lots more casual cross-country skiing than we
have now.
</P>
<P>
   The local ski shop in my town _ a coastal town subject to salty
ocean air, a known snow-wrecker _ once kept a few dozen pair of
skinny skis to rent out to locals who skied on the golf course and
in the town forest on weekend afternoons.
</P>
<P>
   Sometime a decade or so ago, the shop dropped its ski rental
business, not for any lack of interest, but because those Currier
and Ives winters seem to have gone the way of buggywhips.
</P>
<P>
   Or is it just the way memory works? Doesn't every kid remember
the few big snowfalls of childhood and believe that it was like
that every day of every winter? One big blizzard with the power out
for three days, living in candlelight and frigid air, goes a long
way in the memory.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, when one of those matchless days of snow comes along
these winters, we take note. And click on the skis. Wompatuck State
Park in Hingham, Mass. was our spot, a nice woodsy corner of
Boston's South Shore with trails and meadows all rather mellow,
i.e. no hills worthy of mention.
</P>
<P>
   It was easy to forget this matchless Sunday of primary colors _
gold and blue and bright, fresh snow _ that Wompatuck Park is a
former ammunition depot from the World War II era (Lord knows
what's buried down under all that gorgeous snow) or that last time
the Grateful Dead came to town that woebegone band of aging,
time-warped hippies that orbited the band everywhere, ended up
camping in Wompatuck where they threw a blast that scared
suburbanites out of their minds.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, we skied the park, not that there were tons of snow last
Sunday. The skis did tend to hang up on a few exposed rocks along
the woods paths. Still, judging by the crowds that were out skiing
after the one storm in weeks that blanketed the region, there is a
latent hunger in folks everywhere to get out and play in snow.
</P>
<P>
   And the day did raise more questions than answers about our
snowy pursuits. It seems there was a dog in our foursome, a
spirited golden retriever that would run ahead on the trail then,
dismayed about the slowness of its human companions, kept doubling
back as if to tell us to get the lead out.
</P>
<P>
   Along the trail we encountered two ladies skiing in the opposite
direction, and as we stopped to let each other pass, one of them
remonstrated us for skiing with a dog.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want dogs on the ski tracks,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Now understand, the couple who own (are owned by) said dog,
found it a year or so back by following a star in the East that
brought them to the puppy manger to find their furry miracle.
</P>
<P>
   So the dog's owner, an experienced skier who understands well
that dogs are not allowed at real cross-country centers with tracks
set for skis, opined as how this was a state park supported by tax
dollars, and the tracks were only there by the chance passing of
other skiers. They had not been set for skiing at all, and family
pooches had as much right on the paths as the people they brought
there.
</P>
<P>
   This issue was left unresolved, but it did become a focal
controversy in the cross-country world almost as hotly contended as
one which occurred a few weeks before when, as a highly opinionated
person I happen to know was skiing on a golf course, she was
verbally accosted by a man she referred to only as ``a fuming
idiot.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What did he say to you?'' she was asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``To stay off the greens, whatever they are. I thought golf
courses were all green.''
</P>
<P>
   The man told her that skiing on the greens ruins them for
golfers, though she doubted there were any golfers around, and had
not seen one out all day.
</P>
<P>
   No, the man said, the skis make impressions on the greens that
stay when spring comes.
</P>
<P>
   To which the skier, somewhat chagrined at the suggestion that
her weight could make such impressions, ended the conversation by
suggesting that golfers need more of a challenge anyway, and that
they should play in fields of real grass, as the Scottish used to
do.
</P>
<P>
   So here are the questions left for readers to help us with: (1)
Should dogs be allowed to gambol in the snow at non-cross-country
ski areas? (2) Do skiers really imprint golf courses with their
tracks, or is this just more golf folderal?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Tony Chamberlain writes about the outdoors for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
