<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-GRIFFITH-PROFILE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MELANIE GRIFFITH: BAD GIRL MAKES GOOD 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LOUIS B. PARKS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Melanie Griffith has played some dangerous and wild characters
on screen, but perhaps none more so than Sid in ``Another Day in
Paradise,'' opening Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a wild movie, a tough movie,'' Griffith agrees. ``I'd
never been asked to make a movie like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Sid is the girlfriend of Mel (James Woods), a thief and drug
dealer who can be charming _ until he gets drunk. Mel goes on a
road-trip crime spree, taking with him Sid and a pair of drugged up
teen-age lovers.
</P>
<P>
   How tough is Sid?
</P>
<P>
   At one point in the movie, Mel's gang is in a tight spot with
some rival drug dealers. Sid gets them out of the jam with an
aggressively applied shotgun. And she looks comfortable doing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father taught me how to shoot, starting when I was 4, so I
am pretty handy with a shotgun,'' Griffith says. Her voice is
girlish, and she freely sprinkles giggles and four-letter words in
conversation.
</P>
<P>
   Tough though she is, Sid is also the most humane character in
the film, taking a maternal interest in the young lovers, Bobbie
and Rosie, played by Natasha Gregson Wagner (daughter of Natalie
Wood) and Vincent Kartheiser. Sid tries to keep them out of trouble
with Mel and the law.
</P>
<P>
   Griffith, 41, says it was the chance to play a character like
Sid that led her to do the movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never played a heroin addict or a thief or a junkie. Once
in ''Fear City,`` a movie I did a long time ago (1984), I was kind
of a semi-junkie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a phone call from Jimmy Woods saying you've got to read
this script. I'm going to produce it. I'm going to star in it. I'll
split my salary with you, which was nothing anyway.'' She laughs.
``It was a very low-budget film. I didn't do it for the money,
that's for sure. I just thought, `Wow, this is really cool and
different and interesting.' ''
</P>
<P>
   While it's true that Griffith's most successful role was as a
secretary turned smart businesswoman in ``Working Girl'' (with
Harrison Ford), Sid is not a total departure from past roles.
Directors have tended to cast her as wild, bad or sexy.
</P>
<P>
   Griffith's first part, an extra, was at age 14 in ``The Harrad
Experiment'' (1973), which starred her mother, Tippi Hedren (``The
Birds,'' ``Marnie''), and Griffith's future two-time husband, Don
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   But her first attention-grabbing role came in 1975, playing a
wild, promiscuous teen-ager opposite Gene Hackman in ``Night
Moves.'' And early in her career, she appeared in nude photos in
Playboy with Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   After that beginning, she was often typecast as a bad or sexy
woman, including her most notable characters before her
Oscar-nominated ``Working Girl'' role: Brian De Palma's ``Body
Double'' (porn star); Jonathan Demme's ``Something Wild'' (bad
girl): and Mike Figgis' ``Stormy Monday'' (prostitute).
</P>
<P>
   In her private life, Griffith also went through a long period of
drug addiction and a well-publicized rehab program. Her up-and-down
romantic life, especially her two marriages to Johnson and her
latest one to Antonio Banderas, also have received much attention.
</P>
<P>
   So it's surprising that Griffith seems confused at the
suggestion that she has a wild and sexy reputation. She seems more
comfortable when the description is changed to ``free-spirited''.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think maybe I am partly that way,'' she says, sounding
thoughtful.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, ``Working Girl'' opened a broader range of roles
to her, and her nearly 3-year-old marriage to actor Banderas (``The
Mask of Zorro'') has made her personal life more stable.
</P>
<P>
   She has said that Johnson was not supportive, but today, at the
hint of a question about that, she interrupts quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't want to say that.'' She laughs as though sharing a
little joke. ``I know where you're going.''
</P>
<P>
   She has no hesitation, however, saying that Banderas is
encouraging of her and her career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh yeah, completely. He's right here with me. We just saw the
movie (''Crazy in Alabama``) we did together last night.''
</P>
<P>
   Banderas, who is sitting nearby listening, reminds her the
response cards to the sneak preview were good, and she giggles
again. ``Crazy in Alabama'' is a comedy-drama directed by Banderas.
Griffith stars as an eccentric who leaves her husband in the South
to try her luck in Hollywood. The film is due out in late spring or
summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so cool. It's so great, I mean ...,'' she's momentarily
at a loss for words about Banderas' movie. ``He's really good. I
know I'm his wife, but he's really good.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Another Day in Paradise'' is the second directorial effort for
55-year-old photographer Larry Clark. Clark shook up the movie
world in 1995 with his controversial debut film, ``Kids,'' a
graphic portrayal of pre-teen street life, depicting youths
drinking, drugging and having mean-spirited sex. It outraged many
viewers and led to accusations that Clark was too emotionally
involved with his child actors. But there was no denying his
ability to tell a powerful story.
</P>
<P>
   Griffith was impressed with Clark's work on ``Another Day in
Paradise,'' despite the major discord that flared on the set and
afterward. There were times when Clark and Woods and Clark and
co-producer/co-writer Stephen Chin almost came to blows.
</P>
<P>
   Chin and Woods had mortgaged their homes to finance the movie.
Clark, who has had a long history of drug problems, put their
security in jeopardy when he got back on heroin and wouldn't _ or
couldn't _ complete editing the movie in time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Larry is a great guy, he really is,'' Griffith says. ``He
tries really hard, and he made a great movie. I don't want to be
too hard on him because he just got out of rehab. He had a relapse
after he finished the movie, and now he's great again.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing I like about this movie is it's anti-drug,''
insists Griffith, who says she has been drug-free for 10 years.
``There is nothing supportive of doing drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   After her good reviews for ``Something Wild'' and the success of
``Working Girl,'' Griffith seemed on her way to major stardom. But
a series of career choices that seemed good on paper _ ``Bonfire of
the Vanities,'' ``Shining Through,'' ``Born Yesterday,'' ``A
Stranger Among Us,'' ``Milk Money'' _ turned out to be
disappointments or disasters. Griffith's acting reputation took a
beating.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's OK; I don't care.'' she says. ``I'm not bothered by
it, you know what I mean? I feel like I still have a life.''
Another giggle. ``I still have some time.
</P>
<P>
   She prefers to be optimistic that her career is again on the
upswing with her well-received small roles in ``Lolita,'' Woody
Allen's ``Celebrity'' and now a lead in ``Another Day in
Paradise.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty happy with what I've done,'' Griffith says. ``I
mean, my family comes first. Antonio and my kids are much more
important than trying to calculate a career. I just take what
comes.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
