<HEADER>
A1765 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SKI-OLDER-BOS &LR;      02-04 1089
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKI-OLDER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINALLY, HE MAKES THE GRADE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LINCOLN, N.H. _ The day started bad early for Gren Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   He was overdressed. He was sweating. He was scared. He was lost,
his family nowhere to be found. He felt like an unhappy 8-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   But then, he found himself looking into a pair of beautiful and
kindly eyes, a miracle on snow. And the woman said to him: ``Come
with me. I can help you.''
</P>
<P>
   And he did, and she did. And Grenville has lived happily ever
after. So far.
</P>
<P>
   No, Gren Anderson was no little boy on that momentous afternoon
last winter when he made his first turns on a pair of skis. It just
felt that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was 45,'' says Anderson, an investment adviser for Fiduciary
Trust in Boston. ``And I hated winter. It was just a terrible time
for me. Every time it snowed I was bummed.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Anderson had skied once before, which is why he was so
scared at the prospect of doing it again. As a teenager ``I nearly
killed myself'' when he went on a group trip to Woodstock, and so
he had pretty much written skiing out of his life.
</P>
<P>
   But Anderson didn't want to waste an entire season simply
because he hated every winter weekend. And he thought of his wife,
Melanie, who had skied before but wasn't getting the opportunity
now. And perhaps most important, he thought of his 9-year-old
daughter, Ali, whose friends went north to ski on winter weekends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I decided that Ali should really get the chance to know how to
ski,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So Anderson, a man who likes to take life in large bites, made
the grand gesture. He booked a week's lodging at Sunday River last
February vacation, made arrangements for equipment rental, then
went to the Bob Smith ski shop and said, when asked what he needed:
``Picture me in my underwear. Start there.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, his extended family _ sister Kim,
brother-in-law Richard Andrew and kids _ were so delighted with the
coming spectacle of Gren on skis that they rented a condo near the
Andersons for the same week.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were all so excited,'' he remembers, ``and I was getting
nervous. I knew I did not need an audience. I could picture the
humiliation.''
</P>
<P>
   And of course, it is more difficult for someone in middle age to
take up a sport that so many have imprinted in their muscles and
nervous systems as children. As the vacation week approached, Gren
remembers asking himself several times, ``Why did I do this?''
</P>
<P>
   So the inevitable morning arrived, and the first thing Anderson
discovered was that the people at Bob Smith had taken him at his
word and had a field day. He put on all his new ski clothes _ long
underwear, overalls, turtle neck, fleece sweatshirt, new ski
jacket.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could hardly walk with everything on,'' he remembers,
sensing early trouble, ``I fell off the bed and couldn't get up.
They had to help me.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, out into the crowd of a February vacation, he remembers
putting on a little slapstick show (you know the one where you bend
over to pick up the ski pole you dropped and whack someone behind
you with the skis on your shoulder). And he could not quite get out
of his mind a thought that if simple locomotion without skis was
this tough, what would skis feel like?
</P>
<P>
   The first wise idea he had was to sign up for a group lesson,
but he had to wait 50 minutes ``for my public execution.''
Meanwhile his daughter and her cousins all came up to him to give
him a grim ``Good luck!'' before they took off skiing, and his wife
and the in-laws took off, leaving Gren miserable, abandoned, and
sweating. Then things really got scary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went out front and looked up at that mountain and almost
fainted,'' he said. The kids' ``Good luck'' rang in his ears. But
then, something like a devine intercession occurred. Behind him, he
heard a voice at the ski school say, ``Betty, my lesson's been
canceled.'' It was an instructor who was signed up to give an hour
private lesson, and Gren Anderson jumped at the opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like the heavens parted,'' he remembers. ``I was
looking at this beautiful pair of eyes, and I don't think I'd ever
met anyone as nice. I said to her, `I'm out of shape. I've never
skied. My family left me here. And I'm scared.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The instructor, named Maggie, he thinks, ignored his whining and
(after peeling off a layer or two of clothing so that he could
move) simply said: ``Let's go skiing.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the epiphany of Grenville Anderson. From that day, a new
skier was born.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took three days of lessons,'' he says, ``and I'll always be
grateful to Maggie because she was so kind and helpful. At one
point she said, `My job is to make you want to ski. Don't worry.'
''
</P>
<P>
   His biggest fear at first is common to most new skiers: how to
stay in control. From the top of the beginner's hill, Anderson
learned how to ski in a snowplow (wedge), and the first time he
turned left and right all the way from top to bottom, he recalls,
``I was hooked. I knew I had overcome a personal fear. I knew I was
going to ski.''
</P>
<P>
   From there it was to the top and his first run all the way down.
Then to Waterville Valley, more lessons, and this year to Loon over
Christmas vacation, where he graduated to blue runs, still taking
lessons. At one point, after being hit by an out-of-control
snowboarder, Anderson's instructor skied above him, removing his
fear about a similar incident as he was concentrating on his form.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just knew what to do,'' he says. ``He knew I was nervous
about being hit again and took away the fear.'' Just more
supporting evidence, according to Anderson, that lessons are the
way to learn skiing, especially for a scared middle-ager.
</P>
<P>
   And the rewards?
</P>
<P>
   ``Skiing has really changed my life,'' he says. ``The greatest
thing is that I love winter now, and I love being outdoors and
having a new family experience.''
</P>
<P>
   The real reward, he says, came over the Christmas holidays when
he found himself riding up the lift with Ali, now 10. As most kids
know, some of the best skiing snow is found when it rains, but most
people over about age 15 want no part of wearing plastic bags over
their parkas and putting up with all that wet.
</P>
<P>
   But with skiing, Gren Anderson is a fully reborn adolescent, and
as he rode into the soggy heavens, still amazed at where he was and
what he was doing, he heard his daughter say, ``Daddy, it's so
great you're skiing. It's so great to be skiing with you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
