<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-SUNDANCE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUNDANCE LESSONS: LEARNING TO LOVE FILM IN UTAH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN KRICH  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARK CITY, Utah _ ``Wear warm shoes and don't take anything
personally.''
</P>
<P>
   Such was the warning from one movie industry insider as I
prepared to attend my first Sundance Film Festival _ an obligatory
rite of passage and shivery initiation for anyone more than
casually concerned with the future of independent (i.e.,
idea-driven) cinema in this country.
</P>
<P>
   Begun as an outgrowth of actor Robert Redford's laboratory for
budding screenwriters, Sundance has become a genuine American
phenomenon: part idealistic enclave, part networking frenzy, a bit
of left- and right-coast arrogance grafted onto the heart of the
pure West, one schmoozing party in parkas, the breeding ground for
art as much as ``projects,'' a haven for both cinematic purists and
unabashed hustlers.
</P>
<P>
   For a new participant during this year's 10-day, late-January
fest, there were some rude shocks and pleasant surprises. For
starters, Park City, Utah, is pretty darn ugly, a sprawl of condos
and malls all in chocolate brown, best seen at night when the
nearby mountains appear to loom closer.
</P>
<P>
   While the chalets most participants share are plush and
Jacuzzi-equipped, most of the venues are uncomfortably funky and
less than state-of-the-art, with films shown in the town library
auditorium, two hotel convention rooms, a small mall triplex.
</P>
<P>
   Given the capacity, tickets are relatively easy to obtain to all
but the hottest shows. Considering many are thrown by the likes of
Playboy and The Gap, food at most of the parties is sun-dried
meager and quickly snatched-up, the music loud enough to frustrate
all but the pushiest encounters, the lines to get into such
numerous affairs far longer than for most of the films and far
tougher to crash (with bouncers seemingly imported from lower
Manhattan).
</P>
<P>
   The free buses that shuttle cineastes about are remarkably
efficient, featuring the chance to run into budding starlets like
Tamlyn Tomita out of their make-up, piped-in broadcasts of the BBC
World Service, and friendly, folksy drivers who garnish their
restaurant recommendations with quips like, ``There's only so many
ways to burn a steak.''
</P>
<P>
   At Sundance, bottled water is a continuous need and celebs
aren't that easy to come by. My final tally: Ethel Kennedy at the
screening of her daughter Rory's film (a film about Appalachia
called ``American Hollow,'' Roger Ebert snapping shots of every new
director, Robert Townsend guest singing with a blues band, Harvey
Keitel flying in from Rome for the day.)
</P>
<P>
   Here, documentarians are not second-class citizens, ``Q and A''
sessions go forever, and many of the selections remain comfortingly
oddball, low-budget and often on socially-aware subjects in grim
contrast to the deluxe resort environs.
</P>
<P>
   Even at 2 a.m., as lines await the next shuttle or frostbite,
the emphasis is on the movies themselves, with everyone wanting to
know, ``Seen anything good lately?'' At Sundance, the word ``buzz''
takes on a tangible, quantifiable meaning.
</P>
<P>
   The power of big Hollywood bucks, or the prospect of potential
box office trillions, temporarily transforms this tiny mining camp
into America's media capital _ the first place West of the
Mississippi, and the only place in the Rockies, to receive
stackloads of Variety, the Los Angeles Times, Entertainment Weekly,
the New York Times Arts and Leisure Sections, even daily updates of
the on-line Indie Wire finished on laser printers in the basement
of a ski lodge.
</P>
<P>
   Posters pepper every inch of wall (though this year's best ploy
was for the low-budget ``Dylongso,'' which, in the manner of the
film, placed stakes in the snow bearing Polaroid portraits of
``endangered black men'').
</P>
<P>
   Here, cell phone and Internet services get more overloaded than
any of the lifts. ``You're breaking up'' refers to satellite,
rather than emotional, connections. And you regularly overhear
conversations that begin, ``I've just tied up the North American
rights. ...''
</P>
<P>
   All this wheeling and dealing is just dandy, according to a
presenter of Native-American heritage at Saturday's culminating
Awards Night, because Redford had been sensitive enough to ask for
the blessing of the Ute people who once ruled these image-besieged
lands. But does Sundance still belong, as one administrator claims,
``to the community of film artists''?
</P>
<P>
   The proof is in the pudding, or in this case, the
post-production, in how many of this year's honorees would have got
their films made in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly not Berkeley-based Vietnam War widow Barbara
Sonneborn's ``Regret to Inform'' or the biggest winner out of
Milwaukee, ``American Movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Even 26-year-old Tony Bui's ``Three Seasons,'' the big winner
thanks to its timely evocation of a non-threatening, spiritually
uplifting Vietnam, would never have been backed by a big studio due
to its insistence on Vietnamese dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   Though masterful foreign works like Mexico's ``Under a Spell,''
Mali's ``Life on Earth'' and Spain's ``Lovers of the Arctic
Circle'' go largely ignored, there are still plenty of spontaneous
boos when a Mercedes-Benz executive compares a great movie to a
great car.
</P>
<P>
   As I joined revelers in a dizzy night of high-altitude boogieing
at the Park City Racquet Club, I couldn't help feeling that the
event remains vital _ not quite the property of the Utes, but still
not entirely the property of Disney.
</P>
<P>
   Averaging three parties, four movies and five hours sleep per
day, I'd made it through without tearing a knee or getting
pneumonia, a Sundance virgin no longer, and thoroughly seduced.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
