<DOCNO> NYT19990204.0188 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1772 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-CAKE-HNS &LR;      02-04 0994
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-CAKE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKIN' MUSIC A PIECE O' CAKE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Calif.) 
 
By RICK MITCHELL 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ John McCrea of the band Cake has a fundamental problem
with modern rock: He thinks it's environmentally wasteful.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something always has to be negated. And when I think negated,
I think discarded. And when I think discarded, I think landfill,''
McCrea says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everything is useful and nothing should be thrown
away. When you throw things away, you're negating other things to
define yourself. What about just defining yourself without so much
negation? You can't survive without something to dis? You are an
emotionally pathetic being.''
</P>
<P>
   Cake's music acts as a postmodern recycling bin for pop-culture
kitsch. Herb Alpert trumpet lines intersect with wailing P-Funk
keyboards, and disco bass lines bump up against crying pedal-steel
guitars. Through it all, McCrea sings in a droll, deadpan tone that
recalls David Byrne of Talking Heads.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get bored really easily,'' McCrea says. ``I can't listen to
just one kind of music. At this point in the late 20th century,
where we have access to so many different kinds of music, to not be
influenced by a lot of different stuff seems kind of fearful.''
</P>
<P>
   Miraculously, Cake's scavenger's scrap heap of sounds has
produced two huge modern rock hits: ``The Distance,'' from Cake's
1996 platinum album, ``Fashion Nugget,'' and ``Never There,'' from
last year's certified-gold follow-up, ``Prolonging the Magic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I appreciate that they are interested in our wares. Sometimes
I wonder why,'' McCrea says of modern rock radio programmers.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I hear one of our songs in that context, it's always
surprising to me. I don't hear any other songs like our songs on
there. Most of the time I just hear big, chunky guitars and Viking
drum sounds.''
</P>
<P>
   McCrea says he is planning to start his own Internet-radio
station, one that would program a wider mix of music than what can
be found on formatted radio; ``Aretha Franklin followed by AC/DC
followed by Benny Goodman. I think there are more people out there
that would want that than radio thinks. Maybe there's not that many
in any one town, but if we can get people from all over ... ''
</P>
<P>
   He is hoping for a spring launch date. Details can be found on
Cake's Web site: www.cakemusic.com.
</P>
<P>
   McCrea, 34, grew up in the northern California city of
Sacramento. He was performing as a solo singer-songwriter when he
began to hear more parts for his songs than he could play alone on
acoustic guitar.
</P>
<P>
   Cake was formed in the early '90s with electric guitarist Greg
Brown (since replaced by Xan McCurdy), bassist Victor Damiani and
drummer Todd Roper. The lynchpin of the band's sound was the
addition of trumpeter Vincent di Fiore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought about saxophone, and then I thought, `No. Too many
beer commercials had ruined it for me and saxophone,''' McCrea
says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to New Orleans, and I realized, `What is wrong with
trumpet?' I realized there was nothing wrong with trumpet _ just
too many people may have forgotten about it. I also went to Mexico,
which was good. That `ranchera' music makes a lot of sense to me,
Vicente Fernandez and stuff like that. People think it's schmaltzy
because he cries a lot, but I think there's something very powerful
about that ballad tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that McCrea can envision himself as an earnest crooner in
any language.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I'm bad enough to be schmaltzy. That requires a
bravery that no snickering white guy has,'' he says. ``Confessional
poetry in songwriting makes me a little queasy because I'm from a
different world. I'm also a private person. I don't think it's good
for me to let people know such personal stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   McCrea's lyrics tend to come in a stream-of-consciousness flow
in which the literal meaning of the words is less important than
how they sound.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not a poet,'' he says. ``I choose words because they go
well with the notes. And if I can also sneak in some comment about
something, then fine. But that's not my primary goal. My primary
goal is to make music.''
</P>
<P>
   In the publicity photos for ``Prolonging the Magic,'' McCrea and
his compadres are decked out in matching jeans, shirts and cowboy
hats. They look like a Top 40 country cover band, something Cake
most certainly is not.
</P>
<P>
   McCrea admits his ironic sense of humor might have gotten the
better of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the whole young country thing was kind of funny.
Like the jeans are significantly tighter in young country _ really
uncomfortably so, I should add. It's an interesting subculture. I
really do find it fascinating.''
</P>
<P>
   While McCrea insists he actually likes some of the new country
songs, what he really likes is old honky-tonk and western swing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This may sound like an incredible stretch, but I really think
it's true that there wouldn't be a Marilyn Manson without ob
Wills. What Bob Wills played was really pre-rock music. So many
things about that music were, like, for the first time ever.``
</P>
<P>
   Which brings him back to what he views as the fallacy of modern
rock culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a fat, greedy society. Punk rock may look lean and
mean, but it's the same old attitude toward the world,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't mean this as an insult against people. I just think
that the cultural machinery is plush. Throw away your old records,
buy all new ones! It's like musical deforestation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't it ironic that punk-rock, the negation movement, feeds
perfectly into capitalism?''
</P>
<P>
   Good point. But by defining itself by what it's not _ not
punk-rock, not new country _ isn't Cake guilty of doing what McCrea
accuses other people of doing?
</P>
<P>
   ``Only by default,'' he says. ``I am trying to root that
attitude out of myself.''``
</P>
<P>
   Any other pertinent observations?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes. I take back everything I said.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
