<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-IRRESISTIBLE-REVIEW </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S QUITE EASY TO RESIST `SIMPLY IRRESISTIBLE' 

</HEADLINE>
 -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LOUIS B. PARKS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Late in the romantic comedy ``Simply Irresistible,'' actress
Sarah Michelle Gellar sums up the movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't worry,'' she says, ``I won't do anything funny.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing funny, nothing romantic and nothing interesting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Simply Irresistible'' is the early candidate for most
schizophrenic film of the year. The filmmakers _ writer, director
and actors _ simply do not have a clue from one scene to the next
what type of movie they are making. Is it a comedy, a romance, a
fantasy or perhaps a cooking show?
</P>
<P>
   Whatever genre they are copying, they are clumsy at it.
</P>
<P>
   According to distributor Twentieth Century Fox, Gellar (TV's
``Buffy the Vampire Slayer'') is not doing interviews for the film.
Clearly, she wants to forget it.
</P>
<P>
   Gellar is Amanda Shelton, the young owner of a small,
70-year-old New York restaurant called Southern Cross. Amanda
inherited the place from her mom, but Amanda can't cook, and the
Southern Cross is about to deep six.
</P>
<P>
   A mysterious man tells Amanda her dead mom is still interested
in her, and gives Amanda a magic crab. She takes the crab back to
the restaurant, where it climbs on a shelf in the kitchen to watch
everything that goes on in the eatery.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, Amanda is a master chef. Whatever emotions she is
feeling are transmitted through her food to the people who eat it.
</P>
<P>
   Amanda meets a young businessman, Tom Bartlett (Sean Patrick
Flanery), who is about to open an exclusive Manhattan restaurant.
Tom has a policy of never dating any woman more than three times,
because his computerized date tracking program proves that
happiness decreases on the fourth date. But circumstances _ Tom's
chef quits the day before the gala opening _ keep drawing Tom
toward Amanda.
</P>
<P>
   The film plays like the first draft of a script badly in need of
polishing. False starts, half-developed characters and pointless
events lead nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   Amanda finds the lost earrings of her mother, and they briefly
seem to be the cause of her improved cooking, not the crab, but
then that idea is dropped. In the middle of the movie, the romance
of Amanda's food makes Amanda and Tom literally float to the
ceiling of her restaurant, and he decides she's a witch.
</P>
<P>
   We never get any reason why Amanda is so attracted to unpleasant
Tom, no explanation of the man who gave her the crab, no idea why
her mother has such powers from the grave. And so on.
</P>
<P>
   None of that would matter if the movie was entertaining, but
rookie director Mark Tarlov has not a clue how to lift the leaden
dialogue of his wife, rookie screenwriter Judith Roberts, off the
basement steps. Most of the film is staged and shot like a TV
sitcom, with two people standing side-by-side in front of the
camera and tossing inane lines back and forth until you want to run
screaming from the theater.
</P>
<P>
   The acting by generally good actors is so uniformly bad _ like
the first read through of a commercial _ that one must blame
Tarlov. Gellar, who won an Emmy for her teen years on ``All My
Children'' and slays audiences weekly on her WB show, has an
appealing screen presence but it is almost lost here. Flanery
(``Powder'') who was much better seven years ago in TV's ``The
Young Indiana Jones Chronicles,'' seems to be doing a Michael J.
Fox imitation, and failing.
</P>
<P>
   In the main support roles, Dylan Baker (so good in the recent
``Happiness'') and Patricia Clarkson fare no better.
</P>
<P>
   The movie does have one mildly memorable scene in which a
roomful of diners are struck first eloquent, then speechless, by
the wonderfulness of Amanda's food. But any attempt to promote this
film as a ``Babette's Feast'' or ``Like Water for Chocolate'' for
young audiences is insulting.
</P>
<P>
   The PG-13 rating is essentially for a few suggestive words. The
movie has no sex, nudity or violence.
</P>
<P>
   Until Tuesday, Fox planned to release this film without giving
advance screenings to critics, which almost always means the film
is D.O.A. This time, the studio's first instinct was right.
</P>
<P>
   Simply resist it. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
