<SLUG> BC-CENTRAL-MOVIE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CENTRAL STATION' A WINDOW ON WORLD UNSEEN BY HOLLYWOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB FENSTER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - In Rio, the trains are so overcrowded that young men
get their seats by clambering through the windows before the doors
open.
</P>
<P>
   In a train station and a city so packed with life and poverty,
no one will care about the fate of a lost boy and an old woman.
</P>
<P>
   Brazilian filmmaker Walter Salles cares, and he has made
``Central Station,'' a film as poignant in its search for the heart
of humanity as Akira Kurosawa's ``Ikiru.''
</P>
<P>
   Dora (Fernanda Montenegro) is a retired schoolteacher who
supports herself at a table inside the train station by writing
letters for the scores of illiterate people who cannot write their
own _ letters of love, hope and desire.
</P>
<P>
   Dora has grown so bitter in her cynicism, however, that no
desires, no dreams for a better life can touch her.
</P>
<P>
   Still, when a 9-year-old boy, Josue (Vinicius de Oliveira), is
orphaned at the station, Dora takes him in. Is hers a forlorn
effort to help the boy find the father who abandoned him? Or does
she have something else more sinister in mind?
</P>
<P>
   Their search through the city and into the countryside of Brazil
is a journey through the poverty and religion of the nation and the
resilience of the soul.
</P>
<P>
   ``Central Station'' is not the kind of film that Hollywood would
ever make. It's too small, too quiet, too subtle.
</P>
<P>
   It's the kind of simple, profound movie that used to flourish in
Europe years ago, when the Neo-Realism movement produced such
pictures as ``The Bicycle Thief'' and ``The Four Hundred Blows.''
</P>
<P>
   There's still a world cinema that tells the lives of real people
in their dark pain and small joys. However, you have to read the
subtitles to find it.
</P>
<P>
   If the acting in ``Central Station'' appears perfectly natural,
it is a credit to the talents of Montenegro, one of Brazil's
greatest stage actresses, and Oliveira, an airport shoeshine boy
who convinced the director he could play the role. He was right.
</P>
<P>
   In Dora's lined face, we see the bitter weight of age. Josue's
searching eyes hold all the innocence and suspicion of youth.
</P>
<P>
   Salles tells their story in the simple terms of street realism,
and it's emotionally gripping. Many of the people who appear in the
film are not actors. They don't have to be. The director finds
their souls staring into his camera.
</P>
<P>
   People who never see foreign films are missing a world of
pictures for Hollywood's one picture of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Central Station,'' which won a Golden Globe as Best Foreign
Film, will open that world for you.
</P>
<P>
   One thing you don't need the subtitles to realize: The voice of
the train station announcer is distinct to that profession but the
same voice all over the world.
</P>
<P>
   Rated R for profanity, ``Central Station'' is in Portuguese with
Eng lish subtitles. 4 stars. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-04-99 1348EST &QL; 
