<SLUG> BC-LOST-AND-FOUND-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN LOST AND FOUND, EVEN BODY PARTS TURN UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (With: LOST-AND-FOUND-NET)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KATE GURNETT  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The gold wedding band glinted in the barroom
light as Laurie Mahar wiped down the empty table.
</P>
<P>
   She picked it up, read the inscription. She knew the names. He
was a regular.
</P>
<P>
   He'll be back for it, she figured, standing amid the dark wood
panels of Mahar's tavern in Albany. Months later, Laurie Mahar
waits, safeguarding this symbol of love amid the more mundane keys,
coats and pocketbooks her patrons have left behind.
</P>
<P>
   Easy come. Easy go. You can't take it with you. Or, sometimes,
keep it on you.
</P>
<P>
   Walt Disney World collects Space Mountain casualties _ wigs and
toupees _ amid its 1,000-item daily intake of lost items.
</P>
<P>
   At the newly remodeled Grand Central Terminal in Manhattan,
there is plenty of room for lost items. Clerks tag and store
several hundred a day _ putting jewelry in drawers, coats on racks,
cash in the safe.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all organized,'' said clerk Rich Hegmann. ``Whadda you
got? You got radios, cell phones, duffel bags, suitcases,
portfolios. You got packages. You got scarves. You got hats. You
got keys. You got pagers. We just got one today _ how about a
hearing aid? We've had live rats, live mice _ they were in a cage.
They left 'em on the train.
</P>
<P>
   ``Food we discard. That's automatic. That would be a mice
problem. We got raincoats. We got jackets. On a rainy day you got
umbrellas. On a cold day you got gloves.''
</P>
<P>
   Is that it? ``Bobby, what else we got?'' Hegmann calls out.
``Oh, we've had dentures. Prosthetic devices _ two legs. Today we
got an electronic acupuncture device. Ninety-nine percent of the
stuff is left on the train. Body parts. We had body parts.''
</P>
<P>
   Body parts? ``A plastic surgeon left it in a cooler on ice, on
the train.''
</P>
<P>
   What kind?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know. Something like that we don't open,'' Hegmann
said. ``If you crack it open you destroy the property.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps even more surprising is the cash people turn in. Hard,
cold cash. For incentive, unclaimed funds go to the finder after 90
days for less than $500, or after a year for larger sums.
</P>
<P>
   But the hand-ins boost Hegmann's faith in human nature. ``There
are a lot of honest people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At Paul's Cleaners in Albany, the wedding ring doesn't surprise
C.J. LaFalce. His own storeroom contains a party of wedding gowns
left behind by brides over the years.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know, really, what the reason is,'' LaFalce said.
``Once you get to the point where it's a couple years or so _
they're not coming back for them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They either got hit by a bus or they moved to California,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   LaFalce donates the leftover clothing to job-hunting welfare
recipients.
</P>
<P>
   Pricier items are quickly claimed. Like the large diamond ring
left in the tuxedo pocket or the $10,000 necklace tangled in a
woman's sweater. Or the $4,500 wad of bills, bound for Atlantic
City, that the owner left in a dirty pants pocket.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
