<SLUG> BC-LOST-AND-FOUND-NET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAN'T FIND IT? CHECK THE WEB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KATE GURNETT  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Golf clubs. Your relatives. Porcelain China. A homing pigeon.
Fellow Vietnam veterans. A cast-iron sugar cane pot from Boutte,
La. Atlantis.
</P>
<P>
   These lost items, and more, are being sought on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   If you've looked everywhere and run a newspaper ad, going on
line can give your search that extra boost. People and pet listings
predominate.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Concienne was last seen in Louling, La., his daughter says.
Velvet, a Doberman pinscher puppy in a lavender choker, took off
with a collarless German Shepherd in Oakland, Calif. Nathan Winkler
of North Carolina misplaced his Olympus camera.
</P>
<P>
   To complete your search for lost loves or loved items, here are
a few good spots to check on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   _ Lost &AMP; Found International. This site (www.lost-and-found.com)
includes a Lost Friends Center and links to pet recovery. The
company also sells property tags with a toll-free telephone number
to call if the item is found.
</P>
<P>
   For pet listings, try the Pet Action League
(http://www.petrescue.com) and American Kennel Association's Animal
Recovery (http://www.akc.org/carfaq.htm).
</P>
<P>
   There are several spots to check for missing children, including
http://www.children-missing.org.
</P>
<P>
   In the Loft helps locate lost pigeons
(http://205.206.241.99/rprs/.)
</P>
<P>
   If all else fails, click on Amazon.com and buy a copy of ``How
to Find Lost Objects.'' This book provides a complete strategy for
locating lost objects, with examples from Sherlock Holmes to Zen
Buddhism. Author Michael Solomon said he honed his skills in his
office at a Baltimore high school where he oversees the Lost &AMP;
Found.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-04-99 1352EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
