<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990204.0195 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1795 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REFUGEE-SMUGGLING-$AD     02-04 1478
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFUGEE-SMUGGLING-$ADV07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AS SMUGGLERS TAKE TO AIR (PLANES) , CUBAN, HAITIAN REFUGEES
INCREASE
 &HT;    EDs: Optional add begins at 1000 words.
 &HT;    With REFUGEE-DATA-$ADV07.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., Feb. 7 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Flat broke, with no family or friends to turn to, Mario
Acosta says he's a gloriously happy man. Happy to be on U.S. soil,
that is.
</P>
<P>
   Smiling, the Cuban migrant tells a familiar story that, at
first, sounds like so many others, of paying someone he knows only
by reputation to help him escape his communist homeland.
</P>
<P>
   But his tale strikes a unique chord when he reveals his mode of
transportation -- plane, not boat.
</P>
<P>
   ``The economic situation is so bad in Cuba that I would have
done anything to get out,'' explained Acosta, 35, who left behind a
14-year-old son. ``Traveling by airplane is safer and it's more of
a sure thing than traveling by boat.''
</P>
<P>
   To get the money to pay for the trip, he sold everything he had
-- his bed, stereo, all of his clothes.
</P>
<P>
   As a worker in a tobacco factory, he had access to cigars, which
he sold to tourists for U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, he scraped together $2,500, which he gave to a
smuggler promising safe passage to Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The journey, which began Jan. 20, was a two-legged one -- a hop
to Costa Rica, then on to Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Smuggling via plane is one often-overlooked twist in the recent
saga of rising illegal migration from both Cuba and Haiti to South
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, smuggling has become a growing concern in
Florida, which has seen a huge increase in the number of refugee
migrants arriving by both plane and boat.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a marked increase in the flow of migrants to
the southeastern part of the United States, and the larger
percentage is being smuggled in,'' said Lt. Cmdr. Marcus Woodring,
public affairs officer for the U.S. Coast Guard here.
</P>
<P>
   Immigration officials estimate that 80 percent of all illegal
migrants, refugees in South Florida are smuggled.
</P>
<P>
   They say smuggling has been on the rise since the United States
and Cuba signed an immigration agreement in 1995 that allowed
Cubans picked up at sea to be immediately returned to their
country.
</P>
<P>
   This change in U.S. policy forced Cubans to forgo their
home-made rafts and turn to smugglers with high-powered speedboats
fast enough to outrun Coast Guard cutters.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, tales of dramatic landings on Florida's
beaches have grabbed the headlines.
</P>
<P>
   But a growing number of refugees also are turning to smugglers
to arrange trips by plane, which they say gives them an even better
chance of reaching South Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Smuggling via plane works like this: The smugglers receive a
fee, which can range from $2,000 to $8,000, to provide permits so
that the Cubans can fly to Costa Rica or another third country.
There, the Cubans are provided with a place to stay as well as with
false passports so that they can get on a plane to Miami. While in
the plane or at the Miami International Airport, the Cubans often
destroy their false documents. Once safely on U.S. soil, they're
free to request political asylum.
</P>
<P>
   Haitians also use smugglers, but they generally don't destroy
their documents. Instead, they're more likely to pass them off as
genuine.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Miami airport sees a significant number of people every
day coming through with no documents or bogus documents,'' said Dan
Geoghegan(CQ), assistant chief in the U.S. Border Patrol office
here. ``The Cubans get on an airplane in Venezuela or Costa Rica or
wherever and they flush their documents down the toilet.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Cuban President Fidel Castro has acknowledged immigrant
smuggling as a pressing concern.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent speech, he said his government has asked for life
sentences for ``inhuman'' smugglers.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, he urged the Clinton administration to send
back Cubans who reach South Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Cuba reportedly has captured and imprisoned 15 smugglers from
the United States over the past year who are currently awaiting
sentencing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since they are residents of the United States, we are willing
to return them to be punished there,'' Castro said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the U.S. Catholic Conference, an agency here
responsible for helping resettle Cuban and Haitian refugees, has
experienced a big surge in clients. It expects to see 3,500
refugees this year, compared with 2,000 last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people have no money, they're desperate, they feel like
they're going to die unless they leave their countries,'' said Raul
Hernandez, coordinator of Cuban-Haitian programs.
</P>
<P>
   Just last Monday, 11 frightened Cubans washed up on trendy South
Beach just as Emilio Estefan, the Cuban-born musician and husband
of singer Gloria Estefan, was taking his morning jog.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was so cold I brought them a little Cuban coffee just to
welcome them to the land of freedom,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The men, who were taken into custody by the U.S. Border Patrol,
said they left Cuba within the last week aboard a 15-foot wooden
vessel powered by a diesel engine.
</P>
<P>
   In the year ending September 1998, U.S. Border Patrol agents
picked up about 1,200 refugees in South Florida.
</P>
<P>
   They are now on track to more than double that amount this year,
detaining more than 900 since October.
</P>
<P>
   The Coast Guard, which handles those caught at sea, intercepted
1,047 Cubans and 1,206 Haitians in 1998, compared with 406 Cubans
and 587 Haitians in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   This year, immigration officials believe several factors will
keep migrants coming in growing numbers.
</P>
<P>
   The lingering effects of Hurricane Georges continue to drive at
least part of the exodus.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the economy in Cuba has remained stagnant, while an
ongoing political crisis has paralyzed Haiti, where 80 percent of
the population is unemployed or underemployed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Haitians are coming in by boat, and they are also coming in
through the airport,'' said Mark Briesemeister(CQ), a supervising
special agent for the Immigration and Naturalization Service's
anti-smuggling unit. ``They aren't usually smuggled directly from
Haiti, but they come via the Bahamas.''
</P>
<P>
   He said his unit is currently prosecuting 17 smuggling cases.
</P>
<P>
   In a poll of 1,400 Haitians conducted last year by the U.S.
Embassy in Haiti, nearly three-fourths of those surveyed said they
would leave their poor homeland if they could.
</P>
<P>
   ``With total chaos in Haiti, these desperate people don't have
any choice but to try and leave,'' said Ken Boodhoo, an expert on
Haiti at Florida International University.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts say U.S. policy is also to blame for the increased
migration flow.
</P>
<P>
   In March 1998, President Clinton allowed Cuban-Americans to send
up to $1,200 a year to family members in Cuba. He changed the
measure last month to allow any American to send money to anyone in
Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Remittances to residents of Cuba now total more than $800
million a year, a staggering amount that helps keep Cuba's
foundering economy afloat, and in some cases also allows Cubans to
fund their escape.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say U.S. policy affects immigration because these
remittances allow Cubans to pay smugglers to bring them here in
high-speed boats, or however they can,'' said Mark Krikorian of the
Center for Immigration Studies, a Washington, D.C.-based think tank
that favors reduced rates of immigration.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Although immigration numbers are up this year, they're nowhere
near those of the last benchmark year for illegal immigration. In
1994, more than 30,000 Cubans sailed to Florida aboard rafts, inner
tubes, and anything else that floated after Castro stopped his
crackdown on citizens trying to flee.
</P>
<P>
   The crisis forced President Clinton to revise U.S.-Cuban policy
so that Cubans captured at sea would be immediately returned to
Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. policy toward captured Haitians -- about 25,000 of whom
arrived in 1994 -- has been to return them to Haiti whether they're
picked up at sea or on land.
</P>
<P>
   If Cubans make it to U.S. soil, they're generally detained only
a matter of days before being released into society.
</P>
<P>
   That's why a plane or a speedboat have become necessities for
Cubans unwilling to risk being returned to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Reinaldo Mesa, a Cuban psychiatrist, arrived in Miami via plane
on Jan. 17.
</P>
<P>
   He has four brothers and sisters in Cuba, who pooled their money
to pay a smuggler so that Mesa could make the trip to Florida,
stopping in Costa Rica first.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am the only one in my family with a college education, so
they sent me here to earn money to send back,'' said Mesa, 48. ``I
earned only US$17 a month working as a doctor in Cuba, so I can be
of more help to my family if I'm here.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
