A1801 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-PARADISE05-COX     02-04 0468
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-PARADISE05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Junkie flick substitutes shock for plot
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the not-very-subtle irony of the title doesn't tip you off,
maybe the director will. ``Another Day in Paradise'' is another
showy but empty effort from Larry Clark, who previously gave us the
showy but empty ``Kids.''
</P>
<P>
   The sizzle in ``Kids'' was teen-sex chic; the sizzle here is
needle chic. As in lots and lots and lots of shots of characters
shooting up. But as was true of ``Permanent Midnight,'' ``Rush''
and countless others, ``Paradise'' goes under the skin as a
hide-your-eyes shortcut to getting under our skin. It's quick-fix
filmmaking in which the sensationalistic aspect of drug use is
employed to divert us from a familiar plot, cliched characters and
a junkie movie junked up with stuff we've already seen in other,
better movies.
</P>
<P>
   Mel (James Woods) and Sid (Melanie Griffith) are seasoned
small-time crooks/addicts who have been together for years but
haven't been able to have children. They ``adopt'' Bobbie (Vincent
Kartheiser) and Rosie (Natasha Gregson Wagner), a young couple
taking their first tentative steps into a life of crime and smack.
</P>
<P>
   Woods, who co-produced, gets many opportunities to show off his
trademark abusive intensity. He's still brilliant at it, a virtuoso
of violent paranoia. But we've seen it in movies dating back to
``The Onion Field'' (1979). Here, thanks to Clark's inept
direction, Woods' anarchic operatics have no place to go.
</P>
<P>
   Wagner, who will continue to be identified as Natalie Wood's
daughter until she chooses some better scripts, again plays a
nubile young idiot, just as she did in ``Two Girls and a Guy'' and
``First Love, Last Rites.'' She's certainly pretty, and she may
even have talent. What she needs is a new agent.
</P>
<P>
   The movie's saving grace is Griffith. Since getting a little
respect for ``Working Girl'' a decade ago, her career has gone
through major ups and downs. Here, she plays the earth
mother/junkie role that Julianne Moore had in ``Boogie Nights,''
and she does a bang-up job. Whether dispensing black beauties or
chicken soup, toting a big gun or a dainty little needle, she
commands our attention with a tough-tender portrayal that rarely
makes a wrong step.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another Day in Paradise'' does Griffith a big favor. I wish it
did something for the rest of us.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another Day in Paradise''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: D+
</P>
<P>
   Starring James Woods and Melanie Griffith. Directed by Larry
Clark. Rated R for violence, language and drug use. At Lefont
</P>
<P>
   Plaza. 1 hour, 32 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Paradise is hardly the word for it.
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Ringel writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
