<HEADER>
A1802 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-PAYBACK05-COX     02-04 0607
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-PAYBACK05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Payback' never pays off
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Payback'' plays like it looks: cheap, tired, bleached out.
</P>
<P>
   Screenwriter Brian Helgeland makes his directing debut by
shooting this Mel Gibson vehicle in grainy shades of blue and gray.
This bad-film-stock look reinforces the feeling that we're seeing
something that's already been through the projector too many times.
</P>
<P>
   True enough. This is a remake of John Boorman's much better
``Point Blank''; the new version never justifies the revisit. Going
the anti-hero route, Gibson plays Porter, a career thief who heists
$140,000 with his junkie wife (Deborah Kara Unger) and friend Val
(Gregg Henry). They promptly double-cross him and leave him for
dead.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, but he isn't. Returning with a vengeance, he's determined to
track down Val and retrieve his $70,000 cut of the money. That
means infiltrating an organized crime ring called the Outfit, with
help from one of Hollywood's standard-issue high-class hookers with
a 24-karat ticker. This one goes by the name of Rosie (Maria
Bello).
</P>
<P>
   Helgeland, whose uneven screenwriting record includes both
``L.A. Confidential'' and ``The Postman,'' doesn't seem to know
what his movie is. It starts off grim but has flashes of humor and
turns almost farcical in climactic shootouts and explosions.
</P>
<P>
   On top of a wobbly tone, the script cheats and takes easy
shortcuts. We're never in doubt that Gibson's Porter has what it
takes to take down the bad _ or at least worse _ guys. Though in
one scene he'll get beaten to a pulp and in the next he seems
superhuman and invincible. Or at least invisible. He sneaks inside
a fortified, mob-run hotel or slips under a car in broad daylight
to fiddle with its gas line _ while the car is full of the men who
are specifically there to kill him. Helgeland doesn't try to make
these scenes plausible; he just assumes we're supposed to believe
it. Nah.
</P>
<P>
   Porter is one of those one-name guys with a mysterious past and
no discernible character traits. He's probably supposed to be
iconic. But he's a blank point in a stylized city that's neither
Chicago nor New York; it's just a generic, gray metropolis. You
can't tell whether the movie is trying to deconstruct this kind of
gangster flick or is just failing to make it specific, believable
and fun.
</P>
<P>
   The casting is weirdly uneven. James Coburn and Kris
Kristofferson offer some scenery-chewing menace as two members of
the Outfit, while William Devane recycles his suave-thug
performance. Henry makes a standard-issue, sadistic villain, and
Bello is about as believable a hooker as Shirley MacLaine in
``Sweet Charity.'' For that matter, Gibson just doesn't make a
great bad dude. It's a relief when his usual charm leaks through.
</P>
<P>
   David Paymer as a weaselly, small-time hood is a plus, and so is
Tony-winning stage actor John Glover as one of Devane's henchmen.
Best of all is Lucy Liu of ``Ally McBeal,'' in a variation of Famke
Janssen's S&AMP;M killer role in ``GoldenEye.'' Liu plays a dominatrix
who gets turned on by violence. When somebody threatens to shoot
out the brains of a trick lying in bed with her, her comic,
thrilled reaction gives the movie its own good laugh.
</P>
<P>
   At least she's having fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Payback''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   Starring Mel Gibson and Gregg Henry. Rated R for strong
violence, language and drug and sexual content.
</P>
<P>
   1 hour, 42 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A by-the-numbers revenge thriller.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
