<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 13:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1803 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-RUSHMORE05-COX     02-04 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-RUSHMORE05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A fun fable, a captivating Bill Murray
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When 15-year-old prep school student Max Fischer (Jason
Schwartzman) gets ready to tell a woman that her husband is
sleeping around on her, he's considerate enough to first offer her
a choice of sandwiches and beverage.
</P>
<P>
   That tells you something about Max, the irksome yet weirdly
ingratiating hero of ``Rushmore.'' This wonderfully eccentric
comedy is the second film from director Wes Anderson, who co-wrote
the script with Owen Wilson. They also made ``Bottle Rocket'' in
1996. (Nobody saw it; go rent it.) The new movie proves that they
haven't lost the offbeat wit and skewed viewpoint that made their
first one such a nice surprise.
</P>
<P>
   A 10th-grade scholarship student at Rushmore Academy, Max
devotes himself to every extracurricular activity offered: martial
arts, the debate team, beekeeping, whatever. He's very proud of his
fencing skills. And he runs the school's theater club (``The Max
Fischer Players''), directing a gritty stage version of ``Serpico''
or, better yet, a Vietnam drama complete with live explosions.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Max's grade-point average dwindles in direct
proportion to the number of hobbies he's juggling.
</P>
<P>
   But who cares about grades? One of Rushmore's benefactors, a
steel tycoon named Mr. Blume (Bill Murray), recognizes a kindred
spirit in the gung-ho Max. He even helps underwrite Max's latest
project: the construction of a massive aquarium on Rushmore's
baseball diamond. Max comes up with the project because he's
smitten with a first-grade teacher, Miss Cross (Olivia Williams),
who happens to like fish.
</P>
<P>
   The friendship between student and businessman hits a pothole
when Blume falls in love with Miss Cross as well, setting Max off
on a campaign of underhanded, dangerous pranks. These, in turn,
incite retaliatory strikes from Blume. (Bees, bikes and brake fluid
all play a part in the guys' private war.)
</P>
<P>
   Director Anderson understands that prep school isn't just a
place, it's a state of mind that can be found in the skull of a
middle-aged man like Blume. (We see him early in the movie,
floating to the bottom of his pool to escape a party at his own
house; he's like a grown-up Benjamin from ``The Graduate.'') Blume
and Max are perfectly matched opponents, two lovelorn idiots whose
obsession isolates them from the ``normal'' world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rushmore'' itself unfolds in a parallel universe removed from
the ``reality'' of other movies. It's a fable, complete with
theatrical curtains that sweep open for each new chapter of the
comedy. Scriptwriters Anderson and Wilson create their own sort of
dream logic, populating their tale with pungent, unexpected
characters. Max's best pal is a pipsqueak underclassman named Dirk
(Mason Gamble), while his nemesis is a classmate named Magnus
(Stephen McCole), a Scottish lad missing part of an ear. And Max's
dad is a doting, supportive barber, played by Seymour Cassel.
</P>
<P>
   The movie corrals its characters for an ending that has the
all's-well sparkle and shapely resolution of a Shakespearean
comedy. Its vision of romantic fulfillment manages to be both
tongue in cheek and heartfelt.
</P>
<P>
   In its stylistic exaggerations, ``Rushmore'' gets closer to the
truth about high school than all the ``realistic'' teen comedies at
the multiplex (``Varsity Blues,'' ``She's All That,'' etc.). It
captures the heady solipsism of being a teenager, the time when
anything seems possible and love feels like a matter of life and
death. Newcomer Schwartzman strikes all the right notes, making Max
obnoxious but never losing our sympathy, even at his chain-smoking
brattiest. Williams brings emotional shading to what could have
been a thankless role, the idealized object of affection.
</P>
<P>
   But the best work is Murray's. He plays the balding, defeated
Blume with a melancholy delicacy that's both moving and very funny.
His performance is like the movie itself _ captivating, original
and unlike anything else you've seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rushmore''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   Starring Jason Schwartzman, Bill Murray and Olivia Williams.
Rated R for language and brief nudity. 1 hour, 33 minutes
</P>
<P>
   A delightful comedy of bad manners.
</P>
<P>
   FIVE OF BILL MURRAY'S BEST
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Groundhog Day'' (1993): Stuck in time with Andie MacDowell
in this witty romantic comedy.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Ed Wood'' (1994): Playing the small role of Bunny
Breckenridge, a fey hanger-on in the circle of the world's worst
filmmaker.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Scrooged'' (1988): As a hardhearted TV producer who learns
the hard (and often very funny) way to love Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Ghostbusters'' (1984): Who you gonna call?
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Tootsie'' (1982): Rooming with cross-dressing actor Dustin
Hoffman in this classic comedy.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Cosntitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
