<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 14:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1805 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOTARO-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      02-04 1057
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTARO-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRIDE COMETH BEFORE A FALL AT RESALE STORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LAURI NOTARO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - You always go in with a lot of high hopes.
</P>
<P>
   You always enter the resale clothing shop confident that once
you place the pile of once-favorite apparel on the counter, sirens
will sound. Bells will go off. The salespeople will gather around
your heap of clothing, emitting gasps of wonder and small cries.
They, like you, will understand this collection to be the Holy
Grail of used and slightly soiled clothing.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, as the door swung open and I entered the store, I got
the feeling I was a little out of place. I realized I was the only
one in the entire establishment with hair that wasn't the color of
a Teletubbie, and I suddenly felt self-conscious that none of my
facial features were impaled with a skewer the size of a shish
kebab or tire iron.
</P>
<P>
   As I took a number and waited my turn, I looked around and
immediately noticed that most of the merchandise was so skimpy and
little I thought I was in Baby Gap. As I picked up a shirt the size
of my mouse pad, I suddenly had this feeling that I was a genetic
freak, the only one in the universe ever to hit puberty or grow
back fat.
</P>
<P>
   My fears were alleviated, however, when the sales associate
began sorting through my stuff, and placed item after item in the
good pile. With each piece of clothing that made the grade, my
heart did a little jump. I pitied the one little tank top that the
sales girl placed to the side, a raggedy little thing I almost used
the day before to refinish a door.
</P>
<P>
   Considering the obvious quality of the other clothes, I felt
embarrassed by the tank top, and decided to vocalize my apologies
for making the sales girl waste a quarter-second of her time to
look at it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now how did THAT get in there?'' I said as I pointed to it.
``That must be my husband's!''
</P>
<P>
   She looked at me blankly from under her lime-green bangs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This one, I'll take,'' she said, motioning to the rag, then
turned her attention to the big pile. ``That's the stuff I don't
want.''
</P>
<P>
   She took this opportunity to say aloud which items were being
rejected, and that's when I understood I had a better chance being
voted the Fiesta Bowl Queen or finding the winning Powerball ticket
tucked under my bra strap than I did of getting a girl with a bobby
pin rammed through her lower lip to say anything but ``Pass.''
</P>
<P>
   One by one, she lifted garments from the original pile with
pinched fingers and placed them in the reject pile. I saw them all
sail through the air _ skirts, shirts and pants I had once worn
proudly that were now vibrant indicators that I didn't have any
better fashion sense than Kathie Lee Gifford. The stuff I wore in
public three months ago now couldn't fetch three bucks at the
resale auction block.
</P>
<P>
   Humiliated, I felt as if there was a spotlight shining on me
that stripped away my current identity and immediately launched me
back into 10th grade, when I showed up on the first day of school
wearing gauchos and rainbow suspenders when everyone else looked
like Olivia Newton John in the last scene of ``Grease.''
</P>
<P>
   Pass. Pass. Pass.
</P>
<P>
   As I stood at the counter, I became aware that because I do not
dress like Dharma, a Spice Girl or one of the bulimics from
``Friends,'' I have become a frump, and I seriously debated with
myself whether I should tell the bobby-pin girl that these were
really my mother's clothes when she was a secretary for an
orthopedic doctor.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, a vision popped into my head, a flashback from several
nights before when my husband and I were watching ``Seinfeld''
re-runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know,'' he said with a faint little chuckle, ``when we
first met, you reminded me of Elaine.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Really?'' I said, taking it as a compliment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' he continued. ``But now you remind me of the wife on
`Everybody Loves Raymond.' ''
</P>
<P>
   As the bobby-pin girl pushed my mass of rejected dork clothes
toward me, she wore an expression that plainly said, ``Tell me
again why you thought your stuff was so cool you could bring it
here and I'd give you money for them. I am bored by your clothes.
And I am bored by you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's, um, Escada,'' I said, trying to override my
humiliation by pointing to a pair of slacks lying crumpled and
defeated at the top of the mound.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I saw that,'' she said in monotone, scratching the
tattoo on her upper arm as her dead eyes stared at me. ``Eswardo?
They have that at Target now.''
</P>
<P>
   ``ESCADA,'' I said bluntly, knowing full well that although I
bought them at the Nordstrom outlet for 13 bucks, at retail they
demand $400. I also seriously doubted that you could pick up a
Coleman lantern, a package of Twizzlers and an Escada outfit all at
the same place in a strip mall.
</P>
<P>
   She looked at them again, and I was sure that once she realized
her mistake, she'd pair it with the dust-cloth tank top and I'd be
somewhat vindicated. Scouring the pants in her hands with her eyes,
she nodded her head approvingly.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are nice,'' she admitted, ``and I'd probably take them
if they weren't stained.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're stained?'' I answered unbelieving. ``Where? I don't
see any stains!''
</P>
<P>
   She sighed and opened the slacks from the waistband, splaying
the diameter as far as it would go.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right here,'' she said as she pointed to it. ``In the
crotch.''
</P>
<P>
   I gasped as my face flushed red. Honestly, I'd never even worn
the pants, though apparently someone had, which explained a whole
lot of how I got a $400 pair of pants for 13 bucks.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not taking any of this stuff?'' I asked, pointing to
the big pile.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' she replied. ``That's all winter wear _ ''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's FEBRUARY,'' I reminded her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides the pants with the crotch stain,'' she finished.
``Would you like cash or credit for the tank top?''
</P>
<P>
   ``How much for cash?'' I asked, now defeated and gathering my
clump of rejects.
</P>
<P>
   ``A dollar twenty-five,'' she answered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Credit then,'' I said, walking over to the closest rack and
pulling a shirt off a hanger. ``I need to refinish a door.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Laurie Notaro is a freelance writer. Send comments about her column
to the Rep, P.O. Box 2245 NF-19, Phoenix, AZ 85002 or by e-mail at
laurienotaro(at)usa.net. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
