</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-TRIAL (Washington) _ House prosecutors make a last-ditch
appeal for the Senate to hear from former White House intern Monica
Lewinsky at the impeachment trial of President Clinton. But
Republicans signal ebbing support for calling witnesses or a
declaration of presidential wrongdoing. By STEWART M. POWELL, JUDY
HOLLAND and JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-CENSURE (Washington) _ Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan,
D-N.Y., and Sen. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif., work on a censure
resolution that would condemn the president's conduct in the Monica
Lewinsky affair. The Democrats hope to pick up Republicans support
for the brief condemnation and vote on it before voting on the two
impeachment articles against President Clinton. By DAN FREEDMAN and
JUDY HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) - In the good old days, vice
presidents were like children, supposed to be seen and not heard.
But Al Gore has thrown away the mold and is on a highly visible
roll toward the 2000 election, free of special prosecutors, free of
his most serious primary rival and free of any morality taint from
the Monica Lewinsky scandal. By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
