<SLUG> BC-RUSHMORE-DIRECTOR-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEARED TO BE WEIRD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB FENSTER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Here's the Bill Murray theory of tipping: 100 percent.
</P>
<P>
   That system of matching the tip to the bill probably works
better if you're already a rich movie star. But it's the system
Murray taught the young star and director of the comedy
``Rushmore.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When we set off on our publicity tour of the country, Bill
gave us a thousand dollars for tip money,'' ``Rushmore'' star Jason
Schwartzman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked him if the money was for both of us,'' ``Rushmore''
director Wes Anderson interjected. ``Bill said, `Yes, but Jason is
really in charge of it.' Jason sent his $500 back, but I've got
mine in my pocket.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson also has a potential cult hit in his pocket. The
offbeat ``Rushmore'' is about a prep school nerd who, instead of
being ineffectual like most movie dweebs, has the school wired.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson must have Hollywood wired because he convinced the
Disney Studio to put up $10 million to make a strange movie whose
humor is an acquired taste that many people may never acquire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a weird movie, too,'' Anderson said of the film
he wrote and directed. ``I thought we would have a lot of trouble
after ``Bottle Rocket'' (his first film) didn't make any money for
anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``But for some reason this movie had several people who wanted
to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   One of those people was Joe Roth, the decision maker at Disney
when it comes to movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had Joe's support,'' Wes said. ``I don't know that we had
any other support there, but Joe's word was enough.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Rushmore'' was cheap to make compared with the $35 million
that's now average for a studio film. ``We were too small for
anyone to bother us,'' Anderson said happily.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the kind of movie where they tell you who to cast.
They were just taking a shot at an unusual movie. Disney gave us
the green light, and Bill Murray was a bonus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I showed the movie to Joe when it was finished, and he said,
`Great, let's release it.'
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a perfect situation,'' the director speculated. ``I
keep waiting for what it's like when you get in trouble. Sometime
that has to happen. But so far it's been good.''
</P>
<P>
   Overcoming calamity is what ``Rushmore'' is all about, as
Schwartzman, a first-time actor, creates a winning character out of
Max Fisher, the competent nerd.
</P>
<P>
   ``The script was funny,'' Schwartzman said. ``But we wanted to
be serious about it. To Max, none of it is a joke.''
</P>
<P>
   As much as Schwartzman gave to the character, Max gave something
back to the actor.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got back from making the movie, I was more confident in
myself as a person,'' he said. ``I'd done something I was proud of
and felt good about. People thought I was beinQ:f`ooX7t,f''VLp5u.]
uex&AMP;[slC\{f[HR{%
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
