<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   LAWYER-SOFTWARE (Houston) _ A federal district judge issues a
ruling banning self-lawyering software.
</P>
<P>
   GAY-ATTACK (Denver) _ Legislatures in Wyoming, Montana and
Colorado defeat hate crime legislation that had been given a boost
in an odd sort of way by the beating death of a gay student,
Matthew Shepard. Meanwhile his parents ask that their son not
become a political martyr, and an article in Vanity Fair says he
was HIV positive at the time of his death. By James Brooke. (900
words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-ANNIVERSARY (Tehran) _ As Iran marks the 20th anniversary
of its Islamic revolution, there is a widening gap between Iranians
and the defining event of their recent past. More than half of
Iran's 68 million people were born since the events that toppled a
king and stunned the world; millions more can barely remember them.
Among older Iranians, many regard the revolution as no longer
relevant to today's problems. By Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   AUSCHWITZ-CAMP (Frankfurt, Germany) _ Germany's biggest bank,
Deutsche Bank, says loans it made in the Nazi era helped to finance
construction of the Auschwitz death camp. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   ARAFAT (Washington) _ Arafat, the PLO leader, meets with
President Clinton; other developments on the visit. By John M.
Broder.
</P>
<P>
   RUSHDIE-INDIA (New Delhi) _ On orders of Indian government, the
writer Salman Rushdie is granted a visa for the first time in 10
years. India was one the first countries to ban ``The Satanic
Verses.'' By Barry Bearak.
</P>
<P>
   SUDAN-U.S. (Washington) _ The owner of the factory in Sudan
targeted by U.S. missiles says he will sue the U.S. over the
attack. By James Risen.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-TERROR (Washington) _ Attorney-General Reno, Secretary
of State Albright and FBI Director Freeh speak before Congress
about counter-terrorism. By James Risen.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.S. (Washington) _ Secretary Albright gives a speech on
Kosovo. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-ECON (Moscow) _ The Russian government issues economic
figures for 1998: the Economy shrank 4.6 percent, the biggest
decline in four years. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-RIGHTS (Moscow) _ Disappointing U.S. and human rights
groups, the Russian Supreme Court allows a treason case to proceed
against an ex-navy environmental whistle-blower. By Michael R.
Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-DISSIDENT (Beijing) _ China sentences a pro-democracy
campaigner, who sneaked back into the country from abroad, to 4
years in prison. By Elisabeth Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-ECON (Rio de Janeiro) _ Developments in the Brazilian
economic crisis. By Diana Jean Schemo.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-RATES (London) _ The central banks of Britain and
Denmark, which are not part of the euro zone, reduce interest
rates, while the European Central Bank, which sets rates for the 11
euro nations, stands pat. The European Central Bank is trying to
avoid further weakening the euro, which has fallen more than 3
percent against the dollar since it began trading. By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   CREDIT (New York) _ Bonds continue to fall. At midday, the long
bond was down 1 5/32 point, with the yield at 5.33 percent. By
Jonathan Fuerbringer.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At midday, the industrial average was down
76 points, or 0.8 percent, and the Nasdaq index was down 57 points,
or 2.3 percent. Elsewhere, prices fell half a percent in Tokyo and
rose 0.2 percent in Hong Kong. They declined 0.6 percent in
Frankfurt but rose 0.2 percent in London. Stocks were down 2.6
percent in Brazil and 0.7 percent in Mexico. By Robert D. Hershey
Jr.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ Microsoft gets another chance
to try to recover by presenting a new videotape, and the company's
James Allchin will still be on the stand. Then Michael Devlin, the
software developer speaking on the company's behalf, will testify.
By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   BEAR-PROBE (Undated) _ Folo on reports that the Securities and
Exchange Commission's enforcement staff has notified Bear Stearns
and one of its senior executives that it plans to recommend filing
civil charges against them over activities of the firm's big
trade-processing unit.
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE-BROKERS (New York) _ Prompted by customer complaints, New
York's attorney general opens an investigation into online
brokerage firms. And ETrade experiences more technical troubles.
</P>
<P>
   ADVANCED-MICRO (New York) _ Advanced Micro Devices shares, which
tumbled 14 percent Wednesday after the company canceled appearances
at two investment conferences, are down as much as 15 percent
today.
</P>
<P>
   MALAYSIA-ECON (Hong Kong) _ Removing a portion of its capital
controls, and seeking to restore international confidence and
attract the money it needs to rebuild its shattered economy,
Malaysia ends its ban on the withdrawal of money from the country
by foreign portfolio investors. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   RETAIL-SALES (Undated) _ Retailers' sales rose last month, with
some results exceeding forecasts, as chains reduced prices on
coats, sweaters and leftover holiday goods.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   FED-REPORT (Washington) _ The Fed will release the minutes of
the Dec. 22 meeting of its policy committee. By Richard W.
Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   SMITHKLINE (Undated) _ Folo on reports that SmithKline Beecham
is in negotiations to sell its Diversified Pharmaceutical Services
unit to a drug-store chain for more than $1 billion, below the $2.3
billion it paid for it. The company would become the latest drug
manufacturer to withdraw from the pharmacy-benefits business. By
David J. Morrow.
</P>
<P>
   AIRLINES-Y2K (Undated) _ Developments on the first day that
travel plans for Jan. 1, 2000, can be entered into many of the
computer-reservation systems used by travel agents.
</P>
<P>
   HITACHI-OUTLOOK (Tokyo) _ Hitachi, Japan's largest electronics
maker, widens its estimate of the loss it will post for the current
fiscal year to 375 billion yen, or $3.3 billion, from 275 billion
yen. By Stephanie Strom.
