<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIVE   `ANTZ' A   CHANCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
 
By ROB LOWMAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ DreamWorks launched ``Antz'' as a pre-emptive
strike against Disney's ``A Bug's Life.'' Ultimately, Disney won
out in the battle of animated insects, taking in $154 million and
counting, while ``Antz'' took in about $90 million. Not bad,
though, and now if you opted only to see the other insect movie,
``Antz'' is out on video next Tuesday along with two other notable
films _ ``Next Stop Wonderland'' and ``Rounders.''
</P>
<P>
   Ants, as you know, work as part of the collective, and their
social roles are determined at birth _ soldier ants and worker
ants. The theme of ``Antz'' is the search for individuality,
personified in Z (hence the z in the title). Voiced by the king of
neurotics, Woody Allen, Z complains that he feels overlooked as a
middle child in a ``family of 5 million.'' Meanwhile his best
friend, Weaver (Sylvester Stallone) gets the glory and the girl,
Azteca (Jennifer Lopez).
</P>
<P>
   Part of the fun of ``Antz'' is that it echoes Allen's early
films like ``Sleeper,'' ``Bananas'' and ``Love and Death.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Allen's characters in those three films, Z is a
dissatisfied but affable bumbler who has no real political or
social conscience. His only real motivation in life is to find a
woman. Of course, he does, and of course, she is out of his league
_ in this case Princess Bala (Sharon Stone). Infatuated, he
convinces Weaver to switch places with him for a day, which, as in
the other films, puts him in destiny's path. This time, a sinister
plot by the leader of the ants' military forces, Gen. Mandible
(Gene Hackman). He soon becomes the lightning rod for a workers'
revolt (``All we are saying is give Z a chance'').
</P>
<P>
   There is no question that Disney has upped the ante in
animation, and ``Antz'' is quite remarkable visually. There's a
wonderful feeling of depth to the animation, and somehow the ants
all look alike and different at the same time. There are subtle
traits of the characters that make them resemble the actors who are
voicing them. The rest of the cast is impressive, including
Christopher Walken, Dan Aykroyd, Jane Curtin, Anne Bancroft and
Danny Glover.
</P>
<P>
   The humor in ``Antz'' is sophisticated enough for adults, and
most of it isn't over the heads of kids. And, hey, maybe they'll
even let you watch it with them.
</P>
<P>
   `Next Stop Wonderland': For those of us who believe in destiny,
there are films like ``Sleepless in Seattle,'' which some like to
call ``chick flicks.'' I know guys who wouldn't be caught dead
renting anything that didn't have ``Lethal'' in the title.
``Shakespeare in Love'': Which two words don't work here? Hey guys,
our penchant for lists and labels is just too limiting. And it's
nearing Valentine's Day. So rent ``Next Stop Wonderland,'' and
watch it with your significant other.
</P>
<P>
   This charming indie film tells the story of a nurse, Erin (Hope
Davis), and an ex-plumber-turned-biology-student, Alan (Alan
Gelfant), whose paths will inevitably meet. Along the way, however,
they continually meet Mr. and Ms. Wrong while wondering if there is
such a thing as Mr. or Ms. Right.
</P>
<P>
   Though not without flaws, ``Wonderland's'' strong performances
and light humor make it enjoyable. And you know, guys, if you make
the suggestion to watch it, your significant other may even think
you're, well, charming. Bonus: It has a terrific bossa nova
soundtrack.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
`Rounders': Reasons to watch ``Rounders'': Edward Norton. Actually
it's a pretty entertaining film, and John Dahl (``The Last
Seduction'') keeps the action moving in this story of a
poker-player-turned-law school-student (Matt Damon) who returns to
the high-stakes tables in order to help out his buddy, Worm
(Norton), who is in debt to a seedy Russian gambler, Teddy KGB
(John Malkovich).
</P>
<P>
   The film's ending is too pat, but the poker games are fun to
watch. Besides, Norton gives a performance that shows why he may be
the best among Hollywood's younger actors. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
