<SLUG> BC-GUITAR-ACE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN GUITARISTS FRET, REPAIR WHIZ GOES TO WORK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
 
By FRED SHUSTER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
  
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Tina Wood's journey from Britain to Los Angeles
ended the way so many others have when her band broke up and she
was left stranded under the big orange sun.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike others who've found themselves in a similar position,
Wood's story has a happy ending. Thanks to training and experience
in guitar-making, repair and electronics, the Valley resident
landed on her feet and is today among the most sought-after guitar
technicians in the city.
</P>
<P>
   Wood spends her days at one of several Valley music shops where
she repairs, builds and retools guitars and basses _ the Amp Shop,
Splash, the L.A. Bass Exchange and Cassels _ and clients range from
beginners to busy session pros.
</P>
<P>
   She's as much a star as some of her customers. In an era where
music stores are impersonal supermarkets of electronic gear, Wood
takes an artisan's approach to her craft.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tina's real meticulous, careful, and she cares about what she
does,'' said guitarist Al McKay of Earth, Wind &AMP; Fire, one of
Wood's repeat clients. ``She may be hired to do one particular job,
but if she spots something else that needs to be done _ like a
button is missing or something _ she'll replace it for free. She's
definitely one of the best.''
</P>
<P>
   It was 10 years ago that Wood's band scored a record deal that
took them to Los Angeles. A year later, the group was in tatters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad I had something to fall back on,'' Wood said. ``I've
always been intrigued by guitars. I really enjoy working on them
and playing them. It's just creativity.''
</P>
<P>
   Wood currently plays in two groups: Phantom Blue (on the Web at
www.phantomblue.com) and the Bud Lite backing band. The former
outfit appears March 21 at the Gig in West Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The big difference between repairing guitars in London and Los
Angeles has to do with customer attitudes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you get more respect for your art here,'' Wood, 33,
said. ``If you do really good work and take care of your customers
and give good service, they don't mind spending the money. It's
much harder to make a living over there. And people are more
open-minded here.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Stamps, owner of the Amp Shop in Sherman Oaks, said
Wood's agreement to work part-time at his store played ``a major
part'' in his decision to open in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I appreciate the quality of her work and her integrity,''
Stamps said. ``She really puts customer support and service first.
She's an all-around good person and a great guitar player on top of
that. I love hanging out with her.''
</P>
<P>
   In a town where attitudes behind the counter are often
intimidating, and a trip to the local music store can be an
unsettling experience, Wood's demeanor is disarmingly friendly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Setting up a guitar is very personal,'' she said. ``Some of
the studio musicians bring their guitars in every time they have a
session. I do the setups mostly by feel. Although the type of wood
and strings you use are important, the tone of a guitar is still 80
percent created by how you approach the instrument as a player.''
</P>
<P>
   The British-born Wood learned to build guitars at trade school
in London, afterward landing a gig at a busy music shop in the West
End.
</P>
<P>
   Today, she repairs vintage electrics by Gibson and Fender,
off-the-rack Japanese models and a wide array of acoustic fretted
instruments.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of new companies producing quality stuff now,''
Wood explained. ``Obviously, when they're pumping out a lot of
instruments, there's a lot less quality control. It's a saturated
market really.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
