<SLUG> BC-JEFF-BECK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WRITER COBBLES TOGETHER BOOK ABOUT AMAZING GUITARIST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
 
By FRED SHUSTER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
  
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ There are two things in these nine years I've
learned never to pass up _ an invitation to dinner at the Palm
steakhouse and a chance to see Jeff Beck in concert.
</P>
<P>
   The Palm in West Hollywood needs no introduction. As for Beck _
who appears April 17 at the Universal Amphitheatre _ a strange
thing has happened: Someone ``borrowed'' his name.
</P>
<P>
   When many hear of Beck these days, they immediately think of
that geeky Silver Lake goofball, not the great and endlessly
imaginative guitarist. Which is a shame because while the twerp
Beck's records are destined for the cutout bin of the future, even
the guitarist Beck's earliest albums have never ended up there.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody outside of Jimi Hendrix has done more with an electric
guitar or done it with so much humor, style and taste. Take, for
example, Beck's solo on the Charles Mingus classic ``Goodbye
Pork-Pie Hat'' from his 1976 album ``Wired.'' If you don't smile or
even laugh out loud upon first hearing Beck's improvisation on the
theme, maybe you don't have a sense of humor to begin with.
</P>
<P>
   There's something worthwhile on all of Beck's albums, from the
visionary ``Truth,'' ``Beck-Ola'' and ``Rough &AMP; Ready'' through the
masterful ``Blow by Blow,'' ``Wired,'' ``There &AMP; Back'' and ``Jeff
Beck's Guitar Shop.''
</P>
<P>
   Beck's latest effort, ``Who Else!'' (Epic), due March 16, is one
of the better ones. Just wait till you hear the sparse gem ``Brush
With the Blues'' from the disc.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, while there have been dozens of books on rock's other
great guitarists _ Eric Clapton, Hendrix, Peter Green, among them _
there's never been a biography of Jeff Beck.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, that is. South Africa-based writer Annette Carson's
self-published ``Jeff Beck: Crazy Fingers'' goes a long way toward
putting that right.
</P>
<P>
   As the first biography of Beck (available for $17 by mail order
from carsonglobal.co.za, the book follows Beck's career from art
school through the Yardbirds and beyond, while putting to rest many
of the myths that have followed the moody British musician.
</P>
<P>
   Carson is a contemporary of Beck's and worked in the
entertainment industry in Britain from the '60s through the '80s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always thought Jeff was the most amazing guitarist, and I
was impressed with the way he just got better and more inventive
over the years,'' says Carson, a free-lance copywriter. ``But a few
years ago, when I was talking to some friends in their 20s, I
realized they had no idea who I was talking about. So I said, `Hang
on, I'll find you a book about him.' That was when I discovered
there was no book in existence, which I thought was an absolute
disgrace.''
</P>
<P>
   Five years in the making, Carson's marvelous ``Crazy Fingers''
contains no new interviews with Beck, whose management refused to
collaborate with the effort.
</P>
<P>
   But by means of diligent research, personal knowledge and, as
she puts it, ``the dedicated fan movement'' around the world, the
author was able to put together a fascinating and very entertaining
biography of one of rock's most magical and sadly underrated
performers. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
(To reach music writer Fred Shuster with tips or comments, e-mail
him at fshusterearthlink.net) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
