<SLUG> BC-DREADLOCKS-CONVENTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH DREADLOCKS, NO SUCH THING AS A BAD HAIR DAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By VENISE WAGNER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Staajabu never had much love for the comb. It
conjured unpleasant memories of her mother running her down daily
to tear the teeth through her thick hair. In the end, there were
always tears and a sore scalp.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Staajabu has spent most of her 55 years trying to
avoid using a comb. At age 11, she succeeded for about a year,
merely brushing a top layer of hair over a matted mess. She washed
it regularly, so no one was the wiser until her mother touched her
head one day. She was immediately sent to the hairdresser _ who
pressed or permed her defiant locks into straightness.
</P>
<P>
   She's gone from rollers to curling irons, from the Afro to
cornrows and a shaved head.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in her late 30s, Staajabu discovered dreadlocks _ hair
free to twist and turn upon itself in thick, matted locks.
</P>
<P>
   She saw a man in a Philadelphia museum wearing them. Too shy to
ask how he grew his locks, she studied every bend and kink.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was fascinated by the fact that you can have hair and not
pain,'' said Staajabu, of Sacramento, who goes by only one name.
</P>
<P>
   She went home that evening and twisted her own locks.
</P>
<P>
   But her road to locking up wasn't easy. She faced ridicule from
some relatives and colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   In a show of support for other dreadlock fans, she is presenting
the second Dreadlock Conference on Saturday in Sacramento. It will
explore topics such as the history of dreadlocks, tips on caring
for locked hair, employment rights and laws protecting people with
dreadlocks.
</P>
<P>
   The proceeds will benefit the Wo'se Community Church in
Sacramento and International Campaign to Save Mumia Abu-Jamal, a
dreadlocked Pennsylvania death-row inmate convicted of killing a
police officer in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hardly a day passes that someone doesn't ask me about my
hair,'' Staajabu said. ``Do you wash it? Who does it for you? How
long does it take to get like that? Then there are people who don't
ask, they stare. Like I wanted to ask that guy at the museum. It's
unlikely they'll look it up in the library.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly everyone with dreadlocks has stories to share. And there
are increasingly more mainstream figures that dreadlock hopefuls
can look to, including the late Bob Marley, Toni Morrison, Eddie
Murphy, actor T.C. Carson, the late actress Rosalind Cash and, of
course, Whoopi Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   Staajabu cut her locks twice: in 1981 at the request of her
husband, who soon became an ex, and then in 1983 because she wanted
to enter the military. The third time she locked her hair was in
honor of the back-to-nature group MOVE, which was firebombed by the
Philadelphia police in 1985. Many MOVE members, she said, wore
dreadlocks.
</P>
<P>
   She was in the Reserves but managed, until she got an honorable
discharge, to work around regulations prohibiting that hair extend
no more than 3 inches from the head.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's conference drew about 200. This year, Staajabu said,
500 are expected.
</P>
<P>
   Najuma Oseye Munirah hopes the conference will reach out to
those afraid of the consequences of wearing dreadlocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing to be afraid of,'' said Munirah, who is
studying communications at California State University at Monterey
Bay. ``You can be proud of your nappy hair. You can go ahead to
feel the right to wear your hair this way. You're the one who has
to give yourself permission first.''
</P>
<P>
   But the fears are not so easily assuaged. Some blacks still use
the term ``good hair'' to refer to wavy or silky tresses. Nappy,
conversely, has come to signify ugly and undesirable.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are things we have to work through as a people in
general,'' said Tyra Jackson, 29, who sells products for
dreadlocked hair from her home in Oakland. ``One of them is looking
at ourselves with natural hair and seeing ourselves beautiful at
that level.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm worried about those who want to go (locked) but are afraid
of the adversity that they will have to deal with. I know so many
brothers wanting to lock, but have the conflict of what their boss
is going to say. People are thinking about boyfriends and
girlfriends or their mothers.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (The Dreadlock Conference will be held at the Samuel C.
Pannel/Meadowview Community Center, 2450 Meadowview Road,
Sacramento, Calif., 2-8 p.m. Saturday. Admission is $12 for adults,
$8 for students and $2 for children. For information, call
916-443-3322.)
</P>
</TEXT>
