<HEADER>
A1844 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-SWEEPS-SFCHRON &LR;      02-04 1064
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SWEEPS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETWORKS KICK UP A STORM FOR SWEEPS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   David Hill, the Aussie who runs the Fox network and a couple of
sports appendages for Rupert Murdoch, said it ever so elegantly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sweeps suck,'' he blurted out during a recent
question-and-answer session with television critics.
</P>
<P>
   That sucking sound begins Thursday, with the start of the
February sweeps. Anyway, hearing no murmurs of dissent, Hill
pressed forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a network standpoint, sweeps are the worst thing
possible,'' he said. ``They are ridiculous. They're an anachronism.
They were invented in 1901. Ever since they invented it, what point
do sweeps serve?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just ludicrous. What happens is that we all throw our
best stuff on, it's a train wreck, and we spend our time worrying
about November, and then February, and then May, then July, then
November.''
</P>
<P>
   Translation: The networks needlessly burn their best programs in
sweeps months, counting viewers whose regular habits are already
well documented by Nielsen ``people meters'' in 44 constantly
metered markets and fooling no one as they try to jack up the
ratings artificially to fatten ad rates. Bummer.
</P>
<P>
   So, let the train wrecks begin.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Hill's grousing, the February sweeps appear on paper to
be an improvement over the networks' feeble efforts in November.
Then again, there's ``Robbie Knievel's Building-to-Building Death
Jump Live'' Thursday night on Hill's very own Fox. If he falls
short, is it a good thing?
</P>
<P>
   Some of what to watch for in February on the major networks:
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; ABC. &LR;  ABC is taking February by storm, and don't you forget
it. The network's big miniseries, ``Stephen King's Storm of the
Century,'' is casting a shadow over much of the ABC schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``Storm of the Century,'' conceived by King for TV, is about a
storm-socked Maine town and a malevolent stranger. It's a rare
six-hour miniseries, scheduled for Feb. 14, 15 and 18. Tim Daly,
Colm Feore and Debrah Farentino star.
</P>
<P>
   The week will be ``storm week'' on ABC, in which a killer
tornado will rip Sam Donaldson's hairpiece from his head and drop
it on Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   All right, no, but there will be bad-weather-themed stories on
several daytime soaps as well as on ``Home Improvement,'' ``The
Hughleys,'' ``Dharma &AMP; Greg,'' ``Two Guys, a Girl and a Pizza
Place,'' ``The Drew Carey Show'' and ``Spin City.''
</P>
<P>
   Did I say ``Spin City''? On next Tuesday's show, Michael
Flaherty (Michael J. Fox) finally gets down and dirty with Nikki
Faber (Connie Britton).
</P>
<P>
   But I say the not-to-miss ABC event of the month is ``And the
Beat Goes On: The Sonny &AMP; Cher Story,'' a movie on Feb. 22. You
will howl with laughter. You will fall down and clutch your rib
cage.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; CBS. &LR;  Its main ratings grabber should be the annual Grammy
Awards show, on Feb. 24. But the major film production is a tip-off
about the age of the CBS audience. The two-part miniseries is ``Too
Rich: The Secret Life of Doris Duke,'' on Feb. 21 and 23.
</P>
<P>
   The tobacco heiress died in 1993 at age 80, leaving behind a
$1.2 billion fortune and questions about what caused her death.
Lauren Bacall and Lindsay Frost will share the role of Duke;
Richard Chamberlain is the heavy.
</P>
<P>
   CBS has a tearjerker slotted for Feb. 14, a based-on-fact
mother-and-daughter saga called ``Deep in My Heart.'' Anne
Bancroft, Gloria Reuben and Lynn Whitfield star in the story of a
woman of mixed race (Reuben), raised black, who tracks down her
white birth mother (Bancroft) 34 years after she was given up for
adoption.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deep in My Heart'' is calibrated to ensure that couples who
are gaga going into Valentine's Day will end the day quarreling
about whether to watch ``Storm of the Century'' or ``Deep in My
Heart.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Fox. &LR;  On March 2, a day before the close of the February
sweeps, Egyptian archaeologist Zahi Hawass will open a tomb, sealed
for more than 4,000 years, at the pyramid of Queen Khamerernebty
II. It'd be great if it turned out to contain Geraldo Rivera and
one empty bottle.
</P>
<P>
   For the next two Sundays on ``The X-Files,'' series creator
Chris Carter will be peeling away several veils covering the show's
alien conspiracy mystery. Carter won't be revealing everything, but
he has promised to take the wraps off the Cigarette-Smoking Man.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are more Fox ``specials.'' We're talking ``The
World's Most Shocking Moments No. 2: Caught on Tape,'' ``World's
Wildest Police Videos,'' ``World's Most Shocking Medical Videos''
and, on Feb. 25, ``Surviving the Moment of Impact No. 3.''
</P>
<P>
   The impact special will feature colliding trains, trucks and
cars. All, says Fox, ``to show viewers how they can protect
themselves from most traffic accidents.'' Gosh, thanks, Fox!
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; NBC. &LR;  The February centerpiece is ``The '60s,'' a four-hour
miniseries Sunday and Monday from executive producer Lynda Obst
(``Contact,'' ``Sleepless in Seattle'').
</P>
<P>
   Packed with period music, the miniseries is about how the
turbulent decade affected the members of one Chicago family. It's a
small-name cast, though Bill Smitrovich (``Life Goes On''), David
Alan Grier and Charles Dutton have supporting roles.
</P>
<P>
   ``To Serve and Protect,'' on Feb. 14 and 15, is a two-parter
focusing on three generations of New York cops. Craig T. Nelson and
Richard Crenna top the cast.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest cast of the sweeps will turn up in a new three-hour
production of ``Alice in Wonderland,'' scheduled for Feb. 28 on
NBC. This ``Alice'' will be splashy but nonmusical. Tina Majorino
is Alice; she'll be surrounded by Martin Short, Gene Wilder, Ben
Kingsley, Peter Ustinov, Whoopi Goldberg, Miranda Richardson and
others.
</P>
<P>
   For a change, the most competitive night of the sweeps month
might not be a Sunday. Watch instead for a dust-up on Thursday,
Feb. 18.
</P>
<P>
   That's the night when ``Storm of the Century'' concludes on ABC.
But on NBC, in the conclusion of a two-episode ``ER'' arc called,
amazingly enough, ``The Storm,'' George Clooney takes his leave
from TV's top-rated series.
</P>
<P>
   ``ER'' is taking no prisoners. ``The Storm,'' parts one and two,
is partly about Ross' (Clooney) relationship with a dying boy, and
how it triggers a personal and career crisis for him.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently he decides to quit medicine and become a movie star.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
