<SLUG> BC-BOOK-NOTES05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    More biggies on tap at Kennesaw conference
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Kennesaw State University is not generally thought of
as a literary center, but the school has attracted some of the top
writers in the country to its annual literary conferences.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had Ellen Gilchrist, Joyce Carol Oates, Larry Brown,
Ernest Gaines, Ishmael Reed and Gail Godwin,'' says conference
director Mary Zoghby. ``We started the conference 10 years ago to
bring together members of the community with our students and
faculty to celebrate literature and generate enthusiasm for good
books.''
</P>
<P>
   Next week's conference continues the strong tradition: Poet
laureate Robert Pinsky and Pulitzer Prize-winning novelist Alison
Lurie will be featured speakers on a program that includes
readings, seminars and workshops in drama, poetry, fiction and
creative nonfiction. The conference will be held Wednesday-Feb.12
on the Kennesaw campus. All events are free to the public.
</P>
<P>
   Lurie, who won a Pulitzer for ``Foreign Affairs'' in 1985, will
read from her work at 7:30 p.m. Wednesday in Stillwell Theater.
Pinsky, author of ``The Figured Wheel: New and Collected Poems,''
will read at 7:30 p.m. Feb. 11 at Stillwell Theater.
</P>
<P>
   For a complete conference schedule, call 770-423-6296.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Americans abroad: Most of us, at one time or another _ usually
in the middle of a traffic jam _ have dreamed of running away from
home. Rosanne Knorr and her husband, John, actually did it. Two
years ago, the Roswell (Ga.) couple packed their belongings, rented
their house, said goodbye to their children and grandchildren and
moved to France.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took us five years to decide to do it,'' says Knorr, 52.
``After our elderly parents died, we knew if we didn't do it then,
we would never do it. We both agreed we'd rather have an adventure
than more money.''
</P>
<P>
   Settling in a little village in France's Loire Valley, the
Knorrs found they were not alone. Dozens of other Americans were
already there. ``The number of Americans living abroad has
quadrupled in the past 30 years to 3.3 million, according to the
State Department,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the growing interest in living abroad, Knorr drew on
her research to write ``The Grown-Up's Guide to Running Away From
Home'' (Ten Speed Press, $11.95 paperback). The handy book offers
advice on the cost of living in various countries (Mexico is the
cheapest), housing, banking, health care and fitting in with
different cultures.
</P>
<P>
   Adapting to French culture has not been a problem for the
Knorrs. ``Our stress level has dropped dramatically,'' says Knorr,
a free-lance writer who has written several children's books for
Longstreet Press. ``The French have an entirely different attitude
than Americans about life. They prefer spending time enjoying their
friends and families, they take six-week vacations, and they spend
hours over lunch and dinner.''
</P>
<P>
   Knorr will sign her book and, along with her husband, answer
questions at 7 p.m. Wednesday at Barnes &AMP; Noble in Atlanta, 2900
Peachtree Road N.W., 404-261-7747
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Royal advice: Jill Conner Browne is a fallen Southern belle
and proud of it. After all, if she were not a fallen Southern
belle, then she wouldn't have been inspired to form the Sweet
Potato Queens. And if she hadn't formed the Sweet Potato Queens,
she wouldn't have talked four Jackson, Miss., women into shedding
their business attire for green-sequined bathing suits and posing
atop a float in the 1982 St. Patrick's Day parade.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, so many women have clamored to become Sweet Potato
Queens that Browne decided an instruction book was needed. ``You
either have to have the attitude or acquire it,'' says Browne, 46,
a humor columnist for the Jackson Clarion-Ledger. And reading ``The
Sweet Potato Queens' Book of Love'' (Three Rivers Press, $12
paperback), presumably, is the way to acquire it.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the advice _ particularly about the magic words to get
any man to do your bidding _ is not suitable for a family
newspaper, but the other suggestions are better than one of Fat
Mama's Knock You Naked Margaritas that Browne loves so well.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most popular chapters, Browne says, is ``Five Men You
Must Have in Your Life at All Times: a man who can fix things, a
man you can dance with, a man who can pay for things, a man you can
talk to and a man to have great sex with.''
</P>
<P>
   There may be one man who combines all of those talents, but
Browne hasn't found him. ``I haven't stopped looking, though.''
</P>
<P>
   Browne will sign her book at 7:30 p.m. Monday at Barnes &AMP; Noble
in Smyrna (Ga.), 2952 Cobb Parkway, 770-953-0966.
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
