<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 15:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1875 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-ORCHIDQA07-COX     02-04 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-ORCHIDQA07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Truth tantalizes author more than fiction
 &HT;    EDs.: Embargoed for Sunday Feb. 7.
 &HT;    By Teresa K. Weaver
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   One day Susan Orlean is on a plane home to New York, leafing
through a Miami Herald left behind by another passenger. Within
days, she is waist-deep in a South Florida swamp with a charismatic
kook, trying to unravel a real-life mystery of passion and
obsession centered on an exotic flower.
</P>
<P>
   Her adventure was triggered by a few words: ``Nurseryman and
three Seminoles arrested poaching rare plant.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's that kind of headline that stops you and makes you think,
`Huh?' '' Orlean says. It was a fairly short article reporting the
arrest of John Laroche, a ``weirdly appealing'' eccentric who had
been caught trying to sneak several pillowcases full of ghost
orchids _ a federally protected flower that grows nowhere else in
the world _ out of the swamp.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything in the story mystified me,'' Orlean says. ``I had
no idea there were orchids growing wild in Florida. I really was
that much of an orchid virgin. I had no clue. And I couldn't
understand why anyone would steal them. . . . The whole thing just
fascinated me. When I got back to New York, I went to my editor and
said, `I really don't know what this story is, but I'm curious.' ''
</P>
<P>
   After two years of research and a year and a half of writing,
the result of her curiosity is a book called ``The Orchid Thief.''
Orlean, a 43-year-old staff writer for The New Yorker, took a few
minutes on a recent tour stop in Miami to talk about some people's
passion for orchids, and about her own personal passion: writing
what's true.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You've written about surfers, mountain climbers,
bullfighters, but you don't always take a first-person approach.
Why in this book?
</P>
<P>
   A: When I wrote a story recently about surf girls in Maui, the
editors really wanted me to go surfing. I had never surfed before,
and if I had gone, I'm sure it would have somehow worked its way
into the story. But it seemed to me totally beside the point. And
moreover, I was too embarrassed to stand up and try to surf around
these kids who had been surfing since they were 2. So I decided in
the interest of dignity _ and in the interest of the story _ that I
really didn't want to draw myself into it that much.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Orchid Thief,'' though, the connecting thread is really
my journey into this world and my effort to try to make sense of
it. I was a character, and I felt like the story had to radiate
from that perspective. It was such a strange story, and there were
so many pieces of it, but what held them together was that I set
out to try to figure out what this crime was.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What surprised you most in your research?
</P>
<P>
   A: I set out not having any interest in orchids at all. The fact
that they were an object of desire interested me, but I frankly
thought they were weird and ugly. I couldn't imagine that I would
start to appreciate what they look like. . . . I am not an orchid
lover, even now. I resist mightily, but it is hard to be around
something that extraordinary, something that people feel that
passionately about, without beginning to appreciate what it is.
</P>
<P>
   For me, the great surprise is that I used to look at swamps as
places I would never want to go. And although I found walking in
the swamp to be pretty harrowing, I came out fairly amazed _ just
at the kinds of living things in them. . . . When you look at a
swamp, it looks like a big mush. When you're in it that intimately,
when you can take your mind off of the snakes and alligators for a
second, you can appreciate what a complicated, primordial
environment it is.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The ending of the John Laroche story itself was almost
anti-climactic. Did that disappoint you at all?
</P>
<P>
   A: When Laroche first told me he had gotten out of the orchid
business, I had a heart attack. I thought, Oh my God, how can I do
my book? And then I realized that the ending was almost more
fitting _ knowing Laroche and knowing what a fickle but passionate
person he is.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do real-life endings like that make you want to write
fiction?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's funny, but no. In a way, I find it more challenging to
think, OK, the story turned a slightly different way than I would
have expected. Given that, how do I sustain the story? How do I
make it work? Obviously writing fiction isn't easy, but it doesn't
seem like you would ever be faced with that particular challenge.
Here you've got a rock, a match and a mirror. What are you going to
do? There's sort of a battle of wits that I find fascinating. And
in this case, to think, OK, this is not the climax that people
might have expected, but frankly, it is what the story is. It's the
truth. So how do I make that still interesting for the reader?
</P>
<P>
   Q: It sounds like truth might be your particular passion.
</P>
<P>
   A: That's absolutely the case. What really engages me is writing
about real life, and persuading _ or even seducing _ people into
reading it, even when I'm not promising that it will be dramatic or
extraordinary the way fiction can be. What you can get out of truth
is something different, more subtle. I read fiction all the time
and I love it, but I have a secret desire to talk people into
reading things that they didn't think they were going to be
interested in.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's your next project?
</P>
<P>
   A: I have to wait for my next book idea. It's a little bit like
getting married. You end up living with (the subject) for a long
time, in boredom and in happiness, and to make that kind of
commitment, you have to be really sure you love the idea. I'm not
rushing into anything.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I read that Jonathan Demme has optioned ``The Orchid Thief.''
</P>
<P>
   A: Right. I'm really tickled about that. I admire him, I think
his movies are great, and . . . I think he appreciates the
eccentricity of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Q: So who would you cast in the movie?
</P>
<P>
   A: Well, I started thinking about Nicolas Cage as Laroche. Don't
you think? As kind of an appealing maniac?
</P>
<P>
   And of course, Michelle Pfeiffer for me. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Teresa K. Weaver writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
