<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 15:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1876 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-SKUBE07-COX     02-04 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-SKUBE07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Software program is a witless way to rate writing
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday Feb. 7.
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here, in case you're interested, is a description of an insane
asylum:
</P>
<P>
   ``The corridors resound with the shouts and mutterings of the
patients, talking not to one another, but to voices from their
past. They wander the labyrinth gesticulating and answering
inaudible questions. Then it feels as if there's nothing here at
all but memories, and even these may be of things that never
happened. There's no real present here, and no future. There's only
this past. Whisperings and laughter. They are mostly old now _ if
you can talk of them at all. Because nothing really lives in them
except the long-dead. The past has left merely these husks and
jabberings. With its grey cells and corridors, the whole place
resembles a single magnified and shattered brain, in which each
inmate is only a wandering memory trace.''
</P>
<P>
   The passage is from Colin Thubron's novel ``A Cruel Madness,''
written almost 15 years ago. There is no explaining the magic of
good prose, any more than the experience of hearing a piece of
music can be reduced to the notes alone. With language, the words
are one thing and their effect another. But they are not
inseparable. Sound and sense are symbiotic, each enlarging the
other.
</P>
<P>
   In the paragraph above, one could point to familiar words used
in interesting ways _ ``husks and jabberings,'' for example _ or to
the way it builds toward the haunting image at the end. What one
couldn't do, with any profit, is run it through a computer.
</P>
<P>
   But it will soon come to that. Beginning this month, a software
program called E-rater scores essays on the Graduate Management
Admission Test taken annually by 200,000 college students. In the
past, each essay was read by two people, and sometimes a third.
Now, E-rater replaces one of those judges. If it can't judge
creativity, it can nonetheless flag faulty sentence structure,
loose connections in logic and balky transitions. It does something
else, according to The New York Times. It spots words it likes _
starchy words such as ``therefore'' and ``further'' _ and, on the
rationale that these are logic tighteners, grades up when it sees
them.
</P>
<P>
   You imagine the guy at the garage slamming that loud nut gun
onto your wheel. Might not be much artistry to it, but it gets the
job done fast. That's how I think of the people at the National
Educational Testing Service, putting prose on a hoist so the Mr.
Goodwrenches of computational linguistics can give it the 48-point
inspection.
</P>
<P>
   There are ideas so plain stupid you can't take them seriously.
Reading a piece of writing is an act of reflection, one mind
responding to another. It is an investment of one's time, and as
personal as the writing itself. It is not an act of tabulating.
</P>
<P>
   If technology has changed that, no one should be shocked. The
druids of artificial intelligence have been working at it for
years, the ground tilled Dr. Rudolf Flesch. Long before the pocket
calculator, Flesch's ``How to Write Better'' promulgated the
paint-by-numbers lesson that the simple sentence was always best,
the unusual word always wrong and that writing flows not by rhythm
and cadence but the clop-clop-clop of one word following another,
like the hooves of pack horses on pavement.
</P>
<P>
   Using a computer version of this technique, a high school class
in Virginia shot a laser through a paragraph of Rachel Carson's
several years ago and the results _ well, they wouldn't have put
her in honors English. The paragraph in question is the opening one
from ``The Edge of the Sea,'' often cited as an example of masterly
prose.
</P>
<P>
   The computer, though, found faults and fissures undetected by
the human ear. Her ``strength of delivery,'' it said, was ``good
but could be improved.'' So she wasn't perfect. Her use of adverbs
and adjectives was ``within the normal range,'' and her jargon
index was 0.00. At least she got something right. But a number of
her words were on the computer's ``uncommon word list'':
continental, receded, warps, glaciers, even _ imagine this _
eternal. As the computer printout cautioned, a reader ``would need
a 10th grade level of education to understand.''
</P>
<P>
   Say what you want about high school sophomores, most eventually
grow up and don't have to be committed to institutions. Which, come
to think of it, is where we started. There was a time when
competency hearings were held for certain kinds of people. We've
gotten out of the practice, which is too bad. The Educational
Testing Service has given some truly nutty ones the run of the
place, and they're playing with things they'll never understand.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skube writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  E-mail: mskube(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
