<SLUG> BC-STYLE-TEDDY07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The lingerie that outlasts trends is a safe bet to wow your
sweetheart
 &HT;    EDs.: Embargoed for Sunday, Feb. 7.
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA_ Men suffering trepidation over the thought of
purchasing lingerie should take heart: It was a man who, 75 years
ago, invented the undergarment that looks the best on the most
women.
</P>
<P>
   According to fashion historian Lynn Schnurnberger's book, ``Let
There Be Clothes,'' it was Theodore Baer who first devised the
style of undies that women caught up in the flapper craze could
wear comfortably under their party dresses. ``Teddies''
revolutionized the lingerie industry, Schnurnberger writes, because
they were loose enough to dance in yet form-fitting enough to
provide adequate coverage and support.
</P>
<P>
   A 1924 article in Cosmopolitan magazine described the typical
Baer customer as a woman who would ``personally get enough
enjoyment out of standing before her mirror garbed in a sheer silk
teddy to (endure) any sacrifice.''
</P>
<P>
   Talk about enduring _ 75 years later there are styles of teddies
suited to every woman, no matter her age, shape or lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   The original teddy design _ a slinky silk one-piece garment_ has
since been modified to include two-piece versions in a variety of
fabrics. They're a fail-safe for men to purchase as Valentine's Day
gifts (along with the requisite flowers and candy, of course)
because they're not too raunchy or rash.
</P>
<P>
   Margarita Mayo, a sales associate at LaRaine's Boutique in
Atlanta, said the safest route a man can take toward making a
lingerie purchase is getting familiar with his beloved's tastes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you see that your wife or girlfriend has several teddies,
buy her another one,'' Mayo advised. ``But don't buy her any style
of lingerie she doesn't wear already. If she doesn't have a teddy,
it probably means she doesn't like them.''
</P>
<P>
   Other teddy tips: It's better to err on the large side than the
small; remember, it's a gift for her, not you. And when it comes to
buying skimpy things, don't skimp; spend the most you can afford.
Also, if you're not intimate enough to open a drawer and see what
size she wears, you're not intimate enough to buy her lingerie in
the first place
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
