<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-JOE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MY NAME IS JOE' IS GRITTY, ENGROSSING DRAMA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ken Loach is a British filmmaker who, for the past 30 years, has
carved out a special niche for himself in world cinema by making a
series of very distinctive, very bleak, ``kitchen-sink dramas''
dealing with the lives of average working-class Britons.
</P>
<P>
   His movies tend to be so naturalistic that they seem like
documentaries (though they're all tightly scripted, employing
professional actors), and their quality also tends to be hit and
miss _ he regularly alternates a Cannes award winner with a film so
dreary and pointless that it's unwatchable.
</P>
<P>
   With ``My Name is Joe,'' however, he's hit the bullseye. The
film may be another Loachian downer, but it's also an unusually
engrossing drama, love story and character study, with several of
the most magnetic performances he's ever squeezed out of a cast.
</P>
<P>
   Set in Glasgow, the Joe of the title (Peter Mullan) is a
38-year-old recovering alcoholic, on the dole but occasionally
picking up money with odd jobs and absolutely obsessed with his
avocation: coaching a team in the city's amateur football (soccer)
league.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the film traces the romance that arises between Joe and
Sarah (Louise Goodall), an idealistic community health worker he
meets cute one day on the way to a football game, who quickly
becomes his ``soul'' and a second reason for living.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Joe and Sarah are both drawn into the lives of
Liam (David McKay), a young man on Joe's football team who has
kicked his drug habit after a stint in jail, and Liam's wife,
Sabine (Anne-Marie Kennedy), who is back on drugs and working the
streets.
</P>
<P>
   The script chronicles Joe's love story, his maturing process and
the series of moral decisions he must make when he is torn between
keeping the love and respect of Sarah, and his need to save the
life of Liam when he gets in trouble with a gang of drug dealers.
</P>
<P>
   This may sound like the same old ``Mean Streets'' clone, but
somehow the familiar story comes together to be an extraordinarily
powerful _ and utterly believable _ drama, and an exquisitely
poignant ode to the power of romantic love and unselfish
friendship.
</P>
<P>
   Mullan _ who appeared in Loach's ``Riff-Raff'' as well as in
small parts in Mel Gibson's ``Braveheart'' and Danny Boyle's
``Trainspotting'' _ turns in a near-flawless performance. (He won
the best actor honors at the last Cannes Film Festival.)
</P>
<P>
   Louise Goodall _ who appeared in a smaller part in Loach's
``Carla's Song'' _ is just as effective, creating a character of
genuine nobility and resourcefulness: not just a morally ``good''
woman, but as strong a woman character as the movies have produced
in the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe'' is as tight and accessible a piece of story-telling as
Loach has ever given us, and it also represents a big change of
heart. While most of his films are what one critic has called
``studies in banal and hopeless poverty,'' this is a movie about
the possibility of redemption.
</P>
<P>
   Footnote: The Scottish brogues are so thick and the vernacular
so regional that the distributer has decided to subtitle the film.
At first, it's a bit disconcerting to watch a movie in English
subtitled in English, but it soon becomes obvious that ``My Name is
Joe'' would be absolutely incomprehensible without them.
</P>
<P>
   My Name is Joe. Directed by Ken Loach. Screenplay by Paul
Laverty. Cast: Peter Mullan, Louise Goodall, David McKay,
Anne-Marie Kennedy, Gary Lewis, Lorraine McIntosh. Artisan
Entertainment. 106 minutes. In English with English subtitles.
Rated R for violence and drug theme.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
