<HEADER>
A1909 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-60s-SPI &LR;      02-04 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-60s-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPERFICIAL `THE '60S' OVERDOSES IN A CLICHED LOOK AT TURBULENT
TIMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Promotional material for ``The '60s'' boasts that ``the best
movies on television are on NBC.''
</P>
<P>
   Left unsaid in NBC's strutting for February sweeps is that some
pretty awful movies also make their way through the vetting process
at Peacock Central.
</P>
<P>
   ``The '60s'' is one of them. An ambitious but badly constructed
``miniseries'' that can't seem to decide what it is, ``The '60s''
roams over four hours and two nights the way my '60 Falcon did:
aimlessy, and usually on empty.
</P>
<P>
   Especially at the start of Sunday's first installment, as
viewers get to know the white Herlihys of Chicago and the black
Taylors of Greenwood, Miss., the film is stiffer than Grandma's
meringue, flakier than her crust.
</P>
<P>
   In trying to cover too much ground (the student uprising, the
civil rights movement, the Vietnam War, the drug culture, etc.)
with a combination of fiction and actual news footage, ``The '60s''
trivializes a key period in American history by reducing it to a
superficial, cliche-filled treatment backed by a musical melange of
oldies-but-goodies.
</P>
<P>
   Fans of '60s music will enjoy the soundtrack (available on
Mercury Records), with Bob Dylan and Joan Osborne collaborating on
a new version of Dylan's ``Chimes of Freedom.'' But if you like
your characters richly drawn and their dialogue crisply written,
there is no compelling reason to revisit ``The '60s.'' Better to
wait till later Sunday night for a fresh new dose of the '90s on
ABC's ``The Practice,'' where you're not likely to hear Mrs.
Herlihy (Annie Corley) exclaim: ``Michael, I can't believe you left
your report card lying on the counter. For heaven sakes, I'm so
proud of you!''
</P>
<P>
   If there is a central character in this jumble, it is Michael
Herlihy (Josh Hamilton), a straight-A's kind of guy who is wholly
unbelievable as a 17-year-old but reasonably convincing as a
peacenik in college and beyond. Early on, during a civil rights
march in 1962, Michael meets Emmet Taylor (Leonard Roberts), the
teenage son of an activist minister.
</P>
<P>
   Their paths cross again in 1968 during the Democratic convention
in Chicago. Michael is still a peace activist; Emmet, whose life
has been redefined by senseless violence, is a member of the Black
Panther Party. But the idea of seeing how two families made it
through the '60s is dashed as the film spends less and less time
developing the Taylor side of the tale.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the 1960s posed difficult questions and troubling
choices. Director Mark Piznarski makes that clear as we meet
Michael's older brother, Brian, the football hero who chooses the
Marine Corps and Vietnam, and his younger sister, Katie (Julia
Stiles), who chooses to look for love and affirmation in all the
wrong places. Brought up in the civil rights movement, Emmet Taylor
chooses to tune out for a while, but then makes the choice his
father, played by Charles S. Dutton, would recommend.
</P>
<P>
   All these choices are made against the backdrop of momentous
'60s events _ the assassinations, the peace movement, the war _ as
if to suggest everyone was consciously pacing his life to the
steady drumbeat of history.
</P>
<P>
   While presidents and generals might live that way, most people,
even student activists who think they will change the world, spend
a lot of time living their lives against a backdrop far more
mundane. Perhaps if Piznarski had spent less time worrying about
file footage to establish the grave nature of the times, he'd have
crafted a compelling story with more gravity.
</P>
<P>
   Curiously, it was Piznarski who, a few seasons back, directed
the pilot episode of ``Relativity,'' one of the most stunning
series debuts of recent vintage. Obviously, you can't hit it out of
the park every time. ``The '60s'' is as forgettable as that
``Relativity'' episode was memorable.
</P>
<P>
   The '60s. Four-hour television movie about the 1960s, focusing
on two fictitious families torn apart by the decade's tumultuous
events. Starring Josh Hamilton, Julia Stiles, Jordana Brewster,
Charles S. Dutton, Leonard Roberts, Annie Corley, Bill Smitrovich,
Jerry O'Connell and Jeremy Sisto. Sunday and Monday on NBC. KING/5.
Parental guideline rating: TV-14.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: D+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-04-99 1528EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
