<HEADER>
A1920 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-RUSHMORE-SPI &LR;      02-04 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-RUSHMORE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`RUSHMORE' HAS TROUBLE MATCHING EARLY HYPE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The optimum way to experience the already-much-acclaimed
high-school comedy, ``Rushmore,'' may be to discover it and go in
with the low expectations its genre _ and the film's singularly
unappealing trailer _ set up.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, after months of critical praise and accolades _
including several year-end critics' awards (and a likely Oscar
nomination) for Bill Murray, as well as a berth on many 10-best
lists _ one's expectations are high. And the film can't completely
meet them.
</P>
<P>
   It's original, and cumulatively funny, but it doesn't have any
satiric clout, it's instantly forgettable and, while Murray is
effective in his supporting role, he was so much better as the star
of ``Groundhog Day'' and ``What About Bob?'' that an Oscar would
seem an anticlimax.
</P>
<P>
   Set in the fictional Rushmore Academy, the film is an off-beat
character study of one Max Fischer (Jason Schwartzman), a
15-year-old barber's son who somehow made it into this posh,
private school on a scholarship reserved for the financially needy.
</P>
<P>
   Tenth-grader Max is the sparkplug of the student body,
author-director of the drama club, editor of the school newspaper
and yearbook, captain of the debate team, president and prime mover
of virtually every extra-curricular activity from the astronomy
club to the ``double-team dodgeball society.''
</P>
<P>
   His problem is that he's failing all his subjects (in fact, he's
the worst student in Rushmore history) and the long-suffering
headmaster (Brian Cox) has no choice but to throw him out if he
doesn't pull up his grades _ a task for which Max clearly has no
heart.
</P>
<P>
   With this crisis in progress, the script also follows the course
of Max's unlikely friendship with one of the school's benefactors,
a self-destructive steel tycoon named Mr. Blume (Bill Murray), who
loathes himself and his whole family and begins to see Max as the
son he wished he'd had.
</P>
<P>
   And when both Max and Mr. Blume fall in love with the beautiful
and fragile Miss Cross (Olivia Williams), one of the school's
elementary teachers who's been recently widowed, their friendship
turns into an ugly war for the lady's favors.
</P>
<P>
   Writer-director Wes Anderson tells this story in the same
distinct style of his first film, the moderately successful 1996
slacker comedy, ``Bottle Rocket'' _ dead-pan, absurdist humor that
resolutely avoids pratfalls, scatology and the other low rituals of
the modern teen comedy.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson paces his film nicely: he's not afraid of low moments
(unlike most of his MTV-trained contemporaries), and he's not
afraid to start slow and build his comic premise gradually (so
there's relatively few laughs in the first act).
</P>
<P>
   A handful of his sequences are inspired, as when Max arranges
the funding for a major on-campus aquarium after Miss Cross
casually mentions a fondness for goldfish; or when Max mounts a
theatrical version of the Vietnam War, complete with
special-effects explosions and model helicopters.
</P>
<P>
   It's also a rare high school comedy that actually likes its
characters _ and gives them room to breathe. Thus, all of Max's
relationships _ with Mr. Blume, Miss Cross, a young Asian-American
girl with a a crush on him, even the school bully _ have a
surprising depth, resonance and credibility.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's not ``The Graduate,'' and it wants to be. Indeed,
the influence of that 1967 classic of obsessed love can be felt in
virtually every frame. (It even emotionally ties itself to the
mid-'60s with a soundtrack of rock music from that era: The Kinks,
The Rolling Stones, Donovan.)
</P>
<P>
   Part of this limitation is due to its star, and first-time
actor, Jason Schwartzman. He may be the son of Talia Shire and
nephew of Francis Coppola _ and he does dead-pan reasonably well _
but he's really not a skilled enough actor to do anything with this
part but pose for the camera.
</P>
<P>
   As clever and inventive as Anderson is in so many ways, his
movie also never adds up to be anything you can quite place your
finger on, nor does it leave us with any real satisfaction. It
basically works, but it lacks the shaping hand _ and novelistic
sense _ of a first-rate screenwriter.
</P>
<P>
   Rushmore. Directed by Wes Anderson. Written by Anderson and Owen
Wilson. Cast: Jason Schwartzman, Bill Murray, Olivia Williams,
Brian Cox, Seymour Cassel. Disney/Touchstone. Meridian 16, Neptune.
93 minutes. Rated R for language and sexual references.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
