<SLUG> BC-BUYING-VOTES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FREE MEAL FOR VOTING RULED ACCEPTABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARSHA GINSBURG  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A Democratic Party offer of free chicken and
potato salad to get voters to the polls in Oakland's 16th Assembly
District race ``comes very close to the perception of buying
votes,'' but does not break the law, according to the California
secretary of state.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've adhered to the letter of the law,'' said Beth Miller,
a spokeswoman for the secretary of state, who twice has
unsuccessfully supported legislation to prohibit voting
enticements.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic Party's decision to offer the $5 coupon for free
chicken and salad on Tuesday's special election was aimed at
precincts in the district with historically low voter turnout,
according to party consultant Bob Mulholland.
</P>
<P>
   To receive a coupon, voters in the district, which takes in
Alameda, Oakland and Piedmont, had to present their voting stubs
and a handbill announcing the giveaway at one of eight locations in
Oakland _ most of which were in low-income neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   A broadly worded state law prohibits such activity only if there
is a quid pro quo attached, extracting a vote for either a specific
candidate or issue, Miller said. Federal law, on the other hand,
prohibits any kind of enticements for voters, but that law applies
only to federal elections.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic Party, which endorsed former Oakland Mayor Elihu
Harris, said it offered the free-meal deal to boost voter turnout,
but denied it was intended to give Harris a big enough boost to
avoid a run-off election in the state Assembly race.
</P>
<P>
   Harris emerged as the top candidate against fellow Democrats
Frank Russo and Enrique Palacios. But with 48.7 percent of the
vote, Harris fell short of the required simple majority to avoid a
runoff.
</P>
<P>
   The election was held to fill the seat that became vacant when
incumbent Don Perata was elected to the state Senate in September.
Harris will face Green Party candidate Audie Elizabeth Bock, the
only non-Democrat in the race, in the runoff next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to get Democrats out, period,'' said Art Torres,
head of the California Democratic Party. ``There's incentive on my
part in every election to get the vote out.''
</P>
<P>
   Although there was no Republican candidate in the race, GOP
leaders decried the meal deal as offensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found it a little bit hypocritical,'' said Chris Bertelli,
spokesman for the California Republican Party. ``The Democratic
Party claims to be the party of inclusion (that) treats minorities
with respect. But instead of going to them and advocating a point
of view, and discuss an issue of import, they decided to go the low
road and offer whole chickens and potato salad to vote.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-04-99 1545EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990204.0228 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 15:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1928 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PAYBACK-FILM-REVIEW-N     02-04 0629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAYBACK-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PAYBACK': TAKE THAT, AND THAT, AND THEN THAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   No actor should have to mouth the ludicrous hard-boiled dialogue
_ lines like, ``What's the matter, cat got your crotch?'' _ that
lends ``Payback,'' the new Mel Gibson action-adventure film, the
flavor of a stale ``Saturday Night Live'' parody.
</P>
<P>
   This bizarre dud of a genre movie, adapted from the same Richard
Stark novel (``The Hunter'') that inspired the 1967 film ``Point
Blank,'' is set in a dank, urban no-man's land that might be called
Film Noir Manque. Here sadism rules, all women are prostitutes, the
cops corrupt and morality a matter of evil versus evil.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson is Porter, a career criminal who after recovering from
near-fatal gunshot wounds at the hands of his double-crossing
partner, Val (Gregg Henry), embarks on a killing spree to recover
the $70,000 his sidekick stole from him.
</P>
<P>
   Before he's finished, but not before a scene in which we watch
his agonized grimaces as two of his toes are smashed by a
sledgehammer, Porter goes up against the kingpins of a crime
organization called the Outfit, in a battle that culminates with
some cheesy cut-rate pyrotechnics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Payback,'' directed by Brian Helgeland, one of the writers
responsible for the elegant screenplay of ``L.A. Confidential,''
comes at you (not just your toes but your mind) with the subtlety
of a sledgehammer.
</P>
<P>
   In the movie's silliest scene, Porter interrupts the
sadomasochistic idyll of Val and his pet dominatrix, Pearl (Lucy
Liu), who gleefully takes over the beating up of her sleazy consort
once Porter tires of kicking him in the stomach.
</P>
<P>
   Its smirking sense of humor and generic self-consciousness
suggest that ``Payback'' would like to think of itself as a hip
descendant of ``Pulp Fiction.'' But the movie is utterly devoid of
narrative ingenuity and visual and dramatic flair. Its dark bluish
hue and downtown urban landscape (much of it was shot in Chicago)
suggest a no-budget ``Batman.'' Chris Boardman's dreary score
clouds the movie in an atmosphere that suggests second-hand
``Shaft.''
</P>
<P>
   Gibson, affecting his best macho growl, is at least able to keep
a straight face through the tortured purple prose his character,
who narrates the movie, is forced to deliver.
</P>
<P>
   But Henry's Val is a garish comic-book fiend, while Kris
Kristofferson, as the king of all underworld kingpins, delivers yet
another nonperformance, speaking in a dull, sepulchral monotone,
his eyes squinted shut.
</P>
<P>
   What it lacks in originality, ``Payback'' tries to make up for
in sadistic gore. Before they begin shooting and slicing one
another, the characters take cackling relish in describing the
tortures they would like to inflict. Amid the countless beatings
that are administered, one kick in the groin won't do. There have
to be at least three per scene.
</P>
<P>
   What one word might best describe ``Payback''? How about
``loathsome''?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Payback'' is rated R (Under 17 requires accompanying parent or
adult guardian). It has profanity, gore and scenes of torture. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PAYBACK
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Brian Helgeland; written by Helgeland and Terry
Hayes, based on the novel ``The Hunter,'' by Richard Stark;
director of photography, Ericson Core; edited by Kevin Stitt; music
by Chris Boardman; production designer, Richard Hoover; produced by
Bruce Davey; released by Paramount Pictures. Running time: 110
minutes. This film is rated R. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Mel Gibson (Porter), Gregg Henry (Val), Maria Bello
(Rosie), David Paymer (Stegman), Deborah Kara Unger (Lynn), William
Devane (Carter), Bill Duke (Detective Hicks), Kris Kristofferson
(Bronson) and Lucy Liu (Pearl). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
