<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 15:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1932 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX     02-04 0873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTHOR OF `SWIM WITH THE SHARKS' RELATES BUSINESS TIPS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TERESA McUSIC 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Harvey Mackay, the guy who taught us how to swim with sharks, is
back.
</P>
<P>
   His fifth book is ``Pushing The Envelope: All the Way to the
Top'' (Ballantine Books, 348 pages, $24.95).
</P>
<P>
   The title is most appropriate for the envelope
manufacturer-turned-sage, author and speaker. Mackay owns Mackay
Envelope Corp., a Minneapolis-based $85 million company.
</P>
<P>
   Many will remember his bestseller ``Swim with the Sharks Without
Being Eaten Alive.'' Now Mackay wants to inspire us to be the best
at what we do, and there's nary a shark out there to stop us.
</P>
<P>
   The book is part inspiration, part autobiography and part
business wisdom from someone who has been working and observing
work for 45 years. Mackay takes 90 chapters to relay his message.
Fortunately, each chapter is only a few pages.
</P>
<P>
   The format certainly makes for an easy read, and each chapter
has a focused and timely message.
</P>
<P>
   Mackay quotes sources from Will Rogers to Yoda, the Jedi knight
trainer in the ``Star Wars'' movies, who says: ``There is no try;
there is either do or not do.''
</P>
<P>
   Mackay offers numerous anecdotes about companies doing things
right or wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Southwest Airlines is back for the umpteenth time as an example
of the right way to do things. Can a book on successful business
techniques can be written without homage to Herb Kelleher?
</P>
<P>
   Southwest Airlines isn't the only Texas reference, however. Fort
Worth Star-Telegram writer Barry Shlachter, who runs a Texas
products catalog, is mentioned. In discussing creative ways to
thank people, such as clients, Mackay suggests finding out where
they were born and sending them something from their home state.
</P>
<P>
   He notes that Shlachter sends ``Texan in Exile Survival
Rations'' to those unfortunates who no longer live in the Lone Star
State.
</P>
<P>
   The real jewels in this tome come from Mackay's experience as an
entrepreneur, salesman and manager, even if it is in the rather
mundane envelope industry.
</P>
<P>
   Among his best advice:
</P>
<P>
   _ Buyers don't always work 9 to 5. Some come in at 6 a.m.,
others work until 7 p.m. and some come in Saturday mornings. ``For
three hours every morning, two hours every afternoon, and four
hours on Saturday, I had no competition. Naturally, this turned out
to be my most productive time. ... I called them the `Golden
Hours.'''
</P>
<P>
   _ Take the call. Mackay says he hires two people at his company:
the president and the receptionist. ``How your telephone is
answered says more about your company than all your slick
advertising and marketing plans can ever hope to accomplish.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Lighten up. ``There's no excuse for total, self-absorbed
seriousness. It's boring. It pushes others away from you. And it
requires a whole lot of energy to assume such a world view.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't negotiate with yourself. ``Once you've made an offer, if
the other party doesn't accept it, don't make another offer. Get a
counteroffer. It's a sign of weakness when you lower your own
demands without getting your opponent to lower theirs.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Keep it light during speeches. ``Quiet, restful atmospheres
are for sleeping, not speaking. Be sure the lights are turned up as
high as they'll go. Audiences remember more in brightness and share
laughter much more frequently. ... And skip the slides unless
they're absolutely necessary. They're another excuse for your
audience to snooze.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's advice on negotiating a contract, speaking to an
audience or running a sales force, Mackay provides wit and insight
that comes from experience.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Jacket blurbs
</P>
<P>
   ``100 Questions You Should Ask About Your Personal Finances''
</P>
<P>
   By Ilyce R. Glink
</P>
<P>
   TimesBooks, $19
</P>
<P>
   Newspaper columnist Ilyce Glink tackles the dreary world of
personal finance in a straightforward, easy-to-read style that
enables readers to home in quickly on specific issues. This book
follows the same format as two previous books by Glink on home
buying and home selling.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Wear Clean Underwear: Business Wisdom from Mom''
</P>
<P>
   By Rhonda Abrams
</P>
<P>
   Random House, $22.95
</P>
<P>
   Here is another collection of great companies and their stories
from columnist, author and entrepreneur Rhonda Abrams. And, yes,
Southwest Airlines is included again, although Abrams says she
eliminated companies that always show up as great places to work.
The advice Abrams gleans from these companies is simple but true,
and often not found in the workplace.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Navigating Your Career''
</P>
<P>
   By Christopher W. Hunt and Scott A. Scanlon
</P>
<P>
   John Wiley &AMP; Sons, $16.95
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-one of the top U.S. headhunters write a chapter each on
trends and shifts in the business world. Job searches,
interviewing, using a headhunter and negotiating compensation
packages are among the topics. The authors also look at seven hot
career paths, including financial services, information technology,
entertainment/media, health care, consulting and small business.
</P>
<P>
   (Teresa McUsic reviews business books for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-04-99 1556EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990204.0231 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 16:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1945 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IOC-LOBBYING-0205-COX     02-04 1236
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IOC-LOBBYING-0205-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX EDs: Atlanta out.
 &HT;    IN SMOKEY BARS, HOTEL ROOMS OLYMPIC OFFICIALS LOBBY FOR THEIR
LIVES
 &HT;    EDs: This story is also good for use over the weekend.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (s) Sports categories.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAUSANNE, Switzerland _ Niels Holst-Sorensen sits in an
overstuffed black leather chair in the Lausanne Palace hotel bar, a
clubbish old place, its scarlet walls covered with original LeRoy
Neiman paintings of athletes frozen in action visible through the
haze of Cuban cigar smoke.
</P>
<P>
   Holst-Sorensen, a 74-year-old former Danish general and
International Olympic Committee member, is astounded at what has
transpired.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Atlanta, they gave me a compass, a compass!'' he says,
tapping his fingertips on the small cocktail table, causing tiny
ripples in the drinks of two commiserating IOC members. ``And this
they put on CNN! A compass!''
</P>
<P>
   His colleagues nod and murmur affirmations. They feel his pain.
``I don't know what this cost?'' the old general says. ``What? Was
I supposed to ask?''
</P>
<P>
   The answer, apparently, is yes.
</P>
<P>
   Just months ago -- it must seem a million years to the remaining
105 members of the committee -- there was a certain cache in being
an IOC member. It was a great gig, with first-class world travel
and the fawning attention of the dozen or so cities that at any
given time are in hot pursuit of the Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
   The primary competition for bidding cities had for years been
over who could best provide comfort and cheer to the IOC members.
</P>
<P>
   Times are changing.
</P>
<P>
   As the three-day conference on drugs in sports ended Thursday,
it was clear that the old days are gone for good. The questions now
for the members is when will the changes end, and at what cost.
</P>
<P>
   The triumph the IOC had expected from the conference was dwarfed
by the Salt Lake City bidding scandal, which placed a near-crushing
weight on the 105-year-old institution all week.
</P>
<P>
   IOC members left Lausanne looking ahead to March, when the full
committee will meet in a special session to address the Salt Lake
City crisis. The meeting is regarded by many here as the IOC's last
best hope for containing the monster before it does lasting damage
to the Olympic Games themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``We look to March,'' said IOC member Alex Gilady of Israel.
``We look with hope.''
</P>
<P>
   Never has the IOC been subjected to such relentless indignity.
More than 40 members came to Lausanne for the World Congress on
Doping organized to confront the nagging problem of drug use by
athletes.
</P>
<P>
   When the conference was envisioned by the IOC months ago, it was
seen as a platform for the committee to be seen leading the attack
against performance-enhancing drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the week became a forum for abuse by governments,
reporters, athletes and sports officials directed at the IOC --
particularly its president, Juan Antonio Samaranch.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Pound, the IOC vice president spearheading the anti-drug
campaign as well as the scandal investigation, described the week
drolly as ``scream therapy.''
</P>
<P>
   Many speakers proclaimed the IOC too tainted to lead the noble
fight. Renn Crichlow, a former world champion kayaker from Canada,
issued stinging remarks during the conference. ``In Canada and
indeed throughout the world, there is a high degree of cynicism, a
high degree of skepticism and a high degree of mistrust in the IOC
as an organization,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In normal times, such a conference would attract perhaps 100
members of the media, mostly the reporters who routinely cover the
IOC for readers, listeners and viewers around the world.
</P>
<P>
   But with the smell of blood in the air because of the Salt Lake
scandal, the media ranks swelled to nearly 400. They were hostile,
pushy and consistent in their demands for Samaranch to resign -- a
poisoned atmosphere that rendered the IOC members and staff members
puzzled and frightened.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Samaranch's political powers seem diminished.
Certainly, his ability to exert his will over the IOC is at a low
point in his 18-year reign.
</P>
<P>
   In a mini-revolt of sorts, about 40 members made it clear during
a Wednesday breakfast organized to air their grievances that they
will not follow Samaranch's reform edict to surrender their only
meaningful function -- the vote for Olympic host cities.
</P>
<P>
   While no IOC members have publicly joined in the chorus
demanding Samaranch's head, the talk in the Lausanne Palace bar has
at times turned to the topic of ``What if?''
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, the members have greater dread of losing
Samaranch than they have for the blistering to continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only Samaranch can lead us out of this tunnel,'' said Italian
IOC member Mario Pescante, perhaps the most outspoken opponent of
Samaranch's campaign to strip the IOC members of their votes to end
the scandal-tainted bidding process.
</P>
<P>
   IOC members say they fear the 78-year-old president's departure
would lead to chaos. Five senior members have declared their
interest in succeeding Samaranch after his term ends in 2001, and
if he goes now, the committee could splinter at its most perilous
moment.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps more importantly, the members still regard Samaranch
with great respect and feel a deep personal loyalty to him. It is
important to remember that Samaranch handpicked about 80 of the 105
members, making a vote against him for many a personal betrayal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are all united together,'' said Prince Alexander de Merode
of Belgium. ``I am sure that Samaranch will consult with the
members and their wish is that he will continue.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, the great hope is the special session in March. If the
IOC can expel the five members implicated in the Salt Lake City
scandal, and if meaningful reforms can be adopted in the bidding
process, then members say they hope that the storm will begin to
subside.
</P>
<P>
   They also are convinced that the bright spectacle of the 2000
Games in Sydney will provide the impetus needed to close the book
on this dark chapter.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, they acknowledge that a tough road lies ahead. It will take
a two-thirds majority to expel, and some of the targeted members,
notably Jean Claude Ganga of Congo, have vowed to stage a fight to
preserve their memberships.
</P>
<P>
   While IOC marketing officials say fresh consumer polls indicate
that the image of the Games themselves have not yet been damaged by
the scandal, the longer this great public drama persists, the
greater the risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, if this went on indefinitely it would do some
damage,'' said IOC marketing director Michael Payne. ``That's why
the IOC said it would act quickly and decisively to clean its
house.''
</P>
<P>
   And even if the March session is a success, the IOC's hopes
could be dashed if more revelations of wrongdoing surface,
particularly with the release of the investigation report by the
Salt Lake organizing committee as early as next week.
</P>
<P>
   Already, members' first-class trips to the six cities bidding
for the 2006 Winter Games have been taken away in the reform push.
It is a near certainty that the days of wining and dining their
ways around the globe are gone, as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a good run,'' says Gilady, as he stubs out a
half-smoked $10 Cuban in the Lausanne Palace bar. ``But I guess it
must end.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
