<P>
   The New York Times News Service calls your attention to the
following auto features moved during the last week.
</P>
<P>
   For retransmission of these stories, call 888-346-9867.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET-WHEELS-COX (Undated) _ A reminder really shouldn't be
necessary, but all the attention and praise being given the new
Beetle seem to warrant one: Volkswagen is still importing, and
quite frequently selling, the Jetta sedan. Fact is, the Jetta is
the best-selling Volkswagen in North America with 1998 sales
totaling about 90,000, prompting VW execs to call the Mexican-built
car the leader here among German sedans and the only six-cylinder
European car available for under $20,000. By Russ DeVault.
</P>
<P>
   THE MECHANIC-COX (Undated) _ Misdiagnosis of electrical repairs
not only contributes to the animosity between the consumer and the
auto repair industry but also costs millions of hours and dollars
each year in lost revenue. By Nora Carter.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-REVIEW-AZR (Phoenix) Chevrolet Lumina is headed toward the
end of its road, destined to be replaced for 2000 as Chevy's
bread-and-butter family sedan by a more interesting craft bearing
an old name, Impala. The Lumina's styling is attractive, though
generic. Performance is competent, though bland. The overall theme
is mainstream to a fault, offending no one but not enticing anyone,
either. The big plus during its 10 years of existence has been its
affordability. By Bob Golfen.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-REVIEW-BOS (Undated) _ Two-door automobiles, for the most
part, leave me cold. What's the point of having two rows of seats
and one set of doors? I'm not talking about sports cars with back
seats designed for tax collectors (more properly, perhaps, to avoid
them), or wee convertibles with rudimentary melon carriers in the
rear. I refer to real cars, bread-and-butter cars that working
stiffs and families own. By John R. White.
</P>
<P>
   CARS-WILLIAMS-COLUMN-TEX (Undated) _ There's a brand-new Honda
on the market, ready to battle for dominancy in yet another market
segment: the minivan. By G. Chambers Williams III.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-COLUMN-BOS (Undated) _ From time to time, you may have
heard rumblings about OEM vs. aftermarket crash parts _ you
probably wondered what they were rumbling about. OEM stands for
original equipment manufacturer and means a part made for your car
by the company that made your car or made the parts for the company
that assembled your car. Aftermarket means everybody else who makes
pieces for your automobile. Consumer groups from time to time mount
campaigns to focus public attention on the need for OEM parts. By
John R. White.
</P>
<P>
   CAR-SMART-WINDSTAR-MOMS-NYT (Undated) _ While serving as vehicle
line director, supervising the development of the 1999 Ford
Windstar, Mary Ellen Heyde was struck by the unusually large number
of women with young children who were working on the redesign. She
thought it made sense to tap the maternal expertise of these 30
``Windstar Moms,'' most of them engineers, and she consulted them
routinely as the design progressed. With the aim of making the
minivan more family-friendly, the mothers offered suggestions for
innovations and improvements. By Julie Edelson Halpert.
</P>
