A1958 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HANDS-FILM-REVIEW-NYT     02-04 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDS-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HANDS ON A HARD BODY': TRUCK LUST AS A SOURCE OF ENDURANCE IN
TEXAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Prduction notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Benny is a little scary when he gets excited. ``It's like the
first time you kill a really big animal,'' he says in his best
Texas good-old-boy voice. ``Exhilarating!''
</P>
<P>
   The experience Benny is comparing to his hunting triumphs is
having won a pickup truck in 1992 by being the contestant who
lasted longest just standing there with at least one hand on the
truck.
</P>
<P>
   In S.R. Bindler's observant, surprisingly fascinating
documentary ``Hands on a Hard Body,'' Benny is back for the 1995
contest at a Nissan dealership in Longview, Texas, hoping to win
again. He is joined by two dozen or so other contestants with
various styles and motivations.
</P>
<P>
   One participant, Norma, is so overweight that her ability to
last an afternoon, much less the 80 to 100 hours the contest is
expected to last, is questionable, but she claims divine right of a
sort. ``My husband and I have been praying for a truck,'' she
explains. ``I believe that this is what God wants us to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Janis, who is missing a few front teeth, is planning to do it
through sheer determination. ``I finish everything I start,'' she
says. (Apparently this does not apply to her dental work.) Her
husband agrees that she's going to win but as long as he has a
movie camera on him he wants to brag about his ``20-ton
air-conditioner,'' which ``will bring it down to 12 below zero'' in
his living room.
</P>
<P>
   Greg thinks he'll win because he's just out of the Marine Corps;
even Benny agrees that an ex-Marine would have the right mind-set.
J.D., the oldest contestant, has promised his wife he'll win the
truck for her. One of the judges predicts that Kelli will win
because she is preparing and eating properly (unlike another
contestant who was seen eating a hamburger, which would take lots
of energy to digest).
</P>
<P>
   The camera starts rolling at Day 1, hour 1 and stays until the
end, filming the contestants through their 5-minute hourly breaks
and 15-minute breaks every 6 hours, through the period when people
are breaking into fatigue-induced laughter and one contestant,
defeated after 68 hours, walks away, dazed and barefoot.
</P>
<P>
   These may not be people whom moviegoers think they want to spend
time with, but this is accomplished documentary making, finding
universal lessons in determination, struggle, planning, persistence
and the relationship of mind and body. The experience turns out to
be simultaneously primal and complex. Or as Benny sums it up,
``It's a human drama thing.''
</P>
<P>
   To Bindler's credit, he does not look down on his subjects, an
understandable temptation for a hometown boy who went away to NYU
film school. (Recent documentaries like ``Unmade Beds,'' a look at
four chronically single New Yorkers, have shown far less sympathy.)
</P>
<P>
   Bindler observes their quirks _ and can't completely hide that
he thinks it's strange for the local church to have a ``prayer
chain'' to help Norma win the pickup _ but he looks for each
person's humanity and finds it.
</P>
<P>
   When Sydney Pollack made ``They Shoot Horses, Don't They?'' in
1969, the desperation of its dance-marathon contestants was
palpable, but the film's Depression-era setting allowed the
audience some distance. ``Hands on a Hard Body'' hits closer to
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hands on a Hard Body'' is rated PG (Parental guidance
suggested). It contains profanity.
</P>
<P>
   HANDS ON A HARD BODY
</P>
<P>
   Directed and edited by S.R. Bindler; directors of photography,
Michael Nickles, Chapin John Wilson and Bindler; music by Neil
Kassanoff; produced by Kevin Morris, Wilson and Bindler; released
by Legacy Releasing. Running time: 97 minutes. This film is rated
PG.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Russell Welsh, Kerri Parker, Kelli Mangrum, Greg Cox,
Norma Valverde, Janis Curtis, J.D. Drew, Benny Perkins,
contestants, and Blake Long, contest host.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
