<HEADER>
A1969 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WILSON-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      02-04 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILSON-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WWII HERO WALLENBERG MAY GET THAT SPOTLIGHT NOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE WILSON  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   family fortune, a great education, a secure and unlimited
future. In 1944, he risked everything to save Hungarian Jews from
Nazi extermination.
</P>
<P>
   He ranks as one of the greatest _ and least known _ heroes of
World War II.
</P>
<P>
   A Swedish businessman and diplomat, he volunteered to go to
Budapest, Hungary, where the Nazis were moving to wipe out the last
large European community of Jews. His relentless, courageous
efforts prevented Adolf Eichmann from deporting tens of thousands _
estimates reach as high as 100,000 _ to the death camps.
</P>
<P>
   His name was Raoul Wallenberg. Or should I say ``is'' Raoul
Wallenberg?
</P>
<P>
   During his months in Budapest, he lived in constant danger.
Eichmann called him ``Jewdog Wallenberg'' and ordered his murder.
He survived partly because he slept in a different place every
night.
</P>
<P>
   After the war, his humanitarian efforts were ignored by the
Soviets who thought he was a spy and took him prisoner. While the
Russians said he died many years ago in detention, some people
believe he could still be alive. They include Morris Wolff of
Phoenix, who has spent 15 years researching the life and
disappearance of this extraordinary man.
</P>
<P>
   A Yale law graduate and ex-professor, Wolff moved here a year
ago and worked briefly for the Arizona Corporation Commission. He's
now finishing a book on Wallenberg.
</P>
<P>
   Wolff taught human rights law and was practicing in Philadelphia
when he was asked by Wallenberg's family in Sweden if he could help
them. He filed a federal lawsuit in 1984, alleging the Soviet Union
had violated international law.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. District Court in Washington, D.C., found the Soviets
liable for violating Wallenberg's human rights, imposed a fine of
$39 million and ordered them to produce him. The ruling was
appealed, however, and set aside for lack of jurisdiction.
</P>
<P>
   The official Soviet line is that he died of a heart attack in a
Moscow prison in 1947. Others speculate that Josef Stalin had
ordered his execution. But freed Soviet prisoners reported
Wallenberg had been seen into the 1980s, and no credible evidence
of his death has been provided.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1981 book ``Righteous Gentile _'' Wallenberg was a Lutheran
_ John Bierman concluded that he might still be living. He cited
the Soviet tradition of keeping well-known people, from Feodor
Dostoyevsky to Alexander Solzhenitsyn, in confinement for long
periods.
</P>
<P>
   Wolff, whose research draws on both American and Soviet
intelligence reports, is optimistic that Wallenberg survives.
Conversations with two Russian Orthodox priests in 1993 strengthen
his belief. He's hopeful that his book will ``ignite a clamor and
lead the United States to demand an honest accounting of his
life.''
</P>
<P>
   America's efforts on behalf of Wallenberg have been shamefully
slight, especially in light of his U.S. ties. He was an honor
student at the University of Michigan and went to Budapest at the
request of the American War Refugee Board.
</P>
<P>
   With the Cold War's onset, tense Soviet relations apparently
figured into U.S. apathy. Wallenberg's fate wasn't regarded as
important enough to risk stirring up more diplomatic trouble.
</P>
<P>
   A Free Wallenberg Committee was formed in 1980, and for only the
second time in history, Congress granted him honorary U.S.
citizenship (the first honoree was Winston Churchill). But that
campaign and Swedish efforts produced nothing new from the Soviets.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to overstate how much Wallenberg gave up in 1944.
Being a Wallenberg in Sweden is akin to being a Rockefeller in this
country, only bigger. Companies under Wallenberg family control
last year accounted for 40 percent of the Swedish stock market.
</P>
<P>
   Wolff said one reason for writing the book is so more Americans
will know of the sacrifices made by ``one of the most selfless
citizens of the 20th century.''
</P>
<P>
   I hope the book will acquaint more people with a prodigious
hero. And wherever he may be, I hope Wallenberg has found peace. He
would be 86 today. &QL; 
Steve Wilson can be reached at 444-8775 or at
steve.wilson(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
