<SLUG> BC-LESLEYGORE-MUSIC-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FANS STILL FLOCK TO SEE `PARTY' GIRL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDY CORDOVA  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - It's the party that never seems to end.
</P>
<P>
   At only 16 years old, Lesley Gore recorded the endearingly
bratty ``It's My Party'' (``And I'll cry if I want to! Cry if I
want to! Cry if I want to!,'' the chorus endlessly whines).
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-six years later, the record has the comfortable
familiarity of a nursery rhyme. Part of it has to do with the song
rarely being off the radio; the other part has to do with the tune
forever being featured on TV commercials selling golden oldies
collections.
</P>
<P>
   ``It never really died,'' agrees Gore. ``When you look at the
top 20 radio stations in the various cities around the United
States, nine out of 10 of them are oldies stations. That says
something to me about the people that grew up with this music.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore is an interesting paradox. She's a mature, sophisticated
New Yorker who is a regular on the Manhattan cabaret scene, but
she's eternally linked with a song written from a teenager's
perspective. But she won't bash the tune that made her the Britney
Spears of her day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something about the purity and honesty of the song just
works,'' she says, in a husky voice that sounds little like the one
that wailed about Judy and Johnny. ``The other thing, frankly, that
gets me through is watching the audience reaction.''
</P>
<P>
   That's one reason Gore never will spoof that tune, or any of her
other hits. She had a bunch of them, which tend to be overshadowed
by the monstrous ``Party.'' There was the daring riot grrrl anthem
``You Don't Own Me'' (later covered by Joan Jett), the bubbly
``Sunshine, Lollipops and Rainbows'' and ``California Nights,'' a
dreamy Beach Boys-flavored gem from 1967.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people really treat these songs as sacred cows,'' she
says. ``I don't treat them as sacred, but I have respect for the
music. I know what it means to the audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Her career has taken a lot of surprising turns. She played
Pussycat, Catwoman's slinky assistant, on two episodes of
``Batman.'' She wrote the song ``Out Here on My Own'' for the 1980
film ``Fame,'' and wound up getting an Oscar nomination.
</P>
<P>
   But it's her run as a teen queen with an awesome flip hairdo
that earned her a spot in the public's heart. And she wasn't merely
a singing Barbie doll _ Quincy Jones produced most of her hits and
Gore had a hand in writing some of them.
</P>
<P>
   PolyGram and Rhino recently saluted Gore by both issuing CD
retrospectives. Even more impressive is the imaginatively titled
``It's My Party!,'' a five-disc spectacular from Bear Family
Records featuring absolutely everything she recorded between 1963
</P>
<P>
   and 1969 (``an incredible honor,'' Gore says).
</P>
<P>
   On the East Coast, she performs solo gigs in nightclubs.
Elsewhere, it's oldies shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are always asking me when I'm going to stop doing it,''
she says. ``The answer is probably never. And to be honest, it
doesn't make me feel badly. It certainly was a statement back then
that meant something to a lot of people. That's something good,
something to be proud of.''
</P>
<P>
   It is her party, after all. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Randy Cordova can be reached at The Arizona Republic, P.O. Box 2245
NF-19, Phoenix, AZ 85002; or at randy.cordova(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
