<SLUG> BC-WILD-PARROTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARROT MAN MUST SOON LEAVE HIS FLOCK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MACKENZIE WARREN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Mark Bittner, caretaker of the 50 curious wild
parrots who frequent Telegraph Hill, is being forced to flee the
coup.
</P>
<P>
   The self-described ``friend of the flock'' said Wednesday that
the 120-year-old home he has been living in is scheduled for a
major renovation, since it has no foundation, and the property
owner has asked him to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Those who know his work say Bittner is more than a friend. They
say he has devoted the past five years to studying and spoiling the
flock of brightly colored South American conures that have
mysteriously made their way to San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's this guy, a modern-day Haight-Ashbury version of St.
Francis,'' said Judy Irving, a filmmaker who's making a documentary
about Bittner and his birds. ``It's magical, the relationship he's
established with them.''
</P>
<P>
   In June, however, Bittner will have to move when the renovation
begins. Bittner said that was OK. He sees it as a sign he must
leave the birds and move on.
</P>
<P>
   People who have strolled up the hundred or so steps on the east
side of Telegraph Hill and past Bittner's home, Irving said, often
have wondered aloud which is stranger: 50 tropical birds in an
urban setting 4,000 miles from their natural habitat, or someone
crazy enough to devote five years of his life to watch over them?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not doing this out of any kind of eccentricity,'' Bittner
said. ``It's more out of curiosity and love.''
</P>
<P>
   In October 1993, he started to notice the bright green parrots
with various-colored heads while he was putting seed out for other
birds in the neighborhood. He tossed some to the parrots for about
a few months, but after a while a neighbor asked him to stop. The
birds were making too much noise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each day, I had said this would be the last day I fed them,''
Bittner said. ``And when that guy complained, I decided that was
it. I'd just go and scare them off for good.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Bittner said, the parrots weren't impressed when he
stepped out to scream at them. They had taken a liking to him, and
they intended to stay.
</P>
<P>
   So he began looking around for experts to advise him on caring
for the conures, though he did not have much success.
</P>
<P>
   ``After I looked around for a while and researched on my own,''
Bittner said, ``I became the person I was looking for.''
</P>
<P>
   Bittner believes the Telegraph Hill birds were imported from
Ecuador and northern Peru before quarantine restrictions were
tightened in 1992. But the birds are rare: The Convention on
International Trade in Endangered Species has classified them as a
``near-threatened'' species.
</P>
<P>
   The flock includes descendants of cherry-headed conures, a
blue-crowned conure, a mitred conure and some cherry-headed-mitred
hybrids.
</P>
<P>
   Bittner has seen more than 40 parrots born since he became
committed to them nearly five years ago, bringing the total number
that have flown with the flock to about 100. He keeps a daily log
and detailed file on each bird, and has gotten to know each one
personally. All have names and their own personalities, he said.
</P>
<P>
   For a few more months, life will be normal for the likes of
Mingas, Connor, Scrapperella, Picasso, Olive, Pushkin and the
others, and for Bittner, too.
</P>
<P>
   But then Bittner, who spends about $100 a month to feed the
birds, will start the solemn process of distancing himself from his
pals. That way, when his early June move comes around, the
separation won't be so harsh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I'll feel sad,'' Bittner said as he gazed at Mingas.
``But the time will be right. It will be time to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Bittner said he was not upset about moving. He said the property
owner had been gracious and generous. And the time is simply right
for him to go. ``It's time to end it,'' he said. ``Losing this
place is that natural ending.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the parrots? ``They'll be just fine,'' he said. Bittner
said he had made sure they did not depend on him for food. Despite
what he spends monthly on bird feed, he considers what he gives
them little more than dessert.
</P>
</TEXT>
