<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN'S BEST FRIEND, AND PERHAPS ALSO THE ARTIST'S 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By WENDY MOONAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Tails (and tongues) will be wagging when the 123rd
annual Westminster Kennel Club Show opens Monday in Manhattan. Dog
owners from across the country will congregate to parade prized
pets and, perhaps, trade doggerel. (Notice to out-of-town pug
lovers: New York pug owners converge on Pug Hill in Central Park,
near the East 72nd Street entrance, every Saturday morning.)
</P>
<P>
   To take advantage of this, William Doyle Galleries, in
conjunction with Bonhams of London, is conducting an auction called
``Dogs and Cats in Art'' on Tuesday, at Doyle's at 175 E. 87th St.
in Manhattan. The 166 lots include 19th- and 20th-century paintings
by the English animal portraitists John Emms, George Earl, Arthur
Wardle and Richard Ansdell, as well as bronzes and ephemera. There
are toys for grown-ups, like a sturdy papier-mache bulldog with a
bristle ruff from France, circa 1900, that barks out loud with an
articulated jaw when his leash is yanked (estimate: $700 to $900).
</P>
<P>
   And there are some unusual dog accessories. One black and gilded
Georgian-style traveling animal case, for example, is done up in
chinoiserie, with a gilded pagoda-shaped roof, bracket feet, an oak
parquet floor and glass windowpanes on the sides. A pink curtain
drops down the rear of the interior to serve as a backdrop for the
animal inside. The glass box, about 22 inches tall, neatly
disassembles to fit into a travel case (estimate: $5,000 to
$7,000).
</P>
<P>
   The next week, Sotheby's is selling 120 ink drawings of animals,
including several dogs, by Alexander Calder in its Feb. 16 Arcade
auction, ``Impressionist, Modern and Contemporary Art.'' So there's
something for every dog lover around.
</P>
<P>
   The dog has been immortalized in ink and stone since ancient
times. The old cemetery in Athens is full of classical marble grave
steles, circa 500 B.C., with the faithful dog, the widow and the
children carved in bas-relief, mourning their loss. Artists have
also celebrated dogs' unconditional love in jade, porcelain,
needlework, even painted miniatures.
</P>
<P>
   Think of the Duc de Berry promenading through the Loire
countryside on horseback, his two dogs galloping alongside his
horse, in the illustrated manuscript for August in ``Les Tres
Riches Heures du Duc de Berry,'' circa 1415.
</P>
<P>
   Many early depictions of dogs are in hunting scenes. Who can
forget the snarling hound Rubens painted in his bloodthirsty
``Crocodile Hunt''? In this royal hunt scene, circa 1615, the
pitiless dog plays the leading role in his master's effort to bring
down a roaringly mad hippo.
</P>
<P>
   Only in the last few centuries have dogs taken on a kinder look.
It was probably Queen Victoria's interest in breeding dogs that led
to the popularity of dog portraiture in the 1800s, an appeal that
continues today.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Victorians held their dogs very close to their hearts,''
said David Mason, director of the MacDonnal-Mason Gallery, a London
firm exhibiting in Florida at the Palm Beach International Art and
Antique Fair, which runs through Sunday. ``It was the first time
dogs were treated like humans, as part of the family. Dog portraits
became an important oeuvre.''
</P>
<P>
   Sir Edwin Henry Landseer was one of the most popular and
accomplished dog painters of the era, Mason said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Landseer was the Stubbs of the 19th century,'' he said,
referring to George Stubbs, the 18th-century English painter of
zebras, lions and Arabian horses whose paintings fetch millions of
dollars. ``Like Stubbs, Landseer was a perfectionist who studied
and dissected animals so he could paint them more perfectly.''
</P>
<P>
   There are no Landseers in the Doyle sale, but there is an oil by
Richard Ansdell, a Landseer follower from Liverpool. The painting,
``The Good Shepherd'' of 1870, depicts a Scot in a kilt, complete
with sporran and tartan throw, out on the moors holding a lamb he
has rescued. By his side, the poor lamb's mother and a proud border
collie look on. It is saccharine but well painted (estimate:
$50,000 to $70,000).
</P>
<P>
   The Austrians were as besotted with their dogs as the English
were in the 19th century. Janssens van der Maelen, a Brussels
gallery exhibiting at the Palm Beach fair, has a pair of Austrian
terra-cotta Dobermans, circa 1860, that are life-size, beautifully
modeled and full of personality. They were made as garden ornaments
but are elegant enough for any marble foyer. The pair costs
$48,000. These dogs don't come cheap.
</P>
<P>
   In France, bronze dogs were particularly popular in the 19th
century. Robert Bowman, a Palm Beach exhibitor from London, is
selling a sculpture of two playful whippets in cast bronze by
Pierre Jules Mene (1810-79).
</P>
<P>
   ``Mene was a member of the Animaliers, a French group dedicated
to the depiction of animals,'' Bowman said. ``The school was
founded by Antoine-Louis Barye, a top sculptor, and they worked in
and around Paris.''
</P>
<P>
   Bronzes were not made in signed editions at that time, Bowman
said, adding, ``Clients would see an example of a dog at a salon
and order a copy for themselves.'' The trick today, he said, is to
find an early casting, when the chiseling is crisp and fresh. ``You
want to be able to see the pads on the paws, the teeth, the tongue,
the fur,'' he said. ``The work should be almost photographic in its
modeling.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Russian Imperial Court, no material was too good for
figures of dogs. Wartski of London is selling a palm-size Faberge
bulldog in its booth at the Palm Beach fair. It is carved in
bowenite, a translucent, pale green serpentine stone that looks
like jade. The dog has eyes of green demantoid garnets, a
semiprecious stone; a gold collar, and a gold medallion that reads
``First Prize'' in Cyrillic script.
</P>
<P>
   ``Faberge made a lot of dogs, but I've seen only two bulldogs in
my entire life,'' said Katherine Purcell, a director of Wartski.
</P>
<P>
   The Manhattan gallery A La Vieille Russie, also exhibiting in
Palm Beach, has a circa-1870 dog's head carved in crystal that
Faberge mounted in about 1903, so it could be placed on a
mantelpiece or a table.
</P>
<P>
   ``This kind of carving is called reverse crystal, because it's
carved from the inside,'' said Peter Schaffer, a vice president of
the gallery. ``It's just an accident that it was put under a glass
dome and mounted in gold by Faberge.''
</P>
<P>
   He has no idea who might buy it. ``Reverse-crystal collectors
are not necessarily looking for Faberge and vice versa,'' he said.
The price is $45,000.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 21, Christie's New York sold a pair of porcelain dogs,
circa 1765, in its sale of English decorative arts. Named the
Talbot-Shrewsbury Hounds because they had been owned by Baron
Talbot and the Earl of Shrewsbury, they went for $497,500, a record
price for Chinese export porcelain sold in the United States. The
high estimate was $380,000. It seems every dog has his day.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-04-99 1628EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
