<P>
   The New York Times News Service calls your attention to the
following religion features moved during the last week.
</P>
<P>
   For retransmission of these stories, call 888-346-9867.
</P>
<P>
   GOSPEL-GRAMMYS-HNS (San Francisco) _ The road to gospel
Grammydom can be curious indeed. Consider Deniece Williams' career
over more than two decades. For all her rock 'n' roll hits _ solo
and with Johnny Mathis _ Williams had been a Grammy bridesmaid 10
times, but never a bride. A few years ago, she took a gamble and
crossed over to gospel. The result: three Grammy nominations and
three wins. Now she's after her fourth. By Corrie M. Anders.
</P>
<P>
   CATHOLIC-RITUALS-REVIEW-NYT (Undated) _ Although resisting major
change, the Catholic Church has been enacting lesser changes in
ritual and practice designed to render ancient religious customs
compatible with the spirit of the times. In much of this, experts
say, the Vatican struggles to take into account the sensibilities
and convictions of a widely varying membership in broadly differing
societies. A recent statement on exorcism is an example. By John
Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS-CHRIST-COX (Longview, Texas) _ Though Dr. Martin Luther
King Jr. was able to maintain his nonviolent commitment to a
righteous cause some 30 years ago, some observers say that
Christians and politics today make for a stormier brew.
</P>
<P>
   JEWS-SABBATH-COX (Undated) _ From a distance, they look like
ordinary utility wires, but three Atlanta area synagogues now have
ritual enclosures that allow traditional Jews to carry items from
their homes to the synagogue on sabbaths and holidays. Strict
sabbath observers may not carry even a key or a package of Kleenex
on the sabbath. But the cord that is strung around the Toco Hill
neighborhood Beth Jacob synagogues makes a two-mile area
symbolically part of the synagogue. We look at why the synagogues
go to the trouble and expense _ about $10,000 a year _ of
maintaining the cords and what impact they have on the community.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT (Undated) _ Over the last 300 years,
religion and economics have come to constitute distinctly different
spheres, talking two conceptually different languages. They may
address each other, as when Pope John Paul II called again in
Mexico City for solidarity with the hemisphere's poor. But
economists, however sympathetic to such appeals, bristle when
morals get mixed up with economic analysis. Theologians turn very
nervous when someone like William James begins to talk about the
``cash value'' of religious beliefs, as if the sacred could be
given a price tag. By Peter Steinfels.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN-TEX (Undated) _ Although we in this
country focused our attention on John Paul's visit to St. Louis on
Tuesday and Wednesday, his journey to Mexico was filled with
significance. By Jim Jones.
</P>
