<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAYS-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE LAST DAYS': IN HUNGARY, THE FINAL DAYS OF THE `FINAL
SOLUTION' 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Productin notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   James Moll's documentary film ``The Last Days,'' a concise,
devastating history of the Nazis' decimation of Hungary's Jewish
population during the final days of World War II, offers a ghastly,
inverse kind of reassurance.
</P>
<P>
   It reminds us that yes, there are still images and stories of
human cruelty and degradation that we can never get used to, that
we shouldn't get used to, no matter how intensely the mass media
have flooded us with pictures of human nature at its vilest.
</P>
<P>
   The film's most searing images, shown sparingly near the end of
the movie, include scenes of concentration camp inmates liberated
from Auschwitz by Allied troops. These hollow-eyed, tottering
skeletons, starved almost beyond recognition, seem barely human as
they gaze at the camera through eyes of the living dead.
</P>
<P>
   These pictures are matched in impact by the interwoven
testaments of five Holocaust survivors and especially by one
woman's calm, understated account of her days and nights spent
stuffed in a boxcar on its way to a death camp. (Until the doors
were opened, the passengers believed they were being sent to work
in a vineyard.)
</P>
<P>
   Her description of the train's arrival at Auschwitz is
illustrated with haunting rare photographs taken by a Nazi soldier
of the lining up and dispatching of the new arrivals. Those deemed
unfit for slave labor (children up to the ages of 12 to 14, people
over 50 and the sick) were immediately sent to the gas chambers.
</P>
<P>
   Why another documentary on a subject that has been scrutinized
so deeply that some might assume there's nothing left to say or
show? In focusing on Hungarian Jews, the last major national group
to be funneled into the Nazi death machine, the film forces us to
contemplate the Nazis' implacable genocidal fury.
</P>
<P>
   For by the time German troops invaded Hungary on March 19, 1944,
Hitler knew the war was lost. But that knowledge seems only to have
intensified the Nazi effort to carry out the ``final solution'' as
quickly and efficiently as possible, right up until the Allies
liberated the death camps. In less than three months, some 440,000
Hungarian Jews were rounded up and deported.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Last Days,'' which opens Friday at the Clearview Cinemas,
is the first feature documentary from the Shoah Foundation. Its
executive producer is Steven Spielberg.
</P>
<P>
   If the broad outlines of its story are similar to Claude
Lanzmann's nine-hour epic documentary, ``Shoah,'' its brisk pace
and compact form make it the opposite in some ways of Lanzmann's
exhaustive 1985 masterpiece.
</P>
<P>
   Running only an hour and a half, ``The Last Days'' has a
beginning, middle and end. Instead of accruing an immense volume of
detailed testimony elicited through a relentless interview process,
the movie is edited with the precision of a Hollywood film and has
a tastefully subdued musical score by Hans Zimmer. Like Spielberg's
``Schindler's List,'' it even has what could be construed as a
``happy'' ending.
</P>
<P>
   The five Holocaust survivors whose reminiscences form the heart
of the movie are a likable, articulate, youthful-looking group
(they're in their late 60s and 70s), and all seem to have made some
measure of peace with the past. Several are shown surrounded by
large, loving families of children and grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of moving from one to the next in a series of portraits,
the movie weaves their stories into a shifting mosaic of voices.
There is Tom Lantos, a United States Representative from California
who is the only Holocaust survivor elected to Congress; Alice Lok
Cahana, an artist who deals with Holocaust themes; Renee Firestone,
a teacher who works with the Simon Wiesenthal Center's Educational
Outreach Program; Bill Basch, a successful Los Angeles businessman,
and Irene Zisblatt, a grandmother.
</P>
<P>
   Each person's story is so compelling it is worthy of a
feature-length documentary itself. If ``The Last Days'' has a flaw,
it is that the stories have been so abbreviated to keep the film
moving quickly that they feel incomplete.
</P>
<P>
   The individuals, brave as they are, are not as memorable as the
stories they tell. But Moll has done a fine job selecting the
stories that have the greatest metaphoric resonance. One of the
most vivid is Ms. Zisblatt's account of her deportation to
Auschwitz.
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving, her mother had sewn a few diamonds into the hem
of her dress. Arriving at Auschwitz she was strip-searched and hid
the gems in her mouth and eventually had to swallow them. By
swallowing them repeatedly and then retrieving them when she went
to the bathroom, she was able to hold on to the diamonds for the
duration of her stay. They have since been incorporated into a
menorah that has become a family heirloom.
</P>
<P>
   For all the sufferings it recounts, ``The Last Days'' could
almost be described as a warmhearted film. The hatred and cruelty
visited upon its subjects is not reciprocated. All five of the
subjects have built valuable, creative lives. Their willingness to
contemplate the unthinkable, to describe their horrifying
experiences, attests to their hope that humanity can learn from the
past. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE LAST DAYS
</P>
<P>
   Directed and edited by James Moll; director of photography,
Harris Done; music by Hans Zimmer; produced by June Beallor and Ken
Lipper; presented by Steven Spielberg and Survivors of the Shoah
Visual History Foundation; released by October Films. Running time:
88 minutes. This film is not rated. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Congressman Tom Lantos, Alice Lok Cahana, Renee Firestone,
Bill Basch and Irene Zisblatt (profiled survivors). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
