<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE`S NO BORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c. 1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Whatever happens in the Senate to his boss, Vice
President Al Gore is having a good political year.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton will survive, but he is already the ghost of
power past. The future leadership of the Democratic party is
passing invisibly, irrevocably to Gore.
</P>
<P>
   The veep is suddenly free _ free at last _ of his most serious
potential primary challenge for the 2000 Democratic presidential
nomination. When House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt announced
that he would not run for president, he handed Gore a golden
opportunity to unite the party's moderate and liberal wings and
neutralize the nasty in-fighting of which Democrats are so fond.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's two other possible challengers on the left, former New
Jersey Sen. BIll Bradley and Jesse Jackson, trail Gore badly in
organization, fund-raising, grassroots support and political
visibility. They are barely in the race at all.
</P>
<P>
   And as the country has become increasingly impatient to end the
impeachment charade, Gore has become increasingly bolder, going his
own way on the campaign trail. He is still loyal to his friend and
mentor in the White House, but he has clearly been given a much
longer leash on which to operate.
</P>
<P>
   The Nexis research service filed 780 stories about Gore's
activities in the past week alone.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Gore made two trips to California and visited Iowa,
Florida, Colorado, Arizona, New York and Pennsylvania. Most of the
time he traveled solo, although sometimes he appeared with the
president. He brought administration-approved federal goodies for
many of the localities, starred at blockbuster fund-raising events
and steadily accumulated commitments of support from city and state
officials.
</P>
<P>
   He has carved out special issues to advocate that the president
has never stressed, establishing his own identity. In his frequent
travels abroad, he represents the administration not merely in
ceremonial ways but in serious policy discussions.
</P>
<P>
   There is a danger in this of upstaging the president, but
Clinton seems to approve of Gore's new public independence. The
president may be motivated by more than friendship; in case he
needs a criminal pardon, Clinton is more likely to get it from a
President Gore than a Republican successor.
</P>
<P>
   The new federal budget was dubbed the Clinton-Gore budget. Many
administration announcements are reserved for Gore to reveal before
relevant constituencies. The Clinton and Gore staffs coordinate and
overlap. It is all quite remarkable, considering the history of the
two unequal jobs.
</P>
<P>
   In the good old days, American vice presidents, like children,
were meant to be seen and not heard, a secondary presence rendered
harmless through silence. Their usefulness, beyond serving as
fodder for silly jokes, was about that of the human appendix.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Hubert Humphrey used to complain that he was only
interviewed by national media reporters in August, when all other
sources of information were on vacation. An officially scheduled
luncheon once a week was the only way Walter Mondale regularly got
to see President Carter.
</P>
<P>
   George Bush confessed that during his eight years as veep he had
never been invited by President Ronald Reagan into the family
living quarters upstairs at the White House. If Dan Quayle was ever
consulted by President Bush on a serious issue, nobody knows about
it.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, Gore mostly played a dodge game, escaping
several political bullets that could have punctured his hopes of
moving into the White House. He stuck to the president's side, kept
a low profile, minded his manners and bided his time.
</P>
<P>
   But the political dam began to break his way when Attorney
General Janet Reno decided not to approve an outside special
counsel to investigate Gore's controversial habit of dialing for
dollars during the 1996 presidential campaign. Instead of becoming
a central target of the campaign finance scandal, he remained a
peripheral figure.
</P>
<P>
   Most importantly, he has not been personally dragged into the
tawdry story of the president's Oval Office affair with Monica
Lewinsky that underlies the House impeachment and Senate trial.
Gore's own reputation as a faithful husband and high-minded, if
sometimes boring, public servant remains intact. And insofar as
anyone knows, Gore only learned about Monica when the rest of us
did.
</P>
<P>
   In a January USA Today/CNN Gallup poll, 69 percent of those
surveyed said Gore was honest and trustworthy; by contrast, only 24
percent said Clinton had those traits. And 71 percent said Gore
provides moral leadership, although just 20 percent said Clinton
did so.
</P>
<P>
   Gore receives a 64 percent approval rating for the way he
handles his job, slightly less than Clinton's 69 percent. Not bad
for a fellow in an odd, undefined job constitutionally trapped in a
subordinate status.
</P>
<P>
   If his closeness to our disgraced president is not a major
handicap in the Democratic party, it could raise problems in a
general election. Voters indicated in the USA Today/ CNN poll that
it's a toss-up whether his close association with Clinton helps or
hurts. And in recent trial heats, Gore loses to the two leading GOP
contenders, Texas GOP Gov. George W. Bush and Elizabeth Dole.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore's future will rise or fall on Gore's own performance.
He is taking nothing for granted, working to loosen up his wooden
image and campaigning as though his life depended upon it. Whatever
else you think of Gore, this man is a worker.
</P>
<P>
   But the election is nearly two years away, and anything can
still happen. And probably will.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-04-99 1641EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990204.0246 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 16:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1996 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEECEE-THEATER-1100(2     02-04 1217
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEECEE-THEATER-1100(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASHINGTON DRAMA, OFF CAPITOL HILL 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds. Optional sidebar with schedule for current D.C. theaters is
at end of article.) 
(js) 
 By PETER MARKS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For New York playgoers seeking the adventurousness and vitality
of a serious theater town that can provide everything from
sophisticated classics to world-premiere musicals, here's a travel
tip: Don't rely only on your Metrocard.
</P>
<P>
   There's also the Metroliner.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of a three-hour train ride from the Manhattan theater
district lies a city where the majority of standing ovations still
occur during State of the Union addresses, where the hottest acts
invariably are the ones that get voted on in Congress. But while
politics and government will always be Washington's favorite
spectator sports, they are far from the only local sources of
drama. Increasingly, the capital has been making its presence felt
as a significant force in American theater.
</P>
<P>
   Once known primarily as a way station on the road to Broadway,
the city still occasionally performs that role. The New York-bound
``Annie Get Your Gun'' recently concluded a tryout in Washington,
where Andrew Lloyd Webber's ``Whistle Down the Wind'' crashed and
burned two years ago. But the city has evolved into a splendidly
diverse theater destination unto itself.
</P>
<P>
   With five first-class theater troupes _ the venerable Arena
Stage, the Shakespeare Theater, the Woolly Mammoth Theater Company,
the Signature Theater and the Studio Theater _ dozens of smaller
companies and several major houses for the presentation of touring
productions, including the Kennedy Center, Washington can easily
claim a spot along with Seattle and Minneapolis in the top tier of
American theater locales just below New York, Chicago and Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The maturing of these companies has created a more
self-sustaining theater world and has helped the city emerge a bit
from New York's cultural shadow. Washington's leading theater
people, like Howard Shalwitz, Woolly Mammoth's artistic director,
and Joy Zinoman, who holds the same title at the Studio Theater,
say the talent pool has expanded; more actors who live in
Washington can now make a living there. Playwrights nurtured in the
city, like Nicky Silver, at the Woolly Mammoth, and Lisa Loomer, at
the Arena, have gone on to major off-Broadway productions.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, though, the Washington theater development
generating most of the buzz emanates from the 136-seat Signature,
in suburban Arlington, Va., where a whiz of an artistic director,
Eric D. Schaeffer, is staging the premiere of a new musical by the
``Chicago'' songwriting team of John Kander and Fred Ebb. With a
book by Joseph Stein, ``Over and Over'' is based on Thornton
Wilder's ``Skin of Our Teeth'' and features Dorothy Loudon, David
Garrison, Linda Emond, Mario Cantone and Sherie Scott. It has
already sold out through the end of February, and if it's a
critical hit, the show will certainly cement the reputation of
Schaeffer's innovative 10-year-old theater.
</P>
<P>
   I've seen about a dozen productions in Washington in my
two-and-a-half years as a reviewer. Each time I go, I look forward
to returning. The satisfactions have been surprising and
cumulative; for example, in late 1997 a moving revamped version of
the musical ``Working'' at Signature and a tender, human Othello
from Patrick Stewart at the Shakespeare, and, last fall, a loose
and blazingly inventive ``Waiting for Godot'' by Ms. Zinoman at the
Studio Theater that was far superior to a version staged a month
later at the Classic Stage Company in New York, with John Turturro
and Tony Shalhoub.
</P>
<P>
   On my most recent visit in January, my rising expectations were
met by two of the three productions I attended, a snazzy revival of
``The Women'' by Clare Boothe Luce, in the round at the Arena, and
a stimulating staging of the rarely produced ``King John,'' at the
Shakespeare. Only Woolly Mammoth, the most daring of the Washington
companies, had a major disappointment with ``The Last Orbit of
Billy Mars,'' an overwrought new play by Robert Alexander that was
in every sense a bloody mess. (All three are currently running.)
</P>
<P>
   What alchemy, though, accounts for the city's vibrant theatrical
brew? Why is it that Washington has become such fertile turf for
theater artists when, for instance, similarly sized Boston is,
aside from the American Repertory Theater in Cambridge,
comparatively barren?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' said Shalwitz, a Buffalo native and actor who
helped found Woolly Mammoth in New York and moved it to Washington
in the early 1980s after deciding an audience might be found there
for offbeat drama. The theater has carved a niche as a producer of
slightly outrageous plays by the likes of Silver, Wallace Shawn and
Harry Kondoleon. Shalwitz directs new plays in New York as well. A
few years ago, he staged a well-received production of ``Quills,''
by Doug Wright, at the New York Theater Workshop, and he recently
directed another Woolly Mammoth export, Amy Freed's
``Freedomland,'' at Playwrights Horizons.
</P>
<P>
   The company has inhabited its 132-seat theater, a former
automobile showroom, for 13 years. ``And it's funny,'' he said,
``because there are so many things that make you think it would be
harder to do theater here than other cities. The grant money per
capita from foundations is low; the population is transient. But on
the other hand you have a very educated community.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Zinoman's Studio Theater, currently offering a production of
Alfred Uhry's ``Last Night of Ballyhoo,'' is in the midst of an
ambitious retrospective it calls the Millennium Project, in which
it is presenting what it considers a seminal work from each decade
of the 20th century. She says the revolution in Washington theater
has made drama a viable local industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The actors can have a life here,'' she said, adding that her
own company has trained stage performers familiar to New Yorkers,
like Veanne Cox and Cotter Smith. Her subscribers, too, who used to
be more dependent on out-of-town trips for their theater fixes, are
staying home. ``My audience used to go to New York more. Now they
don't seem to go as much.''
</P>
<P>
   Having spent some time mixing with Washington audiences, I don't
think this is mere home-town boosterism. Attending a play at the
Arena or the Woolly Mammoth, you can sense the air of dedication in
the theater.
</P>
<P>
   By New York standards, Washingtonians are positively genteel in
their theatergoing habits. They're silent; they remain alert, and,
in a charming local custom, they actually stay until the end of the
play. When the lights come up at intermission, the spectators head
for the lobby without their coats. More and more in New York, it
seems, playgoers abandon productions at the halfway point. After
intermission, the abundance of freshly deserted seats can give the
auditorium the look of a picked-over garden. In Washington the
audience remains intact all the way through the curtain calls.
</P>
<P>
   The attentiveness may be attributable partly to the politesse of
a city with roots in Southern graciousness. But the fare at the
major theaters is often worth staying for.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   This is not an absolute rule. A couple of seasons ago, for
example, a production of ``Mourning Becomes Electra'' with Kelly
McGillis at the Shakespeare Theater was a popular and critical
success with Washingtonians, but it seemed to me a clinical and
stiff affair, bloodless and nearly endless. More frequently,
however, my response has been closer to my admiration for the
current offering at the Shakespeare, ``King John.''
</P>
<P>
   The work, though popular in Shakespeare's time, is widely
regarded today as a minor history play. The king is a weak,
vacillating monarch, tied to the apron strings of his fearsome
mother, Eleanor of Aquitaine, and with a contestable claim to the
English throne.
</P>
<P>
   But Michael Kahn, the Shakespeare's longtime artistic director,
wisely stages ``King John'' as a turbulent epic, with filmic
freeze-frame battle scenes that recall ``Braveheart'' and Kenneth
Branagh's ``Henry V.'' And he locates in the unlikely alliance of
the craven ruler _ deftly imbued by Philip Goodwin with an aura of
fragility _ and Philip Faulconbridge, (Edward Gero), the complexly
human bastard son of Richard the Lion-Hearted, a story of the
highborn brought low and the lowborn exalted.
</P>
<P>
   The story of John that Shakespeare relates has a peculiarly
contemporary feel in its dissection of the nature of power and of
questions about the very idea of legitimacy. On Ming Cho Lee's
monumental set, which melds modern and medieval influences, Kahn,
Goodwin and Gero explore the legal and psychological holds the
governor has on the governed, culminating in a scene that eerily
foreshadows the current debate over high crimes and misdemeanors.
It is left to Faulconbridge, Shakespeare's ``good'' illegitimate
son, to warn of the dangers to the nation in the arbitrary deposing
of a leader, no matter what his flaws.
</P>
<P>
   If any failing in the production is worth mentioning, it's a
certain colorlessness, a lack of fleshed-out personality, in many
of the performances, including Gero's. There are notable
exceptions: Andrew Long and Ted van Griethuysen are excellent as,
respectively, a conflicted henchman of the king and an insidious
emissary of the pope. And a lack of robustness in the Shakespearean
ranks, it should be added, is an even more entrenched problem in
New York.
</P>
<P>
   At the Arena Stage, a feeling of freshness is detectable, and
not only because the theater, which in the 1960s was in the
vanguard of the blossoming regional theater movement, has a new
artistic director in Molly Smith. The energy is also being
generated by a 63-year-old play that is one of the most
gender-specific of all time: ``The Women,'' an acidic comedy with
44 parts, played in this vivid, eye-catching production by 18
actresses, most of them familiar to Washington audiences, and many
of them good.
</P>
<P>
   Woolly Mammoth's production of ``The Last Orbit of Billy Mars''
by its resident playwright, Alexander, puts on display an efficient
cast, but the play itself is an unfortunate mishmash of obvious
family secrets and credulity-straining sex and violence. Ostensibly
it's the story of a young lesbian, played by Taunya Martin, who is
living with her mother (Beverly Cosham) and is wooed by
relentlessly romantic Billy Mars (Craig Wallace) over the
objections of her possessive brother (Doug Brown).
</P>
<P>
   The play is scrambled Tennessee Williams, a version of ``The
Glass Menagerie'' as Alexander imagines it with echoes in a
run-down neighborhood in the St. Louis of today, right down to
references to a ``gentleman caller.'' In this version, however, the
disaffected brother has the hobbled walk, and the sister's psychic
disability is traceable to the family's particularly brutal
history. The playwright, however, seems just as eager to abuse the
material, because ``The Last Orbit'' deteriorates rapidly into a
kind of live-action slasher movie.
</P>
<P>
   If the revivals remain stronger than the new plays I've seen,
that may be a sign that Washington's theater identity is still a
work in progress. Unlike, say, Chicago _ which regularly sends New
York works that range from Steppenwolf Theater's ``Grapes of
Wrath'' and ``Buried Child'' to the Goodman Theater's current
``Death of a Salesman'' with Brian Dennehy and Elizabeth Franz _
Washington is not yet a net exporter of the local crop.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it doesn't take much for a theater town to enlarge its
dot on the map. And if any city seems poised to do so, it's
Washington. As in any sturdy edifice run by loving landlords, the
structure is solid.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   Theater Town, D.C.
</P>
