<HEADER>
A2015 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PARK-FEES05-COX     02-04 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARK-FEES05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FEES FOR FEDERAL PARKS TO STAY - FOR NOW
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senators and outdoorsmen agreed Thursday that the
trail has been rocky but promising in an experimental program that
has hiked costs for millions of visitors to some of the nation's
favorite public lands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the jury is still out on whether the Recreation Fee
Demonstration Project should be made permanent,'' said David Brown,
executive director of America Outdoors, the national association of
outfitters and guides.
</P>
<P>
   Enacted in 1996, the Recreation Fee Demonstration Program gave
the National Park Service, Fish and Wildlife Service, Bureau of
Land Management and the Forest Service the authority to charge fees
``above and apart'' from the normal appropriations process. As a
result, the General Accounting Office estimated that the four
agencies' combined recreation fee revenues from the project's 312
federal facilities have nearly doubled from about $93 million in
fiscal year 1996 to about $179 million in fiscal year 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The increased money came from new fees on everything from
parking to canoe launching to campsites paid by visitors to popular
public lands ranging from the Shenandoah National Park in Virginia
to the Yellowstone National Park in Wyoming. The lands in the
project include Padre Island National Seashore in Texas, Castillo
de San Marcos National Monument in Florida, and the North Carolina
National Forest.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Energy and Natural Resources Committee held an
oversight hearing Thursday on the demonstration project and whether
it should be expanded or changed.
</P>
<P>
   An Interior Department study showed that the fees have not kept
visitors away from the demonstration sites. Indeed, visitation at
the 312 sites increased from about 243 million in 1996 to 256
million in 1998. That's about the same rate of increase as at sites
where the new fees were not imposed.
</P>
<P>
   However, committee members and witnesses agreed the program does
have problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``At Mount St. Helens in Washington, there are fees for
everything one can imagine,'' complained Sen. Craig Thomas,
R-Wyoming. ``The private sector, as in Disneyland, learned long ago
that paying once at the gate obtained a great deal of customer
satisfaction and good will.''
</P>
<P>
   Committee Chairman Frank Murkowski, R-Alaska, warned that
participating agencies are not cooperating in some common areas _
causing visitors to pay overlapping fees. There is little
consistency in fee structure, he said, with some parks charging a
single entrance fee and others taking additional costs on
everything from film to interpretative hikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing will destroy this program faster than over-achieving
greedy managers,'' said Murkowski. ``Visitors should be given the
opportunity to rest their wallets from time to time.''
</P>
<P>
   The GAO study also showed problems with distribution of the new
revenues. The program requires that at least 80 percent of the
money be spent at the site where it's generated. Advocates say the
money is needed because of a maintenance and repair backlog that
has grown steadily in an era of tight federal budgets.
</P>
<P>
   More spending flexibility may be needed, the GAO said, because
some popular sites are collecting enough fees to fix their backlog
while less visited places are falling further behind. However,
surveys show that visitors want the fees put to work where they are
generated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Visitors and guests who are paying the higher fees fully
expect to see improvements in our parks, refuges and areas sooner
rather than later,'' warned Murkowski.
</P>
<P>
   Some outdoorsmen who pay the fees also had some ideas on the
issue.
</P>
<P>
   The program has ``almost led to a 'money grab' atmosphere within
each federal agency,'' complained Bob Jones, who takes tourists on
river trips in Canyonlands National Park and is president of the
Utah Guides and Outfitters Association. He said he now pays four
``overlapping fees'' for the same river trip.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Moreland, who represents the 232,000 easy riding members
of the American Motorcyclist Association, complained of multiple
fees being paid by off-highway riders at the Imperial Sand Dunes
Recreation Area in California.
</P>
<P>
   The sites should develop variable fees, said Derrick Crandall,
president of the American Recreation Coalition, whose members
produce products ranging from skis to tents to motorhomes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We find it astonishing and offensive that officials in
Yellowstone National Park have publicly labeled visitors criminals
when they give or resell still-valid passes to others _ yet have
taken no action to make passes available that are valid for less
than seven days,'' Crandall told the committee.
</P>
<P>
   But most witnesses said the program should be fixed rather than
abandoned.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
