<HEADER>
A2024 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PEANUTS-THEATER-REVIE     02-04 1132
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEANUTS-THEATER-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CHARLIE BROWN': YOUR SISTER'S GUTSY 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Two photos are being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.)  
 (Editors: Production notes at end of review)  
(DW) 
 By BEN BRANTLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Sally Brown is mad at the world, and if the world has
any sense at all, it will stay out of her way. Though still on the
fair side of 5, Sally has a highly developed sense of the injustice
and futility of life. Her indignation quotient is off the charts,
and her mighty bleat of a voice could bring down the walls of
Jericho. She is not, perhaps, a child you would want to shepherd
through an afternoon at the mall, but on a Broadway stage, she is
invaluable company.
</P>
<P>
   Sally Brown is portrayed by a small but definitely adult actress
named Kristin Chenoweth, who is giving one of those break-out
performances that send careers skyward in the revival of ``You're a
Good Man, Charlie Brown,'' which opened Thursday night at the
Ambassador Theater. She is also the only significant reason for
adults unaccompanied by children to sit through this mild-mannered,
sticky evening of skits and songs inspired by Charles M. Schulz's
long-running ``Peanuts'' comic strip.
</P>
<P>
   You see, Ms. Chenoweth, playing someone who wasn't even a
character in the original Off-Broadway hit of the late 1960s, is
terrifically appealing, but her Sally is simply too strident, too
angry, too agitated to ever be considered merely cute. (Considering
she wears a mop of Shirley Temple curls, this is an
accomplishment.)
</P>
<P>
   A lack of conventional cuteness was what allowed Schulz's
dot-eyed, round-headed creatures to conquer America in the 1950s.
Admittedly, a comic strip that features a dog who fantasizes about
being a World War I flying ace can be long on whimsy. But Schulz
also cannily created a world of children shaped by an age of
anxiety. The atomic bomb, Sigmund Freud and Albert Einstein were
not usual topics of conversation in ``Peanuts,'' but depression,
rejection, sour stomachs and the meaninglessness of existence were.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Brown, the ultimate loser, the boy who never received a
Valentine or won a Little League baseball game, spoke directly to
the nagging fears and self-doubts that many adults were beginning
to realize they would never outgrow. Yet he and his friends never
seemed just like grown-ups in kids' clothing. They were deliciously
sui generis figures in a self-contained universe. Translating them
from pen and ink drawings into flesh and blood performances would
seem to be impossible.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, according to most reviews, this metamorphosis was
achieved winningly when ``You're a Good Man, Charlie Brown,'' with
songs by Clark Gesner and with Gary Burghoff (who went on to play
Radar in the film and television versions of ``MASH'') in the title
role, opened Off Broadway at the tiny Theater 80 St. Marks in 1967.
A ``small miracle'' was how Walter Kerr, writing in The New York
Times, described the show. ``Almost everything works,'' Kerr went
on to say, ``because almost everything is effortless.''
</P>
<P>
   Effortless, unfortunately, is exactly what this new incarnation,
staged by Michael Mayer, is not. The production has been revised to
incorporate new material from Schulz's strips, and, while most of
Gesner's original score remains, it has been extensively rearranged
by Andrew Lippa, who also has written several new songs. The
problem isn't that the new material fails to mesh with the old, or
even that the original material feels particularly dated, though it
does bring to mind the zippy, quick-take revue format made popular
by the old ``Laugh-In'' television series.
</P>
<P>
   The real problem is a matter of scale. ``Charlie Brown'' was
created for an intimate space, and it is telling that when it
reopened on Broadway in 1971, many critics felt that much of its
original charm had evaporated. For this version, the ever-inventive
designer David Gallo has filled the Ambassador stage with
neon-crayon-color sets (matched by Michael Krass' costumes) that
give an electric jolt to the lines of Schulz's fabled
draughtsmanship. But there's an uncomfortable feeling of dead air
that the cast, led by Anthony Rapp (of the original ``Rent'') as
Charlie, must work much too hard to fill.
</P>
<P>
   Songs that were created as droll, low-key character portraits
have been reconceived as showstoppers, and the frail, winsome
little bodies of these numbers just aren't up to the job. When
Linus (B.D. Wong) sings a duet with his famous security blanket,
which has been wired to dance on its own, the sequence has a
flailing, improvised quality that is the stuff of actor's
nightmares.
</P>
<P>
   So does the song in which Charlie Brown wrestles with a
recalcitrant kite. What we should be focusing on is the poor
fellow's exasperation, his sense of being eternally at odds with
his environment. Yet somehow, all I could see was the bobbing kite
string that stretched across the stage. Charlie Brown himself might
as well have been invisible.
</P>
<P>
   This has something to do with Rapp's very strange conception of
his part. The actor, who was a dynamo in ``Rent,'' plays Charlie
Brown not as an aggrieved, complaining target of the slings and
arrows of daily life, but as a passive, saintly innocent.
</P>
<P>
   With his fixed beatific smile, his hair flattened against his
head and his eyes as sweetly glazed as a Krispy Kreme doughnut, he
suggests those clean-cut young people who approach you in airports
with religious pamphlets. This is not a Charlie Brown that anyone,
except possibly some New Age cultist could identify with, and there
is a hole where the show's empathic center should be.
</P>
<P>
   As Schroeder, the Beethoven-loving pianist, Stanley Wayne Mathis
seems comparably hard-pressed to find any real character to play.
As the titanically crabby Lucy Van Pelt, Ilana Levine gives a
shtick-driven performance, hitting each word and each note as
though with a mallet.
</P>
<P>
   Wong, as a lisping Linus, fares better, though he occasionally
slides into preciousness. Roger Bart, in the plum role of Snoopy,
the charismatic beagle, incorporates some delightful doglike
mannerisms. He does a nice job with the ``Red Baron'' number, which
also offers the evening's most ingenious visual effects. But his
hymn to the joys of eating, ``Suppertime,'' which should bring down
the house, is deflatingly oversold in both the staging and the
orchestration.
</P>
<P>
   Mayer has proven himself a solid and resourceful director of
dramas with the recent Broadway productions of ``A View From the
Bridge'' and ``Side Man.'' But as he demonstrated in his staging of
``Triumph of Love,'' he is clearly less comfortable with musicals.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Schulz's characters, though cartoons, are a sly and subtle lot,
and they don't benefit from hard-sell performances. Their sweetly
neurotic souls get lost when their interpreters are beaming away
like an Up With People chorus. (The show's signature song,
``Happiness,'' is, and always was, pure syrup.)
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, it was Mayer who was largely responsible for
shaping the interpolated role of Sally and for casting Ms.
Chenoweth in the part, and for that he deserves much credit.
Debating relentlessly with an unseen school teacher about receiving
the grade of a C on her wire-hanger sculpture, scowling at a
hopelessly tangled jump rope or vengefully explaining to Snoopy
that he is at the bottom of the family's chain of command, Ms.
Chenoweth's Sally finds a mega-volt show-business energy in life's
unresting siege of frustrations.
</P>
<P>
   This is all conveyed through postures that amazingly replicate
the stances of Schulz's drawn characters without seeming stiff (her
accusatory extended arm is divine), and her shiny, perfectly
pitched voice seems a natural extension of her physical presence.
</P>
<P>
   Watching her here is what it must have been like to catch a
novice named Bernadette Peters lighting up a musical spoof called
``Dames at Sea'' 30 years ago. Ms. Chenoweth has appeared in New
York before, most notably in ``Steel Pier'' and Encores' concert
version of ``Strike Up the Band,'' but this is the part that should
seal her reputation. This glow cast by a star-in-the-making gives a
real Broadway magic to a show that otherwise feels sadly shrunken
in a Times Square theater.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   ``YOU'RE A GOOD MAN, CHARLIE BROWN''
</P>
<P>
   Based on the comic strip ``Peanuts'' by Charles M. Schulz;
directed by Michael Mayer; music, book and lyrics by Clark Gesner;
musical supervision, arrangements and additional material by Andrew
Lippa; choreography by Jerry Mitchell; sets by David Gallo;
costumes by Michael Krass; lighting by Kenneth Posner; sound by
Brian Ronan; orchestrator, Michael Gibson; music director, Kimberly
Grigsby; production manager, Arthur Siccardi; production stage
manager, James Harker; general manager, Nina Lannan Associates;
produced in association with Larry Payton. Presented by Michael
Leavitt, Fox Theatricals, Jerry Frankel, Arthur Whitelaw and Gene
Persson. At the Ambassador Theater, 219 West 49th Street,
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Kristin Chenoweth (Sally), Stanley Wayne Mathis
(Schroeder), B.D. Wong (Linus), Roger Bart (Snoopy), Ilana Levine
(Lucy) and Anthony Rapp (Charlie Brown).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-04-99 1658EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990204.0258 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 17:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2028 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOMEVIDEO-2TAKES-NYT &LR;      02-04 0660
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMEVIDEO-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON WHAT IS NEW IN HOME VIDEO 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Black Films By Mail &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Movies by black directors and about black subjects have
difficulty surfacing in Hollywood and even in the independent film
world, so it's interesting to run into all kinds of them, annotated
by the hundreds in ``Facets African-American Films on Video'' from
Facets International, the Chicago mail order company.
</P>
<P>
   Several hundred titles have been organized into two dozen
categories, beginning with feature films. ``Boyz 'n the Hood''
(1991), directed by John Singleton, the first black filmmaker to be
nominated for an Oscar (at 23 he was also the youngest), and
``Menace II Society'' (1993), by Allen and Albert Hughes,
21-year-old twins, are representative of the better-known titles
among the 150 listed.
</P>
<P>
   But there are also numerous offbeat, smaller films of several or
more years ago. Set in Chicago, Akoya Chenzira's ``Alma's Rainbow''
(1994) is a lively coming-of-age film about a strait-laced beauty
parlor owner, her teen-age daughter and the wild Las Vegas-style
relative who comes to put them on the right track with the opposite
sex. ``A hip urban sitcom,'' Stephen Holden wrote in The New York
Times.
</P>
<P>
   In Wendell B. Harris' ``Chameleon Street'' (1991), a mannerly
good-looking young black man (played by Harris) passes himself off
as a surgeon, a lawyer and some other things. ``Harris demonstrates
that he's a triple-threat new filmmaker of original and eccentric
talent,'' Vincent Canby wrote in his review in The Times. If
Harris' career hasn't been marked by high-profile productions
since, ``Chameleon Street'' still stands up on cassette.
</P>
<P>
   The filmmaker Haile Gerima has three acclaimed small films to
her credit in the Facets catalog. Full of rich street vernacular,
``Bush Mama'' (1976) depicts the struggles of a woman on welfare
who is trying to hold her family together in Los Angeles. ``Ashes
and Embers'' (1983) is the story of an Vietman veteran who
overcomes his bitterness with the help of his grandmother and his
friends.
</P>
<P>
   In Ms. Gerima's ``Sankofa'' (1994), the most successful of the
three films at the box office, a fashion model on a photo shoot in
Ghana time travels back to the horrors of slavery in the plantation
South. ``No viewer can avoid the discomforting questions this film
eloquently raises,'' Caryn James wrote in The Times.
</P>
<P>
   A section devoted to early black cinema includes films by such
white directors as Otto Preminger (``Carmen Jones,'' 1954) and King
Vidor (the musical ``Hallelujah!,'' 1929), studies like the
documentary ``Midnight Ramble,'' about black film from 1910 through
World War II, and the huge ``African-American Film Heritage series,
with 10 features by black directors dating back to Oscar Micheaux's
day, in the 20s. Blaxploitation is well covered with more than 50
titles (including ``Sheba, Baby'' and about everything else Pam
Grier starred in during the 70s).
</P>
<P>
   From there the categories range widely: apartheid, writers and
artists, jazz, blues and rhythm-and-blues, opera, rock and rap.
Information: (800) 331-6197. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Antz
</P>
<P>
   Portraying an ant, Woody Allen wallows in a different angst. As
the middle child in a family of five million, Z (the voice of
Allen) tells his therapist that he's feeling insignificant. A
larger destiny awaits, however, after Z falls in love with Princess
Bala (Sharon Stone).
</P>
<P>
   With the colony threatened by termites, the ant General Mandible
(Gene Hackman) decides to defend the species by sacrificing lowly
ants of Z's ilk. For reasons he doesn't fully embrace, Z finds
himself cast as savior in an overplotted computer-animated story
that, Janet Maslin wrote in The New York Times, ``works best just
showing off its prodigious voice talent.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1998. Dream Works. $26.99. 83 minutes. Closed captioned. PG.
Release date: Feb. 9. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Rounders
</P>
<P>
   By day, Mike McDermott (Matt Damon) is a clean-cut law student.
At night he bets his tuition in big-stakes poker games with a
Russian gambling kingpin (John Malkovich) and others. In a world of
secret thrills, the Worm (Edward Norton), a grinning, reckless
friend from childhood, makes seductively good company for a
succession of late-night card scams.
</P>
<P>
   Though John Dahl's film ``finally adds up to less than meets the
eye, what does meet the eye (and ear) is mischievously
entertaining'' (Maslin). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1998. Miramax. $107.37. 120 minutes. Closed captioned. R.
Release date: Feb. 9. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Merry War
</P>
<P>
   In the 1930s, lyrical souls fed themselves on the narcissistic
conceit that the world exists for the poetry that they poured into
slender volumes. Subscribing to this illusion, Gordon Comstock
(Richard E. Grant) is so taken by a favorable review of his first
book of verse in The Times of London (never mind that the review
was written by his editor) that he quits his day job and goes off
to what he presumes is a ready-made position of rank in the world
of letters.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of Robert Bierman's film, based on George Orwell's
novel ``Keep the Aspidistra Flying,'' works to disabuse him of that
notion in a charming period piece ``directed with a fine awareness
of the story's satirical nuances'' (Stephen Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1998. A-Pix. $94.98. 100 minutes. PG-13. Release date: Feb. 9. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clay Pigeons
</P>
<P>
   After watching his friend shoot himself, young Clay (Joaquin
Phoenix) disposes of the body and lands himself amid some sly
cowboys and vixens in contemporary Montana. Clay's trouble is that
he's too nice, which doesn't put him on the most secure footing
with a weird new friend (Vince Vaughn), especially after a woman's
body bobs to the surface of a fishing hole.
</P>
<P>
   As fatalities escalate, Clay becomes a suspect in serial
killings. That he's not such a country bumpkin is duly noted by a
sarcastically urbane FBI agent (Janeane Garofolo), but then David
Dobkin's ostentatiously hip, spiffily photographed genre spoof
``delights by confounding expectations'' (Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1998. Polygram. $106.99. 104 minutes. R. Release date: Feb. 9. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other new titles of interest, some of which may have had a
theater release at one time, appeared on television or been on
videocassette in earlier editions. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GLORIA. Sharon Stone is Gloria in the remake now in theaters,
but this is the original John Cassavetes film, recently reissued on
tape, with Gena Rowlands as agangster's girlfriend who angers the
mob when she takes charge of a neighborhood child whose parents
have been killed by hitmen. 1980. Columbia Tri-Star. $14.99. 123
minutes. PG.
</P>
<P>
   UNDERGROUND. Winner of the Palme d'Or at the Cannes
International Film Festival in 1995, Emir Kusturica's feverish,
whimsical allegory traces the eventual disintegration of Yugoslavia
from the Nazi invasion in 1941 through the fall of communism and
the war in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   The story revolves around Blacky (Lazar Ristovski) and Marko
(Miki Manojlovic), two lusty, boozing buddies who get rich selling
arms to the resistance and later hide themselves away for years in
a cellar crowded with refugees. Kusturica's vision of tragedy and
optimism has been realized with his characteristically ``fanciful
magicianship,'' Janet Maslin wrote in The New York Times. 1995. New
Yorker. 167 minutes. Serbo-Croatian with English subtitles. No
rating.
</P>
<P>
   GET A LIFE! Chris Elliott, a memorable supporting player in
``Something About Mary,'' stars in this 1990 sitcom about an
eccentric 30-year-old paper boy who lives with his mother and
father, played by Bob Elliott, Chris' real-life father and the Bob
of the legendary radio pair Bob and Ray. Considered fairly bizarre
by sitcom standards, the show lasted only a few months, but the
memory lingers on a pair of tapes with two episodes each. Rhino.
$12.95 a cassette. Information: (800) 432-0020.
</P>
</TEXT>
