<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT </SLUG>
  
 `THE '60s': A SOFT-HEADED, UNCONVINCING MINISERIES  
 (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.)  
 (bl)  
 By CARYN JAMES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Don't be alarmed by that fetid scent coming from the direction
of your television; it's borne on the winds of February sweeps,
when ratings determine future advertising dollars and viewers are
assaulted by stink bombs in the shape of insultingly bad movies and
mini-series.
</P>
<P>
   This February promises to be especially foul, loaded with
unintentionally loony versions of recent history. (A Sonny and Cher
biopic is creeping up; consider yourself warned.)
</P>
<P>
   The next expensive dud arrives Sunday with NBC's mini-series
``The '60s.'' The decade is timely for all sorts of good reasons.
On the serious side, the geological shifts of the '60s are at the
root of the culture war dividing the country now. More frivolously,
it might be fun to look back from the distance of three decades at
that garishly colorful period. And by now there is a generation of
adults too young to have any memory of the period at all. Their
reaction to this flavorless, microwavable version is likely to be,
``Huh?''
</P>
<P>
   Spread over two nights, ``The '60s'' mixes historical events
with fictional characters, as trite images from the period zoom by.
The first installment, on Sunday, is not painfully unwatchable,
just dull. At the center of the series is the fictional Herlihy
family of Chicago: an overbearing dad, housewife'60s mom and three
teen-age children who in 1962 are ripe for every obvious
transformation the decade offers.
</P>
<P>
   Katie gets kicked out of a high school dance for doing the
twist. Brian joins the Marines. When he says, ``It's OK, Ma, we're
not even at war with anybody,'' it doesn't take a clairvoyant to
know he'll end up in Vietnam. Michael heads off to college, becomes
an anti-war activist and finds his true love, Sarah, the only woman
thoughtful enough to wear pearls to a protest meeting.
</P>
<P>
   It's on the second night, when the series gets to 1967, that it
becomes conspicuously idiotic. The installment begins in
Haight-Ashbury, where the troubled Katie had fled. The overwrought
scene features so many feathers and flowers in the hair, so many
beads and fringe, so many Afro wigs and street performers in mime
makeup, it resembles a come-as-the-'60s Halloween party.
</P>
<P>
   And the deeper into the counterculture the series goes, the
sillier it becomes; it's hard to depict a counterculture when no
believable culture has been defined in the first place. How is
banning the twist supposed to lead to marching on the Pentagon, or
to characters shouting phrases like ``Up against the wall,
mother!''?
</P>
<P>
   Racial segregation is the one element dealt with here that
clearly sparked '60s activism. But a subplot about a black family
makes those characters mere tokens. In the first episode, Willie
Taylor leads a voter registration march. In the second, his son
becomes a Black Panther. In both, whenever the plot turns to the
Taylors, it seems surprising they are still around in this story.
</P>
<P>
   All the grittiness of the period has been sanitized out of this
mini-series, which doesn't even have the nerve to borrow from
authentic '60s movies like ``Easy Rider.'' Instead, there are so
many techniques stolen and watered down from Oliver Stone films
that he could sue: the scenes in Vietnam borrow the close-ups and
elegiac music of ``Platoon''; when Brian returns from the war, he
seems to have inherited Tom Cruise's wardrobe, hair and mustache
from ``Born on the Fourth of July.''
</P>
<P>
   Black-and-white news film depicts everyone from George Wallace
to Robert Kennedy. But black-and-white inserts of the fictional
characters seem pompous and silly rather than convincing.
</P>
<P>
   When some central characters, after many changes and
separations, are reunited at Woodstock, it may seem a sign of the
mini-series' peace-and-love attitude. But ``The '60s'' is too
soft-headed to be considered either an idealized or revisionist
view of the period.
</P>
<P>
   Like the most burnt-out '60s survivors, though, the series has
somehow maintained its taste in music. Songs from Bob Dylan, the
Byrds, Marvin Gaye and a raft of others are heard throughout, as
they were originally recorded. The soundtrack is more authentic,
lively and revealing than anything else in these four ludicrous
hours.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE '60s'
</P>
<P>
   NBC, Sunday and Monday night at 9 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lynda Obst, executive producer; Mark Piznarski, director; Bill
Couturie, Robert Greenfield and Jeffrey Fiskin, writers; Jim Chory,
producer. Produced by Lynda Obst Productions in association with
NBC Studios.
</P>
<P>
   CAST: Josh Hamilton (Michael Herlihy), Jerry O'Connell (Brian
Herlihy), Julia Stiles (Katie Herlihy), Bill Smitrovich (Bill
Herlihy), Annie Corley (Mary Herlihy), Leonard Roberts (Emmet
Taylor), Jordana Brewster (Sarah) and Charles Dutton (the Rev.
Willie Taylor).
</P>
</TEXT>
