<HEADLINE>
DAVIS' GRADUATION EXAM FACES HURDLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ Hispanic organizations and some Democratic
lawmakers are concerned that Gov. Gray Davis' plan to require high
school seniors to pass a graduation exam could cause minority
students to drop out of school.
</P>
<P>
   The concerns arose Wednesday during a legislative hearing on
Davis' four-part education package. The least controversial bill _
to boost elementary school reading programs _ easily passed the
Assembly Education Committee, but three other Davis bills are under
more intense negotiation.
</P>
<P>
   Although there is an extraordinary effort to pass the Democratic
governor's education reforms before April, lawmakers want to change
the high school test.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bill is certainly going to affect, more than anything
else, the Latino student population,'' said the Rev. Sal Alvarez,
with the National Association of Hispanic Priests and Deacons, who
spoke Wednesday before the Senate Education Committee. ``It could
have a very, very serious detrimental impact.''
</P>
<P>
   The Davis plan would require all students, starting in 2003, to
pass a test in math and English skills in order to graduate.
Students could take the test as early as the 10th grade, and take
it unlimited times _ with different questions each time _ until
they pass. At least 20 other states have similar systems.
</P>
<P>
   Alvarez said intensive tutoring and after-school programs should
be improved before students with limited English are forced to take
the test. One lawmaker suggested spending another double spending,
to $50 million, on an after-school program that began this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we raise the bar (for students), we also need to raise
the support,'' said Elena Soto-Chapa, statewide education director
for the Mexican American Legal Defense and Educational Fund.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Hilda Solis, D-El Monte, said, ``If we are demanding
education excellence, then we must provide the tools. ... I am
concerned that English-language learners are disproportionately at
risk of failing.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Jack O'Connell, D-San Luis Obispo, said he was planning to
offer several amendments to the test legislation, including
provisions to make sure special education students are treated
fairly and that the exam closely matches the curriculum taught in
schools.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Hart, Davis' education secretary, told the committee that
the governor ``has no interest in seeing large numbers'' of
students fail the test. But he added, ``The governor believes
strongly that if we have clear standards ... that students and
teachers can meet those standards.''
</P>
<P>
   About 1.3 million students in California public schools speak a
foreign language but little English, constituting 43 percent of the
nation's students with limited English proficiency. Spanish is
spoken by more than 1 million children in the state.
</P>
<P>
   The state faces a legal mandate to make sure minority students
don't fail the proposed high school graduation test at
disproportionate rates.
</P>
<P>
   In a landmark case brought by Chinese parents in San Francisco,
the U.S. Supreme Court ruled in 1973 that districts must take
necessary steps to ensure that students who lack English are able
to participate equally in classroom activities.
</P>
<P>
   But spending more money on tutoring and boosting education in
low-income schools may not be the whole answer, according to one
recent study.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government's largest education grant program, which
has provided $118 billion in the past three decades, has been
unable to meet its goal of narrowing the achievement gap between
rich and poor students, interviews and documents reviewed recently
by the Los Angeles Times showed.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Department of Education found that the extra computers,
tutoring and more than 132,000 teaching positions paid for by the
massive investment have been insufficient to close the gap in
reading and math performance between poor students and their more
affluent peers.
</P>
<P>
   ``From my perspective, it's difficult to dictate student
outcome,'' said state Sen. Tom Hayden, D-Los Angeles. ``Other
people say the school can turn everything around. The truth is
somewhere in between, but my bias is believing that it's social
conditions, racism and poverty, and not what goes on inside the
school.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
