<HEADLINE>
WOMEN MAKING PROGRESS AS PROFESSORS, BUT STILL LAG MEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE CARROLL and LYNN FRANEY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) _ ...the higher ranks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our situation is tied directly to our salary problems,'' said
Ron Downey, an assistant provost at K-State. Retaining women is
difficult, he said, because K-State's salaries are lower than the
salaries paid at other universities of similar size.
</P>
<P>
   Several administrators and faculty members at UMKC said the
environment there has become much more woman-friendly over the past
few years.
</P>
<P>
   Deans are trying to ensure that women are considered as
candidates to fill faculty job openings. Women who have children
and household responsibilities are less afraid to talk about them
because many male colleagues are taking on more household duties
themselves. With more women teaching on campus, there's a better
support network and a more welcoming atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the environment here now is superb. Of course, some
women faculty might have different opinions,'' said Marvin Querry,
executive dean//vice provost at UMKC. ``Historically there have
been cases where women were not treated fairly. But I would hope
it's getting more favorable. If problems exist, we try to correct
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Carla Klausner, a history professor at UMKC for more than 25
years, said she has seen ``a great deal of change here in the last
10 to 15 years.''
</P>
<P>
   She remembers getting out of graduate school and hearing that
some colleges just weren't hiring women. And she felt some
discrimination when she first came to UMKC, especially because
women weren't receiving equal pay.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, women professors have received special equity raises
to make salaries more equal, she said. And more women have been
hired.
</P>
<P>
   Another female professor at UMKC, Cathy Burnett, said higher
education is improved when more women teach, because they bring
fresh ideas to the classroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``I value diversity and I think that different voices are very
important,'' she said. ``It also challenges the traditional
curriculum and that is good for critical thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   At Rockhurst College, sociology professor Marilyn Carroll said
she thinks there are many reasons for the slower rate of promotions
and pay increases for women professors.
</P>
<P>
   Some women focus more on teaching than on research and
publishing articles, she said. Research often is highly favored in
tenure and promotion decisions, which may leave women behind.
</P>
<P>
   Some faculty and administrators said they believe the current
disparities should disappear as women gain more experience as
professors, sexist attitudes diminish in society as a whole, and
more women graduate with doctoral degrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there are going to be a lot more women, very
highly-qualified women, available for national searches,'' Querry
said. ``The pool's getting larger.''
</P>
<P>
   That may be, Gibson said, but the associations's study confirms
that women will have to work for parity in the academic workplace.
Equality will not come without some effort, she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-04-99 1717EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
