<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 17:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2080 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOMEN-PROFESSORS-2TAK     02-04 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-PROFESSORS-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN MAKING PROGRESS AS PROFESSORS, BUT STILL LAG MEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE CARROLL and LYNN FRANEY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) Women are making inroads as professors on college
campuses but still suffer disparities in pay and promotions, a
national study shows.
</P>
<P>
   In just under 25 years, the percentage of women faculty members
has increased from 22.5 percent to 33.8 percent, according to the
study released this week by the American Association of University
Professors. But many women are in lower-level positions such as
lecturers and instructors; only 18.7 percent of the top-ranked
category of full professors were women in 1997-98.
</P>
<P>
   The findings do not surprise faculty members in Kansas and
Missouri. At the University of Kansas, 14 female professors have
formed a caucus to figure out why women aren't rising more rapidly
in the ranks there.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not pounding our fists on the table,'' said KU law
professor Ellen Sward, one of the organizers. ``We are trying to be
cooperative. At the same time we are trying to be firm about things
we think need to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   The study lists a variety of reasons why women lag behind men:
from subtle discrimination, to traditionally lower expectations for
women to the strains of juggling career and family.
</P>
<P>
   At KU, 14 percent of the full professors employed in 1997 were
women. The numbers were similar around the region. Women made up 13
percent of the full professors at the University of
Missouri-Columbia and 16 percent at the University of
Missouri-Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   The study, published in the January-February issue of Academe,
indicates that more than half the women are in lower positions such
as lecturers and instructors.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997-98, the study said, women represented 55.6 percent of
lecturers; 58.6 percent of instructors and 46.8 percent of
assistant professors _ the profession's full-time entry level
position.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although women are rapidly increasing as a proportion of the
profession they tend to be relegated to less desirable positions at
lower salaries and at somewhat less prestigious institutions than
men,'' said study author Ernst Benjamin, director of research at
the American Association of University Professors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is some evidence of discrimination,'' Benjamin
said. ``But I think also there is a pattern that women are
systematically offered less desirable positions and they take them
because they are less mobile than men _ they have to stay where
their families are _ or they work hours that are more restricted,''
also because of their families.
</P>
<P>
   Women tend to cluster in low-paying fields, such as English,
instead of higher-paying disciplines such as engineering, he said.
And because many women are new entrants in academia, they tend to
have less seniority than men, which affects their salaries and
promotions, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the discrimination that goes on is subtle, said Mary
Gibson, national chairwoman of the association's Committee on the
Status of Women in the Academic Profession.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Subtle discrimination) is much more difficult to identify and
deal with,'' said Gibson, an associate professor at Rutgers
University in New Brunswick, N.J. ``It's done by absolutely
well-intentioned people who don't even recognize they are
discriminating.''
</P>
<P>
   Studies have shown that a male professor's research article will
be considered more valuable than a female's, even when the article
is exactly the same, Gibson said. It's difficult for society to
overcome the ingrained notion that men are more capable than women,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Sward said women in the KU caucus are aware that subtle
discrimination exists, as well as some that is more blatant. They
formed the caucus last semester, she said, after receiving
anecdotal evidence that ``some women were running into problems,
some (of which were) fairly serious.''
</P>
<P>
   Sward declined to provide specifics. However, she said, ``women
should be failing at same the rate as men in promotion and tenure
and they are not.'' Women are failing more often, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The caucus had its first public meeting last week. The women are
working with administrators to gather information on equal pay,
tenure and promotions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are all on the same side here,'' Sward said.
</P>
<P>
   Administrators at Kansas State, KU and UMKC said they believed
they are making progress in hiring more women and are trying to
promote more to the higher ranks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our situation... MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
