<HEADER>
A2087 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-     02-04 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FILMS FOR TEENS NOW STEAMY, NOT SCREAMY  
 SISSY SPACEK WILL RETURN IN 3 NEW MOVIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JAMES STERNGOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ How times change. A year ago the latest crop of
films aimed at teen-agers were mostly focused on ax murders and
other staples of the horror genre. That left some of the young
viewers and not a few parents squeamish. So this year the studios
are mining the teen-age market with none of that nasty horror;
instead, the films are filled with sex.
</P>
<P>
   Teen-agers are proving to be one of the most consistent and
profitable niches in the movie business. Box office receipts
overall are hitting record levels, but with the cost of major
pictures soaring, transforming ticket sales into profits has been
tough. But this is not so with teen-age films, many of which cost a
fraction of a standard studio release: less than $20 million
compared with close to $50 million. In addition, if these films
catch on, teen-agers will go to see them two, three or even more
times.
</P>
<P>
   So it is no surprise that far more films for the teen-agers are
being made. In fact, this year there's an avalanche. What is
surprising, though, is that many of those movies are R rated, or at
least more sexually explicit than teen-age movies in the past, as
they turn away from horror themes and focus instead on
coming-of-age stories.
</P>
<P>
   So far this year two films aimed at the youth market have done
exceedingly well. ``Varsity Blues,'' about a group of high school
football players, has earned almost $40 million in three weeks, and
``She's All That,'' about a high school nerd (played by Rachael
Leigh Cook, above), the prom and the flowering of love, brought in
an exceptional $16 million in its first weekend. ``Varsity Blues,''
which cost about $15 million to make, is R rated, and ``She's All
That,'' which cost about $9 million, is PG-13.
</P>
<P>
   Coming up later this year is a phalanx of other teen-age films
that involve similar coming-of-age plots, including ``Cruel
Intentions,'' with Sarah Michelle Gellar; ``Never Been Kissed,''
with Drew Barrymore; ``American Pie,'' with Natasha Lyonne; ``Next
to You,'' with Melissa Joan Hart, and two with ensemble casts,
``200 Cigarettes'' and ``Ten Things I Hate About You.'' And that is
just a sampling.
</P>
<P>
   Warren Zide, one of the producers of ``American Pie,'' a
Universal Pictures release about a group of high-school students
who decide they must lose their virginity by prom night, expressed
delight that the movie had an R rating.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really feel like some of the funniest things that happen in
high school are R rated,'' said Zide of the movie, which is
scheduled for release May 28. ``We felt like the marketplace was
shifting and that the audience wanted an R rated picture.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that the film, which cost about $11 million, initially
had the even more restrictive NC-17 rating, and that certain
scenes, including one that depicts a woman masturbating, had to be
modified three times before the R rating was obtained.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Tollin, the producer of ``Varsity Blues,'' said the
filmmakers believed that an R rating was necessary for the movie to
be realistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt pretty strongly that for the real issues kids deal
with, and the real way they talk in the locker room, it had to have
this rating,'' Tollin said. He added that there had been some talk
of watering down a few scenes, like one at a strip club, but that
the idea had been rejected, and that, so far at least, the strong
box office results had confirmed the decision.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Tollin emphasized that the movie had not been made
because of market research. ``You get in trouble when you try to
pinpoint trends,'' Tollin said. ``You have to do stories you really
like. The trend away from horror and to these other films is
undeniable this year, but it can't be planned.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Levy, one of the producers of ``She's All That,'' said
the extent of the movie's success so far had left him stunned.
``Shocked is the word,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But he said the success was particularly gratifying because it
had been so hard to get some studio executives to move away from
horror pictures. ``There were a lot of naysayers,'' Levy said.
</P>
<P>
   He pointed out that coming-of-age movies for teen-agers have
been made before; for example, ``The Breakfast Club'' and ``St.
Elmo's Fire'' were popular in the '80s. This time around, he said,
the movies are ``a little hipper, a little more edgy.'' But, he
added, ``They're still about romance.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What we tried to do in our movie was to look at our market and
to update the romantic comedy,'' said Levy, who has produced other
youth market movies like ``Jane Austen's Mafia,'' ``A Kid in
Aladdin's Court'' and ``The Last Time I Committed Suicide.''
``Definitely there was resistance at first because horror was so
big.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that television has introduced a new generation of
actors, invigorating the teen-age movie genre.
</P>
<P>
   ``As television has created newer and younger stars, it has
created recognition and a new platform,'' he said. ``It's not all
Tom Cruise movies. They want the new faces, and we're giving them
the new people.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Freckle-Faced Mom
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when her straight-from-the-plains,
freckle-faced charm seemed to define a certain kind of cinematic
character. Sissy Spacek created some of the more memorable roles of
the 1970s and '80s, noteworthy for their straightforward
soulfulness (except when she played Pinky Rose, the nasty piece of
work who double-crosses her best friend in Robert Altman's ``Three
Women'' in 1977).
</P>
<P>
   Her efforts won her five Oscar nominations between 1976 and 1986
and one statue for best actress, for her role as Loretta Lynn in
``Coal Miner's Daughter'' in 1980. But not long after, Ms. Spacek
started to fade from feature films and did only occasional
television roles. Until now.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Spacek is suddenly back, appearing in two movies with a
third on the way, and she is doing parts that push her into new
terrain.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the biggest change is her role as Helen, the tipsy,
whacky but well-meaning mother of Brendan Fraser's character in the
forthcoming comedy from New Line ``Blast From the Past.'' The film
opens Feb. 12.
</P>
<P>
   She is also in Paul Schrader's ``Affliction,'' in which she
plays Margie, the girlfriend of Nick Nolte's character. And she has
a dramatic role in ``The Straight Story,'' David Lynch's next
movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really haven't a clue what my last movie was before this
group,'' said Ms. Spacek, who still speaks with the strains of her
native Texas, although she now lives on a farm in Virginia. ``I
can't even remember. When you have as long a career as I've had,
you disappear for a while. But then I think somebody said, `What
happened to her?'''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Spacek conceded that at 49, few interesting roles were
coming her way. But she also said that once she married the
production designer Jack Fisk, settled down with him and had
children _ her daughters are now 16 and 10 _ ``honestly, that
became my focus, and it still is.''
</P>
<P>
   She said several things had drawn her back. For one, the
director and co-writer of ``Blast From the Past'' is Hugh Wilson,
her neighbor in Virginia. For another, she said, she relished the
opportunity to do a loopy comedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is way, way, way against type,'' she said. ``I'm thought
of as a dramatic actress, and I just thought I might not have a
chance to do something like this again.''
</P>
<P>
   She added that despite her enthusiasm for the part, she found it
tough to switch gears.
</P>
<P>
   ``Comedy is much harder than drama for me,'' she admitted. ``We
do drama every day of our lives. Comedy is hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Her role in ``Affliction'' is a more traditional dramatic part,
which she said she took largely to work with Schrader.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Spacek added that, since ``Blast From the Past'' follows the
lives of a family that disappears into a backyard bomb shelter
during the Cuban missile crisis, up to the present day, she got to
age 35 years. ``That's the part I enjoyed the most,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She said that while she was grateful for this flurry of
opportunities, she was also glad to be emerging in another new
role, as a stage mother. Her 16-year-old daughter, Schuyler, is
about to act in her first picture, and Ms. Spacek will accompany
her to the set in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to try to just watch and offer encouragement,'' she
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
