<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUGGENHEIM SHRINKS IN SOHO  
 ONE MOBILE MOBILE  
 GETTY GOES SHOPPING  
 GOING PUBLIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Since the Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum opened its
SoHo branch six and a half years ago, there has been speculation
about how the 27,000 square feet of exhibition space would be used,
how popular its programs would be and whether the museum could
afford the high rent in SoHo.
</P>
<P>
   The speculation continues. After months of rumors, the museum
has closed the SoHo branch. But only temporarily, it says, while
the space is reconfigured. Once that is finished, the museum will
shrink by about 7,000 square feet.
</P>
<P>
   One criticism of the Guggenheim SoHo has been that visitors
entered through the museum's store in the southeast corner of the
building, which is on Broadway at Prince Street. To reduce
operating costs, Guggenheim officials said, the museum's southern
end will now be rented out to a commercial venture, yet to be
determined.
</P>
<P>
   The museum entrance on Broadway will move to the north, where
the ground floor exhibition gallery has been, with a second
entrance on the Mercer Street side of the building. The Guggenheim
bookstore will occupy half of the space, on the Broadway side; the
other half, on the Mercer side, will remain as galleries.
</P>
<P>
   Upstairs, the exhibition space will remain the same, and the
museum offices will stay on the third floor and a portion of the
fourth.
</P>
<P>
   When the SoHo branch opened, attendance was projected to be
about 250,000 a year. Judy Cox, a deputy director of the
Guggenheim, said that the branch had actually attracted 125,000 to
200,000 visitors a year and that it had been just about breaking
even most years. The reduction of 7,000 square feet will reduce the
museum's operating costs, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``With our expansions internationally we have more resources for
our large-scale exhibitions,'' Ms. Cox said. ``So we don't have the
needs we used to for SoHo.''
</P>
<P>
   Plans call for reopening the museum in May or June, Ms. Cox
said, but the first exhibition in the new configuration has yet to
be determined. The museum says it still plans to use its SoHo space
to show the permanent collection and to organize shows that explore
the relationship between art and technology.
</P>
<P>
   The store will open sooner, around March 15.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Cox declined to comment on the Guggenheim's interest in
building a huge museum in Manhattan that would be designed by Frank
Gehry, the California architect responsible for the Guggenheim
Bilbao in Spain.
</P>
<P>
   Talks are believed to be under way with the city and state about
building the new museum on a portion of Pier 40, a state-owned
15-acre site along the Hudson River off Houston Street. Museum
officials are also looking at other Hudson River sites. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What has happened to the 1959 Calder mobile that for 40 years
hung from the ceiling of the Chase Manhattan Bank branch at Park
Avenue and 55th Street? Manuel E. Gonzalez, director of the Chase
Art Program, said his phone had been ringing off the hook with
dealers, collectors and curators asking where it had gone.
</P>
<P>
   The mobile, one of the earliest purchases commissioned by Chase
under the guidance of its former chairman, David Rockefeller, has
not been sold. Last week it was flown to the Museum of Fine Arts,
Houston, where it is a centerpiece of ``Art at Work: 40 Years of
the Chase Manhattan Collection.'' Part of the show is also at
another Houston site, the Contemporary Arts Museum.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were all surprised how quickly people noticed it was
gone,'' Gonzalez said. When the show ends on May 2, the Calder will
return to the bank. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The J. Paul Getty Museum in Los Angeles keeps shopping for Old
Masters. Last week it was a buyer at both Sotheby's and Christie's
Old Master sales in New York.
</P>
<P>
   At Christie's, the Getty paid $1.7 million for a group of 20
drawings, ``The Life of Taddeo Zuccaro'' (circa 1590), drawn by the
artist's brother, Frederico.
</P>
<P>
   The museum also bought Coecke's ``Sacrifice at Lystra'' (circa
1534) at Sotheby's for $343,500. The drawing is a rare study for
one of nine tapestries devoted to the life of St. Paul, which are
considered to be among the highest achievements of the Flemish
Renaissance.
</P>
<P>
   The Zuccaro drawings document the toils of an artist and
culminate in Taddeo's first successful commission, to paint the
facade of the Palazzo Mattei in Rome.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the study Taddeo Zuccaro made of the Palazzo Mattei,''
said Lee Hendrix, the Getty's drawings curator. ``It's one of the
few surviving preparatory studies for his facade painting, which no
longer survives.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hendrix said the Coecke drawing was among the finest of the
artist's remaining designs for the tapestries depicting the life of
St. Paul. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Emerging artists who want to create public art works should mark
March 5 on their calendars. That's the deadline for submitting 10
slides of recent work, a resume and a brief statement of interest
to the Public Art Fund, the nonprofit organization that presents
projects around New York City. Applicants must live in New York
State.
</P>
<P>
   This is the fourth year the fund has sponsored an open call as
part of its In the Public Realm Program. Here is how it works:
Seven artists will be chosen by a panel of artists, critics and
arts professionals and paid $1,000 each to create a proposal for a
specific project.
</P>
<P>
   Three or four of these projects will be chosen for completion
over the coming year. Each winning artist gets an additional
$10,000 toward the realization of the project ($7,500 for
fabrication and installation and a $2,500 artist's fee).
Information: (212) 980-3942.
</P>
<P>
   Each artist selected will be asked to choose a part of the city
for the completed work. This spring, for example, Maria Elena
Gonzalez will create ``Floating Home'' at Coffey Park, adjacent to
Red Hook Housing in Brooklyn, which replicates a floor plan from
the apartment complex in the form of a flying carpet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
