<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 17:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2090 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEINER-ART-REVIEWS-NY     02-04 1051
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEINER-ART-REVIEWS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LAWRENCE WEINER': A TO Z, WITH ESTHETIC PUNCTUATION 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
 
(Attn: Holland)  By KEN JOHNSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Thirty years ago, Lawrence Weiner gave up painting
and made words the primary vehicle of his art. Along with
Conceptualist colleagues like Joseph Kosuth, Douglas Huebler and
Robert Barry, he insisted that communicating ideas mattered more
than creating esthetically appealing objects. Since then, Weiner,
who was born in 1942 and now divides his time between New York and
Amsterdam, has been presenting gnomic utterances on indoor and
outdoor walls as well as in the form of posters and books; he's
also produced movies and musical recordings.
</P>
<P>
   For reasons that remain obscure, his texts usually describe
relations in space between objects, sometimes to drolly
self-referential effect, as in a piece that reads, ``Many colored
objects placed side by side to form a row of many colored objects''
_ the objects being, of course, the letters of which the text is
made.
</P>
<P>
   Weiner's work has established him as a fixture of the
internationally institutionalized avant garde. He's particularly
popular in Europe. His signs are always instantly recognizable for
their clean, subtly chic design and eccentric syntax and
punctuation.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the cerebral austerity of what he does is as likely to
inspire puzzlement as illumination.
</P>
<P>
   Consider one of two installations at Marian Goodman Gallery
through Feb. 20, one of three exhibitions devoted to Weiner's work
now on view in New York. A survey of Weiner's posters is at Bound &AMP;
Unbound, and Leslie Tonkonow has a small show of drawings for
posters. The poster and drawing shows run through Feb. 27.
</P>
<P>
   His ``5 Figures of Structure,'' first executed in 1987, is a
sort of mural occupying four walls of the gallery. Five sentences
spelled out in simple, eight-or-so-inch-high black letters describe
five different arrangements of three slabs: ``One slab and another
slab rested against each other on top of a horizontal slab set into
the ground,'' for example. Across the room, arrangements of slabs
are diagrammed by black-outlined rectangles.
</P>
<P>
   To look at this work is to feel perplexed and almost punitively
deprived of esthetic gratification. What is the point of these
oblique descriptions? Do they refer to sculptures that might be
built, and, if so, why not build and show the sculptures?
</P>
<P>
   If language is supposed to be paramount, why must it be so
grimly unpleasant to read? Theory-minded viewers may find the
conceptual implications of this work fascinating, but a lot of
people are surely going to walk away with a shrug thinking they
don't belong to the highly specialized audience for which it seems
to be meant.
</P>
<P>
   The irony is that Weiner's turn to language was motivated by
radically democratic sentiments. Words and ideas, Weiner reasoned,
can be available to anyone, unlike traditional art objects. Anyone
who sees and reads one of his works, he has declared, becomes an
owner of it. This is doubtful; how many people who have seen and
even admired Weiner's work consider themselves owners or
shareholders of it?
</P>
<P>
   It does make sense, however, to think of Weiner as a kind of
public artist, as he himself does. Out in the world, writ large on
buildings, Weiner's texts may exert an interesting resistance to
semiotic business as usual. Passers-by who never ordinarily
patronize art galleries might stop and wonder, for example, at the
big letters on a military building in Vienna spelling ``Smashed to
pieces (in the still of the night).''
</P>
<P>
   In theory, at least, Weiner's interventions in the fabric of
ordinary life might bring about subtle shifts in collective
consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   Weiner's interest in the broad and cheap public distribution of
art has also resulted in an extensive body of poster work, the
subject of a survey at Bound &AMP; Unbound. Arranged to cover one large
wall, the 60 posters advance in a wide chronological wave from 1973
to 1997 and range from pieces that stand alone as artworks to
exhibition announcements to broadsides publicizing the 1980s rock
band New Order.
</P>
<P>
   What's most notable is the movement from spartan plainness to a
rich and poetic complexity. In the work of the last 10 years or so,
his design, typography and color compare favorably with the best
graphic design of early Russian or Dutch modernism.
</P>
<P>
   At the beginning, a yellowed page from 1973 bears an
uncompromisingly minimal, black text that reads, in part, ``With
relation to the various manners with various things: made suitable
to/for, put out of place to/for.''
</P>
<P>
   Near the end is a poster for a 1991 show at Leo Castelli
Gallery, in which black letters on a deep red field read ``Dropped
Stones'' and parentheses bracket each of four squares cut out of
the page, vacancies representing, perhaps, ``dropped stones.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking at the poster show, in conjunction with the show at
Tonkonow, where Weiner's elegant hand and exacting attention to
detail is evident in loosely diagrammatic drawings for posters, one
becomes convinced that whatever the philosophical interest of his
work, he surely has evolved into a superior formalist.
</P>
<P>
   Back at Marian Goodman, the other brand new installation
reflects the trend toward a more inviting formal and poetic
dimension seen in the later posters. Called ``A Basic Assumption,''
it's based on the idea, according to a gallery handout, ``that all
objects assume they are in the right place at the right time.''
Across the wall are arrayed a series of diagonally oriented
rectangles outlined alternately in metallic blue and metallic
orange paint.
</P>
<P>
   Every blue box is occupied by an orange text referring to the
location of some unspecified thing: ``Out of harm's way; a bit to
the side; more towards the light; relegated to the shadows,'' and
so on.
</P>
<P>
   For viewers who pause to meditate on this, the piece begins to
exude a persuasive psychological resonance, which is enhanced by
the optical play of complementary colors and the alternation of
vacancy and fullness.
</P>
<P>
   If you think of the unspecified object as the self, then you
begin to feel in the piece a certain tender emotional poignancy.
But if you still value art mainly for its visual possibilities, it
probably won't change your mind.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
