<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 17:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2095 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MELLOR-PHOTO-REVIEW-N     02-04 1179
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MELLOR-PHOTO-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
D.W. MELLOR: PHOTOGRAPHS WORTHY OF AN OLD MASTER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa.)  (Eds.: Exhibition notes are at the end of review.) 
(js) 
 By MARGARETT LOKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   D.W. Mellor has had several lives in photography. He began to
collect photographs in 1969, soon after receiving a degree in
economics. He ran a photography gallery in Philadelphia from 1979
to 1982. For 30 years he was a freelance photographer who took
mostly color shots. Since 1993 he has been working on his own
black-and-white photography, focusing on a genre that would have
daunted a lesser soul: still lifes inspired by the Old Masters.
</P>
<P>
   In his photographs, about a dozen of which are at the Yancey
Richardson Gallery in SoHo, Mellor shows a firm grasp of Old Master
components: darkness and light, rhythm and balance, texture and
geometry. A few choice dinner table objects are left casually but
artfully on a plain old wood table. The natural light picks out of
the enveloping darkness the glint in the glass, the shine in the
silver, the textures on the skin of fruits and vegetables, the
polish of the table.
</P>
<P>
   Mellor reproduces in precise, exquisite detail on photographic
paper what 17th-century painters recreated in precise, exquisite
detail on canvas. More astonishing is Mellor's ability to produce
black-and-white prints whose sumptuously subtle tonalities echo the
luminous colors one would expect in, say, an old Flemish still
life.
</P>
<P>
   Because they follow a set of formal stylistic conventions,
17th-century still lifes are superficially similar yet strikingly
dissimilar when viewed closely. At a glance Mellor's images appear
to have a sameness. Up close it's another matter.
</P>
<P>
   Take, for instance, ``Still Life With Conch Shell, Amsterdam''
(1998), ``Still Life With Florentine Glass and Two Glasses,
London'' (1997) and ``Still Life With Twist, Venice, Italy''
(1995). The objects in each of these are arranged in a kind of
triangular formation. But the internal dialogue of the images
differs among them.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a silver conch, an ornate metal goblet and a crystal
wineglass, the first of these images has an almost spartan feel, an
impression reinforced by three groupings spread sparingly along the
length of a table. On the left is a large empty metal platter with
a calligraphic twist of lemon peel balanced on its rim, the silver
conch placed behind the plate. The second grouping includes a
peach, a large toy marble, a wineglass, a goblet and a sugar
shaker. At the right of the image is a lone marble. Supplying a
note of age-old solidity is the edge of the table, the light
detailing the wood grain and every nick on it.
</P>
<P>
   The image taken in London, focusing as it does on an ornate
goblet in cut glass and silver, is a luxurious still life. Centered
in the picture is a cluster that also includes an elaborate but
smaller wineglass and a lemon half balanced on the rim of a silver
plate. To the left is a secondary cluster of a fluted glass, a
metal plate, a pear and grapes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Still Life With Twist,'' however, carries a jumbled message.
There is a lovely translucent sliced fruit in the foreground and
the textures of the other fruits are nicely captured. But a lemon
peel is much too artificially hooked from the lip of a wineglass
and around the stem of a metal goblet. And a small classical statue
of a nude leaning against a pear is a jarring touch.
</P>
<P>
   Such a strangely dissonant note also appears in ``Still Life
With Standing Fork, Pacific Palisades'' (1996). Lined up on a table
are grapes piled high in a reticulated silver basket, a peach on a
plate and an old fork standing on its tines. The tip of the fork
handle may be roughly aligned with the top of the basket handle,
but the balance in the image is off, and the fork improbably
standing on tippy toes is too contrived.
</P>
<P>
   But these are only a few minuses in a show that is mesmerizing
in its radiant stillness. The highlight is ``Still Life With Broken
Glass, Amsterdam'' (1998), with its superb balancing of textures
and the play of light on the various surfaces. On the same table
shown in ``Still Life With Conch Shell'' are a 17th-century
drinking glass, a reproduction of which is broken and lies on its
side against a metal plate with a single marble on it. Completing
the arrangement is a half-peeled lemon, its cut peel spiraling
toward a knife.
</P>
<P>
   The anomaly of the broken glass works here, its jagged fragments
a textural contrast to the whimsical curl of the lemon peel. Adding
a mysterious note is the reflection on the intact drinking glass,
which seems to indicate a long room with windows on either side.
</P>
<P>
   While Mellor's still lifes show the influence of Josef Sudek, a
number of whose still lifes are on view in a separate section of
the gallery, four of Mellor's assemblages included in this
exhibition can be said to be a homage to Frederick Sommer, one of
this century's most inventive photographers. Like Sommer, Mellor
photographs images he has created by combining elements from
assorted materials, including old etchings and found objects like
pieces of wood or plaster. Like Sommer's surreal assemblages,
Mellor's are puzzling at first sight and require close study.
</P>
<P>
   ``Les Taurocathaspies, Bryn Mawr'' (1997) includes segments from
an etching of boys on horses and bulls. Because the long and narrow
print was too large for Mellor's 8-by-10 view camera, he first cut
the etching into strips. Two years later, in an abandoned church in
Greece, he found a piece of wood whose painted surface had long
disappeared. The etching strips he wanted in his image fitted
exactly on the piece of wood.
</P>
<P>
   The Sommeresque energy is very evident in ``Les
Taurocathaspies,'' which shows the boys and their animals seemingly
riding upward on a rugged terrain. While boys and animals are
bathed in a light that is broken into shards, all about them is a
murky abstraction of black splotches interspersed here and there
with light gray parallel lines.
</P>
<P>
   Two 1996 companion pieces, also using fragments from etchings,
are ``Apollo, Bryn Mawr'' and ``Last Judgment, Bryn Mawr,'' which
powerfully sum up the story of Marsyas, a skilled flutist,
challenging Apollo to a contest and losing. As punishment, Apollo
had Marsyas skinned alive. Against a beautifully floating
background of indeterminate materials, the Greek god in ``Apollo''
is wildly triumphant, almost flying out of the picture, as a foot
steps out of one backdrop into another. By contrast, Marsyas in
``Last Judgment'' is a ghostly and blurred figure. Behind him is a
large X formed by the assembled portraits of nightmarish faces that
fill the rest of the image.
</P>
<P>
   These assemblages may seem radically different from the still
lifes. But both draw their inspiration from Old Master subjects,
and both are visual deceptions that reveal themselves only if the
viewer takes the time to stop and look.
</P>
<P>
   EXHIBITION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   D.W. MELLOR: IN SITU &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yancey Richardson Gallery &QL;
</P>
<P>
   560 Broadway, at Prince Street &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Through Feb. 20
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
