<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 17:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2104 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2TAKE     02-04 1176
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT REVIEWS OF NOTEWORTHY MOVIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: The word (Star) can be replaced by the symbol)  
 (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is a selective listing by critics of The Times of new or
noteworthy movies and film series playing this weekend in New York
City. (Star) denotes a highly recommended film or series. Ratings
and running times are in parentheses.
</P>
<P>
   Now Playing
</P>
<P>
   (Star) ``AFFLICTION,'' starring Nick Nolte, James Coburn, Willem
Dafoe, Sissy Spacek and Mary Beth Hurt. Directed by Paul Schrader
(R, 114 minutes). Nolte is devastating in the performance of his
career, as Wade Whitehouse, a New Hampshire loner fighting a losing
battle with demons from his past.
</P>
<P>
   Foremost among them: Coburn, terrifyingly authentic as the
drunken, abusive father who long ago cowed his sons into
submission. As directed by Schrader, this pure, unfettered
adaptation of Russell Banks' novel starts on a deceptively ordinary
note, then escalates into inexorable fury. Every little detail
matters. Ms. Spacek and Ms. Hurt expertly play the women who
trigger Wade's crisis (Janet Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   (Star) ``ANOTHER DAY IN PARADISE,'' starring James Woods and
Melanie Griffith. Directed by Larry Clark (R, 101 minutes). From
the director of the bruising and ominous ``Kids,'' this vibrant,
unapologetically seedy road movie is a virtual day at the beach.
</P>
<P>
   Clark's second feature may not have the sting of his first, but
it comes closer to establishing him as William S. Burroughs with a
swooping, pivoting movie camera, bringing bizarrely innocent
enthusiasm to material that might otherwise ooze druggy shock
value, and making decadence as basic as the weather. Woods, as a
junkie, thief and absurdly unlikely father figure, revels in this
full-throttle role (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   ``AT FIRST SIGHT,'' starring Val Kilmer and Mira Sorvino.
Directed by Irwin Winkler (PG-13, 128 minutes). In this overlong
and often desperately banal version of a case study reported by Dr.
Oliver Sacks, Kilmer plays a man whose nearly lifelong blindness
was suddenly alleviated by surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sorvino plays the bright-eyed New York career woman who
falls in love with him, then urges him to change his once-peaceful
life. But the film brings little more than case-study data to
communicating how this man's restored sight affected him, or what
made it a mixed blessing. Sample dialogue: ``Have you ever listened
to the rain? I mean, really (italics)listened?''(end italics)
(Maslin). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Star) ``CENTRAL STATION,'' starring Fernanda Montenegro,
Vinicius de Oliveira and Marilia Pera. Directed by Walter Salles
(R, 115 minutes). In this quiet, luminous Brazilian gem, a joyless
older woman crosses paths with an orphaned young boy. There's
plenty of room for sentimentality here, but the wonder of Salles'
film is all in the telling.
</P>
<P>
   As these characters develop a fractious bond, then embark on a
road trip that takes them vividly to Brazil's hinterlands in search
of the boy's father, Salles brings great tenderness and surprise to
the events that punctuate their journey. Ms. Montenegro's tough
bravura performance was one of last year's very best (Maslin). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Star) ``A CIVIL ACTION,'' starring John Travolta, Robert Duvall
and William H. Macy. Directed by Steven Zaillian (PG-13, 120
minutes). This story of a David-Goliath lawsuit against industrial
polluters, with Travolta first-rate as an ambulance chaser who
develops a conscience, could have been business as usual in the
legal thriller genre.
</P>
<P>
   But Zaillian's keenly observed, beautifully acted film, based on
Jonathan Harr's nonfiction best seller about a case in Woburn,
Mass., doesn't follow familiar formulas. It follows all the
surprises and frustrations of a story that was never black and
white and is all the better for its shades of gray. Duvall is
outstanding as a corporate lawyer full of wily tricks (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   (Star) ``THE GENERAL,'' starring Brendan Gleeson and Jon Voight.
Directed by John Boorman (not rated, 125 minutes). Boorman's best
and most stylish film in years is the deftly told story of Martin
Cahill. Nicknamed the General for his crime-plotting strategies,
this Irish gang leader and master thief is played with splendid
brio by Gleeson.
</P>
<P>
   Photographed gorgeously in black and white, the film tells of
his elaborate art and jewel heists, his unusual domestic
arrangement with his wife's sister and his singular difficulties
with the IRA and the law. Voight is outstandingly good as the
police detective who knows all of Cahill's tricks (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   (Star) ``HILARY AND JACKIE,'' starring Emily Watson and Rachel
Griffiths. Directed by Anand Tucker (R, 121 minutes). The parallel
biographies of the brilliant cellist Jacqueline du Pre (Ms.
Watson), who contracted multiple sclerosis at the height of her
career, and her slightly older sister, Hilary (Ms. Griffiths), a
talented flutist who gave up a professional career to marry and be
``ordinary,'' is one of the most insightful studies of sibling
rivalry ever filmed.
</P>
<P>
   Jacqueline may have won fame and glory, the movie says, but she
remained a desperately needy emotional child who had to have
everything Hilary had (including Hilary's husband). The film is
structured like a concerto, in three movements, the last of which
ends with Jackie's harrowing death in her sister's arms. The drama
is deepened by a soundtrack that makes expert use of Jacqueline's
signature piece, the Elgar Cello Concerto in E minor. Ms. Watson's
Jacqueline flames with an almost scary intensity (Stephen Holden).
</P>
<P>
   (Star) ``MY NAME IS JOE,'' starring Peter Mullan and Louise
Goodall. Directed by Ken Loach (R, 92 minutes). A splendid, feisty
performance by Mullan energizes this film about a recovering
alcoholic trying to rebuild his life. With humor and scrappy
intensity, Joe throws himself into coaching young athletes and
embarking tenuously on a love affair, only to find the expected
challenges to his new sobriety everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Loach's commitment to delineating social issues is accentuated
by the way his star breathes life into Joe and makes viewers root
for his success. Special bonus: this film breaks the
brogue-and-burr barrier by including helpful subtitles for the
overlapping, heavily Scottish-accented dialogue (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   ``PATCH ADAMS,'' starring Robin Williams and Monica Potter.
Directed by Tom Shadyac (PG-13, 110 minutes). As a maverick doctor
intent on making terminal patients laugh, Williams delivers a
little clowning and a lot of maudlin feel-good sentiment, along
with vulgarity left over from the filmmaker's ``Ace Ventura'' days.
</P>
<P>
   He also spends a lot of time being congratulated for his good
works, as the film's minor players are kept busy marveling at his
antics. The real-life story of this doctor may sound like a fine
excuse for Williams to cut loose, but the film version proves
narrow and predictable. Ms. Potter, with a nostrilly resemblance to
Julia Roberts, figures in a romantic subplot with a bizarre twist
(Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (Star) ``THE PRINCE OF EGYPT,'' starring the voices of Val
Kilmer, Ralph Fiennes, Sandra Bullock and Michelle Pfeiffer.
Directed by Brenda Chapman, Steve Hickner and Simon Wells (PG, 93
minutes). First came the great expectations for this animated
magnum opus from Dreamworks. Then came reality, in a film
struggling mightily to balance animated whimsy and biblical
stature.
</P>
<P>
   The upshot is an admirably worthy rendering of the Exodus story,
even if Moses must initially be seen as a playful young scamp.
Biblical plagues and miracles serve as special inspiration for the
animators' reality-bending ingenuity (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   (Star) ``RUSHMORE,'' starring Jason Schwartzman, Bill Murray and
Olivia Williams. Directed by Wes Anderson (R, 93 minutes). A dryly
hilarious portrait of the mogul as a young man, with Schwartzman a
real find as its perfectly horrid little hero, Max Fischer.
</P>
<P>
   Max's prep school, Rushmore Academy, does have a faculty, but
none of the grown-ups have anything like Max's natural authority.
Murray is sneakily fine as the steel tycoon and Rushmore benefactor
who happens to be on Max's own wavelength as they vie for the same
beautiful teacher. A particular treat for its skewed, outrageously
funny memories of a cutthroat boyhood (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   (Star) ``SHAKESPEARE IN LOVE,'' starring Joseph Fiennes, Gwyneth
Paltrow, Geoffrey Rush, Ben Affleck and Judi Dench. Directed by
John Madden (R, 113 minutes). A witty, sexy and merrily literate
delight, with an exhilaratingly clever premise that only gets
better as the film unfolds.
</P>
<P>
   The screenplay, originating as Marc Norman's brainstorm and
turned by Tom Stoppard into razor-sharp dialogue reminiscent of his
``Rosencrantz and Guildenstern Are Dead,'' dares to imagine
whatever it likes about the link between Shakespeare's artistic
passions and his mad yearning for a certain aristocratic beauty.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, this tirelessly inventive comedy envisions an
Elizabethan theater fraught with the same backbiting and conniving
we enjoy today, and has great fun presenting the creation of
``Romeo and Juliet,'' glitches and all. Fiennes and Ms. Paltrow
make a fine, tempestuous duo, and she gives the first great, fully
realized starring performance of her career (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   (Star) ``A SIMPLE PLAN,'' starring Bill Paxton, Billy Bob
Thornton and Bridget Fonda. Directed by Sam Raimi (R, 120 minutes).
This onetime cult horror director makes a flawless transition to
mainstream storytelling with a quietly devastating thriller. And
its fine cast plays out the consequences of a harmless-sounding
error in judgment that winds up leveling everything in its path.
</P>
<P>
   The catalyst is $4.4 million that literally falls out of the
sky, and Scott Smith's story proves how deadly the morality of
expediency can become. When you get the shivers watching this
wintry tale, which features an especially memorable performance
from Thornton, it won't be from the cold (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   ``STEPMOM,'' starring Susan Sarandon, Julia Roberts and Ed
Harris. Directed by Chris Columbus (PG-13, 120 minutes). A man's
ex-wife and new girlfriend lock horns over who can be nicer to his
two children, in a sudsy story made livelier by its two female
stars, both in appealingly high gear.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Roberts plays the nicest person ever to wear black to a
downtown photo shoot, while the especially fiery Ms. Sarandon plays
the suburban mother as mama lion. Even when the prospect of
mortality looms, the story manages to maintain its big, lavish look
and peculiar (under the circumstances) sense of fun. As in ``Home
Alone,'' Columbus directs with sunny indifference to reality,
medical, economic or otherwise (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   ``STILL CRAZY,'' starring Stephen Rea, Billy Connolly, Bill
Nighy, Helena Bergstrom, Juliet Aubrey and Jimmy Nail. Directed by
Brian Gibson (R, 96 minutes). Twenty years after they last dropped
acid in a Druid circle, the members of an over-the-hill English
rock band try to reunite, and the results are meant to be both
funny and heartwarming. Not an easy mix, unless Spinal Tap really
(italics)is(end italics) your idea of a band that needs a second
chance.
</P>
<P>
   Despite an extremely likable cast that fits right into the
spirit of things, the director of ``What's Love Got to Do With It''
and the writers of ``The Commitments'' don't drum up enough drama
or sustained humor to make the most of their premise. The cast is
cheery and game, the material hit-or-miss (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   ``THE THIN RED LINE,'' starring Jim Caviezel, Ben Chaplin, Nick
Nolte, Sean Penn and Woody Harrelson. Directed by Terrence Malick
(R, 166 minutes). From the first frame of this huge, drifting war
epic loosely derived from James Jones' Guadalcanal novel, it's
viscerally clear that Malick is back. The exquisite, oddly detached
visual style that made ``Badlands'' and ``Days of Heaven'' the most
beautiful films of the 1970s is instantly apparent here, even if
the narrative vagueness and brooding voice-overs are also familiar.
</P>
<P>
   The film sprawls, gets lost and occasionally delivers visual
poetry, the kind that could have been greatly helped by tighter
editing. Bottom line: no one who admired Malick's early work should
miss this. But those expecting anything simple will not find it
here (Maslin). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Film Series
</P>
<P>
   ``JAZZ ON FILM.'' Coming of age together in the 20th century,
jazz and film make an ideal union of artistic mediums. And
beginning Saturday, they will be celebrated at the American Museum
of the Moving Image in a festival that ranges over a variety of
filmmaking styles and draws on more than 60 years of Hollywood and
independent features, documentaries and animated films about jazz.
</P>
<P>
   At 2 p.m. Saturday, the legendary saxophonist Illinois Jacquet
will be on hand for the initial screening, ``Texas Tenor: The
Illinois Jacquet Story'' (1992), the fashion photographer Arthur
Elgort's collage of tour film, archival material and revealing
interviews.
</P>
<P>
   At 4:30 p.m., the attraction is Bruce Ricker's ``Last of the
Blue Devils,'' built around a Kansas City reunion of great jazz and
blues musicians, including Count Basie. Admission to the series,
continuing through Feb. 28 at the museum, 34-12 36th Street, at
35th Avenue in Astoria, Queens, is $8.50 for adults, $5.50 for
people over 65 and students with ID, $4.50 for children from 5 to
18 and free for children under 4. Information: (718) 784-0077
(Lawrence Van Gelder).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
