<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 17:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2108 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CROPPING-PHOTO-REVIEW     02-04 1054
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CROPPING-PHOTO-REVIEW-1000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CROPPING AND PICTURE MAKING': WHEN THE EMPHASIS IS ON SELECTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Exhibition notes are at end of review.) 
(js) 
 By VICKI GOLDBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Photography is so simple. You press a button 24 or 36
times, take the film to the photo shop and voila, you've got
pictures. Painting, on the other hand, is so complicated: all that
imagining and drawing and constructing something out of nothing on
a blank canvas. Well, maybe.
</P>
<P>
   In 1901, when photographers were extensively manipulating their
images to prove that their work was at the same level of difficulty
and skill as any other artists', George Bernard Shaw wrote that
photography had not attracted many artists earlier because
``artists were terrified by the difficulty and mystery of the
process, which, as compared with the common run of their daubing,
in which any fool can acquire a certain proficiency, certainly did
require some intelligence, some practical science and some
dexterity.'' He went on to say: ``The artists still have left to
them invention, didactics and (for a little while longer) color.
But selection and representation, covering 99 hundredths of our
annual output of art, belong henceforth to photography.'' Note,
please, the emphasis on selection.
</P>
<P>
   It is obvious but not often pointed out that one truly essential
difference between painting and photography is the heavy weight
photography puts on selection, or editing, whether or not
photographers have the edge in that. Painters and printmakers
certainly edit. They toss out, correct, overpaint finished canvases
that no longer satisfy. But there is only so much work even a
prolific painter can turn out, and after a point history does the
major editing of a painter's work, with a helping hand from
curators and collectors.
</P>
<P>
   Photographers are capable of taking hundreds of pictures in a
single day, especially with a motor drive, and can scarcely help
taking too many to print, much less publish. Editing is an
inescapable part of the craft.
</P>
<P>
   A small but tidy lesson in the way photographers work and some
of the different modes of editing, selection and determining which
image to present to the public is on hand in ``Cropping and Picture
Making: Kertesz, Man Ray, Weston and Winogrand'' at Pace
Wildenstein MacGill. With only 30 pictures in all (though one
``picture'' is a blown-up contact sheet with many images on it)
this show works as a basic demonstration of different approaches,
all of which involve heavy pruning of one sort or another.
</P>
<P>
   Garry Winogrand and Andre Kertesz both worked in ways almost
unthinkable for a painter. Winogrand, who is often quoted as saying
that he photographed to see what things looked like as photographs,
was constantly out in the street snapping, constantly experimenting
with the look of city life and the ability of a swift eye and lens
to write it down and make it new. (The first new book on Winogrand
in years, ``The Man in the Crowd,'' was recently published by
Fraenkel Gallery and Distributed Art Publishers.) He never even got
around to editing some thousands of images _ observations made in
passing and left in heaps and drawers. Very few if any artists have
ever done so many drawings in the same time span.
</P>
<P>
   He had both nothing and too much until he selected. Looking at
his contact sheet presents a puzzle that is part of the medium's
intrigue. The chosen picture is a reasonable choice, but to another
eye there are several others just as good, or maybe just as bad.
The criteria are not obvious, but the act of selecting is at least
as important as the act of releasing the shutter and perhaps more
so, as some of the time Winogrand seems to have been shooting so
fast and so intuitively that he scarcely had time to grasp what was
in the viewfinder. Painters seldom have this kind of material and
never this amount to edit down.
</P>
<P>
   Kertesz edited at another level and at times more radically. One
of his most famous pictures, ``Wandering Violinist'' (1921), turns
out to have been cropped, something not generally known. This does
not affect the quality of the image; it only tells us something
about the way Kertesz worked.
</P>
<P>
   The big surprise at the gallery is a well-known image of a
swimmer's head reflected in the water, shown next to the original
uncropped image. It turns out that Kertesz not only cropped out the
swimmer's hands holding onto a board but also flipped the negative
upside down, so that the reflection is on top and the face reads as
reflection. Painters occasionally crop paintings, too, but before
abstraction came along it would have been nearly impossible and
afterward unlikely that a painter would turn a detail upside down
and see it become one of the landmarks of his or her work.
</P>
<P>
   Cropping is a way of life for some photographers. Walker Evans
even cut some of his negatives, so they could never be printed any
other way. Photographers who work for publications expect that
editors will do the cropping. Margaret Bourke-White was quite
accustomed to cropping her own images for dramatic effect, but when
she went to work for Life in 1936, she insisted that the darkroom
technicians print her negatives to the very edges, making their
work extremely difficult. Yet when editors cut an image in half for
visual impact, she never whispered a word of complaint.
</P>
<P>
   The recent Man Ray show at the International Center of
Photography Midtown revealed a photographer who evidently
photographed full figures or wide scenes in order to find and crop
down to the telling detail later on, unusual to this extent for a
photographer, most unlikely for a painter. There is one such
instance in this show, plus one very different example: a pair of
photograms (images produced without benefit of camera) that were
made by placing the same objects on film in contrasting
configurations.
</P>
<P>
   Here the editing is all a matter of composing and recomposing
elements, a procedure common to both photographers and painters.
The challenge for Man Ray was refashioning the image with the exact
same components; but after all, Mondrian spent much of his life
rearranging pretty similar lines and geometrical forms on canvas.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Winogrand, who would not crop a photograph, worked by winnowing
out single images from a crowd of them. Kertesz ferreted out the
telling detail from a larger field. Man Ray re-edited his own
arrangements. But Edward Weston edited in his eye. Weston was
determined to previsualize his finished print in every detail and
every gradation of tone before he ever released the shutter.
</P>
<P>
   He, too, could try out varying arrangements of the same
elements, as in two nude photographs of his wife in different poses
before the sexually suggestive open mouth of an adobe oven. But if
he was photographing a world he had not arranged, he needed to find
the picture by walking through and around the territory, printing
images in his mind as he came upon them.
</P>
<P>
   At the gallery is a brief succession of pictures he took in the
Colorado desert before and after he photographed a dead man along
the way. Of this succession, only the picture of the corpse still
lives in publications of his work; like any photographer, Weston
edited out the unsatisfactory images. In the main he worked by
pre-viewing, as Winogrand in his way did by re-viewing. Both of
them were editors much of the time; there is almost no other way to
be a photographer.
</P>
<P>
   In the front room of the gallery is ``Guy Bourdin: Early Work,
1952-1960,'' another quiet lesson about photography, this one about
the difficulties of tracking the formation of a style. It helps to
know who Bourdin (1928-1991) was: a foremost French fashion
photographer, the man some credit with bringing sex and violence to
a fever pitch in French fashion magazines in the late 1960s and in
their U.S. counterparts in the mid-'70s. (Helmut Newton gets most
of the credit for that in the United States and doubtless deserves
a lot of it, but Bourdin's contribution to this dubious enterprise
is unfairly neglected because he was reluctant to show in galleries
or publish in books.)
</P>
<P>
   Bourdin did a series of advertisements for Charles Jourdan shoes
that ran in U.S. magazines, with images like one of a wrecked car,
with the outline of a body on the road and a pair of high-priced
shoes on their sides on the pavement. He also took the pictures for
a Bloomingdale's lingerie catalog in 1976 that was virtually a
study of dissatisfaction, sexual unrest and distrust.
</P>
<P>
   The early work offers scarcely a clue to this realm. Bourdin the
fashion photographer was an innovative colorist; Bourdin the art
photographer in the early years worked in black and white. Not so
many people were shooting color then, and besides, he might not
have been able to afford it. Samuel Bourdin, his son, says the
elder Bourdin was so poor he sometimes had only flour and water to
eat.
</P>
<P>
   Surely this show is not the complete roster of work from those
years, so it is not easy to judge where clues to the future sexual
obsessions might lie. But except for one picture of a young girl in
her underwear and one of an oily rubber glove that you might
conceivably make an argument for, there is not even a hint. These
are clean, pure, dark and exceedingly formal images of white
rectangles on dark grounds, cars in perfect profile before striped
walls, picket fences covered with thin lines of grass.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps when the intervening years are filled in, the ties to
the later work will become clearer, as they do in the Pollock and
Bonnard retrospectives, where viewers at least feel they can find
premonitory signs by reading backward. But don't bet on it. Bourdin
was not a fashion photographer until the mid-'60s, and a shift into
commercial work can mean a major change in style, as happened with
Edward Steichen, Irving Penn and others.
</P>
<P>
   Then, too, Samuel Bourdin says that in the late '60s his father
finally got his own studio and, with all that space, began working
with props, setups, narrative, fantasy. Odd what space can do. The
New York School painters began painting enormous canvases when they
moved into lofts.
</P>
<P>
   At any rate, this show suggests that the nice, neat trajectories
one might like to trace for photographers are not always so easy to
work out. Like all visual artists, photographers have to try
various paths when they begin and only in time find the road less
traveled. Bourdin was good enough in his restrained early years.
Later he could be brilliant: hateful, perhaps, at times; but boy,
did he do hateful well.
</P>
<P>
   EXHIBITION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `CROPPING AND PICTURE MAKING: KERTESZ, MAN RAY, WESTON AND
WINOGRAND'
</P>
<P>
   `GUY BOURDIN: EARLY WORK, 1952-1960'
</P>
<P>
   Pace Wildenstein MacGill Gallery
</P>
<P>
   32 E. 57th St.
</P>
<P>
   Through March 6
</P>
</TEXT>
