r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CARVILLE-HOAX-MATALIN     02-04 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARVILLE-HOAX-MATALIN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A VICIOUS HOAX 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This has already moved to clients of Richard Roeper's popular
weekly columns, now being offered as a regular New York Times
Syndicate feature. For a bio &AMP; photo _ as well as special contract
rates _ please contact your sales representative:
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at 732-390-4480;
fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.) 
 &HT;    
 By RICHARD ROEPER  
 c.1999 The Chicago Sun-Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   When I was in Washington recently, nearly every media person I
talked to was hot on a rumor about that oddest of political odd
couples, serpentine Democratic apologist James Carville and
strident Republican mouthpiece Mary Matalin.
</P>
<P>
   It was an ugly rumor. Details varied depending on who was
telling the story, but the gist of it was that Carville had been
arrested after assaulting Matalin and threatening her life.
</P>
<P>
   The story was growing like a poisonous mushroom on the Internet.
In a newsgroup chat room called alt.gossip.celebrities, there was
this post:
</P>
<P>
   ``Seems that cuddly Clinton defender James `Crazyville' shot up
his house and threatened to kill his wife, Mary Matalin. Perhaps
Monica's ex-boyfriend (Clinton) may someday be his cellmate.''
</P>
<P>
   Attached to the post was a copy of a story from the Montgomery
County (Md.) Ledger:
</P>
<P>
   ``ROCKVILLE, MD _ James Carville, vocal supporter and confidant
of President Bill Clinton, reportedly spent last Monday night in
the Montgomery County Jail after he was arrested on suspicion of
firing a gun into a sofa and repeatedly plunging a knife into a
wall during a fight with his wife in their suburban home there
earlier that evening, according to local police sources.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carville, an internationally known political consultant and
Democratic Party campaign manager, allegedly twice discharged a
Glock 9-mm. semiautomatic pistol inside the home, damaged a living
room wall with an oversized hunting knife, threatened the life of
his wife, radio talk show host Mary Matalin, and used physical
force against her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rockville police subsequently took him into custody on
suspicion of domestic violence and brandishing a weapon, both
misdemeanors. He was also charged with discharging a firearm in a
negligent manner, a violation which could be prosecuted with a
felony.''
</P>
<P>
   The story went on to say that police confiscated a cache of
weapons from the house, including ``two shotguns and an AR-15
semiautomatic assault rifle.''
</P>
<P>
   Hot stuff. Little wonder reporters in Washington were trading
gossip like schoolgirls on the day Homecoming Court is selected,
and Clinton-bashers were chortling over the news.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh man ain't it great!'' began one post on the Internet. ``The
great icon of you puke lefties is busted for putting his family and
neighbors in jeopardy for shooting up his house.''
</P>
<P>
   A number of stations subscribing to the American Family Radio
Network broadcast the news, giving it more momentum. (American
Family Radio is a branch of the American Family Association, the
rightwing organization headed by the activist Rev. Donald Wildmon.)
Surely it would be only a matter of time before the major
newspapers and the networks picked up on the story, staking out the
Carville-Matalin household and shouting questions at them the
moment they surfaced.
</P>
<P>
   Only that never happened _ because the incident itself never
happened.
</P>
<P>
   The whole thing was a hoax, which intrepid reporters soon found
out as they tried to follow up on the story in the Montgomery
County Ledger, a non-existent newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   As genuine as the article appeared to be _ written in a
professional style, with all the news-gathering elements seemingly
in place _ there were a number of details that could easily be
checked and debunked.
</P>
<P>
   The police lieutenant quoted in the story? No such guy.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer? Not a real person.
</P>
<P>
   A Nexis search of published articles about the Carvilles reveals
they live in Virginia, not Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   There were even clues contained within the bylines on the County
Ledger story. A ``Lee Canular'' was listed as the main reporter,
with an ``Ami DeCour'' receiving credit for contributing to the
piece. Think French, my friends. Un canular is a trap, a con, a
trick played on someone. The name Ami DeCour is very close to ami
de la cour (``friend of the court'') or ami de coeur (``bosom
buddy''). Whoever the hoaxsters were, they were obviously expecting
someone to figure out the game.
</P>
<P>
   The radio stations that broadcast the report issued apologies
and corrections. Matalin's and Carville's lawyers are trying to
find the origins on the rotten prank.
</P>
<P>
   Good luck. You'd probably have an easier time locating the end
of a rainbow. As Bill Maher of ``Politically Incorrect'' once said,
the Internet is a bathroom wall, and any anonymous clown can write
anything without taking an ounce of responsibility. Regardless of
what you think about Carville and/or Matalin, to launch such a
nefarious ``joke'' isn't funny, it's sick.
</P>
<P>
   By now even the Internet posters have realized the story isn't
true _ but that hasn't stopped the most paranoid of the
anti-Clintonites from speculating about the true origin of the
tale. They're attributing it to ... James Carville. Something about
Carville hatching the plan to win public sympathy as a ``victim''
of a terrible hoax.
</P>
<P>
   The frightening thing is, people who believe such Machiavellian
garbage have the right to vote, and drive cars, and purchase
firearms. Try to forget that when it's time to go to sleep tonight.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Richard Roeper is a columnist for the Chicago Sun-Times, a
radio host and a commentator for Fox News in Chicago _ and has
appeared on programs such as ``Nightline,'' ``The CBS Evening News
with Dan Rather,'' ``Oprah'' and ``The Drudge Report.'') &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
