<HEADER>
A2113 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THEATER-NOTES-NYT &LR;      02-04 1169
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE GREAT WHITE WAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Calif., Great Britain)  (mk) 
 By JESSE MCKINLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After months of bickering and faltering negotiations,
officials at the American Theater Wing and the League of American
Theaters and Producers announced late Thursday afternoon that they
had agreed on a five-year deal to jointly produce the Tony Awards.
</P>
<P>
   The awards will be televised live on CBS on June 6. Broadway
shows must open by April 28 to be eligible, and nominations will be
announced on May 3.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, which runs through 2004, apparently resolves the
acrimonious dispute that began last summer when the league
announced that it would withdraw from the partnership governing the
annual awards after this August.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the wing, which founded the awards in 1947 and owns
the trademark, and the league, which is the co-producer of the
event and handles much of its administrative workload, had been
meeting since then to settle the quarrel, part of which they said
involved the marketing of the awards.
</P>
<P>
   Executives at the league, a trade organization, said they
preferred a higher-profile event complete with corporate
sponsorships and promotional packages tying the Tonys to other
promotions the league runs. Officials at the wing, a philanthropy
of theater professionals founded in the 1930s, consider the awards
a showcase for excellence and oppose using them as a promotion
connected to other events.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall reports surfaced that the league was considering
establishing a rival awards show. The feud angered executives at
CBS, which traditionally broadcasts the ceremony, and network
executives asked the groups to settle their disagreements so that
the show could go on.
</P>
<P>
   The show was dealt a blow last month by the departure of Rosie
O'Donnell, who was its host for two years and had been widely
credited for improving the broadcast's long-sagging ratings. Ms.
O'Donnell said she had a scheduling conflict, and no replacement
has been named.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, executives for both organizations were playing
nice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are pleased that we have been able to renew our
partnership,'' said Roy Somlyo, president of the wing, and Jed
Bernstein, executive director of the league, in a joint statement.
``We look forward to many successful Tony awards.''
</P>
<P>
   `Wit' Wants to Compete
</P>
<P>
   The producers of ``Wit,'' the acclaimed drama by Margaret Edson,
have asked the administration committee of the Tonys to make the
play eligible for this year's awards.
</P>
<P>
   The catch is that ``Wit'' is playing Off Broadway, at the
499-seat Union Square Theater, and the Tonys recognize work only in
Broadway theaters, which award rules define as houses with 500
seats or more. Still, the rules, which also identify the eligible
theaters, can be remarkably malleable. Last year ``Cabaret,''
playing at the former Club Expo on West 43rd Street, not named in
the rules, was given a special dispensation and won several Tonys.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Wit'' producers argued in a letter sent Thursday to the
administrative committee that the play was eligible for the Tonys
because they had tried to move the show to Broadway and had the
money to do so, but were thwarted by theater owners ``who deemed
the play unsuitable for Broadway solely on the basis of its subject
matter.'' The play deals with an English professor's struggle with
ovarian cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ```Wit' would seem to embody the kind of work which Broadway
desperately needs,'' the letter reads, adding that the show's lack
of ``a Broadway zip code seems a paltry reason'' to overlook the
play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wit'' joins a long line of shows playing in ineligible houses
whose producers have petitioned the awards committee for
recognition. Despite notable exceptions like ``Cabaret,'' most are
unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Sherman, a spokesman for the Tonys, said, ``The
administration committee will consider any letter and make a
decision according to the Tony rules.'' The committee is likely to
meet later this month.
</P>
<P>
   Voices of Experience
</P>
<P>
   They are old, to be sure, and also little. And ladies?
Absolutely.
</P>
<P>
   But don't call Anna Wing, 84, or Gabrielle Blunt, 80, little old
ladies.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Wing and Ms. Blunt are the oldest cast members in ``Blue
Heart,'' the program of two short plays by Caryl Churchill at the
Brooklyn Academy of Music. Between them, Ms. Wing and Ms. Blunt
have about 120 years experience on the stage, but for both Britons
this is the first acting turn in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a lovely clear city you have,'' said Ms. Blunt, who had
never visited the United States before. ``I thought it would have
been much more enclosed with skyscrapers.''
</P>
<P>
   Both actresses began their careers in the mid-1930s as repertory
players in Britain. During World War II, Ms. Blunt acted on the
West End and toured for the troops, while Ms. Wing served in the
Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, both have steadily appeared in theaters around
Britain and on film and television. Ms. Wing is also well known for
her four years on the popular British soap opera ``Eastenders.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I never did anything too splendid,'' Ms. Wing said, ``but I
did a lot of work.''
</P>
<P>
   So what has changed since they first started in the business? On
the bad side, both women say television has weakened the desire for
good theater and good acting. And the improvements? Less
exploitation of actors, and more roles for women.
</P>
<P>
   And what has stayed the same?
</P>
<P>
   ``You always feel a beginner in theater,'' Ms. Wing said.
``Except for a few aching legs and that stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Along the Way
</P>
<P>
   _ Executives from Walt Disney Co. met in New York last weekend
with the director Kenny Leon and the poet Reg Gaines about their
progress on ``Hoopz,'' a musical about the history of the Harlem
Globetrotters. Savion Glover is also involved in the project, which
is tentatively scheduled for an out-of-town tryout early next year.
</P>
<P>
   _ A week after news that Al Pacino would not appear in a planned
run of ``Othello,'' to be produced by Alexander Cohen, the Mark
Taper Forum in Los Angeles announced that Pacino would star in and
direct Eugene O'Neill's ``Hughie'' in June. The five-week run will
be a reprise of a 1996 New York run at Circle in the Square.
</P>
<P>
   _ Frances Sternhagen will appear in the Women's Project's final
show of the season, ``The Exact Center of the Universe,'' opening
in April. John Tillinger, now directing ``Night Must Fall'' on
Broadway, will direct.
</P>
<P>
   _ Beginning on Tuesday, the Ensemble Studio, at 549 W. 52nd St.,
will be presenting ``Going to the River,'' a two-week festival of
plays by African-American women.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Collected Stories,'' with Uta Hagen, has announced a Feb. 28
closing at the Lucille Lortel Theater. And at the Walter Kerr
Theater, the producers of ``Beauty Queen of Leenane'' have settled
a scheduling conflict with ``The Weir,'' the theater's next play,
and will close on March 14.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
