<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEMPLETON-INNOVATORS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLDWIDE LAWS OF LIFE:
 WE ALL HAVE IT WITHIN US TO BE ENTREPRENEURS 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Sir John Templeton, the Tennessee-born billionaire and founder
of the Templeton funds, built his fortune on his legendary ability
to perceive value that others overlooked. In his column, he urges
us to recognize the value of spirituality in life.)
</P>
<P>
   (``If there is no dull and determined effort, there will be no
brilliant achievement.'' -- Hsun-tze)
</P>
<P>
   (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN M. TEMPLETON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. Templeton Foundation Press &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; Distributed by N.Y. Times Special Features &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The pyramids of Egypt are considered to be among the Seven
Wonders of the Ancient World. It is said that the Great Pyramid
near Cairo can accommodate the equivalent of ten football fields.
</P>
<P>
   When we think of the tools that may have been used during those
ancient times, one wonders how the seemingly miraculous feats of
pyramid construction were accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   How could the ancient people build such massive structures
without the benefit of modern machinery? What kind of blueprints
did they have to guide them with construction? Whose idea
spearheaded the first construction? What natural resources were
available?
</P>
<P>
   By their insight and foresight, the builders must have seized
every opportunity -- even those that may have appeared to be
obstacles -- and added their faith and creativity to leave such
impressive gifts to the world.
</P>
<P>
   In one sense, we, too, can be a part of that building process.
In fact, each new day with its possible obstacles offers
opportunities to create or build that which we desire. Our
ancestors from around the world may have encountered a river, and
built a bridge and a dam; they entered a forest, and built and
warmed their homes; they cleared a field, and planted and harvested
their crops; they tunneled through mountains, and endured possible
extremes of heat and cold; but they moved onward, forward.
</P>
<P>
   We are blessed to live in a time when one who desires to
organize a business and is willing to take the steps necessary for
the project to unfold can experience the freedom and opportunity to
be an entrepreneur. And world progress needs entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
   If there is a blueprint or guideline to follow, getting started
may not be difficult. The value of a definitive plan is easy to
understand for it can help one to avoid wasting precious moments.
Dedication to the goal and earnest hard work are important values
that can help manifest the dream.
</P>
<P>
   The advice of Harlow Herbert Curtice, an automobile
manufacturer, was to ``do your job better each time. Do it better
than anyone else can do it. Do it better than it needs to be done.
Let no one or anything stand between you and the difficult task. I
know this sounds old-fashioned. It is, but it has built the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   Psychiatrist W. Beran Wolfe put it this way: ``If you observe a
really happy man, you will find him building a boat, writing a
symphony, educating his son, growing double dahlias, or looking for
dinosaur eggs in the Gobi Desert. He will not be searching for
happiness as if it were a collar button that had rolled under the
radiator, striving for it as the goal itself. He will have become
aware that he is happy in the course of living life twenty-four
crowded hours of each day.''
</P>
<P>
   And isn't ``living life'' an important foundation for building
our dreams? Within you, within the creative genius of your mind,
lies the real land of opportunity. Within you lies the insight, the
foresight, the strength, courage, faith, freedom, and ability to
accept and express your opportunities. From the circumstances
around you, from the situations in which you may find yourself,
from the relationships in which you may be involved, you can be
creative!
</P>
<P>
   Choose carefully and through much thought and prayer that which
you desire. Be sure your desire is worthy of your energy, your
time, your creativity, and can bring a blessing of service to
others. Know what you desire to accomplish; and plan, step by step,
day by day, how you may achieve your goal.
</P>
<P>
   The pyramid builders built upon one stone at a time. They
started at the base of the pyramid and worked their way up. Most
projects involve the same process-one step at a time. We start at
the beginning and work our way to the finish line. If we are open
and receptive, the resources needed can be provided.
</P>
<P>
   A journalist was complaining to the French novelist, essayist,
and playwright Marcel Ayme that the modern world hinders the free
development of the human being. ``I don't agree,'' said Ayme
mildly. ``I consider myself perfectly free.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But surely you feel some limits to your freedom,'' the
journalist commented.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, yes,'' replied Ayme, ``from time to time I find myself
terribly limited by the dictionary!''
</P>
<P>
   What is necessary to become an innovator? First, recognize that
you have within you the power to be creative. Next, be willing to
try new experiences, to discover new fields that may offer scope
for developmental activities.
</P>
<P>
   Being open and receptive can teach us much about the world and
help sincere and creative individuals become innovative
entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
   Success-bound people find it important to believe in themselves,
because the frontier exists inside of them. Jesus' teaching
concerning this is found in Luke 17:21, where we are reminded that
``the kingdom of God is not coming with signs to be observed ...
for behold, the kingdom of God is in the midst of you.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the true frontier that we must explore: our own inner
being, our own divinity.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (Excerpted from ``Worldwide Laws of Life'' by John Marks
Templeton. Published by Templeton Foundation Press)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-04-99 1744EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990204.0283 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 17:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2121 &Cx1f; taf-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VT-SKI-ART-2TAKES-NYT     02-04 1058
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VT-SKI-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE HILLS ARE ALIVE WITH SKIERS
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl) 
By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When I got up last Sunday morning to take a shower at the Trapp
Family Lodge in Stowe, Vt., I noticed with some alarm that the
water was tepid, at best. I called the front desk to point this
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, you're at the far end of the lodge,'' the clerk cheerily
responded. ``You need to let the water run for at least 10 minutes.
Turn on the tap, too.'' Then she added an important Vermont fact of
life: ``It  &UR; is &LR;  15 below outside.''
</P>
<P>
   That was a matter of dispute. The temperature recorded at the
top of Stowe's Mount Mansfield at 7 a.m. on Sunday was 0. The radio
news was claiming 11 below, and some people in the lodge lobby said
it hit 7 below in their car. Meanwhile, a thermometer outside a
lodge window was recording a balmy 14 above.
</P>
<P>
   But whatever it was, it was cold. Stowe is not for the pampered.
Sometimes Stowe feels as if it is not for ordinary mortals at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man was not meant to ski,'' my husband, Steve, muttered from
inside his parka as we spent 13 excruciating minutes creeping up
the mountain in the Big Spruce chair lift while the wind tore at
our cheeks.
</P>
<P>
   My family and I spent the weekend downhill and cross-country
skiing at one of the iciest and oldest ski resorts in the United
States. We loved it. Certainly we love the subzero war stories we
get to tell. And it wasn't just a frostbite wonderland: Stowe had a
two- to four-foot base of snow covered with packed powder, all of
it sparkling, at least on Sunday, under sunshine and outrageously
blue skies. ``It doesn't look like Vermont,'' observed Ricky, our
sardonic cross-country teacher and guide.
</P>
<P>
   Skiing at Stowe was born in the 1930s, when the Civilian
Conservation Corps cut the first trail down the mountain. By the
1950s, '60s and '70s, Stowe was the undisputed king of East Coast
skiing, a resort for the rich, famous and expert. But by the 1980s,
upstarts like Killington, Sugarloaf and Stratton had moved onto
Stowe's turf. Today, Stowe is scrambling to keep up, with plans for
a 110-room hotel at the foot of Spruce Peak and renovations to the
no-frills base lodges where skiers buy lift tickets and bump into
each other with their trays over lunch.
</P>
<P>
   But the resort still offers some of the toughest skiing in the
East (not that it mattered to me, a wary intermediate) and one of
the most beautiful settings in Vermont. The village of Stowe has a
white-steepled church, an old-fashioned general store and the usual
shops offering maple syrup and cheese. But it feels like authentic
New England, and at 200 years old, it is.
</P>
<P>
   Out Mountain Road is the Trapp Family Lodge, a Tyrolean-style
hotel still run by the family that inspired ``The Sound of Music.''
The von Trapps settled in the hills above Stowe in 1942, four years
after fleeing the Nazis in Austria, then built the first
cross-country skiing center in America. Today it is considered one
of the best anywhere. Their sprawling lodge, in the luxury category
at Stowe, is also the accommodation of choice if you have a
9-year-old daughter, as we do, who views ``Do-Re-Mi'' as a sacred
text.
</P>
<P>
   We left Friday afternoon from our home outside New York, where
there was not a snowflake in sight, and arrived six hours later to
knee-deep drifts at the lodge. I was expecting something hokey,
maybe with puppets popping up singing ``The Lonely Goatherd,'' but
the lodge was a lovely expanse of blond wood and potted white
hyacinths, if lacking what old-timers say was the personality of
the original, which burned down in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Our room had painted Austrian-style furniture, two queen-size
beds covered with down comforters and assorted pictures of the
Trapp family, which our daughter, Madeleine, inspected. A door led
outside to a small terrace. Almost right next to it, under a bright
moon, I was startled to see a small family cemetery with the graves
of Baron and Baroness von Trapp, the real people played by
Christopher Plummer and Julie Andrews in the 1965 film musical.
Capt. Georg von Trapp died in 1947, Maria in 1987. We did not meet
Johannes von Trapp, their youngest son, born in America in 1939,
who runs the lodge today.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning Steve nursed a sense of dread over breakfast as
he eyed the fit, furry and upscale granola-and-yogurt crowd in the
dining room. We were not exactly a ready-to-attack-the-mountain
family. Steve had not been skiing in 16 years. Neither had I,
unless you count the hour I spent on a slushy bunny slope near
Poughkeepsie the weekend before with my Brownie troop. Madeleine
had been there, too; this weekend would be her second time on skis.
Our 5-year-old son, Teddy, had never skied. Before we were married,
Steve and I had spent a week together at Stowe, sometime in the
early 1980s, but it felt as if that were a century ago.
</P>
<P>
   We drove 15 minutes to Mount Mansfield, the big mountain where
we had skied before; spent 45 minutes in line with a lot of college
students waiting for rental equipment; then realized we needed to
be across the road at Spruce Peak, Stowe's beginner and
intermediate mountain with the ski school and children's program.
There the crowds were thinner, a godsend when it came to stuffing
the children into ski boots in the small rental area. The staff was
friendly and helpful, but skiing, I immediately noticed, had not
gotten cheaper in 16 years. Maybe that's why we hadn't gone back
for so long.
</P>
<P>
   Lift tickets were $52 a day for adults, $32 for children ages 6
to 12, or $136 for our family. A two-and-a-half-hour children's
lesson was $35 a child. One-day ski, boot and pole rental for four
was $92, with a security deposit of $1,200 I left on my credit
card.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm not renting a  &UR; boat &LR; ,'' I said.
</P>
<P>
   The woman who took my money was unmoved. ``If it wasn't so
high,'' she said, ``we wouldn't get the equipment back.''
</P>
<P>
   On the slopes, things got off to a rough start. I almost pulled
my arm out of its socket trying to get Teddy up the rope tow, and I
watched as Steve took Madeleine on a very slow descent with a lot
of falls on, unfortunately, a run named Easy Street.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   After lunch ($32.70 for hamburgers and whatnot) the day improved
when the children headed off to their lessons, and Steve and I went
to the top of Spruce Peak and had two nice trips down Sterling, an
easy and peaceful intermediate run through the trees. By the end of
the run I was turning better than I ever had, which seemed odd for
a tired old mom like me.
</P>
<P>
   But it was a result, I later figured out, of the relatively new
super-sidecut or shaped skis that are far better at carving out
turns. They came out widely on the market in 1993, and have been
available for the past two years at Stowe's rental shop. Shaped
skis, as anybody who skis knows, are to skiing what oversize
rackets are to tennis. One guidebook calls them ``the sexiest thing
to happen to winter sports since the invention of the bear rug in
front of the fireplace.'' I was hooked.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the day, Madeleine could make it in a graceful
snowplow down Easy Street, and Teddy was working on stopping. We
repaired, satisfied, to dinner at the Trapp Family Lodge, where we
had good Wiener schnitzel and trout and were serenaded by a harpist
playing subtle strains of ``Edelweiss.'' Everybody was in a dead
sleep by 10:30. We awoke the next morning, stiff, to try out
cross-country skiing.
</P>
<P>
   None of us had been before, and the lodge's ski center, a short
walk through the snow from our room, was a world away from the
downhill lodge of the day before. A fire crackled quietly in the
hearth as the serene cross-country instructors, who seemed as if
they had all just had massages, helped us with our boots and skis.
This time lessons and rentals for four was $80; the pass for the
lodge's 60-plus miles of groomed and back-country trails came with
our room.
</P>
<P>
   For the next hour, Steve and I went with Ricky, our instructor,
and two other adults for a lesson in the basics, then a peaceful
trip through the woods. Our children went off for a separate lesson
with Suzanne. The day was gorgeous, and we met back at the ski
center, thrilled. I was hooked on cross-country skiing, too. Teddy,
who took to it instantly, said he liked it better than downhill.
</P>
<P>
   To me, cross-country skiing was like folk music _ gentle and
close to nature. The downhill was like rock-and-roll _ exciting,
risky and seductive.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward we had lunch at the Trapp-run Austrian Tea Room, down
the road from the main lodge, where the bratwurst was good and the
mountain views spectacular. The gift shop offered an array of
things Trapp: mugs, books, stationery and remastered recordings of
the original Trapp Family Singers.
</P>
<P>
   (The group disbanded in 1956 after touring the world from its
base at Stowe, but reassembled briefly in 1959 to record its own
version of the score from ``The Sound of Music,'' then a Broadway
musical with Mary Martin as Maria, on which the film was based.)
</P>
<P>
   That recording, and the shop, struck me as a weird blending of
treacly myth and fact.
</P>
<P>
   ``The myth has taken on a reality of its own, and that's
sometimes a little irritating,'' Johannes von Trapp said when I
called him after we returned. ``We've made our peace with it at
this point, but some of us had more trouble with it than others.''
</P>
<P>
   The family has had a complicated relationship with ``The Sound
of Music'' from the beginning: Even before the Broadway musical, in
one of the more famous bad deals in theatrical history, Maria von
Trapp sold the rights to her story for only $9,000 to a German film
company. The American producers of the Broadway show and film, who
included Richard Rodgers and Oscar Hammerstein II, gave her a small
percentage of the royalties, though they weren't legally required
to, and so the Trapp family did make money on ``The Sound of
Music,'' but not the fortune they might have. More recently, two
factions of the family have gone to court over a financial dispute.
However interesting, none of this has any effect on guests at the
lodge.
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, the water for my shower did get hot in 10 minutes.
Von Trapp described the cold last weekend as unusual, but like any
Vermonter he did not seem impressed by it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've skied in Austria when everybody was complaining and
freezing to death,'' he said, ``and I thought it was a perfectly
normal day.''
</P>
<P>
   Here is information about the places mentioned in the article
about skiing in Stowe, Vt.:
</P>
<P>
   Where to Stay
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRAPP FAMILY LODGE, &LR;  Trapp Hill Road, (802) 253-8511 or (800)
826-7000. Weekend room rates: $225 per night for double occupancy;
the room can accomodate four, with a charge of $25 for each
additional person over 13. Hour lessons in cross-country skiing
($14 per adult for group lesson, or $10 per child 18 and younger;
$40 for a private lesson, $10 extra for each additional person.)
Free shuttle service to Spruce Peak and Mount Mansfield ski areas.
There are also special packages for accommodations and meals over
holiday weekends ($384 per night double occupancy). All rental
equipment (skis, poles, boots and bindings): $13 per day ($10 for
children) or $50 for 5-7 days.
</P>
<P>
   Where to Eat
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AUSTRIAN TEA ROOM, &LR;  42 Trapp Hill Road, Stowe, Vt., (802)
253-5705. Hours: 10:30 a.m. to 5:30 p.m. daily. Light lunches,
pastries, Austrian specialities, hot chocolate, desserts.
Sandwiches and entrees from $6.50. Major credit cards.
</P>
<P>
   Where to Ski
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STOWE MOUNTAIN RESORT,  &LR; (Spruce Peak and Mount Mansfield), 5781
Mountain Road, (800) 253-4754 or (802) 253-3500. Daily lift
tickets: $52; $32 for children 12 and younger. Daily equipment
rental: $25; $15 for children 12 and younger; each additional day,
$18; $12 for children. Half-day children's lesson, $35 per child;
full day, $75.
</P>
<P>
   Getting There
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BY CAR:  &LR; To reach Stowe from New York City, take I-95 to the
Cross Westchester Expressway (I-287) and continue on I-287 to I-684
(Exit 9a). Go north on I-684 to I-84 East (Exit 9E) and continue on
I-84 East to I-91 North (Exit 51). Take I-91 North to I-89 North
(Exit 10) and continue on I-89 North to SR-100, which leads into
Stowe.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BY BUS:  &LR; Greyhound offers daily service from the Port Authority
Bus Terminal in Manhattan to Waterbury, Vt., which is about 10
miles from Stowe. Round-trip fare, $124; $62 for children 2 to 11
years old. Information: (800) 231-2222.
</P>
</TEXT>
