<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, Feb. 5, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(js) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Angry seas with swells as high as 20 feet pounded the shores of
Washington Thursday in response to gale-force winds associated with
a relatively routine, wet Pacific disturbance. On Friday, another
batch of rain associated with the approach of the leading edge of
mild Pacific air will arrive. Increasing winds from the
south-southwest will average 20 to 35 miles an hour at the coast by
later in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Then, late Friday night, rain will intensify west of the
Cascades as the center of a very large and powerful Pacific low
pressure system heads toward Vancouver Island. Winds will increase
along the Pacific Northwest Coast, with gusts to 90 miles an hour,
possibly higher, on some exposed beaches in Washington and Oregon
by midday Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, scattered showers and isolated thunderstorms will
sprout from the western Gulf States to the middle Mississippi
Valley as a strengthening northward flow of moist air from the Gulf
of Mexico crosses paths with a Pacific cold front advancing east
across the Plains. As the front marches into Texas Friday night, a
line of thunderstorms will erupt across central and eastern
sections of the Lone Star State, with a few storms possibly
approaching severe levels.
</P>
<P>
   An expansive canopy of clear sky will cover much of the Eastern
States as a tandem of high pressure systems govern the region.
Abundant sunshine, in concert with the presence of Pacific air,
will promote high temperatures several degrees above average from
the Southeast States to the eastern Great Lakes to eastern New
England. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Winter Warmth
</P>
<P>
   Each January during the decade of the 1990s has been warmer than
the long-term average in Tuscon, Arizona. Detailed analysis of the
temperature pattern shows that the bulk of the unusual warmth has
occurred at night. Mild nights have become more frequent in Tuscon
in part because of the way the humans have changed the desert. The
buildings of the city retain some of the heat that would otherwise
dissipate quickly after sunset. Also, city nights have been made
more humid by the evaporation of moisture from the extensive
landscaping. Moist air also discourages quick cooling at night.
</P>
</TEXT>
