<HEADER>
A2131 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LATAM-PRESIDENTS05-CO     02-04 0523
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATAM-PRESIDENTS05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PRESIDENTS OF ECUADOR AND PERU PLEDGE COOPERATION
 &HT;    By EUNICE MOSCOSO
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With words of confidence and hope, the presidents
of Ecuador and Peru pledged Thursday to maintain peace and greater
economic cooperation between their nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not trying to get anything from the other. Our task is
a common task,'' said President Jamil Mahuad of Ecuador.
</P>
<P>
   Mahuad and President Alberto Fujimori of Peru are basking in the
glow of an historic
</P>
<P>
   peace treaty signed Oct. 26 in Brazil, ending more than 150
years of hostilities between the two neighboring South American
countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``It lasted longer than the Inca's empire,'' Mahuad said of the
conflict.
</P>
<P>
   The peace agreement delineates the border in a 48-mile section
of the Andean foothills. Peru and Ecuador both claimed the area,
which was left undefined after a 1941 border war. The two countries
fought over the strip of land in 1981 and 1995.
</P>
<P>
   At a joint press conference at the National Press Club, the
presidents said they were on a quest for $3 billion in aid to build
roads, develop business relations, improve security and promote
tourism and trade.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori and Mahuad said they already had obtained commitments
totaling $1 billion from the Inter-American Development Bank and
the Andean Development Corp. and that they hope to obtain an
additional $2 billion from the World Bank, the International
Monetary Fund, the European Union, Japan and other nations.
</P>
<P>
   The cooperation between Ecuador and Peru reflects a softening of
hostilities in the general public of the two countries, the
presidents said.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1980s, Ecuadorean anger at Peru manifested itself
in anti-Peru T-shirts and offensive trinkets for sale, such as a
Mickey Mouse-type figurine making an obscene gesture, with the
slogan ``Hey Peru!''
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori said he has seen a dramatic change in public opinion
and gave as an example his
</P>
<P>
   1991 trip to Quito, the capital of Ecuador. Political advisers
had urged him not to travel to Quito for security reasons but
Fujimori, often unpredictable, decided to go anyway.
</P>
<P>
   The people ``received me with great enthusiasm,'' he said,
adding that he got a bigger crowd than Mahuad ever did _ a comment
that had the entire room laughing.
</P>
<P>
   Mahuad responded in kind, ``I'm just waiting to get to Lima.''
</P>
<P>
   The friendly, bilingual banter between the presidents
underscored the new, peace-seeking cooperation between the two
nations.
</P>
<P>
   Both said they would forgo weapons purchases for their
respective armed forces for the next four years and use the
billions of dollars they would save on development projects.
</P>
<P>
   The projects are desperately needed in Peru, where 70 percent of
its 24 million residents live below poverty, and even more
desperately in Ecuador, where the 1997 per-capita income was only
$1,392, making it one of the poorest countries in South America.
</P>
<P>
   Mahuad and Fujimori are scheduled to meet with President Clinton
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
