<HEADER>
A2136 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOFTUS-COLUMN-$ADV11-     02-04 0616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOFTUS-COLUMN-$ADV11-NYTR </SLUG>
  
 (For release Thursday Feb. 11)  
 By MARY J. LOFTUS   
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The lights are of the disco-ball variety, reflecting in red and
yellow and green across the rink.
</P>
<P>
   Jewel sings a sultry pop song, its beat bouncing off the
carpeted walls and polished floor.
</P>
<P>
   Each month, my son's elementary school sponsors a skate night at
the local rink, and each time, I accompany him. But on this outing,
I've decided to rent skates myself, in a nostalgic ode to my
seventh- and eighth-grade weekends spent at a Central Florida
roller rink.
</P>
<P>
   Now, at 35, the skates feel heavier on my feet.
</P>
<P>
   It has been, I am shocked to think, more than 15 years since
I've been on skates. I haven't forgotten how, but I have gotten
rusty, as evidenced by my wobbling.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of wearing my tightest jeans and a satin shirt that
catches the light, all the rage when I was in middle school, I am
in a blue knit cardigan and slacks. I've brought along the
newspaper to read at the orange plastic tables in the refreshment
area later.
</P>
<P>
   Adam, still getting used to the idea of balancing on eight
slippery wheels, is propelling himself from video game to video
game, learning to skate by default, since I have agreed to supply
him with quarters only if he plays while wearing a pair of skates.
</P>
<P>
   But I have dared to try the floor, after lacing my boot skates
more tightly around my ankles.
</P>
<P>
   Transported by the music and lights to a time when I knew how to
glide, I push off from the wall, trying to find a cushion of space
where I could be relatively insulated. The rink is crowded tonight,
and finding a spot is like merging onto I-75 during rush hour.
</P>
<P>
   I find my pace, trying not to veer into any of my fellow
skaters. I'm suddenly self-conscious, as if wearing a T-shirt that
says ``WARNING: Middle-age mom on skates, use due caution when
passing.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, I had forgotten the obstacle course of those who wipe
out ahead of you: tiny beginners, who sprawl without warning, arms
outstretched and legs tangled, and overly confident pre-teens, who
have cut a corner too fast.
</P>
<P>
   Then I see Adam waving me over to the side. ``Can I skate with
you?'' he says, holding out a hand.
</P>
<P>
   I reach for him, but think, how will I keep us both afloat? We
push off and are sucked into a momentum that only knows forward.
</P>
<P>
   Adam staggers and I do a quick sideways step, trying to steady
him. I move us toward the center, where the younger skaters are
congregated. It's good to tame the small circle before spiraling
outward.
</P>
<P>
   We do a few mini-laps, as if slipping around an icy pond, and I
finally pull away my hand and insist that he take a solo orbit.
</P>
<P>
   Adam does far better with both hands free, able to balance and
steady himself instead of leaning awkwardly into me. He makes
steady, determined progress, and is soon skating around the larger
rink, hugging the wall but going faster and faster until he is
almost running on wheels.
</P>
<P>
   I have pulled over to the carpet, and watch for Adam to surface
among dozens of other bobbing boys as they circle past. He wipes
out a few times that I see, and a few times I don't. After one
fall, he emerges holding his head, and I feel a sizable bump. We
decide to call it a night.
</P>
<P>
   We return the rental skates and reclaim our sneakers. But the
floor feels watery, as if we are back from sea and can't find our
land legs.
</P>
<P>
   That's the magic of skating, I think. It stays with you. Even 15
years later.
</P>
<P>
   (Mary J. Loftus is a New York Times Regional Newspapers feature
writer. She has master's and specialist degrees in marriage and
family counseling.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
