<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXBUDGET-TEX </SLUG>
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Fort Worth Star-Telegram plans to move the following stories
for clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of Friday,
Feb. 5, and thereafter. If you have any questions, please call Lou
Hudson, Carmelita Bevill or Jim Peipert on the Star-Telegram's
National/Foreign Desk at (817) 390-7785. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   C O M M E N T A R Y &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   JOHNSON-COLUMN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ To most black boys growing up in the Fort Worth-Dallas
area, ``Gooseneck'' Bill McDonald was the man. They held him in
awe. Feared him vaguely. Envied him ferociously. Wondered how he
did it. Still, we knew that for all his wealth, influence and
power, McDonald could not legally drink from a water fountain in a
downtown five and dime that was not specifically marked for
``colored.'' But then, he didn't have to or want to. He could have
opened his own five and dime had he been so inclined. He opened a
bank instead. By CECIL JOHNSON. Story has moved in ``k''
commentary. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   F I N A N C I A L &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Harvey Mackay, the guy who taught us how to swim with
sharks, is back. His fifth book is ``Pushing The Envelope: All the
Way to the Top'' (Ballantine Books, 348 pages, $24.95). The title
is most appropriate for the envelope manufacturer-turned-sage,
author and speaker. Mackay owns Mackay Envelope Corp., a
Minneapolis-based $85 million company. By TERESA McUSIC. Story has
moved in ``f'' financial category. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-04-99 1804EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990204.0293 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 18:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2144 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOHNSON-COLUMN-TEX     02-04 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOHNSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MONUMENT TO A MAN _ AND A PEOPLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CECIL JOHNSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Come here,'' the obelisk beckoned.
</P>
<P>
   From the dark side of the cemetery it called.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come here. Stop a spell. Remember.''
</P>
<P>
   Svelte, glistening in the rays of the early afternoon sun of an
unseasonably warm winter day, reaching up, shining out, it towered
high above the headstones immediately surrounding it and over many
of the granite spires and memorial boulders across the path on the
white side of the historic Grand Avenue cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come here,'' it called wordlessly, summoning me to visit the
place where lay the whitened bones of a black man I had known only
as the stuff of legend, as the conclusion of an often-repeated
boyhood expression that began, ``If I was as rich as ...''
</P>
<P>
   Now, most little white boys usually finished that clause with
the name of Rockefeller, or that of someone local like Amon Carter
or Sid Richardson.
</P>
<P>
   But most black boys in the Fort Worth-Dallas area finished it
with the name Bill McDonald _ Gooseneck Bill. In their eyes, he was
the man. They held him in awe. Feared him vaguely. Envied him
ferociously. Wondered how he did it.
</P>
<P>
   Still, we knew that for all his wealth, influence and power,
McDonald could not legally drink from a water fountain in a
downtown five and dime that was not specifically marked for
``colored.''
</P>
<P>
   But then, he didn't have to or want to. He could have opened his
own five and dime had he been so inclined. He opened a bank
instead.
</P>
<P>
   Located at Ninth and Jones streets, smack dab in the middle of
what once was a pulsating black Fort Worth business district of two
square blocks, it was called Fraternal Bank and Trust.
</P>
<P>
   But that's getting ahead of the story.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come here,'' said the stone. ``Think about a man who was born
a year and three months after Gen. Robert E. Lee's surrender at
Appomattox Court House in Virginia, and what he achieved during his
four-score and four years.''
</P>
<P>
   As I reflected on the unlikely prospect that a son of slaves
might rise to the prominence that McDonald achieved, a brief
documentary of his life unreeled in my mind. I pictured McDonald:
</P>
<P>
   _Growing up (one of 11 children) in a log cabin in College Mound
a few miles from Kaufman, where his father, Lee McDonald, worked as
a blacksmith.
</P>
<P>
   _As a child, working as a house boy for a local rancher and
lawyer, Capt. Z.T. Adams, and as an adolescent working as a court
messenger.
</P>
<P>
   _Attending college in Nashville, Tenn., and getting expelled
just prior to graduation for leading a student strike.
</P>
<P>
   _Returning to Texas, becoming a teacher and principal in several
rural black schools, accumulating farm land, organizing the first
black state fair, and becoming one of the leaders of the Grand
Lodge of Free and Accepted Masons.
</P>
<P>
   _Running the Texas Republican Party between 1896 and 1909.
Although millionaire Col. E.H.R. Green was supposed to be the
state's top Republican, it was his assistant _ dubbed ``Gooseneck''
by a newspaper reporter _ who distributed the patronage jobs in
customs, the post offices, internal revenue and federal agencies to
both whites and blacks.
</P>
<P>
   _Settling permanently in Fort Worth in 1906, buying the Temple
Drug Store and in 1912 opening the Fraternal Bank and Trust, the
first black-run bank in Texas. Fraternal survived the bank runs of
the Depression, although many other Fort Worth banks went under.
</P>
<P>
   _Helping Democrat Miriam ``Ma'' Ferguson defeat Dr. George Butte
in 1924 after it was discovered that the Republican gubernatorial
candidate had ties to the Ku Klux Klan.
</P>
<P>
   _Purchasing and developing land between East Humboldt and East
Terrell streets to provide quality homes for blacks, including his
own mansion.
</P>
<P>
   _Raising money for the construction of the black Masonic Temple
and a YMCA branch for blacks.
</P>
<P>
   McDonald's imposing obelisk, I reflected, befits a man of his
stature. Still, it occurred to me that McDonald's true monument is
the record of his extraordinary life of accomplishment and
contributions _ an amazing catalog of success achieved against
overwhelming odds.
</P>
<P>
   His life testifies to the abiding truth that a determined
person, given less than half a chance, can achieve anything that he
or she desires sufficiently. And during this year's Black History
Month observance, McDonald's story underscores the fact that
African-Americans individually and collectively have come farther,
in a shorter time, over a rougher road than any other people in the
history of the world.
</P>
<P>
   (Cecil Johnson is a columnist and editorial writer for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. You can e-mail him at
cecil(at)star-telegram.com or call him at (817) 390-7663. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
