<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   IOC-LOBBYING _ LAUSANNE, Switzerland _ While the topic of the
meeting here is drugs, International Olympic Committee members are
preoccupied with the tempest within their own teapot. More than 60
IOC members are here and working the cellular phones and hotel bars
trying to work out how the full committee will vote in its special
session in March. Developing color and perspective. (Roughton, Cox
News Service).
</P>
<P>
   SIERRALEONE _ Milton Boyle just wanted to move back home, set up
a commercial fishing business and give something back to the
country of his birth. Sierra Leone has endured its share of turmoil
in recent years, but Boyle had read the news and searched the
Internet for information. Things were under control. He'd heard
Freetown was safe. But he had heard wrong. (Melvin, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS and MAP.
</P>
<P>
   LATAM-PRESIDENTS-0205 _ WASHINGTON _ Presidents of Ecuador and
Peru discuss the historic peace treaty between their countries that
ended 180 years of conflict. Both Jamil Mahuad and Alberto Fujimori
expressed hope and confidence that the peace process will continue
and that they would get billions of dollars from the US government
for their effort. They held a joint, bilingual press conference at
the National Press Club Thursday. (Moscoso, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-OPEN _ WASHINGTON _ Support is building for a proposal
by Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison to change the Senate rules to allow
the public to watch the final deliberations in President Clinton's
impeachment trial. (Dart, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   w/IMPEACH-MANAGERS _ Behind the scenes with the House managers.
(Carr, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   ANTHRAX-SCARE _ ATLANTA _ Even before Thursday's anthrax threat
at downtown office and residential complex, the Centers for Disease
Control and Prevention was on the case. Will include information on
how anthrax sickens or kills. Guthrie (Husted or Tate, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   INS _ WASHINGTON _ The arrest of border inspectors in Arizona on
charges of allowing drugs and illegal immigrants to enter the
country has shaken the Immigration and Naturalization Service,
which has been working to improve its image. (Malone, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   PARK-FEES _ WASHINGTON _ The Senate Energy and Natural Resources
Committee holds a hearing on the Interior Department's Recreation
Fee Demonstration Program, which allowed national parks to charge
fees to users of programs that traditionally had been free. (Dart,
Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT _ WASHINGTON _ Coverage of the Microsoft antitrust
trial. (Glass, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   HANKAARON-GALA _ ATLANTA _ It's an event with a capital ``E.''
We look at what it is taking to pull together Friday night's Hank
Aaron Gala at the Hyatt Regency downtown -- the cash, the celebs,
the security (President Clinton is coming), the entertainment. The
event marks Aaron's 65th birthday; one day this April marks the
25th anniversary of Hank's 715th homer. (Dollar, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 13-15.
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Also moving in (l) lifestyle and (s) sportys categories.
</P>
<P>
   BROWN _ Linda Brown Thompson and Cheryl Brown Henderson,
principals in the landmark 1954 U.S. Supreme Court decision Brown
v. the Board of Education will deliver the keynote address at 7
p.m. today for a program at Sinclair Community College titled
``Bridging the Gaps: Understanding the Past to Unite Our Future.''
The women also will talk to the students earlier in the afternoon
about the lawsuit brought by their father. (Kline, Dayton Daily
News). 12. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   CHELSEA-REACT _ People magazine comes out with a cover story on
Chelsea Clinton, which has elicited protest from the White House.
For years, the media has taken a mostly hands-off approach to
coverage of Chelsea. Now that she's turning 19 and in college, is
she fair game for mainstream media as well as the tabs, which have
already done stories on her? (Harris, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   MUSEUM-MUMMIES _ ATLANTA _ Following the attempt of Emory
UNiversity's Carlos Museum to acquire Egyptian collection. (Fox,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
