A2153 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-OPEN05-COX     02-04 0542
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-OPEN05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HUTCHISON LEADING PUSH TO OPEN SENATE TRIAL DELIBERATIONS
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, a former
television reporter, is leading a bipartisan push to suspend the
Senate's century-old secrecy rule and open the final deliberations
in the Senate impeachment trial of President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``The plain fact is that the public's ability to scrutinize its
government's actions have improved dramatically since the Senate
last tried a president, and we should accept that reality,''
explained Hutchison, the primary author of a motion to allow public
viewing of the concluding debate.
</P>
<P>
   Under rules established for the 1868 impeachment trial of
President Andrew Johnson, the Senate's ``doors shall be closed for
deliberation.'' It would take a two-thirds vote of approval _ 67 of
100 senators voting _ to change the rules and allow televised
coverage. The vote on Hutchison's motion is likely to take place
next week.
</P>
<P>
   Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., has expressed reservations,
comparing the concluding Senate impeachment debate to the secret
deliberations of a trial jury. However, support for the motion
seems to be growing, and Lott is said to be reconsidering his
opposition.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times reported Thursday that ``traditionalists''
such as Sens. Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., and Ted Stevens, R-Alaska, now
favor opening the final deliberations. Both voted against opening
earlier trial debates to the public.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison was joined in her motion by one Democrat, Joe
Lieberman of Connecticut, and Republicans Chuck Hagel of Nebraska,
Susan Collins and Olympia Snowe of Maine, and Arlen Specter of
Pennsylvania. The group scheduled a news conference for Friday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman said Thursday evening that the senator was
unavailable to discuss her progress.
</P>
<P>
   But Hutchison, who was a reporter for a Houston television
station in the late 1960s, has argued that a decision as serious as
the fate of a presidency ``should not be made behind closed
doors.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a unique and historic event for the United States and
the public has a right to know how we arrived at our decision,''
Hutchison said in a statement explaining why she filed the motion.
</P>
<P>
   However, opponents have countered that opening the deliberations
would alter the tradition of jurors reaching their decision in
private, and could prolong the proceedings by prompting all 100
senators to speak for televised posterity.
</P>
<P>
   In a ``Dear Colleague'' letter to her fellow senators, Hutchison
urged even those who had voted to keep earlier procedural debates
secret to open the final deliberations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Open deliberation will give us the opportunity to explain our
decision to the public in a way that the printed record _ if it
ever becomes public _ can never do,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a simple fact of progress that visual images have been
woven into the texture of history, which once relied on only the
printed word,'' explained Hutchison. ``We are making history, and
future generations, as much as our own, deserve to know how we did
so.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
