<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Friday, Feb. 5. If you have
any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
QUAYLE (Phoenix) - Dan Quayle tries to resurrect his political
career by launching an exploratory campaign committee. What lies
ahead? By MICHAEL MURPHY. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
MEXICAN MAFIA (Phoenix) - In a matter-of-fact voice, a former
``lieutenant'' in the Mexican Mafia described how he and another
member twice attempted to kill Arizona prisons director Terry
Stewart and prison guards. His testimony revealed some of the inner
workings and cold-bloodedness of the violent prison gang. Now a
police informant, the witness detailed how several members - with
nicknames like Cool Cat, Ne Ne, Bam Bam and Chino - plotted to kill
Stewart. The plan was to shoot Stewart four times to make sure he
was dead. They each were going to leave four bullets in their guns
``just in case anyone in the restaurant tried to be a hero,'' the
informant testified during a preliminary hearing to determine
whether there is enough evidence to bound three members of the
Mexican Mafia to trial on the charges. By VICTORIA HARKER. Story
will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
AZNOTES (Phoenix) - Arizonans' views on the impeachment trial of
President Clinton. By JULIE AMPARANO. Story will move in the ``A''
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
NOTARO-COLUMN (Phoenix) - You always enter a resale clothing shop
confident that once you place the pile of once-favorite apparel on
the counter, sirens will sound. Bells will go off. The salespeople
will gather around your heap of clothing, emitting gasps of wonder
and small cries. Instead, as the door swung open and I entered the
store, I got the feeling I was a little out of place. I realized I
was the only one in the entire establishment with hair that wasn't
the color of a Teletubbie, and I suddenly felt self-conscious that
none of my facial features were impaled with a skewer the size of a
shish kebab or tire iron. By LAURI NOTARO. Story moved in the ``L''
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
AUTO-REVIEW (Phoenix) - Leave it to Subaru, always the individual,
always unique.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the all-wheel-drive champ brings out another niche vehicle
for a previously unknown niche, the Sport Utility Sedan. Or as it
says on the trunk of the jacked-up Legacy, an SUS. The SUS is built
for people who desire the snow-going, dirt-road-running capacities
of the Outback but still want the sleeker look of a sedan. The
thought of a station wagon strikes horror in many who feel
perilously close to domesticity. By BOB GOLFEN. Story moved in
the``L'' category. Embargoed for Saturday, Feb. 6. &QL; 
 &QL; 
RUSHMORE-MOVIE (Undated) - Even among off-beat movies, ``Rushmore''
is off-off-beat, wigging and wagging without need of a different
drummer. That's the sure sign of a cult hit in the making, as
people who love something different fall for ``Rushmore'' and its
anti-antihero, Max Fischer. A poor kid at a rich kid's prep
academy, Max is in danger of flunking out due to his obsessions:
first, the academy; then the school's new teacher, Miss Cross. 4
stars. By BOB FENSTER. Story moved in the ``E'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
RUSHMORE-DIRECTOR (Undated) - Director Wes Anderson also has a
potential cult hit in his pocket. The offbeat ``Rushmore'' is about
a prep school nerd who, instead of being ineffectual like most
movie dweebs, has the school wired. Anderson must have Hollywood
wired because he convinced the Disney Studio to put up $10 million
to make a strange movie whose humor is an acquired taste that many
people may never acquire. By BOB FENSTER. Story moved in the ``E''
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
CENTRAL-MOVIE In Rio the trains are so overcrowded that young men
get their seats by clambering through the windows before the doors
open. In a train station and a city so packed with life and
poverty, no one will care about the fate of a lost boy and an old
woman. Brazilian film maker Walter Salles cares, and he has made
``Central Station,'' a film as poignant in its search for the heart
of humanity as Akira Kurosawa's ``Ikiru.'' By BOB FENSTER. Story
moved in the ``E'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
LESLEYGORE-MUSIC (Phoenix) - It's the party that never seems to
end. At only 16 years old, Lesley Gore recorded the endearingly
bratty ``It's My Party'' (``And I'll cry if I want to! Cry if I
want to! Cry if I want to!,'' the chorus endlessly whines). Gore is
an interesting paradox. She's now a mature, sophisticated New
Yorker who is a regular on the Manhattan cabaret scene, but she's
eternally linked with a song written from a teenager's perspective.
But she won't bash the tune that made her the Britney Spears of her
day. By RANDY CORDOVA. Story moved in the ``E'' category. &QL;
</P>
