 &HT;    Southern happenings
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  Charleston, S.C. _ The 17th annual Southeastern Wildlife
Exposition, the largest wildlife art show in the country, is Feb.
12-14. The Wildlife Show in Marion Square Park features wildlife
and nature paintings, prints, sculpture, carvings, photography,
crafts and collectibles. In addition, there will be live animal
exhibits, retriever demonstrations, a wild game cooking contest and
dining events including a pig picking and an oyster roast. New this
year is the Sporting Village, with displays of products and
services related to hunting and fishing. 843-723-1748.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hilton Head, S.C. _ The Native Islander Gullah Celebration
kicks off Saturday with Freedom Day Festivities at Simmon's Fishing
Camp and a banquet at Hilton Head Elementary School. The activities
continue through February with a Walkathon and Wellness Expo and a
Gullah barbecue Feb. 13 and gospel celebration Feb. 14. The annual
Arts, Crafts &AMP; Food Expo at the Gullah Flea Market is Feb. 20-21.
1-800-721-7120.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Savannah, Ga. _ The Gastonian, a bed-and-breakfast inn, hosts
a series of Lowcountry culinary weekends with Lowcountry boil,
gourmet breakfasts, chef demonstrations and tastings at host chef's
restaurants. Local chefs participating are Mark Gaylord of the
Dining Group South, which includes the Olde Pink House, Anson,
Garibaldi of Savannah and Bistro Savannah (Friday-Sunday);
Elizabeth Terry, founder and owner of Elizabeth on 37th (Feb.
19-21); and Chris Nason of the Sapphire Grill (Feb. 26-28).
1-800-322-6603.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Columbus, Ga. _ The Springer Opera House, the State Theatre of
Georgia, reopens after a year of extensive renovation with Arthur
Miller's Tony Award-winning drama ``The Crucible.'' 8 p.m.
Thursday-Saturday and Feb. 11-13; 2:30 p.m. Sunday. 706-327-3688.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Mount Dora, Fla. _ The Mount Dora Arts Festival Saturday and
Sunday features live entertainment, children's activities, food and
the works of 285 juried artists competing for awards in painting,
printmaking, photography, jewelry, sculpture and more.
352-383-0880.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Jacksonville _ Soccerfest '99 on Saturday begins with the
Soccer Skills Challenge at ALLTEL Stadium 8 a.m.-1 p.m. The U.S.
Men's National Soccer Team plays the German National Soccer Team at
1 p.m., with a matchup between U.S. and German Olympic qualifying
teams following. 904-353-3309.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Houma, La. _ Mardi Gras in Terrebonne Parish Friday through
Feb. 16 is a family-oriented event with 13 parades featuring
carnival floats, bands and marching units and masked revelers
tossing beads and favors. 1-800-688-2732.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Asheville, N.C. _ The High Country Art &AMP; Craft Guild presents
the 26th annual Winterfest Art &AMP; Craft Show at Asheville Mall
Thursday through Sunday. 828-254-0072.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Lexington, Va. _ Virginia Military Institute Corps of Cadets
Parades are scheduled Friday; April 15, 21 and 23; and May 13. On
the VMI training grounds. 540-463-3777.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Fort Myers, Fla. _ The Edison Festival of Lights, opening
Friday, commemorates the birthday of southwest Florida's most
famous winter resident with events leading up to the Parade of
Lights on Feb. 20. 941-334-2999.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Chattanooga _ River Gallery in the Bluff View Art District
presents ``Jamaa,'' featuring clay masks with found objects by
contemporary folk artist Sammie Nicely and handblown glass by his
nephew, Calvin Nicely. The works combine African and Appalachian
influences. Opening Monday; through February. Artist reception is
Friday evening. 1-800-374-2923.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Montgomery _ The Montgomery Museum of Fine Arts opens four
exhibitions Saturday: ``The Lamps of Tiffany: Highlights From the
Egon and Hildegard Neustadt Collection,'' ``Akari Light Sculptures
of Isamu Noguchi,'' ``Cam Langley Glass'' and African-American
works from the collection of Dr. Albert Holloway and Dr. Gail
Holloway. Through March 28. 334-244-5700.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Silver Springs, Fla. _ George Jones leads off Silver Springs'
1999 Concert Series on Saturday. The country music legend will
perform his greatest hits such as ``White Lightning'' and ``One
Woman Man'' on the park's Twin Oaks Mansion concert stage. The park
is located east of Ocala. 352-236-2121.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Cypress Gardens, Fla. _ Cypress Gardens presents a series of
weekend concerts including Guy Lombardo's Royal Canadians with the
Glenn Miller Orchestra (Saturday-Sunday); Tommy Dorsey Orchestra
(Feb. 13-14); Four Aces (Feb. 20-21); and Four Lads (Feb. 27-28).
Additional concerts are scheduled through May 2. 1-800-282-2123.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Biloxi, Miss. _ Mississippi Gulf Coast Mardi Gras, Saturday
through Feb. 16, celebrates three centuries of revelry since the
first parade in 1699. Parades every weekend in Gulf towns including
Waveland, Bay St. Louis, Gautier, Pascagoula, Biloxi, Gulfport,
Pass Christian and Iberville. 228-896-6699, Ext. 210.
</P>
