A2157 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-XFILES-SECRETS05-COX     02-04 0422
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-XFILES-SECRETS05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Spilling secrets: `X-Files' clearing up mysteries
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Be careful what you ask for, X-philes, because you're about to
get it by the boxcarful.
</P>
<P>
   For years, followers of ``The X-Files'' have been panting for
some solid answers as to how the show's fiendishly Byzantine
conspiracy _ a shadowy alliance between evil aliens and some humans
_ actually works.
</P>
<P>
   In a two-parter beginning Sunday and concluding Feb. 14, creator
Chris Carter gives the show's devotees a Valentine's gift, not only
explaining a lot of the show's mythology but exploding it as well,
setting up the remainder of the series (one more season after this
one, in all likelihood) to head off in some new directions.
</P>
<P>
   For once, the promise of real answers is not just another of
Carter's coy teases. The strange thing (in a TV series full of
strange things) is that once you know it all, it may feel like a
bit of a morning-after letdown.
</P>
<P>
   And fans who followed last summer's ``X-Files'' movie and the
ensuing Internet babble already know more than they may think they
know.
</P>
<P>
   Although there's plenty of action (and the death of more than
one of the players in the mythology), the two episodes are, by
necessity, talkier than normal for ``The X-Files,'' with big chunks
of exposition tossed out like meat to the show's hungry fans.
</P>
<P>
   FBI agents Mulder (David Duchovny) and Scully (Gillian Anderson)
are basically just along for the ride in this two-parter, as the
central characters are the mysterious Cigarette Smoking Man and his
troubled son, FBI agent Spender, whom Smoking Man is trying to lure
over to the dark side. A smoke-wreathed figure who's been
(literally) in the shadows for the show's five-season run, Smoking
Man finally gets dragged out into the daylight, his past, secrets
and even his name revealed (mostly in the second part).
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Mulder kiddingly refers to the fashion cliche
about the color gray being ``the new black,'' and that throwaway
line could also apply to the twisted morality at work in ``The
X-Files.'' Even bad guys have their reasons, it turns out, and
sometimes the reasons aren't so bad. Black hats are hard to find;
the morally gray is much more fashionable.
</P>
<P>
   ``The X-Files'' Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   9 p.m. Sunday and Feb. 14 on Fox .
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: The truth is finally here.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
