<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2174 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-DRUGS-0205-COX     02-04 0582
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-DRUGS-0205-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MEXICO ANNOUNCES NEW DRUG WAR STRATEGY AS KEY U.S. VOTE DRAWS
NEAR
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Just weeks before the annual debate in Washington
over Mexico's role in the drug war, Mexican officials announced
Thursday a new high-tech strategy for cracking down on narcotics
smuggling through that country.
</P>
<P>
   The plan calls for spending between $400 million and $500
million over the next three years. Much of the money will be for
satellite technology, and new ships and airplanes to intercept drug
smugglers passing through Mexican waters and territory.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will use the best technology available in the world,'' said
Mexico's Interior Secretary Francisco Labastida. ``This is a total
war on narco-trafficking.''
</P>
<P>
   Labastida appeared at a news conference here to announce the
plan with Mexican Attorney General Jorge Madrazo, Secretary of
Defense Enrique Cervantes and Secretary of the Navy Ramon Lorenzo
Franco.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of this month, the Clinton Administration must decide
whether to recommend that the U.S. Congress ``certify'' Mexico as a
reliable partner in the international war on drugs. If Mexico is
not re-certified, Congress can withhold U.S. aid and impose trade
sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Congress will have about a month to debate and vote on the
administration's recommendation.
</P>
<P>
   The annual certification of America's drug-fighting partners --
which Mexican officials have routinely criticized as abrasive to
relations between the two countries -- was not mentioned at the
news conference.
</P>
<P>
   In previous years, some U.S. lawmakers have cited corruption
among Mexican military, police and political figures as reasons for
not certifying the country as an honest partner in the war on
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, however, Congress has given approval to Mexico every
year since 1987.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 70 percent of the cocaine smuggled into the United
States comes through Mexico, which has struggled to contain the
spread of corruption among officials charged with catching
traffickers.
</P>
<P>
   One of the more scandalous recent revelations of corruption was
in 1997, when --just before a certification vote -- Mexico's drug
czar was arrested and charged with protecting one of the country's
biggest cocaine traffickers.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the governor of Quintano Roo, Mario Villanueva, is
reportedly under investigation by Mexican authorities for ties to
traffickers -- a charge he has repeatedly denied.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican and U.S. authorities say the Caribbean coast state of
Quintana Roo has become a prime corridor of drug trafficking in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing the new plan Tuesday, Mexican officials stressed
that they will need to develop honest personnel to employ the new
technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``The selection and training of human resources will be of vital
importance to guarantee the success of this project,'' Cervantes,
chief of Mexico's military, said.
</P>
<P>
   The plan, which has already been implemented, calls for the
establishment of a central command center that will receive
satellite and radar information from throughout the country. The
command center will alert teams to check on suspicious aircraft or
vessels.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico is purchasing dozens of new airplanes, high-speed boats,
helicopters, amphibious landing crafts, as well as mobile X-ray
machines to screen both humans and vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
