<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2182 &Cx1f; ttf-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT &LR;      02-04 0486
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT </SLUG>
  
(lh) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Friday, Feb. 5. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The N.Y. Times News Service
Night Supervisor is Lynn Hoogenboom; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
lyhoog(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-TRIAL (Washington) _ The Senate moved to bring President
Clinton's impeachment trial to a prompt conclusion, rejecting a
last-ditch request by House prosecutors to summon Monica Lewinsky
for live testimony. Republicans also shrank from a plan to declare
the president guilty without ousting him from office. (Summary from
wires.) By R.W. Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   With photos.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-ASSESS (Washington) _ As the Senate began hurtling
toward the end of the impeachment trial, the last major question
before it is whether it will find a way to bridge party differences
and rebuke President Clinton while leaving him in office. But
finding the right words, the right formula and the right timing is
proving elusive. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   CATHOLIC-COLLEGES (Undated) _ From Notre Dame to Georgetown,
most Catholic colleges and universities operate as secular
institutions that make only a respectful nod to Catholic traditions
in their mission statement. But now a committee of American
bishops, in response to a Vatican request, has proposed
requirements that would make Catholic colleges and universities
more answerable to the Church _ a move that has alarmed many
Catholic scholars and teachers, who fear their autonomy and
academic freedom are being threatened. By Karen W. Arenson.
</P>
<P>
   With photos.
</P>
<P>
   NY-SUSPECT-SHOT (New York) _ An unarmed African immigrant with
no criminal record was killed by four New York City police officers
who fired 41 shots at him in the lobby of the man's Bronx apartment
building. By Michael Cooper.
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-ANNIVERSARY (Tehran, Iran) _ As Iran marks the 20th
anniversary of its Islamic revolution, there is a widening gap
between Iranians and the defining event of their recent past. More
than half of Iran's 68 million people were born since the events
that toppled a king and stunned the world; millions more can barely
remember them. Among older Iranians, many regard the revolution as
no longer relevant to today's problems. By Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   HUSSEIN _ King Hussein of Jordan suffered internal organ failure
Thursday after last-ditch cancer treatment and was due to be flown
home in critical condition, officials said. (Summary from wires.)
</P>
<P>
   SCREENWRITERS-PAY (Hollywood) _ A group of Hollywood's top
screenwriters have broken through a longstanding financial barrier
by reaching a highly unusual, almost revolutionary, collective
agreement under which Columbia Pictures has agreed to pay them a
portion of the profits of successful movies in addition to their
usual writing fees. By James Sterngold.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-04-99 1833EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990204.0312 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2186 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-CENSURE-HNS &LR;      02-04 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-CENSURE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS PUSH RESOLUTION CENSURING CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN and JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two leading Democrats are close to unveiling a
censure resolution that the Senate could vote on prior to a
guilt-or-innocence vote on the articles of impeachment against
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Sens. Daniel Patrick Moynihan of New York and Dianne Feinstein
of California want to blunt Republican criticism that a censure
resolution is too vague and could be repealed by a future Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, GOP ardor for a harsher ``finding-of-fact''
resolution cooled considerably Thursday amid an avalanche of
Democratic criticism that guaranteed it would not win bipartisan
support.
</P>
<P>
   Such a resolution would put the Senate on record as concluding
that Clinton committed perjury and obstruction of justice in the
Monica Lewinsky affair. By contrast, a censure resolution would
reprimand the president in less specific terms.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats have argued that a finding-of-fact resolution would be
an unconstitutional means of voting to convict Clinton without
bearing the responsibility of removing him from office.
</P>
<P>
   That resolution is ``perilously close to being dead,'' said Sen.
Pete Domenici, R-N.M., one of its chief supporters. If no
Democratic support surfaces, ``I will not offer it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Ted Stevens, R-Alaska, said the proposal ``is sort of out
there, sort of in nether land.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats on Thursday were pushing the censure option. ``Our
hope is that we can move to the articles very quickly and then move
to a censure resolution,'' said Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle
of South Dakota. ``We've been working on it and I'm very pleased
with our progress in that regard.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Senate unlikely to muster the 67 votes needed to
convict Clinton and remove him for office, Democrats are gambling
that censure will rise as the chief alternative to outright
acquittal.
</P>
<P>
   Moynihan and Feinstein are aligned with a Republican, Sen.
Robert Bennett of Utah. Bennett characterized his collaboration
with the Democrats as ``a work in progress.''
</P>
<P>
   The two Democrats presented a draft of the resolution to a
closed-door meeting of Democratic senators on Thursday. The
Democrats are to likely to consider a final version Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Many Republicans, however, remain cool to censuring the
president. ``I personally don't believe a lot of people will want
to do it,'' said Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't think it's sufficient,'' said Sen. Olympia J.
Snowe, R-Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Key sticking points among Republicans over censure have to do
with timing and long-range impact. Sen. Susan Collins of Maine said
Thursday a censure resolution could be repealed by a future
Congress, while the finding-of-fact resolution could not.
</P>
<P>
   Moynihan said the Democratic censure resolution would address
that concern.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Moynihan-Feinstein plan, the Senate impeachment trial
would be adjourned and a vote on the censure measure would then
take place in a regular Senate legislative session. That would
precede a return to the trial and a final vote on the articles of
impeachment, Moynihan said.
</P>
<P>
   If the Senate votes on censure before the final vote of the
trial, ``there's no ambiguity about what happened there,'' Moynihan
said.
</P>
<P>
   Moynihan warned that delaying a vote on censure until after the
vote on the impeachment articles would result in ``endless''
amendments. The effect, he said, would be ``you lose people on both
sides.''
</P>
<P>
   But even if it is voted on prior to a guilt-or-innocence vote, a
censure resolution still could be revoked in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Moynihan spokesman Michael Waterman acknowledged that ``we're in
unchartered waters about how you could deconstruct this in the
future.''
</P>
<P>
   However, he added, ``the hope is it would be unrevocable because
it's bonded more tightly to the Senate sitting as a court of
impeachment. This is an attempt to say to future Congresses that
this censure resolution is inextricably linked to the trial.''
</P>
<P>
   Bennett said censure should come after the trial. ``We do things
one at a time here,'' he said. He described support for a censure
resolution is ``still very fluid.''
</P>
<P>
   Moynihan said he was convinced there would be ``no problem''
getting all the Democrats to agree to the censure motion.
</P>
<P>
   Daschle concurred. ``If you voted for censure prior to the time
you voted on the articles themselves, you would be sending a clear
message that ... we weren't exonerating (Clinton's) actions, we
were not finding the president completely without fault here.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass., said he thought ``a censure motion has
very strong support on our side and there are some people (in
support of it) on the Republican side.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Byron Dorgan, D-N.D., said the majority of Democrats have
supported the censure proposal from the start.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those of us who vote against conviction feel strongly that his
conduct was wrong and we want to express ourselves on that.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Richard Durbin, D-Ill., said he didn't know of a single
Democrat who would vote against censure.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to make it clear that the president's personal conduct
brought disrespect to his office,'' Durbin said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
