</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRISONS-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERT CITES `LEVEL OF DESPAIR' IN TEXAS PRISONS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ An expert on maximum security prisons said
Thursday that Texas' solitary confinement cells are among the most
inhumane he's ever seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The level of despair ... was unparalleled in my experience,''
said Professor Craig Haney, chairman of the University of
California-Santa Cruz psychology department, who has studied
high-security prisons for 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   A frequent expert witness in court proceedings about prison
conditions, Haney was testifying on behalf of Texas inmates in a
hearing before senior U.S. District Judge William Wayne Justice.
The judge is deciding whether to prolong his longstanding
jurisdiction over the 140,000-inmate Texas Department of Criminal
Justice.
</P>
<P>
   In a December visit to three Texas units, Haney said he saw
inmates smeared with feces; urine puddles in cells and hallways;
and apparently mentally ill inmates screaming and banging their
heads against the wall. Others were sullen and withdrawn, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are not subtle diagnostic issues,'' he said. The
isolated inmates were ``in profound distress and pain,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was shattering,'' he said of his visits, adding, ``I was
told this was an everyday occurrence.'' He disagreed with a prison
lawyers' assertion that the bizarre behavior he witnessed were
efforts to grab attention.
</P>
<P>
   Lack of hygiene items, reading materials, education and
recreation contribute to the degrading atmosphere, Haney told the
judge. Inmates are kept in their solitary cells for all but five
hours a week, as specified by previous court rulings, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many complained the deterioration of hygiene was part of their
overall (psychological) decline,'' Haney said. ``They felt they had
their dignity taken away,'' because the inmates don't have access
to commissary items such as deodorant and are given one roll of
toilet paper a week.
</P>
<P>
   With reading materials restricted to law books and legal papers,
and in-cell televisions not allowed, many solitary-confinement
inmates rely on radios to ``anesthesize themselves,'' Haney said,
describing the level of deprivation he observed as ``rock-bottom.''
</P>
<P>
   Prisons routinely _ and constitutionally _ inflict psychological
damage on inmates, Haney conceded to prison attorneys. But those in
Texas' 8,000 solitary confinement, or ``administrative
segregation'' cells, are subjected to far harsher conditions than
inmates in some of the nation's toughest lockups, including the
federal prison at Marion, Ill., and the California ``super-seg''
prison at Pelican Bay, Haney said.
</P>
<P>
   Conditions in the three cited Texas units _ Estelle, Beto and
Eastham _ ``were as bad or worse than any I've seen,'' said Haney.
</P>
<P>
   His testimony followed that of a medical expert who said an
analysis of 1998 inmate deaths from HIV, cardiac problems and
cancer showed an ``extremely alarming'' incidence of ``poor care''
given to sick inmates.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Catarina Kiefa, an expert in biostatistics and preventative
medicine at the University of Alabama-Birmingham, said ``it would
behoove them to do something very fast about it. It would suggest
there are very profound problems in the system.''
</P>
<P>
   Kiefa agreed with other experts' analyses that non-physicians
who treat inmates were not adequately supervised. At least two of
the 73 analyzed inmate deaths were preventable, she stated, adding,
``the human body is very resilient. Just because the person didn't
die doesn't mean the care was appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   The experts' testimony came in the third week of a four-week
hearing. Justice was asked to reconsider his role in the Ruiz
prison-oversight case by new Attorney General John Cornyn, whose
team of lawyers have attempted to show that the state has made
great strides in complying with Justice's previous rulings to
improve health care, reduce crowding and end ``cruel and unusual''
conditions. Justice has handled the Ruiz prison reform case, which
is based on a class-action lawsuit filed in 1972 by inmate David
Ruiz, for about 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   A new federal law mandates that Justice end his oversight role
unless he deems there are on-going constitutional violations.
Justice's ruling is expected in several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
