<P>
   ABOUT-CARS-SATURN (Detroit) _ Necessity is the mother of
invention, and for the Saturn Corp. of General Motors, a rather
simple invention is generating a much-needed lift in sales of its
aging car line. After a recent test-drive of a Saturn SC2, I was
not surprised that the new coupe was doing so well. Even with the
third door, which is nearly invisible when the doors are closed,
the car has the sporty look that two-door buyers like. Yet the
third door opens new markets: Most Saturn coupe owners are single,
but the three-door may prove attractive to parents with small
children, who like the look but need more practicality. By Michelle
Krebs.
</P>
<P>
   CAR-SMART-REARDOORS (Undated) _ The third door on the Saturn
coupe is not your father's _ nor your grandfather's suicide door.
The rear-hinged doors became known as suicide doors because
passengers in those pre-safety belt days could open the doors,
which would catch the wind from the moving car making it impossible
to close them while the car was in motion, and risked falling out
of the vehicle. The biggest difference between the suicide doors of
old and the rear-hinged access door on the three-door Saturn coupe
and some extended cab pickups is the rear doors cannot be opened
unless the front door is open. By Michelle Krebs.
</P>
