<DOCNO> NYT19990204.0317 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 18:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2197 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CATHOLIC-COLLEGES-ART     02-04 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CATHOLIC-COLLEGES-ART-950(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CATHOLIC COLLEGES ALARMED BY CALL FOR MORE ACCOUNTABILITY TO
CHURCH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Ind., Mass., Md., Pa.)  (ART ADV: Photo of students at Fordham University is being sent to
NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By KAREN W. ARENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Fordham bills itself as ``New York City's Jesuit
university.'' But apart from a courtyard statue of Mary and Jesus
and handsome stained-glass windows in a student lounge on its Rose
Hill campus in the Bronx, there are few outward signs of Fordham's
Roman Catholic identity.
</P>
<P>
   Mass is not required. There are no crucifixes in the classrooms.
The faculty of more than 500 includes only 37 Jesuits. And although
the university's president is a Jesuit, the chairman of the board,
the chairwoman of the theology department and the faculty chairman
are not even Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   From Notre Dame to Georgetown, most Catholic colleges and
universities operate similarly _ as secular institutions that make
only a respectful nod to Catholic traditions in their mission
statement.
</P>
<P>
   But a committee of American bishops, in response to a Vatican
request, has proposed requirements that would make Catholic
colleges and universities more answerable to the Church _ a move
that has alarmed many Catholic scholars and teachers, who fear
their autonomy and academic freedom are being threatened.
</P>
<P>
   At a meeting in Washington this week, the Association of
Catholic Colleges and Universities discussed ideas for a
counterproposal that they would present to the committee by May.
The full National Conference of Bishops is expected to vote on the
issue later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the bishops' requirements in particular have caused
concern among educators. One calls for university presidents to be
``faithful Catholics'' and for new presidents to make a profession
of faith and take an oath of fidelity to the church. A second calls
for theology professors, who are now subject to the same criteria
for hiring and promotion as other academic appointees, to be
approved by church officials. The last requirement directs colleges
and universities to fill a majority of the positions on faculties
and boards of trustees with ``faithful Catholics.''
</P>
<P>
   To many Catholic educators, these proposals are blind to the
realities of American higher education: They would handicap them in
recruiting faculty members and students and in receiving government
money, and they raise legal concerns on issues like tenure.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will marginalize our institutions,'' said the Rev. Joseph
O'Hare, president of Fordham. ``The proposals are well-intentioned,
but they might have just the opposite effect they are intended to
have.''
</P>
<P>
   In an article in the Jan. 30 issue of America, the weekly Jesuit
journal of opinion, the Rev. Edward Malloy, president of the
University of Notre Dame, and J. Donald Monan, chancellor of Boston
College, found the proposals ``profoundly detrimental to Catholic
higher education.''
</P>
<P>
   In an earlier issue, the magazine called them ``unworkable and
dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone sees the proposals as a threat. The Rev. James
Conn, a dean and professor of canon law at St. Mary's Seminary and
University in Baltimore, said the concepts already exist in the
church's canon law and are entirely appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was not a whole lot of attention being paid to them,''
he said. ``Now we're saying that they are not going to go away.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. David O'Connell, president of the Catholic University
of America in Washington, says he does not believe the proposals
will destroy academic freedom or institutional autonomy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do believe that the church should clearly be involved in the
institutions that exist under its sponsorship,'' said O'Connell,
whose university is the only national university of the Roman
Catholic Church in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   While other college presidents have objected to being required
to make public oaths of allegiance to the church, O'Connell recited
both a profession of faith and an oath of fidelity when he was
installed as president in November. He said he was baffled that
others were surprised by his actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The profession of faith that I made is the same profession
that is recited by millions of Catholics each Sunday,'' O'Connell
said. ``The oath is a further expression of commitment to church
teaching, something appropriate to my role as president but also
appropriate to my place within the communion of the Catholic
Church.''
</P>
<P>
   Although many Catholic universities around the world are already
under church jurisdiction, those in the United States _ established
by orders like the Jesuits and the Benedictines or by dioceses _
were pulled into a more secular orbit decades ago, partly because
of the need for government funds but also because of the less
religious nature of American culture itself.
</P>
<P>
   The distance widened in the 1960s, spurred by the freer spirit
promoted after the Second Vatican Council was convened and by the
shrinking participation in religious orders, which forced colleges
once run by the clergy to look increasingly to laymen, even
non-Catholics, to fill classrooms and board rooms.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure to reverse these trends comes from Pope John Paul
II, who has sought to reassert the church's primacy in many spheres
and to step back from Vatican II. In 1990, after extensive
consultation with higher education officials, the pope spelled out
his vision in a paper entitled Ex Corde Ecclesiae, or ``From the
Heart of the Church,'' where, he said, universities were born. It
acknowledged cultural and legal differences around the world, but
left details to be worked out region by region.
</P>
<P>
   American church and university leaders have tried three times to
spell out specific norms for Catholic colleges and universities. A
first attempt was deemed overly binding. A second draft was
approved by the National Conference of Catholic Bishops in 1995 by
a vote of 224-6. It affirmed respect for church authority but
called for institutional autonomy and academic freedom.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But the Vatican rejected that version and directed the Americans
to develop a more ``juridical'' version that explicitly addressed
the relationships between church officials and colleges. It is that
attempt, fashioned by a panel of five canon law experts and led by
Cardinal Anthony Bevilacqua of Philadelphia, that so alarmed many
university presidents when it was presented to the bishops'
conference in November.
</P>
<P>
   Like other institutions of higher education, the more than 230
Catholic colleges and universities in the United States are
chartered by local government bodies, accredited by peers from
other academic institutions and receive little or no money from the
church. The colleges, which have more than 600,000 students,
express their Catholic identity in a variety of ways; for most,
however, it is a subtle but distinctive theme.
</P>
<P>
   Fordham's health center, for example, does not dispense condoms
or birth control pills or advice on abortions. The university
refused to grant a group of gay and lesbian students club status or
to give them financial support.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most important, in the Jesuit tradition, the college
emphasizes community service and tries to provide a moral grounding
for its students. All students are required to take two theology
courses, where they discuss concepts like ``what is religion?'' and
look at world religions, including Catholicism _ courses that take
an analytical approach and in which teachers might even differ from
the church.
</P>
<P>
   Catholic university presidents list an array of problems they
would face if the latest proposals were adopted. One is whether
independent trustees would surrender their authority to the church.
Another is that the emphasis on ``faithful Catholics'' could cause
non-Catholics who make financial and academic contributions to the
university to feel like second-class citizens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want Protestants, Jews, agnostics, Buddhists and
others to think they have no place here,'' said the Rev. William
Leahy, president of Boston College. ``I don't want the message sent
that we only tolerate them, that they'll be second in priority.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet another difficulty is how to determine who is a faithful
Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does that mean we inquire into people's private lives?'' asked
O'Hare, Fordham's president. ``That would be very distasteful. And
in today's culture, we would not want to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though he has pledged himself to his Jesuit order, O'Hare
said he was put off by the idea of university presidents being
asked to make a public profession of faith and an oath of fidelity
to the Catholic Church. Asked what he would do, he expressed
uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's as if I were a married man, and my wife said, `We can't
go on this way,''' he said. ``I'd have to make a decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, many Catholic universities are already making
changes. Some, like Georgetown University in Washington and St.
Francis College in Brooklyn, are putting crucifixes in classrooms
again. Others, like Fordham, are establishing new institutes and
research initiatives to pursue religious issues. Boston College has
created a ``vice president for university mission and ministry,''
and now orients new faculty members about the college's Jesuit
heritage.
</P>
<P>
   As the colleges seek to redefine their Catholic identity, a
constant concern is the reaction of their students, many of them
non-Catholic. While some may hunger for a stronger church presence,
others are wary, and say they would not attend a Catholic
university if it were subject to the tenets now being proposed by
the bishops' committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it happened tomorrow,'' said Ryan Brenizer, a junior at
Fordham, ``I would consider transferring.''
</P>
<P>
   Brenizer, a Baptist, said he chose Fordham because of a
full-tuition scholarship and its rigorous _ and nondoctrinaire _
academic program. ``As part of your education, you are supposed to
be able to examine your own values, and risk them,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
