<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 18:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2214 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FRENCH-ART-REVIEW-2TA     02-04 0873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRENCH-ART-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
18TH CENTURY FRENCH DRAWINGS: ENLIGHTENMENT AND LUST IN
18TH-CENTURY FRANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Exhibition notes are at end of review.) 
(bl)  
By HOLLAND COTTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Like every historical epoch, the 18th century in
France was, morally speaking, the best and the worst of times. And
its extremes are reflected in its art.
</P>
<P>
   The endless depictions of erotic sport in the era are reminders
of a royal court notorious for lubricity. Louis XV maintained a
rotating harem at Versailles; his trusted mistress, Madame de
Pompadour, helped to keep it stocked. She even had hopes that her
own daughter might catch his roving eye, although her ambitions
were disappointed when the child died at 10.
</P>
<P>
   This was also the century of the Enlightenment, when
intellectual curiosity was an astringent tonic. One sees its
bracing effects in portraits, including those of Madame de
Pompadour. In one after another, wide-awake, self-amused faces
suggest that the human race, or at least a privileged portion of
it, had suddenly ascended a notch or two up the evolutionary
ladder.
</P>
<P>
   All these impressions are borne out in ``Eighteenth Century
French Drawings in New York Collections,'' a show at the
Metropolitan Museum of Art put together by Perrin Stein, of the
museum, and Mary Tavener Holmes, a guest curator. And they are
further illustrated by several smaller exhibitions elsewhere in the
city.
</P>
<P>
   At the Frick Collection, for example, Francois-Hubert Drouais'
renowned portrait of Madame de Pompadour has just settled in on
short-term loan from the National Gallery in London. Berry-Hill
Gallery next door is offering 18th-century French paintings, and
Wildenstein &AMP; Co. down the street has assembled some choice
drawings from the period. Fold in an array of decorative arts on
display at Rosenberg &AMP; Stiebel, and Manhattan is, at the moment, a
French rococo town.
</P>
<P>
   But the Met's show with 100 works from local public and private
collections offers the broadest chronological sweep. It begins
early, with a red-chalk drawing by Claude Gillot depicting satyrs
in a woodland struggling to pull a cart from the mud while their
passenger, a female faun, looks on in slump-shouldered pique.
</P>
<P>
   Gillot, who died in 1722, was a routinier, and the picture, even
with its slapstick brio, is nothing to linger over. But he was
among the very first artists to test out the components of the
style now known as rococo, and its basic formula is here: a
high-precision mix of nature and artifice, theater and everyday
life.
</P>
<P>
   These elements marry unforgettably in the work of Gillot's
younger colleague Antoine Watteau, one of the supreme luminaries of
European art. Watteau seems to have been an adorable man despite,
or maybe because of, his frayed-wire temperament, all sparks and
short-circuits, pushed to the limit by illness. (One gets some
sense of it in Rosalba Carriera's pastel portrait of him in the
Museo Civico in Treviso, Italy, where he has the tensile,
thoroughbred delicacy of a whippet.) The same feeling comes across
in the six Watteau drawings in the Met show.
</P>
<P>
   Probably the earliest is the Rembrandtesque figure of a peasant
woman. Watteau's line doesn't have much sweep yet; it seems jittery
and crabbed, as if his hand had stayed pressed to the page. But his
innovative layering of red and black chalk, eventually to be
augmented by white, is already in place.
</P>
<P>
   His scrupulous copy of a 16th-century Italian landscape is
fascinating evidence of self-education by an artist who worked
outside the academic mainstream. But the really marvelous things
come next: a graceful study of a not-young nude man; another of a
chubby actor's head, and two pages of superb drawings of women.
</P>
<P>
   In one, the artist sketches the same model's head four times,
tilting it this way and that, as if he was mesmerized by her
swept-back hair. In the second, a seated women in a striped gown
turns to one side with a demure but yielding protest; her skirt is
a turbulent froth of white chalk.
</P>
<P>
   Drawing doesn't get better than this, and Watteau, who died at
37, attracted countless imitators intent on recycling the ``fete
galante'' theme he more or less invented, in which lovers in
Arcadian settings play and dream under the shadow of time. Two of
these painters are in the show: Nicolas Lancret, with a pretty but
brittle drawing of a couple perusing a songbook, and Jean-Baptiste
Pater, with a distorted image of a man whose bulky body is topped
by an impossibly tiny, peevish face.
</P>
<P>
   Given the high standard of technical competence in the period,
this figure comes as a bit of shock. It also provides a welcome
break from the acres of fluff turned out by skilled but sparkless
practitioners like Charles-Antoine Coypel (look for his simpering
Tartuffish self-portrait) and Carle Vanloo, court favorites who
forged careers out of flattery and who seem to have been regarded
as a snooze even in their day.
</P>
<P>
   Francois Boucher, purveyor of high-priced erotica par
excellence, makes an uncharacteristically decorous appearance here
with an ``Adoration of the Shepherds.'' But the show snaps to life
with the work of Jean-Baptiste Oudry.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Oudry specialized in hunting scenes like the noisy little
picture of a hyena attacked by dogs seen at the Met, and his royal
male patrons couldn't get enough of them. (Another vivid and
repellent example is a highlight of the Wildenstein show.) But he
also did landscapes, and his drawings of the gardens at Arcueil, a
decaying estate not far from Paris, seem to emerge from an entirely
different sensibility.
</P>
<P>
   Arcueil's parkland attracted many artists. Most concentrated on
its deserted staircases and pavilions; Charles-Joseph Natoire added
people to the scene, as if he couldn't bear the emptiness. But
emptiness was what Oudry loved. In his Arcueil drawings he banished
every living creature and concentrated on light, silence and
vegetation reasserting its power over human design.
</P>
<P>
   This interaction between nature and culture was of equal
importance to French artists of the next generation, among them
Jean-Honore Fragonard. Like his teacher, Boucher, he was a virtuoso
of the stylishly naughty vignette and the ingratiating portrait.
But his best work was inspired by Watteau's expansive, quicksilver
vision of human life as a tragicomedy with the stage lights always
dimming, and of nature as a kind of untamable, vivacious
intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly it animates two of his outstanding contributions to
the Met show. In the red-chalk ``Gathering at Woods' Edge,'' trees
unearthly in their immensity roil and seethe against the sky,
overwhelming the specklike figures beneath them. And in the
chalk-and-wash ``View of a Park,'' women with parasols drift
through a scene, vaporous as a Chinese landscape, that seems to be
viewed through a rain-drenched window pane.
</P>
<P>
   Fragonard was ruined, in every sense, by the French Revolution.
The Met exhibit ends with that wrenching historical episode, and
the gathering of work in the final gallery feels confused,
disjointed and conflicted in a peculiarly modern way.
</P>
<P>
   An insipid vignette of an aristocratic musicale, ``Perfect
Harmony'' by Jean-Michel Moreau, hangs near Jean-Baptist Greuze's
depiction of a mad bourgeois housewife assaulting her family. A
luxuriant, cushiony pastel self-portrait by Elisabeth-Louise Vignee
Le Brun, portraitist to Marie Antoinette, rubs shoulders with an
eyewitness sketch of the guillotined head of Robespierre.
</P>
<P>
   By the time that Enlightment-spawned terrorist had met his fate,
the world of the 18th century had irrevocably changed. But anyone
eager to recapture its essence can do so at the Frick, where Madame
de Pompadour holds court these days.
</P>
<P>
   In Drouais' portrait, begun in the year before her death at 42,
she is swathed in ribbons, lace and flowered Chinese silk and,
hedged in by books and furniture, looks like a giant, just-bloomed
florabunda rose.
</P>
<P>
   The walls of her salon are empty of paintings; maybe Drouias was
reluctant to give air time to his competition. But the Frick has
made up for this by surrounding her with artists of her time. Some,
like Boucher and Greuze, were her favorites. Others, like
Jean-Baptiste-Sime Chardin, were not.
</P>
<P>
   Chardin doesn't figure in the Met or the Wildenstein shows. He
is thought to have done little drawing; only a few early examples
survive. But two of his small, exquisite oil paintings immediately
flank the Drouais, and they represent the French 18th-century
spirit at its finest.
</P>
<P>
   One painting is a somber still life of plums, cucumbers, a dark
bottle and a clear glass of water that together suggest a
different, more elemental notion of sustenance than is conveyed by
the high-cultural clutter in Madame de Pompadour's portrait.
</P>
<P>
   The other picture, ``Lady With a Bird Organ,'' depicts a woman,
probably Chardin's wife, playing a kind of harmonium as she glances
over at a canary, which she is encouraging to sing.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, her flowered dress is a simpler version of Madame
de Pompadour's; her chair equally elegant but less thronelike. She
is set deep back into the picture rather than in the foreground.
And rather than generating a halo, as Madame de Pompadour seems to
do, she is touched by natural light from a tall window.
</P>
<P>
   One tends to think of Chardin, along with Watteau and Mozart, as
being beyond his time, his material modesty and emotional
discretion a spiritual advance on a deeply flawed age. But ``good''
and ``bad'' are always hard to sort out. After all, the woman in
his Frick painting and Drouais' Madame de Pompadour share the same
18th-century face: expectant, alert, half-smiling. And behind both,
darkness gathers in a corner. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   EXHIBITION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `EIGHTEENTH-CENTURY FRENCH DRAWINGS IN NEW YORK COLLECTIONS'
</P>
