<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 18:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2217 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BELL-ATLANTIC-2TAKES-     02-04 1005
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELL-ATLANTIC-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELL ATLANTIC'S OUTLOOK IS BETTER THAN IT SEEMS
</HEADLINE>
  (bl)  
By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   This year is only five weeks old, but by some measures it
already seems that 1999 will not be kind to Bell Atlantic Corp.,
the nation's biggest local phone company.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Bell Atlantic _ which serves 21.5 million households
and more than 2 million businesses from Maine to Virginia _ lost
out in the bidding to acquire Airtouch Communications Inc., one of
the world's top wireless phone companies. Then AT&AMP;T Corp. unveiled
a uniform 10-cents-a-minute communications package aimed at least
partly at Bell Atlantic's existing wireless business.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, AT&AMP;T formed a venture to offer local phone service
over cable television lines owned by Time Warner Inc., the main
cable operator in New York City, the heart of Bell Atlantic's
territory. And then, just two days ago, MCI Worldcom Inc. revived
its own plan to offer local service in New York.
</P>
<P>
   So why is there a growing sense in the telecommunications
industry that Bell Atlantic's prospects are looking up these days?
Why have investors bid up Bell Atlantic's stock 11 percent this
year, even as shares of the other Baby Bells have lost value?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is that for all of the efforts by others to chip away
at Bell Atlantic's lucrative turf, the company's long-term
strategic picture is finally coming into focus. Bell Atlantic is
poised to become the first Baby Bell given the keys to the $80
billion long-distance kingdom. It is moving fast to become a player
in the market for high-speed data services. And despite the
Airtouch embarrassment, Bell Atlantic still has a strong global
portfolio in the fast-growing wireless business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bell Atlantic is one of the largest companies in what is
perhaps the premier growth industry in the United States today,''
said Eric Strumingher, a communications analyst for Paine Webber.
``They are navigating through a tough regulatory environment and
they are assembling the tools to compete globally.''
</P>
<P>
   That does not mean much, of course, for the company's everyday
customers, with whom Bell Atlantic still has a reputation for
haughty and indifferent service. At the same time, some big
business customers remain unconvinced that Bell Atlantic can serve
their needs as well as the competition.
</P>
<P>
   And Bell Atlantic faces more competition than any other local
phone company in the nation, especially in New York City, with its
dense population of lucrative business customers.
</P>
<P>
   But for all that, Bell Atlantic can make a strong case that in
the telecommunications game of musical chairs currently under way,
it will be one of the half-dozen or so major players with a seat at
the head table when the regulatory and takeover music stops in a
few years. That group of companies will be serving millions of
wired consumers, most of the richest corporate accounts, and will
be making a vast majority of the communications profits.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic certainly faces some regulatory hurdles,
particularly with its pending $52.9 billion merger with GTE Corp.
Even so, the GTE deal, which would give Bell Atlantic a national
communications network and a big wholesale Internet business, seems
almost sure to eventually go through, if only because Bell Atlantic
was already allowed to acquire Nynex Corp. and SBC Communications
was allowed to acquire Pacific Telesis Group.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we've tried to do over the last year and a half is build
a multi-dimensional business,'' said Bell Atlantic chairman Ivan
Seidenberg. ``As we head into '99 we believe our shareholders will
get the benefits of a company that has a lot of big ideas but is
also executing in the areas we have chosen to focus on.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic has been losing ground for a long time. Over the
last few years, its shares consistently underperformed those of the
other big local phone companies. Many communications analysts were
concerned that Bell Atlantic was limited to the slow-growing
Northeast and that it faced intense competition, especially for its
most profitable customers. And they complained that the company's
senior management did not have a clear understanding of how to
reshape their business to take advantage of changes in technology
and regulation.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, that final issue, of management's overall vision,
has been the most damning. But it may be the question that is being
addressed the most quickly. Consider the message Bell Atlantic
delivered to its top 200 managers, who gathered Tuesday for the
first time since Bell Atlantic completed its acquisition of Nynex
18 months ago for a day of briefings by the senior leadership.
</P>
<P>
   The message they heard was that the company's first priority is
completing the GTE merger. That deal would expand Bell Atlantic
geographically and give its data business a big lift.
</P>
<P>
   But just as important as the GTE merger, and potentially far
more vital for consumers, is the question of when, if ever, Bell
Atlantic will get into the long-distance telephone market in New
York state, allowing customers to finally use one company for both
local and long-distance service.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are disadvantaged clearly by our lack of a long-distance
product,'' said Lawrence Babbio, Bell Atlantic's president and
chief operating officer. ``We need to get into the long-distance
business and give consumers a complete package of services.''
</P>
<P>
   The Telecommunications Act of 1996 said that the Bells could
enter the long-distance market in a given state after they
convinced regulators that their networks in that state were open to
potential competitors. Every Bell that has tried to meet that test
has failed.
</P>
<P>
   For the Bells, the question of whether to pursue long-distance
is a tricky one. The question is whether the prospect of taking
billions of dollars in revenue away from AT&AMP;T and the other
long-distance giants is worth making it easier for new companies to
pursue core local phone customers.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, regulators at the Federal Communications Commission
have been put in a tough spot. What do they do when, say, BellSouth
insists that its network in South Carolina is wide open to
competition, but there just do not happen to be any actual
competitors there?
</P>
<P>
   New York may provide a way out of the dead end. In January, the
Supreme Court threw open the question of just what parts of its
networks local phone incumbents are required to sell to
competitors. That could lead to months of delay in the introduction
of local competition as the Bells try to make sure they do not give
more than they have to.
</P>
<P>
   But for Bell Atlantic in New York, that question has become
almost academic. Bell Atlantic has already seen many of its most
lucrative business customers, especially in New York City, defect
to upstarts like MFS Communications and Teleport Communications
Group. And every time that happens, it strengthens Bell Atlantic's
case that it should be allowed to sell long-distance service.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Bell Atlantic made a deal with the New York State
Public Service Commission that the commission would support Bell
Atlantic's federal long-distance application if Bell Atlantic
passed a test of its network designed by KPMG, the consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   The test is mainly designed to determine if Bell Atlantic's
computers can accurately and promptly switch customers to other
local phone providers. While KPMG has not yet ramped up the test to
full blast _ about 15,000 orders a day _ executives close to the
process said that critical test could be over within the next 10 to
15 days.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic would then have to fix problems in its billing
systems, to make them compatible with those of other companies, the
executives said. But Bell Atlantic could be ready to file its
long-distance application with the FCC by the end of next month.
And the FCC would find itself under tremendous political pressure
to approve it.
</P>
<P>
   If Bell Atlantic's New York application succeeds, the company
would suddenly be able to offer a package of consumer services to
rival anything available from AT&AMP;T, the leader in bundling
communications services for residential consumers.
</P>
<P>
   And that would only bolster signs that its long-criticized
customer service in New York was improving. ``The company has made
some very substantial improvements over the last three years,''
said Maureen Helmer, chairwoman of the New York State Public
Service Commission. Ms. Helmer said she expected service in New
York state to reach the level Bell Atlantic provides in its other
markets by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   And Bell Atlantic might even have a lead in offering high-speed
Internet service. Last month, the company struck a deal with
America Online to market their services together, and by the end of
this year Bell Atlantic plans to offer high-speed cyberspace access
to as many as 5 million homes.
</P>
<P>
   But while it might be nice for consumers to be able to use a
single provider for both long-distance and local phone service, the
big goal for Bell Atlantic is to be able to pursue the big-ticket
corporate accounts, the ones that now rely on companies like AT&AMP;T
and MCI Worldcom.
</P>
<P>
   While plain long-distance telephone service is a low-margin
business, there are still rich profits to be won in offering
advanced long-distance data services of the sort used by big
corporations. And there are a lot of big corporations in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going head-to-head with people like AT&AMP;T, British Telecom, MCI
Worldcom for global business services is something that we're also
going to be able to do real well,'' said James Cullen, who is also
Bell Atlantic's president and chief operating officer. ``And that
needs to be done with scale and scope.''
</P>
<P>
   It will not be that simple.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as the consumer market is concerned, AT&AMP;T and Bell
Atlantic will be duking it out,'' Strumingher, the Paine Webber
analyst, said. ``But in the business market it is a whole different
story. The regulatory process is only the beginning of the fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only will Bell Atlantic have to fight the competition, it
will also have to fight its own traditional culture. Big business
customers these days do not want to buy communications products by
themselves. They want solutions, hand-holding and a consultative
partner. And Bell Atlantic has a long way to go in that department.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Bell Atlantic comes in, it's some account manager,'' said
the chief technology officer at a large New York-based financial
institution, on condition of anonymity. ``It's a classic
product-based discussion. I just don't think they're comfortable
saying, `Let's talk about where you're business is going and here's
how we can help you meet your goals.'''
</P>
<P>
   The executive continued, explaining how he had met personally to
discuss such issues with AT&AMP;T chief executive Michael Armstrong and
John Chambers, the chief executive of Cisco Systems, the big maker
of communications equipment. But, he added, ``I don't see Bell
Atlantic's top management.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
