<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 18:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2221 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT-COXX     02-04 0656
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-COXX </SLUG>
 
 &HT;    MICROSOFT SEEKS RECOVERY WITH NEW VIDEOTAPE
 &HT;    Moving in (f) financial and (w) Washington queues
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A key Microsoft Corp. executive and the company's
legal antitrust team worked through the night to produce an
undoctored computer test aimed at recovering the software giant's
shattered credibility.
</P>
<P>
   The upshot was a 70-minute videotape, filmed in ``real time'' in
the paneled conference room of Sullivan &AMP; Cromwell under the
skeptical gaze of government experts.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft Senior Vice President James Allchin narrated the tape,
which was completed at 6:30 a.m. Thursday. It was made after U.S.
District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson on Wednesday had told
Allchin, a star Microsoft defense witness, that he found earlier
obvious miscues by the company in this arena ``very troubling.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 50-day course of the landmark trial, nearly every move by
the warring parties has been carefully scripted in the courtroom.
But the overnight Allchin tape broke that mold because as he noted
on the stand, ``I'm going to take my life in my hands and hope to
connect.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Allchin was referring to his persistent problem in
dialing to the Internet _ in a bid to fairly test a
government-sponsored ``concept program'' that supposedly scrubbed
Windows 98 of its Internet Explorer browser. But Allchin also had
no way of knowing in advance how his supervised experiment would
turn out.
</P>
<P>
   The installed software patch, devised by Princeton University
professor Edward Felten, did not prevent Allchin from surfing the
Internet. But with the Felten program in place, some Web sites
performed poorly. Moreover, Money 99, a Microsoft financial
services application, crashed on a ``Feltenized'' machine.
</P>
<P>
   The Microsoft tests were aimed to demonstrate that Windows 98
and the Internet Explorer browser are inseparable. The government
seeks to show that Microsoft illegally packaged the two in order to
undermine rival Netscape Communications Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft had purchased six IBM Thinkpad laptop computers,
preloaded with Windows 98, to conduct the test. Only two of the
computers were actually used as Felten and two of his aides looked
on.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is clearly going to be broken until you add a browser,''
David Boies, the government's lead attorney, told Allchin in the
courtroom. ``Anything that requires a browser isn't going to work _
isn't that right?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes sir,'' Allchin replied.
</P>
<P>
   Before undergoing a final cross-examination on the witness
stand, Allchin also said that Microsoft had made no effort to debug
the government's scrubbing program nor to run Netscape's Navigator
browser with the Felten program in place.
</P>
<P>
   The driving issue behind these tests is a potentially legally
lethal charge by the Department of Justice and 19 states that
Microsoft crafted an integrated Windows operating system, which
runs on 90 percent of the world's personal computers, in a bold bid
to undermine rival Netscape.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most pivotal exchange in the entire trial to date
came when Boies asked Allchin whether Microsoft decided ``to
include Internet support in Windows in response to Netscape?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Allchin answered. ``The intent was to unify the browsing
experience across different types of transport, if you will, where
the Internet is viewed as transport.... We added it to be able to
communicate and to be able to unify that (experience) for the
consumer....
</P>
<P>
   ``And long before Netscape was created, we were talking about
this. And we had a plan in place that we wanted to achieve that....
It was a technological 'it's obvious' type of decision.''
</P>
<P>
   The outcome of the trial could rest on whether Jackson believes
Allchin, the Microsoft guru behind all versions of Windows, or
whether he concurs with the government's account of what took
place.
 &UR; For use by clients of the New York Times News Service &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
