<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 18:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2222 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-PAYBACK-SPI &LR;      02-04 0512
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-PAYBACK-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEL GIBSON'S LATEST, `PAYBACK,' IS VIOLENT GARBAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   You have to wonder about Mel Gibson. Here's a guy with proven
artistic aspirations (think of his 1990 ``Hamlet'') and the guts to
direct himself in a project as ambitious and against the grain of
current box-office wisdom as ``Braveheart.''
</P>
<P>
   He has the prestige of a best director Oscar and the star-power
bankability of a Steven Spielberg or Tom Cruise. (He could announce
a plan to film the phone book and a dozen producers would line up
to pay him his regular $20+ million fee.)
</P>
<P>
   So what does he do with all this power and credibility? He uses
it to make a piece of garbage like ``Payback,'' a movie that plays
like a compilation of the worst moments of his ``Lethal Weapon''
series, with the gratuitous brutality jacked up to outdo Quentin
Tarantino on his best day.
</P>
<P>
   The plot is a complete ripoff of the John Boorman classic,
``Point Blank,'' which tells the story of a hood who is shot and
left for dead by his double-crossing wife and his best-friend
partner after a caper, and who comes back from oblivion to settle
the score.
</P>
<P>
   The first half of the movie comes off as an unusually violent,
but formula, neo-film noir thriller _ opening with the Gibson
character getting two slugs removed from his back, narrating his
story over a few flashbacks, and then getting hot on the trail of
his junkie wife (Deborah Kara Unger) and sadistic buddy (Gregg
Henry).
</P>
<P>
   Near the middle of the movie _ after beatings, murders and
torture scenes too numerous to mention _ the film suddenly turns
into a goofy comedy, virtually a ``Naked Gun'' version of ``Point
Blank,'' with exaggerated brutality and violence in every scene,
most of it played for crude laughs.
</P>
<P>
   Its two halves are so different in tone that ``Payback'' has the
smell of a film that looked so bad in the rushes that the
filmmakers dramatically changed direction mid-stream, trying to
salvage their sinking ship by turning it into something entirely
different: the single most brutal movie of the '90s _ so brutal
it's hilarious.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Gibson and first-time director Brian Helgeland know what
they're doing. Even in this, his most violent and politically
incorrect role to date, Gibson's blue eyes still shine irresistibly
in that increasingly weather-beaten face: he's a charmer. And there
was definitely laughter at the preview.
</P>
<P>
   But it was nervous laughter, uncomfortable laughter, laughter
that said, ``My God, just how far will they go with this thing? How
brutal and sadistic can one movie be?'' For anyone out of junior
high school, ``Payback'' leaves a terrible taste. No major star
vehicle of the '90s has aimed quite this low.
</P>
<P>
   Payback. Directed by Brian Helgeland. Screenplay by Helgeland
and Terry Hayes. Cast: Mel Gibson, Gregg Henry, Maria Bello, James
Coburn (uncredited), Kris Kristofferson. Paramount. 102 minutes.
Rated R for non-stop brutality and violence.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: D
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-04-99 1859EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
