<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 19:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2224 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-GENERAL-SPI &LR;      02-04 0607
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-GENERAL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE STRONG ACTING, `THE GENERAL' LEAVES US COLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   How can a film that boasts a performance as fine as Brendan
Gleeson's be so void of heart?
</P>
<P>
   That was the question after watching John Boorman's ``The
General,'' which won him the best director award last year at the
Cannes Film Festival.
</P>
<P>
   The film, which Boorman also wrote, is based on the life of
Irish gangster Martin Cahill, who was shot to death by an IRA
bullet outside his home in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``The General'' is a throwback to some of the Boorman's earlier
fare, like ``Leo The Last'' and ``Catch Us If You Can,'' which
starred the English band, The Dave Clark Five.
</P>
<P>
   Boorman has had an up-and-down career since then. He scored with
such films ``Deliverance,'' ``Excalibur,'' ``Emerald Forest'' and
``Hope and Glory,'' but also had flops like ``Where The Heart Is,''
which he directed from his late daughter's screenplay, ``Exorcist
II'' and ``I Dreamt I Woke Up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The General'' plays out like a docu-drama, or even a home
movie, as it's shot in black and white and has the grainy,
self-absorbed intimacy of cinema verite.
</P>
<P>
   And it engages on a primal, earthy level because it allows the
little guy to usurp the establishment. But Boorman tries to make
this ``biography'' of Martin Cahill, who eluded capture for 20
years and was called the General by his tight-knit gang of Irish
thieves, into a tale about a very conscience-stricken crisis of
conflict.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the film is over, we know a lot about this
charismatic thug who plagued the Irish police. For two decades, he
just won't go away, nor can the cops catch him.
</P>
<P>
   He becomes a folk hero to some despite crimes that are from any
image of a noble, Robin Hood-like altruism. Rather, Cahill's
robberies forced employers to lay off their workers because of
there was no money left to pay them.
</P>
<P>
   Cahill, played with humorous, ham-hockish and blunt
lack-of-grace by the extraordinary Irish actor, Brendan Gleeson
(Mel Gibson's best friend in ``Braveheart''), is pitted against his
slum-neighborhood Hollyfield mate, police Inspector Ned Kenny (Jon
Voight).
</P>
<P>
   Cahill, locked into the cruelty of the past, is willing to risk
death to make a mockery of the cops and everyone who defies him. He
even marries his childhood sweetheart, Frances (Maria Doyle
Kennedy), and later has children with her younger sister, Tina
(Angeline Ball), in order to snub his nose at convention.
</P>
<P>
   Despite this glimpse at the reality of this man who purports to
have values and rules as strict and unyielding as those he fights
against, we can't break into Cahill's heart or pain or anything
else that could help humanize him.
</P>
<P>
   Boorman, who has made emotionally involving work in the past,
seems to have purposefully shied away from feeling here. Like it or
not, ``Beyond Rangoon'' was a moving tale of a stranger in a
strange land. And ``Hope and Glory,'' with its portrayal of
memories of a childhood lived under dire conditions, was teeming
with humor and heart.
</P>
<P>
   Though ``The General'' is a visceral experience as well as a
visual one, it never makes a dent in our feelings. While we admire
its technical prowess _ and Gleeson's amazing performance _ we're
almost relieved when this angry, selfish thug goes down in less
than a blaze of glory.
</P>
<P>
   The General. Directed and written by John Boorman. Cast: Brendan
Gleeson, Adrian Dunbar, Jon Voight, Sean McGinley, Maria Doyle
Kennedy. Sony Pictures Classics. 124 minutes. Rated R for violence,
language.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-04-99 1900EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
