<DOCNO> NYT19990204.0330 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 19:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2230 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-TRIAL-HNS &LR;      02-04 1185
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-TRIAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE, EDGING TOWARD END OF TRIAL, REJECTS LEWINSKY AS WITNESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL, JUDY HOLLAND and JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate, singed by public impatience, rejected
an appeal by House Republicans Thursday for former White House
intern Monica Lewinsky to testify at President Clinton's
impeachment trial, clearing the way to end the awkward, year-long
inquiry next week.
</P>
<P>
   Racing through a series of votes with sudden urgency, the
Republican-led Senate slammed the door on potentially embarrassing
personal testimony by Lewinsky that White House lawyers warned
would prolong the trial for weeks.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Senate assured some drama to the final days of the
trial by permitting House prosecutors to use videotaped testimony
by Lewinsky, presidential confidante Vernon Jordan and White House
staffer Sidney Blumenthal in their final arguments Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Senators voted against hearing Lewinsky in person 70-30, with 25
of the Senate's 55 Republicans breaking ranks to join all 45
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The vote in favor of admitting videotaped depositions at the
trial was 62-38, with nine Democrats joining 53 Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., said the Senate
trial that began Jan. 13 would end no later than next Friday with
Senate votes on the two articles of impeachment lodged against
Clinton by the House.
</P>
<P>
   Lott, acknowledging deepening public antipathy with the
protracted impeachment process, called the Senate action ``a
critical day'' that ``guarantees now that we're moving to the final
phase.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott added:``I do think it's time that we get to a vote and that
we move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Lott and other Republicans rejected for a second
time a Democratic bid to move immediately to final arguments and
votes on the articles of impeachment. The vote was 56-44 against
the Democrats' proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the chamber, as senators were voting on a series of
motions, a man sitting in the tourist section of the gallery
screamed out, ``Good God Almighty, take the vote and get on with
it.'' Capitol police escorted the man out of the gallery.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Republicans also defeated a request from Clinton's
lawyers that they receive advance notice about which segments of
the videotaped testimony will be used by House prosecutors in their
summations on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   House prosecutors had already trimmed their request for live
witnesses from seven last week to only three in response to
senators' suggestions that they start cutting back the scope of
their prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish things were different,'' lamented House Judiciary
Committee Chairman Henry Hyde, R-Ill., adding that House
prosecutors had to ``live within'' the limitations set by the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. James Rogan, R-Calif., a former Los Angeles county judge
serving as one of 13 House prosecutors pressing the case against
Clinton, called Senate rejection of Lewinsky's testimony
``unfortunate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We understood that this was sort of a David and Goliath
approach, particularly in light of the public opinion polls that
don't favor us,'' Rogan said.
</P>
<P>
   The House charged Clinton with perjury and obstruction of
justice in his efforts to hide a sexual dalliance with Lewinsky
from special prosecutor Kenneth Starr and lawyers pressing a
$750,000 civil sexual harassment suit against Clinton filed in 1994
by former Arkansas state employee Paula Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Breaux, D-La., said that senators had ``come to the
conclusion that we've heard everything from Monica Lewinsky that we
need to hear.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., said the rapid fire Senate votes
have helped to ease partisan tensions in the Senate. ``The whole
tone is different,'' Schumer said. ``There's a feeling on both
sides of the aisle (of) let's finish this up.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House expressed immediate relief at the outcome of
Senate proceedings that set the stage for the end of the first
Senate impeachment trial of a president since 1868.
</P>
<P>
   White House Press Secretary Joe Lockhart said: ``Today's vote
rejecting the House managers' request for live witnesses indicates
the Senate appears ready to bring this trial to a conclusion.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In rejecting live testimony, Senators turned a deaf ear to
plaintive appeals from the House prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill McCollum, R-Fla., one of the 13-member team of House
prosecutors, told senators that they had ``a moral obligation to
allow Monica Lewinsky to come here and be judged on her credibility
not just by you, but by the public, by all of us, as a live
witness.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Edward Bryant, R-Tenn., a former federal prosecutor in
Tennessee who deposed Lewinsky on Monday, said the Senate needed to
hear Lewinsky because she had shaved her testimony during her
deposition to ``the literal truth only.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant said Lewinsky's testimony was ``clearly tinted _ and some
might even say tainted _ by a mixture of her continued admiration
for the president, her desire to protect him, and her own personal
views of right and wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Asa Hutchinson, R-Ark., responding to senators' request to
bring the trial to a speedy conclusion, conceded, ``we want to have
a final chapter in this national drama.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Lindsay Graham, R-S.C., appealed to the Senate to permit
Lewinsky to testify because White House lawyers were contesting
facts in the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why we need witnesses, ladies and gentlemen, to clarify
who said what, who's being honest, who's not, and what really did
happen in this sordid tale,'' Graham said.
</P>
<P>
   White House special counsel Gregory Craig successfully urged the
Senate to reject Lewinsky's live testimony on the Senate floor,
noting that Lewinsky had already testified 23 times under oath.
</P>
<P>
   Admitting Lewinsky ``will be worse than an exercise in
redundancy, it will be an exercise in excess,'' Craig warned. ``It
will only postpone the end of a trial that nobody wants anymore and
no one wants to prolong any longer.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Senate efforts to speed the trial to conclusion followed the
apparent loss of support for a GOP effort to cite the president for
wrongdoing as part of the impeachment proceeding without voting to
convict him or remove him from office. Supporters of that effort _
the so-called ``finding of fact'' approach _ were pushing it after
they realized that they don't have the two-thirds majority in the
Senate, or 67 votes, to convict and remove Clinton from office.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Budget Committee Chairman Pete Domenici, R-N.M., author
of one of the proposals to cite Clinton for wrongdoing without
removing him from office, said the effort had ebbed because of
Democrats' refusal to join in a bipartisan effort of condemnation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, if no Democrat is going to support it, then I think
that's perilously close to being dead,'' Domenici said. He said he
would not offer his proposal without Democratic support.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-04-99 1903EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
