<HEADER>
A2240 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MALAYASIA-ECON-620&AMP;AD     02-04 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MALAYASIA-ECON-620&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYASIA RELAXES SOME CONTROLS ON FOREIGN INVESTMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ In its first tentative step back into the global
economy, Malaysia announced Thursday that it would relax some of
the sweeping controls on foreign investment that it imposed in
September.
</P>
<P>
   Finance Minister Daim Zainuddin said the government would lift a
12-month moratorium on the withdrawal of foreign capital from the
country. But to prevent an outbreak of capital flight, it
introduced an exit tax that discourages investors from pulling
their money out immediately.
</P>
<P>
   The exchange controls on Malaysia's currency, the ringgit,
remain in force. The currency cannot be traded outside the country,
and its value has been pegged at 3.8 ringgit to the U.S. dollar.
The government will continue to strictly limit the amount of the
currency that residents or visitors can take out.
</P>
<P>
   Still, if Malaysia dug a moat around its economy in September by
imposing capital controls, Thursday's action was the equivalent of
throwing a drawbridge to investors _ at least those with the right
intentions.
</P>
<P>
   ``These new measures are aimed to encourage existing portfolio
investors to take a longer term view of their investments in
Malaysia and to attract new funds into the country, while at the
same time discouraging destabilizing short-term flows,'' Daim said
in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Fund managers and analysts greeted the announcement, which had
been widely expected, with guarded optimism.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a positive thing and they should be applauded for
it,'' said Mac Overton, a manager at the MBF Unit Trust in Hong
Kong. ``But I'm a little skeptical. What's to keep them from doing
it again if things don't go their way?''
</P>
<P>
   Malaysia, which had been a magnet for foreign investment, became
a pariah in the world economy when it unexpectedly cordoned off its
currency and capital markets. Most disturbing to investors was the
12-month ban on withdrawing foreign capital. That decision locked
in $3.5 billion to $4 billion in capital held by foreign portfolio
investors.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad said he wanted to curb sudden
large flows of capital, which he said had destabilized Malaysia's
currency and thrown the country into a recession. Mahathir cited
Western currency traders like George Soros as the primary culprits.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new regulations, investors will be allowed to withdraw
money from Malaysia immediately. But they will be taxed according
to how quickly they act. Those who withdraw capital that had been
in the country for less than seven months will pay a 30 percent
tax. The rate gradually drops to zero for investors who leave their
money in the country for more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the government first imposed the controls, everyone was
afraid there would be capital flight after one year,'' said Razak
Baginda, executive director of the Malaysian Strategic Research
Center in Kuala Lumpur. ``This is a mechanism to soften the blow of
that one-year milestone.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the plan had a good chance of working. P.K. Basu,
a senior regional economist with Credit Suisse First Boston in
Singapore, estimated that $500 million to $1 billion in foreign
capital would be taken out of Malaysia in the next two weeks. But
he predicted that it would be more than replaced by fresh capital
from investors who had been avoiding Malaysia because of the
controls.
</P>
<P>
   Other experts are not so sure. Under the new rules, investors
can move money in and out of the country without restrictions,
starting on Feb. 15. But the government will tax investors who
withdraw profits. Like the exit tax, it is intended to penalize
short-term investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sympathetic to a hot-money tax,'' Overton said. ``But it
still seems like the government is going to have control over my
money.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Malaysian officials have been laying the groundwork for these
changes over the last several weeks. Mahathir met with a group of
portfolio managers in Kuala Lumpur two weeks ago to gauge their
sentiment about Malaysia. And he assiduously courted world leaders,
bankers and journalists at the recent World Economic Forum
conference in Davos, Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   Among the principal arguments Mahathir made is that the controls
had stabilized the economy. By shielding Malaysia from the vagaries
of the global market, the government said, it was able to lower
interest rates and revive commercial activity. Indeed, its central
bank said Thursday that the official forecast of 1 percent economic
growth this year might be exceeded.
</P>
<P>
   Prominent Malaysians acknowledge, however, that the controls
hurt the nation's reputation and left it isolated. In part this was
because they were imposed at the same time that Mahathir dismissed
his deputy, Anwar Ibrahim. Anwar is now on trial on corruption
charges; he may take the stand next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a huge misunderstanding about capital controls,''
said Francis Yeoh, one of the nation's business magnates.
``Investors didn't understand that this was supposed to control
currency speculators, not long-term investors.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
