<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 19:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2241 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STROMAN-DANCE-REVIEW-     02-04 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STROMAN-DANCE-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BUT NOT FOR ME': BROADWAY BRINGS GERSHWIN TO THE GRAHAM TROUPE
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By ANNA KISSELGOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; NEW YORK _ Susan Stroman's ``But Not For Me,'' set to Gershwin
for the Martha Graham Dance Company, may be the first work by a
Broadway choreographer for a modern-dance troupe. Usually the
traffic goes in the other direction, with modern-dance
choreographers often working on Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons vary. Just plain money is an incentive to try
Broadway, and yet modern-dance choreographers often find Broadway a
good place to experiment. But on the other side of the fence,
modern dance has been loath to invite choreographers from the
commercial theater into its own precincts. The world of concert
dance has, until recently, been defined by a self-proclaimed
seriousness.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Stroman, it is true, also has choreographed for the New York
City Opera and off-Broadway. Nonetheless, she is the dominant
Broadway choreographer of the 1990s. Among her shows are ``Crazy
For You'' and ``Showboat'' (both of which gained her a Tony Award),
``Steel Pier,'' ``A Christmas Carol'' and the new London production
of ``Oklahoma!''
</P>
<P>
   If you wonder what Ms. Stroman is doing in the Graham company,
which presented the New York premiere of ``But Not For Me'' at the
Joyce Theater on Wednesday night, the answer is not that complex.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Stroman is enormously talented, which is why she attracted
so much attention so quickly in the first place. Ron Protas,
artistic director of the Graham company since its founder's death
in 1991, invited her to do the third work he has commissioned from
an outside choreographer. The others were Twyla Tharp and Robert
Wilson. Another new work, by Lucinda Childs, will be seen in the
``Duets for Martha'' program next Tuesday at the Joyce Theater.
Graham, it is true, never felt at home with jazz. But to call
George Gershwin a jazz composer is not exactly accurate. Ms.
Stroman's use of Gershwin songs, with the lyrics omitted, focuses
on atmosphere. There is a romantic tinge in the melodies, perfect
for her image of young people in the big city dreaming of happiness
amid the loneliness of the urban crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, she occasionally uses recognizable movements from the
Graham idiom. But she also allows the dancers a contemporary
exuberance. There is some Broadway polish, very different from the
depth of Graham's own fluency. There is also time for glamour, as
Katherine Crockett displays in her knockout performance as the
soloist amid the 10-member ensemble.
</P>
<P>
   The connection between ``But Not For Me'' and the company is
also more formal. The work's world premiere was given in April at
the Library of Congress in Washington. The piece was commissioned
through the Ira and Leonore S. Gershwin Trust at the library. In
1944, the library, through the Elizabeth Sprague Coolidge
Foundation, had also commissioned Graham's great ``Appalachian
Spring.''
</P>
<P>
   To see ``Appalachian Spring,'' revived in the Coolidge
Auditorium in April was to relive a part of history.
</P>
<P>
   ``But Not For Me'' belongs, obviously, to another time and
world. Ms. Stroman has changed and improved the ending, and the
work, if a bit long, succeeds on its own terms. The initial image
of dancers asleep on black pillows may suggest one big pajama
party. But the dreamlike foray into hopes and yearnings adds a
further dimension.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, the songs by George and Ira Gershwin were
arranged by Glen Kelly and orchestrated by Doug Besterman. At the
Joyce, Kelly, as pianist, is the sole musician, and he does not shy
away from an overly emphatic beat. The songs include ``But Not For
Me,'' which runs through the piece as well as ``They Can't Take
That Away From Me,'' `` 'S Wonderful,'' ``They All Laughed,''
``Strike Up The Band,'' ``Liza,'' ``Nice Work If You Can Get It''
and ``The Man I Love.'' To her credit, Ms. Stroman does not
illustrate the discarded lyrics.
</P>
<P>
   The overall style suggests a dream ballet with the dancers in
William Ivey Long's khaki pajamas using the pillows as props
(something to hug). Strongly structured, the piece dissolves into
introspective solos and duets, often touched with dejection.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Stroman is fond of circles and lifts, but she can also
individualize the performers. Ms. Crockett stands out on her own,
and she always gives the Graham works the sculptural, muscular
depth they deserve. Here she is a modern version of the 1940s
pinup, knee bent and, later, leg extended. She reaches out for the
caress she first gives herself.
</P>
<P>
   The other dancers occasionally do a stylized soft shoe and
wiggle their behinds. Mainly they seem to be enjoying themselves.
At the end, Martin Lofsnes emerges from a pile of pillows and
embraces Ms. Crockett. The lively cast included Theresa Da Silva,
Tadej Brdnik, Sandra Kaufmann, Gary Galbraith, Ariel Bonilla,
Elizabeth Auclair, Virginie Mecene and Daniel Cardoso.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere on the program, Galbraith was the new minotaur figure
preying upon Therese Capucilli in Graham's 1947 ``Errand into the
Maze,'' set to Gian Carlo Menotti's melodramatic score. ``Errand''
itself is pure drama.
</P>
<P>
   Inspired by Greek mythology, it is a metaphor for conquering
sexual fear and, by extension, all fear. Isamu Noguchi's decor,
forms resonant with sexual meaning, include the wishbone set to
which the heroine retreats after three solos and three encounters
with her beast.
</P>
<P>
   Graham makes her point through the simplicity of her daring and
the expressiveness of her percussive choreography. Galbraith did
well enough for a debut, and his partnering in the highly active
duet with Ms. Capucilli was fine. She, as usual, offered a superb
performance in one of Graham's great works.
</P>
<P>
   The energy level has been low in some of the ensemble pieces so
far but not in ``Sketches from Chronicle,'' a protest piece of
1936. Christine Dakin, wrapping herself in a red shroud and fearful
of the specter of war that she herself represented, was magnificent
in her glaring serenity. The ensemble, striding through the
striking patterns of the second section, leaped with vigor into the
future in the final section.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
