<SLUG> BC-TILT-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TILT': SOUNDS AND LITTLE FURIES SIGNIFYING LOTS OF THINGS 
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds: Production notes at end of review) 
(DW) 
 By D.J.R. BRUCKNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``Tilt,'' the Talking Band's latest excursion onto
the stage, is all chamber music, in structure if not in the
whirlwind of words and sounds that sweeps its four characters and
two musicians through a swirl of dreams and illusions.
</P>
<P>
   The impression of chaos is so pervasive that, when the last
scene reveals how neatly constructed this odd little play is, the
revelation comes as a surprise that extorts laughter. One would
have thought Ellen Maddow, who wrote the text and composed the
music, had reached the pinnacle of cleverness with her series of
rhythmic plays a decade ago about the housewife Betty Suffer. But
in ``Tilt'' she outdoes herself; her imagination has been
consorting with Mozart and Haydn.
</P>
<P>
   To begin, two musicians (Ms. Maddow and Joe Roseto) wander in
some confusion onto Christine Jones' ingenious set, which has a
life of its own. After sparring over their roles, they set to work
awakening Flo (Tina Shepard) and Ziggy (Paul Zimet), asleep in
separate apartments. On a shelf in Flo's place are two small
figures, Glo (Zakia Babb) and Mop (Isaac Maddow-Zimet); they may be
icons or simply dolls, but they raid the pantry every time Flo
steps out the door.
</P>
<P>
   Morning rituals _ especially Flo and Ziggy dressing with help
from closets with hands _ make up one of those perky dawn
interludes heard in so many 18th-century symphonies, followed by
the thunder of New York street sounds and a tornado of windblown
paper as the two make their way to an office where they are
partners in a mysterious business.
</P>
<P>
   As they argue through several days over who will handle the
phones and who the mail, or what to order for lunch or what time to
close, variations on themes in language, role reversals and
emotional upheavals spell out the amusing central motifs of this
odd composition.
</P>
<P>
   Ziggy is all order. At home he reads obsessively; calls his
lover or spouse, Margaret, who is away on a trip, to recite
exciting discoveries, such as the second law of thermodynamics, and
sleeps fitfully through musical nightmares. Flo is all intuition:
rosy dawn, rosy day; gray dawn, bleak prospect. Without seeing her
icons move she knows they do. She knows what Ziggy thinks, without
much wanting to.
</P>
<P>
   The story is a good deal more subtle and complex than it appears
to be. That Ms. Maddow and this cast are able to convey so much
meaning with so few words and so little variation in movement is
testimony to the mastery achieved by the Talking Band in its 25
years.
</P>
<P>
   Under the direction of Will Pomerantz, the characters, and the
musicians, who are characters too, move with the economical
precision of unexpectedly emotional puppets capable of an
occasional sly smile that lets the audience know a surprise is in
the offing.
</P>
<P>
   They all share such a smile when one of the score of office
phones rings and Flo and Ziggy find they've won a trip to a sort of
Catskills resort where, in a glittering ballroom, they, and Glo and
Mop, dance. It is the minuet, of course: that spirited little
movement that told the knowing listeners in grand old Viennese
parlors that the transport of delight with which Haydn or Mozart
had carried them away was about to float back to earth.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `TILT'
</P>
<P>
   Written and composed by Ellen Maddow; directed by Will
Pomerantz; sets by Christine Jones; lighting by Carol Mullins;
costumes by Mattie Ullrich; sound by Miles Green; stage manager,
Alicia Edwards. The Talking Band presented by La MaMa E.T.C. At 74A
E. Fourth St.
</P>
<P>
   With: Ellen Maddow, Joe Roseto, Tina Shepard, Paul Zimet, Zakia
Babb and Isaac Maddow-Zimet.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
