<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTRE-DAME-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG (TEN) DECISION FOR NOTRE DAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The banner hung from a window of a residence hall on the Notre
Dame campus. The message was clear: ``Big Ten. Big Mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   While the rest of the country was focusing on the Super Bowl in
Miami and the impeachment hearings in Washington, the Midwest _
particularly South Bend, Ind., and the Big Ten offices outside
Chicago _ was preoccupied with Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   To join or not to join? That is the question.
</P>
<P>
   Simple? Hardly. Nothing involving the non-declaration of
independence of the most preeminent Catholic university in college
sports is simple, and the topic of whether Notre Dame would choose
to give it up and join the Big Ten has raged for months.
</P>
<P>
   The lines of debate are also clear. The student body is against
it. The alumni are against it. And a large segment of the athletic
department is against it.
</P>
<P>
   A decision and an announcement will be made Friday in London,
where the Notre Dame Board of Trustees will convene.
</P>
<P>
   Taking the pro side is the academic community, which is almost
unanimously in favor of a Big Ten alliance for the most logical _
and, if you believe the true mission of any univeristy is
education, the most legitimate _ reasons.
</P>
<P>
   By becoming the Big Ten's 12th member, Notre Dame would be
eligible to join a consortium of Big Ten schools and the University
of Chicago called the Committee on Institutional Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   In academic circles, the CIC is a superpower, sharing
world-class minds, resources, and facilities, primarily on the
graduate school level but also in many other academic areas.
</P>
<P>
   Notre Dame is regarded as a fine undergraduate institution, but
becoming part of the CIC would elevate the university to
world-class status.
</P>
<P>
   Or at least that's the argument.
</P>
<P>
   To reach that end, however, the cost would be steep: a loss of
independence, and some say identity in the athletic world as a
unique place.
</P>
<P>
   Tied to that concern would be the diminishment of Notre Dame's
role as the most prestigious Cathloic university in college
athletics.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, almost everyone is keeping their mouth shut
until the meeting in London, in itself a stunning upset.
</P>
<P>
   The Big Ten, which wants a 12th member for competitive reasons
in football _ it would allow the league to have two six-team
divisions and conduct a money-making championship game _ has
focused on the Irish as its target. Its only target thus far.
</P>
<P>
   Big Ten commissioner Jim Delany has made it clear that should
things not work out with Notre Dame _ both sides are wary of being
cast in the role of chaser or chasee _ the inclination would be to
quickly look elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   But first the Notre Dame situation must be resolved. ``If after
the Board of Trustees meets on Feb. 5, and if Notre Dame indicates
a serious interest in pursing Big Ten membership, the Conference
Board of Directors would then consider tendering an offer,'' said
Delany in a statement issued last week.
</P>
<P>
   The decision will have significant ramifications throughout
college athletics.
</P>
<P>
   The Big East is perhaps the most interested observer, since the
Irish are a conference member in all sports but football. If Notre
Dame leaves, the Big East would shrink _ with approval of the
members _ back to 12 teams in basketball.
</P>
<P>
   The addition of Notre Dame also would prevent the Big Ten from
pursuing another conference member, Syracuse, which the Big East
does not want to lose.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Syracuse goes, the Big East football league folds,'' said
one source familiar with the Big East mind-set regarding the Notre
Dame question. ``There will be a fire sale of other conference
teams.''
</P>
<P>
   But the prevailing sense of almost everyone, from people in the
Big Ten to several sources inside the Notre Dame hierarchy, is that
the Irish's answer will be no.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just waiting to see what happens with Notre Dame so we
can deal with the aftermath,'' said Big East commissioner Mike
Tranghese, who has been in constant touch with both Delany and
Notre Dame athletic director Mike Wadsworth.
</P>
<P>
   A decision by Notre Dame to remain an independent in football
would trigger a second series of negotiations. The consensus seems
to be that the Big Ten would make a move toward Syracuse, but the
likeliest result right now would be another polite rejection.
</P>
<P>
   Sensing that, and not wanting to be perceived as searching for
suitors, the Big Ten would probably turn to Missouri, which would
welcome an invitation to join.
</P>
<P>
   And if that happens, a domino effect of reshuffling in
conference alignments could and probably would take place.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-04-99 1913EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
