u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RETAIL-SALES-BOS &LR;      02-04 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RETAIL-SALES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSUMER SPENDING BOOSTS RETAIL SALES IN JANUARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In another sign of the economy's continued strength, consumers
kept up a brisk spending pace in January, giving the nation's
retailers a boost in what is often a slow month.
</P>
<P>
   Retail sales surged ahead, as free-spending consumers took
advantage of clearance sales to load up on winter apparel.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, analysts say that the fourth quarter, which
includes the best holiday shopping season in six years, is likely
to be solid for many retailers, especially for discounters such as
Wal-Mart Stores Inc. and Dayton-Hudson Corp., which operates the
Target discount chain.
</P>
<P>
   January sales, though, can be tricky to gauge. In slashing
prices to lure shoppers for clearance sales, retailers can
sometimes squeeze their profit margins. As a result, strong sales
don't always translate into a strong bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, most January signs were positive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, it was an excellent month for most people,'' said
John Pitt, director of LJR Redbook, which tracks retail sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's shaping up to be a better fourth quarter than we
expected,'' Pitt added. ``The quarter started on an uncertain note
because of (unseasonably) warm weather, and it's ending on a much
stronger note than it began.''
</P>
<P>
   Many US consumers continue to spend, despite the high levels of
personal debt and the end of the holiday season.
</P>
<P>
   ``So long as the economy remains stable, we can expect consumers
to do their thing,'' said Kurt Barnard, president of Barnard's
Retail Trend Report.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most reliable measures of a retailer's performance is
something known as same-store sales, which gauges increases or
declines at stores open for at least a year. Same-store sales
exclude results from recently opened or closed stores.
</P>
<P>
   A composite same-store sales index calculated by Bloomberg News
found that January sales for the nation's biggest retailers were up
8.22 percent over the same month last year.
</P>
<P>
   The January gain was the biggest since last April.
</P>
<P>
   Filene's Basement Corp., the Wellesley, Mass. off-price
retailer, said that same-store sales rose 11 percent in January and
3 percent for the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The increases, the company said in a statement, were ``driven
primarily by an inventory liquidation sale in our fine-jewelry
leased department.'' An ``aggressive level of markdowns'' was also
taken to clear fall inventory, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Filene's Basement, which plans to introduce a new leased jewelry
department later in the year, said that net fourth-quarter sales
grew 13 percent, to $174.7 million, and net sales for its full
fiscal year rose 6 percent, to $588.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Poor sales in January don't always mean disaster. Autumn apparel
sold so briskly at full price that there wasn't enough left over to
offer steep discounts at January clearance sales, according to
Talbots, the Hingham, Mass. retailer of women's clothing. As a
result, same-store sales in January fell 12.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But because sales were better than expected for the last three
months, fourth-quarter earnings could reach 26 cents on a per-share
basis, 2 cents higher than most Wall Street analysts had been
projecting, Talbots said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   For the fourth quarter, net sales rose 7 percent, to $335.3
million, and fiscal year sales jumped 8 percent, to $1.14 billion.
</P>
<P>
   TJX Cos., the Framingham, Mass. operator of such off-price
chains as T. J. Maxx and Marshalls, had another strong month, with
January same-store sales up 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   For the full fiscal year, TJX said, net sales rose 9 percent, to
$7.95 billion. For the year, same-store sales rose 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   J. Baker Inc., a Canton, Mass. retailer that operates such
chains as Casual Male Big &AMP; Tall and Work 'n Gear, said that
January same-store sales were up 13.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   For the year, net sales rose to $584 million from $574 million,
or a bit less than 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   BJ's Wholesale Club Inc. of Natick Mass. said January same-store
sales rose 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``BJ's posted strong gains in apparel, tires, furniture, and
computer equipment,'' said BJ's chief executive, Jack Nugent.
</P>
<P>
   For the full year, same-store sales were up 5.2 percent, and net
sales rose 11.8 percent, to $3.48 billion. BJ's Thursday announced
a 2-for-1 stock split, in the form of a dividend to be distributed
March 2 to stockholders of record as of Feb. 16, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Federated Department Stores posted a January same-store jump of
7.3 percent, but some of the gain came from shifting a big
promotional event for home furnishings from February to January.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
