<HEADLINE>
FIDELITY TO FIELD THIRD INSTALLMENT IN LYNCH AD SERIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Fidelity Investments is about to launch Phase Three of
its much ballyhooed _ and criticized _ Peter Lynch ad campaign,
which was developed by Boston ad agency Hill Holliday Connors
Cosmopulos.
</P>
<P>
   Continuing to feature Lynch as Fidelity's gray eminence and a
font of investment advice, five new TV ads seek to highlight the
performance of some specific Fidelity funds, something previous ads
in the campaign didn't do.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to gain attention, ads launched in September paired
Lynch first with comic Lily Tomlin, then with Don Rickles.
</P>
<P>
   A second flight of ads had Lynch elaborating on his ``know what
you own and know why you own it'' message as he talked about
investment solutions and the pains Fidelity analysts took in
seeking companies to create strong portfolios.
</P>
<P>
   In the new set of ads, Lynch's co-star is not some Vegas comic,
but specific funds such as the Fidelity Aggressive Growth fund, the
Fidelity Dividend Growth fund, or the Fidelity Retirement Growth
fund, which make up a portion of the $752.7 billion in managed
assets Fidelity had at the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   In each new ad, Lynch is posed a question about investing, which
he proceeds to answer with a pithy bromide.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're taking the Peter Lynch campaign to its next evolution,''
said Stephen Cone, president of Fidelity Customer Marketing and
Development. ``We want investors to first know what they own and
why they own it, then we want to provide solutions to help them
decide how to invest. The next extension is to highlight specific
funds that customers might consider for building a diversified and
appropriate portfolio.''
</P>
<P>
   The first round of Lynch ads were not well received by critics
who write for advertising trade publications.
</P>
<P>
   But ad reviews are much like movie reviews: Movies panned by the
critics become box-office smashes all the time.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the artistic merits of the early Lynch ads, their
launch didn't seem to coincide with an immediate stampede of new
investors clamoring to buy Fidelity's products _ even though many
of those products were outperforming rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in December, however, interest in Fidelity funds
surged, according to Cone.
</P>
<P>
   One new TV ad has Lynch saying, ``Despite nine recessions since
World War II, the stock market is up 63-fold because earnings are
up 54-fold _ earnings drive the market.''
</P>
<P>
   Then peformance numbers of a specific Fidelity fund flash on the
screen. Next a graphic issues a call to action, urging viewers to
call Fidelity's 1-800 number or visit its Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Ads from the earlier phase of the campaign, featuring Lynch and
Rickles, will continue to air throughout this year, Cone said.
</P>
<P>
   As it undertook the difficult challenge of using TV ads to sell
mutual funds, Fidelity seemed to come up with a new ad theme almost
every year in the mid '90s. Cone, however, said Fidelity remains
committed to the Lynch campaign.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
