</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOMA-ART-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SIGHT GAGS':   SERIOUSLY NOW, MOMA SHOWS THE HUMOROUS SIDE OF ART 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
  By GRACE GLUECK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Humor, a relatively rare presence in art, is more apt
to occur in drawing than in painting or sculpture, possibly because
line has a quickness and lightness that makes it easy to convey.
But on the navel-searching New York scene, funny art is still
regarded with suspicion, and shows of it are few and far between.
So a new exhibition, ``Sight Gags: Grotesque, Caricature and Wit in
Modern and Contemporary Drawing'' at the Museum of Modern Art
through May 4 is a welcome occurrence.
</P>
<P>
   As for the specialness of humor-in-art shows: did you ever see
an exhibition whose declared theme was seriousness?
</P>
<P>
   It's true that art gradually has been infiltrated by animation
and comic strips, to which this show pays some homage. In fact,
``Sight Gags'' is meant to complement the museum's forthcoming
exhibition, opening April 1, of works on paper by Sigmar Polke, one
of the earliest postwar painters to exploit kitsch and popular
culture in humorous ways.
</P>
<P>
   For this Polke sidebar, organized by Laura Hoptman of the
museum's department of drawings, the Modern has culled some 80
works on paper by 65 artists from its own collection. Although it
has a respectable risibility quotient, it's a hit-or-miss
miscellany rather than a coherent survey of 20th-century
developments. But that may be asking too much from a show drawn
solely from the museum's collection.
</P>
<P>
   Four categories are established: caricature, the grotesque,
visual puns and conceptual jokes, and works inspired by comics and
cartoons, although of course there is overlap. The range of artists
is far and wide, from Jean Dubuffet and Joan Miro to Vito Acconci
and Robin Winters; the mediums run from a video piece by John
Baldessari to sketches for Disney animations to a giant wall
drawing of 1996 by Gary Simmons.
</P>
<P>
   The most penetrating category turns out to be the grotesque,
partly defined in the show as ``earthly and often vulgar'' and ``a
reproach to the spiritual and a negation of the ideal.'' An example
is George Grosz's ``Fit for Active Service'' (1918), a comment on
the selection of cannon fodder. In an examining room overpopulated
by preening officers and doctors, a skeleton is triumphantly
declared ready for battle.
</P>
<P>
   Another view of institutional obtuseness is Alfred Kubin's
``government'' (1901), depicting a shiplike juggernaut rumbling
through a landscape, belching black smoke. Tiny figures idle on one
of its decks while a pompous official on the deck below surveys the
scene as he manipulates what could be a telescope or a gun.
</P>
<P>
   On a different wavelength in the grotesque group is the detached
humor of Surrealism, which lends itself particularly to visual
zaniness, like Max Ernst's ``Farewell My Beautiful Land of Marie
Laurencin, Help! Help!'' (1919), an altered photoengraving of a
large, enigmatic machine ejecting from its top a smaller one. A
pre-Surrealist titillater is Odilon Redon's ``Eye Like a Strange
Balloon Mounts Toward Infinity'' (1882), in which a big,
heavy-lashed eye in the form of a balloon rises majestically above
a grassy field.
</P>
<P>
   Among less otherworldly contributions to this category are Jean
Dubuffet's ``Cow'' (1954), a bovine wreck sadly encumbered by a
very full udder, and his pages from ``El Golea II'' (1948), a
sketchbook that takes off on camels and desert people. They prove
that humor in art is often inseparable from draftsmanship.
</P>
<P>
   The category of wit, which the Modern views as ``the ability to
perceive incongruous relationships and express them in a pointed
and/or sarcastic manner,'' includes entries as disparate as Louise
Bourgeois' ``Hold Up'' (1989), a simple suspender part sewn onto a
piece of pink blotting paper, and Baldessari's ``I Will Not Make
Any More Boring Art'' (1971), a videotape of a hand writing that
statement, like a schoolboy punishment, over and over again on a
piece of paper.
</P>
<P>
   More deadpan specimens are Christo's `` `Museum of Modern Art
Packed' Project'' (1968), a rendering of the Modern done up as a
package; and ``A Flux Suicide Kit'' (1966) by Ben Vautier, a member
of the subversive Fluxus group of the 1960s. The kit contains
matches, a syringe, a razor blade, a fish hook, an electric plug, a
nail and a tiny bullet.
</P>
<P>
   In caricature, the cast is large, from Miguel Covarrubias'
wonderful 1925 rendition of the comedian Fanny Brice _ all nose,
smile and black bangs _ attended by her adoring gambler husband,
Nicky Arnstein, to Robin Winters' ``Metropolitan Acquaintances''
(1974), three large panels bearing dozens of pencil sketches of
hilariously fanciful urban types.
</P>
<P>
   With uncharacteristic chauvinism, the Modern has also seen fit
to include works by or about a couple of its own former staff
members: Rene d'Harnoncourt, a former director of the museum, is
represented by a series of portrait ``D'Hoodles,'' and Monroe
Wheeler, the Modern's director of exhibitions for half a century,
who was sketched by several admirers _ including Ben Shahn _ who
took note of his slightly simian presence.
</P>
<P>
   The show's cartoon and comics section runs from Lyonel
Feininger's 1906 studies for a strip in The Chicago Tribune dealing
with the escapades of ``The Kin-der-Kids'' to Simmons' wall
drawing, ``Boom,'' a very satisfying cartoon explosion of 1996
especially reconstituted for this show. Other delights include
three 1980 comics-influenced drawings by Philip Guston (one is a
Beckettesque view of a ladder placed next to a chain of balls
descending from a calm blue sky) and Elizabeth Murray's ``Popeye''
(1982), a near-abstract collage that makes much of the
spinach-eating sailor's muscle power. (Some of this material, of
course, appeared in the 1990 exhibition ``High and Low,'' the
Modern's report on the bonding of mass and elite culture.)
</P>
<P>
   Although this show is far from an ideal homage to humor, it's
nice to know that one of our great museums is taking the subject
seriously.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
