<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UAM-EARNS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UAM HIT BY HEAVY OUTFLOW IN 1998 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ United Asset Management Corp., a giant holding company
for 50 diverse investment firms, has for years watched clients
withdraw money as competitors garnered a flood of new business. The
leakage, during a strong stock market, has depressed UAM's share
price and sent the company soul-searching.
</P>
<P>
   Now UAM says it is making substantial changes. Some investors,
while encouraged, are not yet convinced.
</P>
<P>
   UAM reported Thursday that clients yanked out a net $4.6 billion
from its units in the fourth quarter. That brought 1998's outflows
to $19.8 billion, compared to $16 billion in 1997 and $3.3 billion
in 1996. While the company staged a turnaround in earnings last
year, UAM chief executive Norton Reamer admitted that client cash
flow was still his top problem.
</P>
<P>
   UAM, which has generally taken 100 percent stakes in its units,
has a hands-off strategy, allowing affiliates to run themselves as
they wish and taking 41 percent of their revenue. Critics charge
that the approach can leave laggard units with little incentive to
attract new business.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Reamer says, he is acting on a vow made last year to invest
only in promising subsidiaries. The winners this year include
Acadian Asset Management Inc. of Boston, which plans a Singapore
office to start a private Asian equity fund, and Rogge Global
Partners PLC, a London fixed-income shop where UAM will bankroll
three new investment professionals. In all, 15 units will receive a
total of $20 million in assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Reamer also said that UAM recently established a group to
concentrate on winning new business at affiliates and reshuffled
its six-person management committee. Late last year, UAM revamped
its marketing approach after realizing that the holding company was
competing with, rather than supporting, its affiliates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're certainly a different company than we were a year ago,''
UAM spokesman John Hubbard said.
</P>
<P>
   Some investors are skeptical. ``I guess we'll see,'' said Larry
Sondike, a senior vice president and fund manager at Franklin
Mutual Advisors, which as of last September was UAM's top
shareholder, with nearly 15 percent of the company's stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether increasing spending at affiliates will stem outflows
remains to be seen,'' Sondike said. But he said he was heartened by
UAM's share buyback and slowdown in expensive acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   UAM once spent all its money acquiring other firms. Now, in a
shift in its core strategy, UAM shells out cash to repurchase its
own depressed stock, a move Reamer deemed a good investment. The
company spent $270 million last year purchasing 11 percent of its
outstanding shares and is now buying 1 million shares a month.
</P>
<P>
   Still, UAM, with $201.4 billion in assets, has not ceased
looking for targets. ``We'd be very interested in doing a large
acquisition in the fixed-income area,'' Reamer said.
</P>
<P>
   Meeting analysts' expectations, UAM saw fourth-quarter net
income rise to $16.5 million, or $0.26 a share share, from a loss
of $75.4 million, or minus $1.09 a share, a year ago. Profits for
1998 were $78.5 million, compared with a loss of $4.1 million in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   Around 45 percent of UAM's business is in defined-benefit
retirement plans. UAM says that the negative cash flow reflects an
industrywide trend toward defined-contribution plans and that every
one of its units is profitable, despite the outflows.
</P>
<P>
   UAM's stock, in the doldrums, rose 3/4 to close Thursday at 23
3/8 on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
