<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN OUTPUT OFF; WORST DROP IN 4 YEARS
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Russia's gross domestic product fell 4.6 percent in
1998, the sharpest drop in four years, the State Statistics
Committee reported Thursday. There were declines in industry,
construction and farming.
</P>
<P>
   Before the financial crisis, Russia's economy appeared to be
leveling off, and the government had hoped it would turn around
last year.
</P>
<P>
   But the plunge of the ruble last summer paralyzed banking,
increased the cost of imports and discouraged investment. Russia's
fledgling financial services sector has been especially hard hit.
Some brokerages have laid off more than half their staff, and
Inkombank, a leading bank, is in bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   The economic woes have been compounded by the fall in oil
prices, which has taken a heavy toll on export earnings. Russia
also suffered its worst harvest in decades.
</P>
<P>
   Some companies have prospered from the drop in imports. But most
Russians have suffered a decline in living standards.
</P>
<P>
   The government has projected that the gross domestic product
will slide by as much as 3 percent this year, but some analysts say
that is optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
