<HEADLINE>
DANIEL JOHNSTON: ECCENTRICITY, INSTABILITY AND ABIDING GRACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By ANN POWERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``My guitar string broke, and I'm really upset,''
muttered Daniel Johnston on Wednesday night at CBGB's 313 Gallery
in Manhattan. The capacity crowd cheered loudly for the Texas-based
singer-songwriter, just wanting to keep him onstage.
</P>
<P>
   Johnston, whose self-produced cassettes became fetish objects
for underground rockers in the early 1980s, has trouble getting
through more than a few songs in his infrequent performances.
Johnston has trouble in general; he has been institutionalized and
takes medication to subdue his mental demons. His drastically
heartfelt songs have earned him admirers, including the band Yo La
Tengo and choreographer Bill T. Jones, but Johnston &UR;  &LR; remains an
outsider artist, relentlessly focused on a microcosmic and
ultimately alienated vision.
</P>
<P>
   Why does one such eccentric get singled out? Here was Johnston,
a rotund man in sweat pants, punishingly strumming a cheap guitar
and warbling in a meek tenor grown rough around the edges. He sang
about Caspar the Friendly Ghost and funeral homes. ``Love will see
you through,'' he intoned, but he also told of feeling like a
vampire. His optimism was as desperately credulous as his fears
were stark.
</P>
<P>
   He might have been huddled before an open guitar case in the
subway baring his heart for quarters. Instead, he was starting a
mini-tour that ends at the Knitting Factory Friday night. His crude
songs did communicate a deep grace; their guileless longing was the
kind most people are too proud to express. Perhaps his audience
feels grateful for that.
</P>
<P>
   Yet how much Johnston's instability influenced his fans'
feelings remained unclear. Do they believe his lack of inner
boundaries make him more honest? And if there is truth in the link
between art and madness, why do all of us not take more time to
listen to the ragged bards on our own street corners?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
