<HEADER>
A2262 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NAUGHTON-THEATER-REVI     02-04 1010
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAUGHTON-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`STREET OF DREAMS': HE'S BEEN AROUND LONG ENOUGH TO KNOW THE SCORE
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes at end of review) 
(DW) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Midway in James Naughton's impeccably suave solo
concert show ``Street of Dreams,'' the lean, handsome, slightly
weatherbeaten actor and singer pauses to reminisce for a moment
about the 1989 Broadway musical ``City of Angels,'' in which he
portrayed an impeccably suave Los Angeles gumshoe. As Naughton
tosses off hilarious snippets of Larry Gelbart's dialogue spoofing
Raymond Chandler, you have the sensation that Naughton and his
stage alter ego of a decade ago aren't all that far apart in
outlook. Both are guys who think they know the score. Both would
rather die than ever be glimpsed losing their cool.
</P>
<P>
   ``Street of Dreams,'' at the Promenade Theater, is an immensely
entertaining musical evening, in which Naughton, accompanied by a
first-rate pop quintet, saunters through assorted popular standards
and jazz nuggets with the assurance of a star athlete marking off
the telephone numbers of favorite dates on his bulging Rolodex.
</P>
<P>
   The show, a theatrical extension of a cabaret act he debuted
last June at the Manhattan Theater Club, is ``presented'' at the
Promenade by Mike Nichols, who has spiffed it up in helpful ways.
</P>
<P>
   This time, the monologues are longer and more carefully worked
out; the material flows more evenly, and the comedy has been
accentuated. Once again, the singer is backed by John Oddo, an
exceptionally talented pianist and musical director leading a group
who also double as background vocalists, in one number becoming the
Mills Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   Naughton is not only a gifted pop-jazz crooner in a tradition
that includes Bing Crosby, Johnny Hartman and Joe Williams; he is
also a polished after-dinner narrator of tall theater tales. A
comic high point of his show is a monologue about actors going up
on their lines that ends with a priceless anecdote about a moment
in which John Gielgud and Ralph Richardson once found themselves
facing each other on the stage unable to make a sound.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Street of Dreams,'' for all its humor, is essentially an
evening of music, in which Naughton applies himself to material as
far-ranging as ``Star Dust'' and Randy Newman's caustic, dramatic
monologue ``My Life Is Good.'' As much as Naughton has
distinguished himself as a musical theater singer, the voice he
displays in ``Street of Dreams'' is revelatory in its flexibility
and sheer beauty.
</P>
<P>
   That voice, a deep, resonant baritone, divides into two parts.
The upper register is a strikingly rich, mellow crooning voice.
Shaded downward, it becomes a noticeably rougher but still fairly
velvety bass-baritone. It's a remarkable instrument, because there
simply aren't many male voices anywhere who make a sound this
languorously inviting. Crooning classics like ``Star Dust,'' ``The
Folks Who Live on the Hill,'' and ``She's Funny That Way,''
Naughton conveys the dreamy, paternal homeyness of a younger,
hipper Crosby.
</P>
<P>
   But beneath his smooth, serenely seductive surface, Naughton
displays a stubborn diffidence. Throughout the show, both in his
singing and in the stories he chooses to tell, you sense someone
who is either fiercely protective of his emotional privacy or
unwilling to explore the vulnerable or tragic side of life. Beyond
being unapologetically beautiful, his singing takes few emotional
risks.
</P>
<P>
   Naughton glides over the surface of Billy Strayhorn's bitter,
alcoholic confession ``Lush Life'' without seeming to notice that
the lyric is a self-lacerating expression of heartbreak and
despair.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of ``Lush Life,'' impeccably suave just won't do.
Crooning the Elvis Presley signature song ``Are You Lonesome
Tonight?'' he also maintains a safe emotional distance, treating
the song's central spoken monologue as dead space that's easier to
mock than to try to bring to life. What makes Presley's version so
compelling is the punchy sincerity he invested in those hopelessly
corny spoken verses.
</P>
<P>
   If Naughton can't bring himself to risk shedding even an ounce
of cool, his casual bravado serves him impressively in the uptempo
songs, especially ``I Want You to Be My Baby,'' an uproarious piece
of jumping jive composed by Jon Hendricks. He also has great fun
with Hank Snow's 1962 country hit, ``I''ve Been Everywhere,'' a
tongue-twisting bit of geographical name-dropping in which he
vocally accelerates into an auctioneer's full-tilt bark. Naughton
can swing hard and loose, and when he does, his voice toughens
without losing its limber pliability.
</P>
<P>
   Dramatically Naughton is most at home with numbers that hand him
full-blown characters. He is very funny, mugging and flapping
around as the pretentious narrator of the Dave Frishberg-Bob
Dorough jazz novelty ``I'm Hip,'' in which a would-be '60s cool-cat
drops all the wrong names (Sammy Davis Jr., Bobby Darin) to certify
his hipster credentials. He is even funnier declaiming ``My Life Is
Good,'' Newman's savage first-person portrait of a smug, soulless
Los Angeles businessman obsessed with cocaine and brand names.
</P>
<P>
   If ``Street of Dreams'' is a virtuosic star turn, it lacks a
definitive number in which the singer makes that final leap and
dares to give himself away. Naughton will soothe you, amuse you and
get your feet tapping. He'll show you many wonderful songs you
might have missed, and wow you with his sound. One thing he won't
do is break your heart.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `JAMES NAUGHTON: STREET OF DREAMS'
</P>
<P>
   Conceived and performed by James Naughton. Musical direction,
John Oddo; set consultant, John Lee Beatty; lighting consultant,
Tharon Musser; sound by Domonic Sack; production stage manager,
Karen Moore; general management, EGS; associate producers, the
Araca Group, Meyer Ackerman; production consultant, Michael Bush.
Produced by Julian Schlossberg, Chase Mishkin and David Stone.
Presented by Mike Nichols. At the Promenade Theater, 2162 Broadway.
 &QL;
