<HEADLINE>
YOU CAN BUY ANYTHING ON THE NET
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Cool Site of the Year Awards were bestowed at Webster Hall
in New York recently, and eBay, the online auction house
headquartered in San Jose, won Coolest Shopping Site of the Year.
But eBay didn't have anyone there to pick up the prize, a void into
which  &UR; Danny Digital  &LR; was delighted to jump. Digital, publisher of
the zine Smug, took the stage, made an acceptance speech and made
off with the prize, a plaque and stand.
</P>
<P>
   Now, &LR;  he's selling it on eBay, with such a winning sales pitch _
``It is made of the finest Lucite, carved from the uncharted peaks
of Mount Lucite in Kenya. ... This puppy is built to last!'' _ that
with a few days left to go, bidding is up to $5,100. Digital says
he's so surprised at that amount that he's decided to donate his
earnings ``to a lefty, humanist charity.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Kristen Seuell &LR;  of eBay says the company might have been
annoyed if Digital had sold the trophy for profit but is happy to
have him sell it for charity. ``We're thrilled that he was able to
pick up our award,'' she said, but puzzled as to why the bidding's
gone so high. ``This guy probably has a lot of friends, or there
are a lot of people interested in having an award of eBay's.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEDERAL FROLICS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Lawrence Helman &LR; , informed by a postal clerk that the
envelope he wanted to mail would cost 55 cents, was handed a
33-cent  &UR; Malcolm X  &LR; and a 22-cent  &UR; Uncle Sam &LR; , a partnership he
calls ``a toast to detente.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Rep.  &UR; Nancy Pelosi &LR; , D-S.F., told Lamplighters manager John
Alecca that she couldn't miss the ironies and relevance to current
events in the 1931 Gershwin musical ``Of Thee I Sing,'' the
Lamplighters' production of which opened last weekend, but that
 &UR; Bill Clinton  &LR; probably isn't in the mood right now to be amused at
the parallels. The show is about a president whose campaign is
based on his quest for love; members of Congress, and just about
everyone else in Washington, are made to look foolish. In a nod to
the present, the sleeves of the chief justice sport stripes.
</P>
<P>
   _ The latest People magazine includes a quote from a 1974
interview with  &UR; Lady Bird Johnson &LR;  in response to a question about
her husband's infidelities. ``If all those ladies had some good
points that I didn't have,'' she said, ``I hope I had the sense to
learn by it.'' Meanwhile, mean-spirited Washington gossip
columnists have been referring to  &UR; Monica Lewinsky &LR;  this week as
the ``Mayflower Mademoiselle.'' Lewinsky stayed in the Mayflower
hotel, but never made sex a profession.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Seasons of Her Life'' (Scribner, $27),  &UR; Ann Blackman &LR; 's new
biography of  &UR; Madeleine Albright &LR; , reveals that the main speaker at
Albright's Wellesley graduation in 1959 told graduates they had
``the ideal preparation to serve at the very heart of the home.''
And  &UR; John Glenn  &LR; has signed with Bantam Books for his memoirs. A
Bantam spokesman said he has ``kept meticulous diaries over the
years.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EARTHLY DELIGHTS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ F &LR; ebruary 5 &LR;  is National Weatherman's Day.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Hair is an essential part of birds nests,'' advises Jump
magazine, ``so leave some of the hair you pull out of your brush
outside for our feathered friends.''
</P>
<P>
   _ What's next on the trendy take-out menu? Pommes Frites in New
York sells ``authentic Belgian fries'' in white paper cones, with a
range of toppings that include garlic mustard and satay peanut
sauce, says Attache magazine.
</P>
<P>
   _ Nestled among Mother Earth News' classified ads offering
preparatory materials for Y2K,  &UR; William Williams &LR;  discovered the
``Humanure Handbook,'' a guide to composting human manure. ``A
classic,'' says the ad.
</P>
