<HEADER>
A2264 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIRTRAN-LOSS05-COX     02-04 0487
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRTRAN-LOSS05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AirTran closer to profitability
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ AirTran Airways failed to fly out of the red in the
fourth quarter, despite strong revenue gains and lower costs.
</P>
<P>
   But the loss narrowed from a year earlier, and AirTran's new
chief executive maintained a long-awaited turnaround is just over
the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have much to look forward to,'' said Joseph B. Leonard, who
replaced D. Joseph Corr at AirTran's helm last month. ``We believe
that in 1999 we will see the results of our reorganization,
improved operations, hard work and caring customer service
reflected in the bottom line.''
</P>
<P>
   Today AirTran is expected to announce schedule changes that will
include an additional destination from Hartsfield International
Airport, and new tour package products.
</P>
<P>
   The airline has 18 gates at Hartsfield but has worked out an
agreement with airport officials to double up at four gates,
providing new room for growth, Leonard said.
</P>
<P>
   AirTran is headquartered in Orlando, Fla., but has its main
flight hub at Hartsfield. Leonard told analysts Thursday he plans
no big shift in that strategy, despite the challenge of competing
with Atlanta-based Delta Air Lines.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth quarter, AirTran Holdings Inc. said it lost $3
million, or 5 cents a share, excluding a one-time $27.5 million
write-off related to planned retirements of Boeing 737s. Including
that charge, the net loss was $30.5 million, or 47 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   In the same quarter of 1997, the carrier lost $40.7 million, or,
63 cents a share, including charges.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue for the quarter rose 51 percent, to $105.7 million, on a
40 percent capacity increase. Operating costs declined 29 percent,
led by a 24 percent fall in fuel prices.
</P>
<P>
   One of the reasons the higher revenue and lower costs didn't
produce a profit was a drop in average fares to $71.30 vs. $83.88 a
year earlier. AirTran in recent months has offered continuous sales
to lift ridership.
</P>
<P>
   That effort was moderately successful, raising average load
factors to 57.1percent for the quarter compared with 52.1 percent a
year earlier. Leonard said further gains this year, coupled with
declining costs, should bring profits.
</P>
<P>
   AirTran finished the year with $24.3 million in cash, down from
$34.5 million at the end of the third quarter of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard said the airline faces about $18.5 million in outlays
this year for required noise modifications to DC-9 jets and
pre-payments on new Boeing 717s scheduled for delivery late this
year. However, he said he expects no liquidity crunch because
AirTran should be ``cash-positive'' from March forward and is
selling some minor assets to build cash. The new jets will be
financed, he said.
</P>
<P>
   AirTran Holdings stock rose 21 7/8 cents Thursday to $3.43 3/4.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
