<HEADER>
A2267 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATLANTA-GAS-RATES05-C     02-04 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATLANTA-GAS-RATES05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AGL chief takes blame for rate disaster
 &HT;    By Matthew C. Quinn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ AGL Resources, parent of Atlanta Gas Light Co., holds
its annual shareholders meeting today with Chief Executive Walter
M. Higgins taking full responsibility for the recent rate fiasco.
</P>
<P>
   ``Theres no question that it's hurt the company,'' Higgins in an
interview Thursday. He noted some similarities to Coca-Cola Co.'s
disastrous launch of New Coke more than a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   Today's 10 a.m. meeting at Cobb Galleria, which is open to
registered shareholders only, is the second for Higgins as
president and CEO of AGL Resources and chief executive of Atlanta
Gas Light Co.
</P>
<P>
   AGL plans to release its first fiscal quarter earnings later
today after the stock market closes.
</P>
<P>
   The company warned last week that earnings would be lower than
analysts expect because of losses at Sonat Marketing Co., a natural
gas wholesale venture in which it holds a 35 percent stake.
Analysts had expected earnings of 38 cents per share, according go
First Call Corp. The Sonat Marketing losses are expected to shave
off about 10 cents per share.
</P>
<P>
   Higgins said the losses stemmed from an error in accounting for
natural gas transactions by the unit, which is managed by
Birmingham, Ala.-based Sonat. They should result in only a one-time
charge, since the accounting has been straightened out, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Higgins said the earnings announcement, coupled with the furor
over Atlanta Gas Lights rates, had clearly contributed to a decline
in AGL's stock price during the last month from $23 to less than
$20.
</P>
<P>
   Higgins noted that most utility stocks have been dropping
because of the anticipated adverse impact of warm weather on sales.
The bond market has also been taking a beating, and utility stocks
tend to follow bonds.
</P>
<P>
   During the meeting today, Higgins said he will review his first
year as CEO, during which the nation's eighth-largest gas utility
began an unprecedented shakeup with deregulation of Georgia's
natural gas market. He will also discuss ``some of what went on''
with Atlanta Gas Light's rates ``and what we have done to try and
deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   The company had undergone ``a thousand post-mortems trying to
understand'' how it so badly miscalculated with the rate structure
that was put in place Nov. 1 with the start of deregulation, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   To recover its expenses as customers began purchasing gas from
marketers, AGL's newly deregulated rates were heavily based on
costs for interstate pipeline capacity theoretically needed to
serve homes and businesses on the coldest day of the year. When
this winter's temperatures turned out to be unseasonably warm,
consumers were left footing hefty bills for pipeline capacity they
didn't use.
</P>
<P>
   After thousands of complaints flooded the utility's call centers
and the Public Service Commission, Atlanta Gas Light reached a
settlement with regulators last week that called for $14.5 million
in refunds and scrapping the rate structure in favor of one based
entirely on actual gas consumption.
</P>
<P>
   According to Higgins, ``dozens of people'' inside the company,
as well as an outside consultant, worked for weeks formulating the
new rate structure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of us, including me, participated in discussions of
setting this up,'' he said. Many options were considered, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that on the final day that anyone said, 'Let's go
with that one,' `` he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Higgins said he knew of no one who spoke up
and warned of the potential impact of warm weather. But he added
that he takes full responsibility for what, in retrospect, was a
big mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nobody else that's responsible except me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Higgins said the comparison to New Coke was a ``very apt
description'' of what occurred. At a special board meeting last
month, he said, board member Frank Barron Jr., vice president of
public affairs at Coca-Cola Bottling Co. of Rome, said the rate
crisis ``was similar to what Coke faced,'' Higgins recalled.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-based soft drink company ``had many of the same
customer issues'' when grocers and other vendors saw their sales
threatened by the abrupt change of brands, he said.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid a repeat of the rate debacle, Higgins said the company
has put together a full-time team, under Henry P. Linginfelter,
former vice president of new business, to ``think through millions
and millions of issues'' that may arise as deregulation proceeds.
</P>
<P>
   One issue is what happens when those customers who have not
selected a marketer realize they have been assigned to one at
random by the PSC.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guess who they will call?'' Higgins mused.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
