u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLE-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT     02-04 0462
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLE-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`NATALIE COLE': DADDY'S TORCHBEARER LIFTS HER OWN TORCH 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ What are Cole family values? The teaming of Natalie
Cole and her uncle Freddy (at the Blue Note through Monday), with
the genial voice of her father, Nat, pumped over the sound system
for the inevitable posthumous father-daughter duet on
``Unforgettable,'' offers an entertaining musical seminar on the
subject.
</P>
<P>
   Another of Ms. Cole's uncles, Eddie, is also making an indirect
appearance, with the performance by Natalie and Freddy of ``Sweet
Someone,'' a ballad he once sang as part of a duo called Eddie and
Betty.
</P>
<P>
   Shared musical values were certainly in evidence at Wednesday's
early show, at which Ms. Cole and her uncle projected the same
studied graciousness that was a calling card of Nat, who died in
1965. Like their legendary relative who casts a benevolent
ever-lengthening shadow over music, the brother and the daughter
are jazz singers who instinctively add a smooth pop gloss to their
material.
</P>
<P>
   Freddy Cole, who is 12 years younger than Nat and the youngest
of five children, puts his own spin on the Cole style. His singing
is noticeably rougher and more overtly blues-tinged. What he shares
with his brother is enunciation so pristine that every syllable
comes out glistening.
</P>
<P>
   In a show that concentrated largely on songs popularized by Nat,
Freddy's blues leanings added a welcome touch of earthiness to
``Wild Is Love,'' ``Never Let Me Go'' and ``To the Ends of the
Earth,'' songs memorable mostly for the fact that Nat recorded
them.
</P>
<P>
   Cole's quintet, which featured himself on piano and Gerry Byrd
on guitar, played with a seamless coordination that suggested the
meshing of well-oiled machinery. When Ms. Cole joined her uncle,
the emphasis remained on Nat songs, the two casually trading verses
of ``Somewhere Along the Way'' and ``Send for Me.''
</P>
<P>
   For her solo set, Ms. Cole brought in her own band. As much as
she tries to emulate her father's warmth and air of supreme ease,
there's always been an undercurrent of tension and ambivalence in
her singing. Should she be daddy's little girl, a light cheerful
chip off the old block recycling Nat's legacy in a spirit of
worshipful nostalgia? Or has the time come for her to strike out
into grittier territory?
</P>
<P>
   The show on Wednesday found her playing it both ways. In
pleasant, lightly swinging pop-jazz versions of songs like
``Smile'' and ``Route 66,'' she was the dutiful daughter looking
back adoringly. But ``Frim Fram Sauce'' and ``I'm a Woman'' found
her grasping at a tougher, bluesier sensuality as though seeking
release from the ultimately limiting and oppressive role of
official torch-bearer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-04-99 1931EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990204.0360 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 19:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2269 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCI-INTERNET05-COX     02-04 0533
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCI-INTERNET05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MCI WorldCom re-enters Internet market
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ MCI WorldCom is back in the Internet access business.
</P>
<P>
   The company announced a new Internet service dubbed MCI WorldCom
Internet aimed at residential customers, through a partnership with
online service CompuServe, a subsidiary of America Online.
</P>
<P>
   Financial terms of the agreement, which is not exclusive for
either partner, were not revealed.
</P>
<P>
   In a conference call Thursday, MCI WorldCom and CompuServe said
the service will feature customized ``start pages'' of news,
sports, weather and other features furnished by CompuServe.
</P>
<P>
   Cost for 150 hours will be $16.95 for MCI long distance
customers and $19.95 for those who use only the Internet service,
with three introductory months priced at $16.95. Prospective users
can sign up now at http://www.mciworld.com or by phone at (800)
459-8892.
</P>
<P>
   MCI previously offered Internet service but was forced to sell
that business to Cable &AMP; Wireless for $1.75 billion to win
regulatory approval for its merger with WorldCom.
</P>
<P>
   The new service is also another step on the comeback trail for
CompuServe, one of the first commercial online services.
CompuServe's business fortunes were sagging until its purchase by
AOL.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's deal provides it with a strong partner and a
guarantee of new online users. Unlike fellow online provider
Prodigy, which ventured onto the Internet alone, CompuServe will
provide content only and let MCI WorldCom provide the dial up
connection.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to CompuServe content, MCI WorldCom Internet
customers will be able to download a licensed version of
CompuServe's Instant Messenger software, free parental control
software from Cyber Patrol, Web page building and Internet search
functions.
</P>
<P>
   ``MCI WorldCom understood that CompuServe was the best brand to
offer their customers the best experiences for busy adults on the
'Net,'' said CompuServe Chief Operating Officer Audrey Weil. ``It's
the first time CompuServe has been a gateway for ISP subscribers.
This represents a significant U.S. revenue stream for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say MCI has to get back into the Internet business to
be competitive within the industry. Christopher Mines, director of
new-media research at Forrester Research, said MCI WorldCom's
challenge will be to differentiate itself in a very crowded market.
However, CompuServe's business focus, combined with airline
partnerships and frequent flyer offerings, should help draw an
initial distinction.
</P>
<P>
   America Online bought CompuServe last year in a three-way
agreement with WorldCom Inc. and H&AMP;R Block Inc., which owned
CompuServe at the time. Dulles, Va.-based America Online has more
than 15 million subscribers, while CompuServe has about 2 million
members.
</P>
<P>
   Although MCI WorldCom's consumer Internet access service does
compete with CompuServe's own online service and with AOL's online
service, Weil stressed that she expects to see more such alliances
among competitors in the future.
</P>
<P>
   _Bloomberg News contributed to this report
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
