<HEADLINE>
UN INSPECTION TEAM CHIEF TO STEP DOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLUM LYNCH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Richard Butler, the beleaguered chief UN
weapons inspector, said Thursday that he would step down at the end
of June. The decision follows an outcry over reports that the
United States used the Australian arms specialist's office to spy
on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Butler told CNN Thursday that he would ``move on'' when his
contract expires June 30. ``I quite frankly don't think I'll be
seeking an extension,'' he said. But he added that he would devote
his remaining five months in office to fighting for the survival of
the UN Special Commission, called UNSCOM, credited with destroying
more Iraqi weapons than the US-led alliance during the 1991 Persian
Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq is showing signs that an expanding US air campaign against
its antiaircraft batteries is taking a toll. US officials said that
Iraq had begun to withdraw its air-defense systems from the US- and
British-patrolled ``no-fly zones'' in southern and northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials estimate that they have destroyed 20 percent
of Iraq's air defense systems since the air war on Iraq, dubbed
Operation Desert Fox, began Dec. 16. The US and Britain have
destroyed or damaged 40 antiaircraft batteries since Dec. 28, when
the US and Iraq began engaging in daily skirmishes in the no-fly
zones.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is evidence that'' Iraqi leader Saddam Hussein ``is
pulling back,'' said US Defense Secretary William S. Cohen. ``I
think it is clear . . . that he doesn't want to lose all of his''
surface-to-air missiles ``and doesn't want to place his troops in
greater jeopardy.''
</P>
<P>
   Butler, meanwhile, has come under pressure from Russia, France,
China, and other council members to resign since he released a
December report that underscored Iraqi intransigence on disarmament
and triggered the US bombing campaign. Those countries have long
supported Iraq's position that UNSCOM has overreached its mandate.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Moscow again demanded Butler's resignation in a
letter to UN Secretary General Kofi Annan. The demand came in
response to Butler's charge, leveled in an interview with an
Australian newspaper, that Russia's UN ambassador, Sergei Lavrov,
was spreading lies about Butler allegedly serving US interests in
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   In his latest report to the Security Council last month, Butler
defended the use of Western intelligence to investigate Iraq's
efforts to conceal its chemical and biological weapons programs.
Butler chronicled a long and persistent Iraqi policy of lying to
the United Nations about the programs. He said that any serious
effort to prevent Iraq from developing new weapons must involve
UNSCOM's weapons specialists.
</P>
<P>
   US officials defended Butler's record.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has done an excellent job at a very difficult time and
we'll continue to push Iraq to comply with disarmament
obligations,'' said US national security spokesman David Leavy.
``We still believe UNSCOM is the best way to deal with the
disarmament of Iraq and we'll continue to work with Chairman
Butler.''
</P>
<P>
   Council diplomats said that Butler's departure would do little
to guarantee UNSCOM's preeminent role in disarming Iraq. In the
wake of the bombing, the UN Security Council has established three
panels to ensure that Iraq meets its obligations to disarm, provide
humanitarian relief to its people, and to account for hundreds of
Kuwaiti citizens who disappeared during the Persian Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   The disarmament panel, which is to be headed by Brazil's UN
ambassador Celso Amorim, provides an opportunity for countries
hostile to UNSCOM to try to dilute its influence. UNSCOM's efforts
to detect Iraq's efforts to rebuild its prohibited weapons program
have been severely undermined by its departure from the country in
December.
</P>
<P>
   But US officials that UNSCOM's expertise must be retained if the
United Nations is ever to eliminate all of its long-range missiles
and nuclear, chemical and biological weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``UNSCOM is not folding,'' said Peter Burleigh, the chief US
representative to the United Nations. ``From the US perspective
it's very important that it continue to function as vigorously as
it has in the past because it is depository of all this accumulated
knowledge about Iraq.''
</P>
</TEXT>
