<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2279 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-UMASS-TUITION-BOS &LR;      02-04 0606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-UMASS-TUITION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELLUCCI OFFERS UMASS TRUSTEES A DEAL ON TUITION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY AND KATE ZERNIKE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Governor Paul Cellucci said Thursday he will restore
$4.6 million to the University of Massachusetts if the board of
trustees reverses its decisions to raise tuition and fees.
</P>
<P>
   At a meeting with Boston Globe reporters and editors, Cellucci
said he was imploring the trustees to keep student costs down, and
if they do, he would not push legislation he filed this week
stripping the board members of control over tuition and fees. Nor
would he veto $4.6 million in funding _ the amount equivalent to
the higher student costs _ from his proposed budget next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to push pretty hard to get the board to change
their vote,'' Cellucci said during the lunch meeting. ``Their
changing their vote would mean the legislation is less likely'' to
be necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Connolly, spokesman for UMass President William M.
Bulger, said that while the trustees were open to the governor's
ideas on how to generate money without raising fees, they also felt
they had ``charted the right course.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're certainly open to any suggestion the governor may
have,'' Connolly said. ``But our chief concern is that university
students have the resources, the technical resources and the
classroom resources, they need to compete.
</P>
<P>
   Connolly said that all five of the student trustees were in
favor of the fee increase.
</P>
<P>
   ``The students they represent want to see some improvements and
want to have some of the additional resources that their
counterparts at other universities have,'' he said. ``They feel
they shouldn't be asking the taxpayers to contribute more, they,
the students, should be contributing more.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he added, ``nothing is set in stone.''
</P>
<P>
   The fee increase the board approved Wednesday _ an average of
$67 for students who do not live on campus, and $251 for those who
do _ will pay for revamping computer labs across the four
undergraduate campuses. The fees will also allow UMass to complete
a fiber optic cable that will enable, say, a student at Dartmouth
to access the Amherst campus library. It will pay the university's
share of new campus center construction in Boston and Lowell,
Connolly said, and 20 percent of student fees goes to need-based
scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci said the relatively small amount of the tuition hike
was not the point because UMass is still expensive compared to
other public universities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want it to be more affordable for more families,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci, outraged that the board members he appointed did not
heed his call to continue the four-year trend of reducing tuition
and fees, filed a bill Wednesday to have the Board of Higher
Education set the rates instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think having control there is important,'' he said. ``I
should have been given a heads-up on this.''
</P>
<P>
   Trustees are appointed to five-year terms and Cellucci believes
they cannot be fired over policy issues. But as the board seats
open up, prospective trustees will be asked where they stand on the
issue of tuition increases, the governor said.
</P>
<P>
   However, the governor will not interfere with UMass President
William Bulger's 49 percent pay raise, believing the former Senate
President has improved standards on campuses throughout the state.
</P>
<P>
   And he said Bulger's salary, eventually climbing to $282,000 a
year, should not factor into the debate over upwardly creeping
tuition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure those issues are related,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
