<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-KOSOVO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON CONSIDERS SENDING U.S. TROOPS TO KOSOVO AS PART OF NATO
FORCE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton outlined Thursday the conditions
under which U.S. military forces would join NATO ground troops in
the troubled Kosovo region as he acknowledged for the first time
that he is ``seriously considering'' deploying American soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials stepped up efforts to make their case
on why the United States should join European forces in the
Yugoslav province if the warring factions reach a peace accord this
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``The time to stop this conflict in Kosovo is now, before it
spreads, and when it can be contained at an acceptable cost,''
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   In Belgrade, the Serbian Parliament voted to send a delegation
to France this weekend for peace talks with Kosovo's Albanians. But
Serb Premier Mirko Marjanovic struck a defiant tone as he vowed
NATO troops would never be allowed into Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   NATO renewed threats of air strikes against Belgrade if
President Slobodan Milosevic continued to maintain his forces in
Kosovo. Troops under Milosevic have been blamed for a massacres and
violence against the ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   The 11 months of fighting there &UR;  &LR; have left 2,000 people dead and
thousands homeless.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said if a peace pact is agreed upon, ``We are seriously
considering the possibility of our participation'' in a NATO
peacekeeping operation. ``No decision has been reached,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   In briefings to a skeptical Congress on Wednesday, Pentagon
officials said the United States could provide 2,000 to 4,000
troops as part of a NATO force of 20,000 to 30,000 soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, is one of several members of
Congress opposed to ground troops in Kosovo because of an unclear
game plan by the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison, an outspoken critic of the administration's Balkan
policy, was one of the members briefed by officials as they sought
to rally Capital Hill support for a possible NATO mission.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton outlined four conditions for U.S. participation: A
strong and effective peace agreement, a demonstrated commitment to
implementing a peace agreement by the parties, the withdrawal of
Serbian security forces and weapons restrictions on Kosovo's
Albanians and a well-defined NATO mission with a clear exit
strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our European allies and partners will have to contribute a
substantial majority of the troops but NATO is a partnership and
they have a right to expect the United States, which has been a
leader of NATO for 50 years now, to be a part of that,'' Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said in another speech
that the U.S. contribution to ground forces ``will be no more than
several thousand troops.'' Albright also warned Milosevic that ``he
can expect airstrikes'' if his forces continue their violence
against the Kosovo Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   A peace plan proposal by the United States, Europe and Russia
would give the ethnic Albanians autonomy, but not independence, for
three to five years. Ethnic Albanians make up 90 percent of
Kosovo's population, but the region also contains many of the
Serbian religious landmarks that make it unlikely the province
would be surrendered peacefully.
</P>
<P>
   The rebellion there marks the continuation of factional fighting
that has been under way since Communism fell in Yugoslavia. Violent
ethnic slaughters marked the independence of Bosnia as ethnic
Serbs, supported by Milosovic, warred with Muslims and Croats in
that region through much of this decade. Unlike Bosnia, Kosovo
remained a part of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton called the fighting in Kosovo the ``biggest remaining
danger'' to peace and stability in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Balkans are an explosive area. They touch on difficult
areas. And unless we can contain, and ultimately defuse, the ethnic
hatreds in that region, they could embroil us, ultimately, in a
much larger conflict with much more human loss,'' Clinton told an
audience at a downtown hotel here.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he feared if the factional fighting continued, he
could draw in neighboring nations such as Albania and Macedonia
and, potentially, NATO's fractious allies, Greece and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, if this conflict continues we'll see another
massive humanitarian crisis; there will be more atrocities, more
refugees crossing borders, more people crying out for justice and
more people seeking revenge,'' Clinton told an audience on hand for
the Malcolm Baldrige Quality Awards ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton cited the United States' military role in Bosnia as an
example of how the nation can help maintain peace in Eastern
Europe. Three years ago, the United States sent 28,000 troops into
Bosnia to help maintain the Dayton Peace Accord.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton initially said the U.S. troops, part of larger NATO
mission, would be withdrawn after one year. However, 7,000 troops
remain there now indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the peace process has taken hold,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also sent a message to the Serbs and the ethnic
Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the Kosovar Albanians, I'd like to say that this is a
chance not just to stop your people from getting killed but to take
control of your destiny, where your rights, your faith and your
culture are respected, and you have the autonomy you have been
promised by law,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the Serbs, this is a chance to prove Kosovo can remain
part of your country while regaining its autonomy and peace. For
the people of both communities, this is a chance to stop wasting
your energies and your lives on a useless war and to start
conserving them for building a more open and prosperous future for
your children,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
