<SLUG> BC-PATAKI-TOUR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOV. PATAKI STARTS NATIONAL TOUR TO TEST PRESIDENTIAL PROSPECTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LARA JAKES and JOHN CAHER +
 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ New York Gov. George Pataki embarks Friday on the
first of several cross-country political trips, raising his
national visibility and possibly testing the waters for a
presidential run.
</P>
<P>
   He travels first to Chicago and, later this month, will visit
Miami and Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   While Pataki has not yet said he will run for national office,
he has also not discouraged speculation that he wants to be
considered as a presidential or vice presidential contender for
2000.
</P>
<P>
   Already, other GOP hopefuls _ including Arizona Sen. John McCain
and former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander _ are flocking to New
Hampshire to prepare for primaries there early next year. For now,
Pataki will forego the snow-shoveling photo-ops in New Hampshire,
while heading to more seasonally moderate climates in the South and
the Midwest to warm up to some of the nation's most powerful
grass-roots leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm going to get a sense of how he's going to play out here
in the Midwest, there isn't any better place to try it,'' said
Hillard Selck, the national Republican committeeman from Missouri,
who asked Pataki to speak at his state's annual Lincoln Day dinner
on Feb. 20.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be willing to tell our neighboring states if he sold
like hotcakes in Missouri,'' Selck said Thursday. ``Then the guys
around us would know about it: Kansas, Iowa, Oklahoma, Arkansas.
That's such a nice little swatch of states out here to have.''
</P>
<P>
   Pataki, who recently formed two national political action
committees to finance his out-of-state travel and to aid other
Republicans, appeared Thursday on NBC-TV's ``Today'' show and
Pataki criticized his party's Washington leadership for dwelling on
the Monica Lewinsky scandal and giving short shrift to local
interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``You almost have two different Republican parties,'' Pataki
said. ``You have the Washington party and then you have the
states.''
</P>
<P>
   Pataki said the GOP, to prevail in 2000, must develop a positive
message spotlighting lower taxes and less government.
</P>
<P>
   One of his themes is that Republican governors should get more
respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1996, Republican governors really took a back seat,''
Pataki said. ``It was largely a Washington national convention and
ticket. We shouldn't do that for 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   His trip to Chicago, where the governor will venture to the
bedrock of conservative, free-market economics _ the University of
Chicago _ marks Pataki's first major out-of-state appearance since
forming the national PACs. The speech is sponsored by the
conservative Federalist Society.
</P>
<P>
   A poll released Thursday by Quinnipiac College shows that while
Pataki remains highly popular in New York, he has almost no support
as a presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``New Yorkers like their governor _ in Albany,'' said Maurice
``Mickey'' Carroll, director of the Quinnipiac College Polling
Institute. ``He doesn't add much to a national ticket.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor is not being paid for any of the upcoming speeches
in Chicago, Missouri or Florida, according to spokesman Michael
McKeon. But the appearances may be worth their weight in gold. At
least, that's what Pataki's political advisers are hoping.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suppose I was looking for the proverbial New York City
slicker, but I found that he speaks a language that the people of
Missouri would find very acceptable,'' said Selck, who heard Pataki
speak recently in Manhattan. He invited the governor to the Show-Me
State shortly thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found myself immensely impressed with Gov. Pataki _ I think
he does a whale of a job.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
