<SLUG> BC-AMA-EDITOR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARVARD CLASS HAS SESSION WITH FIRED JAMA EDITOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY TYE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ The catalog promised that the course would
zero in on ``timely health policy controversies,'' but the 17 or so
Harvard students who had signed up could not have anticipated just
how timely it would be. Or how they'd have a front-row seat in the
hottest policy/personality controversy in the world of medicine.
</P>
<P>
   That's because one of the two professors is Dr. George D.
Lundberg who, just before he began his teaching duties this week at
Harvard's School of Public Health, was fired as the top-ranking
editor at the Journal of the American Medical Association. His
termination set off a firestorm of protest from doctors and medical
editors from Sweden to Britain and Australia to North America.
</P>
<P>
   All of which, say his students, makes for a compelling backdrop
to a course on the inner workings of medical and scientific
journals.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been stressing a lot the separation between owners and
editors, how important that is if you want to maintain
credibility,'' Hannah Cooper, a doctoral student, said after
Thursday's class. ``We have a real-life example of what happens
when owners do insert themselves and control the editorial life of
a journal. Having that played out in front of us really is
instructive.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Nawal Nour, an obstetrician who's working on her master's in
public health, agreed: `I had planned to take this class anyway
because I'm very interested in publishing, but this adds another
dimension about the political aspects of publishing.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get the sense he'd been warned that there were
controversial issues out there, and not to touch them, but he was
willing to take the risk. . . . He was willing to sacrifice his
job.''
</P>
<P>
   Sex and presidential politics were the immediate issues that
last month cost Lundberg his post as editor of the Journal of the
American Medical Association. He published a story on college
students's attitudes on sex that seemed to support President
Clinton's controversial contention that oral-genital contact alone
does not constitute ``having sex.'' The AMA bosses, who already
were losing patience with their blunt-spoken editor, said the sex
story ``inappropriately and inexcusably'' inserted JAMA into the
impeachment debate.
</P>
<P>
   After weeks of angry exchanges between the AMA and Lundberg's
defenders, the AMA and Lundberg on Wednesday announced a cease-fire
and what apparently was a generous financial settlement. Thursday
Lundberg, who was wearing a white sling to protect a fractured
elbow, declined to say anything about the settlement or the AMA,
although he and his lawyer have made clear that the editor will
hold his tongue only through the end of next week, and only for
legal reasons.
</P>
<P>
   His students, however, say he hasn't hesitated to air his views
in class. ``A lot of times you hear his quotes in the press,'' said
Nour, ``but you lose the essence of his humanness. We have seen
that this is a person who has values and integrity.''
</P>
<P>
   In Tuesday's class, she added, Lundberg spent 15 minutes
discussing issues of editorial freedom and integrity, which he says
are at the center of his firing by the AMA. The association insists
the firing had more to do with Lundberg's overstepped reasonable
bounds of behavior, and it has vowed to maintain JAMA's
independence as it conducts an international search for Lundberg's
successor.
</P>
<P>
   But the ongoing JAMA controversy isn't of interest to everyone
in the Harvard class, which is titled ``How to Write, Peer Review
and Publish Articles on Medicine and Health Policy,'' and is
co-taught by health policy expert Karen Donelan. ``I wasn't even
aware of the controversy until two days ago,'' said Robert Krasner,
a professor of microbiology at Providence College who is studying
at Harvard during his sabbatical.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's irrelevant to whatever this course is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-04-99 1942EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
