<DOCNO> NYT19990204.0370 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2286 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DIABETES-GENE-BOS &LR;      02-04 0613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIABETES-GENE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOUSE GENE GIVES RESEARCHERS DIABETES CLUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Researchers say they have found a single cellular
glitch that causes adult onset diabetes, the most common form of
the metabolic disease that affects nearly 16 million Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Using mice with a knocked-out gene that triggered a condition
resembling human diabetes, the Joslin Diabetes Center researchers
say they have homed in on the underlying reason why diabetics'
pancreatic cells do not secrete enough insulin and, at the same
time, why the body's organs lose the ability to respond to insulin.
</P>
<P>
   Finding this root cause of the disease could lead to improved
treatments, said Dr. Ronald Kahn, researcher, director of the
Joslin center, and an author of the paper in the current issue of
the journal Cell.
</P>
<P>
   ``The importance of this in terms of treatment is that it opens
up a whole new avenue of possibilities of what to do'' to restore a
normal insulin balance in adult-onset diabetics, said Kahn in an
interview. One new aim, he said, would be to devise drugs that
restore cells' sensitivity to insulin, the hormone that regulates
the level of sugar in the blood.
</P>
<P>
   In general, diabetes results from too little insulin, which
enables the body to metabolize sugar and convert it to energy. With
too little insulin, sugar backs up into the bloodstream and can
damage vital organs like the heart, kidney and eyes.
</P>
<P>
   In Type I (juvenile) diabetes, the insulin-producing beta cells
of the pancreas simply stop producing insulin, and patients have to
take insulin in daily injections.
</P>
<P>
   In Type II (adult onset) diabetes, which accounts for 90 to 95
percent of all cases of diabetes, the problem is not so simple. On
one hand, tissues like the liver, fat and muscle become
``insulin-resistant'' _ the hormone doesn't work on them to
metabolize sugar properly. In addition, the beta cells cut back on
secretion of insulin. Until now, researchers thought these were two
separate abnormalities.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has always been the question of which came first, the
chicken or the egg,'' commented Joan Harmon, a senior advisor for
diabetes at the National Institute of Diabetes and Digestive and
Kidney Diseases. ``Was there a basic defect in the beta cell that
causes lack of insulin secretion, or is the real problem the
development of insulin resistance'' in body organs?
</P>
<P>
   The Joslin researchers' study suggests that both are caused by
the same problem: the beta cell itself becomes resistant to insulin
(produced by it or by other beta cells) and can't respond to sugar
in the blood, and at the same time it cuts back on producing
insulin. The development of insulin resistance in the beta cells is
apparently analagous to the development of such resistance in
distant tissues and organs, the researchers say.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really says that this insulin-sensing problem in the beta
cell could be the major cause of Type II diabetes,'' said Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   Harmon at the NIDDKD said the paper ``will cause a lot of
discussion'' and provides ``interesting new directions for
treatment'' efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we need to look for now is an oral agent to make the beta
cell more sensitive to insulin,'' said Kahn. ``Then we could
reverse one of the most important defects'' causing diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers made their discovery by breeding mice that
lacked a key gene in the insulin-sensing system of the pancreatic
beta cell. Without it, the cells failed to produce enough insulin
and also became insensitive to insulin, and the animals developed
symptoms similar to human diabetes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
