<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 19:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2289 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HONGKONG-HARVARD-BOS &LR;      02-04 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONGKONG-HARVARD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARVARD CLUB TO TAKE LEGAL ACTION IN ALLEGED THEFT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ The Harvard Alumni Club of Hong Kong voted Thursday
to pursue legal action against its former president, whom club
members accuse of stealing $504,000 from club funds and donations.
</P>
<P>
   Between November 1996 and October 1997, Stephen Wai-wan Chik
allegedly transferred into his personal accounts a donation meant
for the university as well as club monies as payment for
``professional and secretarial services,'' according to financial
documents reviewed by club auditors and attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   Chik, a 1986 graduate, has returned 80 percent of the funds. But
members present _ 38 out of a membership of 300 _ voted
overwhelmingly to sue him for the remainder, and to turn
information over to police for a possible criminal investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The move to hold him accountable will send waves through the
city's elite, since the dynamic young financier was once a darling
of senior alumni in finance and government.
</P>
<P>
   But in a sense, the vote marks a new beginning for the club, a
chance to redeem the group's name and recover from accusations that
a tight circle of powerful alumni stalled the investigation to
protect Chik and Harvard's name.
</P>
<P>
   Although nearly all present voted to take legal action, several
people had reservations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's very practical, because I don't think
there's a good chance of recovering money. . . . Any legal action
takes money and we open ourselves to the possibility that if we
lose, we pay his costs,'' said Reuben Mondejar, who holds a 1988
master's degree in international studies.
</P>
<P>
   The club's executive committee set aside $26,000 last November
for legal fees, and a large chunk has already been spent consulting
lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, said Mondejar, who served as vice president under
Chik, ``I think the members have spoken and I think it's a good
thing. There were views expressed before . . . that the executive
committee was taking decisions without consulting members, so this
was a chance to consult them. It can be seen as a cleansing of the
club.''
</P>
<P>
   Repeated efforts to reach Chik for comment were unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   Amy Weaver, a 1995 Harvard Law School graduate, said: ``It's a
hard call any time you have to decide on litigation. But I think
there are reasons beyond money. There are moral reasons, and I
think people took those into account.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Weldon, a 1959 Harvard graduate who works as a consultant,
said he ``absolutely'' agrees with the vote, because it underlines
respect for law. ``Here we are in Hong Kong worrying about whether
China will allow Hong Kong to exist with the rule of law, and I
don't think we've been following it ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Weldon said that the club and its foundation did not undergo
annual audits, as required by club bylaws and Hong Kong law.
</P>
<P>
   Sabrina Fang, a 1988 graduate and a lawyer, said another member
recounted a story at the meeting of a business associate who called
looking for a reference check on Chik, to whom he had already lent
$2 million. When the businessman learned that the club believed
Chik had taken club funds, he questioned why the club had not
publicized it to warn others.
</P>
<P>
   ``Citizens have an obligation to report crimes _ it seems so
obvious,'' said Fang, who joined other members at the fashionable
China Club Thursday to review documents and get briefed by a lawyer
before voting.
</P>
<P>
   Members voted not to pursue action against former treasurer Yun
Ed Wong, holder of a 1989 Harvard PhD in geophysics, who signed
blank transfer notes that Chik allegedly used to siphon club funds.
Wong, who was an employee of Chik's at the time, gave a speech at
the meeting saying he was ``a victim'' like everyone else and that
he ``trusted (Chik) as a friend and as a fellow Harvard man.''
</P>
<P>
   Chik, who served as president for four years, did not attend the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Wong said he was relieved the club was not
holding him responsible, and said he would cooperate with police.
Wong defended himself against accusations by some members that he
put his friendship and trust of a fellow alumnus over his fiduciary
responsiblity to the rest of the club.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even before me, all the bank statements went straight to the
president,'' Wong said. ``I suppose I could have started a new
trend, but I didn't.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
