<SLUG> BC-PATRIOTS-MOVE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS SEEK ASSURANCES ON NEW STADIUM SITE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and s coding)   For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Connecticut Governor John G. Rowland and New England
Patriots owner Robert Kraft have scheduled a news conference for
Friday in Hartford, but it is unclear if a development agreement
that will legally seal the team's move there will be ready to sign.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for the Patriots were pressing for assurances that the
site of a proposed new stadium in downtown Hartford will be cleared
in time for the team to play its first game by the fall of 2002.
But those guarantees were still being hammered out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pace of the discussions have been relentless,'' said team
vice president Andy Wasynczuk. ``We've been working `round the
clock, the attorneys have been working 22-hour days to complete the
documentation and we're moving ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Rowland moved swiftly this week to allay growing fears among
team officials that a breakdown in negotiations to move a steam
plant on the proposed stadium site could endanger the construction
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Just how the governor's office would compensate or assure the
Patriots that the site will be clear by the summer of 2000, so that
construction on the $350 million project can begin, remained
unclear.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue is if we frame the agreement, we've got to be
comfortable,'' Wasynczuk said. ``It's implicit we're moving forward
with something we're comfortable signing.''
</P>
<P>
   The press conference is scheduled for 2 p.m. in the Old
Judiciary Room of the state Capitol, the same place where Rowland
and Kraft signed a Memorandum of Understanding Nov. 19 to move the
team from Foxborough to a site along the Connecticut River.
</P>
<P>
   But a steam plant that provides service to much of downtown
occupies that location and must be moved in order for the stadium
-- and the larger $1 billion redevelopment project known as
Adriaen's Landing -- to be built.
</P>
<P>
   Although the state has not reached an agreement with the steam
plant company, CTG Resources Inc., it appears that the development
agreement will give negotiators more time to find a way to tear
down the facility.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Thursday, consumer activist Ralph Nader stepped up
his campaign to derail the Patriots deal. In a letter sent to the
governor's office, Nader predicted the deal will not go forward and
warned Rowland to include sufficient ``escape clauses'' for state
taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mounting and multiple forces and problems from many
directions that are confronting this deal will result in the
stadium never being built,'' Nader wrote. ``Here's hoping you will
turn your attention to the state's real needs...''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
