<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2294 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROSENTHAL-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      02-04 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENTHAL-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: MIXING AMERICAN SIGNALS  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By A.M. ROSENTHAL    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The timing was magnificent. As Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright was crisscrossing the Middle East to round up support for
the Clinton administration's policy of helping the Iraqi opposition
overthrow Saddam Hussein, the American general commanding U.S.
forces in the Mideast was once again proclaiming that the idea
stinks.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Magnificent, that is, for Saddam. In one winter, first he
destroys the U.N. arms inspection commission. Then he surges ahead
in the Mideast political war eight years after he lost the military
war to U.S.-led forces. And now, unexpected dessert, along comes
the United States to prove it did not have either a policy to deal
with his resurgence or a president who could command a commander.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It must be delectable humor for Saddam to listen to Gen. Anthony
Zinni, the Marine Corps commander, the ranking U.S. general in the
Mideast, repeatedly put down the Clinton administration by saying
that a ``weak, chaotic and fragmented'' Iraq is more dangerous than
a contained Iraq, and totally dismiss any viable Iraqi opposition.
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That leaves Saddam to wonder which policy, if any, Washington
would use to try to deal with Iraq, and which American, if any, is
in charge.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The last time Saddam misunderstood what a U.S. message was
trying to tell him was about invading Kuwait. He guessed wrong,
invaded and created a war that still bedevils and threatens the
United States, Israel and other targets for the mass-death weapons
that are his paramount goal. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Imagine all the mixed signals U.S. officials concede he is
getting now. Imagine the lives Saddam can take if he picks a signal
that convinces him that America's government is so muddled and
divided that he can strike again.
</P>
<P>
   Zinni has said some things that are true _ helping dissidents
would be dangerous and difficult. But he has not come up with a
solution that would be neither. He has said half-truths _ such as
that the opposition is not viable. That is true now, because the
United States let Saddam slaughter the opposition and the
administration is still talking, not giving, real help to rebuild
opposition forces. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Zinni claim that a weak, fragmented Iraq, presumably after
rebellion, is more dangerous in the long run than a contained
Saddam is now is not information. It is opinion that much of the
administration rejects. But in America, those are judgments to be
made by the civilian powers of government, not the military.
</P>
<P>
   The removal of Saddam might give Iraqi opposition minorities
some of their lands to live in, with a taste of freedom _ but the
horror of it all escapes me.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department is said by a determinedly anonymous
official to disagree with the general, and finds his comments
neither helpful or pleasing.
</P>
<P>
   One way for the administration to deal with his persistent
public denigrating of administration planning, what there is of it,
is to use presidential power _ fire him as quickly as Harry Truman
fired Gen. Douglas MacArthur for cutting across presidential policy
in Korea. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That might convince Saddam, our enemies and our occasional
allies at the U.N. that the U.S. is still brain-alive about the
Iraqi danger and perhaps capable of creating a united policy to
deal with it.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Defense Department minimizes the differences between the
general and the civilian departments, and points out that he is a
highly valuable officer. And Zinni is not the imperious MacArthur.
But it is hard to see how he can lead in the field a policy he has
put down in public. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What about the general's own rights? If the president does not
want to remove him, can the government decently reduce his ability
to speak his mind on policy dangers he may see? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yes. Zinni chose a career that does control that right and often
reduces it _ in public. In private government meetings, civilian,
military or mixed, he has the duty to speak fully. Before
congressional committees, he can request private sessions on
matters he thinks might damage American interests, which some of
his comments do. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If stifling some of his opinions in public damages his own sense
of duty, he has an honorable way out, too little chosen by U.S.
officials. He can resign and speak up. That should satisfy his own
sense of duty _ and not confuse the Iraqis into another disaster
for them and the countries Saddam stalks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
