<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2295 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SIERRALEONE05-COX     02-04 1392
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIERRALEONE05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Experiencing the agony of Sierra Leone
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS, MAP
 &HT;    By Don Melvin
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Milton Boyle just wanted to return home, set up a
commercial fishing business and give something back to the country
of his birth.
</P>
<P>
   Sierra Leone has endured its share of turmoil in recent years,
but Boyle, who lives in Jonesboro, Ga., had read the news and
searched the Internet for information. Things were under control.
Freetown was safe.
</P>
<P>
   So he took his annual Christmas trip back to Sierra Leone,
intending this time to move home for good. His sister, Elizabeth
Toure, followed five days later, bringing her three children _ two
girls and a boy ranging from 11 years old to 15 months.
</P>
<P>
   But on Jan. 6, rebel fighters invaded the capital and all hell
broke loose. Boyle spent four days pinned down in his house. He
barely escaped alive, and the things he saw _ the killings, the
mutilations, the burning buildings _ haunt him even now.
</P>
<P>
   And his sister and her children are stuck in Freetown.
</P>
<P>
   Sierra Leone, on Africa's west coast, is less than half the size
of Georgia and has about 4.7 million people.
</P>
<P>
   It is one of Africa's smallest countries _ with far less area
and far fewer people than Sudan, Nigeria, the Democratic Republic
of Congo, South Africa, Angola, Kenya or Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
   But the humanitarian disaster unfolding in Sierra Leone ranks
among the most severe in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the country's finance minister, James Jonah, accused
the U.N. Security Council of focusing on massacres in Yugoslavia's
Kosovo province while virtually ignoring the brutal killings in
Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
   More than 2,000 people have been killed in a year of fighting
between Albanian separatist guerrillas and Yugoslav forces in
Kosovo. In Sierra Leone, in just the last two months since rebels
renewed their offensive, between 2,000 and 3,000 people have been
killed. Many more have had their hands and feet cut off.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe it is time for the international community and the
Security Council to be more evenhanded in dealing with this
crisis,'' said Jonah. ``You cannot deal with atrocities in Kosovo
and not deal with them in Sierra Leone.''
</P>
<P>
   Jonah is not alone in his assessment. In an essay published last
month in the Washington Post, Reynold Levy, president of the
International Refugee Rescue Committee wrote: ``Today, Sierra Leone
has become the world's largest producer of human misery.''
</P>
<P>
   Levy cited U.N. estimates that 440,000 Sierra Leoneans _ nearly
10 percent of the population _ have fled across the border into
Liberia or Guinea. Rape and kidnapping, he said, have become
commonplace.
</P>
<P>
   Rebels have committed ``barbaric reprisals'' against supporters
of the elected government, Levy wrote: ``The guerrillas have, for
example, burned villagers alive _ not only men, but women and
children. And they've made an example of others by hacking off
their hands or arms, their feet or legs.
</P>
<P>
   ``One such victim, a 6-year-old called Flora, held up her
bandaged arm and asked my colleague, Marie de la Soudiere, `Will my
fingers grow back?'''
</P>
<P>
   Civil war has laid waste to Sierra Leone for eight years.
</P>
<P>
   In May 1997, bands of former Sierra Leonean troops _ backed by
the nearby countries of Liberia and Burkina Faso, according to many
accounts _ seized power from the elected president, Ahmad Tejan
Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
   But nearly a year later, in March 1998, Kabbah was reinstated by
a Nigerian-led military force known as ECOMOG. The rebels fled.
Nigeria kept about 15,000 troops in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
   Against that background, and based on news accounts, Boyle, a
37-year-old businessman who had lived in the Atlanta area for seven
years, decided the time was right to move back to Sierra Leone. His
sister, who had come to the Atlanta area in 1997 to escape the
turmoil and give birth to her third child, would move back, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all went back thinking everything was calm,'' Boyle said in
a recent interview.
</P>
<P>
   Boyle left Atlanta on Dec. 10. His sister, with her three
children _ Melissa, 11, Marissa, 8, and 15-month-old Michelle _
departed five days later.
</P>
<P>
   At first, everything was fine. Boyle stayed in a house in
Freetown that he owns with a cousin. But listening to BBC radio
reports unsettled him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We heard that the rebels were 22 miles away,'' Boyle said.
``So it was very disturbing.''
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 6, the rebels entered Freetown.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys came in and started killing people by the dozens,''
Boyle said.
</P>
<P>
   Cowering in his house, Boyle heard people scream for their
lives. Out the windows, he saw 14-year-olds carrying AK-47 assault
rifles, cans of gasoline and RPGs _ shoulder-fired,
rocket-propelled grenade launchers. He saw buildings set aflame,
and people corralled and used as human shields to prevent the
Nigerian forces from firing.
</P>
<P>
   Boyle could not leave the house _ not to buy food, not to
escape, not even to check on his sister and her children, who were
staying in a house two miles away, and whose phone had been cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was on the floor, primarily, for five days, eating boiled
bananas,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, chaos reigned.
</P>
<P>
   According to Mohammed Luqman, an emergency expert for the
Atlanta-based relief agency CARE, the fighting and the torching of
homes forced 150,000 residents from their neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 9, three reporters were killed. One was abducted from
his home, taken to a rebel base, and shot in the head in front of
his fiancee, according to the New York-based Committee to Protect
Journalists. Another reporter survived after having his eye gouged
out with a machete.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 10, three journalists with Associated Press Television
News were driving through Freetown, escorted by ECOMOG troops when
rebel fighters approached the vehicle and opened fire. Two of the
journalists were hit in the head. One died immediately; the other
was flown to London, where his condition is reported to be
improving.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels' entry into Freetown alarmed Sierra Leoneans living
in the Atlanta area. Feeling that strength lay in unity, three
pro-democracy groups merged into one, Patriots and Friends of
Sierra Leone. One of the group's leaders, Amadu Jabbie of
Jonesboro, estimated that 8,000 Sierra Leoneans live in the Atlanta
area, although the country's honorary consul in Atlanta suggested
that figure was high and an independent estimate has been
impossible to obtain.
</P>
<P>
   In Freetown on Jan. 11, Boyle's cousin, a businessman with
friends among the Nigerian soldiers, managed to get word to the
soldiers that he and Boyle needed help. About 18 soldiers arrived
in a military vehicle and picked up Boyle and his cousin. There was
no way to get to his sister.
</P>
<P>
   On the ride to the barracks, perhaps a mile and a half down
Wilkinson Road, a main thoroughfare through the affluent west side
of Freetown, Boyle saw scores of bodies along the road. Some had
limbs cut off. Others had been decapitated. Vultures feasted on the
dead.
</P>
<P>
   From the barracks, Boyle was helicoptered to Lungi airport
outside the capital, and from there he flew to safety.
</P>
<P>
   The Nigerians _ and President Kabbah _ remain nominally in
control of Freetown. But the capital has been devastated. On
Tuesday, CARE began feeding nearly 7,000 people in a badly damaged
eastern section of the city. Food is scarce, and two taps must
provide water for all of them, said CARE Country Director Nick
Webber.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whole blocks have been totally destroyed, including
stone-structured churches and concrete buildings,'' Webber said.
``The streets are lined with burned vehicles, one after another,
while other houses are intact.''
</P>
<P>
   And this week, hundreds of Sierra Leoneans, fearful that the
Nigerians will pull out and leave them unprotected, have lined up
to get passports or have crowded onto boats and helicopters trying
to find a way out.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, a boat full of refugees fleeing Freetown hit a
rock near the Guinea border and sank, killing 50 people.
</P>
<P>
   Boyle has heard through a relative that his sister and her
children are safe, but he is still trying to get them out. He has
always made an annual Christmas visit to Sierra Leone, but will he
go back?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not any time soon,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
