<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-RATES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EURO WEAKENS AGAINST THE DOLLAR  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ALAN COWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
   LONDON _ Hurt by fears of an economic slowdown across Europe in
the face of expansive growth in the United States, the month-old
European single currency touched a low against the dollar Thursday
as a series of interest-rate decisions reinforced forecasts that
European rates would keep falling.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Resisting political pressures to lower rates, the European
Central Bank, custodian of the monetary policy of the 11 member
nations in the euro zone, left its key interest rate unchanged
Thursday at 3 percent. But there was still widespread expectation
that the rate could be lowered a few times in coming months, said
Michael Saunders, an economist with Salomon Smith Barney. The
anticipation of lower rates was one reason the euro declined
against the dollar in European dealings.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the euro zone, the Bank of England surprised the markets
with a bigger-than-expected cut of half a percentage point in its
key short-term lending rate, bringing it to 5.5 percent, the lowest
in almost five years. Dealers had expected a quarter-point
reduction.
</P>
<P>
   The bank's monetary policy committee, which is trying to keep
British inflation from exceeding 2.5 percent, said the reduction in
the securities repurchase had been dictated by ``the prospects for
international activity and prices, domestic costs and consumer
demand.'' It was the fifth consecutive reduction, reflecting
concerns that Britain's slowing economy could be headed toward
recession.
</P>
<P>
   British rates now have fallen by two percentage points since
October. The country's economic slowdown has been caused in part by
a strong pound, which has diminished exports and reduced consumer
spending.
</P>
<P>
   Denmark, another euro outsider, also reduced its discount and
repurchase rates by a quarter-point Thursday, though for different
reasons.
</P>
<P>
   The Danish currency, the krone, is formally linked to the euro
in an exchange-rate mechanism that is supposed to limit the
currency's fluctuations. The Danish central bank said its rate
reduction, the seventh since October, was made because of the
krone's growing strength against the euro. The move had been
expected.
</P>
<P>
   The European decisions came a day after the Federal Reserve's
policy-making committee decided to leave rates in the United States
unchanged after data last week showing the strongest American
economic growth in two years. By contrast, the European Commission
said last month that its earlier forecast of 2.4 percent growth in
continental Europe this year would have to be trimmed back. The
commission, the day-to-day executive arm of the European Union, has
not yet published a new forecast.
</P>
<P>
   The interest-rate decisions illuminated not just the disparities
between American and European growth, but also the distinctions
between Britain and Continental Europe that, British officials
maintain, preclude participation in the euro currency system for
the time being.
</P>
<P>
   While the euro zone's benchmark interest rate remained at 3
percent, British rates are still the highest among the Group of
Seven leading industrial nations. At its debut on financial markets
Jan. 4, the euro traded above $1.18, but Thursday it was driven
down in European markets to lows near $1.125 _ a fall around 5
percent from the euphoria of its first days, when investors seeking
to build up euro positions sold dollars to buy the new currency. In
New York later, the euro improved somewhat, settling at $1.1344.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sentiment on the euro has turned very gloomy,'' said Kit
Juckes of NatWest Global Financial Markets.
</P>
</TEXT>
