<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2297 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-JAZZ-MALONE-HNS &LR;      02-04 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-JAZZ-MALONE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
KARL Malone has had a change of heart.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Make that another change of heart. Come to think of it, Malone
changes his mind more than wrestling partner Dennis Rodman changes
his hair color.
</P>
<P>
   But Malone swears he is serious this time.
</P>
<P>
   Two months ago he vowed to never again play for the Utah Jazz,
saying he didn't like the way he was treated by the organization.
But after a tearful press conference where he apologized to the
fans and to owner Larry Miller, Malone is back, and claims that he
has his eyes fixed on winning the NBA championship that has escaped
his grasp the past two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always wanted to win a championship, and the Utah Jazz
have a great shot this year,'' he said. ``I have to be a part of
that.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a time this summer when a lot of people were doubting
that. Malone, once one of the last of the NBA's rugged
individualists, started acting well, for lack of a better word,
wacky.
</P>
<P>
   His act became disturbingly like that of Dennis Rodman, long his
nemesis on the court. Malone switched agents, hiring Dwight Manley,
the same guy who was representing Rodman at the time, and started a
wrestling career, appearing in pay-per-view World Championship
Wrestling events.
</P>
<P>
   But Malone says all that is in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will I ever wrestle again? Probably not,'' he said. ``That's
something that I just wanted to do, and I did it. I don't have any
regrets, but now it's time to move on.''
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the Jazz must be thankful that Malone came to his
senses. While Malone was wrestling with both Rodman and the Utah
fans, the rest of the Jazz players were going through their paces
every day of the lockout in team workouts. While the Indiana Pacers
have received a lot of attention for their team workouts, the Jazz
_ sans Malone _ did pretty much the same thing, doing full-scale
team workouts to keep sharp and attempt to get a head start on the
rest of the West.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a lot of guys here for a lot of days, but we've also
had a mixture of other guys from other teams coming and playing,''
said guard John Stockton. ``It made for good basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we have a great jump on everyone else, but
hopefully everyone is in condition because of this.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was an advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys who have been playing together, obviously we know one
another, we know the offense, we know what (coach) Jerry (Sloan)
expects,'' said Greg Foster, who broke a bone in his foot and will
miss three weeks. ``It will be interesting to see just how long (it
takes to start playing well together). I don't think it will take
long.''
</P>
<P>
   It had better not.
</P>
<P>
   While the Jazz should expect to roll from the start because they
are a veteran team with their nucleus intact, they know most of
their toughest competitors in the Western Conference have gotten
much stronger. The Rockets got Scottie Pippen to go with Hakeem
Olajuwon, and the Spurs addressed their needs by getting Steve
Kerr's outside shooting and Mario Elie to address their toughness.
And the Lakers are still looking to make moves.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're very good players, but we still have to see how they
blend in with those particular teams,'' said Utah guard Howard
Eisley. ``But right now we really can't worry about other teams. We
have to make sure we're together with what we want to do and make
sure we're hitting on all cylinders when it's time to go.''
</P>
<P>
   While Malone missed out on the pickup games (all that wrestling
doesn't leave much time for basketball), he says it's time to get
back to work. A rough summer _ trade demands, news that he had
teen-aged twins back in Louisiana that he had never acknowledged,
etc. _ had Malone reflecting on just how good things are in his
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all the stuff that's gone on this summer, I've had to
grow up quick,'' the 35-year-old Malone said. ``Dealing with all
this negative stuff makes you think about things in a different
way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to be more careful with what I do and say, I realize
that. Some things can be distracting, and I got a lot of that out
of the way. I'm ready to just play basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   Sloan knows that Malone will be there when the ball is tossed up
today.
</P>
<P>
   ``Karl's always ready to play. That's never in doubt with him,''
Sloan said. ``He did what he had to do this summer, but he made
sure he was ready to compete when it was time to get back on the
court.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-04-99 1955EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
