<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990204.0379 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2300 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBA-PREVIEW-HNS &LR;      02-04 1042
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-PREVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
IF you're just tuning in for the NBA season, you haven't missed a
thing.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But if you blink from here on out, you might miss plenty.
</P>
<P>
   February usually represents the dog days in the NBA _ basketball
on Prozac. Players, tired of the grind, often simply go through the
motions, not yet able to smell the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   But this season will be more like the NBA on caffeine.
</P>
<P>
   The new season, one full of changes, begins Friday, more than
three months late. And the compressed post-lockout 50-game schedule
will look more like a barnstorming tour, with teams playing three
straight nights on some occasions. Players will be getting to know
teammates on the fly, leading to some uh, interesting games.
</P>
<P>
   But the season that almost wasn't will wind up being one for the
books, one full of changes. There will be no All-Star Game, and, in
part to make up for just that kind of thing, teams are playing for
free in the preseason and doing marathon autograph sessions
afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were sensitive to closing up the wide gap between players
and fans,'' said NBA commissioner David Stern. ``The (players')
union and the league felt it was time for the players to stress
responsibility and commitment to their teams and fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Watching the players the past few weeks has been as
encouraging as watching the fans' reaction to the open scrimmages.
I suppose the fair question to ask us is, `What took you so long?'
Well, we knew this issue was coming and we've tried to take care of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest change is obvious _ the Bulls aren't the favorite to
win the NBA championship. Michael Jordan has retired, Scottie
Pippen is in Houston, Dennis Rodman is well, who cares? And Phil
Jackson is probably in a tepee somewhere, writing haiku poetry and
contemplating life without the aforementioned trio.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, things are going to be different this season.
</P>
<P>
   How different? Try this _ with such a short season, every game
will mean something.
</P>
<P>
   ``With 50 games, it's kind of like college,'' said Detroit's
Grant Hill. ``If the No. 1 team loses a game, it will be like they
slipped in the standings. You sure don't want to start out much
below .500. If you fall far off, you'll have a hard time catching
up.''
</P>
<P>
   And forget about asterisks and all that when it comes to this
year's champion. Even though Jordan and the Bulls are history and
the season has been chopped almost in half, life in the NBA goes
on. ``I think 50 is the fewest number to make it credible,'' said
the Rockets' Charles Barkley. ``I think this is probably going to
be the most exciting year in basketball. There's not a dominant,
dominant team, but I think there's about 10 teams that are very
good. I think this is going to be the most exciting year.''
</P>
<P>
   Talk about changes _ for once, people around the league are
agreeing with Barkley.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to put on a good show from the start, I think,''
said Lakers coach Del Harris. ``Why? Because each game's going to
be very important in a compacted season.''
</P>
<P>
   Everything is new this year, including most of the rosters.
Indeed, the hardest part may be simply figuring out who's playing
where.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen is in Houston, Latrell Sprewell is in New York, Antonio
McDyess is in Denver, Tom Gugliotta in Phoenix and John Starks in
Golden State. Coaches weren't exempt from the wanderlust, either.
Jackson hasn't resurfaced anywhere; George Karl, a fixture in
Seattle, hit the road for Milwaukee; while Paul Westphal slides
into the Sonics' hot seat. And Tim Floyd gets the thankless job of
trying to rebuild the Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   All the movement has made most fans forget the lockout and start
talking basketball again. The NBA has stoked the fires by making
the schedule almost exclusively in-conference, making sure
rivalries were emphasized.
</P>
<P>
   Anything to win back the fans, many of whom were turned off by
the almost-seven-month lockout. And the league doesn't have Jordan
around to pack the arenas anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can see why people would be excited about it, but I wish he
was still playing,'' said Knicks' coach Jeff Van Gundy of Jordan,
trying his best to sound convincing. ``He was everything that was
right about the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's obviously great for the fans, but also for the other
players because he's such a benchmark as far as work, dedication
and commitment to winning, and I wonder where that's going to come
from now.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it will come from the rookies.
</P>
<P>
   While this year's haul isn't exactly being hyped as one for the
ages, it does include some intriguing prospects.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Olowokandi, the No. 1 pick by the Clippers, went over to
play in Italy, but couldn't leave fast enough when he found out how
bad things are overseas. Wait until he sees what life is like as a
Clipper. The guy many view as the best rookie in the bunch lasted
all the way until the 10th pick, where Boston nabbed Paul Pierce
out of Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   It should be the veteran teams that are rewarded this year.
Utah, which features veterans like Karl Malone, John Stockton and
Jeff Hornacek, is looked upon by many as the favorite in the West,
especially after sweeping the Lakers in last year's Western
Conference finals to advance to the NBA Finals for the second
straight year.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of things that went wrong. That's why we got
swept,'' said the Lakers' Kobe Bryant, who recently signed a
six-year, $70 million contract extension. ``Obviously, Utah's the
team to beat.''
</P>
<P>
   Indiana leads the pack in the Eastern Conference, especially
with Chicago going the way of the Florida Marlins. The Bulls? After
winning six championships this decade, they could very easily wind
up being the worst team in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody is going to feel sorry for the Bulls,'' Detroit coach
Alvin Gentry said. ``And Tim Floyd is a great friend of mine. What
happened in Chicago is no different than what happened here in the
years after 1989 and 1990. The only difference is that, for them,
it happened in two days. Here, it happened over a matter of
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, change is a constant in professional sports. It's just all
happening at once this season in the NBA.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-04-99 1957EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
