u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Y2K-AIR-TRAVEL-BOS &LR;      02-04 0567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-AIR-TRAVEL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL AGENCIES PASS A `MILLENNIUM BUG' TEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Travel agents sighed with relief Thursday as their
computerized-reservation systems passed a key test of processing
reservations for travel in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The country's biggest travel booking systems are programmed to
issue tickets up to 331 days in advance _ meaning that Thursday was
the first time most air travelers could buy tickets to fly on Jan.
1, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The occasion was fraught with anxiety that the software-coding
problem known as the Y2K bug might crash some systems. Like
companies in other industries, ticket-bookers such as Sabre Group,
Worldspan LP or Galileo International Inc. have far to go before
they can assure all of their computerized networks will operate
smoothly 11 months from now.
</P>
<P>
   The ticketing networks were programmed to use just the last two
digits of each year to keep track of the date. Such programs might
be confused by the `00' of next year, leading to worries the
booking systems might malfunction or shut down as early as Thursday
when asked to issue tickets in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   That could have been hugely expensive. American travelers bought
roughly 182 million air tickets last year, according to Airlines
Reporting Corp. of Arlington, Va. The systems also handle
reservations for cruise lines, hotels and car-rental companies.
</P>
<P>
   But executives at major reservation systems said they processed
tens of thousands of orders without incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were looking at it as milestone, and it went very well,''
said Jennifer Hudson, spokeswoman for Dallas-based Sabre Group.
Most of the system is owned by the parent of American Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   The earliest order, Hudson said, came from a travel agent in
London seeking a return flight for a businessman planning to return
from Los Angeles to Heathrow Airport in London. It was issued as
normal. ``We've tested and re-tested for this date for months
now...but you never really know what's going to happen,'' Hudson
said.
</P>
<P>
   Total sales figures weren't available for Thursday, she said,
but were expected to approximate last year's. On Feb. 4, 1998, the
Sabre system booked about 10,000 reservations for travel on Jan. 1,
1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're relieved,'' said Ronnie Hauptman, spokeswoman for
Galileo International Inc. in Rosemont, Ill. The company plans to
spend $25 million fixing its system in a project that won't be
complete until June. But Thursday came as a key test of its
mainframe computers, she said, and it passed without incident.
</P>
<P>
   That reassured travel agents, many of whom have already accepted
deposits from consumers signing up for cruises or ski vacations
over next New Year's weekend. ``It could have been a nightmare if
people weren't able to get flights,'' said James Ashurst, a
spokesman for the American Soceity of Travel Agents in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   At Beacon Hill Travel in Boston president Dana Vannasse said he
was heartened the terminals he leases from Sabre worked as
designed. No customers made reservations to fly out Thursday, he
said, but eight clients had already booked trips with Jan. 1 return
dates.
</P>
<P>
   He obtained tickets for them without difficulty. ``Another lady
wants to come back the third and we can't do that for her yet. But
I'm not worried anymore,'' Vannasse said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-04-99 1957EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990204.0381 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2302 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-ROCKETS-PIPPEN-HN     02-04 1976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-PIPPEN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
SCOTTIE Pippen did not just recently become a celebrity. Meals have
been interrupted for years. Crowds have gathered. Traffic has
stopped so drivers could leap out to tell him, ``You're Scottie
Pippen!'' as if he would be as shocked by that revelation as they
are.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now, he laughs. A van full of teen-agers stopped the other day
so the passengers could run at his car for a closer look. A woman
picked him out of a crowd to hand only him a religious pamphlet
with the reminder, ``He is the most important thing.'' Pippen
smiled and said, ``I guess she thinks He's only important to me.''
</P>
<P>
   People are always waving and smiling. He is treated not so much
as the Rockets' savior but as a child adopted to a loving family,
as appreciated as a rock star taking a stage. And Pippen shakes his
head and marvels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy,'' he said, as if that, despite all he has received
and earned over the years, was all he wanted. ``I've been welcomed
here very warmly. People in the organization have treated me very
warmly, and that's more than I can say about the years that I spent
in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels much better here. I'm not saying that I'm the man
here or that I get treated better here, but it's that people are
willing to bend over backward to make sure I'm comfortable and that
this environment is going to be here for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   This is, he always knew, how it should have been. Six
championships would have seemingly made him bulletproof in Chicago,
a ``made man.'' They didn't.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't treated as the Sundance Kid to Michael Jordan's Butch
Cassidy. He was Salieri to Mozart, McMahon to Carson.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen knew better. Basketball knew better. But somehow, the
city that should have known best of all, even the suits who ran the
Bulls, missed the point or were too caught up in worshipping Jordan
to appreciate his partner.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan tried to share at least part of that spotlight, and the
gesture helped. Pippen was always appreciated by teammates who
could relate better to him than to Jordan while still marveling at
Pippen's other-worldly talents. Fans did scream his name before he
came to Houston. They roared each spring in Grant Park when he was
introduced, and Pippen could not begrudge them if they reserved
their greatest admiration for His Airness.
</P>
<P>
   But when they honk horns or scream his name now, Pippen feels
appreciated in a way he couldn't before. Suddenly, there is enough
love to go around. Fans can celebrate him without fear they are
slighting someone else.
</P>
<P>
   And freed from the comparison he couldn't win, and an
organization that stubbornly refused to embrace him, Pippen has
instantly considered himself home in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been here only two weeks, and he's spoken more to the
organization than he had in Chicago in 11 years,'' said Pippen's
wife, Larsa. ``It means a lot. He would play hard no matter what.
They won championships even though he wasn't happy. But it's easier
to go to work when you're happy playing for a team. You want the
team to win. You want to win for the team, to give that back. He's
got great teammates. He's happy to be with Hakeem (Olajuwon) and
Charles (Barkley).
</P>
<P>
   ``The organization is giving him the attention he needs. The
feeling is awesome. People appreciate him. He's finally happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Happiness, however, does not mean a free ride. Pippen was not
seeking an escape from pressure or expectations. He couldn't have
made his point if his challenge had been placed within easy reach.
</P>
<P>
   From the day his trade to the Rockets finally received league
approval, Pippen was charged with bringing a championship _
multiple championships _ back to Houston. He won six with the
Bulls, two with the Dream Team in the Olympics. And when the Bulls
didn't win titles, the Rockets did.
</P>
<P>
   His addition, melded with the improved health of Olajuwon and
Barkley and promising signs from other newcomers, makes the Rockets
clear contenders again. But in a Western Conference crowded with
worthy championship aspirants, they are far from a sure thing.
</P>
<P>
   If Pippen was driven to prove he could win without Jordan, he
gave himself a chance but with an unforgiving grading scale. And if
some have considered his legacy tarnished by the Bulls' failure to
win a championship during Jordan's basketball sabbatical, they will
likely be no more understanding now.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing that, and not disinterested in shaping his legacy,
Pippen believes another title could be within reach.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not being predicted to get out of the West, but I still
see teams realizing that we're a very talented team,'' he said.
``This is a team that right now, once the Chicago Bulls stepped
down, this is the next team with the most experience of being able
to go to the NBA Finals (and win). We have experience on this team,
and we think we have the personnel that can get us there.
</P>
<P>
   ``You go in with a positive attitude. You have to think that
realistically this is a team that will be in the Finals. That's
just how I feel. When I came here, and even before I came here, I
felt like this team had an opportunity to be in the Finals. I think
that with myself added to their roster, it just makes them a little
bit better of a contender.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets expect their newest star to touch everything they
do. The offense will still most often orbit the inside strengths of
Olajuwon and Barkley. But Pippen will work as a point forward,
initiating the work of the Rockets' players in the post while
setting up their collection of shooters outside. And while
directing much of an offense he has never run before, he will have
to provide his usual scoring, rebounding and defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really, there's nothing he can't do on a basketball court,''
coach Rudy Tomjanovich said. ``He's going to help us offensively by
being a player that can shoot outside, take it inside, slash to the
basket, help on the offensive boards. His ball-handling takes
pressure off of our guards. It also gives us a lot more options on
offense. He's a great passer, a good open-court player.
</P>
<P>
   ``On defense, he's one of the most talented players. You can
match him up with almost anybody. I've seen him on point guards.
I've seen him on big people. In the Finals, they put him on the
center. There's nothing the guy can't do on the basketball court.''
</P>
<P>
   But Pippen's ability to affect his teammates' play, to make them
better, might be the most difficult and crucial of his charges.
</P>
<P>
   The fit seems to be there. He will be surrounded by shooters who
can take advantage of opportunities he creates. But finding his
niche between the half-court prowess of Olajuwon and Barkley and
the Rockets' desire to have Pippen make them run, all while
operating a system very different from Chicago's triangle, will
make for a subtle balance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anything is difficult,'' Pippen said. ``It's
just a matter of me learning it. It's going to take some time for
me to be able to carry it over into a game situation. But that's
what practice is about, to try and drill you enough so when you're
in a game situation, you can do things quite naturally and pretty
much be able to read situations out on the court.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be playing that position. That was one of those things I
wanted to know about before I came into this situation, because
that's the position I've been very comfortable playing _
controlling the offense and controlling the tempo of the game. I
feel very comfortable on the floor, so I didn't want to lose that
aspect of my game.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's going to happen, it's going happen naturally,'' Pippen
said. ``It's nothing where I have to go out and try to take over or
do anything. I realize that this is a team that is already
established with some great players. There's no reason for me to
come out and try to disrupt the chemistry they've worked so hard
for.''
</P>
<P>
   In the full season he spent without Jordan, Pippen was a
first-team All-NBA selection and the Most Valuable Player of the
All-Star Game. He averaged 22 points and 8.7 rebounds, the best
numbers of his career. Yet many still label him for the last 1.8
seconds of a playoff game against the Knicks when he sat out,
objecting to the decision to run a play for Toni Kukoc instead of
him.
</P>
<P>
   The shot was good, but the irony of the backlash was that if he
had run the play without protest and Kukoc had missed, Pippen would
have been labeled as unable to deliver the last-second heroics that
came to define Jordan. It didn't help either that the Bulls
painfully lost the series when Pippen was called for a phantom foul
on a missed 3-pointer by New York's Hubert Davis.
</P>
<P>
   The play robbed Pippen of the chance to win a championship
without Jordan. He has that opportunity now. And he understands he
could be defined by what happens in Houston, despite everything
that happened in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be great to win another title and without Mike,''
Pippen said. ``He never won without me. A lot has to happen. But I
have a great situation. I don't anticipate him coming back (to
catch up). He's got quite a few MVP trophies, so I don't know if
I'd have anything over him. But it would be nice to have one more
championship ring than he does.''
</P>
<P>
   There are other things Pippen says he would like to accomplish.
He would like be to All-NBA again. And he considers his first MVP
and his first Defensive Player of the Year award worthwhile goals
within reach.
</P>
<P>
   But if there was one drawback to all the Bulls' success during
Pippen's tenure with them, it was that he averaged 92 games per
season, excluding the Olympics and exhibition games. He has had
major surgery three times, including before and after last season.
</P>
<P>
   But with his back repaired by offseason surgery and a grueling
rehabilitation and conditioning routine, Pippen, 33, believes he is
as strong and able as ever. And he feels rejuvenated by his new
address and the appreciation and approval with which he has been
showered in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen had long been among the most relatively underpaid players
in the NBA at $2.7 million per year and did not attempt to hide his
displeasure with that status. But it might have been more palatable
had Bulls management shown greater appreciation for his
contributions. He was all but traded to the Suns and Celtics before
recent seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Rockets owner Leslie Alexander, on the other hand, has called
Pippen ``a sweet guy.'' And Pippen says he spent more time with
Alexander in a two-day period _ tinkering with the five-year, $67.2
million contract he would get in the sign-and-trade deal _ than he
had with Bulls president Jerry Reinsdorf over 11 years in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has definitely been a lot of weight lifted off me by
getting out of that situation and getting a long-term contract,''
Pippen said. ``I felt that I was fairly underpaid for what I was
doing out on the court for that team _ winning and all the things
that came along with that. It wasn't a great situation to be in.
This is a different situation for me, and I want to be able to give
this organization what they're giving to me. They've invested a lot
in me trying to bring a championship to this franchise, and I want
to be able to return that favor. That's how the business should be
run.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even away from the game, going to restaurants or riding down
the street, people are glad to have me here in their city. The
organization and my teammates have made it a very easy transition
for me. I couldn't imagine it being any easier.''
</P>
<P>
   It is what he wanted all those years, a honeymoon he expects to
last. In fact, after a few weeks of house hunting, the Pippens
decided to start from the ground up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to build our own home,'' Larsa said. ``We love
this place.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
