<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 19:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2303 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LAKERS-HNS &LR;      02-04 1042
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
Shaquille O'Neal is ready.
<TEXT>
<P>
   And he's not afraid to let everyone know about it, either.
</P>
<P>
   In the parlance of the NBA, he's been running smack, angrily
sounding off on a variety of subjects in the preseason. Indeed,
O'Neal has been more like Smaquille O'Neal lately, using perceived
slights to pump himself up for this compressed, 50-game schedule.
The Lakers, he says, are the team to beat in the Western
Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Not the Rockets, whom the Lakers face in the season opener.
</P>
<P>
   Not the old and decrepit Utah Jazz, as he has read in some
publications.
</P>
<P>
   And certainly not the San Antonio Spurs, as he has read in
others.
</P>
<P>
   That one apparently was the most galling of all.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs? A team the Lakers swept last season? A team O'Neal
sees as being so soft that they practically have a chewy nougat
center? And O'Neal fully intends on chewing up any center the Spurs
plan on throwing his way, be it David Robinson or Tim Duncan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to show them who the best big men in the West really
are,'' O'Neal said. ``I'm going to kill them again. I've got to let
them know once again. I don't like David Robinson anyway. Tim
Duncan, you're too light for me down there. I'm tired of it. Now
I'm getting upset. I'm starting to get like Mike Tyson. I'm coming
back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't understand what they're looking at. You know,
they're a pretty dominant big-man tandem, but ain't none of them
can do nothing with me. And I said it. You can tell them I said it.
If they don't like it, they can see me on the court or off the
court. They can't do nothing with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Expect a Spurs-theme rap song soon.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not only the Spurs who are the target of O'Neal's ire.
Why discriminate? O'Neal said he will make the Timberwolves pay for
their refusal to gift-wrap Tom Gugliotta and ship him to LA. O'Neal
had signed off on a deal that would have sent Elden Campbell and
Eddie Jones to Minnesota for Gugliotta, but the Timberwolves
refused to pull the trigger.
</P>
<P>
   Now they, too, will pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to make some moves, but I guess other teams really
don't want to help us,'' O'Neal said. ``So from now on I'll hold a
personal vendetta against Minnesota. They're added to the list.''
</P>
<P>
   It's getting to be a long list.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Harper, who signed a one-year contract with the Lakers
this season, understands O'Neal's anger.
</P>
<P>
   ``It (the article) should be insulting to him,'' Harper said.
``He'll use it to his advantage. He wants respect. The only way to
get respect is to beat Utah and advance past the conference final.
Shaq wants a ring. I want a ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``But Robinson wants a ring, too. (Karl) Malone and (John)
Stockton want a ring. I know what those teams are doing. They're
preparing for war. We're going to go as far as he takes us.''
</P>
<P>
   It seems that ride will be fueled by hot air, which is not only
emanating from O'Neal. Other members of the organization are
starting to get caught up in the hype, targeting this team or that
as future victims of the Lakers' glitzkrieg.
</P>
<P>
   And rest assured that Houston is not being slighted, either.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets have gotten plenty of run since Scottie Pippen
hopped on for the ride. But even Lakers general manager Jerry West,
normally the mild-mannered sort, is starting to pick up on Shaq's
vibe.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can compete against Houston,'' West said. ``No matter who
they have, we can compete against Houston. To get a player like
Scottie Pippen obviously is tremendous for them, but we have a team
that's younger. I think from one to 12, we'll be more talented than
them. But to say we have three players that measure up to the
magnitude of their press clippings, no.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think we have one player on our team that's absolutely
unstoppable. And I don't think they have anyone who can stop him at
this point in time without a lot of help.''
</P>
<P>
   Are you listening, Hakeem Olajuwon?
</P>
<P>
   But there may be a method to O'Neal's madness.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal, perhaps sniffing a real title shot since Michael Jordan
decided to retire, could simply be trying to get the Lakers rallied
in a classic us-against-them mindset. It has to be better than the
us-against-us mentality that could be the Lakers' biggest enemy
this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers could very well be on the verge of greatness, or they
could implode at any time after an offseason of rumored trades.
Campbell and Jones can't be happy after the grapevine had them off
to Minnesota or Chicago. And those rumors still have them on the
move, perhaps going to Toronto. Or Orlando. Or Miami. Or Charlotte.
Or well, you get the picture.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Del Harris thinks (hopes?) Campbell, a classic
underachiever, will understand what happened, that he was in demand
because of his talent, and will soldier along with the rest of the
Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   But there could be plenty of animosity to go around, since
that's not the only problem the Lakers are facing.
</P>
<P>
   Who's going to step up to replace Nick Van Exel, who should have
been called ``Nick of Time'' because of his propensity for
last-second heroics? Van Exel, who was traded to Denver before the
lockout, was one of the rare ones _ a player willing to put himself
on the line to make the big play _ and the Lakers don't really have
those in abundance.
</P>
<P>
   There's also the fact that Jones has to deal with the fat
contract extension _ six years, $70 million _ Kobe Bryant received
last week. And then there's Rick Fox, who took a lot less money
last year to come to the Lakers, only to be rebuffed in his
attempts to cash in this year. The Lakers wound up giving him the
middle-class exception ($1.75 million), which means that he, too,
will have a frown that needs turning upside-down.
</P>
<P>
   This is a battle that could be fought on several fronts.
</P>
<P>
   West, however, is already involved in damage control.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's a danger in messing around with a team that
won 61 games with a lot of injuries last year and hasn't been
together very long,'' he said. ``We would have to think that this
would be looked upon as a powerful team (even) if we didn't do
anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Nope, they're saving that for the rest of the league.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
