<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CITY-CENTER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITY CENTER TRYING TO CATCH UP WITH NEW YORK'S TOP CULTURAL
INSTITUTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By KATHRYN SHATTUCK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Despite its landmark building, affordable tickets,
all-star roster and a musical-theater series that has been a
launching pad for Broadway, City Center has never quite radiated
the luster of Lincoln Center or Carnegie Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Now, says Raymond A. Lamontagne, its new chairman, the 55th
Street institution is gearing up to change its reputation as the
poor relative of its uptown neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   One month into his appointment, after succeeding Howard M.
Squadron, Lamontagne has already proposed a series of initiatives
to move City Center into the top tier of the city's cultural
institutions. Most important, he said in an interview, is a capital
campaign to build an endowment and the development of a board with
greater financial resources.
</P>
<P>
   ``City Center has zero endowment,'' Lamontagne said. ``It has
always been known as the `people's theater' and has never had the
same sort of financial backing as Lincoln Center or Carnegie Hall.
I want to put together a case statement for raising money so we can
do more self-presenting, fix the building and bring in more
organizations.''
</P>
<P>
   After five years as a board member, Lamontagne, the president of
Seavest Inc., a family investment office, and the Encore Co., a
private investment concern, replaced Squadron, who stepped down on
Jan. 1 after being chairman for 23 years. At the same time, Elaine
Malsin, a former president of the Paul Taylor Dance Company and a
board member, was promoted to co-chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Squadron led the drive to save the City Center building from
demolition and oversaw the center's incorporation in the 1970s as a
self-sustaining entity separate from City Center Music and Drama
Inc., the parent company of City Center 55th Street, the New York
City Ballet and the New York City Opera. He was instrumental in
expanding the center's dance-based programming to include music and
theater over the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Howard is really the father of City Center,'' said Judith E.
Daykin, the president and executive director. ``He took us through
the incorporation to become a driving force in the arts, and we
will miss his generosity and dedication.''
</P>
<P>
   Lamontagne says he is eager to build on Squadron's legacy, and
building a more powerful board is a high priority. Even with the
actors Joanne Woodward and Alec Baldwin among its ranks, ``there
aren't a lot of fancy big names, but the people we have are working
hard,'' he said. ``I'll be working to add greater financial clout
to the board.''
</P>
<P>
   Money will also be earmarked for a program to attract less
affluent audiences and for score restoration, which lies at the
heart of the center's highly successful series ``City Center
Encores! Great American Musicals in Concert.'' The series, now in
its sixth season, started off by presenting rarely heard, early
Broadway musicals in concert productions. The center took a leap in
1996, however, when it mounted a concert staging of the 1975
musical ``Chicago,'' starring Ann Reinking and Bebe Neuwirth. It
was so successful that it moved to Broadway, where it remains, and
won six Tony Awards. The ``Encores'' series, which has a 96 percent
renewal rate among subscribers, has received awards from Jujamcyn
Theaters, the New York Drama Critics Circle, Lucille Lortel and the
Outer Critics Circle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can not only save great American treasures but also have a
pipeline of things `Encores' can do for the next few years,''
Lamontagne said. ``We need to take advantage of the fact that there
are still people who remember history. They won't be around
forever.'' ``It's time to make a huge leap forward,'' Lamontagne
said. ``We're in a terrific position right now. We've balanced our
budget, paid our debts. It's just a very strong team.''
</P>
<P>
   ``City Center is a great turnaround story,'' he added. ``From a
place that was ignored a few years ago, we have come back and made
a substantial contribution to the cultural life of New York.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-04-99 2000EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
