<DOCNO> NYT19990204.0385 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2306 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SPURS-HNS &LR;      02-04 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SPURS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Suffice it to say that the gauntlet has been
thrown at the feet of David Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   Gauntlet? Heck, Shaquille O'Neal dumped Robinson's entire
wardrobe out on the street and dared the Admiral _ or Tim Duncan,
for that matter _ to do something about it.
</P>
<P>
   After reading an article that had the Spurs, a team the Lakers
swept last season, listed as the preseason favorites in the West,
O'Neal went ballistic, basically saying he could have his way with
either San Antonio center and that if they didn't like it, ``they
can see me on the court or off the court. They can't do nothing
with me.''
</P>
<P>
   So that's how it's going to be this season.
</P>
<P>
   As if things weren't intense enough with the NBA going to a
50-game post-lockout schedule, along comes O'Neal to start turning
up the heat on the Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, however, has refused to bite. So far.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nope,'' Robinson said when asked if he had any response to
O'Neal's tough talk. ``That would be foolish, just getting involved
in that. I don't have anything to say about that. It's all going to
be decided on the basketball court. You have to go out and you have
to win games. That's what it's all about.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's what the Spurs are supposed to be all about this
year. But first, some say, they have to change their mindset.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs have long been accused of being the NBA's equivalent
to a Furbie _ soft and fuzzy, but outrageously marketable. They
were the NBA's good guys, and bad apples like Dennis Rodman and
Vernon Maxwell weren't tolerated for long. The Spurs were built
around Robinson, whose spit-and-shine image is that of the
All-American good guy. The Naval Academy instead of the streets.
Standing at attention during the national anthem rather than
popping gum and looking for babes in the stands. Smiling and
fan-friendly rather than aloof or trash-talking. Classical music
vs. rap.
</P>
<P>
   All the things that are pretty much uncool in the NBA these
days.
</P>
<P>
   Guys like Duncan and Avery Johnson fall right in line. Not that
they're not intense competitors, because they are. But they're not
really intimidators, and the Spurs haven't had one of those since
Antoine Carr, who signed with the Rockets this season, skipped town
four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Where are the Baseline Bums when you need them?
</P>
<P>
   Well, the Spurs went out looking for tough guys, players who
have been tested in big games where championships have been on the
line.
</P>
<P>
   And they found them in Mario Elie and Jerome Kersey.
</P>
<P>
   While Robinson is known as The Admiral, Elie, the former Rocket,
and Kersey, who spent last season with the Sonics, are more like
drill sergeants. Elie, from American International University, and
Kersey, who went to college at Longwood (Va.), are guys who had to
be hard as nails just to make it into the NBA, so they won't be
very tolerant to any perceived softness.
</P>
<P>
   Elie immediately took up the cause, making sure he had the
Admiral's back when O'Neal started rapping the Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shaq, I don't know what he's thinking,'' said Elie, who played
on the Rockets team that swept O'Neal's Orlando Magic in the 1995
NBA Finals. ``The guy is a great player, but all you have to do is
foul him down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he had made some free throws and taken his team to the next
level, then he can talk. We know he's a great player, so you don't
have to tell anybody. David (Robinson) is a great player. Tim
(Duncan) is a great player. They just go out and do their jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   And Steve Kerr will be expected to do the same. Indeed, the
Spurs shored up their outside shooting by getting Kerr, another
big-game veteran, from the Chicago Bulls' fire sale. Those three
are expected to make huge contributions for the Spurs. The Spurs
also welcome back Sean Elliott at the three spot _ that's small
forward, for you non-scouting types _ after he played just 36 games
last year because of knee problems.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott has looked sensational so far, but the rest of the cast
is pretty much the same. Johnson is back at the point, but the
Spurs, who only seem to have been looking for a shooting guard
since George Gervin retired, are going with erratic Jaren Jackson
at that position after Vinny Del Negro decided to play in Europe
during the lockout, then signed on in Milwaukee afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Elie, Kerr and Kersey have an air about them that demands
respect. And Elie and Kerr have something else, too _ rings. And
they know how to get them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some guys walk into the locker room and it's instant
credibility,'' said Spurs coach Gregg Popovich. ``The seriousness
of the group and the confidence of the group automatically rises
without the guy even saying a word. That's the way it is with
Mario.''
</P>
<P>
   Avery Johnson has been just as impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys,'' he said, ``even talk like champions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
