<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2308 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-BREAKFAST-BOS     02-04 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-BREAKFAST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUNTRY CAN `WALK AWAY FROM' TROUBLES, CLINTON TELLS AUDIENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Just hours before the Senate resumed his
impeachment trial, President Clinton told an elite gathering at a
prayer breakfast that if South African President Nelson Mandela
could ``walk away from 28 years of oppression in a little prison
cell, we can walk away from whatever is bothering us.''
</P>
<P>
   He asked his audience of diplomats and members of Congress,
prime ministers and Cabinet officials to ``pray that we can all be
purged of the temptation to pretend that our willfulness is
somewhat equal to God's will.''
</P>
<P>
   Without directly mentioning the sex scandal that led to his
becoming the second president to be impeached in more than 131
years, Clinton said, ``All the great peacemakers in the world in
the end have to let go and walk away, like Christ, not from
apparent but from genuine grievances.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's remarks came at the annual National Prayer Breakfast,
a tradition in Washington since 1952, when the House and Senate
came together to pray for newly elected President Dwight Eisenhower
and his government.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, an overflowing crowed of some 2,600 people, including
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat whose attendance caused a few
members of Congress to stay away in protest, jammed into a hotel
ballroom for spiritual nourishment and breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   Politics was to be checked at the door, a point underscored by
the harmless banter between Clinton and Representative Steve
Largent, an Oklahoma Republican who hosted this year's event and
also voted to impeach Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have had a terrific relationship with Steve Largent, and he
has yet to vote with me,'' Clinton joked, reaching over to pat the
congressman's back. ``I know there is no politics in this prayer
breakfast.''
</P>
<P>
   Largent responded: ``Mr. President, as you said I may not have
voted with you in the four years I've been in Congress, but I want
you to know that I care for you and love you, and that's part of
the mystery of Jesus.''
</P>
<P>
   Largent also threw a friendly jab at Vice President Al Gore. ``I
was joking with the vice president earlier about how the prayer
breakfast was Thursday, but his prayers were answered earlier in
the week when (House Minority Leader Richard A. Gephardt) pulled
out of the presidential race.''
</P>
<P>
   But the efforts at civility and reconcilation extended only so
far.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Bob Barr, a Georgia Republican who has long
called for Clinton's removal from office and is one of the House
prosecutors in the impeachment trial, rose from his seat and exited
the room right before the president went to the lectern to speak.
</P>
<P>
   If impeachment was on anyone's mind, it was left to Senator
Joseph Lieberman, a Democrat from Connecticut, to make the only
direct reference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lord, may I say a special prayer at this time of difficulty
for our president,'' he said. ``That you would hear his prayers.
That you help him with the work he's doing with his family and his
clergy. That you accept his atonement.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton devoted most of his remarks _ which he said he had
stayed up late the night before discussing with his wife _ to a
prayer for world peace from Ireland to the Middle East, Bosnia to
Kosovo, Ethiopia to Eritrea, India to Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ask you to pray for peace, for the peacemakers, and for
peace within each of our hearts _ in silence,'' he said, bowing his
head to lead the audience in a moment of silent prayer.
</P>
<P>
   But the president's comment that Nazi German dictator Adolf
Hitler preached a ``perverted form of Christianity,'' angered a
Catholic group.
</P>
<P>
   William Donohue, president of the Catholic League, asked Clinton
to apologize for what he described as ``a remarkably ignorant
comment about Hitler and Christianity.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement issued from his New York office, Donohue said,
``Anyone who has studied Hitler knows that this is pure nonsense.''
</P>
<P>
   After the breakfast, Clinton met with Arafat for about 20
minutes, and reiterated the US position that unilateral steps, such
as a Palestinian declaration of statehood in May, would be
unhelpful, according to White House spokesman Barry Toiv.
</P>
<P>
   Later, meeting with a group of business leaders, Clinton for the
first time said the United States was ``seriously considering the
possibility'' of deploying American troops as part of an
international peace force in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   He said no final decision had yet been made, but he outlined
four conditions that must be met, including a commitment by both
parties to end the violence and a well-defined NATO mission with a
clear exit strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that happens we are seriously considering the possibility
of our participation in such a force,'' Clinton said. ``We are
discussing it now with Congress and our allies, but no decision has
been reached.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
