<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 20:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2310 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIDS-TESTS05-COX     02-04 0537
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDS-TESTS05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HEALTH/SCIENCE: Routine drug-resistance tests suggested for some
with HIV
 &HT;    By Lillian Lee Kim
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Drug-resistant forms of the AIDS virus are showing up
more and more often, worrying doctors and patients who fear they'll
run out of treatment options before new drugs become available.
</P>
<P>
   Testing viral strains for resistance to HIV drugs still is an
imprecise science, but AIDS researchers appear to be leaning in
favor of it to plan patients' drug therapy, especially for pregnant
women and their infants, some newly infected people and health care
workers exposed to HIV-infected blood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is clear that resistance tests will be widely
available over this year, and I would clearly approve of them,''
said Dr. Brian Gazzard of Chelsea and Westminster Hospital in
London. Gazzard spoke Thursday about resistance testing at the
Conference on Retroviruses and Opportunistic Infections in Chicago,
a scientific meeting on AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   A pilot study of 153 patients completed in December showed
roughly three in four people with HIV whose drug therapy had
stopped working were infected with resistant viral strains. Another
study among HIV-positive, active-duty U.S. military concluded that
about one in five recently infected people had resistant virus.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of the biggest problems we have,'' said Dr. Melanie
Thompson, lead researcher at the AIDS Research Consortium of
Atlanta. She also treats people with HIV at her private practice in
Atlanta. ``So many patients are losing so many options.''
</P>
<P>
   Several studies presented at the Chicago conference concluded
that resistance testing might be helpful.
</P>
<P>
   There are two types of resistance tests, neither of which has
federal approval. Phenotypic tests measure the performance of HIV
drugs _ of which 14 are approved _ against an HIV strain. Genotypic
tests genetically map part of the virus, then search for key
mutations associated with resistance to certain drugs.
</P>
<P>
   But interpreting tests results isn't as simple as looking at the
gene map and checking off drugs. Some HIV drugs are more
susceptible to resistance than others; for instance, the widely
used drug 3TC is rendered useless by a single, common mutation.
Some mutations cause cross-resistance among drugs, eliminating
several options at once.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson plans to test for resistance only when she thinks it
useful, such as for newly infected people who are acutely ill.
</P>
<P>
   The tests also are well-suited for pregnant women and newborns,
Thompson said, since cases have been recorded of mothers passing
resistant virus to babies. Also, health care workers exposed to
infected blood through needle sticks or other accidents should be
tested, said Robert Lloyd of Applied Sciences, a resistance testing
lab in Norcross owned by Visible Genetics Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Yet many AIDS specialists _ including Gazzard _ still aren't
willing to fully rely on the tests. ``Using resistance testing
intelligently is going to be a major and taxing undertaking,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Lillian Lee Kim writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
