<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 20:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2311 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TVSURFER-COLUMN05-COX     02-04 0612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TVSURFER-COLUMN05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NBC reduces ` '60s'to a string of cliches
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   You better inhale if you want to get through these '60s.
</P>
<P>
   Formerly an interesting decade, it's now a laughable miniseries.
NBC's ``The '60s,'' airing at 9 p.m. Sunday and Monday, makes the
four hours it takes to cover those 10 years feel like a millennium.
Man. It leaves no stock character unturned, no song from the era
unsung, no ``bummer, man'' unspoken. It's the kind of '60s
nostalgia that makes you nostalgic for the '90s. It's the '60s as
K-Tel might package it and offer for $8.99 on late-night TV.
</P>
<P>
   It's actually a little bit irresistible like that _ a one-shot,
cut-rate guilty pleasure. Guided by executive producer Lynda Obst
(``Contact,'' ``Sleepless in Seattle''), it runs with Gumplike
speed through the decade's icons and signposts, as if they were
stacked on shelves in a Sam's Warehouse.
</P>
<P>
   Actual news footage is spliced throughout the drama _ King's
March on Washington, Wallace's ``segregation forever'' speech, the
1968 Chicago riots _ while the drama often turns black-and-white to
make it appear more urgent. The soundtrack moves from the Chiffons
to the Doors to the Band, though you get the feeling somebody has
his hand on a button just dying every few frames to play Dylan's
``The Times They Are a Changin'.''
</P>
<P>
   These '60s are witnessed and experienced largely through the
eyes of a Catholic family in Chicago. They're all anybody needs:
Marine veteran Dad (Bill Smitrovich), just-aiming-to-please Mom
(Anne Corley), Notre Dame-bound quarterback son Bryan (Jerry
O'Connell), straight-A son Michael (Josh Hamilton), good-time
daughter Katie (Julia Stiles).
</P>
<P>
   Everything is ranch house, prom king ``Pleasantville'' _ until
somebody puts on ``The Twist'' and Southern blacks start sitting at
lunch counters. By then, 1962, a certain nervousness is creeping
around the decade's '50s-style edges. When Kennedy is shot in 1963,
the '60s that everybody means when they say ``the '60s'' finally
show up.
</P>
<P>
   Within the next few years, Bryan is fighting in Nam, Michael is
protesting the war, and Katie is pregnant and living the San
Francisco hippie life. Man. Mom's getting happy feet, too (``I
always imagined something a little more Jackie Kennedy in my
life''), though she doesn't give up on poor Dad, who's watching the
end of the world as he knows it.
</P>
<P>
   That all plays out on a predictable emotional time line: Nam vet
comes back a mess (think Tom Cruise in ``Born on the Fourth of
July''), anti-war protestor wants to make love not slogans, and
hippie chick tires of her jobless ``old man'' and returns home with
her son for three squares a day (though not before Dad apologizes
for being such a jerk). The movie's foot-through-the-TV moment
comes late Monday, when all the siblings somehow wind up together
at Woodstock.
</P>
<P>
   There's a parallel '60s experienced by a black Mississippi
family. It features Charles S. Dutton as an activist King disciple
trying to temper the hate of Leonard Roberts, his radicalized
teenage son. But in the spirit of that era, the black family is
used in this miniseries as a kind of token nod toward diversity and
often feels more insulting than inclusive.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it's hard to single out anyone or anything here for insult.
Nobody looks good. They're all cliches wrapped in stereotypes,
displayed with well-worn, hackneyed banality.
</P>
<P>
   To coin a phrase. Man.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: D
</P>
<P>
   Drew Jubera writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: channelsurfer(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
