<HEADER>
A2317 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HITACHI-OUTLOOK-NYT &LR;      02-04 0662
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HITACHI-OUTLOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HITACHI INCREASES ESTIMATE OF LOSSES, OTHER JAPANESE COMPANIES MAY
FOLLOW 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ The stronger yen is pinching Japanese businesses and
could hamper the recovery of the nation's economy, but the
government may be reluctant to intervene again to lower the
currency's value.
</P>
<P>
   Hitachi Ltd., the sprawling conglomerate that makes everything
from semiconductors and personal computers to kitchen cabinets and
rice cookers, Thursday increased its estimate of losses for the
fiscal year that ends March 31 and attributed the rise largely to
the stronger yen.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which has already started revamping its operations,
said it expected to lose an additional 125 billion yen, or $1.1
billion, bringing its estimated losses to 375 billion yen, or $3.3
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Hitachi attributed the additional losses to the yen's rise and a
one-time charge of 185 billion yen. In November, when the company
made its original estimate, it had expected the yen to hover around
125 to the dollar, but since October the yen has averaged 117.9 to
the dollar, lowering the anticipated value of Hitachi's overseas
earnings. A strong yen is damaging because it makes Japanese
exports, a possible engine of economic recovery, much more
expensive, and therefore, less competitive abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Other major Japanese exporters, many of which expected the same
exchange rate as Hitachi , are expected to follow suit and announce
reduced earnings prospects over the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Japanese government intervened to cap the yen's
rise in mid-January, it is hovering between 112 and 113 to the
dollar, and many economists believe the currency's continued
strength will further depress corporate Japan's prospects. Without
factoring in the yen's rise, many analysts have estimated that more
than 70 percent of Japanese companies will report losses this
fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   Eisuke Sakakibara, Japan's vice finance minister for
international affairs, did not rule out further intervention when
he spoke last week at a meeting of world financial leaders in
Davos, Switzerland. But he added that the strengthening of the yen
``is not causing problems for the Japanese economy'' and that
Japanese companies were competitive at levels of 115 to 116 yen to
the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   He said that exchange rates that prevailed during the onset of
Japan's financial crisis, when the yen approached 150 to the
dollar, were an aberration. ``Arguing that such rates are necessary
ingredients for the recovery implicitly assumes that Japan is still
amid a severe financial crisis,'' he said, adding that the
financial crisis ``is about to end.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts were somewhat surprised by the increase in Hitachi's
estimated loss. Although rich in cash, the company's balance sheet
has weakened over the last three years to a point where its net
debt, or the liabilities that would be left on its balance sheet
after using all of its cash to pay down debt, is approaching 1
trillion yen, or $8.85 billion, said Steven Myers, senior analyst
at Jardine Fleming Securities in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Profit in the next fiscal year is in question if the yen
doesn't weaken,'' Myers said.
</P>
<P>
   Hitachi has been working to revamp its heavy electric and
consumer electronics businesses and is still working to pare costs
at its semiconductor operations, whose profitability has suffered
from a lack of investment in upgrading plants and equipment.
</P>
<P>
   It is also working to trim employees through attrition and early
retirement to reduce costs. Top management has also been shuffled,
although analysts think the changes in the executive suite,
scheduled to take place this summer, will be largely cosmetic.
</P>
<P>
   But most analysts regard its efforts as minimal and have been
urging it to get out of unprofitable businesses. ``I hope that this
will kick management into gear to seriously reshape the group,''
Myers said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
