<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTONS-CHELSEA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARTICLE ABOUT DAUGHTER DISTRESSES CLINTONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Chelsea Clinton has her mother's strength and her
father's optimism. Despite feeling betrayed, angry, and humiliated
by The Scandal, the 18-year-old first daughter loves her parents
and won't wear her emotions on her sleeve. And as for the story
that Chelsea collapsed last fall after breaking up with her
boyfriend, that was ``blown way out of proportion,'' a friend told
People magazine.
</P>
<P>
   The cover story, ``Grace Under Fire,'' which hits the newsstands
Friday, is no hatchet job. Still, the Clintons are having a fit
over the story, the first piece that promises ``an intimate look at
the deep bond of love that sustains the Clinton women through their
painful family ordeal.''
</P>
<P>
   The strong White House reaction _ including an extraordinary
appeal to the magazine from Marsha Berry, the first lady's press
secretary, to kill the story _ signaled more than a fear that
Chelsea's privacy had been violated. It suggested a worry that at
age 18, and as a player in the White House family drama, Chelsea
might become a window for other media to probe the complex and very
private relationships of the Clintons.
</P>
<P>
   And some wondered whether the Clintons weren't trying to have it
both ways _ to stage-manage Chelsea's media exposure as the devoted
daughter in a happy-family portrait during a year of scandal, while
keeping the Stanford sophomore safely away from the unfiltered
glare of the press.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't become a virgin a second time,'' said conservative
commentator Arianna Huffington, noting that when the Clintons
needed the family image in the 1992 campaign, they invited People
magazine into their home for a story and photographs. ``The reason
the Clintons are making such a public stand now is not so much
because they are mad at People magazine _ it's a glowing story _
but because they want to stop an avalanche of media coverage of
their daughter.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Chelsea has been largely, remarkably, out of the media
spotlight during her father's tenure in the White House. In 1993,
the Clintons firmly laid down the law about Chelsea's privacy after
the then 12-year-old was portrayed in an unflattering ``Saturday
Night Live'' skit. In the mainstream media, the off-limit
instructions on Chelsea by and large, have been followed.
</P>
<P>
   At least until the People profile.
</P>
<P>
   ``We deeply regret and are profoundly saddened by the decision
of People magazine to print a cover story featuring our daughter,
Chelsea,'' the president and Hillary Rodham Clinton said in an
joint statement that went out in a press alert Wednesday night.
``For over six years, the media has understood and respected the
unique situation facing Chelsea as she grows up in the spotlight
focused on her parents.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons said Chelsea should be spared scrutiny because,
other than in family situations, she ``has not taken on a public
role.'' And they pleaded with the media to ``continue its policy of
restraint with respect to our daughter.''
</P>
<P>
   Executives at People magazine said they were sensitive to the
appeal, but not persuaded to stop publication. ``Chelsea is nearly
19 years old and a poised young adult,'' said Carole Wallace,
People's managing editor. ``We feel that because she is an
eyewitness to the family drama and historical events unfolding
around her, she is a valid journalistic subject.''
</P>
<P>
   Gail Collins, author of ``Scorpion Tongues,'' said while the
press has been happy to leave Chelsea alone, it is getting harder
to make a rational argument that she is too young or vulnerable to
be protected by the old rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough to say you can draft Chelsea and send her to war,
but you can't write about her,'' said Collins, who is an editorial
writer at the New York Times. ``How old was Monica _ 21? _ when she
had an affair with the president? Nobody is arguing that she was
too tender to be bothered with.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Chelsea has been called up by the White House in its
time of greatest peril. There was the touching picture of Chelsea
clutching her parents's hands as they left the White House in
August in the wake of the president's disclosures of an
extramarital affair. The White House made much of Chelsea's romance
last year with an all-American boy. And former Senator Dale Bumpers
of Arkansas referred to Chelsea by name during his speech before
the Senate impeachment trial last month, suggesting the family had
suffered enough in a relationship that was ``incredibly strained,
if not destroyed.''
</P>
<P>
   Brit Hume, the Washington managing editor for Fox TV News, said
``it's a very close call'' for the press in deciding if, as People
magazine said, Chelsea has become a ``valid journalistic subject.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unfair to say you are a public figure by extension of who
you are related to,'' Hume said. ``But if Chelsea crosses the
threshold, if she is consciously putting herself out there as a
symbol of support for her father, it's hard to argue that she isn't
news.''
</P>
<P>
   Hume said many journalists operate on the ``out-there factor'' _
that is, once a story appears in a wide-circulation publication
like People, the subject becomes fair game for the rest of the
press.
</P>
<P>
   The wall protecting Chelsea started to break down in November,
when many media outlets, including The Boston Globe, reported that
Chelsea had broken up with her boyfriend and had sought treatment
at Stanford's health center for stress-related symptoms. The story
first appeared in the tabloid newspapers, the National Enquirer and
the Star, but it did not get wide attention in the mainstream press
until the New York Post reported it.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Rosensteil, director for the Project for Excellence in
Journalism, a nonprofit group that monitors press performance, said
the Clintons's efforts to protect their daughter from the media
horde have been ``one of the genuinely endearing things about this
tragically messed up family.'' He accused People magazine of
exploiting Chelsea.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is garbage,'' Rosensteil said. ``Chelsea's story is not
important, there is no overriding public good in reporting it. This
is exploitation to sell magazines, and journalists everywhere
should stand up and say, `Shame on you; don't you have any
decency?' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
