<HEADER>
A2322 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-PACERS-HNS &LR;      02-04 0550
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-PACERS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
IT just doesn't sound right.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Bulls have always entered the season as the favorites to win
the NBA title, haven't they?
</P>
<P>
   But no Michael and no Scottie means no chance for the Bulls. In
case you haven't heard, Michael Jordan has retired and Scottie
Pippen is a Rocket, meaning the NBA title is once again up for
grabs.
</P>
<P>
   ``No team is the perfect team,'' said NBC analyst and Hall of
Famer Bill Walton. ``It's going to be a great season _ for the
first time nobody knows who is going to win the championship.''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone has an opinion, though, and in these post-lockout,
post-Jordan times, it's the Indiana Pacers who are just about
everyone's favorite to win this year's NBA championship.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine that _ a former American Basketball Association team
favored to win the NBA title. The Pacers were always expected to be
in the running for the ABA championship, winning three, but they've
never been considered among the top NBA contenders.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers return everyone from the team that extended the Bulls
to seven games in last year's Eastern Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   Even Charles Barkley, one of the toughest people to impress,
seems taken with the Pacers, who spent the lockout playing together
at a local Indianapolis gym.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Indiana is the team to beat,'' he said. ``They have
the advantage because they practiced the whole time during the
lockout and they have everybody back. They don't have to worry
about chemistry problems. They almost beat the Bulls last year, and
I think people fail to take that into account.
</P>
<P>
   ``They took the Bulls to seven games, and you can't remember the
last time that happened.''
</P>
<P>
   But can they handle the pressure? The Bulls did, year after
year. It remains to be seen if the Pacers can do the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really stretched the Bulls to the limit last year and
keeping that same team intact, I think all eyes are upon you,''
said guard Reggie Miller. ``You've got to take that with a grain of
salt. Everyone has a shot this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Miami, with Riley, is always in the hunt. Now that (Latrell)
Sprewell's in New York, you almost have to give them the edge. With
a healthy Patrick Ewing, and Allan Houston and Sprewell at the two
and three spots, that's very dangerous. Just because everyone on
paper is picking us, we still have a long ways to go.''
</P>
<P>
   There is another element to this season that has gone largely
unspoken. Last year, Pacers coach Larry Bird didn't know what to
expect. This year, he will demand nothing less than championship
effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like it,'' said Bird of the pressure. ``When I played, we
had a lot of expectations in Boston and I like it for this team
here. We'll see what they're made of.''
</P>
<P>
   It's rubbing off. The Pacers are starting to feel like they're
the favorites, which is half the battle at this level.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have only so many years left with this group, so it does
put a lot of pressure on us this year to go further than we've
been,'' said Indiana center Rik Smits. ``A championship is our goal
this year.''
</P>
<P>
   It's going to be a fight, though, with several teams looking to
jump into the void left by the dismantling of the Bulls' dynasty.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
