<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990204.0403 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2339 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANTHRAX-SCARE05-COX     02-04 1091
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTHRAX-SCARE05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Anthrax threats taken seriously, but appear to be hoax
 &HT;    By Jack Warner and Lyda Longa
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Four shivering NBC employees had to strip in the
middle of Peachtree Street behind makeshift curtains and suffer a
shower of water and bleach in a decontamination trailer Thursday
after they received a letter purporting to contain deadly anthrax
spores.
</P>
<P>
   Similar threats were received at two points in Washington, D.C.,
and at the main post office in Columbus, Ga. The FBI is
investigating all four threats, which appear to be hoaxes.
</P>
<P>
   No extraordinary measures were taken at the other three
locations. But the Atlanta Fire Department responded swiftly to the
letter received at the NBC News bureau in Colony Square, blocking
off the Midtown intersection, pulling up a special 30-foot long
trailer and completing the process of full decontamination on four
women before it was decided there was no threat.
</P>
<P>
   All of the threats apparently came in standard business
envelopes. Inside were plastic sheets or bags with dark powdery
substances and typed sheets of paper announcing the presence of
anthrax and a message of some sort. The FBI refused to reveal what
the messages contained.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Ross, spokeswoman for the Postal Service's South Georgia
District, said the envelope received in Columbus contained a letter
in large type that said: ``You have now been exposed to anthrax,''
an additional photocopied page and a small, plastic film-wrapped
parcel containing less than a tablespoon-full of cinnamon-colored
powder.
</P>
<P>
   The envelope, postmarked Independence, Calif., was addressed to
the Postal Service at 3916 Milgen Road, the main post office in
Columbus. The post office is on the northwest side of the city.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Ryan, a field producer for NBC, said when the employee
opening the day's mail saw the note, ``she evacuated the room and
called the FBI, CDC, police and fire.''
</P>
<P>
   There were eight people in the 11th-floor bureau at the time, he
said. Atlanta police dispatched the call as a bomb threat and two
officers responded. When firefighters arrived, Ryan said, they
initially began to remove the employees but quickly changed their
mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``People in space suits came in and sprayed us head to toe with
bleach,'' he said. The two police officers were also sprayed. Late
Thursday, the gray carpet in front of the reception desk had turned
a dingy white.
</P>
<P>
   Hazardous materials officers from the Atlanta Fire Department
took the employees up one floor and ``back to an elevator they had
secured, and down to the street,'' Ryan said.
</P>
<P>
   Several employees were taken into the decon trailer and showered
with their clothes on, Ryan said, but then experts apparently
decided that was insufficient.
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters strung tarpaulins between the trailer and a fire
truck to shield the workers and one by one, four women disrobed and
stepped into the shower. As each finished the shower, she stepped
through another door into a warming room and wrapped herself in
sheets to be rushed by ambulance to Grady Hospital. Their clothes
were placed in an air-tight canister.
</P>
<P>
   After the fourth woman was showered, Ryan said, ``they decided
the threat wasn't that serious and the rest of us didn't need to go
through it.'' However, word didn't reach Grady in time to stop the
women from having to undergo yet another decontamination shower. An
Atlanta police officer was also treated at Grady.
</P>
<P>
   There was no official announcement that the envelope was a hoax,
however, and every office in Colony Square received a note warning
that employees who begin to experience ``cough, fever or chest
pressure'' should contact Dr. Joseph Steinberg at CDC. None of the
NBC workers was reporting any symptoms Thursday evening.
</P>
<P>
   Worried employees of American International Group, an insurance
firm that shares the 11th floor with NBC, gathered near the trailer
wanting treatment. Elisha McKinley, one of the AIG workers, said he
was leaving for lunch when two NBC employees burst out of their
office across the elevator hall and said they had ``opened a
package and it had anthrax in it.'' McKinley said he went back into
his office and started getting workers out.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, McKinley said, he and his co-workers were told to go
home, shower thoroughly and wash their clothes in hot water.
</P>
<P>
   The ninth, 10th and 11th floors of Colony Square were evacuated,
but most of the offices in the 24-story building closed for the
day.
</P>
<P>
   The Columbus envelope was opened by Sue Fairley, secretary to
the Columbus postmaster, who routinely opens mail addressed to the
Postal Service there. Fairley did not open the plastic-wrapped
package or read the photocopied material, Ross said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said it looked faded, like something that been copied over
and over,'' Ross said.
</P>
<P>
   Fairley and two mail carriers who handled the envelope were
counseled by hazardous materials specialists with the Columbus Fire
Department, who advised them to wash their hands and forearms to
the elbows with chemicals, Ross said.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, the letters went to the Washington Post and the
Old Executive Office Building, which houses the office of the vice
president and other White House offices. Subsequent field tests by
the FBI found that neither envelope actually contained anthrax. It
was not clear why such a test could not be made in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   FBI spokeswoman Elisa Foster declined to say where the NBC
letter was postmarked, but said FBI was treating the threat
seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time there are threats made through the mail, it's a
federal crime,'' Foster said. ``It's still a serious issue because
we all responded as if it was potentially anthrax. It isn't over.
We're going to investigate.''
</P>
<P>
   Foster said it was too early to determine if one group or person
was responsible for the letters. But Foster said such threats are
common.
</P>
<P>
   ``This happens every day,'' she said. ``This isn't unusual.''
</P>
<P>
   Phony threats of anthrax have become the bomb scares of the
'90s, emptying nightclubs, abortion clinics, schools, churches and
federal offices across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Individual targets are also becoming commonplace. Neal Horsley,
a Carrollton man behind the controversial anti-abortion Nuremberg
Files web site, received a letter in November claiming to contain
anthrax.
</P>
<P>
   Horsley underwent a decontamination wash-down. The letter was
ruled a hoax after testing.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
