<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUSCHWITZ-BANK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEUTSCHE BANK RELEASES DOCUMENTS SHOWING FINANCING FOR AUSCHWITZ 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also AUSTRIA-HOLOCAUST) 
(DW) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ Deutsche Bank AG, which is negotiating to
settle claims with Holocaust survivors to gain regulatory approval
to take over Bankers Trust, released documents Thursday that showed
that it had helped finance the building of Auschwitz.
</P>
<P>
   The disclosure occurred as Deutsche Bank, the biggest in
Germany, is under pressure from Jewish organizations and other
groups to open its archives and compensate those who lost property
or lives because of the bank's collaboration with the Nazi
government.
</P>
<P>
   The release is the first time that the bank has acknowledged a
financing role in the death camps, though the bank's involvement in
the Third Reich has never been a secret. The documents were
released by the bank historian, Manfred Pohl, who said they were
recently found in an extensive collection of records.
</P>
<P>
   Although Pohl said his activities were independent from the
management, the release also may have been a signal of good faith
in the talks with the survivors.
</P>
<P>
   It appeared to be received that way. The secretary-general of
the World Jewish Congress in New York, Israel Singer, announced
that he would soon meet the bank chairman, chairman, Rolf-Ernst
Breuer, to discuss a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   German officials are scheduled to discuss on Monday a broad
compensation fund for Holocaust survivors with Stuart E. Eizenstat,
the U.S. under secretary of state for business affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Bank is one of many German companies that face a series
of U.S. class-action suits over survivors' claims. Many of the
biggest industrial companies, including DaimlerChrysler AG, Siemens
AG and Volkswagen AG face claims over their use of slave-labor in
World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Bank faces claims over its role in seizing property and
other wealth from German Jews, as well as its role as Hitler's lead
banker.
</P>
<P>
   Alan G. Hevesi, the New York City comptroller, has promised to
block the bank's $10.1 billion purchase of Bankers Trust Corp.
unless it reaches an agreement over Holocaust claims. Partly
because of political pressure from Hevesi, Switzerland's biggest
banks agreed in the summer to pay $1.25 billion to settle claims
over dormant Nazi-era gold deposits.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Bank needs U.S. regulatory approval to buy Bankers
Trust. The historical records indicate that the bank provided
construction loans for at least part of Auschwitz. They also
provide evidence of secret accounts controlled by the SS that were
used to transfer money taken from Jews who had been deported or
sent to the death and concentration camps.
</P>
<P>
   Pohl said that he had identified 10 companies, including the
giant I.G. Farben chemical company, that used loans and bank
credits in connection with building Auschwitz.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Bank also provided a line of credit totaling 400,000
reichsmarks to a small company, W. Riedel &AMP; Son, that built walls,
bridges, floors and roofing at Auschwitz. Because the credit was
secured by accounts receivable, Pohl said, Deutsche Bank managers
knew exactly which projects they were financing and received
regular status reports.
</P>
<P>
   The bank also provided a much bigger line of credit to Farben,
though Pohl said it was difficult to tell how much of that money
was used to build Auschwitz.
</P>
</TEXT>
