<DOCNO> NYT19990204.0407 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2348 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-MUTANT-AIDS-BOS &LR;      02-04 0979
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-MUTANT-AIDS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUTANT AIDS STRAINS INFECTING THOUSANDS, STUDIES SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Thousands of Americans are being infected with mutant
strains of the AIDS virus that have built-in resistance to the only
drugs doctors now have to attack the microbe, according to two new
reports presented here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, at least one in five newly infected individuals carries
a viral strain resistant to at least one of the three types of AIDS
drugs, while about three percent are infected with viruses
resistant to all three drug classes.
</P>
<P>
   The spread of hard-to-treat AIDS viruses is certain to grow,
said Dr. John Mellors of the University of Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   ``Experience tells us that once resistant virus is there, it
tends to increase,'' Mellors said at the Sixth Conference on
Retroviruses, the type of viruses that cause AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   The new studies come only six months after researchers reported
the first evidence that multiply-resistant strains of the human
immunodeficiency virus (HIV) had infected individuals in San
Francisco and Geneva, Switzerland. Before then, scientists had
crossed their fingers against the possibility, hoping that the
genetic mutations that allow the virus to elude the drugs would
make them less ``fit,'' or likely to be transmitted from one person
to another.
</P>
<P>
   Now researchers know for certain that those earlier cases were
bellwethers of a rapidly increasing phenomenon. It's a byproduct of
the spectacular success in multidrug treatments for AIDS that have
emerged in the past three years, as the virus responds by
developing mutations that allow it to elude the drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Public health officials had hoped that widespread use of the
drug ``cocktails'' would stem the spread of HIV by making patients
on the new therapies less likely to transmit the virus. But John
Kaplan of the US Centers for Disease Control and Prevention said
that is probably not happening, partly because patients are still
infectious despite the drugs, and because many are not practicing
safe sex.
</P>
<P>
   ``As patients develop resistance, that probably lowers the
ability of anti-HIV treatment to reduce transmission,'' Kaplan
said.
</P>
<P>
   The new evidence comes from two very different and
geographically dispersed populations _ a racially diverse group of
95 active-duty military personnel from bases scattered around the
nation, and 69 largely white men from Boston, Los Angeles, San
Diego, Dallas, and Denver.
</P>
<P>
   The diversity of the two groups suggests the spread of
drug-resistant viruses is a general trend, rather than confined to
certain groups or locales.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 40,000 Americans become infected with HIV each year
_ nearly 110 daily. The new studies suggest that perhaps 23 of
them, or 8,432 a year, are acquiring HIV strains resistant to at
least one class of antiviral drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps 3 a day, or more than 1,000 a year, are being infected
with viruses that can elude all three classes of antiviral
medications.
</P>
<P>
   Among the 69 patients in the five-city study, for instance,
seven had viruses that were resistant to at least one protease
inhibitor, the mainstay of current treatment, and four individuals
harbored HIV resistant to all four such protease drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The trend is alarming to public health officials and AIDS
doctors, who fear that treatment options will slip away for a
growing number of newly infected patients.
</P>
<P>
   That already is a growing problem among chronically treated
individuals, whose HIV may not be resistant at first but is able to
acquire drug resistance over time. One study presented here this
week found that one-third of patients who have been taking one of
the original successful multidrug ``cocktails'' saw the virus
reappear in their bloodstreams within three years.
</P>
<P>
   The stubborn resistance problem is causing considerable
uncertainty among AIDS specialists about whether to monitor
patients closely to signs of resistance mutations, using tests that
cost $400 to $900, and what to do if the tests come back positive.
</P>
<P>
   One study presented Thursday showed that patients ``failing'' on
triple-drug therapy did much better if their doctors had access to
information about their resistance profile to guide them in
choosing ``salvage'' therapy.
</P>
<P>
   But the transmission of resistant viruses, as opposed to the
development of resistance within a patient during treatment, poses
a new set of problems.
</P>
<P>
   If a physician doesn't recognize that a new patient harbors
resistant HIV, he is likely to prescribe drugs that fail to
suppress the virus, allowing it to gain the upper hand within the
patient's body. That not only compromises the patient's chances of
successful treatment but permits the virus to acquire more
drug-resistance mutations that could be passed on if patients fail
to practice safe sex.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, several authorities urged that doctors begin
routinely testing new patients' blood with the costly resistance
tests.
</P>
<P>
   ``Routine resistance testing may be critical to selecting
optimal initial treatment regimens,'' said Susan Little of the
University of San Diego, who presented results of the five-city
study.
</P>
<P>
   Currently doctors generally do not screen new patients for signs
of resistance mutations but treat first. Typically, they now
discover a patient has a resistant virus only when the drug regimen
fails to suppress the virus promptly.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, after one Boston man had a slow response to a
common triple-drug regimen, Massachusetts General Hospital doctors
discovered he had been infected with a virus that was resistant to
two types of drugs. They switched him to a different drug
``cocktail'' composed entirely of drugs of a third class called
non-nucleosides, which so far have kept his virus below detectable
levels.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
