<SLUG> BC-CHINA-DISSIDENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINESE PRO-DEMOCRACY ADVOCATE SENTENCED TO 4 YEARS IN PRISON 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By   ELISABETH ROSENTHAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ A Chinese court Thursday sentenced a pro-democracy
advocate to four years in jail for illegally entering China and
``providing financial assistance for activities endangering state
security,'' his family said.
</P>
<P>
   The man sentenced, Wang Ce, 50, had been living in Spain since
1992 and had sneaked into China last October through Vietnam. He
also studied in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In November, he met with Wang Youcai, a dissident who was
sentenced to 11 years in prison the next month for his involvement
in the fledgling China Democratic Party. At that meeting, Wang Ce
gave Wang Youcai $1,000, which he said was to help cover the living
expenses of a friend who was jobless.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic Party, which was founded in June 1998, is a loose
national network of dissidents seeking to promote democratic change
in China and was increasingly active last fall until a government
crackdown stalled its efforts.
</P>
<P>
   In December, after tolerating the group's activities for several
months, the Chinese authorities abruptly declared the group to be
an illegal organization, arrested or detained many of its leaders
and sentenced three of its most prominent members _ Xu Wenli, Qin
Yongmin and Wang Youcai _ to prison terms of more than 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Wang Ce is one of a handful of Chinese dissidents overseas who
decided to sneak back into China last fall _ a decision some said
was prompted by what appeared to be the growing momentum of the
Democratic Party. Two others were sentenced to three years in a
labor camp last month.
</P>
<P>
   Although Wang was living in Spain, he is still a Chinese
citizen. Zhang Qiyue, a spokeswoman for the Chinese Foreign
Ministry, said he used forged documents to enter China..
</P>
<P>
   Though severely damaged by the crackdown, members of the China
Democratic Party say they will persevere. Just Thursday, a new
affiliate of the party was established in Hebei province, according
to the Hong Kong Center for Human Rights and Democratic Movement in
China. The Democratic Party was also planning a national meeting in
the central city of Wuhan, the center said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
