<DOCNO> NYT19990204.0410 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2354 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHELSEA-REACT05-COX     02-04 1105
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHELSEA-REACT05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Magazine story may open floodgates for stories on first daughter
 &HT;    By Lyle V. Harris
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When it comes to media coverage of presidential
offspring, the kid gloves have come off.
</P>
<P>
   The new edition of People magazine features a glowing profile of
Chelsea Clinton that her parents are criticizing as a violation of
their 18-year-old daughter's privacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``For over six years, the media has understood and respected the
unique situation facing Chelsea as she grows up in the spotlight
focused on her parents,'' the Clintons said in a statement. ``We
have been very grateful for the media's restraint in allowing
Chelsea the privacy that any young person needs and deserves.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons reportedly made a personal plea to block the story
and said they were ``profoundly saddened'' the magazine refused to
honor their wishes.
</P>
<P>
   The story, ``The Ties That Bind,'' examines the close but
complex bond between Chelsea and Hillary Rodham Clinton, one that
has tightened since revelations that President Clinton engaged in
``improper relations'' with former White House intern Monica
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The eight-page cover story does discuss some aspects of her
personal life, such as the breakup with her college boyfriend and
her feelings of betrayal after her father's indiscretion surfaced.
But it's also filled with innocuous details, such as Chelsea
wrapping a blanket around her mother during a beach picnic in 1997.
Even so, that type of information until now has been off-limits by
most mainstream publications.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1992 campaign, Chelsea was sometimes seen on the
stump with her parents. They've kept her out of the public eye
since then, but that's changed in the past year. She has been
photographed on foreign jaunts with her mother and holding hands
with her parents in apparently symbolic gestures of reconciliation
the day after Clinton publicly confessed his affair with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton biographer David Maraniss said that despite their
efforts to safeguard their daughter's privacy, the president and
Hillary Clinton also have used Chelsea as a political prop.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a certain hypocrisy here,'' Maraniss told People.
``For the most part, they try to protect her, but when a political
situation requires using Chelsea, they will.''
</P>
<P>
   Carol Wallace, managing editor for People, defended the decision
to write about the Stanford University student, who turns 19 on
Feb. 27, because of her increasingly visible profile in recent
months.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are certainly sensitive to the Clinton's concerns about
their daughter but there is a great deal of admiration for this
mother-daughter relationship,'' Wallace said in a statement.
``Chelsea is nearly 19 years old and a poised young adult. We feel
that because she is an eyewitness to the family drama and
historical events unfolding around her she is a valid journalistic
subject.''
</P>
<P>
   Chip Carter, the middle son of former president Jimmy Carter,
said he believes the People story represents a drastic change in
the rules for covering the first family.
</P>
<P>
   Carter, 48, said press secretary Jody Powell hammered out a
``gentleman's agreement'' with reporters that kept them from
covering his once-shy baby sister, Amy, who was 9 when her dad
became president.
</P>
<P>
   ``The deal was that the press could take pictures of her on the
first day of school, but not the next day. They left her alone, and
they respected that,'' Carter said. ``Back then I think the press
was a lot gentler than it is now.''
</P>
<P>
   Once she left the White House to attend Brown University, Amy
Carter become a celebrity of sorts by getting arrested for
protesting for animal rights. Since then, she has avoided the media
spotlight and lives quietly with her husband in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sister doesn't do press,'' said Carter. ``She's a very
private person now and I think she's going to remain that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Chelsea has never been interviewed, although reporters have been
invited to off-the-record dinners with her during foreign trips.
She has only spoken in public overseas, in roundtable discussions
with other young people. Last year, tabloids violated the Chelsea
``no-fly'' zone by reporting on the breakup with her college
sweetheart.
</P>
<P>
   Washington Post media reporter Howard Kurtz said the People
story could mark a turning point in mainstream media coverage of
the president's daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The People cover story is a big deal because it means the wall
is eroding and it could open the floodgates for media scrutiny and
harassment,'' said Kurtz, adding that his paper rarely writes
stories about Chelsea. ``If I set the rules for how we covered
people, I'd be awfully cautious about descending into the personal
angst of a teen-ager who is trying to grow up outside the glare of
scrutiny.''
</P>
<P>
   But a public role is not unusual for the children of presidents.
Anna Roosevelt served as substitute hostess for her father. Amy
Carter was trotted out for state dinners and to play the violin for
Egyptian President Anwar Sadat at Camp David. Lyndon Baines
Johnson's then teen-age daughters, Lucy and Linda, made speeches
and kept full public schedules. Barbara Bush's eldest grandchild
introduced her to the 1992 Republican national convention.
</P>
<P>
   But when historian Carl Sferrazza Anthony suggested ``it would
be wonderful'' if Chelsea introduced Hillary Clinton to the
Democrats' 1996 convention, the first lady turned frosty, for the
first time in their many conversations.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said absolutely, unequivocally no. There was not even a
hesitation or consideration of that,'' recalled Anthony, author of
the upcoming ``First Families.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. George Rainbolt, a professor of media ethics and philosophy
at Georgia State University, said that Chelsea has entered a gray
area between private figure and political celebrity that may be
difficult to escape.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Chelsea has moved herself into the spotlight, and
clearly it has been politically useful for the president to have
this young woman, his daughter, standing by his side,'' Rainbolt
said. ``The press has a right to cover her, but I hope they would
use their rights responsibly and not use it as an excuse to start a
stampede.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter had some advice for Chelsea if she's going to survive in
the White House fishbowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``My guess is that she is a remarkable girl and you can't be
incognito if you're the president's kid, so she better learn how to
deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   _The Associated Press contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
