<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-GOP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATORS _ EVEN GOP _ MAY BE GROWING WEARY OF TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a rare moment of unruliness, a bearded man in a
business suit interrupted the Senate impeachment trial Thursday,
standing up in the public gallery to shout, ``God Almighty, take
the vote and get it over with!''
</P>
<P>
   Senators looked up in surprise. Chief Justice William H.
Rehnquist called for order. The man, Richard Douglas Llamas, 48,
was arrested and taken away, and the trial soon resumed.
</P>
<P>
   But throughout the day, as senators backed away from one
proposal to have a ``finding of fact'' vote and ditched another to
call Monica S. Lewinsky to testify in person, it seemed the
maverick guest may have expressed the views of others besides
himself.
</P>
<P>
   Senators in both parties have for weeks shown interest in ending
the trial of President Clinton sooner rather than later, and
according to the current schedule, it is supposed to finish by late
next week.
</P>
<P>
   And although a motion to move straight to closing arguments was
rejected almost entirely along party lines, some Republicans
indicated an increasing weariness may have played a part in the
other decisions, which essentially told the House prosecutors it
was time to wrap things up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do think it's time we get to a vote and we move on,'' Senate
Majority Leader Trent Lott said.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Susan M. Collins of Maine, one of the members of the GOP
task force that drafted the finding-of-fact proposal, said there
were ``all different motivations'' for waning Republican support of
her plan. But chief among them was exhaustion _ and fear of
exhaustion among voters back home.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some who are worried about the political
consequences of dragging out the trial and feel this would add
further delay,'' Collins said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The White House had a similar interpretation of the day's
events. In a written statement, spokesman Joe Lockhart said,
``Today's vote rejecting the House managers' request for live
witnesses indicates the Senate appears ready to bring this trial to
a conclusion.''
</P>
<P>
   Adding pressure was Senate Minority Leader Thomas A. Daschle,
who continued his ongoing attack on the GOP for the length and
scope of a trial the public clearly does not support. Before
heading into the trial Thursday afternoon, Daschle said, ``The
longer it goes the more it becomes a partisan trial, a Republican
trial.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, predictably, denied political concerns played a
role in the votes on witness testimony or the decision to abandon
the fact-finding proposal. But few concealed their enthusiasm for
ending the trial by Feb. 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the pressure is entirely internal,'' said Senator
Gordon Smith, a Republican from Oregon. ``No one needs to twist my
arm to want to get out of this.''
</P>
<P>
   Others still turned the tables on Daschle, indicating that
efforts to pass a censure resolution after the votes on the
articles of impeachment would be as time-consuming as the trial
itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tired? I'm just doing my job,'' said Senator Ted Stevens, a
Republican from Alaska. ``I think I'm going to get tired of the
subject when it comes back up with a censure resolution. We're
going to get all the way through and finish this, and then people
are going to want to go through it all again with the censure
business. Then I'll be tired.''
</P>
<P>
   Senator Robert F. Bennett, a Republican from Utah, also pitched
Thursday's votes as nothing unusual, saying lightly that among his
colleagues, ``of course there's a sense of wanting to get this
done.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There always has been,'' he said, ``right from the
beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Llamas, a resident of Washington, D.C., was arrested
shortly after 4:15 p.m. and charged with disruption of Congress, a
misdemeanor with a maximum $500 fine and up to six months in jail.
</P>
<P>
   Although an arrest was made during the impeachment debate in the
House of Representatives, Llamas' was the first arrest since the
Senate trial began Jan. 7, according to Lt. Dan Nichols of the
Capitol Police.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
