<HEADER>
A2361 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-ASSESS-425&AMP;AD     02-04 1075
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-ASSESS-425&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOTH PARTIES LOOK FOR SOMETHING MORE THAN SIMPLE ACQUITTAL
</HEADLINE>
  (See also IMPEACH-TRIAL, IMPEACH, IMPEACH-SCENE, IMPEACH-MANAGERS,
IMPEACH-LEWINSKY, IMPEACH-REPUBS) 
(fe) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL  
 
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As the Senate hurtles toward the finale of the
impeachment trial, the last major question before it is whether it
can find a way to bridge party differences and rebuke President
Clinton even while leaving him in office.
</P>
<P>
   There is a longing in the Senate for something more than a
simple acquittal of Clinton. But finding the right words, the right
formula and the right timing is proving elusive, as the apparent
collapse on Thursday of a Republican ``finding of fact'' proposal
demonstrated.
</P>
<P>
   A variety of forces ranging from party loyalty to concerns about
history, precedent and the Constitution are pulling the sides
apart.
</P>
<P>
   These forces are intensified, as the Republicans and Democrats
maneuver over competing formulas to chastise the president, by the
desire of each party to protect itself, especially in the 2000
elections, while putting the other at a political disadvantage.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Sen. Phil Gramm, a conservative Texas Republican,
came close to threatening that he would mount a filibuster against
any Democratic move to censure Clinton. ``I think what is happening
here is a great effort by politicans to have it both ways,'' he
charged. ``Anybody who wants to vote another way other than guilty
or not guilty is trying to find political cover.''
</P>
<P>
   So while the parties may yet find common ground next week, it is
also plausible that the impeachment trial could end with Clinton's
acquittal and nothing more _ except a new political-cultural debate
in 2000 over whether the Democrats are the party of sex, lies and
obstruction or whether the Republicans are the party of government
intrusion into private life.
</P>
<P>
   Many members of both parties seem to share a desire to see
Clinton pay some further price for the nation's yearlong ordeal.
Some Democrats do not want their vote against conviction next week
to signal that they condone Clinton's sexual relationship with a
former White House intern and his lies to the nation. And
Republicans do not want to see Clinton celebrate his acquittal and
portray it as a political victory over a partisan impeachment
drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a very strong majority of both parties that does not
want to see this president get off scot-free,'' said Sen. Robert
Bennett, R-Utah, who is working with two Democratic senators,
Dianne Feinstein of California and Daniel Patrick Moynihan of New
York, to fashion a censure resolution. ``If we can just find the
right set of words for people to come together, I think there are
80 votes or more for censure,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But the rise and fall of the Republican idea for a ``finding of
fact'' shows how difficult this can be. The plan was the brainchild
of Republican moderates who may very well vote not to convict
Clinton but still wanted some way to show to voters _ and the
party's conservative base _ that they thought the president had
committed serious offenses.
</P>
<P>
   So they proposed that the Senate find that Clinton ``willfully
provided false and misleading testimony'' to a grand jury and that
he ``engaged in conduct to delay the discovery and to cover up the
existence of evidence and to alter testimony related to a federal
civil rights lawsuit and a United States grand jury
investigation.'' This finding, which would have required only a
majority vote, was to be part of the permanent impeachment
proceedings. That vote would have been followed by the vote on
conviction and removal, which it is already known will not produce
the 67 votes necessary to prevail.
</P>
<P>
   The idea had a secondary appeal as well for some Republicans.
For it would give some validation to the House Republicans who
impeached Clinton on a near party-line vote. Republican Senators
want to protect themselves, but they are also trying to give some
support to their colleagues in the House, who now hold only a
six-seat majority and could be in danger of losing control of the
House in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   But the plan ran into a wall of Democratic opposition, in part
because of its permanence in the impeachment record (censure by
contrast could always be repealed in a future Congress, as Andrew
Jackson's was), in part because of questions over whether it would
put Clinton in legal jeopardy in a future prosecution and in part
because of feelings that such a move would be unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're trying to aim at President Clinton, and they're going
to hit the Constitution,'' said Sen. Byron Dorgan, D-N.D. And even
some Republicans raised constitutional objections and worried that
such a finding would set a precedent that could encourage
congressional majorities to use impeachment as a political weapon.
</P>
<P>
   A censure resolution could well run into the same kind of
buzzsaw. The language will have to be tough enough to attract
Republicans and yet not so tough that it scares off Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   But the same Republicans who have doubts about the
constitutionality of the finding of facts, object to censure. And
there are also Republicans who see a censure measure as little more
than a shield to protect Democrats who have spent years trying to
shed the images of the 60s and convince voters that they too
believe in family values.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Appell, a Republican poltical strategist, said he thought
that even though Americans in the short term want the trial of the
president to be over, votes to acquit Clinton would have long-term
political consequences for the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to be in such denial that the president of the
United States committed perjury and obstruction of justice,' he
said, ``then we're going to hang it around your neck for all of
eternity. From now on the Democratic Party is the party of perjury
and obstruction of justice.'' As an afterthought he quipped: ``They
are already the party of sex. That's nothing new.''
</P>
<P>
   Prepared for just such a debate and certain from the polls that
they can carry the majority of Americans with them, Democrats can
already see their counter-argument. ``The Republicans are the party
of prying into your personal lives,'' said Sen. Tom Harkin, D-Iowa.
``Your privacy will never be protected by Republicans.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
