<HEADER>
A2365 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-HOUSTON-VS.-LA-HN     02-04 1061
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-HOUSTON-VS.-LA-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN McCLAIN  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
HONOLULU _ A survey of 25 Pro Bowl players shows that Houston is an
overwhelming favorite over Los Angeles for the 32nd NFL franchise.
<TEXT>
<P>
   A vote taken at AFC and NFC practices this week turned out 22-3
in favor of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner Paul Tagliabue said last week at the Super Bowl
that owners hope to pick between Houston and Los Angeles at their
spring meetings in March.
</P>
<P>
   Players don't have a vote, which is too bad for Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fans in Houston seem to be itching for another team,'' San
Francisco 49ers receiver Jerry Rice said. ``They want a team they
can support.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest with you, I think it would be a little more
difficult in Los Angeles. LA's more relaxed. There are so many
things to do there. I don't think the fans in Los Angeles are as
supportive as Houston.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston has a potential owner in Bob McNair. Houston has $200
million in public money. A retractable-roof stadium is ready to be
built. All McNair needs is for the owners to vote for Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Houston needs a team,'' Dallas Cowboys guard Nate Newton said.
``Houston's on the move. They're ready to build a new stadium. With
the proper stadium and an owner who's going to cater to the fans, I
think things should work in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Houston has everything ready to go, why not take advantage
of it? The people in Houston proved they'd support a team. If an
owner will share a little love, they'll support him.''
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles is expected to get the team over Houston because it
is the country's second-largest television market. Houston is 11th.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's never worked,'' Newton said about giving the franchise
to Los Angeles because of its television market. ``It didn't work
for the Raiders or Rams. The Raiders left. The Rams left.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the league should go where it works. And it's proven
that it'll work in Houston.''
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles has two groups competing for ownership. It doesn't
have public money.
</P>
<P>
   Oakland Raiders owner Al Davis has a lawsuit pending about
whether he owns the rights to the Los Angeles market. Davis hopes
to return to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a layman here, but I assume that the bigwigs recognize LA
as a place that ought to have a team,'' 49ers quarterback Steve
Young said. ``I would think every effort would be made to put a
team in Los Angeles, because it's a money game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, it's not like the Olympics. Hopefully, it'll be
based on merit. If it's based on merit, Houston maybe should get
it. From things I hear in the wind, they (the league) want $1
billion or more (for the stadium and expansion fee).
</P>
<P>
   ``In LA, who knows? But if someone in LA comes up with a good
plan, I think that's probably where they'll go.''
</P>
<P>
   The players are aware of what Houston has done to try to get an
expansion franchise to replace the Oilers, who moved to Nashville,
Tenn., after the 1996 season. The Oilers officially become the
Tennessee Titans after Sunday's Pro Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to see Houston get it,'' said New York Giants
defensive end Michael Strahan, who played at Texas Southern.
``Houston has great fans. Houston has everything set up and ready
to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, Los Angeles is a bigger television market, but there's
more to it than television market. Houston has some of the greatest
fans in the world. I think it should matter how many people are in
the stands. Houston deserves another team. I think Texas deserves
another team. California already has three teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Seattle Seahawks defensive end Michael Sinclair, who grew up in
Beaumont, thinks the league understands that Houston let the Oilers
go because of owner Bud Adams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they were showing disrespect for the owner, not the
team,'' Sinclair said. ``It was frustration with the owner, and the
team got caught in the crossfire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to see Houston get another team. It's prepped and
ready to go. Houston's got such a great fan base. I remember when
the Astrodome used to be packed. And Houston's a better place than
Los Angeles as far as quality of living.
</P>
<P>
   ``Houston wants the NFL. I just hope the NFL wants Houston.''
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker Chad Brown, Sinclair's teammate with the Seahawks,
sides with Houston. When he played for Pittsburgh, Brown performed
in front of sold-out crowds in the Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm from Los Angeles, and there's a reason LA lost teams,''
Brown said. ``There's just so much going on in LA. There are so
many interests other than football. I think the attitude in LA is,
`Well, we can watch it on TV if we want to watch it at all.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the league should look at it from a people aspect, not
just the size of the television market. Houston was a good place to
play. The stadium was full, and the fans were really loud. I think
Houston probably deserves a franchise a little more than LA.
</P>
<P>
   ``If LA gets the team, they'd better do a great marketing job.
They'd better come up with some really cool shirts. It's a tough
sell in LA because of all the competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota Vikings defensive tackle John Randle grew up in Hearne
and played at Texas A&AMP;I, now known as Texas A&AMP;M-Kingsville. He
resides in Houston in the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it should definitely be Houston,'' Randle said. ``I
think Houston deserves another team. Houston just isn't the same
without the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up in Texas, and I was a fan of the Houston Oilers. For
Houston to not have a team takes away some of the flair and pride
of Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona Cardinals cornerback Aeneas Williams grew up in
Louisiana and played at Southern University. He has family in
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're both very important markets. I don't think it's fair
to single one out, because both are deserving of teams,'' Williams
said. ``But California already has three teams, and Texas has one,
so maybe Houston should get it.''
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee running back Eddie George played his first season in
Houston and was named NFL Offensive Rookie of the Year. He never
wanted to leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``I liked Houston a lot because it's a great city,'' George
said. ``The fan support was great for a long time. I used to watch
the `House of Pain' days on television.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unfortunate that we left. I think Houston deserves
another team, and I hope you get one.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
