<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 20:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2369 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-STEVENS-TEX     02-04 1197
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-STEVENS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEVENS PICKS A WINNER OVER SUPER BOWL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY MOSS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Gary Stevens was in Miami last weekend and
had tickets to the Super Bowl. But instead of attending the game,
he returned home to California to ride General Challenge in a
stakes race at Santa Anita.
</P>
<P>
   History will decide if it was a wise decision. Early returns
look encouraging.
</P>
<P>
   At about the same time Denver was putting away Atlanta, General
Challenge was running away with the Santa Catalina Stakes for
3-year-olds by three lengths, and is now undefeated in three
starts. The gelding is among a cluster of Kentucky Derby contenders
in the stable of trainer Bob Baffert, who also saddled the past two
Derby winners.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens had changed his travel schedule two weeks earlier, after
sitting atop General Challenge at Santa Anita for an awesome
morning workout.
</P>
<P>
   ``After I worked him, I didn't want to miss a horse of this
caliber to watch a football game,'' Stevens explained.
</P>
<P>
   So after Stevens ran third on Baffert-trained Silver Charm on
Saturday in the Donn Handicap at Gulfstream Park in suburban Miami,
he hopped a flight back to Los Angeles while Baffert stayed behind
for the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's so talented and I have so much confidence in him that I
didn't have any question that he was the best horse in the race,''
Stevens said. ``We just wanted to teach him something, and to me,
mentally, he passed all of the tests. It's just a matter now of
getting him prepared for the big dances.''
</P>
<P>
   The first big dance is the Santa Anita Derby on April 3. The
ultimate goal is the senior prom: the May 1 Kentucky Derby.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert said he is loathe to rank his 3-year-olds, then
mentioned that General Meeting probably is no better than third
best in his current Derby pecking order. He already has the early
favorite in Exploit, another unbeaten colt, who runs tomorrow in
the San Vicente Stakes. He has a promising colt named Prime Timber.
His two best fillies, champion-to-be Silverbulletday and Excellent
Meeting, often run faster times than colts.
</P>
<P>
   That pecking order isn't set in stone, though. Just look at last
year. Indian Charlie was the darling of the Baffert barn heading
into Derby week, but his ``other'' horse, Real Quiet, came within a
whisker of sweeping the Triple Crown.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I know is I get them ready for the Kentucky Derby,'' said
Baffert. ``And when they turn for home, the good Lord will take
over.''
</P>
<P>
   For choosing General Challenge instead of football, Stevens
earned a check of $6,390, or 10 percent of the owner's share of the
purse. That isn't much more than the illegal street value of a few
choice Super Bowl tickets. But obviously, Stevens is thinking ahead
a few months.
Spotlight
Unbeaten gelding needs smarts to go with speed
Temperence Time, a son of 1980 3-year-old champion Temperence Hill,
vaulted onto the list of early Derby prospects with an impressive
victory Saturday in Oaklawn Park's Dixieland Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   But his trainer, Kenny Smith, knows too much about his
four-for-four gelding to start dreaming yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got tons of talent, he's definitely a runner,'' Smith
said. ``But he's been a challenge, let me put it that way. His main
problem is, he's not as smart as he needs to be. You never know
what the hell he's going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   At Oaklawn in December, jockey Tim Doocy was aboard Temperence
Time for a workout when the horse inexplicably made a beeline for
the outside rail. Doocy was tossed to the dirt, and as he lay face
down, he wondered to himself where his misbehaving mount had gone.
Doocy quickly got his answer: Temperence Time stepped on his back.
</P>
<P>
   ``The horse walked all over him,'' Smith recalled with a
chuckle.
</P>
<P>
   Thankfully, Temperence Time showed better judgment in the
Dixieland. He rated just behind the leaders for the first time in
his career before drawing away to a 41/4 length victory. His next
start, said Smith, will be in Oaklawn's one-mile Southwest Stakes
on Feb. 27.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully he won't run out to the outside rail, but who
knows?'' Smith said. ``This is the time of year he's got to step
up. If he'll improve, maybe he can go on and be something special,
because he's got a lot of potential. But it's a slow process.''
NO BLUES FOR FOLSOM Former Dallas mayor and Lone Star Park investor
Bob Folsom owns a minority interest in Puerto Madero, upset winner
over Silver Charm in the Donn Handicap. Folsom didn't attend the
race. He watched on TV. And he said he probably won't make the
overseas flight for the 5-year-old's next scheduled appearance in
the March 28 Dubai World Cup, now a $5 million race. Eddie D.
CLOSING IN Eddie Delahoussaye needs two more victories to become
the 14th North American jockey to record 6,000 victories.
Delahoussaye, 47, will join Bill Shoemaker, Laffit Pincay Jr., Pat
Day, David Gall, Angel Cordero Jr., Jorge Velasquez, Chris
McCarron, Sandy Hawley, Russell Baze, Larry Snyder, Carl
Gambardella, Earlie Fires and John Longden. ON THE TUBE Exploit's
1999 debut tomorrow in Santa Anita's San Vicente Stakes can be
viewed on ESPN from 3:30 to 4:30 p.m. as part of the network's
``Road to the Triple Crown Series.'' A NEW TWIST Man-bites-dog
story: Free House is in great shape for Sunday's San Antonio
Handicap at Santa Anita, but his trainer is hurt. Paco Gonzalez,
53, went down in a training accident Wednesday morning while
galloping Free House's younger brother and suffered a fractured
collarbone. INJURY REPORT Out of action: Arrested Dreams and Bet Me
Best. Once-beaten Arrested Dreams, Lone Star's champion
thoroughbred 2-year-old filly of 1998, is to undergo arthroscopic
surgery in Kentucky on both knees and will miss most of the rest of
the year. Bet Me Best came out of his victory in Sunday's Hutcheson
Stakes at Gulfstream with a minor bone chip in his right knee and
will be sidelined until late summer. The seven-furlong Hutcheson
was undefeated Bet Me Best's first race for owners Art and Jack
Preston of Houston, and Bill Casner of Southlake, who purchased him
privately. PASSING OF A LEGEND Paul Mellon's death Monday night at
91 will be felt worldwide in economic and philanthrophic circles,
but breeding and racing was one of the billionaire's lifelong
passions. He trimmed his thoroughbred holdings in recent years, but
his Rokeby Stable was an international force for decades, and in
1993 he got a long-awaited and richly deserved Kentucky Derby
victory with Sea Hero. COMEBACK REPORT Jockey Chris Antley, who
hadn't ridden in 16 months due to weight problems, returned
Wednesday at Santa Anita, and one of his two mounts was
disqualified for interference. Mike Smith, riding again at
Gulfstream Park after missing five months with fractured vertebrae,
won his first race of the year Wednesday in his fourth mount. HE'S
BAAAACK Injury-prone Silver Goblin is ready to run again at Oaklawn
Park. The 8-year-old gelding, who has won more than $1 million and
finished second to Cigar in the 1995 Oaklawn Handicap, hasn't
started since chipping a bone in his right ankle last summer at
Lone Star Park and undergoing surgery.
</P>
</TEXT>
