<HEADLINE>
TECH'S SHARP CLOSES IN ON MILESTONE VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Sometime this month, barring cataclysmic
events yet unforeseen, Texas Tech coach Marsha Sharp will record
her 400th victory.
</P>
<P>
   In her 17th year guiding the Lady Raiders' excellent program,
Sharp stands 395-127 coming off 1998 Big 12 coach of the year
honors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reckon we can get five more?'' Sharp queried.
</P>
<P>
   If the 10th-ranked Lady Raiders (19-2, 8-1) can hold their own
in the last days of playing in leaky Lubbock Municipal Coliseum,
odds are good they indeed can get five more.
</P>
<P>
   Tech turned into the eight-game finishing stretch Saturday by
knocking off Baylor, the first of five games at home in the second
half of conference play, after winning four of five road games in
the first half. After a much-needed mid-week bye, the Lady Raiders
play their first of three roadies at Texas tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   The defending Big 12 champions have been one of the new league's
banner programs. And like all good programs, have proven successful
on the road. Boosted by a remarkable 7-1 road record last season,
Tech has won 17 of 23 away games since the Big 12's inception.
</P>
<P>
   That hasn't been easy _ as this season's two-point victories at
Baylor and Oklahoma and a three-point win at Oklahoma State attest.
Certainly not as easy as winning on the road was in the old
Southwest Conference for at least one reason _ proximity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took for granted how easy travel was in the old SWC,''
Sharp said. ``And we were at more of a disadvantage than anyone
else if you think about it. But it doesn't even compare to what we
face in the Big 12. It seems to me like we've been playing Big 12
games for a solid year. It's really a brutal scenario.''
</P>
<P>
   Tech has to be favored then to win its second consecutive
regular-season title for two reasons _ superior depth and the
remaining schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa State (15-3, 7-1) still has to play at Nebraska, Kansas
State, Kansas and Baylor. Kansas (16-6, 6-3), like Tech, gets a
second-half schedule break with remaining road games at Missouri,
Oklahoma State and Kansas State _ none being arduous trips for the
Jayhawks, who lost first-half games at ISU, Nebraska and Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Tech's second-half schedule, however, does pose a rugged finish
that could send the Lady Raiders into the Big 12 tournament
gasping. They're at Nebraska on a Sunday, at Colorado on a
Wednesday, then finish with the Longhorns on the last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``That last week is scary,'' Sharp said. ``Three tough games in
seven days, two long trips. Then we turn around and leave on Monday
for the conference tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of variables involved, but sometimes road
games are more mentally exhausting than physically. I know I feel
older than I am. But then of course, I started doing this when I
was 16, right?'' \Ntagtop:Mike Jones, (817) 390-7760
Texas' Clay no longer just a 3-point bomber
Will Clay was recruited to Texas to fit into former coach Tom
Penders' free-wheeling offense that appeared perfectly suited to
his style. In two years at San Jacinto JC, Clay set a school record
with 112 three-pointers in his freshman season and finished by
setting a career mark of 205 long-range bombs.
</P>
<P>
   This season in a more strict system, Clay's shot has deserted
him. He's connected on only 27 of 100 from beyond the arc, three of
31 in nine Big 12 games. But the Bryan native apparently has shaken
the frustration of dealing with the slump and given indication that
he's going to provide a boost for the Longhorns down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   He had 20 key points in victories over Massachusetts and Texas
A&AMP;M.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here, we've got guys who can score. So it's not a big thing
for me to score,'' Clay said. ``So, I'm saying how can I make
myself respected on this team? And it's by playing defense, taking
the ball to the hole, handling the rock and taking good shots when
I'm open. And that's the role I'm going to take.''
</P>
<P>
   UT coach Rick Barnes left him little choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him, `If you want to be a shooter, my job's easy.
You're either making them and you play or you're missing them and
you sit. Or, you can decide you want to be a player and play
defense, rebound and realize you've got some pretty good guys
inside who if you get the ball to are going to get double-teamed
and you'll get all the shots you want.'
</P>
<P>
   ``And Will is starting doing all those things.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people have called and said if coach Penders was here
it would be different,'' Clay said. ``But I tell them coach Penders
is not here, I'm happy where I am. We're winning, and I feel like
everything else will fall into place.''
EDDIE'S BAFFLED Oklahoma State (16-5, 7-2) has won three in a row
and five of six heading into tomorrow night's crucial battle at
Oklahoma (15-7, 6-3). But the Cowboys shot over 50 percent on
Tuesday against Iowa State for the first time since Dec. 22 and
continue to puzzle coach Eddie Sutton.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've played the easiest part of our schedule,'' Sutton
proclaimed. ``The rest of our games are winnable, but they're also
losable. Our two best players \RAdrian Peterson, Desmond Mason\S
have been inconsistent, and we're not playing as well as we should
as a team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's got me baffled. I don't know why. It's been a strange
episode all year.'' KELVIN'S BUMFUZZLED Oklahoma meanwhile, escaped
Baylor on Wednesday with a 59-58 victory, a win that left Sooners
coach Kelvin Sampson in straits to Sutton's over his team's lapses
in offense. Baylor went on a 15-1 run to overtake OU (55-54) with
1:23 to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard an old football coach once use the word
`bumfuzzled','' Sampson recalled. ``I think that's the way I am
now. I'm bumfuzzled.'' NO PLACE LIKE, WHERE? Baylor's Lady Bears
won their first Big 12 road game Wednesday at Texas A&AMP;M, where you
can totally disregard home-court advantage. The Aggies' first-year
coach Peggie Gillom's team (7-12, 2-7) is now 0-4 in conference
games and 2-8 overall in A&AMP;M's shiny new Reed Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great arena, but not for us,'' Gillom said.
</P>
<P>
   Which is good news for tomorrow's visitor. Oklahoma (9-10, 3-6)
is winless in seven road games, 0-4 on the Big 12 road and just
nixed one jinx. Wednesday's 71-69 victory against Texas was their
first in six games decided by two or fewer points. A PALACE ON THE
PLAINS This thought after touring in-progress United Spirit Arena
in Lubbock last week.
</P>
<P>
   Reed Arena is a very nice facility. But because of the seating
configuration, it strikes me as a multi-purpose arena where
basketball is played. Tech's new facility is a basketball arena
where other events can be held. Spectators are going to love this
place and so will the resident teams. Players' lounges include a
hot-tub in addition to therapeutic whirlpools. Individual dressing
areas for the women's team have in-place hair dryers.
</P>
<P>
   And the huge media workroom will feature individual phone lines
and hookups that tap into the university's on-line service.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
