<SLUG> BC-BKC-TEXASTECH-MALONE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED RAIDERS ON THE WAY BACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUBBOCK, Texas _ Just what impact Moses Malone Jr. will have on
Texas Tech's basketball program will be determined in seasons to
come.
</P>
<P>
   But there has already been at least one positive spin as a
result of the January transfer of the 6-foot-3 shooting guard with
the famous basketball lineage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly attracted a lot of media attention,'' Red Raiders
coach James Dickey said.
</P>
<P>
   The positive attention brought by Malone's transfer from the
University of Houston seemed to be sorely needed. Dickey's program
has existed under a cloud since the Big 12 tournament in March
1997, when the NCAA declared two players were wrongly certified as
eligible and the university pulled a 19-9 team from consideration
for an NCAA Tournament berth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Moses is definitely a name and the fact that he went to Tech
definitely helps the program,'' said Mike Kunstadt, one of the
state's recognized basketball recruiting experts and publisher of
``Texas Hoops'' newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   ``He certainly gives them a high-profile player. And Tech has
got to start getting the kinds of kids they were getting before
this cloud came over the program. That whole thing was their
undoing. And the thing of it was, the coaches weren't at fault.
They just had to pay the consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   The question now becomes whether Dickey can revitalize a program
that won 30 games and advanced to the 1996 NCAA Tournament round of
Sweet 16 and would have made another appearance in '97 if not for a
since-rescinded Big 12 rule that demanded forfeiture of games in
which ineligible players participated.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question in my mind that James is the guy who can
get us back on top in the Big 12,'' Tech athletic director Gerald
Myers said. ``He's the same coach he was in 1996. He's an
outstanding recruiter. And we're going to have one of the most
outstanding on-campus facilities in the country \Rby next season\S.
So I have no doubt that he's going to get this program turned
around.
</P>
<P>
   ``James is in a secure position. Heck yeah, he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Dickey is operating with 11 scholarships this season, 11 next
season and 10 the year after before returning to full strength
(13). But the NCAA issued no other sanctions on the program after
the eligibility inquiry. And Malone said it was Dickey's reputation
as a coach who can develop a player's all-around game that brought
him to Tech, where he is paying his own way until a scholarship
comes open for next fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach Dickey is basically the reason why I came,'' said
Malone, who says he also considered TCU, George Washington and
Miami. ``He's a great coach and a great guy who can help me succeed
in my personal goals. Someone who can make me a better player, who
can work on all aspects of my game and help make me a better
person.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good about the future of the program here. If I didn't,
I wouldn't have come.''
</P>
<P>
   Such things are conjecture, but Dickey and others say Tech lost
several high-profile players while the NCAA took the university's
athletic program apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``That really, really hurt them,'' Kunstadt said.
``\RDuncanville's\S Chris Owens and \RDallas Kimball's\S Jeryl
Sasser are only two players that immediately come to mind who
probably would have gone to Tech if not for the investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Has Tech recovered? The Raiders lost prized recruit Chris Ogden
of nearby Seminole to Texas in November, though Ogden said his
desire to leave the area was almost equal to his attraction to
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' Dickey said with a wry smile. ``At least people can't
use \Rthe investigation\S against us anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   The uncertainty of Tech's eventual penalty also played a factor
in center Tony Battie's decision to enter the NBA draft in the
spring of 1997, rather than play his final year. Battie's presence
alone almost certainly would have prevented the Raiders' slide to
13-14 last season.
</P>
<P>
   This season, injuries have restricted Dickey's rebuilding
efforts. But he says, and history testifies, that junior-college
players blossom in their second season. Dickey brought in five last
fall, two of whom have two more years of eligibility after this
one.
</P>
<P>
   Though Malone is far from a polished player, he is a natural
scorer, which is something Dickey sorely needs.
</P>
<P>
   Dickey says he is as committed as he's ever been.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited about the future,'' he said. ``The arena is going
to be outstanding and the league is tremendous in terms of
exposure. We're going to have to be very careful in selecting our
players the next two years. What we've got to do is get back the
eye of the tiger that we had through 1997.''
</P>
</TEXT>
