<HEADER>
A2372 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-TRIAL-ART-2TA     02-04 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-TRIAL-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE VOTES AGAINST CALLING LEWINSKY TO TESTIFY IN PERSON 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also IMPEACH, IMPEACH-ASSESS, IMPEACH-SCENE, IMPEACH-MANAGERS,
IMPEACH-LEWINSKY, IMPEACH-REPUBS) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By R.W. APPLE Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After voting by more than two-to-one not to call
Monica Lewinsky to testify in person at President Clinton's
impeachment trial, the Senate on Thursday approved by a narrower
margin a plan to show ``all or parts'' of her videotaped deposition
during floor arguments on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   That will give the nation its first chance to see and hear her
own account of the illicit affair with Clinton that led to his
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   On the question of taking testimony from Ms. Lewinsky, the vote
was 70-30 against doing so. The Republicans split almost evenly,
with 30 favoring such testimony and 25 opposing it. Geographically,
the ``no'' votes were widely distributed, with a dozen from the
West, five from New England and six from the South. Nor was there
any clearly discernible ideological pattern.
</P>
<P>
   ``Recognizing reality,'' as Rep. Bill McCollum, R-Fla., put it,
the House prosecutors or ``managers'' did not even attempt to call
other witnesses. Nor did the White House ask that any of its own be
called.
</P>
<P>
   The other important vote, 62-38, came on the question of using
videotapes in the trial. It was for the most part a party-line
vote, with nine Democrats, mostly self-described mavericks, joining
the Republicans, and two New England Republicans _ Sens. James
Jeffords of Vermont and Olympia Snowe of Maine, who are both much
more liberal than their party _ joining the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate will hear closing arguments from House prosecutors
and White House counsel on Monday. Sen. Trent Lott of Mississippi,
the majority leader, said he and his colleagues would begin their
deliberations Tuesday, with the vote on the two articles of
impeachment on Thursday or Friday.
</P>
<P>
   By eliminating the possibility of calling Ms. Lewinsky or any
other witnesses, and by pulling back from the idea of a ``finding
of fact'' that would have accused Clinton of wrongdoing without
finding him guilty, the lawmakers removed two major obstacles to
the early conclusion to a trial that many on Capitol Hill and in
the country at large have grown weary of.
</P>
<P>
   There was a marked air of anti-climax in the chamber on
Thursday. Little ardor or urgency marked the speeches, which did
not come close to filling the time allotted. But in a rare moment
of spontaneity in a carefully scripted trial, a spectator was
arrested and hustled away after he stood in the Senate gallery and
shouted, ``God almighty, take the vote and get it over with.'' He
was identified by the Capitol police as Richard D. Llamas, 48, of
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Six roll-call votes, four of them procedural or largely
symbolic, produced a mixed verdict for the White House, which had
feared more than anything else a subpoena forcing Ms. Lewinsky to
testify in the well of the Senate. But even showing the videotape
of her deposition, taken on Monday, was described by one
presidential lawyer, Gregory B. Craig, as certain to ``add to the
agony, to the embarrassment, and to the humiliation'' already
suffered by Clinton and his family.
</P>
<P>
   There are ``no bombshells'' and ``no explosions'' in the
videotapes, Craig assured the senators.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican prosecutors will use the tapes in describing and
analyzing the deposition of Ms. Lewinsky as well as that of Vernon
Jordan, Clinton's closest confidant, who testified Tuesday, and
that of Sidney Blumenthal, a White House aide, who testified on
Wednesday. The White House will also have the opportunity to use
the tapes in its rebuttal.
</P>
<P>
   ``This would be a duel of snippets and excerpts,'' Craig said in
opposing the use of any portion of the videotapes during the trial.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors sought to show that the depositions changed the
case. But only Rep. Asa Hutchinson of Arkansas, who questioned
Jordan, went into specifics. He said that Jordan had testified on a
number of points that he said demonstrated more clearly then before
that Clinton had instigated and overseen the search for a job for
Ms. Lewinsky in New York.
</P>
<P>
   That search is seen by the Republicans as part of a cover-up.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchinson also said, as previously reported, that Jordan had
changed his story about a breakfast he had with Ms. Lewinsky on
Dec. 31, 1997, at the Park Hyatt Hotel here. Previously, he said he
had no memory of it.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Hutchinson said, he not only confirmed that the
meeting had taken place but confirmed that Ms. Lewinsky had talked
to him about copies of some of her notes to the president she was
keeping at her apartment. Ms. Lewinsky has testified that Jordan
told her to go back and make sure they were not there, but
Hutchinson did not mention that point in his presentation. Jordan
reportedly told prosecutors on Tuesday that he did not instruct her
to throw away notes.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ed Bryant, R-Tenn., who deposed Ms. Lewinsky, conceded that
she had been ``very guarded in each response and almost
protective,'' making it hard to develop new evidence in the
deposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her testimony is clearly tinted and some might even say
tainted,'' Bryant said, ``by a mixture of her continued admiration
for the president, her desire to protect him and her own personal
views of right and wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. James Rogan of California, who deposed Blumenthal, made
much of the fact that Blumenthal had said flatly that Clinton had
lied to him about the nature of the Lewinsky affair. He asserted
that Blumenthal had ``shed some incredible new light'' on the case,
but he did not make its nature clear.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Seemingly frustrated by the managers' inability to build support
for their case in the Senate, Rogan at one point aimed an unusually
sharp dart at his audience. Noting that senators had the
opportunity to view the tapes in a secure room, he said: ``If one
senator has failed to personally sit through this deposition and
every deposition, that senator is not equipped to render a verdict
on the impeachment trial of the president of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   McCollum also sounded nettled, lecturing the senators on what he
called their ``moral obligation'' to call Ms. Lewinsky as a
witness.
</P>
<P>
   In his portion of the argument, Rep. Lindsey Graham of South
Carolina reassured the Senate that the managers would respect the
Senate's dignity if they were able to call Ms. Lewinsky to testify
in person.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give us this witness,'' Graham pleaded. ``We will do it in a
professional manner. We will focus on the obstruction. We will try
to do it in a way not to demean the Senate. And we will try to do
it in a way not to demean Ms. Lewinsky.''
</P>
<P>
   Craig did not even deign to reply to the managers' specific
points. Instead, he argued that the Senate and the nation had
already heard and seen enough without releasing the videotapes of
the three witnesses' testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Putting them into the trial record and using them in Saturday's
session, he argued, would mean that ``the pictures, the voices and
the words on these tapes would flow directly and irreversibly into
the life of the nation.'' He cited a poll published in The New York
Times on Wednesday showing that three-quarters of the public did
not want the videotapes released.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our view,'' Craig said, ``the Senate has leaned over
backwards to accommodate the managers. We believe that it is time
for the Senate to say that it's time to vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Sen. Tom Daschle of South Dakota, the minority leader,
moved that the Senate do exactly that. But the Republicans turned
back his effort on a near-party-line vote, just as they had
rejected an effort last week by Sen. Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va., to
dismiss the charges.
</P>
<P>
   When both Craig and the managers completed their arguments well
before time ran out, Lott seemed momentarily at a loss as to how to
proceed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had expected that this would take a little bit longer,'' he
said, and the senators laughed, something they have not done very
often lately.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
