s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-SENIORITY-$ADV07-     02-04 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-SENIORITY-$ADV07-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.M.)  
 WHY ROLL THE DICE?  
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, FEB. 7)
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By FRED BROCK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the politicians and lobbyists in Washington strive to score
political or ideological points in the Social Security debate, they
should be aware that people like Edith Chvala are watching them.
Like some economists, she questions the wisdom of staking Social
Security funds on the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Chvala, 75, lives alone in a mobile home seven miles
southeast of Silver City, N.M., on $703 a month _ $542 from Social
Security and $161 from a pension.
</P>
<P>
   She jokes about being poor, but is quick to point out that she
is blessed with good health. Many older people are in worse
financial shape, she says, often because they are faced with large
prescription bills not covered by Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   As she watches the struggle over Social Security, Ms. Chvala has
come to at least one conclusion: She is not excited about proposals
that would put a portion of the funds, now invested in Treasury
securities, into the stock market _ whether it's President
Clinton's plan for the government to invest the money or the
Republicans' notion of allowing individuals to invest part of their
Social Security tax payments themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a gambler,'' she said. ``It seems like they want to
gamble with our retirement money.''
</P>
<P>
   If Ms. Chvala is cool to the ideas, so is L. Douglas Lee, chief
economist at HSBC Securities in Washington. Unlike many of his Wall
Street brethren, he has reservations about privatization, despite
the billions of dollars it would pump into the stock market. And he
is one of a number of economists who believes that low-ball
economic projections and assumptions have led to erroneous
conclusions that the Social Security system must be ``saved'' or
``fixed.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee, who is 51, has nothing per se against investing retirement
funds in the stock market. But he points out that the Social
Security system is more than a retirement program, with features
like benefits for the disabled, or for dependent children after the
death of their working parent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the government should fund the social welfare aspects
of Social Security,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Privatizing Social Security, he said, won't increase the overall
resources of the economy, but merely shift them around. And it
could drive up interest rates by decreasing the money available to
the Treasury, forcing it to borrow more in the private sector.
</P>
<P>
   Lee says the conventional wisdom that the current system faces
bankruptcy is ``a little silly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Economic forecasts are wrong a large part of the time,'' he
said. ``We have to be very careful about making major policy
decisions based on projections, especially when other projections,
which are very reasonable, show a very different outcome.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said that putting part of the budget surplus into Social
Security, in effect reducing the federal debt, as President Clinton
has proposed, would build the nation's resources. That would likely
bring economic growth, which would increase payments into the
Social Security fund, he said. He thinks the Republican plan to cut
taxes would only encourage consumption.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing we can point to over the last few years that has
had a positive effect on savings has been to reduce the federal
deficit and move into surplus,'' he said. ``This produces growth,
and that's what's going to be needed in order to meet the promises
that have been made to future retirees.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, decisions about Social Security will have direct
effects on real lives of real people _ like Ms. Chvala.
</P>
<P>
   A native of Germany, she came to the United States in 1930, when
she was 7. She grew up in New York, living in Queens and then
Sheepshead Bay, Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   She married in 1945 and followed her husband, a construction
worker, around the Northeast. In 1970, they moved to Buffalo, where
she worked as a nurse's aide for 20 years. That job was the source
of her small pension. The couple divorced in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   At the urging of a son, she moved to New Mexico in 1990, when
she was 67. She used her savings to buy a mobile home and parked it
rent-free on her son's property. The son later divorced and moved
to Arizona, but his former wife allowed Ms. Chvala to stay.
</P>
<P>
   Four times a week, Ms. Chvala drives her 1985 Chevy Blazer to
Western New Mexico University in Silver City, where she swims and
is a volunteer at the school's museum.
</P>
<P>
   She thinks she might qualify for some sort of welfare, but would
rather get by without it, as Social Security lets her do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like my independence,'' she said. ``I don't want to ever
have to live with my children. I am so thankful for my health. My
plan is to just drop dead when the time comes.'' And she would
rather that politicians keep their hands off Social Security in the
meantime.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
