<HEADER>
A2375 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-SMART-REARDOORS-A     02-04 0574
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-SMART-REARDOORS-ART-$ADV07-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SUICIDE DOORS' FIND NEW LIFE IN SAFER FORMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, FEB. 7) 
(af) 
 By MICHELLE KREBS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Car doors hinged at the rear, like the small third door of
Saturn coupes and the rear access doors of many long-cab pickups,
have traditionally been known as ``suicide doors'' among car buffs.
</P>
<P>
   While this design is virtually as old as the closed-cabin car,
the origin of this description is unclear. But it no doubt had
something to do with the dangers posed by doors that could fly open
if a passenger accidentally pulled on the lever-like door handles
of the time.
</P>
<P>
   And if the front-opening door went ajar while the car was
moving, wind could catch the door and fling it back, possibly
throwing the passenger out of the cabin.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, if a parked car with suicide doors was sideswiped
while an occupant was getting out, that person could be pinned
between the door and the body; in a similar accident involving a
front-hinged door, the door would be more likely to be sheared off.
</P>
<P>
   Rear-hinged doors _ often those in back, though sometimes in the
front _ were particularly popular in the 1930s, when they showed up
on cars from everyday Fords and Fiats to elite Bugattis and
Rolls-Royces. The doors made it easier for women in dresses to get
out gracefully, and auto designers liked being able to place the
door handles and hinges wherever they wished.
</P>
<P>
   A car with rounded doors or a steeply raked windshield could
have its front doors hinged on the ``B'' pillar _ the support
between the front and rear doors _ more easily than on the ``A''
pillar attached to the windshield.
</P>
<P>
   By the 1960s, suicide doors had pretty much faded away.
Exceptions included the squared-off Lincoln Continentals of 1961-67
and four-door Thunderbirds of 1967-69.
</P>
<P>
   Although it has a similar look when open, Saturn's third door is
different from those old designs in key ways. Like the access doors
of pickups, the Saturn's rear door cannot be opened unless the
front door is open; otherwise, the release is not exposed.
</P>
<P>
   The Saturn's latches, like those of all vehicles, undergo
rigorous testing and must meet federal standards, said Tim Hurd, a
spokesman for the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration.
Indeed, Saturn uses interlocking latches that attach to the front
door and to the body, said Beth Miakinin, chief engineer of the
Saturn S-Series.
</P>
<P>
   Recognizing that people might recall old-time suicide doors when
looking at the Saturn, Ms. Miakinin said the engineering goal was
to make the three-door Saturn as safe as, if not safer than, a
regular coupe by every standard.
</P>
<P>
   To insure that the third door held up in side impacts, a beam,
foam padding and a piece of sheet metal pleated like an accordion
were installed to absorb crash energy. Because there is no B
pillar, the rear door was designed with hefty pieces of sheet metal
to provide added strength, and reinforcements were added to the
rear door hinge.
</P>
<P>
   While the safety agency has not yet crash-tested the three-door
model, Saturn's engineers said they were confident it would measure
up to the two-door equivalent.
</P>
<P>
   Hurd said his agency had not received complaints about any
rear-access door now on the market. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
