<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSEUM-MUMMY05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlantans giving money for mummies
 &HT;    By Catherine Fox
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The first call came straight from the heart.
</P>
<P>
   Her child had been enthralled with the mummies on a class trip
to the Michael C. Carlos Museum, so an Atlanta mom, who read of the
museum's plea for funds needed to acquire a first-class collection
of ancient Egyptian mummies and coffins, offered to pitch in $100.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Carlos director Tony Hirschel says he's received
about a dozen pledges, ranging from very small amounts up to
$100,000. The contributors want to remain anonymous, and Hirschel
declined to release the total amount of Thursday's pledges.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not over yet,'' he cautions. But time is running out. The
Carlos has until the end of today to finish raising $2 million
needed for the purchase. After that, other institutions will be
free to compete.
</P>
<P>
   Late Thursday, Hirschel was guardedly optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very encouraging to get all these calls, and it's
wonderful to see the people of Atlanta responding to an initiative
that could mean so much to the city.''
</P>
<P>
   Each phone call puts him closer to securing the 80 artifacts,
including bronzes, clay figurines, pottery, basketry, relief
fragments and canopic jars (containing the mummy entrails). The
collection is housed in a museum in Niagara Falls, Ontario, where
it has been since the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   The mummies and coffins, spanning 1000 B.C to the second century
A.D., are the most important artifacts in the collection, which was
assembled in the mid-19th century. Egyptologists in Milwaukee and
Boston agreed that their acquisition would put the Carlos on par
with museums like the Metropolitan in New York and the Museum of
Fine Arts, Boston.
</P>
<P>
   What about Emory University itself? Its endowment, $4.1 billion
as of Aug. 31, ranks sixth among American universities. Couldn't it
kick in or even loan its museum the money?
</P>
<P>
   ``Emory's resources are designated and allocated through a
deliberate and thoughtful process,'' says William H. Fox, senior
vice president for institutional advancement. ``Undesignated or
unallocated resources are therefore not readily available. When an
exciting opportunity such as this collection comes to our
attention, we must seek new funding through fund-raising.''
</P>
<P>
   Says Hirschel, ``This is a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity, and
we need to act immediately if we are to take advantage of it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
