A2378 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BISHER-COLUMN05-COX     02-04 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BISHER-COLUMN05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Aaron played the game right
 &HT;    By Furman Bisher
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Henry Aaron 65 years old? Of course not! He can't be.
He'll always be a kid, rounding second base in that easy home-run
stride. Tipping the cap to the cheering fans. You never saw him
thrust his fist in the air, go into a home run trot, making a big
fuss about himself because he'd hit another ball out of the lot.
And he could have done it 755 times. That just wasn't his style.
</P>
<P>
   If you wanted to see a man play the game the way it was supposed
to be played, you'd pay to go see Henry Aaron. He was always being
compared with Willie Mays, but they were as different as a
Rolls-Royce from a Corvette. Henry was the Rolls.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody once wrote that the difference between Aaron and Mays
was that Aaron's cap fit better. Mays' cap was always flying off,
like part of the act. Flamboyance was no part of Aaron. No
showboating. No ``hotdog'' in him. He was just about as solid as a
ballplayer could be, on and off the field.
</P>
<P>
   While he was chasing the Babe Ruth home-run record, the New York
Times dispatched a reporting sleuth to flush out the secrets of the
Aaron ``we didn't know.'' After a couple of weeks of following him
around, the reporter came to the conclusion, ``This man is a
helluva man. He's everything he seems to be.'' So much for
sleuthful reporting.
</P>
<P>
   Once I worked with him producing his autobiography. We made no
attempt to go for sensation. It was mainly growing up and baseball.
He never brought up the subject of civil rights, and it was his
book, complete with signature. It wasn't yet a main thrust of the
times. Later, in another book with another writer, the subject was
indeed prominent, as was the title, ``I Had a Hammer.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, I had done a story for the Saturday Evening Post on a
then-emerging star in Milwaukee, but still a shy, humble,
open-faced lad who had no idea how great he might become. The
clubhouse man had even misspelled the name over his locker. He had
burned up the South Atlantic League on the way up, and in that
story I wrote, ``He led the South Atlantic League in everything but
hotel accommodations.'' That was as close to borderline as I ever
dared.
</P>
<P>
   He wore a single-digit number in his early days as a Brave, a 5.
He decided he wanted two numbers on his back. He just liked the
look and the sound of it, his preference. He settled on 44, and
there must have been something symbolic in it. He hit 44 home runs
in four different seasons.
</P>
<P>
   He was not a picky hitter when he was developing. He'd swing at
a lot of pitches that weren't strikes and turn an amazing number of
them into base hits. Edd Roush, the old Hall of Fame outfielder,
worked around the park during spring training in Bradenton, Fla. He
said, ``I've never seen a player with Aaron's ability to swing at
bad pitches and convert them into hits.'' You would have to say Edd
Roush knew something about hitters.
</P>
<P>
   It seems quite odd that Aaron and Ruth almost share the same
birth date. Today, the 5th, is Aaron's. Ruth was born Feb. 6,
although 39 years earlier. Sort of sobering that he was not around
long enough to see Aaron break his record, nor was Roger Maris
around to see Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa break his.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, the night of Aaron's record-breaking, Atlanta was like a
world's fair. Writers and broadcasters had been tracking the chase
even as the 1973 season came to an end. Before one game late in
September, Aaron had told the herd of reporters gathered around
him, ``If I don't hit one tonight, you might as well go home.'' The
game was rained out, and history had to wait.
</P>
<P>
   The 715th homer, hit off Al Downing, has been played and
replayed. It was one of Atlanta's great moments, if not the
greatest. He hit his first off Vic Raschi, the old Yankee
transferred to St. Louis, April 23, 1954. He hit the 755th off Dick
Drago of the Angels July 20, 1976, in County Stadium, fittingly,
where it all began.
</P>
<P>
   Now, on this 5th of February, he will be celebrated at the Hyatt
Regency Hotel, having reaching the age of 65, set off by a
distinguishing touch of gray. The years have treated him kindly.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: furman(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-04-99 2042EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990204.0427 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 20:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2379 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HANKAARON-GALA05-COX     02-04 0623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANKAARON-GALA05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    All-star party to celebrate Aaron's 65th
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ So, how exactly do you prepare for dinner with 1,400
of your closest friends _ including the president?
</P>
<P>
   If, like Hank Aaron tonight at the Hyatt Regency Atlanta's
Centennial Ballroom, you're the guest of honor, you sit back and
marvel. Something like an army of technicians, caterers, florists,
designers and volunteer gofers have been running every which way to
create the perfect party. Aaron will be celebrating two big
numbers: his 65th birthday and the 25th anniversary year of his
record-breaking 715th home run.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a high-end awards show that has a heartbeat,'' says
Rebekah Jones of Atlanta-based Trru Production Services, the
company responsible for running sound and light systems and cueing
the entertainment, which includes the Temptations (Aaron's favorite
music act), pop vocalist Jeffrey Osborne and a chorus of eight
children who have participated in programs funded by Aaron's
Chasing the Dream Foundation _ the charity that's benefiting from
the soldout dinner. ($1.2 million has already been raised.)
</P>
<P>
   Jones also has to make sure 16 guest speakers get to the
microphone on time and don't overstay their allotted two minutes of
toasts and reminiscences. Among guests expected to attend are
baseball's Reggie Jackson, Ernie Banks, Dave Winfield, Frank
Robinson, Ken Griffey Sr. and Sammy Sosa; boxing champ Evander
Holyfield; country singer Charley Pride; the Rev. Jesse Jackson;
and sportscaster Bob Costas.
</P>
<P>
   The size of the event has ballooned since President Clinton
decided to appear. ``With all the VIPs in attendance, we need more
lighting,'' says Jones. ``We're trying to come up with something
that allows the event to maintain its elegance.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones has a crew of 40 and a volunteer staff of 50 to pull off
the job. Trouble is, as she allows, ``The Hyatt Ballroom is booked
about as much as the Fox Theatre.'' By the time her crew can access
the ballroom, technicians will have to cram 12 hours of work into
just under four.
</P>
<P>
   The menu, table settings and color of the flowers _ laid out at
140 tables _ all selected by Aaron's wife, Billye, the gala's chief
organizer, are top secret. But a few details were revealed by
Edmund Faget, director of corporate sales for Event Design Group of
Atlanta. ``People look to us to decorate for an exquisite look,
usually,'' says Faget, whose company often handles private parties
for Ted Turner and did the decor for country singing star Travis
Tritt's recent wedding. To achieve that, the ballroom will be
ringed by 14 neo-classical pedestals _ or torchiers _ constructed
of wrought iron featuring a harlequin pattern. These are wrapped in
creamy chiffon fabric and festooned with flowers and branches
flowering with what Faget called ``plum blossoms.''
</P>
<P>
   Event Design Group is doing all this in the spirit of charity.
If you want the same for your next shindig, the tab would be
$11,900. And you have to give the lamps back the next day.
</P>
<P>
   Bummer, huh? But, hey, you can definitely afford the wine that
will be served. Forest Glen Winery of Sonoma, Calif., donated 40
cases of merlot and chardonnay to the gala at the request of Wine
Institute, a nonprofit organization that promotes the California
wine industry. At $10 a bottle, the merlot is ``soft and easy to
approach,'' says Brian Loomis, spokesman for Forest Glen. And that
chardonnay? ``One hundred percent barrel-fermented. It's a
technique used with the more expensive wines that gives a full,
rich, complex taste.''
</P>
<P>
   Nice touches for a humble hero.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
