<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANKAARON-GALA05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    All-star party to celebrate Aaron's 65th
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ So, how exactly do you prepare for dinner with 1,400
of your closest friends _ including the president?
</P>
<P>
   If, like Hank Aaron tonight at the Hyatt Regency Atlanta's
Centennial Ballroom, you're the guest of honor, you sit back and
marvel. Something like an army of technicians, caterers, florists,
designers and volunteer gofers have been running every which way to
create the perfect party. Aaron will be celebrating two big
numbers: his 65th birthday and the 25th anniversary year of his
record-breaking 715th home run.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a high-end awards show that has a heartbeat,'' says
Rebekah Jones of Atlanta-based Trru Production Services, the
company responsible for running sound and light systems and cueing
the entertainment, which includes the Temptations (Aaron's favorite
music act), pop vocalist Jeffrey Osborne and a chorus of eight
children who have participated in programs funded by Aaron's
Chasing the Dream Foundation _ the charity that's benefiting from
the soldout dinner. ($1.2 million has already been raised.)
</P>
<P>
   Jones also has to make sure 16 guest speakers get to the
microphone on time and don't overstay their allotted two minutes of
toasts and reminiscences. Among guests expected to attend are
baseball's Reggie Jackson, Ernie Banks, Dave Winfield, Frank
Robinson, Ken Griffey Sr. and Sammy Sosa; boxing champ Evander
Holyfield; country singer Charley Pride; the Rev. Jesse Jackson;
and sportscaster Bob Costas.
</P>
<P>
   The size of the event has ballooned since President Clinton
decided to appear. ``With all the VIPs in attendance, we need more
lighting,'' says Jones. ``We're trying to come up with something
that allows the event to maintain its elegance.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones has a crew of 40 and a volunteer staff of 50 to pull off
the job. Trouble is, as she allows, ``The Hyatt Ballroom is booked
about as much as the Fox Theatre.'' By the time her crew can access
the ballroom, technicians will have to cram 12 hours of work into
just under four.
</P>
<P>
   The menu, table settings and color of the flowers _ laid out at
140 tables _ all selected by Aaron's wife, Billye, the gala's chief
organizer, are top secret. But a few details were revealed by
Edmund Faget, director of corporate sales for Event Design Group of
Atlanta. ``People look to us to decorate for an exquisite look,
usually,'' says Faget, whose company often handles private parties
for Ted Turner and did the decor for country singing star Travis
Tritt's recent wedding. To achieve that, the ballroom will be
ringed by 14 neo-classical pedestals _ or torchiers _ constructed
of wrought iron featuring a harlequin pattern. These are wrapped in
creamy chiffon fabric and festooned with flowers and branches
flowering with what Faget called ``plum blossoms.''
</P>
<P>
   Event Design Group is doing all this in the spirit of charity.
If you want the same for your next shindig, the tab would be
$11,900. And you have to give the lamps back the next day.
</P>
<P>
   Bummer, huh? But, hey, you can definitely afford the wine that
will be served. Forest Glen Winery of Sonoma, Calif., donated 40
cases of merlot and chardonnay to the gala at the request of Wine
Institute, a nonprofit organization that promotes the California
wine industry. At $10 a bottle, the merlot is ``soft and easy to
approach,'' says Brian Loomis, spokesman for Forest Glen. And that
chardonnay? ``One hundred percent barrel-fermented. It's a
technique used with the more expensive wines that gives a full,
rich, complex taste.''
</P>
<P>
   Nice touches for a humble hero.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
