<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 20:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2384 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ABOUT-CARS-SATURN-ART     02-04 1130
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABOUT-CARS-SATURN-ART-$ADV07-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SATURN SC2: WINNING A JACKPOT WITH DOOR NO. 3 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, FEB. 7) 
(af) 
 By MICHELLE KREBS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Necessity is the mother of invention, and for the
Saturn Corp. of General Motors, a rather simple invention is
generating a much-needed lift in sales of its aging car line.
</P>
<P>
   Saturn's coupe and sedan, developed in the 1980s and introduced
in 1990 _ with few significant changes since _ compete in a part of
the market that has been ice-cold. Small-car sales have plunged 20
percent over two years as buyers shifted to sport utilities,
midsize sedans and more luxurious cars.
</P>
<P>
   A midsize Saturn, the L-Series, comes this summer, and yet
another freshening of the small cars is due. Still, the existing
models will not be replaced until the 2003 model year.
</P>
<P>
   Against that backdrop, Saturn executives and a group of dealers
held a brainstorming session on what they could do to bolster sales
while they waited for new products. One suggestion came from Stuart
Lasser, who owns three Saturn franchises in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   His eight-year-old son had been complaining about how hard it
was to climb into the rear seat of the two-door model. Why not add
a third door? Lasser asked.
</P>
<P>
   About that time, minivans were arriving with four doors, and
extra doors were being added to extended-cab pickups. At auto
shows, design studies like the Pontiac Rageous and Mercury MC4 _
both of them ostensibly coupes _ had small back doors aimed at
making them somewhat practical.
</P>
<P>
   Within six weeks of Lasser's suggestion, Saturn had engineered a
prototype of a three-door coupe. The model scored well in consumer
clinics, and Saturn decided to put the change into production. As
of November, all Saturn coupes were built with a small, rear-hinged
door behind the driver's door.
</P>
<P>
   A month later, Saturn reported a spurt in sales, its first
month-over-month increase since April and one of the few positive
notes in the smal-car market. The gains continued in January, with
coupe sales up 28 percent from a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   After a recent test-drive of a Saturn SC2, I was not surprised
that the new coupe was doing so well. Even with the third door,
which is nearly invisible when the doors are closed, the car has
the sporty look that two-door buyers like.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the third door opens new markets: Most Saturn coupe owners
are single, but the three-door may prove attractive to parents with
small children, who like the look but need more practicality.
</P>
<P>
   From the outside, one cannot immediately detect the third door.
Last summer Saturn invited some journalists to a preview of future
products. Unable to ascertain what was different about the coupe on
display, reporters walked around it muttering, ``What's the big
deal?'' under their breath.
</P>
<P>
   Then a Saturn executive opened the driver's door and popped open
the small door behind it. The innovation was suddenly so obvious.
``Why didn't anyone think of that before?'' I blurted _ a line that
Saturn executives seized on to use in advertising.
</P>
<P>
   On close inspection, the outline is evident, but doesn't detract
from the car's swoopy look. The door has no handle, inside or out;
it can be opened only by grasping a small lever exposed when the
front door is opened. The third door _ its window is fixed in place
_ is not particularly convenient for rear-seat passengers, but that
small seat isn't suited for adults anyway.
</P>
<P>
   The extra door is ideal for tossing in a gym bag, a briefcase or
a couple sacks of groceries. It allows children to scurry in
without having to tip the front seats forward, and it lets parents
buckle in their charges without straining their backs.
</P>
<P>
   It is ideal for a driver with a wheelchair, who can swing the
chair in behind the driver's seat after he or she is positioned at
the wheel. With no center pillar, there are no obstacles for
loading or unloading the wheelchair.
</P>
<P>
   One suggestion, though: Saturn should consider lighting the area
around the latch, which I fumbled for in the dark when unloading my
children.
</P>
<P>
   Because the third door is so useful, one may wonder why Saturn
didn't add another to the other side. The main reason is the
expense, in a market segment highly sensitive to price, but Saturn
officials say that consumers who want four doors will buy four-door
models _ that is, sedans.
</P>
<P>
   Despite adding the third door, Saturn has lowered prices
slightly for 1999. The SC1 now starts at $12,885; the SC2, with a
bigger engine and nicer trim, opens at $15,445.
</P>
<P>
   Because adding the door meant eliminating the center pillar, the
driver's shoulder belt was relocated from the pillar to the side of
the seat. That works fine as long as the belt remains in the loop
that serves as its guide. But on my test drive, the belt popped out
often and pressed against my throat.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the third door, little has changed on the plastic-bodied,
front-drive, four-passenger coupe. Despite continual efforts to
muffle the engine, including yet another try this year, the Saturn
is still noisy, especially compared with small cars like the Toyota
Corolla.
</P>
<P>
   ``This car is loud,'' my 10-year-old daughter observed. And
aside from the engine roar, at 8 miles an hour an aggravating groan
comes from underneath. After hearing this on two test cars, I asked
Saturn officials about it. They assured me that the abnormal noise
was normal, a routine function involving the anti-lock brakes.
</P>
<P>
   The SC1 base model continues to be powered by a
single-overhead-cam four-cylinder engine. Displacing 1.9 liters, it
is rated at 100 horsepower. The uplevel SC2 comes with a
dual-overhead-cam engine that produces 124 horsepower. A five-speed
manual transmission is standard; a four-speed automatic is
optional.
</P>
<P>
   Saturn was among the first small-car makers to offer traction
control, which helps to keep wheels from spinning on slippery
surfaces, and it is still one of the few with this feature. (It is
included with anti-lock brakes.) Having just come through out one
of Michigan's snowiest Januarys on record, I greatly appreciated
the traction control, which turned the coupe into a sport utility
on my unplowed street.
</P>
<P>
   Saturns' hallmarks are economy and reliability rather than
quiet, comfort and performance. The handling is nothing special,
and acceleration is only adequate.
</P>
<P>
   But dealers do, generally speaking, coddle their customers, who
get royal treatment on par with that accorded Lexus owners, who
spend far more. Plus, Saturn stores offer something one can't find
anywhere else: a two-door car that has three doors.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
