<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROWN05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sisters acknowledge help of other families in Brown v. Board
decision
 &HT;    WITH PHOTO
 &HT;    By Benjamin Kline
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Two sisters whose case made school segregation
illegal were in town Thursday to say it wasn't just them.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Brown Thompson, 55, and her sister Cheryl Brown Henderson,
48, of Topeka, Kan., are forever linked by family name to Brown v.
Board of Education, the landmark 1954 U.S. Supreme Court decision
that found separate but equal schools unconstitutional and led to
the slow desegregation of schools nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   The Brown sisters, daughters of the late Rev. Oliver Brown, a
plaintiff in the Topeka lawsuit brought in 1951 by the NAACP, spoke
at Sinclair Community College as part of Sinclair's Black History
Month celebration.
</P>
<P>
   They have formed a Brown Family Foundation and obtained National
Historic Site status for Topeka's former Monroe Elementary School
to promote multicultural awareness and research on equity and
excellence in education.
</P>
<P>
   Part of their personal educational effort, they said, is to
correct ``myth'' that has arisen from the case that started in a
city where black families were widely dispersed, but black children
had to attend all-black schools no matter how close they might live
to white schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``One myth is that our family was the only one involved,'' Brown
Thompson told Sinclair students at an afternoon gathering. ``There
were 12 families.''
</P>
<P>
   In texts and dramas of the events, the late Thurgood Marshall is
portrayed as the battling NAACP attorney who won the case. Marshall
did argue it before the Supreme Court, the sisters said, but a
lawyer named Robert Carter handled the Topeka part. The Brown
family never met Marshall, the sisters said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Life magazine photos of little Linda Brown, standing with
her books in front of her school, made her a national symbol akin
to the ``Little Rock Nine'' blacks trying to attend class at that
city's high school, or Rosa Parks refusing to give up her bus seat
to a white man in Montgomery, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody realized how far-reaching this case
would become,'' Brown Thompson said. She and her sister felt they
received a good education in Topeka schools and did not suffer the
harassment experienced by children in other cities during the civil
rights movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have racial strife,'' she said. ``Efforts to
integrate the teaching staff (Topeka had four black schools, 18
white) were the only problem,'' Brown Henderson said, because they
threatened some teachers' jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Racism today? It depends on the locale, Brown Thompson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The South has a better way,'' she said. ``They come right out
and tell you if they don't like you. The more subtle racism in the
North is more treacherous than blatant racism, I think.''
</P>
<P>
   Today the pattern has come full circle, Brown Henderson
observed. Today black children are bused to ``magnet schools'' or
to more racially balanced schools just as, 45 years ago, they were
bused inconveniently to all-black schools.
</P>
<P>
   The important message for today's young people, Brown Thompson
said: ``It was young people who made a difference'' in the civil
rights movement, most of them parents in their late 20s and early
30s.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
