<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-DAY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON AND ARAFAT APPEAR AT ANNUAL PRAYER BREAKFAST 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton and Yasser Arafat, partners in
the Middle East peace process and high-voltage generators of
controversy, appeared Thursday at an ecumenical prayer breakfast,
testing the faith and charity of hundreds of guests.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Arafat did not speak, his attendance for the first
time at the annual National Prayer Breakfast touched off a boycott
by some religious groups and members of Congress, who said that he
was not fit to appear at such a gathering because of his suspected
sponsorship of terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was received more politely than Arafat by those at the
breakfast, some of whom have publicly condemned the sexual behavior
and deceptive statements that led to his impeachment and trial.
Sen. Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut, who has been one of the
harshest Democratic critics of the president's conduct, asked God
to hear Clinton's pleas for forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman said, ``Lord, may I say a special prayer at this time
of difficulty for our president, that you would hear his prayers,
that you help him with the work he's doing with his family and his
clergy, that you accept his atonement.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Steve Largent of Oklahoma, a conservative Republican who
headed this year's prayer breakfast and who voted in December to
impeach Clinton, said that he seldom agreed with the president on
matters of politics and policy. But he said that did not affect his
spirit of Christian brotherhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. President,'' Largent said, ``I may not have voted with you
in the four years I've been in Congress, but I want you to know
that I care for you and love you and that's part of the mystery of
Jesus.''
</P>
<P>
   In his brief remarks, Clinton made no mention of his personal or
political troubles, delivering a high-minded appeal for peace and
reconciliation around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, in his public remarks and later in private, thanked
Arafat for his efforts toward peace with Israel. The president said
that peace is not made among friends, but between enemies, and
requires a willingness to put aside historical grievances and
personal slights. He also paid tribute to Leah Rabin, the widow of
the slain Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin. She also attended
Thursday's prayer session.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ask you to pray for all of us, including yourself,'' Clinton
said to the 2,600 people who attended the breakfast in the ballroom
of the Washington Hilton, ``to pray that our purpose truly will
reflect God's will; to pray that we can all be purged of the
temptation to pretend that our willfulness is somehow equal to
God's will; to remember that all the great peacemakers in the world
in the end have to let go and walk away, like Christ, not from
apparent but from genuine grievances.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton met privately with Arafat for 20 minutes after the
breakfast to discuss the status of the Middle East peace process.
Clinton also met briefly with Mrs. Rabin.
</P>
<P>
   Several members of Congress who customarily attend the prayer
breakfast, which is sponsored by Congress and has been held
annually since 1942, sat out this year's event to protest Arafat's
appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Michael Forbes, R-N.Y., said that it was inappropriate to
invite Arafat to such a gathering.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very much offended by the presence of Yasser Arafat, who
is a man who has American blood on his hands,'' Forbes said, citing
suspected Palestinian involvement in terrorist acts that killed
American citizens, including the murder of Leon Klinghoffer aboard
the cruise ship Achille Lauro in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   But Largent said that he was not making a political statement by
including Arafat. He said that Benjamin Netanyahu, the Israeli
prime minister, had also been invited but declined because of
scheduling problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is precisely the type of event that people like Arafat
ought to be invited to,'' Largent said. ``The idea of a prayer
breakfast is to bring people together for reconciliation and
healing and forgiveness and talk about those issues that Jesus
taught.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-04-99 2051EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
