<HEADER>
A2393 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-JOBS-$ADV07-NYT &LR;      02-04 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-JOBS-$ADV07-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAINTING INSTEAD OF NUMBERS  
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, FEB. 7)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Va.)  (af) 
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Life is strange, which explains why some seemingly easy
resolutions fail and some seemingly impossible dreams come true. At
the outset of a new year, as they take stock of their careers,
readers were asked about both resolutions and dreams. And they
responded with letters and messages that ranged from immediate
wishes to long-term goals.
</P>
<P>
   On July 3, 1996, at 38, David Peikon retired from his job as
vice president of sales for Federal Business Products, a printing
company in Clifton, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   It was the culmination of a resolution made six years earlier,
when as a printing executive he landed a long-term exclusive
contract with Chase Manhattan Bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized that the financial windfall that might follow would
allow me to achieve financial independence and a chance to pursue
my ultimate dream of a career as a painter,'' Peikon writes from
Bethpage, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   He said he put together a plan that included careful financial
planning, elimination of debt and improvement of his self-taught
artistic skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gave myself until February 1996 (my 15th anniversary in
business) to achieve my goal,'' he said. ``What followed was a
seven-day-a-week marathon consisting of five days in the office and
two days at the easel.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Peikon had his first solo show. He says his paintings
are selling well, and as 1999 begins, he is represented by a large
art consulting firm and two galleries.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the way,'' Peikon writes, ``the motto for my business is
engraved on a charm around my neck _ `Keep within your heart a
place for dreams.' '' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 31, 1996, Barbara Zingman made her resolution for 1997:
better management of work time. She failed. She set the same goal
for 1998.
</P>
<P>
   As a corporate historian, Ms. Zingman must parcel out her work
week among various tasks: research, interviews, archiving and
marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, she says, she decided to construct a time line.
Because she operates out of her office as well as her home in
Manhattan, she bought not one but two of those huge wall calendars
with plenty of space to chart each day's activities.
</P>
<P>
   But she also needed a small date book for jotting down
appointments while on the phone, plus a Filofax (useful when she
moves around town seeing clients and doing research) and scheduling
software.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately,'' she says, ``when I finally completed my
by-now intricate time line it was toward the end of February _ the
project completion dates for which I had originally set up my
management tools were long overdue.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``There I was, retired from Rutgers University's philosophy
department after 26 years,'' writes Loretta Mazlen Mandel of
Princeton, N.J. Though no longer an administrative assistant and
freshman adviser, she decided to do some substitute teaching at
nearby schools. Then she decided to take on temporary work at the
Bristol-Myers Squibb corporate offices in Princeton.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the fact that she was, as she puts it, no longer 30
years old, she was invited back again and again.
</P>
<P>
   And then Raymond Joske, director of the company's advanced
health care department, which develops pharmaceuticals, offered her
a full-time job coordinating 20 field representatives who sell to
hospitals and health maintenance organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Mandel writes, ``What totally blew my mind was that here I
was, 68 years old, and being offered the position and a new
career.'' She took the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``My hat is off to Bristol-Myers Squibb and to Ray Joske for
giving a woman a chance to start or continue a career without
concern for age,'' she writes. ``So get the message out there to
those women who want to stay in the work force later on in life
that there is that chance, if only someone would give it to
them.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The transition from 1998 to 1999 for me was the realization of
a dream,'' writes Joshua Lipsman. ``On Jan. 1, I started as the
executive director of New York Gay Men's Health Crisis, since 1981
the world's oldest and largest organization serving men, women and
children with HIV and AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   ``By training, I am a physician and a manager with expertise in
public health and preventive medicine. I have spent the past seven
years serving as the director of public health in Alexandria, Va.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that as a government employee, he ``had increasingly
come to feel a lack of integration between my personal identity as
a politically progressive, openly gay man and my career as a
successful civil servant.''
</P>
<P>
   But when he saw an advertisement in a Washington area newspaper
for the GMHC job, Lipsman, now 43, said he was only mildly
interested, just enough to apply.
</P>
<P>
   As the interview process unfolded, he began to realize what a
close fit there was between the job and him.
</P>
<P>
   Finishing his first month on the job, learning and loving every
minute of it, he says, ``I still look in wonder at all these
changes _ new job, new home, new life _ and remind myself that when
one concentrates one's energies on a life's intention, truly much
is possible.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
