<HEADER>
A2405 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HUSSEIN-1STLD-WRITETH     02-04 0610
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUSSEIN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-575(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAVELY ILL HUSSEIN FLIES HOME TO JORDAN
</HEADLINE>
 
(SUBS to rewrite hed; no other changes.)  (fe) 
 By WILLIAM A. ORME Jr.  
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ King Hussein of Jordan went home on Thursday to die,
leaving the Mayo Clinic by private jet with an American military
escort.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors said the king, 63, who is suffering from non-Hodgkins
lymphoma, was in critical condition, after a bone marrow transplant
on Tuesday apparently failed. The king, who has been in power since
1952 and has been integral to the peace effort in the Middle East,
wanted to ``die in his own country,'' an aide said.
</P>
<P>
   When Hussein made a triumphal return to Jordan three weeks ago,
pronouncing himself completely recovered, he was the pilot of his
own plane. On his trip home on Thursday, his plane was accompanied
by two American fighter jets, which saw the plane safely from the
clinic in Rochester, Minn., to the Canadian border.
</P>
<P>
   The Jordanian royal family, in a brief statement read Thursday
night on state television, confirmed only that Hussein had left the
Mayo Clinic and that his destination was the King Hussein Medical
Center, an army hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is obvious what this means,'' said a family
spokesman in Amman, who asked not to be named.
</P>
<P>
   Various news organizations were reporting that the king had
suffered organ failure, and the Associated Press in Amman reported
that it had received a faxed statement from Hussein's private
physician, Lt. Gen. Samir Farraj, that his condition had ``become
critical due to the failure of the function of internal organs.''
There were no details on the extent of the organ failure.
</P>
<P>
   A Clinton administration official said that Hussein's condition
upon leaving the hospital was extremely grave and that it was
believed that he might already be on life support aboard the
aircraft, but the official said he did not have independent
confirmation of that.
</P>
<P>
   Jordanian government spokesmen said Thursday night that they
could neither confirm nor deny broadcast reports in the region
citing concerns that the king might not survive the long flight
home.
</P>
<P>
   Reports from Jordan indicate that he is returning to die,
presumably on Jordanian soil, rather than in a foreign country, the
administration official said. Already there are said to be plans
for a funeral on Sunday or Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The news that the king might have lost his long battle with
cancer stunned already shell-shocked Jordanians. During his brief
visit home, he unexpectedly ousted his brother Hassan, who had been
his constitutionally designated successor as crown prince for 34
years. After naming his eldest son, Abdullah, as his chosen heir,
the king abruptly returned to the clinic in the United States on
Jan. 26, barely a week after his joyful homecoming. His doctors
said he was being rushed back to the United States because of a
fever and blood count abnormalities.
</P>
<P>
   The celebratory national mood was punctured, and Jordan's
concerns moved to the future of the country and the health of the
king.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   World leaders, too, expressed concern on Thursday about the
king's condition. President Clinton, speaking at the National
Prayer Breakfast in Washington a few hours before the king's
departure from the United States, said, ``I ask you to pray for our
King Hussein, a wonderful human being, a champion of peace who, I
promise you today, is fighting for his life mostly so he can
continue to fight for peace.'' Yasser Arafat, visiting Washington,
joined the president in prayer.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   After Hussein underwent his second bone marrow transplant
operation in Minnesota on Tuesday, there were increasingly
insistent reports in the Israeli press and in regional diplomatic
circles that the operation had failed and that his health was
rapidly deteriorating.
</P>
<P>
   In Jordan, however, reports on state television and the local
press stressed initially positive reports that the king's condition
had stabilized.
</P>
<P>
   Family members said privately that the king was in good spirits
after the operation, demanding a cigarette over his doctor's
objections and joking with visitors. As recently as Thursday
morning senior officials in Amman were discussing government
projects that would be revived when the king returned home after an
expected recovery period of a few months.
</P>
<P>
   Many Jordanians speaking privately had said they were distressed
and mystified by the uncharacteristic haste and imperiousness with
which Hussein demoted his loyal younger brother and put Abdullah in
line for the throne. Abdullah himself is said to have learned of
the king's decision only one day before it was publicly announced.
</P>
<P>
   As Jordanians were absorbing the news of the king's condition
Thursday night, his sense of urgency and assertion of command
seemed in retrospect not only understandable, but admirable. ``He
knew that he was running out of time,'' said a Jordanian journalist
who had been critical of the palace upheaval.
</P>
<P>
   For the last week Jordan has been gripped by the palace drama of
the sudden transition in the line of succession from the
internationally respected Prince Hassan, 51, to Prince Abdullah,
37, an army brigadier general of considerable personal charm and
professional military accomplishment but almost no experience in
politics or diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
   Abdullah, still not universally recognized by the Jordanian
public, had just begun presiding over cabinet meetings and
appearing on television welcoming a parade of foreign well-wishers
from Secretary of State Madeleine Albright to Arafat to Persian
Gulf sultans. Now Jordanians are confronted with the imminent
possibility of the country's first monarchical succession in 47
years, a prospect unnerving to ordinary citizens here and the
country's neighbors alike.
</P>
<P>
   Abdullah, however, appears to be assuming his unexpected new
role with a poise and confidence that has surprised some veteran
Jordanian political observers. A boyish 37, he has a self-assured
informality that is a marked contrast to the aloof, intellectual
demeanor of his uncle, Hassan.
</P>
<P>
   He has two other key strengths that differentiate him from his
predecessor as crown prince. As a career soldier, he is said to be
genuinely popular in the military, an institution dominated by the
ethnic Jordanian East Bank minority. And as the husband of a
middle-class Palestinian from the West Bank, he is seen
sympathetically by Jordan's Palestinian majority.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to Amman in recent days are known to have been assured
by Crown Prince Abdullah and his aides that Jordanian foreign
policy under a new regime would continue essentially unchanged,
with a continuing commitment to the Middle East peace effort and
eventual statehood for the Palestinians in the Gaza Strip and
formerly Jordanian West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   The prince, who had headed the Jordanian army's respected
special forces unit, is said to have developed warm relations with
senior Israeli military officers with whom he collaborated on
border security and counterterrorism operations.
</P>
<P>
   He also enjoys several close friendships with his generational
counterparts in the royal families of the Persian Gulf states,
relationships that may already be delivering dividends for Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Kuwait, which suspended diplomatic relations with Jordan after
Jordan sided with Iraq in the Gulf War, informed the new crown
prince that it will be reopening its embassy in Amman. Saudi
officials, who cut off crude exports as a reprisal for Jordan's
Gulf War stance, are now discussing a resumption of oil sales to
Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Abdullah is also well known in the Pentagon, and in key
congressional commitees. His lobbying in Washington for military
aid helped lead to an increase in U.S. security assistance to $75
million in 1998 and a promised $200 million more in the next three
years.
</P>
<P>
   But he not a recognized figure to the general public in his own
country, much less in the rest of the Middle East. While Abdullah
maintained a deliberately low profile as a career military officer,
speculation in the region about possible changes in the Hashemite
succession centered more on his younger brothers, Prince Ali, now
23, the eldest son of the late Queen Alia, and Prince Hamzah, 18,
the first-born son of the king and his current wife, Queen Noor.
</P>
<P>
   Israelis are especially anxious as they prepare to mourn a man
who has ruled their neighbor almost since Israel was founded a half
century ago and who has in recent years acquired an almost sainted
status here. The King Hussein whose forces fought Israelis on the
streets of Jerusalem in 1967 has been supplanted in the popular
imagination by the King Hussein whose wrenching funeral oration for
murdered Prime Minister Itzak Rabin solidified his image here as
Israel's one genuine friend in the Arab world.
</P>
<P>
   Abdullah, though he is presumed to share his father's views, is
almost completely unknown, in a region with a well-developed fear
of the unknown.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu phoned Abdullah to
congratulate him on his designation as crown prince last week and
announced plans to visit the prince in Amman on Sunday in what
would have been the Israeli leader's first visit to Jordan in
almost two years _ plans that may now have to be postponed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
