<HEADER>
A2407 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-LEWINSKY-NYT     02-04 0570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-LEWINSKY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEWINSKY, RELIEVED, WILL TRY TO GET ON WITH HER LIFE
</HEADLINE>
  (See also IMPEACH-TRIAL, IMPEACH, IMPEACH-ASSESS, IMPEACH-SCENE,
IMPEACH-MANAGERS, IMPEACH-REPUBS) 
 (bl) 
By DON VAN NATTA Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ At long last, Monica Lewinsky got some good news
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In a friend's apartment in New York, Ms. Lewinsky watched on
live television as the Senate decided not to require her to testify
in person at President Clinton's impeachment trial, which her
lawyers have characterized as ``an unseemly circus.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Monica and her family are pleased that she does not have to go
through the painful and humiliating ordeal of having to testify on
the floor of the Senate,'' said Judy Smith, a spokeswoman for Ms.
Lewinsky. ``The Lewinsky family hopes closure will come soon for
everyone else involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky will now grapple with the challenge of getting on
with her life, Ms. Smith and several other friends said.
</P>
<P>
   It will not be easy. Ms. Lewinsky owes more than $1 million in
fees to lawyers and consultants. She has not worked for more than a
year, and has no employment prospects. And one of the few ways she
can chip away at her mountain of debt is to sit down for an
exclusive interview with Barbara Walters of ABC News. Although ABC
is not paying Ms. Lewinsky for the interview, Channel 4 in Britain
has agreed to pay her $600,000 for the foreign rights to the
interview, her associates said.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Lewinsky cannot participate in the interview without the
permission of Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr, who has insisted
that she remain silent for now.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky could be required to testify at future court
proceedings involving the president, if Starr seeks an indictment
against Clinton or other targets of his ongoing criminal
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Ms. Lewinsky asked a federal judge to force
Starr's office to grant her permission to begin speaking to the
media. Starr opposed it.
</P>
<P>
   That same week, Starr asked the same judge to require Ms.
Lewinsky to be interviewed by the House managers, drawing criticism
for taking sides in the Senate trial.
</P>
<P>
   After being granted complete immunity from prosecution by
Starr's office last July, Ms. Lewinsky promised to cooperate with
the ongoing criminal inquiry and to testify truthfully in any
forum. Starr included language in Ms. Lewinsky's immunity agreement
that required her to answer questions truthfully before grand
juries ``and in any other executive, military, judicial or
congressional proceedings.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Smith said Thursday night that Ms. Lewinsky's lawyers would
ask U.S. District Judge Norma Holloway Johnson of to give Ms.
Lewinsky the opportunity to speak with Ms. Walters and other news
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky spent several hours Thursday speaking with Andrew
Morton, who wrote her book titled ``Monica's Story,'' which is to
be published later this month by St. Martin's Press. Ms. Lewinsky
received a $600,000 advance for the book.
</P>
<P>
   Although she has answered questions on 23 occasions about her
relationship with the president, Ms. Smith and others said Thursday
that Ms. Lewinsky believed that she would have to testify again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's the question: Is it really over for her?'' said a close
friend who spoke with Ms. Lewinsky on Thursday. ``Will she be
needed to testify again and again and again?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-04-99 2107EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
