A2412 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-MARSHALL-STARS-TE     02-04 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-MARSHALL-STARS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HE'S STILL A HUGE HIT, BUT MARSHALL NOW HAS GOALS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Grant Marshall conclusively proved his toughness
in junior hockey in the 1990-91 season.
</P>
<P>
   He broke his neck in a game in December, but returned just in
time for the playoffs. Ignoring the potential for further physical
damage, Marshall went after the biggest guy on the ice.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first hit was against \REric\S Lindros,'' he said. ``If you
want to see if you can come back from injury, who better than the
biggest guy? I went after him and hit him, and did a 180 face plant
on the ice. It hurt my pride a bit, but my neck was fine. I went
out there and hit some more guys and knocked them on their butt,
and I felt really good.''
</P>
<P>
   Nine years later, Marshall still is a tough guy. A week ago, he
dropped the gloves with Tampa Bay's Sandy McCarthy. Despite giving
up height and weight, the Stars' 6-foot-1, 193-pound forward held
his own with the 6-3, 235-pound McCarthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always known what my role is, and that's to bring that
physical presence,'' Marshall said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, though, Marshall has to bring something else. He's playing
on a scoring line with Joe Nieuwendyk and Jamie Langenbrunner, and
even getting some time on the power play.
</P>
<P>
   The tough guy has to think about offense, instead of just doling
out hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to bring that extra element, which is more of an
offensive element, to the table,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall was skilled enough to be a first-round draft pick of
the Toronto Maple Leafs, and he had 32 goals and 51 assists his
first full season in juniors. But as the seasons went on, he became
a checker, a grinder, an enforcer. A tough guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to play with what gets you here and what you do
best,'' Marshall said. ``You still have to bring that grit level
and show up every night.''
</P>
<P>
   This season, Marshall already has nine goals, tying a career
high. He has three game-winning scores, tied with Mike Modano for
second on the team behind Brett Hull's seven. His 15.5 shooting
percentage also is second on the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always known I'm talented enough to create plays and
bring a bit of an offensive element to my game,'' he said. ``I know
I can put the puck in the net and create some scoring chances as
well.''
</P>
<P>
   While Marshall has added some offense, his job on the second
line primarily is to play hard, be physical and let Nieuwendyk and
Langenbrunner take care of putting the puck in the net.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the most part you can't change your game,'' Marshall said.
``For me that's grinding it out, and creating space for Joe and
Jamie. They're great players that you learn a lot from and feed off
of. It makes you want to bring that all-around, hard-nosed grit
level as well as the offensive level.''
</P>
<P>
   The grit level is why Stars coach Ken Hitchcock put Marshall on
the second line. His job is to provide energy, not highlight-reel
goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Same role, same player,'' Hitchcock said. ``We're just taking
advantage of his skill level. No change. If it changes, he'll be
going back to the fourth line.''
</P>
<P>
   Marshall can put the puck in the net, or set up a teammate with
an assist. He can be a productive part of a scoring line. But in
the final analysis, he's still the same tough guy who once took
that run at Eric Lindros.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting more ice time and more of a chance to play, and I
think for the most part I'm making the best of it,'' Marshall said.
``But you've still got to play the game. If that means taking a
punch for the team, or getting into a fight, or doing whatever it
takes, it doesn't matter what line you're on you've still got to do
it.'' KECZMER, GUSEV TAKE TRIP Dan Keczmer and Sergey Gusev headed
to Kalamazoo after practice yesterday for three games with the
Stars' affiliate in the International Hockey League. They'll play
in Kalamazoo tonight and tomorrow, return to Dallas in case they
are needed for the Stars' game against the Colorado Avalanche on
Sunday, then play Tuesday in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   For Gusev, who has played just 14 games, it's a chance to stay
sharp. For Keczmer, it's an opportunity to hasten his transition
from defense to left wing. PRACTICE PRODUCTIVE The Stars practiced
for an hour yesterday, a day after a 90-minute workout.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had two days of real good jump at practice, real good
tenacity and energy on the ice,'' Hitchcock said. ``We've had good
focus. I think this has been very good for us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-04-99 2112EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
