A2413 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOREST-AUDIT-575&AMP;ADD-     02-04 0879
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREST-AUDIT-575&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL AUDITORS HIT FOREST SERVICE FOR LAX CONTROL OF LOGGING 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JOHN H. CUSHMAN JR.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Federal auditors have found that the Forest Service
frequently fails to assess, prevent or correct environmental damage
from logging on the national forests.
</P>
<P>
   After inspecting 12 timber projects in the field from 1995 to
1998, the Agriculture Department's inspector general found that all
were deficient and that ``immediate corrective action is needed.''
</P>
<P>
   A new report found that the environmental studies required
before logging was approved were poorly done, the rules to protect
streams and wildlife habitat from undue damage during logging were
not followed, and plans to repair some of the harm after logging
were not carried out.
</P>
<P>
   Roger C. Viadero, the inspector general, reported on Jan. 15 to
Mike Dombeck, the agency's chief, that the review found ``numerous
serious deficiencies.'' Agency officials generally agreed with the
report's conclusions and recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   The problems not only cause lasting harm to publicly owned
natural resources, the report emphasized, but also cost the
taxpayers money because many timber sales are canceled for
environmental reasons, and the government then must pay penalties
to the timber companies for breach of contract.
</P>
<P>
   The report put an official stamp on the kind of complaints that
environmental advocates have lodged with the agency for years, and
it was welcomed by groups that are suing the agency in federal
court seeking a complete halt to logging on federal lands on the
ground that it does more environmental harm than economic good.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an extremely damaging report to the Forest Service's
case because it shows that Forest Service decisions can be based on
inadequate and incomplete research and analysis,'' said Brian
Dunkiel, a lawyer for Friends of the Earth, one of the groups suing
the agency.
</P>
<P>
   The forest service said it is already moving to correct the
problems, ordering every regional forester to send special teams
into the woods to make sure its rules are being enforced
</P>
<P>
   ``This audit is healthy and it is representative of folks'
growing concern about how their forests are managed,'' said
Christopher Wood, the senior policy aid to Dombeck. ``We are
stewards of the public's trust as well as their resources, and it
is unacceptable when we don't comply with our own environmental
regulations.''
</P>
<P>
   The audit uncovered many problems in the complex paperwork that
accompanies the agency's sales of timber on publicly owned land to
private logging companies. The Forest Service prepares at least
2,000 environmental assessments each year, in which it is required
to document in detail virtually every possible environmental
consequence of each sale. In 1997, the agency sold more than 3
billion board feet of timber for nearly $500 million.
</P>
<P>
   The report also disclosed problems in how the logging was
actually carried out. It documented instances of logging too close
to streams, and other cases in which too many trees were felled or
proper steps were not taken to prevent soil erosion.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the audit was under way, local officials moved to
correct some of the problems the inspectors found, halting several
timber sales because surveys of endangered species had not been
done and because too many trees were being cut.
</P>
<P>
   That proved costly for the agency, which in one such case had to
pay $650,000 to logging companies for breach of contract. Over the
years, cancellations due to improper environmental planning have
cost the agency tens of millions of dollars.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The report included several specific examples of the kind of
problems that the auditors believe are pervasive.
</P>
<P>
   In the Clinch Ranger District in Virginia, where clear-cutting
was usually prohibited within 50 feet of a stream, agency
biologists doubled the buffer strip at one site to protect water
quality because there were many species of endangered mussels
downstream. But inspectors found a clear-cut spot within 15 feet of
the stream, and a survey found that in six of nine spots examined
the buffer strips ranged from 13 feet to 85 feet. The result was
excessive sediment in the water.
</P>
<P>
   In the Laurentian Ranger District in Minnesota, the agency
permitted a 50-acre clearcut even though 30 additional acres were
clearcut on adjacent county land. That oversight meant that the
assessment of cumulative environmental harm, a required document,
was flawed. Similar flaws were found repeatedly at other locations.
</P>
<P>
   In eight out of 12 cases examined, biological evaluations did
not consider all the imperiled species that were known or expected
to live in the forest where logging was to occur. The auditors
found that the evaluations did not consider 364 of the 436
threatened, endangered or sensitive species that could be found in
those areas. One project was described as improving the habitat for
ruffled grouse, and its evaluation stated that no imperiled species
were found there, while the auditors found that 127 threatened,
endangered or sensitive species were either known or likely to live
in the area.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
