<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-BIAS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIVERSITY'S LOSS IN BOSTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston School Committee didn't answer the bell for round
three in its fight to maintain a vestige of integration at Boston
Latin School. Instead the committee decided unanimously this week
not to ask the US Supreme Court to rule on the constitutionality of
an admissions policy that used a careful combination of test
scores, grades, and race to build a diverse and highly qualified
student body at the prestigious high school.
</P>
<P>
   The School Committee lost courage after the federal Appeals
Court invalidated a lower-court ruling by US District Judge Joseph
Tauro that supported the city's sensible admissions plan. Civil
rights groups, including the NAACP, feared that the Boston Latin
plan lacked sufficient coherence and documentation. They lobbied
the School Committee not to appeal the case to the Supreme Court in
light of the high court's conservative bent and its recent
rejections of affirmative action for minorities. So on this
critical issue for all Americans, civil rights leaders counsel that
it is best to go underground now and live to fight another day.
</P>
<P>
   The situation is maddening. Contradictory court decisions on
discrimination remedies bang around the country like billiard
balls. The courts and public wrongly equate today's good policies
promoting integration with bad policies of the past that enforced
segregation. School officials cry out for clarity but instead get
advice on strategy. They are told to push a case to the Supreme
Court that looks more like the Bakke decision, which prohibited
racial quotas but left room for universities to consider race,
among other factors, in admissions.
</P>
<P>
   So now the nation is asked to pretend that 11-year-olds who seek
seats for seventh grade in Boston Latin can somehow reveal their
multidimensional personalities in a college-like admissions
process. It's nonsense, of course, but it allows the fiction to
continue that race-based problems in America can be solved solely
by nonracial means.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston School Committee had a chance to walk in the front
door and prove the educational value of diversity. But it flubbed
it. The challenge awaits a braver and better-prepared protector.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-04-99 2122EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
