A2420 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDITORIAL-WAGES-BOS &LR;      02-04 0368
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-WAGES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRICKLING DOWN AT LAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Figures from the Commerce Department indicating that real income
rose 5.1 percent last year conceal other welcome news: Over the
last three years, low-income workers have benefited from the
economic boom. The ability of the economy to reward these workers
is strong evidence for the continuation of successful government
policies.
</P>
<P>
   While US economic growth is strong, economic troubles abroad
provide a brake against inflationary expansion, as confirmed by
last year's 1 percent inflation rate, lowest since 1959. The
Federal Reserve was wise to keep interest rates stable this week so
the economy can continue its expansion. The strong economic growth
_ 3.9 percent last year _ argues against the overstimulation of the
proposed tax cuts sought by congressional Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Low-wage workers still make far less than they did in 1979,
according to the Economic Policy Institute, but they have
significantly exceeded the levels of 1989, before the last
recession.
</P>
<P>
   A tight labor market in 1996 through 1998 has forced employers
to raise wages. The gap between the wages of black and white
workers is narrowing after a 15-year period when it widened.
Workers are benefiting from increases in productivity, a gain that
eluded them in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   The national median wage _ $11.29 an hour, or $451.16 a week _
is hardly munificent. People at this level or below could use more
help from government to pay for child care, afford health
insurance, buy a home, or educate their children or themselves. If
the economic expansion continues, money ought to be found for these
purposes from increased federal tax revenues. Regional variations
should also be addressed. Massachusetts workers have not yet closed
the gap.
</P>
<P>
   How long the boom will continue is anyone's guess. The
leadership team of President Clinton, Federal Reserve chairman Alan
Greenspan, and Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin has wisely avoided
anything that would cause the economy to falter. Unless a downturn
comes, it would be folly to change policies that benefit American
workers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-04-99 2123EST &QL; 
