<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LET'S HOPE NELSON KEEPS US AMUSED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Admittedly, Don Nelson amuses me.
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly, this should be the lowest priority, if any priority
at all, in judging Nelson's attempted rescue effort involving our
local Lost Cause.
</P>
<P>
   But since it's the Mavericks, amusement of the right kind is
actually a large upgrade. Instead of laughing at the whole sorry
situation, and there's been almost a decade of such folly, I now
find myself chuckling along with almost every episode of Life With
Nellie.
</P>
<P>
   The man makes a lot of moves, which translates to a lot of
chuckles. For now, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Without question, Nelson is all brass, and it's long been a
personal theory that only the fearless survive in professional
sports. Plus, there's his track record, even if it's now somewhat
ancient, on bringing back NBA franchises from the dead.
</P>
<P>
   This we know. Nelson is in total charge of this tomb. For the
only time in Mavericks history, there's one vote on every
basketball decision made at 777 Sport Street, downtown Dallas. As
the combo general manager-coach, Nelson answers only to himself.
</P>
<P>
   His critics in the NBA, and there are more than several, will
tell you this is the basketball equivalent of Saddam with a nuclear
arsenal. In the end, no one will be left standing.
</P>
<P>
   Local opinion, however, can differ. The demise of the Mavericks
from the late '80s is traceable to a variety of basketball voices
speaking up, but none loud enough to be heard. Nelson provides a
180. He does all the talking, and if what Nelson says and does
turns out bogus, what's there to lose, except more games. Here's a
franchise that has seen 30-plus wins in a season exactly once since
1990.
</P>
<P>
   It's a good thing, by my scorecard, that no one can save Nelson
except Nelson. Not sidekick son, Donnie. Not Junior Perot, the
owner void of a basketball clue (this is not necessarily a bad
thing). Not Terdema Ussery, Perot's business-side team president.
</P>
<P>
   Under normal circumstances, such as the NBA opening on schedule
in early November, this would have been the season of reckoning for
Nelson. By April, enough evidence could have been stockpiled to
either fire him or kiss up to him.
</P>
<P>
   But as an abbreviated season begins tonight for the Mavericks in
Seattle, Nelson has 50 games to play around with, setting up the
team and himself for 1999-2000. Judging any club by what is about
to happen will be extremely risky.
</P>
<P>
   One guy, however, who doesn't look at it that way is Nelson
himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got no complaints over cramming the 50 games into three
months,'' he said yesterday before boarding the team charter to
Seattle. ``Young guys need practice and repetition, which we won't
have much of, but there's nothing better than games. We have a
bunch of those and they come in a hurry.''
</P>
<P>
   For all his mass-player shuffling over the last two years,
Nelson can now be held totally responsible for two _ last summer's
acquisition of point guard Steve Nash and the drafting of Dirk
Nowitzki. Along with Michael Finley, this is the future, one way or
the other.
</P>
<P>
   Nash is important because of his position, and also because the
one transaction Nelson whiffed on was dealing point guard Sam
Cassell. Everything else was a direct result of needing to dump
Jamal Mashburn and Jim Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``The major pieces are now in place, and I'd also add Samaki
Walker to Michael, Dirk, and Nash,'' said Nelson. ``Where we
eventually end up as a franchise will be determined by those
players.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson's goal for this season seems realistic, until you
consider it's the Mavericks involved:
</P>
<P>
   ``To have something to play for, that's what I want,'' said
Nelson. ``I want to be a playoff contender, and then slip into the
eighth spot, and give these young guys some playoff exposure.''
</P>
<P>
   I'd say, can't do.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson says, ``I think that's a reasonable goal. Just to be in
the hunt is vital to us.''
</P>
<P>
   The league showed the Mavericks absolutely zero respect _ and
why should it _ by scheduling nine of the first 11 games on the
road, with Houston and Utah the Reunion visitors.
</P>
<P>
   That smells of a possible 0-11 start. Even in a ``free '' season
for Nelson, it would be hard to keep chuckling. But above all else,
in the end there will be only one man to blame, or, hopefully,
bless.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
