<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-PREVIEW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUBSTANCE OVER STYLE IN NEW NBA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Now that Michael Jordan has realized the
grass is greener on the fairways, the NBA title is again available
to the best team instead of simply the best player.
</P>
<P>
   Still hobbling from the lockout, the NBA is faced with the tasks
of replacing Jordan, rejuvenating an apathetic fan base and pumping
air back into its deflated game. A Cliffs Notes version of the
season tips off tonight and in the end, old-school fundamentals
should win out over hip-hop bravado.
</P>
<P>
   Though the NBA and NBC has its fingers crossed that a glitzy
Knicks-Lakers Finals will lure disenchanted fans back to arenas and
televisions, what the league is more likely to get is a breath of
fresh retro air via an old-school matchup of the fundamentally
sound Utah Jazz and Indiana Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not the most glamorous or controversial teams, but
they definitely play the best team basketball,'' said Phoenix Suns
guard Jason Kidd. ``New York and the Lakers and some other up-tempo
teams would cause a lot of excitement, but I'm not so sure that
good old-fashioned X's and O's wouldn't be better for us. Nobody
that knows basketball would be surprised to see them \RUtah and
Indiana\S playing in the Finals.''
</P>
<P>
   Even before Jordan's departure and the lockout, fans were
nauseated by predictable and stagnant offenses, low-scoring games,
and the off-court legal troubles of Gen-X players.
</P>
<P>
   Though matching the Los Angeles Lakers' Shaquille O'Neal and
Kobe Bryant against the New York Knicks' Latrell Sprewell and
Patrick Ewing would certainly attract coast-to-coast attention, the
general feeling around the league is that nothing will ferry fans
back like fundamental chest passes, basic blocking out, solid
picks, made free throws, clean police blotters and unselfish,
humble play.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, fans who used to watch Jordan are now ready to
watch basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's still a lot of guys who can do things to get you
excited and out of your seat,'' said Milwaukee Bucks guard Ray
Allen. ``But it's more about teamwork and depth now, things I think
fans love to see too.''
</P>
<P>
   Taking advantage of the fall of the Chicago Bulls' empire, the
Jazz, Lakers, Houston Rockets and San Antonio Spurs in the West and
the Pacers, Knicks and Miami Heat in the East are the favorites in
an irregular season that arrives three months late and 32 games
short.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls are gone, but the bull's eye isn't. It's focused
squarely on the Pacers, who return 12 players from the team that
pushed Chicago to a Game 7 in the Eastern Conference finals last
May. Indiana, which added veteran forward Sam Perkins in free
agency, is using that near miss against the Bulls as motivation.
</P>
<P>
   Offered a consolatory victory parade by the city of Indianapolis
last summer, coach Larry Bird politely declined.
</P>
<P>
   ``We told them we'd take a rain check,'' said guard Reggie
Miller, the star of a starting five that averages 32 years of age
and 11 years of NBA experience. ``There is still an emptiness from
Game 7, but over the summer that disappointment turned into
commitment. We're not underdogs anymore, we're the team to beat.
But that's cool, let's rock and roll.''
</P>
<P>
   With everyone from Jordan to Heat coach Pat Riley tabbing the
Pacers as the East's beast, the Knicks' trio of
Sprewell-Ewing-Allan Houston figures to push New York deep into the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   In the West, the Lakers appear to be the biggest, strongest,
fastest, quickest and deepest. But as they proved in last spring's
4-0 loss to the Jazz in the West finals, it's a team that loses its
composure in tight situations, misses too many free throws and has
trouble defending teams with patient half-court offenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can be awesome and intimidating,'' Rockets coach Rudy
Tomjanovich said. ``But in a 50-game season, I don't see anybody
running away with anything.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Lakers grab the spotlight with 24 national television
appearances, the Jazz will try to capitalize on their closing
window of opportunity with the familiar John Stockton-to-Karl
Malone foundation. Utah, which has won 126 regular-season games the
past two seasons, has seen its bench weakened via the departure of
Antoine Carr to Houston.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt the toughest division in basketball will be the
Midwest, also home to the Rockets and their Hall of Fame trio of
Scottie Pippen-Charles Barkley-Hakeem Olajuwon, and the San Antonio
Spurs, who added experienced shooters Mario Elie, Steve Kerr and
Jerome Kersey to complement their David Robinson-Tim Duncan front
(sky)line.
</P>
<P>
   In a wide-open season that should see elite teams winning 40 and
cellar-dwellers like the Los Angeles Clippers struggle to win 10,
the only given is the downfall of the Bulls. With Tim Floyd in Phil
Jackson's coaching chair and Brent Barry in Jordan's shooting guard
spot, the Bulls plummeted from 3-1 favorites in Las Vegas to a
100-1 long shot to win another championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing's for sure,'' Detroit Pistons coach Alvin Gentry
said. ``Nobody's going to feel sorry for the Bulls.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
