<HEADLINE>
NEW DATA AND FED HELP TREASURIES RESPOND TO A FALL
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bond prices fell sharply early Thursday and then cut
their losses as investors tried to sort out several rumors, deal
with new data showing that the economy is still strong and confront
growing fears that the next move by the Federal Reserve will be to
raise interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   All these concerns mean that Friday's employment report could
have a significant effect on bond trading. If the job growth in
January turns out to have been a lot stronger than expected, more
investors will be convinced that interest rates, despite low
inflation, are headed higher. That would touch off further bond
selling and probably help send stocks lower. The Wall Street
consensus for January nonfarm job growth is 138,000, according to
Bloomberg News.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are facing a situation where the Fed has threatened to
tighten if the economy does not slow down,'' said Louis Crandall,
chief economist at R.H. Wrightson &AMP; Associates.
</P>
<P>
   In late trading Thursday, the price of the benchmark 30-year
bond fell 17/32, to 99 15/32. The yield, which moves in the
opposite direction from the price, rose to 5.29 percent from 5.25
percent Wednesday. In the morning session, the bond was off as much
as 1 12/32, and the yield was up to 5.34 percent.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for the rebound appeared to be the indication that
Federal Reserve policy-makers, who left interest rates unchanged
after their meeting on Wednesday, also did not alter their stance
on prospects for future rate moves.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts had been worried that the Fed's stance, which has
been neutral, was shifted to suggest that policy-makers thought
their next move on rates was likely to be an increase.
</P>
<P>
   But the Fed said it would announce any important change in the
stance right after policy meetings rather than waiting until the
release of that meeting's minutes, which are published about six
weeks later.
</P>
<P>
   One rumor that set off selling Thursday concerned Friday's
employment report. Traders said there was talk in the morning that
the Bureau of Labor Statistics had mistakenly printed January's
jobs data on its Internet site ahead of Friday's scheduled release
and that the report showed nonfarm payroll jobs jumped by 350,000
in January, well above forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the bureau said, ``There was no premature
release of the data today.'' In November, the October jobs data was
put out a day early on the bureau's Internet site. And last month,
the producer price index for December was released a day early.
</P>
<P>
   Another rumor was that Japanese investors were selling U.S.
Treasury securities, in part to make up for recent losses in the
Japanese bond market.
</P>
<P>
   A more concrete influence on the market was the economic data,
which were all strong and are forcing Wall Street economists to
revise their growth forecasts upward for the first half of this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Factory orders jumped 2.3 percent in December, to $343.5
billion, a record. At the same time, retailers reported that sales
at chain stores open at least a year climbed 8.3 percent in
January, surpassing forecasts by as much as two percentage points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
