<SLUG> BC-ARAFAT-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TELLS ARAFAT TO EASE ISRAELIS' CONCERNS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton on Thursday warned Yasser Arafat
against declaring Palestinian statehood without an agreement on the
politically explosive issue with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton met with Arafat at the Washington Hilton on Thursday
morning, after both had attended an annual ecumenical prayer
breakfast where Arafat's appearance had touched off a boycott by
some religious groups and members of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   In both his public remarks at the breakfast and privately in his
20-minute meeting with the Palestinian leader, Clinton thanked
Arafat for his efforts toward reconciliation with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   But he prodded Arafat to do more to ease Israeli concerns about
the safety of Jewish residents of territories that come under
Palestinian control.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton reminded Arafat that ``final-status talks'' with Israel
are to begin on May 4 to deal with the most intractable issues,
including sovereignty for Palestinians, the future of Jerusalem,
border security and the allocation of scarce water resources.
</P>
<P>
   Any one-sided efforts by Arafat to address these questions _
particularly Palestinian statehood _ would be resisted by the
United States and certainly by Israel, Clinton said, according to
his aides.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president reiterated the longstanding U.S. position that
unilateral steps are not helpful to the process and this issue is
an issue to be discussed in the context of the final status
talks,'' a senior official said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
