<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS STILL HAVE ECONOMIC FLEXIBILITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ This winter provided two significant events
regarding the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   General manager Doug Melvin could not pry right-hander Roger
Clemens from the Toronto Blue Jays, and the organization witnessed
a substantial increase in its payroll.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the Rangers will retain the financial flexibility
to acquire Clemens or others who become available via trade this
season. This despite an Opening Day payroll that could climb to $75
million with the contractual result of arbitration-eligible
right-hander Aaron Sele.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always hope that we would have flexibility,'' Rangers
president Tom Schieffer said. ``I think we recognize that at some
point in time you have to do some fine-tuning on even the best of
ballclubs. We know that's the case, and we try to plan for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Tom Hicks has proven that if you can go to him and
say, `This gives us a better chance to win,' then he will do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hicks, the Rangers' owner, appeared willing to renegotiate
Clemens' existing contract during Melvin's dogged pursuit of the
five-time Cy Young Award recipient throughout November. The
Rangers, though, could not satisfy the Blue Jays' demands, and
discussions ceased.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not much has happened. I think Clemens is going to stay with
Toronto,'' Schieffer said, ``and if they're in it, he'll stay there
all year. If they're not in it, my guess is they'll start talking
about it again near the trade deadline. That's not to say something
couldn't happen before then, but it doesn't have the feel of
something that's about to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens, though, might not be the only front-line pitcher who
could become available this season. Oakland's Kenny Rogers,
Cincinnati's Denny Neagle, Philadelphia's Curt Schilling, Kansas
City's Kevin Appier and Minnesota's Brad Radke loom as potential
trade acquisitions near the July 31 deadline.
</P>
<P>
   The significance of the Rangers' July 31 additions this past
season cannot be dismissed. Right-hander Todd Stottlemyre,
shortstop Royce Clayton and third baseman Todd Zeile helped the
Rangers secure their second American League West title in three
seasons, but their services did not come without a steep price.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers parted with left-hander Darren Oliver, third baseman
Fernando Tatis and three minor-league players and inherited more
than $2.6 million in additional player salaries for the season's
final two months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we would have won if we had not made those moves
last year,'' Schieffer said. ``We felt that with those moves we
could win, and we did win. We also felt with those moves that we
could go further than we did.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' postseason experience proved brief. The eventual
World Series champion New York Yankees dismissed the Rangers with a
three-game sweep in their best-of-five, AL Division Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought that the Yankees had a better team than we did on a
162-game basis, but we thought we might be able to sneak up on them
in a five-game series,'' Schieffer said. ``The fact of the matter
is we pitched well enough in that five-game series to sneak up on
them, but they pitched better. They were obviously a team of
destiny in 1998, but if you ask me: `Could we have won without
making those trades?' I don't think so.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made the trades, and we won the division. It gave us the
opportunity to go further, but unfortunately it didn't work out.
It's not all bad, though, to continue to win around here. It was a
long time before we won the first time, and now we've won two of
the past three years. We would rather have a winning tradition
established than just a tradition of futility.''
</P>
<P>
   The Commissioner's Office computed the Rangers' 1998 payroll to
be the seventh-highest at $67,956,293. That includes $5,576,415 to
cover health and pension benefits, medical costs, insurance,
workmen's compensation, unemployment and Social Security taxes,
spring training allowances, meal money, All-Star Game expenses,
travel and moving expenses, postseason pay and college
scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   Schieffer expects that figure to climb to $81 million or $82
million this season, yet the Rangers will retain the financial
flexibility to inherit additional player salaries this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope that we don't have to do that,'' Schieffer said. ``We
hope that everyone will be clicking along, and we'll be 10 or 15
games ahead and don't have to make any moves. It's not just the
money at that point and time. It's the prospects you have to give
up.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we would love to be able to do is go through a season and
not give up any prospects, but the first thing we want to do is
win. We're prepared to do what it takes to win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
