<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-TRIAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE DENIES IMPEACHMENT MANAGERS LIVE LEWINSKY TESTIMONY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate, in a crucial blow to the beleaguered
House impeachment managers, Thursday rejected a last-ditch plea for
Monica S. Lewinsky to testify in President Clinton's trial, opting
instead to permit videotaped testimony by the former White House
intern in a nationally televised session Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   With a growing number of Republicans hungry for the trial to end
and wary of hearing live testimony on the Senate floor about
Clinton's sex scandal, 25 GOP senators joined the united Democratic
minority to block Lewinsky's appearance, in a surprisingly lopsided
vote, 70-30.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, the Senate voted, 62-38, to grant the House
team's ``fall-back'' request: to show video clips of Lewinsky and
two other witnesses in a three-hour presentation Saturday of the
evidence against the president. The White House lawyers also will
have three hours for their presentation.
</P>
<P>
   The moves keep the Senate on track to complete the historic
trial by next Friday, Feb. 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a critical day, and guarantees now that we're moving to
the final phase of the impeachment trial,'' the Senate majority
leader, Trent Lott, said afterward.
</P>
<P>
   The White House, which has increasingly escalated its attacks on
Senate Republicans for voting last week to continue the trial, saw
hope in Thursday's action. ``Today's vote rejecting the House
managers' request for live witnesses indicates the Senate appears
ready to bring this trial to a conclusion,'' said White House
spokesman Joseph Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
   The developments unfolded as Republicans, facing unanimous
Democratic opposition, also effectively dropped their bid for a
bipartisan plan to cite Clinton for wrongdoing during the trial
without convicting him.
</P>
<P>
   Rising in its place was an alternative proposal to censure
Clinton outside the impeachment proceedings, which also faces major
obstacles, despite marginal GOP support.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the scramble for an exit strategy, the House Republican
managers abruptly scaled back their quest for live testimony,
requesting only Lewinsky's appearance, and abandoning their plan to
seek additional subpoenas for Clinton's friend Vernon E. Jordan and
White House adviser Sidney Blumenthal.
</P>
<P>
   But even that tactic failed. The aversion to summoning Lewinsky
to the Senate floor was so powerful that only one New Englander
voted for the request: Senator Bob Smith, a New Hampshire
Republican, who is considering running for president.
</P>
<P>
   Only the most conservative GOP senators, including Lott, voted
to hear Lewinsky tell her account on the Senate floor of her role
in Clinton's alleged attempt to cover up his sexual affair with
her. Two articles of impeachment allege that Clinton committed
perjury and obstructed justice to conceal the relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is time to bring this impeachment trial to an end,'' said
Senator James M. Jeffords, a Vermont Republican, who until Thursday
had voted for the House team to proceed with its case against
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky, who has been questioned 23 times about Clinton's sex
scandal, issued a statement Thursday expressing relief at the
Senate's decision to spare her from a public interrogation in the
well of the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Monica and her family are pleased she does not have to go
through the painful and humiliating ordeal of having to testify on
the floor of the Senate,'' said a spokeswoman for Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   In the vote to permit showing parts of the videotapes, Jeffords
joined Senator Olympia J. Snowe of Maine as the only Republicans to
oppose showing the images of Lewinsky, Jordan and Blumenthal in
their presentation Saturday. All three witnesses gave private,
videotaped depositions earlier this week, which the senators later
viewed privately.
</P>
<P>
   ``The depositions served their purpose,'' Snowe said. ``I don't
think we would have gained any new information by seeing edited
versions of them on the Senate floor.''
</P>
<P>
   Nine Democrats broke party ranks to support the House request to
show the videotapes, including one New Englander: Senator Joseph I.
Lieberman of Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   A subsequent motion by Senator Patty Murray, a Washington
Democrat, to permit written transcripts rather than videotapes in
the presentations was defeated, 73-27, with 20 Democrats joining
all but one Republican, Snowe, in opposing the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman and Senator John F. Kerry were the only New England
Democrats to oppose Murray's motion.
</P>
<P>
   The House managers, who wanted to call as many 15 witnesses to
the Senate floor when the trial began, grudgingly endured the
latest in a series of restrictions on their case.
</P>
<P>
   Despite nearly unanimous agreement that Clinton will be
acquitted, members of the House team argued they deserved the right
to present their case at least partly on their terms. And the
strain showed several times as they were rebuffed yet again.
</P>
<P>
   ``If one senator has failed to personally sit through'' the
videotaped deposition, Representative James F. Rogan of California
said during the trial, ``that senator is not equipped to render a
verdict on the impeachment trial.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, when White House lawyers asked for advance notice of the
video clips the House intends to play Saturday, Rogan quoted a
former California judge as saying, ``It's none of your damn
business what the other side is going to put on.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republican majority supported the House managers on that
point, 54-46, with only Jeffords breaking ranks in either party.
</P>
<P>
   But Rogan's remarks further bristled Democrats, who have
complained for days that Senate Republicans are prolonging the
trial only to satisfy their conservative base and save face for the
House managers.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry, who argued unsuccessfully for the White House to have
ample time to prepare to rebut the House presentation, denounced
Rogan's comment as ``arrogant and inappropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   For an hour Thursday, the House team argued that the depositions
had produced sigificant new evidence to require Lewinsky's live
testimony or the videotaped presentation.
</P>
<P>
   Citing portions of Lewinsky's deposition, Representative Asa
Hutchinson of Arkansas asserted that Lewinsky set up a meeting last
year with Jordan to try to ``cushion the shock'' of her friend
Linda R. Tripp possibly disclosing details of the president's
affair with Lewinsky. An excerpt from the deposition quoted
Lewinsky as saying she had never told Clinton that she had confided
in Tripp about the relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``So that was sort of my intention in meeting with Mr. Jordan,
was hoping that I could give a little information and that would
get passed on,'' she testified.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan, who had testified before a federal grand jury that he
never had that breakfast meeting with Lewinsky, conceded in his
Senate deposition that the meeting occurred. In addition, Jordan
acknowledged that he discussed notes that Lewinsky had written to
the president, but he did not corroborate Lewinsky's assertion that
he had told her, ``Go home and make sure they're not there.''
</P>
<P>
   Hutchinson asserted that Jordan acted as Clinton's ``agent'' in
illegally trying to coneal his affair with Lewinsky from lawyers in
a sexual harassment suit that Paula Corbin Jones filed against the
president and settled last year for $850,000. As part of the
alleged effort, Jordan helped find Lewinsky a job in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The transcripts show that Jordan undertook the search on
Clinton's behalf at the behest of the president's personal
secretary, Betty Currie. ``There is no question but that through
Betty Currie I was acting on behalf of the president to get Ms.
Lewinsky a job,'' Jordan said in his Senate deposition.
</P>
<P>
   The House managers alleged that Jordan helped find Lewinsky the
job to encourage her to file a false affidavit in the Jones case.
When Jordan learned that Lewinsky completed the affidavit,
according to a transcript of his deposition, he told Clinton, ``Mr.
President, she signed the affidavit.''
</P>
<P>
   Complete transcripts of the three depositions are to be made
public Friday as part of the Congressional Record. Copies of the
videotapes are not expected to be released until after the trial.
</P>
<P>
   But special White House counsel Gregory B. Craig argued before
the Senate that the depositions yielded ``no bombshells'' or
``dynamite'' that warranted Lewinsky's video clips to be shown.
</P>
<P>
   Forshadowing Saturday's session, Craig warned that permitting
the House managers to show their ``greatest hits'' from the
videotapes could prompt the White House to respond in kind. ``This
would be a duel of snippets,'' Craig said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the current format, the trial will not be in session
Friday, as the House managers and Clinton's lawyers prepare for the
presentations Saturday and their closing arguments on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   With the trial winding down, both sides struggled to bridge the
partisan gulf to find an agreement on a sanction of Clinton short
of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Edward M. Kennedy lashed out at the Republican ``finding
of fact'' plan, which would cite Clinton for wrongdoing during the
trial. ``It would turn the Senate into a kangaroo court,'' Kennedy
said. ``I don't think Senator Lott wants to go down in history as
the chief kangaroo.''
</P>
<P>
   Snowe, a key sponsor of the ``finding of fact'' plan, said the
proposal is dead without Democratic backing. She said she remained
open to a possible censure after the trial, but she harshly
criticized a proposal that several Demcorats floated Thursday to
temporarily suspend the trial next week to impose the censure.
</P>
<P>
   ``That sounds like a real political concoction if I ever heard
one,'' Snowe said. ``That is really trying to jury-rig the
Constitution during an impeachment trial to achieve what they want
as a political goal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
