<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HAWKS05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hawks aim high with eager veteran lineup ready for opener vs.
Cavs
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ No, these are not the same old Atlanta Hawks.
</P>
<P>
   Given scant preparation time, they are better trained and better
prepared than they have any right to be.
</P>
<P>
   They are feisty and confident, maybe a little cocky, because
they figure they have a little secret. And that is how good they
can be.
</P>
<P>
   This is a team that says it wants to win and acts like it
intends to win _ with the caveat that it hasn't been tested. But
that is why they play the games, the first of which is tonight at
the Georgia Dome against the Cleveland Cavaliers.
</P>
<P>
   When the lockout ended last month, the Hawks were in a
rebuilding mode, prepared to ride out a rough season while looking
ahead to next year's free-agent market and the move into a new
arena. But a series of signings altered their thinking. So, while
construction continues on their future home, the Hawks will go to
work in the Dome and Alexander Memorial Coliseum with lofty
immediate goals.
</P>
<P>
   With an abbreviated road to travel _ 50 games in place of 82,
because the lockout shortened the season _ the Hawks have given the
public some information to go on.
</P>
<P>
   The returning veterans on the team _ Dikembe Mutombo, Steve
Smith, Mookie Blaylock and Tyrone Corbin _ last spring challenged
their coach to make them work harder, to set the standards higher
for practice, to set down tough rules of conduct.
</P>
<P>
   That was their commitment coming out of last season's bitter
disappointment, a first-round playoff loss. They held up their end
throughout the lockout by training hard, playing together in a
loose approximation of the unified drills that have brought such
acclaim to the Indiana Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   The club brought back the same five players who finished the
season but will not put the same starters on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Corbin, 35, has been replaced by LaPhonso Ellis, signed Saturday
after Denver renounced him.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis is easily the highest-rated small forward the Hawks have
had since Danny Manning raced Dominique Wilkins out of town in
1994. Corbin isn't even the backup, at this point. The Hawks are
going with rookie Roshown McLeod, although a strained left
hamstring might hold him back the next few days.
</P>
<P>
   In itself, that move signifies an upgrade for the bench, but
there is more. Anthony Johnson, a second-year player out of College
of Charleston, moves behind Blaylock at the point. At 6 feet 3 with
a natural point guard's instincts, Johnson was good enough to start
62 games at Sacramento last season.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Gray, who appeared in only 30 games before re-fracturing his
right foot, has shown startling offensive skills and has displayed
a more businesslike attitude in his second season. His talent is
such that the Hawks did not go after Dell Curry, a dangerous
scorer, when Charlotte elected not to re-sign him.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle, the Hawks acquired Mark West, a 15-year veteran,
to play behind Mutombo. As recently as two years ago, West logged
about 13 minutes a game in Cleveland. That's about what the Hawks
are asking.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, in a move critical to team moral, the Hawks brought
back another veteran, Grant Long, who plays behind starting power
forward Alan Henderson. Smart, tough and well-conditioned, Long is
that rare performer who talks and plays the same game.
</P>
<P>
   The14-member roster _ which shrinks to 12 on Feb. 19 _ is
rounded out with forward Chris Crawford and rookie guards Shammond
Williams and Jeff Sheppard. Center Scot Pollard, acquired with a
draft pick from Detroit for Christian Laettner, was placed on the
injured list Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Is coach Lenny Wilkens happy? Oh, yes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a terrific camp,'' he said Thursday. ``We really got
after it. The players were hard on each other, so much so that I
wanted to make our final practice easier, because I didn't want to
take the risk of getting anybody hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, other than McLeod's accident _ he stepped on a
teammate's foot _ and Pollard's severe bout of flu, the Hawks came
through eight days of double sessions without incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other than having so many guys join us late, everything was
exactly what I wanted,'' Wilkens said, a reference to days lost
before Henderson and Corbin signed contracts and free agents Ellis
and Long, who had been a Hawk for two years before, made their
decisions. The former got in five days' work, the latter four.
``And when they came in, they were all business,'' Wilkens said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grant has the benefit of knowing the system, but I'm relying
on the goodwill of my teammates,'' Ellis said. ``When I get lost,
they help me out.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellis might have trouble learning some of the terminology, but
he was Mutombo's teammate in Denver for four years, and that gives
him a leg up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may take LaPhonso and (me) a couple games to get into the
swing of it,'' Long said. ``I know the plays, but I still have to
think a second. But that will pass. We'll be OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilkens said, ``They'll be fine. I'm not worried about them. I'm
so delighted with what they bring to our team.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only is this by far the deepest team Wilkens has had since
coming to Atlanta in 1993, Smith, the team's leading scorer at 20.1
points a game, thinks it also will prove to be the toughest.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got some solid pros on this team, guys who play with
their hearts and their head,'' Smith said. ``I'm committed to
stepping up. I'll set a tone. So is Mookie. Alan is an emotional
younger guy, and Grant is an emotional older guy. Ty and Mark are
smart veterans. Dikembe's got a lot of pride. Our rookies are
smart, and they have good leaders to follow.''
</P>
<P>
   HAWKS ROSTER
</P>
