<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-BRIEFS05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Who's who in NBA's Class of '99
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   MOST LIKELY TO SUCCEED
</P>
<P>
   _ EAST: Indiana. Last year, in Game 7 of the Eastern Conference
finals, the Pacers were five points short of upsetting the Bulls.
They return the entire team, plus wily veteran forward Sam Perkins.
It seems only an injury to Reggie Miller could derail the Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   _ WEST: Los Angeles Lakers. Shaquille O'Neal is determined to
take this talented bunch to the summit, and with the development of
Kobe Bryant and the influence of newly acquired Derek Harper, don't
bet against him in the truly wild West.
</P>
<P>
   MOST DRAMATIC CHANGES
</P>
<P>
   _ EAST: New York. With the addition of explosive personalities
in Latrell Sprewell and Dennis Scott, the Knicks changed the fabric
of their team. They no longer are tough and grinding, now that
Charles Oakley and John Starks have departed.
</P>
<P>
   _ WEST: Sacramento. The Kings, perpetual doormats, gave up
All-Star guard Mitch Richmond, but they acquired big men Chris
Webber and Vlade Divac to go with rookie guard Jason Williams and
rising star Corliss Williamson. They're no longer the team you want
to face to end a losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   LEAST IMPROVED
</P>
<P>
   _ EAST: Washington. Mitch Richmond and Rod Strickland form a
star backcourt, but the Wizards have no center, no small forward
and a bench made up of nobodies. They're doomed for their usual
finish place of .500 or lower.
</P>
<P>
   _ WEST: Minnesota. Stephon Marbury likely will be a better floor
leader, but the loss of Tom Gugliotta is significant. Former No. 1
pick Joe Smith signed as a free agent, but his game is suspect.
Once thought to be a team on the rise, the Timberwolves are frozen
in neutral.
</P>
<P>
   MOST LIKELY TO SURPRISE
</P>
<P>
   _ EAST: Cleveland. The Cavaliers added only forward Johnny
Newman to their young, talented core, and that's all they needed.
With Mike Fratello in charge, they'll contend.
</P>
<P>
   _ WEST: Portland. The Trail Blazers have a quality starting
five, and the addition of defensive point guard Greg Anthony and
scorer Jimmy Jackson make them even deeper and more dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   CLASS CLOWNS
</P>
<P>
   _ EAST: Chicago. Oh, how the mighty has fallen. Bring a roster
with you to the game to identify the Bulls. It's not even right to
call them the ``defending champions.'' How are they going to have a
championship-ring ceremony with the core spread around the league?
</P>
<P>
   _ WEST: Clippers. Well, they are the Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
