<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2435 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBA-PREVIEW05-COX     02-04 1220
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-PREVIEW05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Post-Jordan title hopes widespread
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The NBA will get a new champion this year; that much
is certain. But who will it be? And how?
</P>
<P>
   The other teams had to feel ambivalent last month when Michael
Jordan retired and the Chicago Bulls' management subsequently
dismantled the three-time titlists so that it probably will be
years before they are competitive again. Surely, the clubs that
Jordan has whipped over the years hated to see him go. Any true
competitor would like the chance to pay back his nemesis.
</P>
<P>
   However, winning a championship is so difficult and so rewarding
that the other pervasive feeling when Jordan bid adieu had to be _
hallelujah. With him gone, the title chase became a free-for-all,
attainable by almost any contender.
</P>
<P>
   The pace of free-agent signings and trades was frenetic, after a
labor lockout that delayed the start of the season three months. At
one point, movement backed up because the league office couldn't
handle the overflow of business.
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, the deals were done with the idea of winning it
all now. ``There are at least a half-dozen teams poised to make a
real good run at it now that Chicago is out of it,'' Miami Heat
coach Pat Riley said. ``Michael Jordan and his cast no longer loom
over the confidence of other teams. Teams have to be excited
knowing they are not suffering _ and painfully so _ at the hands of
Michael Jordan. I don't see one dominant team that can take your
confidence away in a game.''
</P>
<P>
   And so, optimism reigns around the league. The season, usually
82 games per team, begins its shortened version of 50 tonight. With
it, clubs have placed an urgency on finding a rhythm quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The teams that have been together the longest should have a
distinct advantage,'' Sacramento Kings coach Rick Adelman said.
``People think that the offense will be a big factor because of
that. But I think the teams that'll be much further along are going
to be the teams that get off to a good start at stopping people.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston, which won two championships in the years Jordan did not
play an entire season during his first ``retirement,'' has risen
from a club on the border to the upper echelon, with the
acquisition of Jordan's brilliant sidekick, Scottie Pippen. After
coach Phil Jackson and Jordan retired, Chicago signed Pippen and
dealt him to Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``With (Hakeem) Olajuwon, Charles (Barkley) and Pippen, Houston
has three of the top 50 players in NBA history,'' Los Angeles
Lakers coach Del Harris said. ``With those three, you have to
consider them the wild card.''
</P>
<P>
   Many other wild cards are out there, too. In the Eastern
Conference, the Indiana Pacers took the Bulls to seven games in the
conference finals last year. Added to their veteran nucleus of
Reggie Miller, Mark Jackson and Rik Smits was Sam Perkins, the
lanky big man who can defend the low post and hit the 3-point shot.
Perkins played in the NBA Finals with the Los Angeles Lakers and
the Seattle SuperSonics.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Pacers should be brimming with confidence,'' Washington
Wizards coach Bernie Bickerstaff said.
</P>
<P>
   The feeling in New York is that the Knicks will be confident,
too _ in time. The Knicks, who vowed never to acquire players with
questionable character, went out and traded for the notorious
coach-choker, Latrell Sprewell. With the addition of Sprewell and
Marcus Camby, New York got younger and more athletic. But in giving
away Charles Oakley and John Starks, the Knicks lost their heart
and soul.
</P>
<P>
   In the Western Conference, back-to-back runner-up Utah welcomes
back old hands Karl Malone, John Stockton and Jeff Hornacek, but
key backup big man Antoine Carr bolted for Houston.
</P>
<P>
   After the expected period of shoddy play, it should be an
exciting race, Harris said, because ``the West is loaded.''
</P>
<P>
   The San Antonio Spurs have their big, talented front line of
David Robinson and Tim Duncan. The Lakers added stabilizing force
Derek Harper to their ultra-talented mix. Phoenix, which lost
Antonio McDyess to Denver, made out by signing free agent Tom
Gugliotta, a better all-around player.
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal considers this his and the Lakers' year. ``No
more excuses,'' the game's dominant big man said.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the Bulls' certain demise, any predictions are risky.
Teams played only two exhibition games apiece, six fewer than
usual. Some All-Atars, including Cleveland's Shawn Kemp and Miami's
Tim Hardaway, came into camp after the lockout grossly out of
shape.
</P>
<P>
   Coaches wrestled with how strenuously to work their teams. In
Washington, Bickerstaff went so far as to hold practices three
times a day. It's an unprecedented move, but one Bickerstaff deemed
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time is of the essence,'' he said. ``From a conditioning
standpoint, I wanted to push them. You can't put five weeks of
regular camp into two. But you can do your best.''
</P>
<P>
   Many coaches say they'll use the first month of the season
monitoring minutes played more than diagramming X's and O's.
``Definitely,'' Golden State coach P.J. Carlesimo said, ``I'll
coach differently early. You have to play guys in spurts more so
than extended minutes. Until they get into the kind of game shape
they would be coming out of a normal training camp, you have to
make sure you don't keep a guy out there too long.''
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of injuries hung over the brief camps. Miami's
Voshon Lenard, New Jersey's Kerry Kittles and Charlotte's Glen Rice
and Anthony Mason are among those out for extended periods _ Mason
for the season. But it could have been worse.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't help that several teams have gone through a major
revamping of rosters, meaning the shortened preseason made it even
more difficult to mesh new players with old ones. All in all, it
was '``an interesting experience,''' Nets coach John Calipari said.
</P>
<P>
   How interested will fans be in the games? The NBA has mandated
lower ticket prices around the league in an effort to extend itself
to its followers. But the early indications were that it'll take at
least half and maybe all of the season to rekindle interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about the product,'' Milwaukee guard Ray Allen said. ``We
know they're upset with the product, but if we put a quality
product out there, the real basketball fans will come back.''
</P>
<P>
   One effect of smaller crowdscould be that the home-court
advantage is lessened because of fan apathy resulting from
post-lockout bitterness. In Miami, the Heat filled only half of its
arena for a preseason game against intrastate rival Orlando. And
the tickets were free.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can't give tickets away, I don't know what we can do,''
Heat center Alonzo Mourning said.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the playoffs roll around, the hope is that spectator
passion will have returned. By then, a number of teams could
challenge for a title that might have been unavailable if Jordan
had not left the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a reality,'' Detroit's Joe Dumars said. ``It's wide
open for everyone. It's a shortened season, no dynasty _ every
reason in the world for teams to feel like they can get that ring.
So, while it wasn't good for the game that Michael retired, it was
great for a lot of teams.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
