<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2436 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-TERROR-550&AMP;A     02-04 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-TERROR-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMBASSY SECURITY BUDGET IS FAR LESS THAN PANEL URGED 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JAMES RISEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration budget to upgrade
embassy security around the world is far less than the
recommendation that an independent review panel made last month.
</P>
<P>
   But State Department officials said a new White House working
group was reviewing whether to increase the budget request to build
more embassies and comply more closely with the findings of the
review board. The panel was established after the bombings of two
U.S. Embassies in East Africa in August.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department has asked Congress for $300 million to
improve security and construct embassies in the new budget year.
The department has asked for another $300 million the next year,
the last budget that the Clinton administration will submit.
</P>
<P>
   Those figures fall well short of the $1.4 billion a year in new
security spending recommended last month by the independent
accountability review board. The panel, led by a retired admiral,
William J. Crowe Jr., investigated the two embassy bombings.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright told a Senate
Appropriations subcommittee on Thursday that budget constraints had
limited her department's ability to match the panel
recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   State Department officials later said that the budget request to
Congress had been drawn up before the independent panel's
recommendations and that State Department officials had joined the
White House group that is looking for ways to increase the budget
proposal.
</P>
<P>
   The administration's proposal was criticized on Thursday by Sen.
Judd Gregg, R-N.H., and chairman of the Appropriations
subcommittee. Gregg noted that the State Department would quickly
fall billions of dollars behind the Crowe panel's recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   ``At some point your ability to rebuild and your ability to fix
up these embassies is going to outstrip the money that's been put
in the budget for you,'' Gregg told Albright. ``Those numbers are
not going to work.''
</P>
<P>
   State Department officials acknowledged that the budget figures
did not come close to the recommendations, but said they believed
that they represented a ``good start'' on new construction. The
administration plans to spend $36 million next year to build new
embassies, to buy sites and to and design up to seven new
embassies.
</P>
<P>
   The department will ask for an additional $268 million to
continue to pay for new security measures included in a $1.4
billion emergency supplemental budget that Congress approved last
year. That comes on top of the $350 million that the department
usually budgets for diplomatic security, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   To stay under limits imposed by budget laws, the administration
has proposed to spend $300 million in 2001 and $450 million in
2002. The administration has asked for a total of $3 billion over
five years beginning in 2001 to build 50 to 60 embassies.
</P>
<P>
   The money would not reach its peak of $900 million until 2005.
The five-year spending plan that begins with the fiscal year 2000
would spend $2.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The administration wants Congress to lock in future spending in
this year's budget. ``Our fear is that people will lose the urgency
that they now have in the wake of the embassy bombings, and so we
want to lock it in now,'' said a spokesman for the State
Department.
</P>
<P>
   (STRY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   Although congressional officials said they favored added
spending on embassy security, Congress rarely makes such long-term
budget commitments.
</P>
<P>
   The budget problems are eerily reminiscent of those that
confronted the State Department in the mid-1980s, when another
independent panel investigated another embassy bombing and
recommended another ambitious spending program.
</P>
<P>
   After the bombing of the Embassy in Beirut, Lebanon, in 1983, a
panel headed by another retired admiral, Bobby Inman, urged the
building of dozens of new and more secure embassies. The board
criticized the State Department for not taking security seriously
enough and recommended that the government rebuild most of its
foreign posts.
</P>
<P>
   But after initially embracing the findings and building a few
embassies, the State Department and Congress gradually abandoned
efforts to put into effect the recommendations at most embassies.
</P>
<P>
   Although Albright has said she takes the Crowe panel findings
seriously, administration and congressional officials made it clear
Thursday that they were not very likely to match its ambitious
spending levels.
</P>
<P>
   Gregg is not now willing to give the State Department an
exemption from the budget caps, an aide said. He wants the
department to find money from other parts of its budget, and that
would make the task far more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's a priority you can find money to fund it,'' the aide
said. ``Then you find out what is truly important.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
