<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECH SHARES DOWN SHARPLY THURSDAY; NASDAQ FELL 3.3 PERCENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Please note that the word STAR in parentheses has been used
in the second graf instead of the symbol, which is
non-transmittable to some newspaper systems.) 
 (af)  
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Computer-related shares fell sharply Thursday,
dragging the NASDAQ composite index down 3.3 percent, its biggest
loss in more than five months, as Merrill Lynch cut its estimate on
Intel's profits for 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The skid in high-technology stocks reverberated elsewhere, but
less severely, in a session also marked by frantic activity in the
stocks of online brokerage houses amid temporary shutdowns for a
second day in the processing system at E(STAR)Trade, the No. 3
Internet broker.
</P>
<P>
   The NASDAQ composite fell 83.34 points, its third-biggest point
drop ever, to 2,410.07. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index fell
23.58, or 1.85 percent, to 1,248.49. The Dow Jones industrial
average held up relatively better and even nosed briefly into
positive ground in the afternoon before slipping 62.31, nearly 0.7
percent, to 9,304.50.
</P>
<P>
   One measure of the wild swings in technology shares was Siebert
Financial, a minor player in the online brokerage industry, which
soared as high as 70| from Wednesday's close of 49{ and then dived
after the attorney general of New York said he was investigating
the ability of online brokers to process large numbers of trades.
The stock ended with a loss of 6\, at 43\.
</P>
<P>
   Other factors weighed on the market as well. Saying stocks had
simply become too expensive, Douglas R. Cliggott, the top U.S.
equity strategist at J.P. Morgan Securities, recommended lowering
holdings in stocks to 50 percent from 60 percent, putting 25
percent in cash and keeping bonds at 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on current 30-year Treasury yields and our guess at
first-quarter corporate earnings, the S&AMP;P 500 is now 16 percent
rich relative to our fair value measure,'' Cliggott said.
</P>
<P>
   To justify today's prices, he added, profits would have to rise
12 percent this year and bond yields would need to drift back
toward 5 percent. He said such an outcome was not very likely.
</P>
<P>
   Considerable money was also shifting Thursday from technology
and other highflying issues into economically sensitive areas like
the paper industry. Union Camp rose 3 7/16, to 67|; Georgia-Pacific
was up 3 3/16, to 69 15/16, and International Paper, the
second-best performer among the Dow industrials, climbed 2|, to 44
3/16. The best performer was another such stock, Alcoa, which
jumped 3|, to 86 11/16.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see profit taking in the recently strong tech stocks, and
some money flowing into cyclicals,'' said Robert H. Stovall,
president of Stovall/21st Advisers.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft was the biggest drag on the S&AMP;P 500, falling 7}, to
159 1/16. Intel was right behind, falling 8 9/16, to 130[; followed
by Lucent Technologies, down 7[, to 102~; Cisco Systems, off 5~, to
105\; General Electric, down 2}, to 100[, and Dell Computer, off
5{, to 102].
</P>
<P>
   Internet shares other than brokers were also pummeled, with Ebay
slumping 39\, to 239; Yahoo falling 21 1/16, to 337, and Amazon.com
declining 7}, to 118. ``It was a pretty bleak day,'' said Neil T.
Eigen, a managing director at J&AMP;W Seligman. ``A lot of these
Internet stocks have paused.''
</P>
<P>
   Advanced Micro Devices, Intel's biggest rival in chips,
announced that it might report an operating loss for the first
quarter after having been expected by Wall Street to earn 13 cents
a diluted share. Trading was halted, and the stock fell 2 1/16, to
18~.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest drag on the Dow, accounting for almost 40 percent of
its decline, was IBM, which fell 5 11/16, to 169 9/16. AT&AMP;T lost 3
9/16, to 91 7/16, and J.P. Morgan fell 3], to 100~. Morgan was one
of several weak bank issues.
</P>
</TEXT>
