<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2455 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-MANAGERS-NYT &LR;      02-04 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-MANAGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANAGERS FIND THEIR HOPES ARE FRUSTRATED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Ark., Ill., Calif.)  (See also IMPEACH-TRIAL, IMPEACH, IMPEACH-ASSESS, IMPEACH-SCENE,
IMPEACH-LEWINSKY, IMPEACH-REPUBS) 
(mk) 
 By LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The hangdog look on their faces was unmistakable as
they sat waiting for the make-or-break votes Thursday, at the
prosecutors' table on the Senate floor.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the House managers' best arguments, all those
concessions they believe they made, 70 Senators rose to their feet
Thursday and, in effect, voted to bring the trial to an end next
week without calling a single live witness.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could argue they didn't have a trial,'' said Rep. Bill
McCollum, R-Fla., one of the House managers. ``Is that frustrating?
Of course, it has been frustrating. Is it frustrating every day?
There is a point after which it's not frustrating personally
because you know it's just going to be that way.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But it isn't the thing we think is right,'' McCollum added.
``I don't think history will judge them well for making that
decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Since they crossed the divide between the House and Senate, the
13 House prosecutors in the impeachment trial have faced a string
of hurdles before a Senate eager to shoosh them up, politely, but
unfailingly.
</P>
<P>
   Publicly and privately, they have been lambasted for their
zealousness, criticized for their political naivete and
strong-armed into ditching their grandiose plans for a ``full
trial.'' A self-righteous bunch, their critics say.
</P>
<P>
   In the beginning they wanted as many as 12 witnesses to tell
their tales in the well of Senate. It never happened. They wanted
President Clinton to testify. He never did. Even their hopes for
taking reams of depositions were downsized. They deposed three
witnesses, and even then they were forced to choose: Betty Currie
or Vernon Jordan, the president's secretary or his confidante.
Jordan won out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really are coming from different worlds,'' said Rep. Asa
Hutchinson, R-Ark., one of the House managers, referring to the
House and the Senate. ``From the very beginning we're thinking
like, a real trial, and they are thinking in terms of the unique
procedures.''
</P>
<P>
   As they walked off the Senate floor Thursday, the House
prosecutors tried to flash the best light on the Senate's decision.
They said they were ``well-received'' by the Senate overall, and
some even talked about the bonds they have formed with certain
Senators.
</P>
<P>
   And they spoke again of obligation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The House has given us a responsibility,'' Hutchinson said.
``They did not tell us to go to the Senate for a few days and throw
up our hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., the chairman of the Judiciary
Committee and the lead prosecutor, softened his tone a bit. Asked
whether the Senate was considering any of his recommendations early
in the day, he replied, ``They didn't hang up on me, let's put it
that way.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They've treated us nicely,'' said Hyde. ``I regret the
implication that there is friction between us.''
</P>
<P>
   But nick the surface, and prosecutors say it has been difficult
not to smell a whiff of condescension from the well-scrubbed
Senate, no matter how courtly their manner.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchinson said that, while the prosecutors have been treated
respectfully, despite their pleas for more witnesses and a heftier
investigation, the gang of 13 can't help but quip about their
second-class status when they get together for meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a little bit of humor that goes around the committee,
a sense of being unwanted from time to time, and we joke about
it,'' Hutchinson said. From that has sprung a sense of camaraderie.
``We have had a lot of rocks thrown at us,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   It was clear to McCollum that senators screen the Senate
chamber, searching for breaches of decorum, just as mothers at a
debutante ball might crane their necks to root out undesirables.
That attitude, he said, helped stymie the prosecutors' case for
witnesses, especially Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just didn't want to, as White House counsel said, sully
the Senate floor,'' McCollum said. ``It wasn't a question of right
or wrong, fairness, good, bad or indifferent. It was just something
about letting Monica Lewinsky come to the floor. They didn't want
to let that happen. I didn't agree with that. It's a Senate thing,
I guess.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. James Rogan, R-Calif., who is one of the managers,
complained about the lack of ``ham sandwiches'' in the Senate
cloakroom, when asked about his disappointment with the other
chamber.
</P>
<P>
   But it was Hyde who best summed up the relationship between the
Senate and the 13 prosecutors, at least through the eyes of the
prosecutors. ``You view us as reformed alcoholics,'' Hyde told a
senator one afternoon, a big grin on his face. ``You're very proud
of what we attempted to do in our lives. You just don't want us
hanging out on the porch all that long.''
</P>
</TEXT>
