<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-TOBACCO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: `TOBACCO BONDS' FOR SCHOOLS  (DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Friday, Feb. 5:
</P>
<P>
   In a city of crumbling bridges, aging water pipes and antique
computer systems, there is no more urgent capital priority than
building and repairing schools.
</P>
<P>
   Last week Mayor Rudolph Giuliani proposed a novel way of tapping
an additional $2.5 billion for New York City schools in the next
five years. He wants to create an agency that would issue bonds for
school construction, paying them off with revenues expected from
the settlement of New York state's lawsuit against tobacco
companies. Although we were initially skeptical, the idea is worth
pursuing if its problems can be resolved.
</P>
<P>
   The need for school expansion and repairs is beyond doubt. The
Board of Education has proposed a five-year, $11 billion program to
create room for a flood of new students and to upgrade existing
facilities. In his latest budget, Giuliani said the city would
supply $6 billion of the funds, with the rest coming from federal
and state sources.
</P>
<P>
   But the city faces a problem in finding the money, as it is at
the limits of its borrowing capacity. The state Constitution limits
debt to a fixed percentage of the value of the city's real
property, a ceiling reached a couple of years ago. The state
Legislature in 1997 created a new city agency with borrowing
authority, but now even this agency is close to its cap.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than ask the Legislature to increase the cap for this
agency, Giuliani wants the city to create another new corporation
to issue $2.5 billion in bonds, secured by $6.7 billion in revenue
from the tobacco settlement over the next two decades.
</P>
<P>
   Both the mayor and the city comptroller, Alan Hevesi, must
investigate potential legal problems, including the current dispute
over whether any of the tobacco money might have to be shared with
the federal and state governments. In addition, there is some
skepticism in Albany that the city can create a new debt-incurring
agency without legislative approval.
</P>
<P>
   Ideally, Giuliani should have used the city's
multibillion-dollar surpluses to pay down debt or pay for capital
projects. Some worry that too much of the budget is being siphoned
off for debt service. Still, if the legal and financial problems
can be cleared up, tapping the tobacco funds seems a prudent step
to rebuilding the city's deteriorating school system.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
