u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-ART-NYT     02-04 1150
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS ENDGAME NEARS, SENATORS ON BOTH SIDES MANEUVER FOR POSITION
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Texas, Idaho, Utah, Ala., R.I., Iowa, Calif., N.Y., Maine,
Okla., Neb., Conn., Fla.)  (See also IMPEACH-TRIAL, IMPEACH-ASSESS, IMPEACH-SCENE,
IMPEACH-MANAGERS, IMPEACH-LEWINSKY, IMPEACH-REPUBS) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subsribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A Senate Republican proposal to rebuke President
Clinton's misconduct all but collapsed Thursday after Democrats
closed ranks to reject it. Democrats immediately promoted their own
plan to censure the president, but that version received a cool
reception from many Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   With an end to the four-week impeachment trial in sight and
Clinton's acquittal virtually preordained, both parties are
jockeying to express their dismay at the president's behavior and
protect themselves from any public backlash that Clinton is eluding
punishment.
</P>
<P>
   While they may sound similar, the competing reprimands serve
different purposes. Republicans want the Senate to stipulate that
Clinton lied under oath and obstructed justice, but not remove him
for that. Democrats want to condemn the president's behavior but
clear him of any impeachable offense.
</P>
<P>
   The impasse the senators struck Thursday was as much over the
timing of any vote on the rival rebukes _ before or after the vote
on the articles _ as on their actual wording. Each side is also
trying to wrap their resolution in the mantle of bipartisanship, a
tall order at this point.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans sought to approve a ``findings of fact'' that
concluded Clinton committed wrongdoing without removing him from
office. Under this approach, senators would vote on the findings
before the final impeachment votes and, if approved, the findings
would become a part of the official trial record. Convicting the
president would require 67 votes, but the findings-of-fact would
need only a 51-vote majority.
</P>
<P>
   Republican sponsors said they would put the motion up for a vote
only if at least five Democrats backed the plan. When none did
Thursday, saying it was unconstitutional, Republicans all but
pulled the plug on the proposal. ``It's in desperate need of a
life-support system,'' said Sen. Larry Craig, R-Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   Majority Leader Trent Lott refused just yet to pronounce the
idea dead, saying after Thursday's proceedings that senators ``will
keep talking about that.''
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats, led by Dianne Feinstein of California, rushed to
fill the void and revived their idea for a freestanding censure, to
be considered outside the trial proceedings. Mrs. Feinstein said
her two-page proposal _ which she declined to make public Thursday
_ focused on the president's misconduct while the findings-of-fact
gleaned their essence from the two impeachment articles, perjury
and obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Robert Bennett, R-Utah, embraced the censure resolution and
sought support for it among other Republicans. At least two other
Republicans, John Chafee of Rhode Island and Richard Shelby of
Alabama, said Thursday they would support a rebuke. ``A censure
resolution that is thorough, tough and bipartisan would be in
order,'' Shelby said.
</P>
<P>
   But most other Republicans oppose censure or are deeply
skeptical. ``We want finality, and that's a `guilty' or `not
guilty' vote, and let the chips fall where they may,'' said Sen.
Charles Grassley, R-Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. James Inhofe, R-Okla., who opposes censure and
findings-of-fact, said, ``Anything that we do that's outside the
parameters of what we originally talked about is offering political
cover.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, said he is so opposed to censure that
he left the door open to waging a filibuster to block it.
</P>
<P>
   A compromise suggested Thursday by Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan,
D-N.Y., would be to adjourn the trial briefly next week, vote on
the Democratic censure plan, and then resume the trial to vote on
the impeachment articles.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we wait to vote on censure, there'll be members on their
side who will be mad and members on our side who'll say, `It's
over. Let's leave it that way,'' Moynihan said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   This approach would likely win virtually unanimous Democratic
support and perhaps that of many Republicans, and sidestep the
Democrats' concern of making a reprimand a part of the formal
impeachment record.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans, however, dismissed this idea as a gimmick.
``Now that sounds like a real concoction,'' said Sen. Olympia
Snowe, R-Maine, an author of the findings-of-fact. ``That is really
trying to jury-rig the Constitution and the impeachment trial in
order to achieve what they want as a political goal.''
</P>
<P>
   A bipartisan agreement seemed miles apart Thursday night, though
many senators said that was the tonic the impeachment proceedings
needed right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``A joint censure is the only way to do this at this point,''
said Sen. Bob Kerrey, D-Neb. ``Once the leadership is committed to
do it, it will not be that difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott, who supports the findings of fact, said senators had until
Wednesday to hammer out a resolution.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The trial is in recess Friday, to allow the House prosecutors
and White House lawyers time to prepare for Saturday's session,
when each side will have up to three hours to show portions of the
videotaped depositions.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Closing arguments are to begin Monday, and senators could begin
their deliberations Tuesday. There will be a vote to suspend the
rules, which require closed deliberations, and open the final
debate to public viewing.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Between now and then, senators said there would likely be
intense activity off the Senate floor to win a majority for a
censure or findings-of-fact resolution.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, for example, are still hoping to persuade a few
Democrats, like Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut and Bob Graham of
Florida, to embrace the findings-of-fact. But Democratic aides said
Thursday night it was highly unlikely any Democrats would defect
now.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sensing that senators might not be able to bridge this partisan
divide, Republicans and Democrats were already preparing defenses
against the charge that, without some form of rebuke, the president
would be vindicated of all wrongdoing.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think any president that has been impeached and tried
by the Senate, even though he may not be removed, could feel like
he's gotten off scot-free,'' Lott said.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Finding a graceful way to end the acrimonious proceedings will
be a challenge, most senators concede. ``Sometimes when you get
right in the middle of a storm, it's difficult to see all the
details,'' Kerrey said. ``Right now, I think everybody but us has
got it figured out that we're all standing here buck-naked, and
we've just got to end it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
