A2460 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-HASTERT-NYT &LR;      02-04 0376
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-HASTERT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: HASTERT STUMBLES  (DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Friday, Feb. 5:
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Hastert, the new House speaker, says he wants to avoid
the blunders of his predecessor, Newt Gingrich. He is headed in the
wrong direction. The other day Hastert said that campaign finance
reform would stay on the back burner while lawmakers take up Social
Security, health care, tax and spending issues. That course would
effectively bury a reform bill that commands overwhelming
bipartisan support and can be passed quickly.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign reform measure sponsored by Reps. Christopher Shays
of Connecticut and Martin Meehan of Massachusetts passed the House
last year by a vote of 252 to 179. Sixty-one Republicans defied
Gingrich and supported the bill. Republicans say even more of their
party members would be willing to get aboard this year if Hastert
does not make campaign reform a partisan issue, as Gingrich did.
</P>
<P>
   The question is whether the new speaker will let Republicans
vote their consciences or follow the demands of Tom DeLay, the
party whip. DeLay was the new speaker's biggest booster, but now is
the time for Hastert to declare his independence and show that he,
and not his former benefactor, is in charge.
</P>
<P>
   The Shays-Meehan bill would ban ``soft money'' donations to
political parties, closing a loophole through which corporations,
special interests, rich donors and labor unions have poured money
into political campaigns. If the bill can get to the Senate by
March, there will be time to build pressure on Trent Lott and other
Republican leaders to let the majority of senators win passage
there. The danger is that if action does not occur soon,
congressional and presidential candidates will already be embarked
on raising hundreds of millions of dollars in unregulated soft
money for their campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, when Gingrich tried to block the bill, House members
organized a petition forcing it to the floor. Greatly embarrassed,
Gingrich retreated and eventually allowed a vote. Supporters of
reform should get ready for the same tactics to pressure Hastert.
Better yet, he should heed their demands and bring the bill to the
floor now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
