<HEADER>
A2467 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIDS-TESTS-630&AMP;ADD-NY     02-04 1096
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDS-TESTS-630&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 TESTS MAY HELP FIGHT DEVELOPMENT OF DRUG RESISTANCE IN AIDS
VIRUS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By LAWRENCE K. ALTMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Two new laboratory tests promise to improve therapy
for individuals with drug-resistant strains of the AIDS virus and
to reduce the risk that the virus will develop resistance in others
who are newly infected, researchers said at the close of a five-day
AIDS meeting here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Drug resistance has become a critical factor in the failure of
potent drug cocktails in many individuals infected with HIV, the
AIDS virus. Studies have shown that resistance can result when
individuals do not adhere to prescribed regimens, allowing the
virus to change and become resistant to the medication. Other cases
result when an individual infected with a resistant virus transmits
it to another person.
</P>
<P>
   HIV can develop resistance to any of the marketed drugs, and
over time the virus can develop cross-resistance to all members of
the three main classes of anti-HIV drugs: nucleosides,
non-nucleosides and protease inhibitors. By identifying genetic and
other markers in the virus that indicate drug resistance, doctors
hope to use one or both of the tests to match more precisely the
drugs prescribed with the virus strain identified in the patient.
</P>
<P>
   Drug resistance is estimated to affect only a small percentage
of infected individuals now, said Dr. John W. Mellors of the
University of Pittsburgh. But he said health officials were
concerned that further spread could increase the problem of
resistance and wipe out some gains made in AIDS therapy in the last
three years.
</P>
<P>
   One new method, genotype testing, pinpoints genetic mutations in
HIV. The second method, phenotype testing, determines the degree of
susceptibility or resistance of HIV when it is grown in a test tube
after the addition of selected drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The tests have different limitations and the findings need to be
interpreted carefully. Genotyping is easier to perform and costs
$200 to $400 a test, as against a cost of $700 to $1,000 for
phenotyping. Because phenotyping is done in test tubes, the
findings may not necessarily predict what happens in the body.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists have been using both tests in many research studies,
and many doctors now use them in prescribing drugs for some
patients. But wider application of the tests to routine patient
care is still about a year away for a number of reasons,
participants at the Sixth Conference on Retroviruses and
Opportunistic Infections said.
</P>
<P>
   Much needs to be learned about precisely when and how often
either or both tests should be used in patient care. ``We are still
in infancy in understanding the relationship'' between test
findings and therapeutic success, Mellors said.
</P>
<P>
   Experts have begun drafting the first recommendations for the
tests, and they are expected to be issued as early as this summer,
Dr. Robert T. Schooley, a meeting official, said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Among the questions that scientists need to answer are these:
Which, if any, of the tests should be used when anti-HIV drugs are
first prescribed? Should the tests be used only when drugs begin to
fail?
</P>
<P>
   A number of studies are now showing that experts have been wrong
in some of their earlier practices in treating drug resistance.
</P>
<P>
   Mellors said scientists had assumed that when a patient was
taking a combination of drugs and it failed, the virus had
developed resistance to all drugs in the combination. ``We now know
that that is not the case,'' Mellors said. ``Usually one drug in
the combination fails, and which one depends on which drugs are in
the combination.''
</P>
<P>
   The expectation is that with findings from the tests, doctors
can now focus on changing the resistant drug, not the entire
combination. However, people at the conference cautioned that
studies are needed to document that such an approach will work.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Precise figures on the frequency of HIV drug resistance are
lacking because there is no national tracking system. Experts can
make estimates only from small studies.
</P>
<P>
   Mellors cited two studies looking at the frequency of resistant
virus among individuals who were infected within the past two
years. About 3 percent of newly infected individuals had HIV
resistance to the anti-HIV drugs belonging to the nucleoside group,
from 5 to 15 percent had resistance to the non-nucleoside drugs,
and from 1 to 10 percent had resistance to the protease inhibitor
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Resistance figures for the protease inhibitors is lower because
they were generally marketed latest, giving them less time to
develop resistance, Mellors said. In recent years, doctors have
used a test that measures the viral load, or number of AIDS viruses
in the blood, to guide drug therapy.
</P>
<P>
   Genotyping helped improve the short-term therapeutic success in
a study carried out in several hospitals that Dr. John D. Baxter of
Cooper Hospital/University Medical Center in Camden, N.J., reported
here on Thursday. The study included 153 patients whose viral load
rose after 16 weeks of treatment with drug cocktails, indicating
that the drugs were failing.
</P>
<P>
   The patients agreed to be divided into two groups. In one group,
the study leaders told the patients' doctors about the findings of
the genotype tests and advised them on the drug regimen. In the
other group, the doctors were not informed of the genotype
findings. After three months, more members of the group that
received expert advice had less HIV in the blood than did members
of the group that did not receive such advice.
</P>
<P>
   The time period is far too short to draw firm conclusions about
the effectiveness of using drug resistance tests to reduce the
guesswork in prescribing anti-HIV drugs, participants said.
</P>
<P>
   The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention in Atlanta, the
federal agency that is responsible for tracking HIV, is using
genotyping as it begins to develop a national surveillance system
for the incidence of HIV drug resistance. The monitoring is similar
to the centers' efforts to track drug-resistant strains of
gonorrhea, another sexually transmitted disease, Dr. Harold W.
Jaffe, a CDC official, said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   With time, the agency intends to use both genotyping and
phenotyping with the aim of detecting trends in resistance and
determining which populations are most affected, Jaffe said. The
information will then be used to make treatment guidelines, as in
gonorrhea and tuberculosis.
</P>
</TEXT>
