<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-HORSES-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAFFERT THREE-PEAT?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA, Calif. _ The balance of power among Kentucky Derby
candidates tilts toward California this winter, and the difference
is the heavyweights in trainer Bob Baffert's barns at Santa Anita.
</P>
<P>
   In stall 15, there's Exploit, dozing through a dull Thursday
morning. In 18, Prime Timber is stretching his neck and snorting at
a visitor. In 25, Forestry is tethered to the back wall.
</P>
<P>
   Across a dirt road, in stall 32, Finder's Gold is glaring at a
passerby, ears pinned against his dark head. In 36, General
Challenge is nuzzling a hay bale, specks of feed on his white face.
</P>
<P>
   Rarely are so many Derby contenders found in one place, even 12
weeks before the May 1 race at Churchill Downs.
</P>
<P>
   But for Baffert, boasting wins in the past two Derbies with
Silver Charm and Real Quiet, the hard part isn't attracting top
3-year-olds, it's plotting prep schedules for all of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only plan I have is to get them to the Derby,'' Baffert
said, half-joking.
</P>
<P>
   The local countdown begins in earnest Saturday when Exploit, No.
1 in most national 3-year-old rankings, starts his season in the
7-furlong San Vicente Stakes, a step toward the April 3 Santa Anita
Derby.
</P>
<P>
   Here are our rankings, which might be titled So Many Horses, So
Little Space:
</P>
<P>
   1. Prime Timber: Son of Sultry Song, winner of the 1\-mile
Hollywood Gold Cup in 1992, the Aaron Jones-owned colt ran second
to since-sidelined Tactical Cat in the Hollywood Futurity, which
was the springboard for Real Quiet, A.P. Indy, Best Pal, Alysheba,
Ferdinand and Snow Chief. He's recovered from a heel bruise and
virus and aiming for Santa Anita's San Rafael on Feb. 28.
</P>
<P>
   2. Exploit: Much-hyped after skipping the Breeders' Cup to go 4
for 4 as a 2-year-old _ including stakes wins at Churchill _ for
owners Bob and Beverly Lewis. Some doubt his breeding (Storm Cat)
and style (aggressive) fit 1\ miles. On the other hand, a loss in
the San Vicente, a sprint after a 10-day layoff, shouldn't be held
against him.
</P>
<P>
   3. Cat Thief: Dull third in last week's Hutcheson sprint is
excusable (see Exploit). He'll stay at Gulfstream Park to prep for
the March 13 Florida Derby in the Feb. 20 Fountain of Youth.
</P>
<P>
   4. General Challenge: California-bred from Golden Eagle Farm won
third in a row _ and new respect around the country _ in last
week's Santa Catalina. Baffert has three of our top four.
</P>
<P>
   5. Aly's Alley: Used a Derby-style rally to be second in
Breeders' Cup Juvenile at Churchill for low-profile trainer John
Tammaro. Next: Fountain of Youth.
</P>
<P>
   6. Millions: Laurel Futurity winner was a good second in the
1[-mile Remsen, which produces good 3-year-olds in New York the way
the Hollywood Futurity does here.
</P>
<P>
   7. Vicar: Trained by Carl Nafzger (Unbridled), the son of Wild
Again chased Exploit home in the Kentucky Jockey Club and was a
troubled fifth as the Holy Bull Stakes favorite at Gulfstream.
Next: Fountain of Youth.
</P>
<P>
   8. Worldly Manner: Won Del Mar Futurity for Baffert, then was
sold to Sheikh Mohammed of Dubai, where he'll prep for the Derby
with training races. A Daily Racing Form cartoon showed turbaned
carpenters erecting a Churchill Downs replica in the desert.
Anything's possible when you own a country.
</P>
<P>
   9. Answer Lively: Maligned Breeders' Cup Juvenile winner was a
puzzling seventh at the New Orleans Fair Grounds last week. Don't
panic about early-season results. Real Quiet was eighth in his 1998
debut.
</P>
<P>
   10. The Groom is Red: It wouldn't be Derby season without
trainer Nick Zito. Give Rick Pitino-owned Champagne Stakes winner
one more chance (in the Fountain of Youth) after his allowance-race
loss Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The second 10: 11. Excellent Meeting and 12. Silverbulletday,
the Baffert fillies; 13. Honest Lady, Bobby Frankel's girl; 14.
Finder's Gold, whom Baffert may point for the March 14 Louisiana
Derby; 15. 6-furlong San Miguel winner Cape Canaveral; 16.
early-blooming Belmont Futurity winner Lemon Drop Kid; 17. smart
maiden-breaker Forestry; 18. Chief Minister, who might be Victory
Gallop trainer Elliott Walden's best since Bet Me Best is hurt; 19.
Menifee, another Walden colt; and 20. Certain, 4 for 4 around two
turns in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   20 to follow: Zito's Cryptodiplomacy, Adonis, Doneraile Court
and Wondertross; trainer Ron McAnally's late-starting Crowning
Storm, Domination and Apremont; Blue Tune and Epic Honor, second
and first for trainer Jeff Bonde in Golden Gate Derby; Holy Bull
winner Grits'n Hard Toast, winner of the Smoke Glacken Award for
worst name; Norfolk winner Buck Trout; Lecomte upsetter Some Actor
and runner-up Desert Demon; Remsen winner Comeonmom, in Dubai with
Worldly Manner; sprint rocket Texas Glitter; Remsen also-ran
Casanova Star; Mountain Range, 13th in the Lecomte; Lisa
Lewis-trained Capsized; and San Vicente entrants Futural and
Aristotle.
</P>
<P>
   To be updated in the weeks ahead.
</P>
<P>
   __ The weekend: Exploit's 3-year-old debut in the San Vicente is
only a warmup act on a Santa Anita weekend that features Saturday's
Strub and Sunday's San Antonio Handicap.
</P>
<P>
   The Strub, for 4-year-olds, is Event of the Year's and rider
Corey Nakatani's race to lose now that San Fernando winner Dixie
Dot Com is injured. Dr Fong (Gary Stevens) and Quake (Chris
McCarron) join the troupe.
</P>
<P>
   The Saturday card starts at noon.
</P>
<P>
   The San Antonio opens the 5-year-old campaign of Free House
(McCarron). He was assigned 123 pounds, four to seven more than his
opponents, including Malek (Alex Solis) and possibly Cavonnier
(Stevens).
</P>
<P>
   __ Eddie D. countdown: One reason for the popularity of Eddie
Delahoussaye, who is two wins from becoming the 14th jockey with
6,000, is his sparing use of the whip. Typical was A.P. Indy's 1992
Breeders' Cup Classic victory. Delahoussaye never struck the colt.
</P>
<P>
   He recalled recently: ``Everybody said, `Why didn't you hit him?
It's a $3 million race!' I said, `Why'd I want to hit him? He's
running!' Simple as that.'' &QL; 
A WEEK AT THE RACES
</P>
<P>
   __ Santa Anita leaders: Jockeys (through Wednesday): Alex Solis,
33 wins; David Flores, 25; Gary Stevens, 21, Chris McCarron, 19;
Kent Desormeaux and Laffit Pincay, 18. Trainers: Bob Baffert, 13;
Bobby Frankel, 10; Ron McAnally, 9; Richard Mandella, 8; Wally
Dollase, 7.
</P>
<P>
   __ Handicapper helper: Post position 1 _ closest to the rail _
is as tricky as ever in Santa Anita sprints, producing only eight
winners so far, just over half its fair share. Horses with early
speed can overcome the disadvantage; five of the eight winners led
gate to wire.
</P>
<P>
   __ On the stakes schedule: At Santa Anita: Saturday, $500,000
Strub Stakes, 4-year-olds, 1[ miles, $150,000 San Vicente,
3-year-olds, 7 furlongs, and $125,000 Pro or Con Handicap,
California-bred fillies and mares 4 and up, 1 mile on turf; Sunday,
$300,000 San Antonio Handicap, 4-year-olds and up, 1[ miles, and
$200,000 La Canada, 4-year-old fillies, 1[ miles. At Gulfstream
Park: Saturday, $$200,000 Gulfstream Park Breeders' Cup Handicap,
3-year-olds and up, 1] miles on turf.
</P>
<P>
   __ Mileposts: Paul Mellon, who died in Virginia on Monday at age
91, was the only owner to win the Kentucky Derby (with Sea Hero,
1993), Epsom Derby and Prix de l'Arc de Triomphe (both with Mill
Reef, '71). He owned American horses of the year Fort Marcy ('67)
and Arts and Letters ('69) and was voted the nation's leading owner
and breeder ('72). . . . On his first day riding after 16 months of
weight and personal problems, jockey Chris Antley was disqualified
from second to fourth in a turf race Wednesday at Santa Anita, the
DQ resulting in a three-day suspension. Welcome back. . . .
Wednesday's eighth-race superfecta paid a Santa Anita-record
$130,540.80 for $1. Laffit Pincay swept a $974.80 late double. . .
. Donn Handicap winner Puerto Madero is aiming for the March 28
Dubai World Cup and probably will skip the March 6 Santa Anita
Handicap, second stop in the NTRA's 11-race series for older
horses. Missing the Big 'Cap would cost owners R.D. Hubbard and
Dwight Sutherland a shot at a $5 million bonus for sweeping the
series' five major races. Silver Charm, third as the Donn favorite,
is shooting for the Big 'Cap. . . . Free House trainer Paco
Gonzalez, 53, broke a collarbone when he was thrown while galloping
another horse Wednesday at Hollywood Park. . . . American
racetracks paid a record $978.3 million in purses in '98, up 6
percent from '97, the fifth increase in a row, the Jockey Club
announced. Wagering set a record at $13.6 billion, of which a
whopping 81 percent was bet off-track. . . . And the beat goes on:
Santa Anita has agreed to send its races out over the Youbet.com
interactive computer wagering system. . . . Ariel Smith, the
16-year-old apprentice who made nary a dent here, is third in the
Aqueduct standings behind Aaron Gryder and Rene Douglas. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of New York: New York Gov. George Pataki proposes to
raise the takeout on non-win-place-show bets from 25 to 27 percent.
Throw the bum out!. . . . Gulfstream Park jockey Jocy Gomez was
suspended 15 days for concealing extra weight in her clothes for
prerace weigh-ins and then removing it before races; her horses
would carry about two pounds less than their assignment. Gomez
denied it. Whatever she did, it wasn't working, because she'd
ridden two winners at the month-old meet. . . . Jockeys' win
percentages rarely tell the whole story: Corey Black (18.6 percent)
started the week at Santa Anita 11 for 43 in sprints, 0 for 16 at 1
mile and up, and 0 for 12 on turf. . . . Canterbury Downs in
Minnesota will host the first Claiming Crown Aug. 7 _ a six-race,
$560,000, Breeders' Cup-style program for claiming horses. Nice
idea, some caviar for the horse world's blue-collar workers. . . .
Harness driver Rick Kuebler began the week at Los Alamitos eight
wins from 3,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
