<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 21:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2471 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-FRANCE-NYT     02-04 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-FRANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR ALL SIDES IN KOSOVO, A SECLUDED RENDEZVOUS
</HEADLINE>
  (See also KOSOVO-US) 
(bl)  
By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   RAMBOUILLET, France _ The former royal French hunting castle
where peace negotiations on Kosovo are to start Saturday is a world
away from Wright-Patterson Air Force Base in Dayton, Ohio, where
similar talks led to an uneasy peace for Bosnia in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Dayton bristled with intimidating U.S. military might and
technological prowess. Rambouillet, whose inhabitants call
themselves Rambolitains, is a backwater tourist attraction
subsisting on past glory. The cozy 18th-century brick castle
attached to a 14th-century stone dungeon tower lies at the edge of
town, about 30 miles south of Paris.
</P>
<P>
   French Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine and British Foreign
Secretary Robin Cook, the co-chairmen of the talks, will formally
open the negotiations Saturday afternoon. The tall iron gates will
then be closed, French officials say, leaving the Serbian, ethnic
Albanian and international negotiators inside to talk, eat and
sleep in the 30-bedroom castle until they produce an accord.
</P>
<P>
   ``The principle is to force the different parties to work out an
agreement, and communication is not the first priority,'' Bernard
Valero, a French Foreign Ministry official, said, indicating that
blow-by-blow accounts would come from the participants, if at all,
not from the organizers.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, the negotiators will be cooped up until they produce
an agreement that gives the province, which is 90 percent ethnic
Albanian, some sort of autonomy from Serbia for a three-year
interim period.
</P>
<P>
   They will have no more than two weeks from Saturday to agree,
and if they do, Britain, France, the United States, Germany and
other countries are expected to send in 20,000 to 30,000 troops to
keep the peace. If there is no agreement, NATO warplanes could
attack Serbian military targets, unless the Albanian side is the
main obstacle to peace.
</P>
<P>
   Isolation, or at least as much as is possible in the age of
portable phones, and the ever present pressure of possible military
intervention were the keys to success in Dayton.
</P>
<P>
   But then as now, the real key to peace was held by Slobodan
Milosevic, the leader of the side whose brutal attacks against
civilians finally made the international community ready to use
military force.
</P>
<P>
   And though Milosevic went to Dayton, he is not expected to come
to Rambouillet, but instead to send a delegation led by a deputy,
Milan Milutinovic. Milutinovic told the chief U.S. negotiator in
the Dayton talks, Richard Holbrooke, in 1995 that he would have no
authority or flexibility in any talks on Bosnia because, he said,
``the Master,'' meaning Milosevic, ``will pull all the strings.''
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke, whose relationship with all the protagonists and
whose connections with the Clinton administration were crucial to
success at Dayton, will not be in Rambouillet either.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those considering other Daytons should proceed with caution,''
Holbrooke wrote in his memoir of the Bosnia talks, ``To End a
War,'' published last year by Random House.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a high-wire act without a safety net,'' he went on.
``Much work must precede the plunge into such an all-or-nothing
environment. The site must be just right. The goals must be clearly
defined. A single host nation must be in firm control, but it is
high risk for the host, whose prestige is on the line. The
consequences of failure are great.''
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview, Holbrooke said he would be in daily
telephone contact with the lead mediator in the Rambouillet talks,
Christopher Hill, the U.S. ambassador to Macedonia, who was also
Holbrooke's chief deputy in the Dayton negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Hill has developed the kind of relationship with Serbian and
Kosovo Albanian representatives that he and Holbrooke had with
Serbian, Croatian and Bosnian leaders in Dayton.
</P>
<P>
   And it was Hill who, with a European Union negotiator, Wolfgang
Petritsch, developed the framework for the negotiations that Cook
presented to both sides last weekend, along with an ultimatum for
the Serbs to appear at the talks or face NATO bombing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all going to come down to Chris, who's been designated
the Contact Group negotiator, not the American one,'' Holbrooke
said, referring to the six-nation group _ the United States,
France, Britain, Italy, Germany and Russia _ that called the talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the chances are greater than 50-50 for an acceptable
outcome,'' Holbrooke said. ``The key to the whole thing is a
permitted entry into Yugoslavia by NATO ground troops, and the
allies will be there if we're there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
