Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- Feb. 4, 1999 -- PEANUTS-THEATER-REVIEW-1,
2-04 -- The ace: Roger Bart as Snoopy in ``You're a Good Man,
Charlie Brown.'' The play was inspired by Charles M. Schulz's
long-running ``Peanuts'' comic strip. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) VARADERO, Cuba -- Feb. 4, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., FEB. 7
-- CUBA-TOURISM-3-COX, 2-04 -- The cash-strapped Cuban government
spent $8 million to open this 18-hole golf course, the first built
in Cuba since the 1959 revolution which brought Cuban President
Fidel Castro to power. The manicured course just steps from the
popular beach was enlarged from a nine-hole course on the
expropriated property of the du Pont family. (Rick McKay/Cox News
Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) HAVANA -- Feb. 4, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., FEB. 7 --
CUBA-TOURISM-2-COX, 2-04 -- A shopper looks over some of the many
t-shirts available at a shop near one of the tourist hotels in
Havana recently. Portraits of Cuban revolutionary leader Ernesto
``Che'' Guevara dominate many of the shirts in the store that sells
goods in exchange only for U.S. dollars. Over the past five years
the number of tourists visiting Cuba from Canada, Italy and other
foreign countries has doubled, to 1.4 million a year. An estimated
85,000 Americans visited surreptitiously last year. (Rick McKay/Cox
News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) VARADERO, Cuba -- Feb. 4, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., FEB. 7
-- CUBA-TOURISM-1-COX, 2-04 -- Tourists on Varadero Beach. With 15
miles of pristine beaches, Varadero, a city of 19,000 just 90 miles
east of Havana, has long been a tourist magnet. Over the past five
years, the number of tourists visiting Cuba from Canada, Italy and
other foreign countries has doubled, to 1.4 million a year. An
estimated 85,000 Americans visited surreptitiously last year,
flying in from Mexico, the Bahamas, or other foreign locales. (Rick
McKay/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- Feb. 4, 1999 --VOGEL-DRAMA-PRIZE, 2-04 -- Mo
Gaffney, left, and Swoosie Kurtz in ``The Mineola Twins,'' a play
by Paula Vogel, a Pulitzer prize winning playwright. Bringing that
sense of home to the theater has been Ms. Vogel's way for decades.
(Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) MINNEOLA, N.Y. -- Feb. 4, 1999 -- VOGEL-DRAMA-PRIZE-1,
2-04 -- Playwright Paula Vogel near a local water tower. Vogel, 47,
who won the Pulitzer prize for drama last year, was once rejected
by the Yale School of Drama and also turned away by the prestigious
Eugene O'Neill Playwrights Conference - 12 times. The play for
which she won the Pulitzer, ``How I Learned to Drive,'' about the
incestuous relationship between a girl and her uncle, had a
successful run Off Broadway and was the most produced new play in
America last year, with 26 regional productions. (Sara Krulwich/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- Feb. 4, 1999 -- OUR-YOUTH-THEATER , 2-04 --
Mark Ruffalo and Missy Yager in a revival of Kenneth Lonergan's
drama ``This Is Our Youth.'' The play, a dark comedy which follows
three post-adolescents on the Upper West Side through a bungled
cocaine deal, reopens Sunday night at the Douglas Fairbanks Theater
on Theater Row. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK-- Feb. 4, 1999 -- ORGAN-MUSIC , 2-04 -- Organist
Jon Gillock at the Riverside Church recently. Western music has
generally moved far from its origins in plainsong and other kinds
of religious chant, but one instrument, the organ, has never been
able to heave itself out of the church. (Chang W. Lee/New York
Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- Feb. 4, 1999 -- OKLAHOMA-REVIVAL, 2-04 --
Susan Stroman, center, the Broadway choreographer, with the Martha
Graham troupe members rehearsing''Gershwin Graham'' in October of
1997. Stroman received enthusiastic reviews of the revival of
``Oklahoma!'' at the Royal National Theater in London last July.
Almost everyone declared that the show really deserved its
exclamation mark and that Ms. Stroman, a two-time Tony Award
winner, was a prime participant in making this new version a hit.
(Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- Feb. 4, 1999 -- DEATH-OF-SALESMAN-REVIVAL,
2-04 -- Kevin Anderson, playing Biff, left, and Brian Dennehy, in
the lead role as Willy Loman, during rehearsals for a new Broadway
production of ``Death of a Salesman'' opening on the play's 50th
anniversary. The play has become an institution, part of the
accepted theater canon, and today even boasts its own website,
where, in an ironic twist on its central theme, you will be able to
purchase souvenirs. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
