<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 2/4/99. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) NEW YORK -- Feb. 4, 1999 -- BKN-KNICKS-VANGUNDY, 2-4 --
Jeff Van Gundy clinging to the leg of the Miami Heat center Alonzo
Mourning last April, allowing himself to be dragged around the
floor like a rodeo clown. Over the last three years, Van Gundy has
been his players' tireless protector and defender through flagrant
fouls, fights and suspensions. With the reputation Van Gundy has
constructed, it is no wonder that Latrell Sprewell, upon his
introduction as a Knick, referred to Van Gundy as a ``player's
coach.'' (G. Paul Burnett/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) SAN FRANCISCO -- Feb. 4, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., FEB. 7
-- INVEST-WITH-YOCKEY, 2-04 -- Mark Yockey near his office. In
managing his fund, he shops for European companies with
profit-minded management. (Peter DaSilva/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) DRESHER, Pa. -- Feb. 4, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., FEB. 7 --
SALESMANSHIP, 2-04 --Selling need not be painful for either seller
or buyer, according to Jacques Werth, right, who built his theories
on his sales experience and his observation of other sellers. He
listened to a BMW salesman. (Laura Pedrick/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) CHICAGO -- Feb. 4, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., FEB. 7 --
CLEESE-MANAGE-TRAINING, 2-04 -- John Cleese speaking at the
Training 99 Conference and Expo. Cleese, who has a law degree from
Cambridge University, has been making management training videos
for the last 25 years. (Steve Kagan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. -- Feb. 4, 1999 --ADV. FOR SUN.,
FEB. 7 -- BIZ-PROFILE-EGAN, 2-04 -- Michael Egan leans on ``Horn
Blower,'' a sculpture by Eduardo da Rosa, at the offices of Dancing
Bear Investments. Egan's passion is building companies. (Susan
Greenwood/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) NEW YORK -- Feb. 4, 1999 -- SUSPECT-DEATH-N.Y., 2-04 --
Ahmed Diallo, top, an unarmed African immigrant with no criminal
record, was shot and killed early Wednesday morning by four New
York City police officers who fired 41 shots at him in the lobby of
the man's Bronx apartment building, the police said. Neighbors
looked at the shooting scene in the photo below. (Bottom: Richard
L. Harbus/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) UNDATED -- Feb. 4, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., FEB. 7 --
CAR-SMART-REARDOORS, 2-04 -- The third door on the Saturn coupe,
seen here, is not the usual so-called ``suicide door'' from the
1960's. The biggest difference between those doors of old and the
rear-hinged access door on the three-door Saturn coupe, and some
extended cab pickups, is that the rear doors cannot be opened
unless the front door is opened as well. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) WASHINGTON -- Feb. 4, 1999 -- HUSSEIN-3-B&AMP;W, 2-04 --
From lower foreground left: Jordan's King Hussein, Sen. Joseph
Lieberman, Abraham Daskal, late Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak
Rabin and President Clinton at the White House in July 1994. Daskal
was a friend of the Hussein's grandfather, King Abdullah. Gravely
ill, King Hussein left a U.S. hospital on Thursday accompanied by
his wife and family members after cancer treatment seemed to have
been unsuccessful. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) WASHINGTON -- Feb. 4, 1999 -- HUSSEIN-2, 2-04 -- From
left: King Hussein of Jordan, Israeli Prime Minister Yitzak Rabin,
President Clinton, Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak walk towards the Rose Garden of the White
House to sign the Middle East peace accord in September 1995.
Gravely ill, King Hussein left the Mayo clinic in Rochester, Minn.,
on Thursday, after an unsuccessful bone marrow transplant and was
flying home to Jordan, accompanied by his wife and family members.
(Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) WASHINGTON -- Feb. 4, 1999 -- KOSOVO-U.S., 2-04 --
Secretary Madeleine Albright reads off a teleprompter as she
addresses the United States Institute of Peace the involvement of
U.S. troops in Kosovo. President Clinton, speaking for the first
time about sending U.S. ground troops to Kosovo, said it was better
to act sooner rather than later to stop violence between Serb
forces and Albanian separatists. Albright spoke on the same subject
later in the day at a hastily arranged speech to the institute.
(Carol T. Powers/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) WASHINGTON -- Feb. 4, 1999 -- HUSSEIN, 2-04 -- Jordan's
King Hussein, center, reaches out to late Israeli Prime Minister
Yitzhak Rabin as President Clinton applauds at the White House
before a meeting on the Mideast peace process in July 1994. Gravely
ill, King Hussein left a U.S. hospital on Thursday accompanied by
his wife and family members. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) WASHINGTON -- Feb. 4, 1999 -- CONGRESS-TERROR, 2-04 --
Louis Freeh, director of the FBI, left, speaks with Attorney
General Janet Reno during a hearing on terrorism by the Senate
Appropriations Committee on Capitol Hill on Thursday. According to
testimony by Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, the Clinton
Administration plans to spend far less money to upgrade the
security of American embassies around the world over the next two
years than was recommended by an independant review panel just last
month. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) WASHINGTON -- Feb. 4, 1999 -- CONGRESS-TERROR, 2-04 --
Louis Freeh, director of the FBI, left, speaks with Attorney
General Janet Reno during a hearing on terrorism by the Senate
Appropriations Committee on Capitol Hill on Thursday. According to
testimony by Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, the Clinton
Administration plans to spend far less money to upgrade the
security of American embassies around the world over the next two
years than was recommended by an independant review panel just last
month. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) WASHINGTON -- Feb. 4, 1999 -- CLINTON-DAY, 2-04 --
President Clinton acknowledges a standing ovation at the Malcomn
Baldrige Award presentation ceremony in Washington. The Senate
moved to bring President Clinton's impeachment trial to a prompt
conclusion, rejecting a last-ditch request by House prosecutors to
summon witnesses. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) WASHINGTON -- Feb. 4, 1999 -- IMPEACH-2, 2-04 -- Sens.
Olympia Snow, left, and Pete Domenici, emerge from a Republican
caucus meeting on Capitol Hill on Thursday. The Senate moved to
bring President Clinton's impeachment trial to a prompt conclusion,
rejecting a last-ditch request by House prosecutors to summon
Monica Lewinsky for live testimony. Republicans also shrank from a
plan to declare the president guilty without ousting him from
office. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- Feb. 4, 1999 -- CATHOLIC-SCHOOLS, 2-04 --
Students on the campus of Fordham University, in the Bronx, walk
past a statue of Archbishop John Hughes, founder of the school and
the first archbishop of New York, on Thursday. A committee of
American bishops, in response to a Vatican request, has proposed
requirements that would make Catholic colleges and universities
more answerable to the church. The move that has alarmed many
Catholic scholars and teachers who fear their autonomy and academic
freedom are being threatened. (Angel Franco/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) WASHINGTON -- Feb. 4, 1999 -- IMPEACH-1, 2-04 -- Senate
Majority Leader Trent Lott talks with reporters outside of the
senate chamber on Thursday. Lott told reporters he hoped the senate
would wrap up the impeachment trial of President Clinton by the end
of the week. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) STOWE, Vt. -- Feb. 4, 1999 -- VT-SKI, 2-04 -- A ski lift
at the base of Mount Mansfield in Stowe, one of the iciest and
oldest ski resorts in the United States. Skiing at Stowe was born
in the 1930's, when the Civilian Conservation Corps cut the first
trail down the mountain. By the 1950's, 60's and 70's, Stowe was
the undis puted king of East Coast skiing, a resort for the rich,
famous and expert. But by the 1980's, upstarts like Killington,
Sugarloaf and Stratton had moved onto Stowe's turf. (Matt Anderson
/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) MOSCOW -- Feb. 4, 1999 -- RUSSIA-ECON, 2-04 -- Two
pensioners look for bargains down Rizhsky market. The Russian
government issued economic figures for 1998: the Economy shrank 4.6
percent, the biggest decline in four years. (James Hill/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- Feb. 4, 1999 -- PEANUTS-THEATER-REVIEW-2,
2-04 -- Kristin Chenoweth, left, starring as Sally, providing some
cheap psychiatric help to Charlie Brown, played by Anthony Rapp, in
``You're a Good Man, Charlie Brown.'' The play was inspired by
Charles M. Schulz's long-running ``Peanuts'' comic strip. (Sara
Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- Feb. 4, 1999 -- PEANUTS-THEATER-REVIEW-1,
