<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICAN-MAFIA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MEXICAN MA FIA' ATTEMPTS TO KILL ARIZONA PRISON DIRECTOR
DESCRIBED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By VICTORIA HARKER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ In a matter-of-fact voice, a former ``lieutenant'' in
the New Mexican Mafia described how he and another member twice
attempted to kill the state prisons director, Terry Stewart, at his
favorite lunchtime hangout.
</P>
<P>
   He and another member of the gang, John Alday, were given the
responsibility of staking out the Oaxaca Mexican restaurant near
the state Capitol to wait for Stewart, he said in Maricopa County
Superior Court on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   They also were given the job of killing Stewart once he went
inside and sat down for lunch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was gonna shoot him twice first, then John was gonna shoot
him twice to make sure he was dead,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Now an informant for police and prosecutors, the witness
detailed how several members _ with nicknames like Cool Cat, Ne Ne,
Bam Bam, Joker and Chino _ plotted to kill Stewart. Three men were
arrested in the scheme: Alday, Michael Garcia and Raymond Llamas.
</P>
<P>
   A preliminary hearing started Thursday before Judge Gregory
Martin. Martin will hear testimony from witnesses to determine
whether there is probable cause to bind the three over for trial.
</P>
<P>
   The informant's testimony revealed some of the inner workings
and cold-bloodedness of the prison gang that began in Arizona's
penal system.
</P>
<P>
   At 23 years old, he was driving a brand new Lexus he bought with
the money he made ``working the streets'' for the gang. In order to
become a member, he said he had to stab someone.
</P>
<P>
   But his position and standing in the gang dissolved when he
refused to reveal the location of a friend targeted for murder. He
was stabbed 22 times for his betrayal. That's when he agreed to
testify for the state against the three defendants. Now, a
contract, or ``green light,'' is out on his life, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The gang's reason for wanting to kill Stewart? To force prison
officials to back down on policies that are hampering the gang's
illicit activities, he said. In particular, the gang is angered by
new policies that isolate New Mexican Mafia members, making it
difficult to carry out business as usual.
</P>
<P>
   Gang members also wanted to send a message that their power
extends beyond the razor wire into the streets, said the informant,
who is not being named for security reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was gonna be our way to show, `We're out here now,' '' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   If Stewart's death did not result in changes, gang members
discussed killing prison guards next, he said. They even considered
videotaping the murder of a guard.
</P>
<P>
   There were several meetings to discuss how Stewart would be
killed, he said. Garcia, 37, and Llamas, 32, officers within the
gang, ``called the shots,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, he and Alday, 27, were to carry out the actual
killing.
</P>
<P>
   Revolvers were their gun of choice so no shell casings would
leave a trail in the restaurant. After the shooting, each man would
still have four bullets in his gun ``in case somebody tried to play
hero in the restaurant,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   They attempted two times to carry out their orders. The first
time, they were seated just a few feet away from Stewart in the
restaurant. But there were too many police eating there that day.
Instead, they ate lunch with their guns tucked in their waistbands,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   On their second attempt, they again were seated just feet from
Stewart. After water and chips were served, the informant said he
started to reach for his gun when two policemen walked in.
</P>
<P>
   The two assassins ended up just eating lunch again.
</P>
<P>
   Officers in the organization decided to put the murder on hold
for a few months to come up with a better plan.
</P>
<P>
   In the interim, authorities learned of the murder plot and the
three men were arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, who was in court Thursday, said the informant's
nonchalant manner as he testified was ``chilling.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one thing to have someone come to you and brief you,''
Stewart said. ``Let me tell you, it truly has a chilling effect
when you see someone talk about how he was going to kill the
director.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors and police say the informant and others who plotted
the killing are members of the New Mexican Mafia.
</P>
<P>
   But the informant testified in court that there is no such
organization, a surprise to prison officials. The informant said
there is only the Mexican Mafia.
</P>
<P>
   His testimony about the inner workings of the gang will be
considered ``breaking faith'' or violating the ``code of silence''
among members, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The preliminary hearing will continue Monday and is expected to
last three to five days. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
