</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AZNOTES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE EXPRESS THEIR VIEWS ON IMPEACHMENT TRIAL _ INDIRECTLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JULIE AMPARANO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Even through the bulletproof glass in the police
station lobby, the disgust is visible.
</P>
<P>
   The officer on duty shifts from one foot to the other, rests his
hand on his holster, then offers a smirk when asked for his opinion
about President Clinton and the impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not allowed to discuss politics,'' he explains. ``It's
against policy.''
</P>
<P>
   I tell him I had come to Phoenix police headquarters downtown
this morning to talk to officers and get their views on the
Washington scandal. Do they approve of how the law is being
handled? What do they think of Clinton? He is, after all, the
nation's top cop.
</P>
<P>
   My last statement makes the officer feign sickness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh please,'' he bellows, unable to resist the remark. ``I
think you can tell from my gestures what I think of President
Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   The three other officers working on the desk behind him snicker
and shake their heads.
</P>
<P>
   I can read between the lines.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the police station, officers stream in and out of the
building. Some have finished their shifts and are heading home or
to the gym. Others are just starting the day.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting on a ledge beyond the doors, I stop many and ask them to
tell me about Clinton. Some decline. But others are eager to give
their views.
</P>
<P>
   This 12-year veteran is angry about it all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't get me started,'' he says. ``First, let's take a look at
the president's actions. He lied under oath. Next, he obstructed
justice. He is supposed to be an enforcer of the law. He is
supposed to set an example.''
</P>
<P>
   The officer then talks about how each day he puts his life on
the line for the law. And for what?
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, the president of the United States doesn't respect the
law,'' he says. With that, he is off.
</P>
<P>
   Another police officer wants to talk about the trial and the
lawmakers. But she doesn't feel right talking in front of the
station. So I walk around the block with her.
</P>
<P>
   She's been on the police force for two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politics has gotten in the way. This isn't being taken
seriously,'' she complains. ``This is about the Democrats vs. the
Republicans. It's not about finding the truth or justice. That's
what gets me, because that's my entire job.''
</P>
<P>
   Another policeman, a veteran of 20 years, wants to focus on the
money being spent on the Clinton mess.
</P>
<P>
   ``For what? For a slap on his hand?'' he asks. ``We need more
cops on the streets. We need money for so much more. Can't they
see? They're just so out of touch.''
</P>
<P>
   As President Clinton's impeachment trial progresses, Julie
Amparano is taking the pulse of people in the Valley. Do they care
about the trial? Do they want him removed from office? What does
captivate Americans? She looks for the answers. Amparano can be
reached at 444-8394 or at julie.amparano(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
