<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUAYLE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUAYLE PICKS UP BACKING OF REP. SALMON IN ARIZONA FOR PRESIDENTIAL
BID 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Former vice president Dan Quayle began his
presidential campaign in Arizona by picking up a potent endorsement
Thursday maverick GOP Rep. Matt Salmon of Mesa.
</P>
<P>
   ``Make no mistake about it. I am going to do it I am running for
president,'' the former vice president said during a Phoenix news
conference.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle and his wife, Marilyn, appeared before a small group of
supporters with Salmon and his wife, Nancy, signaling Quayle's
first major endorsement in the state's Republican Party hierarchy
and a significant split from Arizona's other presidential aspirant,
Sen. John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Salmon introduced Quayle as a ``personal friend and a great
American'' at an event that was intended to announce the start of
Quayle's presidential exploratory committee. Quayle made a similar
announcement the day before in Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   The news conference, though, was merely a formality in Quayle's
carefully orchestrated plan to launch his bid for the 2000 GOP
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Quayle said he plans to begin campaigning
full-time next week, traveling to key early primary states of Iowa
and New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm there . . . I'm running for president,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle said he is trying for an early win to build momentum and
credibility among GOP voters before California's do-or-die March 7
primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to win before you get to California. You've got to
win early,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle plans to base his campaign in his adopted home town of
Phoenix, where he spent much of his childhood years and where his
campaign headquarters are located.
</P>
<P>
   He plans a formal kick-off in April in Indiana and Phoenix,
trying to attract additional attention as he enters an increasingly
crowded GOP field.
</P>
<P>
   In Arizona, the spotlight will be on his contest with McCain,
who earlier this week told reporters, ``I can beat anybody'' in the
state's presidential primary.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle said he had no comment on McCain's remark, but said,
``We'll do very well here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got deep Arizona roots,'' he said, who attended public
elementary and secondary schools in the Phoenix area. He has his
wife returned to Arizona in 1996, and now live in Paradise Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a lot of friends in Arizona,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle also indicated he is staying out of the debate over when
to stage Arizona's primary, saying the decison was up to the
Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   After he first announced his intentions to run two weeks ago in
CNN's Larry King Live program, many Republicans indicated they
wanted to support Quayle but were unsure whether he could shed the
baggage he accumulated as vice president.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Quayle said he is prepared to dispel any lingering
doubts about his candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   His appeal will become apparent on the campaign trail, Quayle
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they list to me and read and hear my message, slowly and
surely, we will win them over,'' he said. ``When they see me,
they're going to say this is different.''
</P>
<P>
   In his statement, Quayle sounded many familiar themes - strong
family values, middle-class tax cuts, a restoration of a strong
foreign policy and a ``return or respect and credibility to the
Oval office.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me be clear - I will be the Republican nominee for
president, and I will beat Al Gore,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Murphy can be reached at 444-8546 or at
michael.murphy(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
