</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-ECON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAZIL PLEDGES CURBS ON DEBT AND BUDGETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By DIANA JEAN SCHEMO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRASILIA, Brazil _ After weeks of uncertainty about the course
Brazil would pursue to stabilize its troubled economy, officials
here reached a revised agreement with the International Monetary
Fund Thursday night, pledging to enforce substantially greater
budget discipline than originally promised and to keep inflation
below 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In a news conference at the Brazilian Finance Ministry shortly
before he concluded three days of negotiations here, the IMF's
first deputy managing director, Stanley Fischer, said, ``We have
achieved the goals that we had in mind when this visit began, to
set out a good framework for moving ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   The new agreement calls on Brazil to increase the independence
of the central bank, to contain debt at a level below 45.6 percent
of the gross domestic product, and to produce a primary spending
surplus in the range of 3 to 3.5 percent this year _ substantially
greater than the 2.6 percent surplus the original accord promised.
</P>
<P>
   The primary surplus reflects government spending but not
debt-service payments and is considered a barometer of Brazil's
budget discipline.
</P>
<P>
   Finance Minister Pedro Malan also pledged that Brazil would
accelerate privatization of the energy and banking industries, and
said, ``We reiterate our firm commitment to the agenda of
reforms.'' But he said the accord did not call for the
privatization this year of Petrobras, the state oil company, or of
the Banco do Brasil.
</P>
<P>
   The revised agreement was essential for the IMF to release the
second portion of a $41.5 billion standby loan pledged to Brazil in
November, when this vast nation, one of the world's 10 largest
economies and the leader of Latin America, began hemorrhaging
dollar reserves as investors lost confidence in the nation's
solvency.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the country's situation has only worsened. Dollar
reserves sank to $26 billion from $72 billion, with $17 billion
leaving last month alone. Its currency lost approximately 30
percent in value against the dollar. Interest rates are at 39
percent, despite record-level unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   The IMF funds that Brazilian officials initially said would be
needed solely for confidence, and would probably never even be
used, now cannot get here fast enough.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the original accord, the revised deal counts fighting
inflation as a goal of the IMF-backed stabilization program, an
important point in selling the agreement to the Brazilian Congress
and public. While people here resent IMF-imposed austerity
measures, they will accept almost any sacrifice to avoid a return
to the era of hyperinflation, when double-digit cost increases each
month were a fact of life.
</P>
<P>
   While noting that an increase in prices to compensate for the
currency's devaluation is inevitable, officials said that high
interest rates were necessary to dampen demand and keep inflation
under control.
</P>
<P>
   The revised agreement says keeping inflation under 10 percent a
year would be pursued ``through firm monetary and financial
policies, strong and sustained fiscal adjustment and an intensified
structural reform effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked how far Brazilians could expect to see interest rates come
down, Fischer said, ``The critical issue now is to control
inflation.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that a technical and negotiating team would probably
remain through the end of next week, going through fiscal accounts,
projections and plans, and would make its recommendations to the
IMF board in ``not more than two weeks, and I hope much less than
that.''
</P>
<P>
   The board would then have to vote on releasing further money to
Brazil. Asked whether more than $9 billion could be released,
Fischer said, the fund's team ``will make a decision on how much to
recommend.''
</P>
<P>
   While the original agreement promised the second installment of
aid by the end of February, the revised agreement says it will come
``as soon as possible,'' but allows for that as late as March 31.
</P>
<P>
   Malan sidestepped questions about precisely how Brazil would
achieve a greater primary surplus, and to what extent the
government would rely on further budget cuts or tax increases to
accomplish that.
</P>
<P>
   An austerity budget cut of 8.7 billion reais was passed by the
Brazilian Congress last week, but the government can spend
substantially less than authorized without congressional
involvement.
</P>
<P>
   The only piece of the accord that specifically depends on
Congress is a final vote extending and increasing a tax on
financial transactions, which is to reach Congress at the end of
March.
</P>
<P>
   Legislators Thursday, however, seemed ill inclined to support
any further austerity measures should the government turn to them
to raise taxes more. Tens of thousands of civil servants are
expected to lose their jobs this year as mandated layoffs take
effect, and members of Congress appear to be distancing themselves
from the president and his austerity measures.
</P>
<P>
   Emerson Kapaz, a lawmaker from President Fernando Henrique
Cardoso's Brazilian Social Democracy Party, said that because of
the financial transaction tax increase, ``we cannot raise taxes any
more.''
</P>
<P>
   Many members of Congress allied with the president said,
however, that Brazil could simplify the tax system, which
contributes to rampant evasion and corruption. Kapaz noted that
only 20 percent of companies, for example, are up to date on their
tax payments.
</P>
</TEXT>
