<HEADER>
A2494 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-IOC-DRUGS05-COX     02-04 0564
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-IOC-DRUGS05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gray areas exist for new drug agency
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAUSANNE, Switzerland _ Looking out at a roomful of sports
leaders and politicians, International Olympic Committee President
Juan Antonio Samaranch declared a ``great victory for clean
sports'' Thursday as he closed the World Conference on Doping in
Sport.
</P>
<P>
   But after three days of speeches and sound bites, the only
significant consensus reached by delegates to the IOC-led
conference was agreement to go forward with plans for an
international doping agency.
</P>
<P>
   A declaration by the delegates calls for a working committee to
be in place by May to establish the framework for the drug agency,
which Samaranch has promised will be in use by the Sydney Olympics
in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC pledged to raise $25 million to help set up the agency,
most of which is to be budgeted for out-of-competition testing and
to fund research aimed at detecting performance-enhancing
substances. Ultimately, the agency will be run by a director and an
executive council with representation from the IOC, international
sports federations and the scientific community. Names tossed about
Thursday as a possible chair ranged from diplomats in the mold of
Henry Kissinger to retired Nobel Prize scientists.
</P>
<P>
   If the conference ended in victory, it was a bitter one for
Samaranch, with questions about his leadership of the IOC filtering
into the debate on doping. Sports leaders, politicians and athletes
repeatedly called for the agency to be independent of the IOC and
rejected a proposal that he head it.
</P>
<P>
   Delegates also rebuked his liberal interpretation of doping,
approving a resolution that defines it as the use of substances
``potentially dangerous to athletes' health and/or capable of
enhancing their performances.'' After the doping scandal at the
Tour de France last summer, Samaranch suggested that banned
substances not known to damage an athlete's health should not be
prohibited.
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch did lead the move away from a firm two-year suspension
for a serious first offense, a shift from the IOC's stance before
the Atlanta Olympics. Both the United States and the 15-member
European Union opposed the weaker version, which will allow a
two-year ban to be modified for ``exceptional circumstances.'' That
gives federations opposed to the blanket ban, such as soccer and
tennis, the possibility of seeking lighter penalties for drug
infractions.
</P>
<P>
   Primo Nebiolo, head of the track and field federation, said he
thinks federations will feel pressure not to grant too many
exceptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the best (resolution) for the benefit of sport and the
Olympic movement,'' Samaranch said. ``It kept the Olympic movement
united.''
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch denied that the IOC retreated in the face of
opposition, saying he wasn't surprised by the criticism voiced by
government leaders during the conference. But it was clear a nerve
had been touched by the words of Gen. Barry McCaffrey, the White
House drug czar.
</P>
<P>
   ``We listened with a lot of attention to Gen. McCarthy,''
Samaranch said with a smile, pausing as laughter filled the
conference room. ''We are very thankful he is so interested in the
IOC. We told him he has many problems in his own country regarding
doping.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
