<HEADER>
A2495 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-ACC-ANALYSIS05-CO     02-04 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ACC-ANALYSIS05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ACC recruting breakdown
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   CLEMSON
</P>
<P>
   _ The class: New Tigers coach Tommy Bowden didn't make as big an
impact as expected, but the class is solid. Clemson allowed too
many players to leave the state, including offensive lineman Kevin
Breedlove, who went to Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   _ The jewel: Quarterback Willie Simmons of Quincy, Fla., was
among the South's best and turned down Georgia Tech and Florida to
sign with Bowden. He fills an immediate need.
</P>
<P>
   _ The sleeper: Defensive lineman Marcus Lewis of Dunwoody wasn't
on any lists last fall, but he attracted interest from Miami before
choosing Clemson.
</P>
<P>
   DUKE
</P>
<P>
   _ The class: Former Florida assistant Carl Franks got a late
start but still managed to sign 17 prospects. Franks was one of the
Gators' top recruiters, so he should make a future impact.
</P>
<P>
   _ The jewel: Nick Brzezinski of Ivonia, Mich., was among the top
tight ends in the Midwest. He is an excellent blocker and had 29
receptions as a senior.
</P>
<P>
   _ The sleeper: Fullback Alex Wade of Newtown, Pa., is a strong
runner and adequate blocker.
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA STATE
</P>
<P>
   _ The class: The Seminoles didn't have a lot of scholarships,
but coach Bobby Bowden seemed to sign an all-American with every
one. FSU got highly regarded defensive back Rufus Brown and running
back Nick Maddox on signing day.
</P>
<P>
   _ The jewel: Defensive end Darnell Dockett of Burtonsville, Md.,
was the top prospect in the Mid-Atlantic. He had 310 tackles and 47
sacks in three years and also was a standout offensive lineman.
</P>
<P>
   _ The sleeper: Alonzo Jackson of Americus was one of the state's
top defensive line prospects. His future could be on the offensive
line.
</P>
<P>
   MARYLAND
</P>
<P>
   _ The class: The Terrapins' group was considered mediocre at
best before Ron Vanderlinden landed quarterback Latrez Harrison of
Atlanta's Washington High. None of SuperPrep's top-10 prospects
from Maryland signed with the Terrapins.
</P>
<P>
   _ The jewel: Harrison seemed headed anywhere but Maryland. But
he backed off his commitment to Auburn only days before the signing
period started.
</P>
<P>
   _ The sleeper: Most schools were recruiting Eric Dumas of Mays
High to play on the offensive line, but the Terps offered him a
chance to play defense.
</P>
<P>
   NORTH CAROLINA
</P>
<P>
   _ The class: The Tar Heels put together a solid class for the
second year in a row under coach Carl Torbush. Only seven of UNC's
22 prospects are from the state, but the Heels did particularly
well in Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   _ The jewel: Defensive back Michael Waddell committed to the Tar
Heels early but then seemed to lean toward FSU. He was among the
nation's best, drawing comparisons to Deion Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   _ The sleeper: Defensive lineman Jeb Terry is from a small
military school in Culver, Ind., but Torbush likes his speed and
intensity.
</P>
<P>
   N.C. STATE
</P>
<P>
   _ The class: Armed with a new contract and last season's bowl
appearance, Wolfpack coach Mike O'Cain landed his best class in
recent years. N.C. State hit Georgia especially hard, landing five
players from the Peach State.
</P>
<P>
   _ The jewel: Defensive back Marcus Ellerbe of Rockingham, N.C.,
committed to North Carolina early but then switched to the
Wolfpack. He had 73 tackles and two interceptions as a senior.
</P>
<P>
   _ The sleeper: Both Georgia and Georgia Tech looked long and
hard at Tony Campbell of Cedar Shoals High in Athens. The Wolfpack
lists him as a wide receiver, but his future might be in the
secondary.
</P>
<P>
   VIRGINIA
</P>
<P>
   _ The class: The Cavaliers have one of the ACC's top classes,
but they had to go outside their home state to assemble it. The
Cavs signed just two of SuperPrep's top-10 prospects in Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   _ The jewel: Quarterback Bryson Spinner accounted for 37
touchdowns in his senior season, passing for 1,338 yards and
rushing for 888 more.
</P>
<P>
   _ The sleeper: Offensive lineman Shomari Chism of Atlanta drew
interest from several big-name schools, including Georgia Tech. If
he improves his footwork, he could develop into a starter.
</P>
<P>
   WAKE FOREST
</P>
<P>
   _ The class: Demon Deacons coach Jim Caldwell seemed headed
toward a terrible class until he pulled off a shocker, landing
all-America quarterback C.J. Leak of Charlotte. Wake Forest signed
only 10 prospects.
</P>
<P>
   _ The jewel: Leak was ranked among the nation's top prospects
and turned down Notre Dame, Penn State, Kansas State and Syracuse
to sign with Wake. He's the foundation of Wake Forest's future.
</P>
<P>
   _ The sleeper: The Demon Deacons were the only team to make an
offer to offensive lineman Chad Rebar of Throop, Pa. But Rebar's
size (6-3, 290) gives him the potential to develop into a starter.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
