<SLUG> BC-FBC-GATECH-ANALYSIS05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tech fills its needs at most spots
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;    By Norman Arey
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Georgia Tech's recruiting effort fortified every
position the Jackets went after except tight end. The Yellow
Jackets lost only center Craig Page off the offensive line from
last season, but left guard Noah King, right tackle Jon Carman,
backup left guard Jason Burks and tight end Conrad Andrzejewski
will be seniors this year. So, coach George O'Leary brought in
three offensive linemen in anticipation of the graduations.
</P>
<P>
   Flanker/tailback Charlie Rogers and backup split end Mike
Sheridan are gone, but split ends Dez White and Brett Basquin and
flankers David Powell and Kelly Campbell return. Still, the Jackets
signed three wide receivers.
</P>
<P>
   Tech's backfield has quarterback Joe Hamilton and backup George
Godsey returning, but freshmen Brian Camp and Andy Hall, along with
redshirt freshman Jermaine Crenshaw, give the Jackets five
quarterbacks on scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   Running back is well stocked, with sophomore Joe Burns, senior
Phillip Rogers, redshirt sophomore Sean Gregory and fullbacks Ed
Wilder and Virgil Johnson, but O'Leary, saying a team ``can't have
too many running backs,'' signed four more, headed by Sidney Ford
of Lindale and Jermaine Hatch of Baton Rouge, La.
</P>
<P>
   Tech had quite a few defensive holes and spent the majority of
its scholarships there. The Jackets have four defensive linemen
coming to replace the graduated Jesse Tarplin and Nate Stimson up
front. Delaunta Cameron and Justin Robertson left two holes at
linebacker, and Tech signed three.
</P>
<P>
   The defensive backfield, which was only marginal at best, lost
strong safety Jerry Caldwell and cornerback Jason Bostic. O'Leary
signed five defensive backs, including Jeremy Muyres of Lilburn and
Cory Collins of Egg Harbor, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   _ Strengths: The Jackets did well at the skill positions,
bringing in two quarterbacks, four running backs and five defensive
backs. The best of the defenders might be Collins, a 5-foot-11,
175-pounder who perhaps is the best defensive back in the East and
rated as the No. 8 skill athlete in the country by SuperPrep
magazine. Tech also is happy with Camp, the Ohio prep player of the
year, and running backs Ford and William Glover.
</P>
<P>
   _ Weaknesses: The Jackets really needed a tight end to help
Andrzejewski and sophomore Russ Matvay. Now O'Leary must take a
look at his roster and see if someone can be moved to the position.
</P>
<P>
   _ One that got away: The Jackets would have loved to have signed
Godsey's brother Gary, a tight end who signed with Notre Dame. Tech
also liked quarterback Willie Simmons of Quincy, Fla., but he chose
Clemson.
</P>
<P>
   _ Can't miss: The Tech staff loves wide receiver Anthony Lawston
of Baltimore. The 6-4, 215-pounder could play several positions.
Collins and Glover and linebacker Recardo Wimbush also are rated
high, and defensive lineman Greg Gathers, Camp and offensive
lineman Raymond Blake also look strong.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sleeper: Hatch was at the top of everyone's list entering his
junior year at Catholic High. But he tore up his knee that year and
most teams backed away. After coming back strong his senior year to
rush for 954 yards, catch 30 passes for 461 yards and account for
21 touchdowns, Arkansas, LSU and Miami tried to get back in the
picture, but Hatch signed with Tech.
</P>
<P>
   GEORGIA TECH SIGNEES
</P>
