<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-RECRUIT-ANALYSIS05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Analysts rate Longhorns the consensus winner
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Mack Brown has been at Texas for one season, but he
already appears to have put the Longhorns back on the college
football map.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who left North Carolina for Austin, delivered to Texas
the nation's No. 1 recruiting class this week, according to the
three nationally recognized analysts.
</P>
<P>
   The Longhorns won No. 1 distinction from Bobby Burton of the
National Recruiting Advisor in Texas, Tom Lemming of Prep Football
Report in Illinois and Allen Wallace of SuperPrep in California.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hook 'em, Horns!'' Burton said. ``Texas simply has the best
group from top to bottom.''
</P>
<P>
   There are few classes better at the top than Texas' group, which
includes four Parade All-Americans and USA Today's national
offensive and defensive players of the year _ quarterback Chris
Simms of Franklin Lakes, N.J., and linebacker Cory Redding of North
Shore, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Simms, the son of former New York Giants quarterback Phil
Simms, had committed to Tennessee before signing with Texas. The
Longhorns also got two players hotly pursued by Georgia _ wide
receiver Bo Scaife of Denver and offensive tackle Alfio Randall of
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Also in all three top-10s were Alabama, LSU, Michigan, Notre
Dame, Ohio State, Texas A&AMP;M and UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   Lemming ranked Georgia's group of 25 prospects as the nation's
second-best, and Wallace had the Bulldogs 10th and Burton had them
12th.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Tech's class of 26 players was ranked 16th by SuperPrep.
</P>
<P>
   Jamie Newberg of Atlanta-based Border Wars gave Georgia the
SEC's top class, followed by Alabama, LSU, Florida and Tennessee.
Newberg said Florida State had the top group in the ACC, followed
by Clemson, Georgia Tech and North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   RECRUITING CLASS RATINGS
</P>
<P>
   _ The National Recruiting Advisor
</P>
<P>
   1. Texas; 2. Ohio State; 3. Notre Dame; 4. UCLA; 5. Texas A&AMP;M;
6. Alabama; 7. LSU; 8. Tennessee; 9. Miami; 10. Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   _ Prep Football Report
</P>
<P>
   1. Texas; 2. Georgia; 3. Notre Dame; 4. Ohio State; 5. Alabama;
6. Texas A&AMP;M; 7. UCLA; 8. Michigan; 9. LSU; 10. Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   _ SuperPrep
</P>
<P>
   1. Texas; 2. Ohio State; 3. Michigan; 4. Texas A&AMP;M; 5. UCLA; 6.
Alabama; 7. Florida; 8. Notre Dame; 9. LSU; 10. Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
