<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 22:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2499 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-SEC-ANALYSIS05-CO     02-04 1098
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-SEC-ANALYSIS05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SEC recruiting breakdown
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   ALABAMA
</P>
<P>
   _ The class: Crimson Tide coach Mike Dubose has gotten serious
about recruiting, luring recruiting coordinators from Florida State
(Ronnie Cottrell) and Georgia Tech (Lance Thompson) in the past two
years. As a result, Alabama signed its second top-25 class in a
row.
</P>
<P>
   _ The jewel: Saleem Rasheed of Birmingham was rated the South's
No. 1 LB prospect by some services. He had 157 tackles and 15 sacks
as a senior.
</P>
<P>
   _ The sleeper: Charles Jones was a standout QB at Burke County
High, but some people think he could be an All-SEC DB or WR.
</P>
<P>
   ARKANSAS
</P>
<P>
   _ The class: Houston Nutt followed up his surprising Citrus Bowl
appearance with an outstanding class. The Razorbacks signed seven
of SuperPrep's top 10 signees in the state.
</P>
<P>
   _ The jewel: RB Cedric Cobbs of Little Rock, Ark., was coveted
by Georgia and Texas A&AMP;M, but he chose to stay home. He rushed for
2,043 yards and 15 TDs on 157 carries as a senior.
</P>
<P>
   _ The sleeper: WR Sparky Hamilton of Lufkin, Texas, is a big
target and had 100 catches during his prep career. If he receives
an SAT boost, Hamilton could help immediately.
</P>
<P>
   AUBURN
</P>
<P>
   _ The class: Not a bad effort for new Tigers coach Tommy
Tuberville, considering his late start. He upgraded Auburn's skill
positions, signing six WRs, two QBs and four RBs.
</P>
<P>
   _ The jewel: WR DeAndre Green of Prichard, Ala., was among the
South's best, finishing his career with 210 catches, 2,900 yards
and 43 TDs.
</P>
<P>
   _ The sleeper: Auburn thinks Georgia and Georgia Tech both
overlooked DL Dexter Murphy of LaGrange and WR Detronn Harris of
Westlake.
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA
</P>
<P>
   _ The class: Gators coach Steve Spurrier addressed his major
needs by signing six LBs and six DL. Florida's group of LBs, which
includes Matt Farrior of Virginia and Byron Hardmon of Florida, is
probably the nation's best.
</P>
<P>
   _ The jewel: Sprinter Lito Sheppard of Jacksonville could play
both ways. He is among the nation's best CB prospects and has
big-play ability on offense.
</P>
<P>
   _ The sleeper: Marshall Schaap of Belleview, Fla., had only 10
catches last year in a run-oriented offense, but he was the top TE
at Florida's summer camp.
</P>
<P>
   KENTUCKY
</P>
<P>
   _ The class: Departed QB Tim Couch and coach Hal Mumme's Air
Raid offense allowed the `Cats to take their effort nationally. The
Wildcats signed players from 10 states other than Kentucky,
including seven from Texas.
</P>
<P>
   _ The jewel: Derek Smith is considered the best TE from Kentucky
since Frank Jacobs signed with Notre Dame more than a decade ago.
Smith might play basketball at UK, as well.
</P>
<P>
   _ The sleeper: WR Ernest Simms of Houston County High didn't
draw a lot of interest because of his height (5-8), but Mumme loves
his 4.3 speed.
</P>
<P>
   LSU
</P>
<P>
   _ The class: Tigers coach Gerry DiNardo signed 10 of SuperPrep's
top 15 recruits from Louisiana. The class got better when QB Josh
Booty returned from minor-league baseball.
</P>
<P>
   _ The jewel: Eric Edwards of Monroe, La., was the nation's
top-rated TE and has been compared to former LSU star David
Lafleur.
</P>
<P>
   _ The sleeper: WR Chris Davis of Greensburg, La., jumped from
the marching band to football as a senior and finished with 48
catches for 1,054 yards and 10 TDs.
</P>
<P>
   MISSISSIPPI
</P>
<P>
   _ The class: New Rebels coach David Cutcliffe started too late
to make a real impact, but landing QB Eli Manning of New Orleans
gave the former Tennessee assistant some instant credibility.
</P>
<P>
   _ The jewel: Although he wasn't as hyped as older brother
Peyton, Manning was one of the nation's top signal-callers. And,
with Romaro Miller returning, Manning won't be thrown into the fire
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   _ The sleeper: If Marietta High WR Lee Jackson qualifies, he'll
be a steal for the Rebels. Jackson is big and has soft hands.
</P>
<P>
   MISSISSIPPI STATE
</P>
<P>
   _ The class: Not as JUCO-heavy as last year, but Bulldogs coach
Jackie Sherrill still got seven players from the junior-college
ranks. He continued to attract the best players in Mississippi,
beating the Rebels in most head-to-head battles.
</P>
<P>
   _ The jewel: Mississippi State surprisingly landed RB Dontae
Walker of Clinton, Miss., early. Walker rushed for 1,880 yards and
33 TDs last year and turned down FSU and Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   _ The sleeper: Kamau Jackson of Atlanta might have been the
state's top LB last year, but he couldn't play during his senior
season at Washington High because of eligibility problems. If
Jackson qualifies and puts his off-the-field troubles behind, he
could become an All-SEC player.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH CAROLINA
</P>
<P>
   _ The class: First-year coach Lou Holtz had a disappointing
effort. The Gamecocks and Clemson allowed too many players to leave
the state. However, stealing RB Derek Watson of Williamston, S.C.,
from Tennessee on signing day was a big coup.
</P>
<P>
   _ The jewel: Watson could have a tough time getting in school,
but if he does, the Gamecocks' running game will get immediate
help.
</P>
<P>
   _ The sleeper: RB Ryan Brewer was Mr. Football in Ohio, but his
apparent lack of breakaway speed caused larger programs to shy
away. Holtz landed a hard runner.
</P>
<P>
   TENNESSEE
</P>
<P>
   _ The class: The Volunteers followed their national championship
with a top-20 class, but the group lost a lot when QB Chris Simms
defected to Texas. Tennessee didn't finish particularly well.
</P>
<P>
   _ The jewel: Albert Haynesworth of Hartsville, S.C., was the No.
1 DL prospect in the nation, but a mediocre senior season caused
his stock to drop. Still, Tennessee projects him as the next Reggie
White.
</P>
<P>
   _ The sleeper: DE Constantin Ritzmann of Tallahassee is a
foreign-exchange student from Germany who has played only one
season of competitive football. But he's a quick learner _ he had
150 tackles and 25 sacks in 14 games.
</P>
<P>
   VANDERBILT
</P>
<P>
   _ The class: Vandy coach Woody Widenhofer continues to address
his offense, as 12 of the Commodores' 19 signees project for that
side of the ball. Vandy signed players from eight states other than
Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   _ The jewel: LB Mike Adam of Hales Corner, Wis., might be
Vandy's most-recruited player. He turned down Iowa, Notre Dame and
Northwestern, but he will battle for playing time at the
Commodores' deepest position.
</P>
<P>
   _ The sleeper: OL Jordan Pettit of Olive Branch, Miss., missed
most of his senior season with a broken hand. Vandy, the only
school to make an offer, believes he will develop into a starting
guard or center.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-04-99 2210EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
