</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UGA-ANALYSIS05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dogs overcame coaching losses
 &HT;    WITH PHOTO
 &HT;    By Chip Towers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ Georgia's 1999 recruiting effort might be as
impressive for what the Bulldogs had to overcome as for what
players they landed.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia was able to put together a top-10 class despite the loss
of two coaches during the height of recruiting, with its
coordinator pursued by another school and while strapped by
NCAA-sanctioned scholarship limitations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our coaches and players did a really good job of coming
together, taking up the slack and holding on,'' coach Jim Donnan
said.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving for new jobs in December were longtime Donnan assistants
Chris Scelfo (head coach, Tulane) and Mickey Matthews (defensive
coordinator, Baylor). But potentially the most damaging problem was
Auburn coach Tommy Tuberville's relentless quest to bring
recruiting coordinator Rodney Garner back to his alma mater.
</P>
<P>
   Garner turned down a generous raise and an opportunity to become
the Tigers' assistant head coach and remained with Georgia. But
even after Garner stated publicly that he would remain with the
Bulldogs, rumors persisted through signing day that he would be
bolting for Auburn after recruiting season ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to recruit a young man and then go somewhere
else after I came out in the Atlanta paper and said that I
wasn't,'' Garner said. ``That would hurt my credibility, tear it to
shreds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy,'' he said. ``I came to Georgia with one goal in
mind and that's to win a national championship.''_ Strengths: The
class fulfills Georgia's needs. The Bulldogs needed wide receivers
and signed five, including two consensus all-Americans. They needed
help in the kicking game and signed the top two kickers on their
list. They lost senior tight ends Larry Brown and Jermaine Wiggins
and signed two in Robert Brannon and Jason Rader.
</P>
<P>
   _ Weaknesses: Although Donnan insists he's pleased with what he
got, the Bulldogs' top two running back prospects went elsewhere,
and Georgia was unable to persuade any quarterbacks to play behind
Quincy Carter and Nate Hybl.
</P>
<P>
   The number of prospects to enroll next fall could determine the
overall quality of the class. At least seven of those signed
Wednesday have not met the school's entrance standards.
</P>
<P>
   _ One that got away: Much was made of Nick Maddox's last-minute
decision to sign with Florida State rather than the Bulldogs, but
the running back Georgia wanted most stepped out of the picture
Monday. As good as the 5-foot-10, 180-pound Maddox is, Cedric Cobbs
of Little Rock, Ark., was more of what the Bulldogs were looking
for _ a big, strong back (6-1, 217) capable of carrying the ball 30
times a game.
</P>
<P>
   _ Can't miss: Wide receivers Reggie Brown and Durell Robinson
are easy picks here, but all three offensive linemen Georgia landed
have all-star potential. Because the Bulldogs signed five linemen
last year and redshirted others, offensive line was not a priority.
But they made up for quantity with quality, as Josh Billue (6-6,
300) of Guntersville, Ala., Kevin Breedlove (6-5, 295) of Clemson,
S.C., and Alex Jackson (6-5, 310) of Quincy, Fla., were rated the
best at their positions in their respective states.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sleepers: Georgia's coaches think they got a few hidden gems
in linebacker Kendrell Bell, defensive back Kentrell Curry and wide
receiver Damien Gary. Curry, a 6-3, 186-pound defensive back, is a
prototype free safety whose notoriety probably suffered because of
his early November commitment.
</P>
<P>
   GEORGIA SIGNEES
</P>
<P>
   Name _ Pos. _ Ht. _ Wt. _ Hometown (High school)
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Bailey _ ATH _ 5-11 _ 180 _ Folkston (Charlton County)
</P>
<P>
   Josh Billue _ OL _ 6-6 _ 300 _ Guntersville, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Brannon _ TE _ 6-4 _ 225 _ Charlotte (Independence)
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Breedlove _ OL _ 6-5 _ 295 _ Clemson, S.C. (Daniel)
</P>
<P>
   Reggie Brown _ WR _ 6-2 _ 185 _ Carrollton
</P>
<P>
   Decory Bryant _ DB _ 5-11 _ 185 _ Orlando (Lake Highland Prep)
</P>
<P>
   Dantra Clements _ DB _ 5-11 _ 175 _ Sharpsburg (East Coweta)
</P>
<P>
   Kentrell Curry _ DB _ 6-3 _ 186 _ Toccoa (Stephens County)
</P>
<P>
   Terrence Edwards _ ATH _ 6-2 _ 175 _ Tennille (Washington
County)
</P>
<P>
   Vince Faison _ ATH _ 5-11 _ 192 _ Lyons (Toombs County)
</P>
