<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2501 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-DRUGS-PROSPORTS05     02-04 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-DRUGS-PROSPORTS05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Major sports resist curbs
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAUSANNE, Switzerland _ In 1988, Canadian sprinter Ben Johnson
injected himself with steroids to cope with a hamstring injury and
ran the race of his life at the Seoul Olympics. Caught by
drug-testers, he was forced to hand over his gold medal and was
sentenced to eternal disgrace.
</P>
<P>
   A month later, Los Angeles Dodgers slugger Kirk Gibson used a
steroid injection to deal with his own hamstring injury. He struck
a dramatic game-winning home run and was enshrined in World Series
folklore, a sports hero to this day.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Mark McGwire became baseball's season home-run
champion while taking androstenedione, an over-the-counter dietary
supplement that would have gotten him busted at the Olympics. U.S.
shot putter Randy Barnes, gold medalist at the Atlanta Games, was
suspended after testing positive for andro.
</P>
<P>
   The difference in drug acceptance within the separate arenas of
major professional sports and the more amateur-like sports of the
Olympics was at the core of the debate at the World Conference on
Doping in Sport, which ended Thursday. Delegates proposed putting
curbs on performance-enhancing substances while knowing that the
pro stars in the United States and Europe _ often, role models to
youths _ are allowed to use certain drugs and nutritional
supplements away from the Olympic spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   And now that athletes from NBA millionaires to cyclists on the
drug-infested Tour de France circuit are joining the Olympic family
in increasing numbers, the headache won't go away.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, such sports as cycling and soccer successfully
fought for a compromise provision in the proposed two-year
suspension for a positive drug test, allowing for the penalty to be
modified for ``exceptional circumstances'' _ such as an American
baseball player using andro.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wouldn't have this problem if we didn't have professional
sports in the IOC,'' said Roland Baar, a member of the IOC
Athletes' Council and a silver medalst in rowing at the Atlanta
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Some argue that the Olympic movement is trapped in its
hypocrisy, that it markets the Games as a pure, innocent sports
event, rather than entertainment like the Super Bowl, while at the
same time sending out invitations to pro athletes.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the comments this week were directed toward U.S. sports.
Dick Pound, an IOC vice president from Canada, said, ``The closer
you are to the Olympic movement, the more you are concerned about
doping. The farther away from it you are, the less you care. All of
a sudden, you are in Mark McGwire land, and this is a national hero
all souped-up.''
</P>
<P>
   Arne Ljungqvist, the Swedish IOC member and the international
track federation's medical director, said, ``To have drugs used by
healthy young people who are supposed to be role models for our
young generation, it is just not (proper). If they accept it in
professional sports in the United States, then it is my advice that
they look at it again. This is against every sort of medical
ethics, to use strong drugs intended for the cure or prevention of
disease on healthy people. You can't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Olympic athletes have been divided into two groups. Those from
international sports federations who do not compete in professional
leagues face varying degrees of out-of-competition drug testing
year-round and at major events; pro hockey players, baseball
players and others face minimal testing, if any, and are rarely
caught.
</P>
<P>
   The world of athletics has discovered that the public does not
perceive positive drug tests as an effort to clean up a sport as
much as a signal that the sport might be drug-infested.
</P>
<P>
   Who gave a second thought while watching the Super Bowl to how
pharmacology played a role in developing the muscled Falcons and
Broncos? But when an Olympian speeds up the track or down the pool
and breaks a record, suspicions are automatic.
</P>
<P>
   A die-hard faction is holding on to a dream of having the pros
tested like everyone else, of drug-testers showing up unannounced
seeking urine samples from the wealthiest of athletes. If they
flunk, the guilty would be suspended for two years, like everyone
else.
</P>
<P>
   A majority of IOC members are less worried about the pros and
more concerned about hanging on to what they can of the Olympic
ideal. They argue that testing for performance-enhancing drugs is
more critical in nonteam sports such as track and swimming, where
performance can be quantified and world records assume exalted
status.
</P>
<P>
   ``The opportunity to be an Olympic champion only happens once
every four years,'' said Anita DeFrantz, one of two American
representatives to the IOC. ``The chance to be in the Super Bowl is
annual. The chance to be in NBA playoffs is annual. If the people
involved in professional sports in the United States don't care
about their athletes, that is unfortunate.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
