<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-NOTES05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Women drivers making impression
 &HT;    By Kent Mitchell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Fifty-eight drivers completed the first Women's Global
GT Series tryouts last week at Road Atlanta. Another tryout is
scheduled for March 29 for those who couldn't be at the first one.
</P>
<P>
   Participants in the tryouts are attempting to qualify for the
series' 16-car fields, and the results have been surprising, WGGT
Series executive director Lyn St. James said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have a larger body of competitive race drivers than
anticipated,'' she said. ``We knew we had race-car drivers, but we
didn't know they'd be this good. I expect we'll clear 40 or 50.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to driving, competitors were given physical and
mental tests by the Human Performance Institute. In one test,
Krista Baker-Barr of Cumming did 502 abdominal crunches, about
three times her nearest competitor.
</P>
<P>
   The drivers are as interesting as they are talented. Jean Kinser
of Carrollton married Adam Malley last year in Victory Lane at
Daytona International Speedway. Malley is a national champion in
the SCCA's ``H'' production series.
</P>
<P>
   Milka Duno of Caracas, Venezuela, has competed five master's
programs _ naval engineering, business organization, marine
business, naval architecture and marine biology _ and she isn't 30
yet.
</P>
<P>
   Final results will be available after the March 29 tryouts.
</P>
<P>
   Sports cars
</P>
<P>
   The teams that were the first two finishers in the Rolex 24 at
Daytona were eclectic. In addition to Riley &AMP; Scott Mark III
regulars _ team-owner Rob Dyson and Butch Leitzinger_- there was
Andy Wallace, a Panoz regular. The second-place Ferrari 333SP is
Atlanta-connected through one of its sponsors, Lease Plan. It is a
similar ride to the one Wayne Taylor and team took to victory in
the first Petite Le Mans at Road Atlanta last year.
</P>
<P>
   Supercross
</P>
<P>
   After winning the first two Supercross events of the year, Ezra
Lusk of Bainbridge has been hampered by bad luck. The latest, in
Round 4 at Seattle, was a first-turn crash involving a number of
bikes. Lusk is fourth in point standings with 65. Mike LaRocco
leads with 82. The tour comes to Atlanta on Feb. 20 at the Georgia
Dome.
</P>
<P>
   F1
</P>
<P>
   Three-time Formula One World Champion Jackie Stewart has played
many roles at Indianapolis Motor Speedway: Rookie of the Year, and
almost overall winner, of the 1966 Indy 500; another strong showing
in the 1967 Indy 500; calling the race on ABC-TV for 15 years; and
driving the pace car in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Now he's coming back as owner of the Stewart-Ford F1 team in the
inaugural United States Grand Prix at Indianapolis' new road course
in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   IRL
</P>
<P>
   After a disappointing season debut at Orlando _ 22nd by
defending Pep Boys Indy Racing League champion Kenny Brack, because
of an accident, and a ninth by Billy Boat _ A.J. Foyt Racing has
ordered two new Dallaras.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want them both to have new cars for Indy,'' team manager
Tom LaMance said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
