<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: RIGHTEOUS IN DEEDS AND WORDS
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The National Basketball Association begins its fractured season
Friday night, looking for renewal. But before I can embrace the new
season, I have to bring closure to a pro football season that ended
Sunday with an embarrassing, dull thud.
</P>
<P>
   The National Football League saw its marquee game deflated over
the weekend by an alleged act of misconduct from a player, Eugene
Robinson, who had been considered one of its most upstanding
citizens. By now, everyone knows the story of the Atlanta Falcons'
star safety who was arrested last Saturday night for allegedly
offering an undercover police officer $40 for oral sex in a seamy
area of Miami. The Falcons' Ray Buchanan, repeating a refrain that
has become quite familiar recently, said to a roomful of reporters,
``If anybody in here has never sinned, why don't you raise your
hand and let me know. We all fall short.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course we do. But in a climate where power and affiliation
often determine whose shortfalls become known, the point is that
the person who has the pen has the power. Walter Payton said as
much earlier this week when he held a news conference to reveal
that he had a rare disease that requires a liver transplant.
</P>
<P>
   A few days earlier, Payton had appeared at a news conference
with his son Jarrett, who announced that he will play football at
the University of Miami next year. Walter appeared gaunt and told
reporters that he had lost weight while training for a marathon. A
local Chicago sports anchor said at the time that Payton looked
``all shriveled up'' and that he resembled Mahatma Gandhi. ``I
think I could take him on,'' the anchor had said.
</P>
<P>
   Payton said earlier this week that he felt obliged to make his
illness known. ``Since they have the airwaves,'' he said, referring
to the news media, ``there's no way you can combat that unless you
just come out and tell what's happening.''
</P>
<P>
   The Payton episode is reminiscent of Arthur Ashe's public
admission that he had the virus that causes AIDS in 1992. Ashe was
forced to make the disclosure when USA Today told him they had
confirmation and planned to run the story. In each case, Ashe and
Payton were victims _ or casualties _ of the battle to maintain a
media with no restrictions other than those that are self-imposed.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday morning before the Super Bowl, reporters sat in a room
while Robinson received the 1999 Bart Starr Award from the
Christian group Athletes In Action, which annually honors an
athlete of high moral character. Saturday afternoon, reporters
found themselves engaged in a contentious debate over the fitness
of Lawrence Taylor, with his many off-the-field problems, to be
elected to the Pro Football Hall of Fame. By Saturday night we were
all stunned by the news of Robinson's problems.
</P>
<P>
   In the process of lambasting the media for sitting in judgment
of him, Taylor made a crucial point when he said, ``They have no
idea who the hell I am because they get their information from the
media.''
</P>
<P>
   True. We don't know. What bothered me about Robinson, more
rather than less, was the idea of somehow being ``had.'' Of being a
member of the congregation that discovers its preacher is a crook.
Or, perhaps feeling the crude naivete of a customer who buys snake
oil from the medicine man and really expects it to work.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson's act becomes increasingly relevant at a time in sports
when increasing numbers of high-profile athletes say they have
become Christians. They use basketball courts, football fields,
interview rooms and locker rooms to speak about the power of the
Word. They motion toward the sky after every good play. They pray
at midfield and center court after each game. ``Praise God'' and
``Amen'' are as much a part of post-game quotations now as ``I'm
glad we won.''
</P>
<P>
   With the great media scrutiny of athletes, like Robinson, who
lace conversations with beliefs, these men find themselves with an
additional burden of proof, proving that they are more than mere
locker-room Christians. Thursday, Robinson, in Hawaii with his
family for the Pro Bowl, said he refused to shrink. ``The one thing
I don't intend to do is cower and hide,'' he said. ``God made me a
person who really likes and cares about people.''
</P>
<P>
   Fan attraction rests on a delicate balance between an
appreciation for skill, a deep-seated yearning for heroes and
heroines, and a measure of truth and consistency. Coming out of the
Super Bowl and the NBA lockout, the gulf between heroism, truth and
consistency is wider than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   Each side had better work to narrow that gap, before we all fall
in.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
