<DOCNO> NYT19990204.0512 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 22:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2505 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WELLS-SFCHRON &LR;      02-04 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WELLS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Kinder, Gentler Bank Deal  &HT;       
 By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
When big banks join forces, massive job cuts usually follow.
</P>
<P>
   One of the key rationales for the wave of mergers that's washed
over the industry has been the hundreds of millions of dollars of
costs banks could wring out by shuttering overlapping operations
and firing excess employees.
</P>
<P>
   But the new Wells Fargo claims it is carrying out a different
kind of bank merger.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the nations's seventh-largest bank, created when
Minneapolis' Norwest bought San Francisco's Wells Fargo and took
its name, insist their eyes are on boosting sales, not slashing
costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're fundamentally a growth business,'' said President Leslie
Biller, the bank's No.2 executive. The takeover of Wells Fargo ``is
a nonevent in terms of people elimination.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells Fargo is delaying most merger-related job cuts so that
positions can be eliminated by natural attrition rather than
layoffs, Biller said.
</P>
<P>
   Since the purchase took effect in November, the new Wells Fargo
has laid off 492 people out of a workforce of about 100,000. Most
of the cuts took place in Texas and New Mexico, where Norwest and
Wells Fargo both had branch networks and are shutting offices that
serve the same territory.
</P>
<P>
   In the Bay Area, about 25 employees, including eight senior
executives, lost jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Looking ahead, bank officials said they won't rush to combine
headquarters functions. They will keep two separate human resources
and finance staffs through 2000, when the bank combines computer
systems for those departments.
</P>
<P>
   And Wells Fargo recently launched a formal ``Retain and
Retrain'' program with a full-time staff of three to help employees
who lose jobs find other positions at the bank. Some 1,300
positions are currently listed through the program.
</P>
<P>
   The bank is acting not out of altruism, but as a matter of
business strategy, Biller said.
</P>
<P>
   The old Norwest prided itself for having one of the best records
in banking for selling lots of different products to its customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that our products are better, it's the quality of
execution and that comes down to people,'' noted Biller. ``We think
that's our competitive advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   Even suspicious employees said they see signs that the bank
takes its commitment seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Judith Novick's job as a supermarket banking project manager at
the old Wells Fargo's Concord office was eliminated in November.
</P>
<P>
   When she was handed her pink slip, the Walnut Creek resident
also got a pep talk from her boss encouraging her to look for
another job at the bank. A few weeks later, she found a
Concord-based managerial position in the bank's credit and debit
card division.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of WELLS05 (105841 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Novick, who saw thousands of staff members lose jobs after Wells
Fargo bought First Interstate three years ago, said she expected
more of the same when Norwest took over.
</P>
<P>
   When the new bank said it wanted to keep employees whose jobs
were cut, ``I, along with a lot of other people, were rather
skeptical,'' Novick recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Now, she's concluded, ``they're doing their best to not let
anyone go.''
</P>
<P>
   The bank asked Novick to speak about her experience. Several
other employees, who were contacted privately, said they shared her
views.
</P>
<P>
   While they are eager to speak about programs for displaced
employees, Wells Fargo officials dislike talking about their
job-cutting plans.
</P>
<P>
   Wells Fargo has already announced cuts at call centers and
back-office facilities in locations such as Oregon, Montana,
Nebraska and Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   Other banks routinely estimate how many positions they expect to
disappear in mergers. North Carolina's NationsBank, for example,
estimated it would lay off 5,000 to 8,000 people following its
purchase of BankAmerica last year.
</P>
<P>
   Wells Fargo refuses to project job losses. When executives are
asked how many jobs they expect to eliminate, ``they've been very
tight-lipped,'' noted Jay Tejera, a Minneapolis analyst with the
brokerage Dain Rauscher Wessels.
</P>
<P>
   Bank officials say the reason they won't estimate total
merger-related job losses is that they haven't yet decided. ``It's
not as if we have a file in a cabinet somewhere with a secret
number on it,'' said Biller.
</P>
<P>
   But Biller also said he worries about how employees and
communities might interpret screaming headlines about big job cuts.
``We don't want to lead with the wrong message,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So far, that hasn't been a problem. When Wells Fargo told city
officials that it planned to shut a loan-processing office in Fort
Wayne, Ind., costing 140 jobs, ``they said, `These are our
reasons.' They were very forthright,'' said Beth Neu, Fort Wayne's
economic development director.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said they suspect the bank's managers, especially chief
executive Richard Kovacevich, are torn.
</P>
<P>
   On one hand, managers want the bank to be as lean and efficient
as possible. On the other hand, they fear that aggressive
cost-cutting would prove wrenching for employees, eroding the sales
enthusiasm that lies at the core of the bank's strategy.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of WELLS05 (105841 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  ``At the end of the day, (Kovacevich) hasn't figured it out
yet,'' said Carla D'Arista, an analyst with Friedman, Billings,
Ramsey in Arlington, Va.
</P>
<P>
   There are clues where the bank is headed, though.
</P>
<P>
   When Norwest and Wells Fargo unveiled their deal last year, they
said they expected to trim annual expenses by about $650 million
annually, about 8 percent of the two bank's combined expenses. Most
of the savings would come from cutting jobs.
</P>
<P>
   That 8 percent target is modest compared with, say, the 37
percent goal of the old Wells Fargo when it took over First
Interstate. And, after talking with Kovacevich, D'Arista said she
thinks the bank is now setting its sights lower.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
