<HEADER>
A2506 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STREET-SFCHRON &LR;      02-04 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STREET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Wow, a Dot.Com Firm That's in the Black  &HT;       
 By Mark Veverka  
 c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
TMP Worldwide certainly isn't a household name.
</P>
<P>
   And it definitely doesn't have a widely recognizable ticker
symbol (TMPW).
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not nearly as well known as we should be,'' laments TMP
Chief Operating Officer Jim Treacy.
</P>
<P>
   But that could change as fast as you can say, ``dot-com.''
</P>
<P>
   TMP is an Internet play that investors can actually sink their
teeth into. It boasts real businesses that make cold cash,
including an already profitable Internet operation. No joke.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, you may now be familiar with TMP's job-finding Web
site,  &LR; Monster.com,  &LR; which just held a huge coming out party during
the recent Super Bowl telecast. The entertaining black-and-white
spots featured little kids musing about what they wanted to do when
they grew up, such as climb the career ladder to a job in middle
management. Or aspire ``to be forced into early retirement.''
</P>
<P>
   The satire-laced point is: The next generation is going to
job-hop like mad. And if TMP has its way, restless employees will
find their jobs by filing their resumes with Monster.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you think they're going to manage their careers like we
did, you're crazy,'' says Treacy. ``There's no lifetime employment
at IBM (anymore).''
</P>
<P>
   Here's how Monster.com works. Jobseekers keep resumes on file
with Monster.com and tell TMP what they want to do, how much they
want to earn and where they want to live. Then, TMP sells its
service to corporate human resource departments for subscription
fees, matching job openings with resumes in its database.
</P>
<P>
   When certain criteria match, TMP contacts the jobseekers and
asks for permission to release their resumes to the potential
employers. Jobseekers don't pay a dime. Yesterday, Monster.com
stated that it listed more than 175,000 jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Monster.com isn't built on profit-projections for the year 2010.
In the third quarter, TMP's Internet business earned operating
profits of $775,000 on $13.3 million in revenues. It may not be
much, but its black ink is flowing in the right direction. Internet
revenues may swell as much as $80 million in 1999, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of STREET05 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Revenues from Internet operations are only expected to account
for about 12 percent of total revenues in 1999, says financial
analyst Brett Manderfeld of Piper Jaffray in Minneapolis. He rates
the stock a strong buy, with a price target of $64.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, TMP stock has already enjoyed a huge run. It has
nearly doubled since December, when it was trading under $30 a
share. Yesterday, it closed at $57.75, up $1.75 after Treacy met
with investors at the NationsBanc Montgomery Securities technology
conference.
</P>
<P>
   Still, TMP's earnings per share have grown by about 40 percent a
year over the past three years. And if the Street decides to value
this stock at even a fraction of what it does some less worthy
dot-com stocks, the stock may yet have more gas in its tank.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going from $30 (a share) to $55 has been a great move, but
getting from $55 to $85 might be more difficult,'' says Manderfeld,
whose firm does not have an investment banking relationship with
TMP.
</P>
<P>
   So, if Internet operations account for just a fifth of revenues,
what are TMP's traditional businesses?
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, TMP (the acronym stands for telephone marketing
programs) is a classified advertising agency that is morphing into
a job search and placement company.
</P>
<P>
   The company's original and ongoing business is designing and
placing classified advertisements for big employers, such as Sears,
Roebuck and Ryder, in newspapers. And yesterday, TMP announced that
Lucent Technologies and McKesson HBOC are among its newest clients.
</P>
<P>
   TMP is also the world's largest Yellow Pages advertising agency,
meaning it places and designs advertisements for corporations in
thousands of directories worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Most important, perhaps, is that TMP is a headhunter. Its career
services operation fills job slots from interns to CEOs. After
certain acquisitions close, including a buyout of Australia's
Morgan &AMP; Banks, the career search business will generate close to
$275 million a year, Manderfeld says.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if the economy turns sour and unemployment rises,
TMP's core operations could suffer. That is probably the stock's
biggest downside, analysts and investors say.
</P>
<P>
   What's compelling about TMP's stock is that its Web site is not
the heart of its business model. The Net is a business-to-business
tool that will allow the company to perform many of its traditional
services more efficiently and effectively, notes financial analyst
Steven Horen of NationsBanc Montgomery Securities in San Francisco.
Horen rates TMP a buy with a price target of $70.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1990s, TMP has built its businesses through
acquisition, such as the purchase of Monster.com, and that is
likely to continue, Horen says.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need to look at their skill as consolidators and their
competency in their core businesses'' to appreciate this stock,''
Horen says. ``Then you might look to the potential of their
Internet business for a pop.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Street Smarts runs every Tuesday, Wednesday and Friday. Mark
Veverka can be reached by mail at 901 Mission St., San Francisco,
Calif. 94103, by phone at (415) 777-8444 or by e-mail at
mveverka(AT SIGN)sfgate.com
</P>
</TEXT>
