<SLUG> BC-ECOMMERCE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 FAO Schwarz Patches Hole In Web Site  &HT;       
 By Jamie Beckett 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
FAO Schwarz, one of the world's largest toy stores, has plugged a
leak on its e-commerce Web site that inadvertently allowed anyone
to see consumers' e-mail addresses, telephone numbers and other
personal information.
</P>
<P>
   The leak, the latest to highlight concerns about Web security,
occurred despite the New York retailer's assurances on its site
that its technology is designed to ``guarantee the security and
privacy of our patrons.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It really raises the question of how much you trust the place
you're giving out information to,'' said Space Rogue, editor of the
Hacker News Network ( &LR; www.hackernews.com &LR; ), which reported the
breach to FAO Schwarz. ``Just because it's a big brand name doesn't
mean there's no risk.''
</P>
<P>
   The toy company's leak was one of several Web security problems
in recent weeks. Under threat of a boycott, Intel Corp. recently
backed down slightly from a controversial plan to add a security
feature to its computer chips that would have been used to monitor
the online activities of Internet users.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, an apparent spammer broke into the Dilbert
Zone cartoon site and stole a list of e-mail addresses of members.
Those members were then sent unsolicited e-mail offering to sell
them the list for $5. On Wednesday, Dilbert cartoonist Scott Adams
issued an online apology for the ``violation of trust.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the FAO Schwarz problem arose when shoppers opted
not to put their credit card information online, but to complete
their order by fax or regular mail. The company said it fixed the
leak on Wednesday after being notified by a reporter for Wired News
( &LR; www.wired.com &LR; ).
</P>
<P>
   Under normal circumstances, shoppers could choose a toy to buy
and complete an online order form for it that contained their
address, telephone number and e-mail address.
</P>
<P>
   They could put their credit card number onto the form, if they
wished. Or they could print the order form, writing the credit card
number on the form and then faxing or mailing it to the company to
complete the order.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, the security breach occurred on the online form
for fax and mailing purposes. The data on this form was not secured
because FAO Schwarz assigned identification numbers sequentially on
the forms and where it stored the data.
</P>
<P>
   By changing the user identification number on the order form, a
sophisticated computer user could easily peak at information on
another customer's order form.
</P>
<P>
   Rogue said an enterprising hacker could write a computer program
to harvest and steal personal data from FAO Schwarz's database.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for FAO Schwarz said she did not receive Rogue's
e-mail, sent to the address listed on the site, until yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Brooke Adkins, vice president of public relations at the toy
company, said FAO Schwarz takes security problems on the site quite
seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``We fixed the problem three hours after we found out about
it,'' she said, adding that users' credit card information was
never accessible, despite the leak.
</P>
<P>
   Ira Winkler, a security expert and author of ``Corporate
Espionage,'' said that FAO Schwarz apparently made two mistakes.
First, it gave users easy-to-figure-out sequential identification
numbers instead of using some random system. In addition, he said
it appears that although the toy company encrypted consumer
information while it was being transmitted, it stored the data on a
Web server instead of on a secure server behind a firewall.
</P>
<P>
   Adkins said she could not comment on the exact cause of the
leak.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think others can steal their credit card as it goes
across the Internet, but that's not it,'' said Winkler, who is also
president of the Internet Security Advisors Group ( &LR; www.isag.com &LR; ).
``It's when it's on the other side, sitting on some company's
server'' that it's vulnerable.
</P>
</TEXT>
