<SLUG> BC-MACWEEK-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 EMediaweekly Ceases Publication, Fires Staff  &HT;       
 By Dan Fost  
 c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
The successor to MacWeek, once a legendary magazine catering to the
Apple Computer faithful, announced yesterday it will cease
publication immediately and lay off its 30 employees.
</P>
<P>
   EMediaweekly, which gave free subscriptions to 85,000 readers,
was published by Mac Publishing LLC, a San Francisco joint venture
of computer magazine titans International Data Group and Ziff-Davis
Publishing Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``The financial model wasn't working,'' said Colin Crawford,
publisher of the magazine and president and chief executive of Mac
Publishing. ``We were not able to support it by advertising
revenues.''
</P>
<P>
   Magazines dependent on Apple for advertising have ``nowhere to
go,'' said Martin Reynolds, an analyst with Dataquest, a market
research firm in San Jose. ``There's only one supplier in the Mac
market.''
</P>
<P>
   That situation grew particularly acute in summer of 1997, when
Apple stopped licensing its technology to makers of ``clones,'' or
other computer that ran the Macintosh operating system and
software.
</P>
<P>
   MacWeek was founded in 1987 by Michael Tchong, and Ziff-Davis
bought it the following year. According to Tchong's Web site, the
magazine brought in $38 million in its peak year, 1993.
</P>
<P>
   But as Apple started losing software developers to the onslaught
of Microsoft Corp.'s Windows operating system, the magazines
covering the Mac universe also began to falter.
</P>
<P>
   In August 1997, Ziff-Davis took its two Mac publications,
MacWeek and MacUser, and merged them with IDG's Macworld. MacUser
disappeared. A year later, MacWeek became eMediaweekly _ catering
to people developing content on Macs and PCs. Now only Macworld
survives in print, with Crawford claiming 500,000 paying readers.
</P>
<P>
   MacWeek and eMediaweekly live on in cyberspace, and Crawford
said he will keep adding new content to those Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Computer magazines in general are hitting some hard times. In
October, Ziff-Davis folded three magazines _ Internet Business,
Equip and Windows Pro.
</P>
<P>
   In the past year, online media began to gain a foothold with
readers and advertisers, digging into print advertising sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``The malaise you're seeing in computer magazines in general is
a very strong indication of the impact the Internet is having on
tech media,'' said Tchong, MacWeek's founder, who now writes an
e-mail newsletter called Iconocast. ``There are some pretty awesome
Macintosh sites doing a fabulous job.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 1 of MACWEEK0 () &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
