<SLUG> BC-PROVIDIAN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Providian Hiring 1,000 for Oakland Site  &HT;       
 By Peter Sinton 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Providian Financial Corp., the San Francisco company that makes
loans to people with flawed credit records, announced plans
yesterday to hire up to 1,400 more employees, including 1,000 at a
new operations center in Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   Providian, the ninth-largest credit card lender with more than
$14 billion in assets, needs more employees to keep pace with its
phenomenal growth. Last year, Providian expanded its workforce from
nearly 4,000 to close to 6,000 to handle a customer base that had
jumped from 5 million to 8 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the key profit drivers is customer and account
growth,'' said Providian Chief Financial Officer David Petrini.
``We plan to &UR;  &LR; add 200,000 to 300,000 accounts a month and need
people for sales, service and collections.''
</P>
<P>
   Providian currently has about 1,500 employees in San Francisco,
more than 2,000 in Pleasanton, about 1,000 more in Fairfield and
Sacramento, and 1,500 in Utah, Kentucky and New Hampshire. About
two-thirds of the total work the telephones.
</P>
<P>
   Providian said it picked Oakland because of its diverse,
multilingual workforce and some nice tax incentives. The company
said it was promised about $50 million in financial benefits over
10 years, including state enterprise zone hiring credits and other
tax relief.
</P>
<P>
   Starting in May, it will fill 145,000 square feet of an office
building at 1333 Broadway, which previously were occupied primarily
by city government. Providian also will hire about 400 employees
for another new operations center in Arlington, Texas, which will
help service clients in the central time zone.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike retail banks, Providian doesn't feature traditional
branches or desire walk-in traffic. It relies instead on direct
mail and telemarketing, using sophisticated credit-scoring
techniques to select customers who may have had credit problems but
can be charged enough to cover Providian's risks.
</P>
<P>
   Providian's net income last year increased 55 percent, to $296.4
million from $191.5 million in 1997. Even though the company writes
off about 6.5 percent of its consumer finance loans, which is
higher than most of its peers, its profit margins are remarkable.
Last year, the difference between the company's borrowing costs and
what it charges customers (the net interest margin) widened to 11.8
percent from 11.2 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of PROVIDIA () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Providian is growing by acquisition as well as internal growth.
Last year, it bought a $2.2 billion credit card loan portfolio from
First Union and $350 million in credit card assets from Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter's Bravo card program.
</P>
<P>
   Providian's startling growth has not gone unnoticed on Wall
Street. Over the past 12 months, Providian's stock price has nearly
tripled, rocketing from $32 to $91.31.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 2 of PROVIDIA () &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
