<SLUG> BC-ONTECH-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Why the Japanese Haven't Cracked U.S. PC Market  &HT;       
 By David Einstein  
 c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Despite more than two years of trying, Japanese companies have
failed rather dismally to crack the U.S. market for desktop
computers.
</P>
<P>
   Sony, which began courting consumers with much fanfare in 1996,
has gained nothing but frustration, along with an insignificant
market share. According to Dataquest, Sony sold only 55,392 PCs in
the United States during the third quarter of last year, out of a
market total of 9.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Toshiba has scaled back its desktop campaign and is
concentrating on shoring up its flagging share of the notebook
market.
</P>
<P>
   Hitachi, which has been selling a $2,500 all-in-one PC with a
flat display, said yesterday it will shutter its U.S. PC operation,
headquartered in Milpitas. Hitachi Data Systems in Santa Clara,
which sells large corporate computers, will continue to operate and
may pick up some functions of the PC operation. Company officials
said 13 of 90 employees have been laid off.
</P>
<P>
   When it entered the PC market in October of 1997, Hitachi said
it hoped to sell 200,000 PCs annually in the United States. But it
sold only 10,000 in the third quarter of last year.
</P>
<P>
   Why haven't the Japanese been able to compete? You'd think the
country that cornered the market on stereo equipment and
televisions and has taken a huge bite out of the U.S. auto market
could also succeed with PCs.
</P>
<P>
   Industry observers point to several problems that have plagued
Japanese computer companies that do business here:
</P>
<P>
   _With marketing offices in the United States and research and
development in Japan, Japanese computer-makers are hopelessly
fragmented. Language and cultural differences hinder fast, flexible
decision making. And far-flung geographical logistics make it hard
to bring new products to market quickly enough to compete against
U.S. rivals like Compaq, IBM and especially Dell, the direct-seller
that can get the latest technology into a customer's hands faster
than you can say Pentium.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of ONTECH05 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  ``When you have to be innovative with features and pricing on a
minute's notice, it's very difficult to do it from 5,000 miles
away,'' said Kim Brown, a PC analyst with Dataquest.
</P>
<P>
   _In the automobile industry, Japan in the 1970s went up against
U.S. companies that were sluggish, lacked innovation and saw no
need to make small cars. In hindsight, the success of Toyota and
Honda was a slam dunk. But U.S. PC-makers are strong and quick, and
they haven't given the Japanese even the glint of an opening.
</P>
<P>
   _Desktop PCs have become commodities, making price the major
consideration for buyers. Sony may boast advanced audio and video _
as befits its electronics heritage _ but it hasn't been able to
compete on price in the fast-growing sub-$1,000 market.
</P>
<P>
   _Lastly, Japanese companies have hurt themselves by not offering
stock options to U.S. employees. As a result, talented sales and
marketing people tend to look elsewhere for work. ``They (the
Japanese) just refuse to acknowledge that people want a piece of
the company,'' said Brown.
</P>
<P>
   A lack of stock options may be one reason behind the troubles of
Packard Bell NEC, the Sacramento PC-maker whose market share has
been sliding for two years. Before Japanese giant NEC took control
of the company last year, Packard Bell recruited managers with the
promise of an initial public offering. But NEC has put the IPO on
hold, limiting the firm's ability to recruit.
</P>
<P>
   What makes the situation really ironic is that Japan contributes
many of the components that go inside the PC, such as floppy disk
drives, CD-ROM drives and DVD drives. And Japan is a big source for
monitors, particularly the new flat displays that are now becoming
affordable.
</P>
<P>
   That's small consolation, however, if the PC says ``Compaq'' on
the outside and has a sticker saying ``Intel Inside.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 2 of ONTECH05 () &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
