<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2KTRAVEL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Travel Industry Passes First Y2K Test  &HT;       
 By Benny Evangelista 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
The travel industry yesterday passed a critical Year 2000 test with
flying colors.
</P>
<P>
   There were no glitches reported on the first day most airline
reservation systems could start booking airline tickets for Jan. 1,
2000, on domestic carriers like United, Delta and American.
</P>
<P>
   That was a relief for officials at the biggest travel
reservation services, the Sabre Group, Galileo International and
Worldspan, who did not know for sure until yesterday whether their
Year 2000 Problem preparations would work.
</P>
<P>
   Ronnie Hauptman, Galileo's Year 2000 project manager, said the
travel industry's success should give hope to other companies also
grappling with the Y2K problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key is to get started, do an inventory, evaluate your
systems and take appropriate remediation efforts,'' said Hauptman,
who was up all night watching for glitches at Galileo's
headquarters in Rosemont, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of work involved, but as our company has seen,
the payoff is tremendous. This was just another day for us, which
is just the way we wanted it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not seeing any problems with the (computer) systems at
all,'' said Dina Long, a vice president with the American Society
of Travel Agents. ``The question is, will there be enough inventory
available for everyone who wants to travel.''
</P>
<P>
   The Y2K problem stems from a widely used space-saving shortcut
that could confuse computers into reading the year 2000 as the year
1900. That would be disastrous for the computer-reliant travel
companies that process airline, rental car, hotel and cruise
reservations.
</P>
<P>
   Today, airline tickets for Jan. 2, 2000, will go on sale. Most
airlines only book flights up to 331 days in advance.
</P>
<P>
   Hauptman said the next test will come April 4, when tickets for
Feb. 29, 2000, will go into the computer systems. Next year is a
leap year, and an offshoot of the Year 2000 problem is the
possibility some programs may not recognize leap day correctly.
</P>
<P>
   Although most U.S. airlines began selling seats for January 1
yesterday, Southwest Airlines won't start selling tickets for
another five to seven months.
</P>
<P>
   Continental Airlines started selling seats for next year on
January 28, and has not experienced any problems.
</P>
<P>
   The big challenge for travelers now will be finding enough
accommodations for Millennium parties.
</P>
<P>
   Most cruises are booked solid and demand is heavy for hotel
rooms in popular destinations like Las Vegas and Paris, even with
prices that are reportedly 30 to 50 percent higher than normal.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the high-demand destination destinations are booked
up,'' said Long. Travel agencies are now looking for hotels and
tour operators to announce more millennium vacation packages, Long
said.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of Y2KTRAVE () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Also, travelers also will find most airlines are making all fares
for travel from Dec. 16, 1999, to Jan. 10, 2000, nonrefundable to
keep customers from booking on more than one carrier to reserve
seats, Long said.
</P>
<P>
   The airlines normally use that restriction for discount fares
during popular travel seasons. For the millennium, most are
extending the restriction to include full-fare seats, Long said.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 2 of Y2KTRAVE () &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
