<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIOTECH-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Biotech Industry Faces Urge-to-Merge Question  &HT;       
 By Tom Abate 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Faced with a cash crunch that has changed their financial
environment, biotech firms face a Darwinian dilemma: Is the urge to
merge smarter than the drive to remain independent?
</P>
<P>
   That's what 300 biotech industry executives asked themselves
yesterday at a daylong conference in Redwood Shores on how to
finance small biotech firms when Internet startups have wowed Wall
Street.
</P>
<P>
   Chiron Corp. co-founder Edward Penhoet, now dean of public
health at the University of California at Berkeley, sparked the
debate by predicting cash would never be as plentiful as in the
industry's early days, when companies like Chiron ``raised money in
ungoldly quantities'' but disappointed investors with relatively
poor returns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did a financing every spring,'' Penhoet joked. ``It was
like the tulips coming out.''
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco merchant banker Steve Burrill provided the data to
prove why biotech is now experiencing a winter of discontent. Since
it can take 10 years and $200 million to develop a drug, small
biotech firms need repeated cash infusions from stock and private
equity investors.
</P>
<P>
   But the inflow of money from initial public offerings and other
stock deals slipped from $4.4 billion in 1996 to $2 billion in
1998, while private financing has plateaued at $2 billion. The only
cash source on the rise is large pharmaceutical company
investments, which have soared from $2 billion in 1996 to $6.2
billion last year.
</P>
<P>
   But Burrill said some biotech firms mortgage their futures when
they accept pharmaceutical investments, because such deals usually
involve selling the marketing rights to the drugs the biotech firm
is developing.
</P>
<P>
   With these financing realities in mind, Jon Duane, cq &LR;  a
management consultant with McKinsey &AMP; Co. in Palo Alto, proclaimed
that small biotech firms _ and there are more than 200 such firms
with market capitalizations under $100 million _ would be better
off if they quit selling themselves piecemeal and merged with one
another or sold out to large biotech or drug firms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consolidation is necessary,'' he said. ``And merger and
acquisition is the way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   But no sooner had Duane sat down than Stelios Papadopoulos, cq
 &LR; a PaineWebber merger specialist, rose to pooh-pooh the notion that
biotech firms were ripe for wholesale consolidation.
</P>
<P>
   ``For each deal, it takes a year to iron out the ego, management
and geography issues,'' Papadopoulos said.
</P>
<P>
   Adding that it takes ``creativity and craziness'' for a
scientist to start a biotech firm, he said it was a hard
psychological about-face for such visionaries to ``calm down, be
rational (and decide) it's time to merge now.''
</P>
<P>
   Joining the debate were two Bay Area CEOs who have lived through
biotech mergers. John Walker, CEO of Axys Pharmaceuticals, and
Benjamin McGraw III, CEO of Megabios Corp., said the trick in
combining biotech firms was to get any layoffs done quickly, while
wooing key people to make sure they stay.
</P>
<P>
   McGraw said he was surprised at how tough it was to get
scientists at two firms to agree on which projects have more merit
when allocating research funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``You will have to get really ugly with your own scientists,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 1 of BIOTECH0 () &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
