<HEADER>
A2516 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WORKWAYS-SFCHRON &LR;      02-04 1148
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKWAYS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Employers Can Limit Free Speech  &HT;       
 By Ilana DeBare  
 c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Question: &LR;  I work for a government agency and was given a written
reprimand for writing a letter to the editor of a local newspaper.
My letter was critical of the newspaper's coverage of my agency.
Admittedly, I used some colorful language to make a satirical point
and I criticized the reporters harshly. But wasn't this reprimand a
violation of my free-speech rights?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Answer: &LR;  The First Amendment says that Congress can't pass any
laws abridging freedom of speech. But it doesn't say anything about
employers who want to limit their workers' speech.
</P>
<P>
   The result is that private-sector employers have great leeway to
restrict what their employees say. Companies can penalize workers
for obscene, harassing or just plain rude conversation. They can
penalize workers for bad-mouthing the company in public. They can
even penalize employees for simply talking to the media without
prior authorization _ the kind of situation you seem to be in.
</P>
<P>
   There are a few exceptions: Private-sector employees can't be
punished for speaking out about health or safety hazards. And in
California, the state labor code says employers can't punish
workers for their political activities _ which could be interpreted
to include writing letters to the newspaper about public policy
issues.
</P>
<P>
   In your case, you're a government worker _ not a private-sector
employee.
</P>
<P>
   So you've got a somewhat stronger free-speech claim because your
employer is the government and the First Amendment is aimed at
preventing government limits on speech.
</P>
<P>
   Does this mean your employer can't punish you for writing that
letter? Maybe. Maybe not. It depends on the details of your
situation _ what your letter said and whether it really harmed the
interests of the agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``The courts would apply a balancing test,'' said Craig Cornish,
a Colorado Springs lawyer who co-chairs the workplace-privacy
committee of the American Bar Association. ``They would look at
whether the employee's right to free speech outweighs the
government's interest in maintaining an effective workforce.''
</P>
<P>
   If you want to challenge this reprimand, you should talk to a
lawyer about the details of your case. Call the local chapter of
the American Civil Liberties Union, or call your local bar
association for a referral to an experienced employment lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Jobs on Hold
</P>
<P>
   Q: Time and again, I've applied for an advertised position only
to be told that the job is ``on hold.'' What's going on here? Are
recruitment agencies running fictitious ads so that they can
attract a whole bunch of candidates to add to their database? I
hate to waste my time applying for positions that aren't really
open.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: Relax. This is probably just run-of-the-mill corporate
disorganization, not some diabolical plot by evil recruitment
agencies.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of WORKWAYS () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  It's actually pretty common for companies to list a job but then
put the hiring process on hold.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just did an analysis for one of our major clients and found
that of 61 job orders, they ended up canceling eight,'' said Gary
Nelson, CEO of Nelson Human Resources, a staffing firm based in
Sonoma.
</P>
<P>
   Here are a few of the reasons why this happens:
</P>
<P>
   _Companies may list the same job with a half-dozen recruiting
firms. Then they're swamped with candidates. So they ask the firms
to stop forwarding any more names until the hiring manager has
weeded through the existing pile.
</P>
<P>
   _Companies may be hiring so much that they lose track of which
positions they've filled. So they put some job listings on hold
while they catch up on paperwork and figure out what's still really
open.
</P>
<P>
   _Companies may have planned on filling a position but then had a
sudden budget crunch that forced them to halt hiring temporarily.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes at the end of their fiscal year, companies will have
a hiring freeze of up to a month while they have to rejustify all
the positions for the next year,'' said Eric Wheel, general manager
of Management Recruiters International in Mill Valley. ``We've even
seen cases where the hiring manager doesn't know that a job has
been frozen. The president tells human resources to freeze all
jobs, and the manager first hears about it from the recruiter.''
</P>
<P>
   Is there anything you can do to avoid applying for positions
that aren't currently available? Not really: It's just one of the
many little detours people face on the road to a new job.
</P>
<P>
   So don't take it personally, and don't get all worked up about
deceitful recruiting agencies. Just keep on applying. Eventually,
you'll get the job you want.
</P>
<P>
   Touting Wellness Training
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have a small company that provides health and nutrition
training at corporations. It seems clear to me that improving the
health of employees will boost company productivity. But how do I
demonstrate this with my clients' bottom line?
</P>
<P>
   A: Your business is a tiny part of a big trend _ ``wellness
programs,'' as health promotion programs in the workplace are
called.
</P>
<P>
   A 1998 survey by Hewitt Associates concluded that 91 percent of
large U.S. companies now offer some kind of wellness program, up
from 64 percent in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   These range from cholesterol screenings and flu shots to
nutrition classes or stop-smoking workshops.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of studies have tried to document the
dollars-and-cents impact of wellness programs. ``These studies
generally conclude that companies save about $3 in medical costs or
$4 in absenteeism for every $1 spent on health promotion,'' said
Dr. Steven Freedman, a health care quality expert with William M.
Mercer in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   How can you quantify the impact of your particular trainings?
Frankly, it's very difficult.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of WORKWAYS () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Suppose you could get one of your client firms to track employee
absences before and after you provided a training. Suppose that
absences, in fact, declined.
</P>
<P>
   You'd still have a tough time proving that the decline was due
to your training _ rather than to a lighter flu season, a new crop
of younger and healthier employees, or some other unrelated factor.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, your best bet is probably to rely on the general
studies cited by Freedman.
</P>
<P>
   You can find a good summary of existing research on the
financial impact of corporate wellness programs in the March/April
1998 issue of ``The Art of Health Promotion,'' which is published
by the American Journal of Health Promotion. For a back copy, call
the Journal at (248) 682-0707.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Send your work and career questions to Ilana DeBare, Workways, San
Francisco Chronicle, 901 Mission St., San Francisco 94103. Or send
e-mail to workways(at sign)sfgate.com. &LR;   &LR; Or call (415) 764-2815. We
can't respond to each query, but we will answer as many in print as
we can. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
