<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOOPER05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Murder trial just Looper's latest crisis
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Byron Looper forever linked a campaign slogan to his
identity when he legally changed his middle name last year from
Anthony to (Low Tax). But the really wacky stuff had swirled around
the former metro Atlanta resident before that.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks after he was elected tax assessor in a small Tennessee
county in 1996, Looper hardly ever came to work, according to Joel
Reimer, who was a campaign adviser to Looper and worked in the tax
office until Looper fired him. When Looper did come to work, he
worried about wiretaps in his office, according to Reimer, and
hired a security chief to investigate. In March, a grand jury
indicted him on 14 counts of official misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   After a former girlfriend served him with a paternity suit,
according to a lawyer representing Looper, he said she ``left me
with heart palpitations, a small box of memorabilia and a red
G-string.''
</P>
<P>
   But questions bobbing in the wake of those minidramas lack the
weight of the one Looper will be asked about today in court: Did he
shoot to death a political rival to try to win an election in
November?
</P>
<P>
   At his Circuit Court arraignment in Crossville, Tenn., Looper
will be read a first-degree murder charge that accuses him of the
Oct. 19 fatal shooting of state Sen. Tommy Burks.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Trant, the attorney defending Looper, said he will plead
innocent. He has filed a motion to move the trial from Cumberland
County to neighboring Roane County because of ``tremendous
prejudicial publicity.''
</P>
<P>
   Investigators have not indicated whether they have any physical
evidence linking Looper to the crime.
</P>
<P>
   Brilla Garrett, who was Looper's second in command in the
assessor's office, said in a recent television interview that she
had had faith in Looper's innocence. ``I'm a supporter of his. ...
He believes he will be proven innocent,'' Garrett said.
</P>
<P>
   Since his arrest three months ago, according to published
reports, Looper has fired employees at the tax assessor's office
from his jail cell, his elected office has been stripped away, he
has been dogged for blood samples in the paternity suit, and has
fired a defense attorney. Every twist in the real-life soap opera
makes waves across the Tennessee farming region just down from the
Cumberland Plateau.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the biggest thing to hit the county in living
memory,'' said Henry Fincher, a lawyer who managed a last-minute
write-in campaign against Looper. ``It galvanized the community.''
</P>
<P>
   A popular Democratic incumbent, Burks was found shot dead in his
pickup truck. He had been preparing to take kindergarten students
on an annual tour of his pumpkin farm.
</P>
<P>
   In the following days, Looper, the Republican opponent, was
nowhere to be found. Townspeople wondered why Looper hadn't called
the family to offer condolences.
</P>
<P>
   Police staked out Looper's house. Four days later, Looper drove
up at 12:56 a.m. in his navy blue Chevy Beretta. He calmly greeted
officers and offered them Cokes, according to news accounts of the
arrest.
</P>
<P>
   After the slaying, Looper's had been the only name left on the
ballot for Tennessee state Senate District 15. Then Burks' widow,
Charlotte, registered as a write-in candidate. She won 96 percent
of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   One of the candidates to replace Looper as tax assessor is Kim
Burks Blaylock, the oldest daughter of the man Looper is charged
with killing. From jail, Looper tried running his office. He wrote
letters and faxes. He fired a deputy assessor, accusing the man of
``poor attitude, failure to perform his job adequately and
threatening superiors.'' County officials successfully removed
Looper from office Jan. 26.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was upset by that. He wanted to keep that job,'' said
defense attorney Trant.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
