<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 22:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2522 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RETAIL-SALES-ART-NYT &LR;      02-04 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RETAIL-SALES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.)  
 BRISK STORE SALES DEFY USUAL JANUARY DOLDRUMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By LESLIE KAUFMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Perhaps January is not just for clearance sales anymore. Still
feeling in a spending mood even after a generous Christmas shopping
spree, Americans continued to show interest in both liquidation and
full-priced merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   January sales in stores open at least a year, a standard
industry measure, jumped an impressive 7.4 percent, according to
the Goldman, Sachs retail composite index. That was up from 4.5
percent in January 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The increases, which exceeded analysts' expectations by 2
percent to 3 percent, were particularly notable because they
occurred across the retail spectrum. Discounters, as usual, led the
pack. But everyone (with only a few outstanding exceptions), from
specialty apparel stores to the previously beleaguered department
stores, shined.
</P>
<P>
   ``If your numbers weren't good, you stood out like a sore
thumb,'' said Kurt Barnard, president of Barnard's Retail Trend
Report.
</P>
<P>
   Because January is a relatively unimportant month for the retail
industry, typically accounting for only about 5 percent of annual
sales, the surprisingly buoyant sales were expected to have a
positive but minimal impact on earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Still the numbers were good enough that many in the industry
believed it indicated that January was evolving into more than just
a month to liquidate inventory.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Feiner, a senior retail analyst with Lehman Brothers,
said, ``Up until the last years, January was a clearance month. Now
retailers are bringing in spring merchandise earlier and having the
month stand on its own instead of just dumping goods.''
</P>
<P>
   Continued consumer confidence was the main reason for rising
sales. Mary Tolan, a global managing partner for retail with
Andersen Consulting, said: ``People just have a lot more to spend.
Also they are increasingly being paid by variable compensation'' _
bonuses, for example _ ``that comes late in the year, so that could
affect January sales, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The arrival of cold winter weather after an unseasonably warm
December also played a role in pushing sweaters, snowblowers and
other seasonal goods off the shelves. Susan Eich, a spokeswoman for
Dayton Hudson Corp., said, ``There was definitely a pent-up demand
for cold weather apparel.''
</P>
<P>
   Discounters continued to barrel ahead of the crowd in January.
Wal-Mart, the nation's largest retailer, experienced a 10.3 percent
jump in sales in stores opened a year. Family Dollar topped that
performance with a 13.1 percent gain. And Target, a unit of Dayton
Hudson Corp., enjoyed a 9.6 percent rise. According to analysts,
those gains came from strong sales of regular-price merchandise as
well as sale goods.
</P>
<P>
   Specialty stores also continued their run. Sales for the Gap
Inc., powered by phenomenal performances at its Old Navy and Banana
Republic divisions, rose 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Taylor Stores posted 13.3 gains. A spokeswoman, Jill Golden,
said the company ``was pleased with customer response to both our
sale and full-priced lines.''
</P>
<P>
   The department stores, which in recent years have suffered by
being neither as cheap as the discounters nor as chic as the
specialty stores, managed to hold their own last month. Federated
Department Stores Inc., which operates both the Macy's and
Bloomingdale's chains, had an increase of 7.3 percent. Dayton
Hudson department stores even managed to outperform its hot sister
division Target with 11.8 percent growth.
</P>
<P>
   Saks Inc., which owns both Saks Fifth Avenue and the Profitt's
stores, had an 8 percent increase. A spokeswoman, Jennifer Mann,
said that clearances had been carefully controlled. ``There were no
promotions beyond those scheduled,'' at the beginning of the fiscal
year, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The season's big losers were the familiarly troubled names. J.C.
Penney &UR;  &LR; saw sales in stores open a year slide 1.5 percent from last
year. The midmarket retailer, suffering from heavy competition from
discounters, has been struggling for nearly four years to redefine
its niche.
</P>
<P>
   Talbots Inc., whose results declined 13 percent, was also sorely
out of line with its competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Baum, senior retail analyst with Goldman, Sachs, said
that the most important result of the unusually strong January may
be that retailers are well positioned for the next season. ``We've
learned that the consumer is still alive and well and that most
stores have successfully cleared out fall and winter merchandise
and are set to be busy this spring,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
