<HEADLINE>
FRANKLIN KEYSAR, STAGE MANAGER, DIES AT 60 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
 N.H., Mass., Conn., R.I., Tenn. )  c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Franklin Keysar, a production stage manager for more
than 20 Broadway shows, died on Jan. 25 at Lenox Hill Hospital in
Manhattan. He was 60 and lived in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was liver cancer, his publicist said.
</P>
<P>
   Keysar, who was born in Warren, N.H., graduated from the Boston
University School of Fine and Applied Arts. He was stage manager at
the Manhattan Theater Club for the Stephen Sondheim revue ``Putting
It Together,'' with Julie Andrews, and for Woody Allen's ``Floating
Light Bulb'' at Lincoln Center Theater.
</P>
<P>
   He also worked at the Trinity Repertory Company in Providence,
R.I., the Williamstown Theater Festival in Massachusetts and the
Long Wharf Theater in New Haven.
</P>
<P>
   Alfred Uhry's ``Last Night of Ballyhoo,'' which won a Tony Award
in 1997, was Keysar's 24th Broadway show as a production stage
manager.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his mother, Bertha, of Warren; three sisters,
Phyllis Colby-Mudgett and Patti Bartlett, both of Bristol, N.H.,
and Virginia Keysar of Piermont, N.H.; and three brothers, Philip,
of Yarmouthport, Mass., Donald, of Warren, and Gary, of
Elizabethton, Tenn.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
