<SLUG> BC-BEAR-PROBE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEAR STEARNS INQUIRY EXTENDED 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A state court judge approved a move Thursday that
gives the Manhattan district attorney's office more time to
continue its investigation of the Bear Stearns Cos.' ties to the
failed brokerage firm A.R. Baron &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Edward McLaughlin of New York State Supreme Court
extended an order that has halted testimony since August in
arbitration hearings involving A.R. Baron. The stay will now last
until March 19.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors are reviewing whether Bear Stearns, which cleared
A.R. Baron's trades, knew of or aided a scheme in which A.R. Baron
executives defrauded investors of $75 million. A.R. Baron and 13
former employees have pleaded guilty or have been convicted of
criminal charges.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors want testimony halted in the related arbitration
proceedings because they do not want witnesses in the criminal
inquiry to testify yet in the arbitrations, which might help Bear
Stearns learn about what prosecutors know.
</P>
<P>
   A Bear Stearns spokeswoman declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, The Wall Street Journal reported that the
Securities and Exchange Commission staff had notified Bear Stearns
that the staff intended to recommend that a civil lawsuit be filed
against the firm.
</P>
</TEXT>
