<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 22:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2530 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-MANAGERS05-CO     02-04 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-MANAGERS05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Witness ban decried as unfair
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ One by one they stood, the House managers, offering
a final plea for calling witnesses in President Clinton's
impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   They made their request even though they believed the deck was
stacked against them. They made their request even though they had
been told for weeks by senators of their own party that they did
not want to hear live testimony in the sordid saga of the
president's affair with a former intern.
</P>
<P>
   As predicted, the vote for bringing forward even one witness in
the perjury and obstruction case against the president failed, and
failed big _ by 40 votes.
</P>
<P>
   Now the only way the public will hear witnesses will be via
videotapes of their depositions _ videotapes that prompted Sen.
Robert Bennett (R-Utah) to say he was glad to have had a
fast-forward button when he viewed them.
</P>
<P>
   The vote against calling witnesses to the Senate chamber only
affirmed a prevailing view among House prosecutors that the trial
has not really been a trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``The senators have denied themselves the ability to render a
fair verdict, and they have denied us the ability to present a case
in a fair way,'' said Rep. Bob Barr (R-Ga.), one of the
prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Barr said he no longer loses sleep over the twists in the trial
because ``all semblance of fairness'' vanished when it was made
clear weeks ago that prosecutors would not be allowed to call
witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew they were going to vote it down,'' Barr said. ``The
Senate, for all their stature, is not that subtle when it comes to
telling others what it wants.''
</P>
<P>
   And even the less vocal critics of the Senate's actions agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the traditional sense of a trial, it really hasn't been,''
said Rep. Henry Hyde (R-Ill.), the leader of the prosection team.
``It hasn't been a trial because witnesses were omitted and the
prosecution (was) restricted on how much and in what fashion they
could present their evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a different sort of a creature,'' Hyde said. ``I
wish things were different. I'd like a freer process. But we live
within the parameters they give us.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked why the prosecutors continued to push forward given
the clear resistance in the Senate from his own party, he said it
comes down to ``duty.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If we walk away from our duty, how do we explain that to
history?'' asked Hyde. ``It's a matter of conscience, a matter of
the Constitution. It's a matter of doing our duty, onerous and
unpleasant and backlashy as it may be.''
</P>
<P>
   If the House prosecutors had merely taken the temperature of the
country and heeded the polls, the trial would have been long over,
Hyde said. But that would not be upholding the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors say that from the beginning they have had to
fight to win approval for procedures that are considered de rigueur
in typical court proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   That point was dutifully noted by Rep. James Rogan (R-Calif.),
the prosecutor who grilled White House aide Sidney Blumenthal under
oath earlier in the week.
</P>
<P>
   In urging the Senate to call witnesses to the floor, Rogan said
it was unusual to stop the ``triers of fact'' from calling
witnesses to prove their charges.
</P>
<P>
   There is a reason the Founding Fathers created a judiciary
system in which trials are open, he said. ``For the sake of this
body, please allow this trial to be a public trial in the real
sense.''
</P>
<P>
   The frustration of the prosecutors boiled to the surface after
the vote on calling a witness failed. Rogan and White House
attorney David Kendall tussled over Kendall's request to view the
video snippets that the prosecution wanted to display Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the appropriate legal response to your request is
that it is none of your damn business what the other side is going
to put on,'' said Rogan, quoting a former California Supreme Court
justice's response to a similar request in a case there.
</P>
<P>
   To that Kendall retorted that he didn't think that ``trial by
surprise has a place here.''
</P>
<P>
   After it was over, Sen. Paul Coverdell (R-Ga.) said he thought
the proceedings had been fair. Sure, House prosecutors did not get
everything they had sought, but that is the case with any
proceeding. ``I think we've been fair to all parties,'' Coverdell
said.
</P>
<P>
   That is hardly how the House prosecutors see it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so sorry that there was such a push on the part of some to
just ram through this thing and treat it as though it was an
afterthought, rather than a constitutional process,'' Rogan said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
