<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 22:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2534 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-AFRICA-2TAKES-NYT     02-04 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-AFRICA-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FINE LINE BETWEEN AN OFFER OF HELP AND A BRIBE 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: See also OLY-Drug)  By IAN FISHER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAIROBI, Kenya _ What is the difference, Charles Mukora wondered
Thursday, between a sincere offer to help athletes in a poor nation
like Kenya and a bribe?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' said Mukora, 64, who has found himself
portrayed as a villain, if a pleasant one, in the Olympic bribery
scandal. ``Perhaps you can tell me?''
</P>
<P>
   Mukora was expelled last month as a member of the International
Olympic Committee after being accused of accepting $34,650 for his
personal use from officials in Salt Lake City seeking to steer the
2002 Winter Games their way. He admits to taking the cash.
</P>
<P>
   But Mukora, one of more than 100 officials from around the world
who decide where to award the lucratively valuable designation of
Olympic site, contends that the money went solely to train distance
runners at a camp he owns that faces the gorgeous snowy cap of
Mount Kenya.
</P>
<P>
   Disputing the conclusions of the Olympic committee that ousted
him, Mukora says his only crime is to have been caught in an
inevitable conflict. He is from a poor nation _ and from Africa,
like three other of the six expelled committee members _ with
little money to train athletes but with the power to help decide
where the Games will be held.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you travel to a rich country or people from rich countries
visit you, you more or less point out the areas you want to
develop,'' said Mukora, who insisted he had never promised his vote
to anyone. ``Usually, the likely thing, they will suggest, `We can
do this or this.' And usually they offer to do something.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Olympic officials, past and present, acknowledge the logic
of Mukora's argument. It is no accident, they say, that Olympic
committee members from Africa and South America have found
themselves caught up in the scandal, and it does not mean that
Africans or others from underdeveloped countries are more disposed
to corruption.
</P>
<P>
   The Olympics have over the last 20 years grown into a huge and
quite profitable enterprise, and cities around the world have
become aggressive in trying to win the rights to stage them. At the
same time, the Olympic committee responsible for awarding the Games
has expanded to include more and more members from countries that
often have no chance of staging the Games themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The neediest countries, said Keba Mbaye, an IOC member from
Senegal who was on the six-member commission that investigated Salt
Lake City, are those most vulnerable to inducements.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of targeting of members and their votes has not been
helped, Olympic officials concede, by the imprecise guidelines laid
out by the IOC itself. The committee allows competing cities to
offer aid to sports programs in the countries of committee members
voting on the bids, but forbids such aid being given in return for
a vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``The line between an offer and a bribe,'' Mukora concluded,
``must be really very thin.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Mukora's protest that he is an ``innocent victim of
circumstance,'' there has been little public sympathy for him here
because many people suspect that the allegation he benefited
personally might be true.
</P>
<P>
   His Mount Kenya camp is a weedy collection of old farm buildings
where on one recent day two athletes performed perfunctory
stretches in front of a visiting reporter. He has also been accused
of receiving what amounted to $35,000 from officials in Sydney,
Australia and, oddly, a shipment of 500 bicycles from Beijing. Both
cities vied for the Games in 2000. Sydney officials have admitted
that they cannot definitively say where at least $12,000 they gave
to Mukora wound up.
</P>
<P>
   Even some of his friends _ like the legendary runner, Kipchoge
Keino, who Mukora coached to a gold medal in the 1968 Olympics _
applauded his decision last week to resign from the International
Olympic Committee rather than fight his expulsion.
</P>
<P>
   This past week, Mukora also resigned as head of Kenya's national
Olympic committee, a post he had held for 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you know you are guilty of whatever you have done, why
argue?'' asked Keino, who is reported to be in line as Mukora's
successor on the national committee.
</P>
<P>
   It was a sharp fall for a man who, for more than three decades,
had been the public face of sports in Kenya. As a coach and sports
administrator, he had done perhaps as much as anyone to make Kenyan
athletes some of the best in the world.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Though he had been a soccer and field hockey player in his own
right, Mukora rose to prominence after he coached the Kenyan
national team at the 1968 Olympics in Mexico City, where the nation
won its first gold medals and marked the beginning of three decades
of successes in track and field. The team performed well under
Mukora's coaching four years later at the Olympic Games in Munich.
</P>
<P>
   In 1969 he became a marketing trainee for Coca-Cola in Nairobi.
Soon he became the manager of external affairs and Coke's liason to
the sports world. Newspaper clippings that track his career, in
business and in the intrigues of amateur sports, are uniformly
glowing. He retired from Coke in 1990 for what he then called
``greener pastures.''
</P>
<P>
   He later became involved in politics. He represented a district
near Mount Kenya between 1992 and 1997 in Parliament and is said to
be close to Mwai Kibaki, head of the Democratic Party, who finished
second in the 1997 presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   But his real job began just before he left Coke. He became, in
quick succession, head of the national Olympic committee and a
delegate to the international committee. Money appears to have been
a major concern of his from the start.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the high quality of its athletes, Kenya has few
reliable, and no large, sources of income to train Olympic
athletes. The government gives only sporadically, according to the
national committee.
</P>
<P>
   Several private camps for runners _ the athletes who receive the
best care in Kenya _ are sponsored by shoe companies like Fila.
Nike has helped pay the national committee's expenses for seven
years now.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics, like Mukora Thiong'o, a former friend who is
secretary general of Kenya's wrestling program, suggested that at
least some money went into Mukora's own pocket. He accused Mukora,
for example, of selling the 500 bicycles from Beijing from a sports
shop he owned in downtown Nairobi. Mukora did not deny the
allegation in a news conference last week.
</P>
<P>
   Mukora also has given conflicting accounts of the money given
the Kenyan Olympic committee by Sydney. He initially said that the
money went only to train Kenyan athletes in Australia but later
said that, like the money from Salt Lake City, some $10,000 went
into a private foundation, which he runs with his son Peter, that
funds the camp near Mount Kenya. Mukora said he envisions the camp
as a huge athletic center that will ultimately cost $2.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, sports officials in Toronto say that Mukora was one
of two members of the Amateur Athletic Association who tried
unsuccessfully to solicit $1 million for their votes in 1991 to
award Canada the 1993 outdoor track and field championships.
</P>
<P>
   Though he lives in a wealthy part of Nairobi, Mukora has said he
would not fight his expulsion because he cannot afford to fly to
the Olympic headquarters in Switzerland to defend himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say I am rich because I wear nice clothes,'' he said
after a news conference last week. ``But I'm a poor man.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-04-99 2230EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
