<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 22:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2538 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-VANGUNDY-7     02-04 1099
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-VANGUNDY-725&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VAN GUNDY TONES EGOS DOWN, AND KNICKS ARE LOOKING UP  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Pa., Ind., N.Y. )  By SELENA ROBERTS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Last April, Jeff Van Gundy clung to the leg of Heat
center Alonzo Mourning and allowed himself to be dragged around the
floor like a rodeo clown.
</P>
<P>
   Five months before that, Van Gundy stood outside of a locker
room in Philadelphia after a miserable Knick loss and ridiculed his
own coaching abilities, saying, ``I disgraced myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the last three years, Van Gundy has been his players'
tireless protector and defender through flagrant fouls, fights and
suspensions. As a Knicks assistant coach for seven years, he was
the same way, once letting loose with an irrational outburst in
defense of John Starks. At the root of all these instances, is one
noble cause: his players.
</P>
<P>
   With the reputation Van Gundy has constructed, it is no wonder
that Latrell Sprewell, upon his introduction as a Knick two weeks
ago, referred to Van Gundy as a ``players' coach.'' While Van Gundy
shrugged off Sprewell's assessment, there is no doubting the
emotional bond the coach has created between himself and his top
players. He is unshakably close and unconditionally loyal.
</P>
<P>
   But is he too close, too loyal? Or has he struck just the right
relationship with his players to pull off the challenge before him?
When the renovated Knicks open the season in Orlando Friday, the
37-year-old Van Gundy will begin juggling a carton full of egos
that could crack at any time.
</P>
<P>
   As delicately as possible, he will try to integrate the brazen
aggressiveness of Sprewell without setting back the progress Allan
Houston made last year. He will attempt to deploy an undersized
Larry Johnson at power forward without risking his wear, and push
Marcus Camby without alienating him.
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, he has to convince Patrick Ewing that he is just as
star-worthy as a rebounder as he was in his decadelong role as the
only go-to guy in orange, white and blue. Perhaps Van Gundy,
leaning on a 10-year relationship with Ewing, has just the right
delivery, timing and tact to change the role of an often-stubborn
superstar.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was impossible for me,'' said Mavericks Coach Don Nelson,
who was fired after four stormy months with the Knicks in 1996.
``Patrick still saw himself as a dominant player, and I didn't see
it. He wasn't ready to accept change, just like Johnny Starks
wasn't ready to accept the sixth-man role for me. It's a difficult
thing. The person has to be ready to do it and make the sacrifice
for the team. Now, maybe it's different. I would think it wouldn't
be as hard for Patrick. But that wasn't the case when I was there.
It didn't work out for me. As a result, I wasn't there very long.''
</P>
<P>
   Lose Ewing, and Van Gundy could lose his longtime ally. Lose too
many games, and his ``player's coach'' label won't matter. Van
Gundy, with two years to go on a $2 million-a-year contract,
understands the tenuous nature of his position, and tries to find
humor in it.
</P>
<P>
   On the wall in his office, there is a framed back page from a
tabloid: Van Gundy with his neck in a noose. After Dave Checketts,
the president of Madison Square Garden, submerged his own morality
code and made a trade for the controversial Sprewell, the Knicks
are afloat in more talent than ever. There's no Michael Jordan in
the way, and no more excuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is, if we're not successful, I won't be here,''
Van Gundy said. ``I know that in every NBA job you win or you're
out. I know guys like a Phil Jackson _ or whoever else _ would want
this job. It's a very good job. But after three years, I think I'm
much more comfortable with the fact I've proven I can do a good
job. So I'm pretty secure with what I can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Sprewell's past, which includes the choking of the
Golden State coach, P.J. Carlesimo, Van Gundy was unabashed in his
desire to coach the three-time All-Star. He asked for this, and now
he has to alter a decade-old offense that centered on Ewing in the
post and a defense that relied on the jettisoned Charles Oakley in
the paint. Now, everyone has to pass, and everyone has to rebound.
Van Gundy has all but turned a theme of unselfishness into a
campaign slogan: Up with teamwork, down with ego.
</P>
<P>
   ``The unselfishness is there right now,'' Van Gundy said after a
good practice on Wednesday. ``When the lights go on, and the stats
are kept, I think we'll see for real.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Last year, the Pacers eliminated the Knicks in the second round.
Still, last year was a breakthrough season for Van Gundy. Not only
did he piece together a playoff team with a lineup threadbare after
injuries to Ewing and Chris Dudley, but he also managed to separate
himself from the shadow of Pat Riley. As a punctuation to that
fact, Van Gundy's undermanned team _ without Johnson, too, because
of his Game 4 fight with Mourning _ walked into Miami Arena and
defeated the specter of Riley with a Game 5 victory.
</P>
<P>
   At that moment, Van Gundy was not the student anymore. But Van
Gundy did not go unscathed last year, either. Often, his
substitution patterns were erratic and seemed guided by the comfort
he had with the players he knew well and was loyal to. As a result,
Van Gundy was criticized for trusting Starks, but wavering on
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I wouldn't have had it any other way,'' said
Houston, who, at the urging of Van Gundy, developed a more
aggressive game last year. ``With Jeff, as frustrated as I got, I
knew he saw something in me and had high expectations of me. He
still does. He still gets on me in practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside of practice, Van Gundy is selectively critical. He may
pick on Camby's work ethic, and question Dennis Scott's
conditioning. But almost as a policy, Van Gundy never points a
finger at his prized players, certainly not Ewing.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy's owes much of his rise to Ewing. Some of his own
players privately wondered if Van Gundy's attachment to Ewing was a
detriment to the team during last year's playoff series against
Indiana. Ewing made a valiant return from wrist surgery, but did
Van Gundy allow him too many minutes and too many shots?
</P>
<P>
   This year, Van Gundy's balancing act will be scrutinized even
more. But after all the time Van Gundy has spent building
relationships with his players and becoming the ``player's coach''
his team has grown to trust him unconditionally.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all respect Jeff,'' Houston said. ``We believe in what he's
doing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
