<SLUG> BC-CANADA-QUEBEC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OTTAWA AND PROVINCES (BUT NOT QUEBEC) AGREE ON SOCIAL PROGRAM 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By ANTHONY DePALMA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ A new deal that was supposed to reinforce Canada's
fragile national union by balancing power between the federal and
provincial governments has once again isolated the mostly
French-speaking province of Quebec from the rest of the country.
</P>
<P>
   After a closed-door meeting Thursday at Prime Minister Jean
Chretien's private residence in Ottawa, the leaders of nine
provinces and two territories agreed to a three-year administrative
arrangement under which the federal government agreed not to
introduce new national social programs unless a majority of the
provinces first accepted them.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government also agreed that any new programs dealing
with health, education or other social benefits would come with
federal funds.
</P>
<P>
   As an incentive to the provinces, the federal government also
agreed to increase money to the provinces for health care. The
exact amount will not be known until the new federal budget is
revealed later this month, but it is expected to total several
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Until last Saturday, Quebec's leaders believed they could accept
Ottawa's offer, which would have been taken as a strong sign of
Quebec's willingness to remain in Canada after several attempts to
separate.
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday, Premier Lucien Bouchard of Quebec said the federal
government had dropped an important provision that would have
allowed provinces to back out of national programs but still accept
the federal funds that would have accompanied them, if they
substituted local programs with similar goals and standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not on the same train today,'' Bouchard said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Quebec's refusal to join, Chretien called the new
arrangement a success. ``This will make Canada better,'' he told
reporters after the four-hour meeting broke up.
</P>
<P>
   Premier Mike Harris of Ontario said, ``It is an advance for all
of us, including Quebec.''
</P>
<P>
   The struggle between Ottawa and the provinces has gone on since
Canada's beginning in 1867. Mindful of the way strong states'
rights in the United States had contributed to the outbreak of the
Civil War, Canada's founders attempted to form a strong central
government.
</P>
<P>
   But partly because of the special demands of Quebec, which sees
itself as a separate nation, and also because of the western
provinces' desire for control of their own affairs, power has been
shifting to the provinces.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the federal government continues to try to impose some
sense of national identitity, fearing that unbridled provincial
power could lead to uneven levels of social benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I intend to offer the same thing to everybody,'' said
Chretien, who has been especially worried that without national
social programs, poor provinces might try to offer reduced levels
of services.
</P>
<P>
   But the provinces often see federal programs as unacceptable
meddling. Even something as seemingly uncontroversial as college
scholarships for needy students caused an uproar because Chretien,
who considers the scholarships part of his legacy as prime
minister, wants the federal government to bypass provincial
education officials.
</P>
<P>
   In a personal victory for Chretien, the arrangement signed
Thursday allows Ottawa to provide education grants when the money
goes directly to recipients, but not when it goes to educational
institutions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
