<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 22:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2551 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-SUSPECT-SHOT-1STLD     02-04 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SUSPECT-SHOT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNARMED MAN DIES AFTER POLICE FIRE 41 SHOTS AT HIM
</HEADLINE>
 
(subs 7th graf to fix typo, changing `of' to `off'; adds 25 new
grafs at end; story is now 2 takes) (also see NY-SUSPECT-COPS and NY-SUSPECT-PROFILE) 
(bl) 
By MICHAEL COOPER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ An unarmed West African immigrant with no criminal
record was killed early Thursday morning by four New York City
police officers who fired 41 shots at him in the doorway of his
Bronx apartment building, police said.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear Thursday why the officers had opened fire on the
man at 12:44 a.m. in the vestibule of his building at 1157 Wheeler
Ave. in the Soundview section of the Bronx. The man, Amadou Diallo,
22, who came to the United States from Guinea more than two years
ago and worked as a street peddler in Manhattan, died at the scene,
police said.
</P>
<P>
   The Bronx District Attorney's office is investigating the
shooting, whose details were still murky Thursday night because
there were apparently no civilian witnesses and none of the police
officers involved have given statements to investigators. But
Inspector Michael Collins, a police spokesman, said investigators
who went to the scene of the shooting did not find a weapon on or
near Diallo.
</P>
<P>
   Relatives and neighbors described Diallo as a shy, hard-working
man with a ready smile, a devout Muslim who did not smoke or drink.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very angry,'' said his uncle, Mamadou Diallo. ``He was a
skinny guy. Why would the police shoot somebody of that nature 30
or 40 times? We see the police and we give them all the respect we
have.''
</P>
<P>
   A friend, Demba Sanyang, 39, said: ``We have a very undemocratic
society back home, and then we come here. We don't expect to be
killed by law enforcement officers.''
</P>
<P>
   The four officers involved in the shooting were assigned to the
aggressive Street Crimes Unit, which focuses largely on taking
illegal guns off the street. All four officers, who were in
plainclothes, used their 9-millimeter semiautomatic service
pistols, which hold 16 bullets and can discharge all of them in
seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the officers, Sean Carroll, 35, and Edward McMellon, 26,
emptied their weapons, firing 16 shots each, police said. Officer
Kenneth Boss, 27, fired his gun five times and Officer Richard
Murphy, 26, fired four times. All four have been put on
administrative leave.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the officers _ Carroll, McMellon and Boss _ have been
involved in shootings before, which is unusual in a department
where more than 90 percent of all officers never fire their weapons
in the line of duty. In those previous incidents, Carroll and
McMellon were found to have acted properly, police said; the case
of Boss _ he shot and killed a man said to be armed with a shotgun
on Oct. 31, 1997, in Brooklyn _ is still being reviewed by the
Brooklyn district attorney's office.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Police officers are trained not to fire unless they fear for the
lives of themselves or others. But once they decide to shoot, they
aim for the center of the body and fire until they ``stop'' their
target.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday morning, the four officers were patrolling the East
Bronx in an unmarked car, hoping, the department said, to make
arrests and in the process turn up information about a serial
rapist in the area.
</P>
<P>
   At 12:44 a.m., the officers encountered Diallo. All four got out
of the car and approached him as he stood in the vestibule of his
building, the department said.
</P>
<P>
   A police official who spoke on condition of anonymity said that
a neighborhood resident who had gone out to move his car to another
parking spot reported seeing a man, who police believe was Diallo,
loitering in the vestibule. The man described him as ``acting
suspicious,'' said the official, who did not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   The officers did not communicate over their radios before they
approached Diallo, police said, so investigators do not have an
initial report of why they confronted him.
</P>
<P>
   A second police official who spoke on condition of anonymity
said, ``We don't know what happened, because we haven't spoken to
them, but it looks like one guy may have panicked and the rest
followed suit.''
</P>
<P>
   After the shooting, the officers called in on their radios,
police said, and neighbors telephoned 911. Soon other officers
arrived on the scene, followed by detectives and the ranking
officers who are required to respond to all police shootings.
</P>
<P>
   An investigation began, and no weapon was found on Diallo,
Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   A pager and a wallet were found lying next to his body, a police
official said.
</P>
<P>
   Diallo, a member of the Fulani ethnic group, came from the
village of Lelouma. He came to New York two and a half years ago,
following the steps of relatives. He worked as a street peddler,
selling socks, gloves and videos on 14th Street in Manhattan. He
sent much of the money he earned to his parents back home, friends
said.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Diallo arrived home from work around midnight, said
his roommate, Momodou Kujabi. The two men discussed who was going
to pay the Con Edison bill, and then Diallo turned on the
television and Kujabi went to bed. Another roommate, Diallo's
cousin, Abdou Rahman Diallo, was already asleep.
</P>
<P>
   Kujabi said he thought Diallo might have gone out for something
to eat, as he often did after coming home from work.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the shots, and a knock on the door, he said. It was
the police.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Kujabi said the officers brought him down to the vestibule to
identify his friend's body. ``I said, `How can this happen?'''
Kujabi recalled. ``I left this guy less than 30 minutes ago.''
</P>
<P>
   An autopsy found that Diallo died of multiple gunshot wounds to
the torso, said Ellen Borakove, a spokeswoman for the Chief Medical
Examiner's Office. Further tests are required to learn how many
wounds there were and where the bullets entered his body, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Stuart London, a lawyer representing the officers, said he was
still trying to determine the facts of the case. ``It would be
premature to comment,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani urged people to withhold judgment on the
case. ``We've had terrible mistakes in this city when people have
reacted to rumors and intuitions and feelings,'' he said. ``Let's
let the situation run its course and then let's react to the
facts.''
</P>
<P>
   But as news of the shooting spread through the neighborhood,
where many immigrants from Mauritania and Guinea live, people
gathered to ask themselves why a young man with no history of
trouble would be shot by police.
</P>
<P>
   Kyle Waters, a lawyer representing Diallo's family, said: ``My
concern is that this was an overreaction on the part of the New
York City Police Department. There was nothing to indicate that he
was a criminal, nothing to indicate that he had a weapon. For him
to be sent back to his homeland in Guinea in a box is a horrible
tragedy. The family wants some sort of justice here.''
</P>
<P>
   New York state Assemblyman Ruben Diaz, who represents the area,
said: ``I'm appalled by this. It's outrageous. It clearly shows
excessive force was used.''
</P>
<P>
   Steven Reed, a spokesman for the Bronx district attorney's
office, said, ``The shooting is under investigation by our office,
and it's likely that it will be subject to a grand-jury review.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said the circumstances of the shooting were unclear
because the officers involved had invoked what is known as the
48-hour rule, which gives police officers two business days to
consult with their union lawyers before they speak to
investigators.
</P>
<P>
   But police officials said that was not the case; instead, they
said, they have not spoken to the officers because the Bronx
district attorney's office asked them not to. That is common
practice in police shootings.
</P>
<P>
   First, prosecutors pursue possible criminal charges, and police
officers, like other citizens, can invoke their right against
self-incrimination. Then the Police Department pursues possible
administrative charges. The 48-hour rule comes into play here,
because police officers can be dismissed if they refuse to answer
questions.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Diallo's relatives began making plans to return his
body to his parents in the village of Lelouma. ``I think there is
no reason to shoot someone more than 30 times,'' said Mamadou
Diallo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
