<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-DRUGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IOC ADOPTS WATERED-DOWN DRUG DECLARATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By PAUL L. MONTGOMERY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAUSANNE, Switzerland _ After three days of debate, the
International Olympic Committee adopted a watered-down declaration
on doping Thursday at its drug summit that only underscored its
eroded authority.
</P>
<P>
   While Juan Antonio Samaranch, the IOC president, said the
declaration brought ``hope for the athletes of the world, hope for
the fans and hope for human dignity,'' the 15-nation European Union
rejected the Olympic committee's leadership and did not approve the
declaration as the summit came to a close Thursday U.S. support was
lukewarm.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the American position on doping fell under
attack again. Richard Pound, an IOC vice president from Canada,
criticized the United States' attitude toward doping, pointedly
noting that Mark McGwire, who used a supplement banned by the
Olympics while setting the home run record last summer, had become
a national hero.
</P>
<P>
   ``The closer you are to the Olympic movement, the more you are
concerned about doping,'' Pound said. ``The farther away from it
you are, the less you care. All of a sudden you are in Mark McGwire
land, and this is a national hero all souped up.''
</P>
<P>
   The IOC's efforts to push through an antidoping program that it
would control failed during the summit here.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution adopted on Thursday proposes only the
establishment of a committee at the IOC and work by the national
governments within three months to form a council of the proposed
committee to elect a president, appoint a staff and begin work by
the summer games in Sydney, Australia, next year.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC backed off actually creating an antidoping agency and
imposing mandatory two-year drug sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Banks, the British minister of sport, who has been
prominent in the attack on Samaranch and the IOC, said some of the
provisions of Thursdays resolution were ``both minimalist and
permissive.'' ``These issues are bigger than the IOC,'' he said.
``It might come as a surprise to the IOC to find there is actually
something bigger than the IOC, but there is.''
</P>
<P>
   From Washington, Gen. Barry R. McCaffrey, the director of the
Office of National Drug Control Policy, who had represented the
U.S. government at the conference but left early, expressed
qualified approval of the resolution. He said that it was a ``good
first step'' but that the United States had concerns about the
creation of a worldwide antidoping agency independent of the IOC,
stiffer sanctions for athletes caught using drugs, and the will of
international sports to step up research into detecting currently
undetectable performance-enhancing substances.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC called the conference last summer after doping scandals
at the Tour de France and elsewhere and had expected to remain in
charge of the worldwide antidrug effort. In the meantime, however,
some European governments began to take antidoping action
independent of international sports bodies.
</P>
<P>
   The main IOC proposal was for creation of a worldwide agency to
conduct drug testing in and out of competition, refine analyses of
urine and blood samples, and educate the young against using sports
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Before the conference, Samaranch said he expected to preside
over the agency and suggested Prince Alexandre de Merode, who has
headed the Olympics' antidrug committee for 30 years, as director.
Soon after the conference opened, however, most of the major
industrialized countries indicated that continued IOC control of
the antidoping effort would be unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he might be elected president of the proposed
committee, Samaranch said, ``I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Banks said Samaranch's control of the antidoping agency was
unlikely, however, ``If we are going to start off the right foot, I
think it would be better for the IOC not to be in the chair,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The equally contentious problem of sanctions for athletes caught
doping was also not resolved. The IOC had proposed a minimum
two-year ban for a first offense and the existing life ban for a
second. In the final declaration, powerful sports federations in
the Olympic movement for cycling, soccer and tennis had won
mitigation of the two-year ban if special circumstances were found.
</P>
<P>
   Criticism at the conference ranged beyond the Olympic movement
when Pound made his remarks about McGwire, who acknowledged last
summer that he used the supplement androstenedione, which is banned
by the IOC, the NF L and the NCAA.
</P>
<P>
   The dietary supplement is not banned by Major League Baseball,
the NBA or the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire's agent, Robert Cohen, called Pound's statement
``incorrect and highly irresponsible.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the Major League Baseball Players Association also
took exception to Pound's comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's unfortunate but the pressure of the IOC's other
problems seem to be having their effect on Pound,'' said Donald
Fehr, the association's executive director, alluding to the bidding
scandal enveloping the Olympic committee.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
