<HEADLINE>
KRAFT, AN EARLY BIRD, SHARES LEAD WITH QUIGLEY 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Fla., Cal.)  By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEBBLE BEACH, Calif. _ Greg Kraft was awake by dawn on Thursday
morning, but the early start was worthwhile.
</P>
<P>
   Drawing the second-earliest tee time at Pebble Beach Golf Links,
Kraft enjoyed his best round of the year, taking advantage of calm
early-morning conditions and perfectly manicured greens. Shooting a
six-under-par 66 and heading a leader board that included some
unexpected names, Kraft shared the lead with Brett Quigley after
Thursday's first round of the AT&AMP;T Pebble Beach National Pro-Am.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Jacobsen, who won at Pebble Beach in 1995, was one stroke
behind in third place after shooting a 67 at Poppy Hills, one of
three courses on which the tournament is played.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the weather problems that have plagued this prestigious
event in recent years, 8 of the top 12 players in the world ranking
have entered _ Tiger Woods, David Duval, Mark O'Meara, Davis Love
III, Vijay Singh, Jim Furyk, Justin Leonard and Phil Mickelson.
</P>
<P>
   With names like that in the field, who expected Kraft and
Quigley to share the first-round lead? Yet, while many prominent
players started slowly _ Duval, winner of 9 of his last 29 events,
shot an even-par 72 at Spyglass Hill Golf Course _ Kraft was
steady, in a bogey-free round that included six birdies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt pretty comfortable on the greens today, after coming
here for eight years,'' said Kraft, a 34-year-old from Clearwater,
Fla., who is still looking for his first victory on the PGA Tour.
``My first few years here, I didn't understand that everything
breaks to the ocean. It took a little while to trust and learn
that. But I like it so much here, I've never skipped it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going into the day, I was worried about my early draw. It
could be damp, cold, windy. I was wondering what to expect.
Actually, it was very benign, not much wind, and it wasn't that
cold.''
</P>
<P>
   Compared with last year, when heavy rain postponed the finish
for six months and shortened the event to 54 holes, Thursday's
conditions were a picnic under partly sunny skies, although the
wind picked up as the day progressed. Most of the best scores came
at Pebble Beach. Quigley, who lost his full-time playing privileges
last year, also played at Pebble Beach. Charles Raulerson, who was
tied for fourth at 68, had the best score at Spyglass Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Many fans ventured to Spyglass Hill to follow the glamour group
of Woods, who was paired with the actor Kevin Costner and O'Meara,
who was paired with Ken Griffey Jr. Neither O'Meara (71) nor Woods
(72) was in top form, but the small gallery following Kraft saw
some splendid shots. Starting on the back nine, Kraft built early
momentum with a six-foot birdie putt on No. 10, and he followed
that with his best shot of the day _ a 50-foot birdie putt at the
par-3 No. 12. Kraft took that long putt as a sign that things might
go his way.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm putting well, my attitude is always good, because no
matter what happens, you can always make up for it with a putt,''
he said. ``But if I'm struggling with my putter, I'm frustrated.''
</P>
<P>
   Kraft secured his tour card for this year by finishing 94th on
the 1998 money list with $326,571, including a tie for fourth at
the United Airlines Hawaiian Open. His best round last year came at
the PGA Championship, when he set the Sahalee Country Club course
record with a 63. Kraft shot a 73 that Sunday and fell into a tie
for 23d, but the 63 was satisfying.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft spent much of November and December having a sore left
shoulder treated after it bothered him for more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The shoulder is great and the swing is fine,'' Kraft said.
``After the work I put in during the off season, it would be sweet
to win. A lot of mornings I dreaded getting up and working out, but
it all seemed to pay off today.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
