<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAVS, YES MAVS, EYE PLAYOFFS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ After a decade of futility, the clouds no
longer appear dark to the Mavericks.
</P>
<P>
   The days when this team had a better chance of winning the NBA
draft lottery than winning its share of basketball games seemed to
have passed. Two years of wheeling and dealing by coach/general
manager Don Nelson have the Mavericks entering tonight's season
opener at Seattle with their deepest and most experienced team this
decade, their most scoring muscle since Jason Kidd, Jim Jackson and
Jamal Mashburn were in town and a legitimate chance at making the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson, the Mavericks' coach and general manager, revamped his
roster this season by bringing in rookie Dirk Nowitzki, adding
veterans John ``Hot Rod'' Williams, Gary Trent and Steve Nash, and
re-signing free agent Cedric Ceballos.
</P>
<P>
   Combining those five with budding all-star Michael Finley,
Samaki Walker, A.C. Green, Shawn Bradley, Hubert Davis, Robert
Pack, Erick Strickland and Chris Anstey fills Nelson with high
expectations for the Mavericks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're pretty good, but I think we have to prove it,''
Nelson said. ``... Making the playoffs is a goal that we have.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a reasonable goal, considering how deep in the tunnel
this franchise has been this entire decade. Other than a brief
flurry during the 1994-95 season when Kidd, Jackson and Mashburn
led the Mavericks to a 36-win season, the Mavericks have done
nothing but trip over themselves in the 1990s. The decade includes
an 11-win season in 1992-'93 and a 13-win season in 1993-'94.
</P>
<P>
   Walker has the longest running tenure of any of the current
Mavericks players. And he didn't come aboard until the summer of
1996. But Walker likes the crop of players Nelson has assembled.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't replace superstars like Jason Kidd, Mashburn, Chris
Gatling and Jim Jackson,'' Walker said. ``Those are all-star
material guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I can say that the personalities here of the players are
such that I think we're going to win for the simple fact that we
come out here and work hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Finley has emerged as the Mavericks' go-to player, and he and
Ceballos provide a formidable 1-2 scoring punch. Nowitzki, Nash and
Walker also add scoring strength.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finley is a future all-star for many years to come, but going
down the roster you don't have too many Finleys on this team,''
Walker said. ``But you do have some players with significant
abilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Strickland has noticed the quality of the depth the Mavericks
have on their roster, and says it makes for some competitive
practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody goes out every day in practice and challenges each
other, and it makes us better,'' he said. ``Practice has been very
intense. We get after each other, we're very physical, and we push
each other each day. I think that's what's going to make us better
in the long run.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Mavericks attempt to change their losing ways, and be one
of the eight teams in the Western Conference to advance to the
playoffs, they received no help from the NBA schedule-maker during
this 13-week, 50-game season. Nine of their first 11 games are on
the road. And the two home games are against two of this year's top
NBA title contenders, Utah and Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``My preparation to them really is that there aren't going to be
a lot of practice days for the entire season, so we're going to
have to make adjustments as we go,'' Nelson said. ``We're going to
be either in the air \Rtraveling\S or on the floor playing ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are very few days off, so prepare themselves mentally.
I've prepared them physically, so they're ready to roll.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
