<SLUG> BC-RODEO-JOHNSTON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRONC RIDER'S FAST COMEBACK NOT ADVISED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRETT HOFFMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ When the plane started going down, Scott
Johnston never thought he was going to die. After all, the trees
were there to break the fall of the single-engine plane carrying De
Leon resident Johnston and three other cowboys to a rodeo in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The crash of the Cessna 210 killed the pilot and left Johnston
with a broken back. But the 25-year-old Australian never thought he
wasn't going to compete again. And despite advice from friends and
physicians that he has come back too early, Johnston is not only
competing but is among the leaders in saddle bronc riding as the
semifinal round starts today in the Southwestern Exposition and
Livestock Show Rodeo at Will Rogers Memorial Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no use in letting fear getting in the road,'' Johnston
said. ``When the plane started going down, it wasn't as bad as
you'd think.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were praying all of the way down. I didn't think we were
going to die. I thought that we would get through it. We first hit
treetops, and the impact of hitting the trees is what caused our
injuries.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnston underwent surgery to fuse two vertebrae in his lower
back. A rod was inserted to solidify the fusion, and the recovery
time from such a procedure can be two to six months, said Tandy
Freeman, a physician with the Justin Sportsmedicine on-site medical
team at the rodeo.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been advised not to ride,'' Freeman said. ``The risk he
takes now is not giving the fusion enough time to get solid. It's
pretty impressive that he's riding.''
</P>
<P>
   The crash occurred on Nov. 4. En route to a San Francisco rodeo
were Johnston; Marvin Garrett, a four-time world bareback riding
champion; Mark Garrett, also a world champion in bareback riding;
and Thad Bothwell, who had already secured a berth in his first
National Finals Rodeo in bull riding.
</P>
<P>
   The plane ran out of gas and went down near Lodi, Calif.. Pilot
Johnny Morris, a retired rodeo cowboy who died in a hospital two
weeks after the crash, had attempted to switch the fuel lines over
to a reserve tank. But after the fuel-tank transfer malfunctioned,
the plane crashed into treetops.
</P>
<P>
   After the plane snapped through the trees, fell to the ground
and caught on fire, the five men scrambled out of the cabin.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Garrett escaped almost unscathed and is competing in the
Fort Worth Rodeo. But his elder brother, Marvin, underwent surgery
to fuse three vertebrae in his back and secure his broken right arm
with a plate, and his return is indefinite. Bothwell underwent
surgery to fuse two vertebrae and to remove a disk; his return also
is indefinite.
</P>
<P>
   Johnston might not have been on that plane had he not had
trouble with his work visa last season, which kept him from
returning to the United States from Australia. He eventually worked
out the problem and returned to the North American rodeo circuit
last July.
</P>
<P>
   He was trying to compete in as many rodeos as possible to
accumulate enough money to qualify for the National Finals Rodeo in
December. Cowboys sometimes travel by small plane if they are
competing in more than one rodeo in a week.
</P>
<P>
   When the plane crashed, Johnston was en route to the Grand
National Rodeo, the Professional Rodeo Cowboys Association's last
major regular-season show, and was in striking distance of making
the National Finals.
</P>
<P>
   Three months later, Johnston, a former National Finals Rodeo
average winner, has turned in attention-grabbing scores of 78 and
75 and has qualified for a semifinal round, which is scheduled
during performances this afternoon through Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   If Johnston continues his pace, he will advance to Sunday
night's final. For Johnston, who now is ranked second overall with
a combined score of 153 on two rides, the Stock Show Rodeo was his
first outing since the crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first ride was a little awkward because I had to get new
equipment after the crash,'' Johnston said. ``All of my equipment
was burned in the plane crash.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnston began competing again Jan. 24 at the Stock Show Rodeo
and aggressively spurred his saddle bronc to pick up extra points.
His score of 78 finished third in the first round and he earned
$1,611.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a little pain during my first ride,'' Johnston said.
``But several days later, I got on another horse in Rapid City,
S.D., and I didn't have any problems at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnston's wife, Jane, said she feels confident that her husband
has not returned too soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was God that got him out of that plane and it was God that
is still watching over him,'' she said. ``We've prayed after the
accident and have relied on God to heal him. I believe that he has
the ability to win and he will be OK.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mark Garrett said he is concerned about Johnston's rapid
return.
</P>
<P>
   ``I dang sure don't like it,'' Garrett said. ``If it was me, I'd
wait until I get 100 percent. But I hope that it works well for
him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
