<SLUG> BC-WRITERS-DEAL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WRITERS CUT DEAL FOR SLICE OF SONY MOVIE PROFITS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE MCNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Nearly three dozen of Hollywood's top
screenwriters reached an unprecedented deal Thursday with Sony
Corp. that will pay them a significant cut of profits if their
films are hits.
</P>
<P>
   The deal was instigated by 34 writers who have won or been
nominated for 21 Academy Awards. Each will now deliver at least one
script to Sony over the next four years at the fee from their last
film, but can earn much more if their movies turn into box office
hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sony grasped the concept that writers, just like stars and
directors, should be earning more on successful films,'' said Ron
Bass, whose credits include ``My Best Friend's Wedding.'' ``The
studio really looked at it from the point of fairness. We're
grateful to them for finally putting their money where their mouth
is instead of just offering lip service about partnerships with
writers.''
</P>
<P>
   The basic agreement gives writers 2 percent of Sony's gross
receipts from a movie -- the company's 50 percent cut of box office
and ancillary sources like home video -- after the studio has
recouped production, distribution and marketing costs but before
distribution fees and profit participations to stars and directors.
</P>
<P>
   What's distinctive about the agreement is Sony's willingness to
allocate profits to writers before figuring its net, or overall
profits, something done currently for only a few powerful players
like ``Titanic'' director-writer James Cameron. Most current deals
call for top writers to receive ``net'' points from studios, but
studios have been criticized for decades for turning a profitable
movie into a ``net'' loser by adding ancillary costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It galls us that we can write a very successful script and see
the net points become worthless,'' said Nicholas Kazan, whose
credits include ``Reversal of Fortune.''
</P>
<P>
   Sony's formula will pay off only on successful films. For
example, if a movie costs $60 million to produce and $30 million to
distribute and market, then takes in $240 million in worldwide box
office, Sony's cut would be about $120 million and its gross profit
would be a fairly impressive $30 million. Under that example, a
writer with sole credit would be paid an additional $600,000, or 2
percent of Sony's gross profit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did not come in with a proposal that would significantly
alter the economics of the business,'' Bass said.
</P>
<P>
   Industry executives say the pact will give Sony an edge over
rivals in attracting strong screenplays without exposing the studio
to huge additional payouts. Daniel Petrie Jr., executive director
of the Writers Guild of America West, predicts the deal could
encourage the other major studios to improve their deals for
writers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would bet the other studios will realize that the top
writers are going to want to work at Sony,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sony also has agreed to offer the same profit-participation
arrangement for the next seven years to any writer who either: gets
nominated for an Academy Award or Writers Guild Award; gets paid at
least $750,000 for work on one screenplay; or receives payment of
$1 million for a spec script.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is that it's a good deal for us,'' said Amy Pascal,
president of Sony's Columbia Pictures. ``We will have a better
selection of scripts from some of the best writers in the
business.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea of approaching a studio grew out of informal Thursday
night get-togethers that started in June among Kazan, Bass, Frank
Pierson (``Dog Day Afternoon''), Phil Alden Robinson (``Field of
Dreams'') and Tom Schulman (``Dead Poets Society''). Robert Towne,
acknowledged as one of Hollywood's best script doctors, played a
crucial role in suggesting a partnership with studios and
preliminary talks began several months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Towne also said at one of those meetings, Get gross points and
respect will follow,'' Kazan said.
</P>
<P>
   Petrie said being frozen out of gross points has been a longtime
source of frustration for writers. ``There are lots of reasons but
part of it is that the writing deal is so early in the process that
you're often not even sure if it's going to lead to a movie,'' he
added. ``This agreement certainly levels the playing field.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal is also distinctive in several other ways, including
the number of writers involved, the willingness of Sony and the
writers to go public about the pact and the lack of advance leaks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears that screenwriters can keep a secret,'' Kazan said.
``It really has been the town's best-kept secret,'' Pascal agreed.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
