A2566 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-SKETCH-NYT &LR;      02-04 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-SKETCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARATHONER-LAWMAKERS NOW SPRINT FOR THE FINISH LINE 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ ``It mystifies me,'' said former Sen. Bob Dole,
sympathizing with old Republican colleagues enmeshed in President
Clinton's impeachment trial. ``Clinton created the problem, and we
got the blame.''
</P>
<P>
   His brief comment, outside a legislative hearing well removed
from the trial, had the ring of political epitaph as the Senate
court clearly pressed Thursday toward having the arduous proceeding
run just one more week and not a hear-ye or a motion longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``You should at least let us have Monica Lewinsky here live,''
one House prosecutor pleaded before the court. But the senators sat
silent in their seats, preparing a firm bipartisan rebuff _ a
cross-aisle shudder of sorts _ at the very invitation that they
personally eye ``the demeanor, the temperament, the spontaneity''
of the former White House intern with whom the president
misbehaved.
</P>
<P>
   The 70-to-30 vote barring live testimony from Ms. Lewinsky in
the Senate chamber closely paralleled the public's polled attitudes
against any fresh spectacle. With the vote, there was a sense in
the Capitol of the court's inevitably rounding into the homestretch
of a yearlong national steeplechase, of members' finally securing
the chamber against the tabloidization of Senate dignity.
</P>
<P>
   Out in the corridors, the chief prosecutor, Rep. Henry J. Hyde,
was sounding increasingly weary as he coined a new word _
``backlashy'' _ that echoed Dole's frustration at how the public
seems to be blaming the Republican Party more than the misbehaving
president for the continuing impeachment ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   With Clinton's acquittal widely expected, the House prosecutors
were nevertheless showing considerable fight to the finish. They
enlisted the Senate's Republican majority to rebuff the Clinton
defense team's motion for advance notice of which videotaped
excerpts from witness depositions the prosecutors will present in
Saturday's court session.
</P>
<P>
   Approval of the motion would have allowed the White House to
better prepare for the video ``duel of snippets'' that the
president's lawyers predict.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is none of your damn business,'' said one prosecutor,
Rep. James E. Rogan of California, happily crediting a California
jurist for his riposte as Republicans beamed and laughed. As he won
the point, the proceeding was suddenly interrupted by a man in the
public gallery who stood and angrily bellowed, ``God Almighty, take
the vote and get it over with!''
</P>
<P>
   Neatly dressed and trimly bearded, the intruder departed with a
smile of satisfaction, hustled out in the clutch of security guards
even as Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist gaveled for his
banishment. The shouted plea from above seemed unnecessary, as the
majority leader, Sen. Trent Lott, emphasized throughout the day
that the proceeding was now firmly positioned for no more surprises
and a finish by Friday of next week, as planned.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe even a day sooner, the Senate leader suddenly began
suggesting, sounding like a sea captain holding out the promise of
an extra grog ration to a crew grown weary of the bounding main of
impeachment. Lott seemed unflappable as he handled a few unexpected
objections and explained the most significant of Thursday's votes:
the one allowing video excerpts from the depositions of three
witnesses, among them Ms. Lewinsky. In the long year of scandal
investigation, this will be the first time she is seen testifying.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it will make their case more understandable,'' Lott,
speaking after the session, said of the prosecutors' plans for
Lewinsky excerpts. Then he paused and added with a bright-eyed
smile, ``And, frankly, more interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   Tune in, one of the prosecutors advised, although this latest
benchmark in the sex-and-mendacity story will begin sometime after
10 a.m. on a Saturday, not exactly prime time for a nation measured
as increasingly fed up with the subject.
</P>
<P>
   A tinge of approaching deliverance was in the Capitol air as the
Senate majority readied the votes that would finally dash the hopes
of their House colleagues for some larger and longer trial of the
president. The opening prayer was that the senators henceforth be
gifted with the ``wise and listening heart'' of Solomon.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Conrad Burns, R-Mont., seemed off on an understandably
wistful tangent when he voted with the Democrats for a short-cut
move to the trial's climactic stage: final arguments and then
balloting on the articles of impeachment. He instantly realized his
error, corrected his vote to a booming ``no'' and added a double
thumbs-down for good measure as the idea failed.
</P>
<P>
   Burns drew laughs and backslaps from colleagues at the
felicitous urge to finish. Just one more week, the court seemed to
exult after a month in mute passivity. The day's disputes by the
trial attorneys sounded more than familiar and had a lulling
quality, even when they touched upon sex.
</P>
<P>
   When Gregory B. Craig, special White House counsel, asked how
America could ever protect its children from embarrassing details
that might surface in those dueling snippets on Saturday, two of
Rehnquist's four young grandchildren could be seen snoozing
unscandalized in the gallery. Earlier, all four watched, proudly
smiling in fascination, as their grandfather arrived in his
gold-striped robe, gaveled the place quiet and once more intoned,
``The Senate will convene as a court of impeachment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
