<HEADER>
A2640 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-IMPEACH-HNS &LR;      02-04 1339
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-IMPEACH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE REJECTS LIVE TESTIMONY FROM LEWINSKY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate turned down a request Thursday by House
prosecutors to allow live testimony from Monica Lewinsky in the
impeachment trial of President Clinton, but did agree to hear
videotaped excerpts from her latest deposition.
</P>
<P>
   By a vote of 70-30, with 25 Republicans joining with all 45
Democrats, the senators rejected the motion to allow Lewinsky's
appearance in the Senate chamber, which many GOP lawmakers had
feared would turn the Senate trial into a spectacle.
</P>
<P>
   But moments later the lawmakers approved a motion by a vote of
65-35 _ with 10 Democrats voting for it and two Republicans against
_ that would give the public its first glimpse of the young woman
testifying. The videotaped excerpts of her most recent deposition
will be played by prosecutors in their closing arguments Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate also agreed that the 13-member Republican prosecution
team can present videotaped excerpts from depositions taken earlier
this week from Clinton friend Vernon Jordan and White House aide
Sidney Blumenthal. However, they rejected an appeal by the White
House to be given advance notice of what portions of the videotapes
the prosecution plans to use in their final arguments.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to deny Lewinsky's live appearance set the stage
for a final vote next week on whether to convict or acquit Clinton
of the charges of perjury and obstruction of justice outlined in
the two articles of impeachment against him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was a critical day and guarantees now that we're
moving to the final phase of the impeachment trial,'' Senate
Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., told reporters after the
votes. ``Barring some dramatic interruption, we will be through
(next) Thursday or not later than Friday.''
</P>
<P>
   The vote against Lewinsky's live testimony disappointed House
prosecutors. But they were elated with the opportunity to air parts
of her videotaped deposition, saying that it would give not only
the lawmakers but the public a chance to ``judge for themselves''
the young woman's credibility.
</P>
<P>
   The vote to allow the videotapes in the Senate chamber marked a
significant moment in the yearlong sex scandal that led to the
first impeachment trial of a president in 131 years. Until now, the
public has only read and heard audio tapes of Lewinsky's personal
accounts of her relationship with the president and her view of
whether he asked her to lie about it and tried to cover it up by
influencing the testimony of potential witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Although the taped depositions are expected to provide little if
anything in the way of new evidence, prosecutors are convinced that
if senators and the public can only watch Lewinsky reaffirm and
expand on testimony she had already given 23 times, they will be
stunned by what one lawmaker called ``her youth and
vulnerability.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. James Rogan, R-Calif., a member of the House prosecution
team, said her deposition would provide ``the full flavor'' of how
the president ``took advantage of this young woman'' and tried to
enlist her help in covering up their relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would just invite everyone to stay tuned on Saturday,'' said
Rep. James Sensenbrenner, R-Wis., another House prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, some Republicans who have suggested that prosecutors
have yet to build a credible case that Clinton intentionally
committed perjury and obstructed justice, say the Lewinsky
videotape could change some minds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone will see their daughter or see their sister when they
look at that videotape,'' said Sen. Gordon Smith, R-Ore.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's defenders, however, said the videotape shows only ``a
mature and articulate young woman'' who set out to seduce the
president of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's absolutely nothing new there. We've read it all
before, we've heard it all before,'' said Sen. Tom Harkin, D-Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   In arguing against live witness testimony and the public release
of videotapes, White House special counsel Greg Craig warned the
Senate that the public could react angrily just as it did when the
House released independent counsel Kenneth Starr's detailed and
sordid report on the Clinton-Lewinsky relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should learn a lesson from America's experience with what
happened in the House,'' Craig said. ``More is not always better.''
</P>
<P>
   Craig told the senators that nothing was to be gained by having
Lewinsky testify in person or allowing prosecutors to present
``snippets'' from her deposition. He said, however, that the White
House would not object to allowing the use of deposition
transcripts in closing arguments.
</P>
<P>
   ``You already know the facts. You have already read what they
have had to say on many different occasions. And you have already
seen and read their most recent testimony under oath,'' Craig told
the senators. ``It simply can no longer be credibly argued that you
need testimony from these witnesses to flesh out the factual record
or to resolve conflicts or to fill in the evidentiary gaps, or to
look the witnesses in the eyes and assess their credibility.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In our view ... the Senate has leaned over backwards to
accommodate the managers. We believe it is time for the Senate to
say it's time to vote (on whether to convict Clinton and remove him
from office),'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Most senators appeared to agree Thursday that despite their best
efforts, House prosecutors will not get the 67 votes they need to
convict Clinton and remove him from office. They also seemed to
agree that there is not enough support from senators on either side
of the aisle for a ``finding of fact'' motion that would allow them
to essentially declare Clinton guilty of wrongdoing but not kick
him out of the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the finding of facts issue is probably dead,'' said
Sen. Chuck Hagel, R-Neb. He said he and a number of other
Republicans opposed it because they felt it would be
unconstitutional under the rules governing impeachment proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Lott also suggested that he was no longer willing to delay the
end of the trial just so Republicans could keep Clinton from
``gloating,'' as one GOP senator put it, over having been acquitted
of the impeachment charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that any president that has been impeached and
tried by the Senate, even though he may not be removed, could feel
like he's gotten off scot-free,'' Lott said. ``I do think it's time
we get to a vote and we move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan being worked out now, the prosecution and defense
will begin closing arguments Saturday and wrap them up on Monday.
After that, senators would begin their deliberations, which could
last up to three days.
</P>
<P>
   One Democratic proposal that's attracting attention from
Republicans would call for the Senate to adjourn the trial for a
brief period following the deliberations to vote on a resolution of
censure against Clinton. Then the trial would resume and the Senate
would hold a final vote on whether to remove Clinton from office.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Democrats and Republicans had hoped to present a more
bipartisan front in the aftermath of the vote along party lines
last week that allowed prosecutors to take new testimony in the
case. The vote against having live witnesses on the floor was
clearly bipartisan.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison of Texas joined 24 of her
Republican colleagues who voted with the Democrats not to allow
Lewinsky to testify in person. Most of those Republicans said they
had learned all they needed from simply watching Lewinsky's
videotaped deposition.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Sen. Phil Gramm of Texas, however, voted in favor of
having Lewinsky appear live, noting that the Senate had never held
an impeachment trial without hearing from witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Both Gramm and Hutchison voted in favor of allowing House
prosecutors to play videotaped excerpts of Lewinsky's deposition.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
