<SLUG> BC-BOEING-LAYOFFS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DETAILS OF BOEING LAYOFFS EMERGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BRUCE RAMSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Offering specifics about total job cuts in Washington
state for the first time Thursday, The Boeing Co. said it expects
to trim 24,000 to 28,000 positions by the end of next year.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing spokesman Peter Conte said the new figure includes 7,500
cuts _ either by layoffs or attrition _ that occurred between
January 1998 and mid-January.
</P>
<P>
   The company had previously said it would lose up to 48,000 jobs
across the United States between June 1998 and December 2000. But
it never said how many it expected to lose here. Conte said
Thursday that between 50 and 60 percent of the total, and probably
closer to 60 percent, would be in this state.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing's employment in Washington had already shrunk from
104,000 last June to 96,500 by Jan. 14. The new forecast pegs the
total at the end of next year at 75,000 to 80,000 _ about what it
was in mid-1996.
</P>
<P>
   Though the forecast job cuts are fewer than some had feared, the
number is more than the state's Office of the Forecast Council had
thought. Their forecast, issued in November, projected losses of
20,700 through the end of next year. Bret Bertolin, senior economic
forecaster, said those numbers would have to be revised.
</P>
<P>
   Also for the first time, Boeing's Conte said that 3,000 to 4,000
of the jobs ultimately lost would be at the Long Beach, Calif.,
division, where the company is phasing out production of the MD-80,
MD-90, MD-11 jet transports. Employment at Wichita, which supplies
parts for assembly lines here, ``will see a decline by at least a
couple thousand,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing's layoff machinery continues to grind, spitting out
60-day warn notices, followed by 14-day notices of impending
layoff.
</P>
<P>
   The company reports no figures of how many of these notices it
has given out, but the two big unions, which together represent
about two-thirds of employees, do report them. The International
Association of Machinists and Aerospace Workers said 720 members
were laid off Jan. 29, and that 1,054 are holding 60-day notices.
The Seattle Professional Engineering Employees Association reported
191 layoffs of SPEEA-represented workers Jan. 29 and that 1,025 are
holding 60-day notices.
</P>
<P>
   The Machinists and SPEEA are both gearing up with programs to
help members retrain and find jobs. SPEEA plans a Job Fair in the
Kingdome March 16-17 with booths from more than 300 companies,
including, they hope, a certain company from France: Airbus
Industrie.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not confirmed,'' said SPEEA contract administrator Rich
Plunkett. ``We're still working on it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
