<SLUG> BC-CAPITAL-HEDGE-FUND-900&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONG-TERM CAPITAL BACKERS EARNS MODEST PROFITS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Conn.)   (af)  
 By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Wall Street firms that rescued the giant hedge fund
Long-Term Capital Management last fall learned at a gathering
Thursday that they had made a modest profit on their investment and
that the hedge fund was not as risky as it once was. But hopes of
getting their money back quickly were dashed, according to
executives close to the unusual gathering.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since late September, when the firms injected
$3.6 billion to save Long-Term Capital from bankruptcy, top
executives from Merrill Lynch, Goldman, Sachs, Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter, Citigroup, Lehman Brothers and other consortium members
discussed the Greenwich, Conn., hedge fund's performance and
debated its future.
</P>
<P>
   People who attended said that all of the consortium members
reaffirmed their commitment to the fund, at least for the immediate
future.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting came amid a swirl of speculation about the stability
of the consortium and talk of a rift between the fund's founding
partners, led by John W. Meriwether, and the leaders of the Wall
Street banks and brokerage firms that now control 90 percent of the
fund's assets.
</P>
<P>
   At least two of the 14 consortium members have let it be known
that they want to cash out their investments in the fund as soon as
possible. But one person close to the discussions said it was
unlikely that any investors would get their money back before next
fall at the earliest.
</P>
<P>
   Meriwether and his colleagues have recently visited
institutional investors around the world to present their view of
why the fund almost collapsed five months ago. The partners have
also explored the possibility of raising new money from wealthy
investors, with an eye to insuring the fund's survival even if some
or all of the Wall Street firms pull out.
</P>
<P>
   Long-Term Capital partners have also voiced suspicions,
including in a Jan. 24 article in The New York Times Magazine, that
some unnamed Wall Street brokerage houses, including at least one
that is part of the rescue consortium, had actively sought to
undercut Long-Term Capital in September by trading against it in
financial markets. Some Wall Street executives said Meriwether's
suggestions had soured the relationship between the fund and its
rescuers.
</P>
<P>
   But people informed about the meeting Thursday at the offices of
Skadden, Arps, Slate, Meagher &AMP; Flom, the law firm that brokered
the deal to save the hedge fund, said no changes in the fund's
ownership were likely in the short term.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's just no one out there with $4 billion who's ready to
jump in,'' one person said. Meriwether did not attend the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The banks and brokerage houses have appointed representatives to
work at Long-Term Capital's offices and oversee its investments.
But the meeting Thursday was described as the first time senior
executives from the bailout firms gathered to get a firsthand
briefing about its performance.
</P>
<P>
   Among the attendees were: Herbert M. Allison Jr., Merrill's
president; Peter F. Karches, Morgan Stanley president, and John A.
Thain, Goldman, Sachs' chief financial officer.
</P>
<P>
   They learned that from the time they had invested in Long-Term
Capital until the end of last year, the value of their investments
rose by 11 percent after subtracting fees and expenses, people
close to the fund said. The portfolio continued to post small gains
in January.
</P>
<P>
   The executives were also told that the risk profile of the
portfolio had been ``substantially'' reduced. That means both that
the stock and bond market investments the fund has are safer than
before, and that the amount of money it borrows to purchase
securities has been reduced. But one person close to the discussion
said that risk reduction ``still has further to go'' before people
are satisfied.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The meeting came as Long-Term Capital's partners, led by
Meriwether, have begun a campaign to rehabilitate the fund's
battered reputation. Partners have visited existing investors in
Europe, the Americas and Asia.
</P>
<P>
   People involved with the fund said the partners had made about
20 separate presentations that lifted the veil of secrecy that has
long shielded the fund's basic trading strategies even from its own
investors.
</P>
<P>
   During that road show, the partners explained in detail the
reasons for its near collapse last fall. They also sought to
demonstrate that in better times the amount of borrowed money the
fund used was not unusual by the standards of big banks or
brokerage houses, though they acknowledged that leverage ballooned
to enormous levels _ as much as $100 in borrowed money to $1 in
equity _ as the fund's capital was depleted in the summer and fall.
</P>
<P>
   The partners have also tried to raise new money. They are
worried about the fund's long-term survival, especially amid
rumblings that some members of the consortium are pondering how to
extract their investment, people close to the fund said.
</P>
<P>
   But there's no indication that the fund is close to raising new
money or finding a billionaire backer who could purchase the stakes
held by some or all of the Wall Street firms. A spokesman for the
fund declined to comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
