<HEADLINE>
3 OF THE 4 OFFICERS WERE ALSO INVOLVED IN OTHER SHOOTINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (With NY-SUSPECT-SHOT; also see NY-SUSPECT-PROFILE) 
 (bl) 
 By KIT R. ROANE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Three of the four plainclothes officers who shot a
Bronx man to death early Thursday had been involved in other
shootings, one of which is still under investigation, police said.
</P>
<P>
   All four officers _ Edward McMellon, 26, Sean Carroll, 35,
Kenneth Boss, 27, and Richard Murphy, 26 _ have been placed on
administrative duty, a standard department procedure, while the
department investigates the shooting of Amadou Diallo, 22, in the
vestibule of his Soundview apartment building.
</P>
<P>
   The officers, all assigned to the Bronx Street Crimes Unit, an
elite and often dangerous assignment, had been looking for a
suspect in a series of rapes, police said. It remained unclear
Thursday night why the officers shot at Diallo, who died in a
fusillade of 41 bullets.
</P>
<P>
   Boss, who has been on the police force for seven years, is under
investigation in the October 1997 fatal shooting of a man who
police said was menacing people with a shotgun in front of an
apartment building on Sheffield Avenue in East New York, Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   According to police, Boss shot the man, Pat Baily, after Baily
fled into a nearby apartment building. Although it remains unclear
whether Baily was holding a weapon when he was shot, a shotgun was
found next to his body, police said. Baily died of his injuries at
Brookdale Hospital Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   The shooting is under investigation by the Brooklyn district
attorney's office, which is trying to ``determine whether there are
issues that need to be resolved by a grand jury,'' said Patrick
Clark, the spokesman for the office.
</P>
<P>
   McMellon, a five-year police veteran, was cleared after shooting
and wounding a man in East New York, Brooklyn, last June. Police
said the man had a loaded 9-millimeter handgun.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll, who has also been on the force for five years, was
found to have been justified in firing his gun last August on
Wilson Avenue in the Bronx. He said he had fired at a suspect after
hearing a bullet pass over his head. Neither a suspect nor any
weapons were ever recovered.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy, who has been on the force for four years, has not been
involved in any previous shootings and has never had a complaint
against him lodged with the Civilian Complaint Review Board.
</P>
<P>
   McMellon has received five complaints, while Boss and Carroll
each have received three, said a law enforcement official who spoke
on the condition of anonymity. The official said that none of the
complaints, which ranged from accusations of excessive force to
abuse of authority and racial insensitivity, had been
substantiated.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll was the only one of the group to have two years'
experience in the Street Crimes unit, whose members are often asked
to search out crimes in progress and to get guns off the street.
</P>
<P>
   Since they joined the unit in October, Murphy has made eight
felony arrests, seven of them for gun possession, and Boss has made
five gun-possession arrests, one for auto theft and one for
narcotics possession.
</P>
</TEXT>
