</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MENCHU-CRITICS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MENCHU SAYS CRITICS HARBOR POLITICAL AIMS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DEBORAH TEDFORD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GEORGETOWN, Texas _ Nobel laureate Rigoberta Menchu said
Thursday that a New York Times story and an anthropologist's book
that report inaccuracies in her autobiography had political
overtones that undermine the human rights movement in Central
America.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe this comes from a political purpose,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Menchu, 50, said the Guatemalan military cooperated with the
Times on a Dec. 15 story that sought to discredit her account of
atrocities in Guatemala.
</P>
<P>
   That story outlined the results of a 10-year study by U.S.
anthropologist David Stoll that found key elements of Menchu's book
were untrue. It also said interviews conducted by Times reporters
corroborated Stoll's findings.
</P>
<P>
   Menchu said the Times used files from Guatemala's Association of
Retired Military Personnel to discredit her. Those files were
withheld from a special United Nations commission investigating the
oppression of indigenous people, but are the focal point of a
soon-to-be-released report denying accounts of the atrocities of
Guatemala's bloody civil war, she said.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the Times did not return a call seeking
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Menchu became a spokeswoman for the indigenous people of Central
America and an internationally known human rights activist
following publication of ``I, Rigoberta Menchu.'' Largely because
of the book, which tells of her life as an uneducated and oppressed
Maya, she was awarded the 1992 Nobel Peace Prize.
</P>
<P>
   But the Times interviews and Stoll's book found that key
portions of the book were not true. Among their findings:
</P>
<P>
   _ A land dispute central to the book was not a fight between her
father and rich landowners of European descent, but a family
dispute.
</P>
<P>
   _ Menchu was not an uneducated peasant, but actually received a
quality education in a private school.
</P>
<P>
   _ The brother Menchu claimed she saw burned alive by government
troops actually died under far different circumstances unseen by
any family member.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to reporters after a speech before a crowd of about
1,200 at Southwestern University, Menchu would not address the
truth or falsity of specific findings. Instead, she talked of using
``collective memory'' to chronicle historical events and depicted
herself as an actor in the history of the Maya people.
</P>
<P>
   She did, however, criticize the Times story as an attempt to
diminish the problems of the Maya, such as the inability of an
individual to gain clear title to a plot of land, a significant
problem the government should be able to resolve.
</P>
<P>
   She also chastised Stoll and the Times for taking her to task
over her account of her brother's fiery death by saying it is
offensive to suggest that a person should witness the burning death
of a family member.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the finding that she had received a private
education, Menchu replied that she had worked as a servant at the
Belgian-Guatemalan Institute in Guatemala City, but was taught to
read Spanish by the nuns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was 16 and a servant. No educational institute gives someone
who cleans the floors a degree, but the nuns did teach me to read
Spanish,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Menchu questioned the timing of the Times article and Stoll's
book, saying they undermined two important reports that will be
released later this month _ by the United Nations and by the
Catholic Church _ cataloging human rights violations in Central
America.
</P>
<P>
   Menchu asserted that the story and the book not only offended
her, but all the indigenous people of Guatemala and Central
America.
</P>
<P>
   Menchu is in Texas for a two-day symposium examining Spain's
cultural legacy in the Americas. University spokesman Eric Van
Danen said it is the Nobel laureate's first public appearance in
the United States since the controversy erupted over her book.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
