<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-ANALYSIS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLIPPERS STRONG IN FRONTCOURT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In the bygone daze of Bill Fitch, what a Los
Angeles Clippers player didn't know could hurt his feelings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't that easy communicating with coach Fitch,'' said
center/forward Lorenzen Wright. ``Sometimes, if guys didn't know
something and it meant asking him, they'd decide they'd rather not
know the answer.''
</P>
<P>
   How much difference can a year and new coach Chris Ford make?
Part of the answer will be revealed tonight at the Sports Arena,
where Ford and the Clippers open their 50-game season against the
Phoenix Suns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have a real gauge,'' said Ford, who has 10 players
returning from last year's team that finished 17-65. ``They've been
great at accepting what we've been teaching. But they have to stay
on this page. If they stay on this page and do the things we've
been working on, our chances of winning will certainly be better.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford, who played for Fitch in Boston, has taken a page from his
predecessor's manual on relating to young players, ripped it from
the text and started over.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's made a big difference in generating the enthusiasm we
have,'' said point guard Darrick Martin. ``He's much better at
communicating with the players. He'll tell you exactly what he
expects from you.''
</P>
<P>
   Communicating is one thing, talent to make the playoffs is
another.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, they exhibited enough requisite pluck and long-term wisdom
to draft 7-foot rookie Michael Olowokandi. Small forward Lamond
Murray appears primed for big numbers in the last season on his
contract. Second-year forward Maurice Taylor is a powerhouse with
star and highlight-reel potential. Another robust forward, Rodney
Rogers, arrived for training camp with offensive-line potential but
continues to drop surplus weight and should be productive.
</P>
<P>
   The aforementioned Wright provides considerable bang for the
buck at both low-post positions, rookie Brian Skinner could be
Charles Oakley on training wheels and undrafted rookie Tyrone Nesby
has a knack for the spectacular.
</P>
<P>
   So . . . the frontcourt is worth watching.
</P>
<P>
   But the backcourt could go directly to cable.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the roll call: Martin, Pooh Richardson, Eric Piatkowski,
James ``Hollywood'' Robinson and Charles ``Spider'' Smith. Each is
a legitimate NBA player and quality citizen, but there's not an
all-star threat in the bunch. Martin and shooting guard Piatkowski
are expected to start tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know there's a lot of negative talk about our backcourt,''
Ford said, ``but if they do the things we're trying to do, we'll be
fine.''
</P>
<P>
   What else can the man say?
</P>
<P>
   Well, he can say the arrival of free-agent point guard Sherman
Douglas will, at least, perk up the offense. Douglas, who played
for Ford in Boston and Milwaukee, is a nine-year veteran with
passing and leadership skills. He's not much of a shooter or
defender but was the best playmaker available.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sherman is a very fierce competitor,'' Ford said. ``He knows
how to play the game.''
</P>
<P>
   And Ford knows how to coach. In seven seasons, his teams are
291-283. Last year in Milwaukee, he possessed an extremely talented
starting lineup, but the disparity between it and his bench was too
much to overcome after three starters were injured.
</P>
<P>
   Ford plans to increase the tempo in L.A., because the Clippers
have several fine athletes with comparable skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (players) said they wanted to run,'' Ford said, ``so
here's their chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Murray and Taylor might be the only Clippers who can
create a scoring opportunity after an offensive set is blown up,
Ford might attempt to generate points from his defense. Much of
training camp was spent teaching his new team to bait the
opposition into a gauntlet of traps.
</P>
<P>
   And young legs will help. The abundance of forward talent will
enable Ford to spread precious minutes during the more brutal
stretches of the condensed schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Olowokandi should provide an inside presence and flexibility,
allowing Wright to match up against the ruffian power forwards in
the Western Conference. Murray, the early choice as team MVP, can
swing to shooting guard when Ford feels like using his brawnier
lineup.
</P>
<P>
   With a move to the Staples Center on the horizon, the Clippers
seem to be on a minor roll. Ford, if given time, could produce a
winner. Olowokandi, Taylor, Skinner, Wright and Murray represent
solid choices on draft day. The next order of business is patience.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team still has to find its identity,'' Ford said.
</P>
<P>
   Good idea. The old ID rarely has taken the Clippers past the
NBA's playoff bouncers. &UR; !dlim!!end! &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
