<HEADER>
A2723 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOUISIANA-PACT-NYT &LR;      02-04 1137
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOUISIANA-PACT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOUISIANA POLITICIANS SIGN NONAGGRESSION PACT 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By KEVIN SACK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BATON ROUGE, La. _ Even by the unconventional standards of
Louisiana politics, what happened at the Governor's Mansion here
last Thursday afternoon was more than a bit odd. All eight of the
Louisiana government's statewide elected officers, six Democrats
and two Republicans, sat down together and signed a nonaggression
pact in which they effectively agreed not to campaign against one
another in this year's elections.
</P>
<P>
   They presented the agreement as a high-minded effort to avoid
the bitter partisanship that the public finds so distasteful in
Washington these days. But critics saw it as a me-first exercise in
incumbent protection that undermines both political parties.
</P>
<P>
   While the pact among the signatories is not the same as their
endorsing one another, it has been interpreted that way by many
party loyalists, and the reaction from Republican and Democratic
leaders has ranged from puzzlement to outrage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not pleased at all,'' said Ben Jeffers, the Democratic
state chairman. ``We've been working hard to convince our officials
that it's a bad idea.'' Jeffers said the pact would hurt
fund-raising and grass-roots organizing, in part by sending a
``signal to the electorate that parties don't matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike G. Francis, the Republican state chairman, said he had
``mixed feelings'' about the agreement. He said it might help the
party achieve its primary goal: re-electing the state's immensely
popular Republican governor, Mike Foster. But Francis acknowledged
that Foster's pledge to stay on the sidelines might make it more
difficult for the party to recruit candidates for other statewide
offices. ``That's the question,'' Francis said, ``and I can't
answer that question right now.''
</P>
<P>
   To some extent, partisanship has always meant less in politics
here than in other states. Candidates from both parties run against
one another in open primaries, and leadership positions in the
Legislature are determined more by political philosophy than by
party affiliation.
</P>
<P>
   The pact became particularly nettlesome for the Democrats when,
on the day after it had been signed, Rep. William J. Jefferson, a
Democrat from New Orleans, announced that he planned to run for
governor against Foster. No other Democrats had declared for the
race, and the Democratic officials who were parties to the
agreement said Jefferson's announcement had caught them by
surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Some now worry that the pact may generate a racial backlash.
Jefferson is black, and Democratic leaders are concerned that black
party loyalists will be deeply offended if six white Democratic
leaders stay out of a race that pits a black Democrat against a
white Republican.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's a lot to think about along those lines,''
Jefferson said in an interview Thursday, reaffirming plans to run.
``I know in the heat of a race things get very emotional. And there
are Democrats who want to see our party remain strong and
competitive, and they'll be deeply concerned that the person
carrying the party banner at the moment was abandoned by the
Democratic leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Jefferson and Jeffers, the Democratic chairman, said they
believed that some of the signers might withdraw from the pact now
that Jefferson had announced his candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   Although none of the signers are considered particularly
vulnerable this year, the pact seems to have been driven largely by
their instinct for incumbency protection. It will allow the
68-year-old Foster, a onetime Democrat who has never demonstrated
great partisan loyalty, to concentrate on his own race without
being drawn into down-the-ballot sideshows. And for the six
Democrats, it may provide some protection against any threat posed
by Foster's coattails.
</P>
<P>
   But some of the signers said the significant factors were that
they all worked well together and the public had grown disgusted
with the partisan strife surrounding the impeachment and trial of
President Clinton. All of those interviewed said that Louisiana's
elected officials got along swimmingly these days despite partisan
differences and the congeniality in the Capitol had helped the
state thrive.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are fed up about Washington, and it seemed like an
important statement for us to say, `You know, you can work
together,''' said Lt. Gov. Kathleen Babineaux Blanco, a Democrat.
``It doesn't have to be a war zone.''
</P>
<P>
   Foster, a wealthy businessman who is only the second Republican
to be elected governor here this century, agreed. ``The Republicans
have waited a long time for a Republican governor, and they want
him to be successful,'' he said. ``And you can't be successful if
you're always having partisan fights, a la D.C.''
</P>
<P>
   The agreement says: ``We as a group believe that we should put
the business of Louisiana's citizens ahead of partisan politics. In
this spirit, we would not want partisan political infighting to
stand in the way of Louisiana continuing to move forward.''
</P>
<P>
   The officials agree to offer ``mutual help and support so that
we can continue to work as a team during the coming four years,
with the goal of continued prosperity.''
</P>
<P>
   The signers, in addition to Foster and Blanco, are Secretary of
State W. Fox McKeithen, a Republican, and Attorney General Richard
P. Ieyoub, State Treasurer Ken Duncan, Commissioner of Insurance
James H. Brown, Commissioner of Agriculture Robert F. Odom and
Commissioner of Elections Jerry M. Fowler, all Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the officials declined to say whether they personally
wanted their counterparts re-elected. ``My personal feelings and my
public posture are two different things,'' McKeithen said. ``I
don't think it's relevant to this agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   It is only recently that Republicans have gained ground here.
Although 62 percent of the state's voters are registered as
Democrats, the Republicans hold five of seven seats in the U. S.
House in addition to the governorship.
</P>
<P>
   Foster, a bull-necked businessman who is known for his straight
talk, his folksy style and his love of duck hunting, has impressed
many Louisianians by improving the state's fiscal condition while
also finding money to raise teacher salaries and pave highways. In
a poll conducted late last month by Southern Media and Opinion
Research, 78 percent of those questioned, including 76 percent of
Democrats, approved of his job performance. Half of those surveyed
said they planned to vote for him regardless of his opposition.
</P>
<P>
   The governor maintains that he owes some of his success to his
avoidance of partisan feuds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm never going to turn down anybody who wants to be
supportive,'' he said. ``I think you can have as many enemies as
you go looking for.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
