<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUNS-CASSTEVENS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEAK SEASON FOR SUNS HEAD TRAINER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The NBA season is so close at hand you can reach out
and touch it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ouch''.
</P>
<P>
   Squeeze it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Owwwwww''.``''
</P>
<P>
   Smell it. The unmistakable scent of liniment is in the air.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, belatedly, ready or not, the Phoenix Suns and 28 other
teams begin a new season, and while no one knows how many games
will sell out, it's expected that training rooms around the league
will be standing room only.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Proski already is a busy man.
</P>
<P>
   Right, Joe?
</P>
<P>
   The Suns' trainer glanced out the window of his small office
that adjoins the training room. ``Excuse me a minute,'' Proski
said, putting the conversation on hold.
</P>
<P>
   Another patient had walked in. Luc Longley's back is bothering
him. The Suns' 7-foot-2 center blames the muscle stiffness on the
drive he recently made from Chicago to Phoenix, his new NBA home.
</P>
<P>
   Injuries are a part of NBA life. They could become a ``way'' of
life during this abbreviated season, especially the first few
weeks, when players play themselves back into shape.
</P>
<P>
   Rex Chapman will miss tonight's opener against the Los Angeles
Clippers. He is nursing a sore hamstring muscle. Tom Gugliotta's
shoulder hurts.
</P>
<P>
   Check around the league. Charlotte has lost Anthony Mason for
the year. Teammate Glen Rice had elbow surgery and may miss half
the season. The New York Nets will start without Rony Seikaly and
Kerry Kittles. Boston's Ron Mercer is nursing a sore knee.
</P>
<P>
   With NBA teams limited to two exhibition games, how many more
sprains and aches and pains can we expect? Fifty games in 90 days.
How well will older players hold up? Danny Manning is the first NBA
player to come back from three reconstructive knee surgeries. How
much should he play? Three nights in a row?
</P>
<P>
   Danny Ainge wonders. He worries like every other coach. He calls
the increased risk of injuries ``scary.''
</P>
<P>
   During Thursday's spirited workout, Chapman hustled across the
court. Planting himself in front of rookie guard Toby Bailey, Rex
took a hard charge.
</P>
<P>
   Chapman wasn't hurt, but he could have been. As Ainge relived
the incident, he smiled and shook his head and covered his eyes
with a hand. ``Oh, man. . .''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be interesting,'' Proski said, between massages
and ice packs. ``We've already had a lot of twinges and strains.
When you play three games in three nights, or five games in seven,
it's going to take a toll on veteran players.''
</P>
<P>
   Proski knows about the cumulative effect of life in the NBA. The
Suns' one and only head trainer would have been on the injured
himself had this season not been delayed by a labor fight.
</P>
<P>
   In May Proski underwent 12 { hours of surgery. Doctors opened
him up, front and back. Asked what they did, the trainer picked up
a clear plastic bag from his office desk. The sampling of metal
bolts, screws and plates looked like an assembly kit that comes
with a book case or a desk.
</P>
<P>
   Surgeons used the hardware to repair Proski's spine. He spent 10
days in the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   For 32 years Proski has used his healing hands to help injured
athletes overcome a Heinz variety of ailments. In recent months he
traveled the long steep road of recovery himself.
</P>
<P>
   Proski was placed in a body cast. Getting out of bed was an
accomplishment; taking his first step a triumph.
</P>
<P>
   The trainer smiles at the memory of the day his family went to
Wisconsin and left him at home alone. Unable to bend over, Joe
waited three hours before a friend came by and slipped on his socks
and tied his shoes.
</P>
<P>
   During his convalescence, Proski inched his way from his house
to the front gate, using a walker. While players and owners argued
for months over how to divide $2 billion in revenue, he graduated
to a cane.
</P>
<P>
   Proski is still moving a little slowly. But the man who could
become the team's MVP in this strange fragile year is back at work,
happy to be among his aspirin bottles and elastic bandages and
analgesic balms, consulting with doctors and at the beck and call
of players on the mend. &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at 602-444-8635 or at
david.casstevens(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
