<HEADLINE>
CITY URGED TO REVOKE PERMIT FOR TRUMP TOWER NEAR U.N.
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: A graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By CHARLES V. BAGLI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In what is fast becoming a cause celebre both for
Manhattan community groups and for their wealthy patrons, a group
of East Side residents asked the city on Thursday to revoke Donald
J. Trump's permit to build the tallest residential tower in the
world across the street from the United Nations and to halt
demolition on the site.
</P>
<P>
   The group, the Beekman Hill Association, says the city illegally
granted Trump a permit to build the 861-foot bronze-and-glass
tower. The group contends that the tower is out of scale with the
neighborhood and would soar 300 feet above the United Nations
Secretariat.
</P>
<P>
   The members of the association include the former Citibank
chairman Walter B. Wriston, the former television news anchor
Walter Cronkite, the film director James Ivory and the oil
billionaire David Koch.
</P>
<P>
   The association has raised more than $150,000 and hired
publicists and lawyers for what it believes could be a protracted
court battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel this 90-story building is not only out of character
with the neighborhood but it is also illegal,'' said Seymour Flug,
the former chairman of the Diners Club who is chairman of the
association. ``We're not antidevelopment or anti-Trump. We want to
encourage developers to come in here. All that we ask is that they
build a legal building.''
</P>
<P>
   Workers are now demolishing the 18-story United Engineering
Center, which is on Trump's construction site. Trump and his Korean
partner, the Daewoo Corp., bought the development site on First
Avenue about two years ago for $52 million. They then quietly
bought up the unused development rights from the neighboring
properties on the block for another $30 million.
</P>
<P>
   Flug said the City Buildings Department wrongfully allowed Trump
to transfer development or air rights from other properties on the
block. But even if the transfer was legal, Flug and his lawyers
said the zoning regulations governing the development rights should
have resulted in a shorter, more squat building than the slim tower
that Trump is calling Trump World Tower.
</P>
<P>
   The Buildings Department, which received the association's
request Thursday, declined comment.
</P>
<P>
   With his permits in place and $360 million of financing in hand,
Trump said that he was confident that the project would proceed. He
said he had obtained the permits from the Buildings Department and
the City Planning Department after city officials reviewed these
issues ``ad nauseam.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people are going to lose their views and these are the
people who are fighting the job,'' Trump said. ``Welcome to New
York.''
</P>
<P>
   Executives at the Trump Organization say they already have sold
80 multimillion-dollar apartments in the tower, even though it will
not open for another two years. The building is expected to have
376 apartments.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-04-99 2322EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
