<SLUG> BC-BBC-ASU-FLORIDAST.-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASU PITCHERS WORK MAGIC  
 DESPITE INEXPERIENCE, SQUAD IS UNBEATEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Coach Pat Murphy said ``we're doing it with mirrors,'' he
wasn't kidding.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona State's top six pitchers have 1{ scholarships among
them. It is not exactly a formula for success, but the baseball
team has thrived. The Sun Devils take an 11-0 record into a crucial
three-game series at Florida State that begins today.
</P>
<P>
   With ASU's early schedule a bit on the light side, this will be
the most telling series to date.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really will get a much better sense of where we're at,''
Murphy said. ``Of all the controversy we've faced this season, it
has given us a little instability. But our players have handled
that part very well. They're acting very mature for an
inexperienced ball club.''
</P>
<P>
   That controversy includes adjusting to a new Pac-10 schedule and
playing with wood bats. If any part of the team has set itself
apart during that time, it has been the pitching staff.
</P>
<P>
   The group's ERA is 1.34. The pitchers have struck out 113 and
walked just 18. It's an impressive statistic considering the Sun
Devils lost four of their top five pitchers from last season, are
without two of their top recruits _ Paul French and Ian Perio _
because of elbow injuries, and unexpectedly had three other
recruits sign professional contracts.
</P>
<P>
   ``To think of the way these pitchers are sticking to the plan is
kind of neat,'' Murphy said. ``It says a lot about (new pitching
coach John) Pawlowski and the job he's done with the staff. We
never emphasize one section of the program, but if there's a
surprise, it's the way Pawlowski has rooted himself in such a way
that these guys have taken to his teachings.''
</P>
<P>
   In one way, the use of wood bats, which will continue until the
Pac-10 says otherwise, has helped the staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's allowing them to gain confidence while throwing
strikes,'' Murphy said.
</P>
<P>
   One of those players is Will Waldrip, a transfer from Brigham
Young who attended Flagstaff High School. Two of his three
victories are complete-game shutouts.
</P>
<P>
   Another is Jon Switzer, who will start Sunday. Murphy found the
freshman left-hander in his baseball camp.
</P>
<P>
   Although the offense has produced just one home run, Murphy
believes this team has a lot more power than last year's. Wood bats
are the culprit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd have 25 home runs,'' he said. ``Third baseman Andrew
Beinbrink would have eight to 10.''
</P>
<P>
   The Seminoles (3-0), who are ranked No. 4 by ``Baseball
America,'' have agreed to use wood bats for this series. They
opened the season with a three-game sweep of North
Carolina-Ashville last weekend and finished seventh at the College
World Series last year.
</P>
<P>
   The 12th-ranked Sun Devils would receive an emotional boost by
beating Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a little bit of everything,'' Murphy said. ``We've got
a little speed, a little defense, a little bit of hitting, a little
bit of pitching and a lot of good attitude. I think that's the
key.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
