r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-COYOTES-NOTEBOOK-     02-04 0618
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GENERAL MANAGERS PUT SHOOTOUT TALKS ON HOLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - NHL general managers wrapped up four days of league
meetings Thursday in Palm Springs, Calif., but one of the subjects
up for discussion _ the future of overtime games _ was dropped from
the agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Because 75 to 80 percent of overtime games remain tied after a
five-minute extra period, there has been talk that the league might
consider adopting the shootout policy, which has become so popular
in International Hockey League games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time to see if what we have makes sense,'' NHL
Commissioner
 &UR; Gary Bettman said.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to Thursday's game against the San Jose Sharks, five of
the Coyotes' past eight games had ended in ties. Their 10 ties
overall already are more than the club had in seven of its first 19
NHL seasons and they are well within reach of breaking the
franchise record for most ties in a season _ 15, set in 1991-92.
</P>
<P>
   General Manager  &UR; Bobby Smith, however, isn't in favor of adding
a shootout to decide games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you should play 60 or 65 minutes of hockey and
then have your game decided in a skills competition between two
players,'' he said. ``I don't think a tie is an unacceptable
outcome to a hockey game. It is in a playoff game, but we play
overtime until we settle it.'' &QL; 
Tkachuk sidelined &QL; 
Coyotes captain  &UR; Keith Tkachuk, who recently missed eight games
because of a fractured rib, did not play Thursday because of what
the team described as a lower back strain suffered during Tuesday's
2-2 tie with Calgary.
</P>
<P>
   It's the 13th game Tkachuk has missed this season because of
various injuries but there is a possibility he could be back in the
lineup for Saturday's game against Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise for left wing  &UR; Mike Sullivan, who's missed 11 games
because of a cracked rib, although he's more probable for Monday's
rematch against the Sharks. &QL; 
Traveling circus &QL; 
Thursday's game marked the first of a 10-game, three-week trip for
the visiting San Jose Sharks, who now head to Los Angeles before
returning back to Phoenix on Monday. After that, it's on to
Chicago, St. Louis, Tampa Bay, Miami, Detroit, Buffalo and
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   It's the second-longest trip in NHL history, surpassed only by
the Calgary Flames' 11-game trip in 1988, caused because of the
Winter Olympics that year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know who made our schedule, but obviously, we did
something wrong,'' said recently-retired  &UR; Bernie Nicholls, now an
assistant coach for the Sharks. ``I mean, how many other teams
started in Japan and then get a 10-game trip?''
</P>
<P>
   How does one pack for such a trip?
</P>
<P>
   ``The dress code on this team is not that strict,'' center  &UR; Bob
 &UR; Rouse said. ``I know some guys who can stretch one turtleneck out
for a week.'' &QL; 
Slap shots &QL; 
The Coyotes have signed free-agent defenseman  &UR; Sean McCann of the
IHL Orlando Solar Bears to a one-year deal and assigned him to
Springfield of the American Hockey League. McCann, 27, who is
6-foot, 195 pounds, had four goals and 13 points in 42 games for
Orlando this season. McCann was the Florida Panthers' first overall
choice in the 1994 NHL Supplemental Draft.
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman  &UR; Keith Carney has assumed the role of official
spokesperson for the Thunder on Ice program, which introduces ice
hockey into Arizona's high schools as a club program. During the
second week in April, more than 100 students will participate in
the state's first ever prep club championship. League play is
expected to start in the fall. For information, call (602)
234-6912.
</P>
<P>
   Seven years ago today, Tkachuk signed his first pro contract. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
