<HEADLINE>
HEBERT GETS CONTRACT EXTENSION WITH DUCKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE HUNT  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Mighty Ducks goalie Guy Hebert could have
tested the free-agent market after this season and probably would
have received lucrative contract offers from several National
Hockey League teams.
</P>
<P>
   But Hebert has said repeatedly that he wants to stay in Anaheim.
Thursday he proved it, spurning the chance to become an
unrestricted free agent and signing a three-year contract
extension.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a great honor to have been a part of this
organization for the last six years,'' said Hebert, 32, the first
player the Ducks selected in the 1993 expansion draft. ``Hopefully,
I'll be able to end my career in Anaheim and maybe have a Stanley
Cup to go with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``No question I could have tested the market. But I wanted to
stay in Anaheim. Everything that's transpired will benefit me as a
hockey player. You want to get what you're worth, but you also want
to be happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Ducks president and general manager Pierre Gauthier said it only
took a couple of weeks of negotiating to reach agreement on the
contract terms, which he declined to announce per club policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guy was due to become an unrestricted free agent and we feel
he would have been the best goaltender available,'' Gauthier said.
``We believe it is a great signing for us today.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been a very key player and he's an original Mighty Duck.
To be able to keep him in our organization for the foreseeable
future is a great step for us. We felt it was very important to do
it right away. We didn't want a distraction (during the team's
playoff drive).''
</P>
<P>
   Hebert, who began his career with the St. Louis Blues, is
16-18-7 in in 41 games this season. He has a 2.31 goals-against
average and a career-high five shutouts.
</P>
<P>
   He has a career record of 115-132-33 with a 2.91 career
goals-against average.
</P>
</TEXT>
