<HEADER>
A2735 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REAGAN-LEGACY-LADN     02-04 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REAGAN-LEGACY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAGAN ALUMS FONDLY RECALL ERA AT SIMI VALLEY SUMMIT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY PHIL DAVIS  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SIMI VALLEY, Calif. -- Ronald Reagan was once asked whether it
was true he earned only a C average while at Eureka College in the
1930s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' replied Reagan, then president of the United States.
``Even now I wonder what I might have accomplished if I'd studied
harder.''
</P>
<P>
   The fond anecdote drew laughter and applause Thursday as more
than 300 Reagan administration alumni gathered at the Ronald Reagan
Presidential Library &AMP; Museum to rehash the Reagan era and wish the
ailing former president a happy birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan, who will turn 88 on Saturday, suffers from Alzheimer's
disease and could not attend the conference or his nighttime
birthday gala. But former first lady Nancy Reagan attended, as did
former U.S. Attorney General Edwin Meese, United Nations Ambassador
Jeane Kirkpatrick and conservative pundit William F. Buckley Jr.
</P>
<P>
   The mood of the day was cheerful, but many remembrances seemed
more like a wake for the former president, who was often referred
to in the past tense.
</P>
<P>
   Maureen Reagan said her father's decline has been mercifully
gentle.
</P>
<P>
   ``The disease is horrible, but he's doing well,'' she said. ``He
makes it easy for us. He's very lovable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He would have enjoyed the stories and humor,'' said former
Sen. Nancy Kassebaum Baker. ``It was very much a part of his
governing strength. He could ease tension with a story. People who
disagreed with him would often end up doing what he wanted without
even realizing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Reagan made only a brief appearance at the conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sad to see his wife sitting there hearing all this and
him not being here,'' said Lawrence Goldberg, a San Francisco
resident who worked on both Reagan's and Richard Nixon's
presidential bids.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have great affection for President Reagan,'' he added. ``He
restored confidence and honor to the presidency -- something we are
sorely lacking today. His foreign and economic policies are still
with us to this day. Reagan just had it.''
</P>
<P>
   As historians debated Reagan's historical legacy, former
administration staffers greeted each other with hugs, handshakes
and shared tales of their lives since Reagan left office a decade
ago. They reveled in the powerful legacy of the administration and
the continued national economic prosperity that began with
Reaganomics in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   Ben Jarratt, who served in Reagan's press office for six years,
credits Reagan with inspiring him to open nine Burger King
franchises in Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   ``He set free the American entrepreneurial spirit,'' Jarratt
said.
</P>
<P>
   The gathering brought a touch of Washington to Simi Valley, if
only for a day and a half. During a discussion of Reagan's economic
policies, one woman slipped into the hallway to check on the Senate
impeachment trial of President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh my God!'' she said with a frown. ``Twenty-five Republicans
defected and voted against having Monica Lewinsky as a witness.''
</P>
<P>
   Dinesh D'Souza, author of ``Ronald Reagan: How an Ordinary Man
Became an Extraordinary Leader,'' drew appreciative chuckles when
he compared former President Nixon's long, thoughtful diary entries
to Reagan's brief notes on, for example, his historic first meeting
with Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wrote, `Can't give away the store on SDI!!' That's it,''
D'Souza said. ``Historians were maddened.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ronald Reagan could sit down with you and tell jokes just like
one of the guys,'' said Don Totten, a former Reagan campaign
official from Illinois. ``You were not intimidated by the office
when you sat down with Reagan. You were definitely intimidated when
you sat down with Nixon.''
</P>
<P>
   Those close to Reagan marveled at how his down-home simplicity
belied a much deeper and secret personality that continues to
confound historians.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president's humor was not written for him by staffers. He
had an innate, quick sense of humor,'' said David Swoap, who served
as an official under Reagan in Washington and in his Cabinet when
he was California governor. ``But he also had this incredible
depth. He had the ability to zero in on the heart of a complicated
issue and sum it all up in about three sentences.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He thought seriously about these issues,'' Kirkpatrick said.
``There are a lot of people who didn't think President Reagan
thought seriously; so much the worse for them.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
