<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 23:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2736 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CATSKILLS-REVIVAL-ART     02-04 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CATSKILLS-REVIVAL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTORS STIR HOPE OF CATSKILLS REVIVAL
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By JOSEPH BERGER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A mere two months after the closing of the Concord Resort Hotel
touched off a new wave of obituaries about the Catskills, fire-sale
real estate prices and renewed hopes for casino gambling have
prompted a surge of investment in the old Borscht Belt.
</P>
<P>
   The 1,100-room Concord, built in the late 1930s by a hair-tonic
magnate, was snapped up in mid-January for $10.25 million by an
investment group that plans to spend $40 million to convert it into
a Sheraton franchise and market it to a clientele more diverse than
its traditional base of Jewish vacationers.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Grossinger's, the Catskills' fabled grand dowager
and the career springboard for entertainers like Milton Berle and
Eddie Fisher, was sold at a federal bankruptcy auction in Manhattan
for $6 million to a partnership that includes Louis R. Cappelli,
one of the leading builders in Westchester County, outside New York
City.
</P>
<P>
   Cappelli is a major contributor to Republican politicians, most
prominently Gov. George E. Pataki, who controls the fate of
gambling in the region. Cappelli's lawyer, Joseph S. Rosenthal,
said that the partnership plans to convert Grossinger's into a
``five-star golf resort and spa'' whose success would not be
dependent on gambling but would greatly profit from it.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the region's more upbeat mood stems from the improved
prospects for casino gambling. In December, regional officials of
the U.S. Bureau of Indian Affairs recommended approval of a $500
million casino on land at the Monticello Raceway that would be
given in trust to the St. Regis Mohawk Indians.
</P>
<P>
   Although the plan still awaits the endorsement of the U.S.
Secretary of the Interior and Pataki, this first federal
recommendation has attracted the interest of investors around the
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a great stock that has tremendous value but isn't
selling for a lot of money,'' said Alan Gerry, a cable-television
entrepreneur who owns the muddy farm in Bethel where the 1969
Woodstock concert was held. ``Then one guy recognizes its value and
other people start putting in money. That's what's going to
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   There has been talk of a rebirth before, but those hopes turned
out to be wishful thinking, and the Catskills has more than enough
forlorn main streets and dilapidated bungalows to give the skeptics
reason to gloat.
</P>
<P>
   The most concrete evidence of a revival, the old Stevensville
Resort Hotel, which closed nine years ago and had been destined for
demolition, will reopen in May as the 355-room Swan Lake Golf and
Tennis Resort Hotel. Its lobby has been fitted with crystal
chandeliers, suits of armor and a 12-foot-long jade boat that make
it as opulent as anything Catskills legend ever served up.
</P>
<P>
   It also has a nonkosher Korean and Japanese kitchen intended for
a more diverse clientele.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the land once occupied by the sprawling Laurels
Country Club was bought last month for $1.05 million by developers
who plan to build a Las Vegas-style hotel and entertainment
complex.
</P>
<P>
   In Bethel, Gerry is hoping to turn the old Woodstock site into a
theme park devoted to popular music. Last year the site played host
to a concert that drew 70,000 people over three days. This summer
Gerry is hoping to produce four weekends of music.
</P>
<P>
   Although developers hope that the St. Regis Mohawk casino will
be approved, they insist that their plans are not dependent on
gambling.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it happens, it would be frosting on the cake,'' said James
Hoppensteadt, a former Sheraton executive and now vice president of
Concord Associates, which purchased the Concord in a federal
bankruptcy auction.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the recent spate of deals, Sullivan County, the
heart of the Catskills with 70,000 year-round residents, had been
making itself more alluring, promoting the demolition of moribund
properties and advertising itself as a playground for fly-fishing,
eagle sightings, golf and skiing. Main Street storefronts have been
restored and 15-year tax abatements provided to developers like
those at the Stevensville.
</P>
<P>
   Although it may seem paradoxical, officials in Sullivan County
believe that the new investment in the Catskills is largely due to
the fact that hoteliers finally have stopped waiting for the
gambling miracle that would ride to the rescue.
</P>
<P>
   An important catalyst for the recent flurry of activity is that
prices for rundown hotels have hit rock bottom _ the Concord's
value fell by half in a matter of months _ low enough so that
investors can afford to put up the capital needed for extensive
renovations.
</P>
<P>
   The old Catskills provided a style of vacation that fell out of
favor by the late 1960s. The groups from which guests were
traditionally drawn grew more educated, cosmopolitan and
cholesterol-conscious and more interested in vacations in Tuscany
or the Hamptons. They tired of three banquets a day and found the
hotel tummlers _ frantic round-the-clock jesters whose ranks once
included Danny Kaye and Jerry Lewis _ shopworn and shrill.
</P>
<P>
   But the upstart developers believe the Catskills will have a
fresh appeal to working couples who may find it difficult to
coordinate three-week vacations to Europe and would like shorter
getaways that are only an hour and 45 minutes' drive from
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Said Zev Scharf, a partner in the new ownership of the Laurels,
``Whatever worked against the Catskills before can work for it
now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
