<DOCNO> NYT19990204.0563 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 23:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2738 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     02-04 0929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG FISHER IS OLD RELIABLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ The yellow team was in the huddle and the
20-year-old swingman was reminding his point guard and everybody
else within earshot that he's the go-to guy. It was late in a
recent Lakers scrimmage but not too early to head off trouble at
the pass.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen-year veteran Derek Harper listened to Kobe Bryant go
off, then discreetly pulled Derek Fisher aside, as Gus Williams had
once done with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Listen, Fish,'' the one Derek told the other. ``You've gotta
remember, you're the guy running the show with the game on the
line. You have to be in control of the team, not let the team
control you.''
</P>
<P>
   What Harper didn't have to say is, it's not easy being point
guard to the stars.
</P>
<P>
   People look at you the way Michelle Pfeiffer's male admirers
eyeball David Kelley. You can count on being widely (and warily)
regarded as a lucky so-and-so to be linked with All-Stars Shaquille
O'Neal and Eddie Jones and Bryant and steering an offense that
everybody assumes is running on cruise control, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think I have it easy because of the (caliber of)
players around me,'' Fisher said. ``I know a lot of people think
I'm the weak link in the chain. But in a sense, I'm the link
holding the chain together.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at Shaq, I have to get him touches inside. A guy as
young and talented as Kobe, he's a shooter, he's paid to score; I
have to get him his touches. A guy like Eddie, he's not going to
say much, but I can sense it, I can feel it, I can see it in his
body language that he's frustrated if he's not getting his
touches.''
</P>
<P>
   Fisher frets over his teammates' psyches, he really does. He's
always looking out for them, so it bothers him when they don't look
out for anybody but No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basketball is not fun if everyone's not willing to make the
extra pass, set a screen or play good defense,'' Fisher said. ``The
main thing that will be said this season when everybody starts to
freelance is that there's no leader on this team that can take
control. It'll be the point guard's fault. Or the head coach's.
</P>
<P>
   ``But until we get to the point where everybody's interested in
what WE'RE getting out of this and not what THEY'RE getting out of
it, there's no sense even kidding ourselves into thinking we can be
the best team in basketball. Until then, we'll continue to peak and
then fall off.''
</P>
<P>
   So the Lakers have to realize it's not all about style before
they can become a team of substance. Who better to show them the
way than their most unassuming player?
</P>
<P>
   Fisher, 24, is that and so much more. He's a tireless worker and
an unselfish teammate. He's the rare player who'd rather take a
charge than a shot and he cares more about the bottom line than his
own line in the box score.
</P>
<P>
   He's as dependable as the old family sedan and about as flashy.
Maybe that's why he's so easy to overlook.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher came out of the same draft as Bryant, separated by 11
picks and a world of hype. Bryant was the teen phenom from
Philadelphia; Fisher the obscure player out of Arkansas-Little
Rock.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like, perception-wise, I was starting two feet under
before I even started,'' Fisher said. ``I feel like I'm having to
dig myself out.''
</P>
<P>
   There ought to be more ways to earn notice than to drive the
fanciest car, run with the swankiest crowd, endorse the most
products or put up the best numbers. Yet, despite two solid pro
seasons spent mostly as a backup to Nick Van Exel, Fisher feels
more invisible than ever.
</P>
<P>
   Someday soon somebody's bound to notice that he's the first one
at practice and one of the last to leave. Or that he's the first
one to help a teammate get his shot and the last looking to pad his
own stats. In the meantime, if it's unconditional acceptance Fisher
is after, he probably should go out and get a dog.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes it's frustrating,'' Fisher said. ``I feel the way I
carry myself and what I stand for, I deserve a certain level of
respect. I don't expect to be one of the stars on this team. But
there are some times I wonder if the guys have the same respect for
me as they do Eddie, Kobe and Shaq.''
</P>
<P>
   So what if he's not the product of a big-time college program?
When Fisher wrote a letter that he distributed to each of his
teammates imploring them to come together and play as one during
the Western Conference Finals against Utah, they could at least
have applauded his passion, not crumpled the paper up and left it
for the janitor.
</P>
<P>
   So what if he doesn't hang with the Hollywood heavies? When
Fisher contacted his teammates at the start of the lockout and
again at its end to try to organize group workouts, the least they
could have done was gotten back in touch with him.
</P>
<P>
   That's OK. Fisher is nothing if not persistent.
</P>
<P>
   When training camp got under way in Santa Barbara, Fisher was
troubled by what he saw. Too many guys were freelancing. There
wasn't a whole lot of teamwork going on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't feel everybody had left their personal agendas
behind,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So he spoke up. In a voice that sometimes cracked with emotion
Fisher said, ``If everybody's not interested in playing as a team,
let's get it out in the open now. Because if we're just going to do
our own thing, I'll go out and pad my own stats so I can get (a
new) contract next year.''
</P>
<P>
   That got everybody's attention. Starting tonight, we'll find out
if Fisher has been able to keep it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
