<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 23:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2739 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SUNS-MASTER-PLAN-     02-04 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUNS-MASTER-PLAN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOPE REVIVED BY SUCCESSFUL PLAN B  
 MCDYESS' DEFECTION REWRITES BLUEPRINT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Plan, plan, plan.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns have been through more of them than the old Soviet
Union, a kingdom that was reduced to Clipperdom.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody is forecasting such a fate for the Suns. The empire
without a crown isn't on a fast-break pace to become the NBA's
version of Kazakstan, an exiled franchise forever without a chance.
</P>
<P>
   But the Suns aren't exactly headed for the inner circle, either.
Something called the lockout got in the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``A funny thing happened on the way to the Forum,'' Suns
President Jerry Colangelo said a couple of weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't laughing.
</P>
<P>
   A philosophical Colangelo made the comment the day after Antonio
McDyess' jump to Denver landed in Phoenix like a grenade.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns were left to pick up the pieces. They did so in a swift
fashion that might prove brilliant. Forward Tom Gugliotta signed.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the loss of McDyess summed up the Suns' plight.
They had spent all of the 1997-98 season planning a major shopping
spree. Financial flexibility was a theme for the season. They had
about $15 million to spend.
</P>
<P>
   But then the owners locked out the players. For the Suns, there
was double meaning in the term lockout. They were the optimistic
shopper with a fistful of cash, who suddenly couldn't get into the
store.
</P>
<P>
   A summer plan for negotiations and news conferences turned into
a long, anxious stretch full of wondering and hoping. They
succeeded with Plan B, the alternate hustle to sign Gugliotta after
the loss of McDyess.
</P>
<P>
   But their real hope, Plan A, was to sign both. Widespread and
well-founded speculation about Scottie Pippen changed when he
underwent back surgery after last season's final championship run
with the Chicago Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen's age, 33, and history of injury played heavily in the
Suns' decision not to make a run at him. Instead, he went to
Houston as the Suns waited in vain on McDyess before making a
concerted move on Gugliotta, who had supplanted Pippen as their
prime target.
</P>
<P>
   With the acquisition of 7-foot-2 center Luc Longley in a deal
with Chicago, the Suns' hope was for a front line of McDyess and
Gugliotta to flank the big man. It was intriguing and potentially
imposing. But it didn't happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're refocusing on a different team than I had expected,''
Suns Coach Danny Ainge said. ``There was a time a couple of months
ago when we expected a different level of talent. Then there was
time a couple of weeks ago when I wasn't expecting anything at all.
But now, I'm optimistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Fact is, McDyess might have slipped from the Suns' grasp,
anyway. As it turns out, he was at least thinking about a return to
Denver even before the owners locked their doors to the players.
</P>
<P>
   There are questions about the Suns' timing and decision not to
lock McDyess into a long-term deal before the work stoppage.
</P>
<P>
   But Colangelo said he was confident at midseason last year that
a new deal could be reached with McDyess' agent at the time, Arn
Tellem. McDyess then fired Tellem and hired Tony Dutt last summer,
a lockout period during which NBA management was prohibited from
talking to free agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a hunch then that he wasn't coming back,'' Colangelo
said.
</P>
<P>
   But by then, the process was under way. General Bryan Colangelo
went to work under the revised salary cup rules and put together a
Longely deal that was critical. It allowed the Suns more money to
offer Gugliotta in the first season of his six-year, $58.5 million
contract. Instead of offering less than $6 million in the first
year, the Suns were able to offer Gugliotta $7.8 million because of
salary cap space cleared in the Longley acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   They also were able to keep $3.5 million for a one-year contract
for Clifford Robinson and then a six-year, $22.1 million deal for
Rex Chapman.
</P>
<P>
   Chapman was a given in any Suns plan. He had announced that he
would return for the league average salary.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson became a key part of the plan as signs of McDyess'
departure began to mount. All the while, the Suns were adding other
pieces along the way. Backup center Joe Kleine signed. George
McCloud re-enlisted for a second season. Rookies Pat Garrity, Toby
Bailey and Gerald Brown got standard contracts. Chris Morris was
added two days ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing things on the run,'' Ainge said.
</P>
<P>
   From a team with a long history of being at its best while on
the run, it's a plan in process. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
