<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 23:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2740 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SUNS-KIDD-AZR &LR;      02-04 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUNS-KIDD-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S KIDD'S TEAM NOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Ever since the Suns duped the Dallas Mavericks into
trading Jason Kidd the day after Christmas in 1996, there never has
been a doubt about who would be the club's point guard of the
future.
</P>
<P>
   However, for a season and a half, there was robust debate about
the point guard of the present.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the point guard of the Suns' past, Kevin Johnson, is
shopping the free-agent market, and the 1999 Suns are Kidd's alone
to run.
</P>
<P>
   From the first days of the club's training camp, when he was
going at a break-neck pace and even getting into the faces of
teammates, Kidd has demonstrated that he's ready to take on the
chore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tempers flared a couple of times, and I was glad they did,''
Kidd said. ``I wanted to see where everybody was at. I wanted to
know if everybody was on the same page.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm going into battle, if I'm going on a mission, I want to
know who's going to follow me in. I wanted to set that tone from
Day 1.''
</P>
<P>
   It was something Kidd had been reluctant to do in the past. He
followed KJ as a collegiate star at California, admired him as a
pro. So Kidd looked upon the Suns as KJ's team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did defer to him,'' Kidd said. ``That's an awkward situation
to be traded to a team that has a Hall of Fame point guard on the
team for a long time. I didn't want to say very much.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to lead by just playing hard, and that's still the way
I love to lead. I still don't like to say too much, but if there's
a time to say something this year, I will.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to be accountable, and the best way is to lead by
example. I've been physical in practice. The guys will tell you
I've been playing like it's the playoffs. We have to be a tougher
team this season, and I put on a little weight, got a little
stronger in the off-season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want us to be more physical, and that means I have to play
that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Kidd's teammates have noticed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jason just seems to be on a mission,'' guard Rex Chapman said.
``He goes hard every day and hasn't taken a practice off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can understand why Jason was reluctant (to assert himself).
This is, what, his fifth year in the league? It wasn't just a thing
with Kevin being with the Suns for so long, it was following him at
Cal and all of that. Kevin was a guy who had earned his stripes,
and it was tough for Jason.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tough for Kevin, too. And it wasn't easy for (Coach)
Danny Ainge. He played with Kevin and has a lot of respect for him
as a player and a person. That's not an easy situation to be in. I
think they all handled it pretty well.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ainge said Kidd has to have a greater comfort level now. In
Kidd's first season in Phoenix, he came off the bench at one point
and often played without the ball because KJ was at his best with
it. KJ also sacrificed, playing shooting guard alongside Kidd and
starting only 12 of the 50 games he played last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He sure seems (more comfortable) in practices and (exhibition)
games so far,'' Ainge said. ``He does seem like he has a comfort
level.''
</P>
<P>
   Ainge said he saw occasions when Kidd was reluctant to assert
leadership, but not anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't just Jason, I saw it in KJ, too,'' he said. ``I
think they both like each other and respect each other. It just
wasn't perfect for either one of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did see a little bit of that (reluctance). They tried, and I
give them credit, and we had pretty good success.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Jason is very excited that this is his team now. He's
come in with that attitude and seems like he's been on a high from
the day he arrived at camp, from the first day. I think everything
about Jason is better than it's been in his basketball life.
</P>
<P>
   ``His practice habits are better. His intensity in practice is
better. There are things he can still improve on, but I think he's
going to be a very good leader for this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Kidd's strengths are still his open-court game, defense and
relentlessness. Since that trade, the Suns have attempted to retool
to fit those strengths.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the fastest point guard in the league,'' Ainge said.
``We want to play up-tempo, and at the same time, we recognize that
we have to be able to execute in the half court. And I think Jason
has really improved his half-court game.''
</P>
<P>
   Chapman agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been shooting the ball with confidence, and that's been
the only thing that's ever been questioned with Jason,'' Chapman
said. ``He sure has shot it well in the preseason.''
</P>
<P>
   Chapman figures that the rest of the NBA is about to find out
about Kidd's mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things that bothers me most about people
overlooking our team right now is that we've got the best point
guard in the NBA,'' he said. ``That's got to say something.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
