<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 23:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2742 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBA-RULES-AZR &LR;      02-04 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-RULES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOCKOUT'S LEGACY: PARITY  
 SUNS, OTHER TEAMS LIKELY TO KEEP STARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Suns President Jerry Colangelo likes to tell the story
of a conversation he had with ESPN's basketball expert, David
Aldridge, after the NBA lockout was lifted.
</P>
<P>
   Aldridge, Colangelo said, told him the Suns are the ``poster
child'' of the new collective bargaining agreement.
</P>
<P>
   And at that point, Aldridge had a good argument. After all, the
Suns had a plan that started more than two years earlier when they
traded Charles Barkley to the Houston Rockets.
</P>
<P>
   It was designed to give them as much salary cap room as possible
for the 1998 off-season, when almost half of the league's players
would be free agents.
</P>
<P>
   The lockout blew that plan apart.
</P>
<P>
   But ultimately, it may create an NBA that gives all 29 teams a
fair chance to compete for championships. It will limit the amount
of money the best players can get, but filter some of it down to
the middle class of players, particularly long-time veterans.
</P>
<P>
   It is designed to make it easier for teams to keep their own
best players, restricting free-agent movement, thereby creating
more continuity and perhaps fan loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   And it means it won't be the Suns on that poster.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the real poster child might just be the last dynasty _
the Chicago Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls had a plan, too, if Michael Jordan decided to retire.
It was to break up the team, take some lumps for a season and clear
as much salary cap space as possible for next summer's free-agent
class.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago is in position to have as much as $20 million available
for next summer's shopping spree. Trouble is, there may not be
anybody to spend it on. Thanks to the new rules, teams are at an
advantage in signing their own players to contract extensions.
</P>
<P>
   And many of the best young players already have been scratched
off the list of free agents.
</P>
<P>
   Antoine Walker re-signed with the Boston Celtics, Shareef
Abdur-Raheem re-upped with the Vancouver Grizzlies, Zydrunas
Ilgauskas signed a new deal with the Cleveland Cavaliers, the Los
Angeles Lakers got Kobe Bryant's name on a new pact and Allen
Iverson agreed to an extension with Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   There still will be players available, perhaps Stephon Marbury
of Minnesota or New York's Marcus Camby. But the options are far
fewer for the Bulls, as they will be for any other team that
attempts to clear a lot of space and rebuild with free agents in
the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``The general attitude is that teams won't lose their best
players to free agency anymore,'' Colangelo said. ``There is more
incentive to stay, but there are going to be exceptions. Tom
Gugliotta didn't. Antonio McDyess didn't. But you see a lot of the
young players signing now with their teams, like Kobe, Shareef and
Antoine Walker.''
</P>
<P>
   The team that drafts a player, or already has him under
contract, has an advantage because a player can get a longer
guaranteed deal _ seven years instead of six _ with his own team,
and because he can get annual raises of 12.5 percent of his base
salary compared to a 10 percent increase from other teams.
</P>
<P>
   There will still be some movement, but it usually will be based
on factors other than money _ lifestyle, a team's style of play, an
organization's reputation. They are factors that have helped the
Suns attract free agents in the past and, in the long term, could
help them again.
</P>
<P>
   There's another potential side effect: With limits on how much
all players can make, there figure to be fewer battles with agents.
In fact, some players are hiring lawyers on an hourly basis to
handle their contracts rather than pay an agent a percentage of it.
</P>
<P>
   The end result of it all, however, is that teams with greater
resources won't have an advantage in signing players. And making a
quick fix through free agency is next to impossible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's a feeling that if you try to strip your team
all the way down, it might take you a while to come back again,''
Colangelo said. ``If you have to start over again, it's going to be
very difficult. Teams that have their players in place are ahead of
the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why if we had not recovered by signing Gugliotta, we
would have been behind the 8-ball to some degree. The way it played
out, we wouldn't have had any cap space if we tried to put it off
for a year.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; While the Suns have made some big scores in the free-agent era
_ starting with Tom Chambers and moving on to the likes of Danny
Manning, A.C. Green and Gugliotta _ the prospect of building via
trades and drafts isn't exactly frightening to them.
</P>
<P>
   Kidd, Charles Barkley, Kevin Johnson and McDyess are among their
prominent trade acquisitions. And while their draft-day success has
been intermittent, partly because they've had few early selections,
they have made some late choices of uncommon value: namely Jeff
Hornacek (46th choice, 1986), Dan Majerle (14th, '88), Cedric
Ceballos (28th, '90), Wesley Person (23rd, '94), Michael Finley
(21st, '95) and Steve Nash (15th, '96).
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to see more emphasis on trades and on the draft,
which I think is healthy,'' Colangelo said.
</P>
<P>
   Suns General Manager Bryan Colangelo said the Suns never gave
any serious thought to the plan Chicago is following, which would
have meant trying to sign a lot of players to one-year deals and go
after next summer's free agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not my nature to say, `Wait till next year,' '' Jerry
Colangelo said. ``And when you're 59 years old, your time is
running out.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-04-99 2342EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
