<DOCNO> NYT19990204.0568 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-04 23:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2743 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-COPPER-WORLD-USAC     02-04 0612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-COPPER-WORLD-USAC-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USAC DRIVER STRIKES INDY GOLD  
 JUST BEING THERE A DELIGHT FOR HEWITT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Jack Hewitt is from the old school, the school of hard
knocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took me 25 years to get to (the Indianapolis 500),'' said
Hewitt, a short-track specialist from Troy, Ohio. ``But at least I
got there.''
</P>
<P>
   Hewitt, at 46, got there last May, then delivered one of the
most memorable quotes in Indy 500 history.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the feach (short for feature or main event), I'm going
to Eldora (Speedway) for a sprint-car race,'' Hewitt told an ABC
pit-road announcer before the start of the Indy 500.
</P>
<P>
   Jokingly informed he shouldn't refer to the Indy 500 as ``the
feach,'' Hewitt just shrugged his shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think to a real race-car driver, Indy is just another
feature,'' Hewitt said. ``It's everything that goes along with it
that makes it so special. Then, when you finally get to the race,
it's like a cherry on top of the biggest hot fudge sundae of your
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Hewitt still is wallowing in its sweetness.
</P>
<P>
   Although he is a star from another era, an era that still
managed to put a Bettenhausen, Unser and an Andretti in the Indy
500, Hewitt never did quite make it to racing's pinnacle.
</P>
<P>
   Until last year, when an 11th-hour offer came knocking at
Hewitt's door.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a Hollywood script without the sex and violence,'' said
Hewitt, who is driving a U.S. Auto Club Silver Bullet and USAC
midget in this weekend's U.S. Tobacco Co. Copper World Classic at
Phoenix International Raceway. ``I mean, I went from having no
ride, to getting a phone call at the last minute to go take my
rookie test at (Indianapolis Motor Speedway).
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, within four hours, I crash and tear the car up. The crew
fixes the car and the next day I spin out and lose it. But I didn't
hit anything, so I come back and practice some more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, I'm the first one out to qualify and the pit crew waves
me off. We eventually make the show and I start in the seventh row,
which is the row that's right on the last set of bricks that are on
the racetrack.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wind up with a flat tire early in the race, but still finish
12th. Unbelievable and amazing. I'm still thrilled by it.''
</P>
<P>
   Although it was Hewitt's only IRL start of the season, it wasn't
the year's only grand moment.
</P>
<P>
   In September, Hewitt won the 4-Crown Nationals at Eldora,
becoming the first driver to capture all four divisions (USAC
Silver Bullet, midget, sprints and United Midwest Promoters
modifieds) on the same day.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't know how difficult that is,'' said driver Jason
Leffler, last season's USAC Silver Bullet and midget champion. ``To
me, it's truly amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Hewitt has trouble believing it really happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody thought it was impossible,'' said Hewitt, the
1986-87 USAC Silver Bullet champion and holder of about 75 career
USAC wins in three divisions. ``I thought so, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Making Indy still is my best moment, but Eldora is a close
second. It's real close.''
</P>
<P>
   So close that Hewitt still gets goose bumps thinking about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people thought I had a chance to win all four in 1993,
but after I won the first one, I got hurt in the second race,''
Hewitt said. ``Another car hit the wall and landed on top of me. It
broke my neck and right arm.''
</P>
<P>
   But not Hewitt's spirit, who remains determined to return to
Indy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm on a mission to get back in an IRL car this year,'' said
Hewitt, who missed the IRL season opener last month, but hopes to
land a ride for the next race on March 28 at PIR. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
