<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-UTAH-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW UTAH COMMITTEE TRIED TO PULL JOB STRINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Also see OLY-Africa) 
 (rk) 
 By JERE LONGMAN and JO THOMAS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ In the summer of 1993, as Salt Lake City was
attempting to win the 2002 Winter Games, two of its top-ranking
Olympic officials tried to find a job for the unemployed husband of
the Olympic representative from Finland.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Joklik and James C. Beardall, both members of the board of
trustees of the Salt Lake City bid committee, separately wrote
letters to the Weyerhaeuser Co. in Tacoma, Wash., seeking a
forestry job for Bjarne Haeggman. The letters were retained by the
bid committee and made available to The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   In one letter, Beardall wrote that it would be ``helpful to our
Olympic bid effort'' if the company would provide a job to
Haeggman.
</P>
<P>
   Joklik and other board members have insisted in recent weeks
that they knew nothing about Salt Lake City's aggressive campaign
to provide jobs, cash payments, tuition aid and lavish gifts to
delegates of the International Olympic Committee whose votes
determined where the Games would be played.
</P>
<P>
   Joklik and Beardall, who is president of an Ogden, Utah, lumber
company, did not respond to telephone calls seeking comment. Their
lawyers also did not return telephone calls.
</P>
<P>
   A Weyerhaeuser spokeswoman confirmed that its letters to Joklik
and Beardall were authentic, and that Weyerhaeuser records did not
show that Haeggman had ever been hired.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's extremely disappointing,'' said Ken Bullock, a member of
the board of trustees of the Salt Lake City organizing committee
who has been critical of its business practices. ``If you have
correspondence, clearly you are a participant in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal authorities are now investigating whether the Salt Lake
City effort violated any laws. No one has been accused of
wrongdoing. The correspondence between Weyerhaeuser and the
committee begins in the summer of 1993.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter dated June 29, Joklik wrote a letter to George
Weyerhaeuser, chairman of the board of the Weyerhaeuser Co., saying
that he had met Pirjo Haeggman, an IOC member from Finland, while
on a visit to the Olympic Museum in Lausanne, Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   Joklik described her husband, Bjarne Haeggman, as an
``outstanding forester,'' and added that Joklik ``was wondering
whether Weyerhaeuser might have any position for which to consider
him.'' The letter is signed ``Frank.'' It was written on the
personal letterhead of Joklik, who was chairman of the board of
trustees of the Salt Lake City bid committee.
</P>
<P>
   In a response bearing a Weyerhaeuser letterhead, and dated Aug.
12, 1993, a company official informed Joklik that officials had
explored employment opportunities in Russia but that it could not
find ``an appropriate match'' for Bjarne Haeggman's abilities.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks later, on Aug. 26, 1993, Beardall wrote to Edward P.
Rogel, Weyerhaeuser's vice president for human resources, asking
whether a job could be found for Haeggman in western Canada.
Beardall noted that Finland had 20 percent unemployment, and that
``it would be very helpful to our Olympic bid effort if we could
help Mr. Haeggman find employment.''
</P>
<P>
   After Salt Lake won the bid, Beardall was appointed to oversee
internal auditing for the Olympic organizing committee.
</P>
<P>
   A way was eventually found to help Haeggman. Beginning in May
1994, the committee began paying him $3,000 a month, with total
payments reaching $30,000 to $35,000, a bid committee official
said.
</P>
<P>
   According to an organizing committee official, who spoke on
condition of anonymity, the bid committee's files contain a
document saying that Haeggman was working for Great Basin
Engineering, a company based in Salt Lake City and Ogden, Utah.
This arrangement, the document asserted, had been approved by
Thomas K. Welch, the bid committee president.
</P>
<P>
   Jay R. Anderson, president and owner of Great Basin, said he
never employed Haeggman. Anderson said he did recall a conversation
in 1993 with Welch, a close friend, who asked if Haeggman could
undertake an 18-month study of reforestation in Finland through his
company.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson said he sent a memo that same day to David Johnson, the
bid committee vice president, setting out what he understood about
the proposal, but heard nothing more of Haeggman.
</P>
<P>
   Pirjo Haeggman resigned from the IOC last month after it was
revealed that her husband had worked for the Salt Lake bid
committee and that he had also been hired in a forestry job in
Canada, while having his rent paid by the Toronto committee that
unsuccessfully bid on the 1996 Summer Games. Attempts to reach the
Haeggmans Thursday were unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   Joklik, who resigned on Jan. 8 as president of the Salt Lake
City committee, has said that he knew nothing of the assistance
provided to IOC members and their families. Telephone calls
Thursday to him and his attorney seeking comment were not returned.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, Joklik has said through his lawyer that the
``details'' of the bid work were handled by Welch and Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Details continued to emerge Thursday that appear to show that
gift-giving to IOC members was frequent and out in the open. In
July 1990, for instance, while Salt Lake City was unsuccessfully
pursuing the 1998 Winter Games, the Mormon capital's first official
visit by an IOC member was made by Slobodan Filipovic of
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Former Utah Lt. Gov. W. Val Oveson presented a Winchester
.30-.30, the rifle that won the West, to Filipovic, who would die
of cancer on June 15, 1995, a day before Salt Lake City won the
right to play host to the 2002 Games.
</P>
<P>
   Oveson said he recalled giving Filipovic a gun, but had no idea
what it was worth and had no part in planning the presentation of
the gift. During his eight years as lieutenant governor, he said,
he frequently was the host for Olympic-related events and that
gift-giving was part of his duties.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never felt anything was excessive,'' said Oveson, who is now
national taxpayer advocate for the Internal Revenue Service.
</P>
<P>
   Utah Gov. Mike Leavitt, who has been critical of scholarships
and cash payments made to IOC members, said in an interview
Thursday that he was frequently called upon in Salt Lake City and
abroad to present gifts to IOC delegates. Often, he said, he did
not know what the gifts were beforehand and was not told what they
cost.
</P>
<P>
   A Salt Lake City bid official said the governor gave such gifts
as clocks and expensive luggage. IOC members are prohibited from
receiving gifts with a value greater than $200. It could not be
learned whether the price of the gifts exceeded this amount.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not inconceivable that I gave away luggage,'' Leavitt
said. ``I did whatever I was asked to do at the time I was asked to
do it. I had no idea what the rules of the IOC were. If there were
in fact gifts given in violation of IOC protocol, I would have had
no context to know that.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that he had not personally seen anything involving gifts
that appeared to him to be unreasonable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see that as being the problem here,'' Leavitt said.
The problem, he said, ``are these so-called scholarships and cash
payments.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Were the IOC's expectations higher than reasonable? Yes.''
Leavitt said. ``Did they operate in an atmosphere of opulence? Yes.
Did I feel comfortable with that? The answer to that is no.''
</P>
<P>
   In a trip that was emblematic of the complex mix of interests in
Salt Lake City's bid effort, the governor and his mother, Anne
Leavitt, traveled with six other passengers to the 1994 Winter
Games in Lillehammer, Norway, on a private jet that the governor
said was owned by Leucadia, a corporation that owns one of the
resorts which will be used for Olympic skiing and snowboarding in
Park City, Utah.
</P>
<P>
   On board the same plane, arranged by the Salt Lake City bid
committee, was a cargo of $21,000 in used medical equipment
intended for the son of an IOC delegate from Algeria. Leavitt said
he knew nothing of the cargo.
</P>
<P>
   A member of the Salt Lake City contingent in Norway said that
Leavitt's plane arrived at a small airport 90 minutes from
Lillehammer at noon on Feb. 11, 1994, and that the medical
equipment was unloaded from the plane in duffel bags.
</P>
<P>
   An invoice included in Salt Lake City bid documents shows that
medical instruments valued at $21,725 were transferred from Thomas
D. Rosenberg, a prominent Salt Lake City orthopedic surgeon, to the
bid committee on Dec. 23, 1993. A flight manifest detailed the same
items.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenberg was a close friend of Welch, the bid committee
president.
</P>
<P>
   The Salt Lake City committee files include a letter from
Rosenberg to Yacine Zerguini, a surgeon from Algeria, about a
possible visit to Utah. Yacine Zerguini is the son of Mohamed
Zerguini, an IOC member.
</P>
<P>
   Both Zerguinis attended the Olympics in Lillehammer, bid
committee officials said. Rosenberg, through his secretary,
declined to comment, citing ongoing investigations of the Salt Lake
City bid practices. Yacine Zerguini could not be reached in El
Biar, Algeria. His father, Mohamed Zerguini, who has not been
implicated in the IOC's investigation of the Salt Lake City
scandal, said in an interview from Algeria that ``I'm not aware of
that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-04-99 2354EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
